<HEADLINE>
IRABU'S EFFORT SEEMS LACKING, SO YANKEES PUSH PITCHERS HARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Hideki Irabu's lackadaisical play on Saturday
spurred coaches to conduct the Yankees' version of boot camp
Sunday, and 14 pitchers, including Irabu, went through an hourlong
series of drills in single file, some bending over and gasping.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu would have been first in line if the coaching staff had
had its way _ the first in line to acknowledge responsibility for
an approach that infuriated many of his teammates. First in line to
demonstrate aggressiveness the coaching staff would love to see all
the time. First in line to show them that his appalling body
language in Saturday's exhibition game was an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   But when the pitchers stepped forward to practice covering first
base, Irabu was last in line. He was last in line when they fielded
bunts, last in line when they backed up third, last in line when
they ran bases, moving with great deliberation all the while. Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said later that he wished
Irabu went through the drills ``with a little more enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu is not immediately in jeopardy of losing his place in the
Yankees' rotation. But with his play Saturday, when he failed to
cover first base or hold runners and appeared to others within the
organization as if he just did not care, according to one teammate
who did not want to be identified, Irabu is on the verge of
alienating other Yankees who compete desperately and daily. Irabu
next pitches Thursday, and Stottlemyre said he needed to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll see a big turnaround in his next outing,''
Stottlemyre said, ``because the same kind of outing would create a
lot of doubts _ not for me, but in the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre likes pitchers, empathizes with them, rarely utters
a negative word about them. When he gently suggested that Irabu
``may have quit a little bit'' Saturday, it had the same shock
value as any George Steinbrenner blast.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, however, did not seem to understand the criticism Sunday,
at one point laughing at the implication of reporters' questions to
him. Asked if he would do anything different in his outing Saturday
if he had the chance, Irabu said, ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course he tries hard all the time, he insisted. Of course he
concentrates all the time. ``I pitched in 30 games over the course
of the season last year,'' Irabu said through an interpreter,
George Rose, ``and I did my best in every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu tired of inquiries about the appearance that he stopped
competing, about body language that indicated to others that he did
not care _ that he ``quit a little bit.'' With measured sarcasm,
Irabu said: ``Sometimes I feel like I should stand up straight and
put on a silk necktie. Maybe that will make them feel I'm
concentrating.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Yankees were thrilled with Irabu's effort. He
had taken to following the example of Roger Clemens, working out
diligently, and he lost about 10 pounds in a week. Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager, had said at the start of camp that Irabu needed
to step up his effort this year, and that is what Irabu did.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu has gained most of that weight back, and the era of
good feelings evaporated quickly when teammates saw him fail to
cover first base Saturday, lob pickoff throws and ignore base
runners, which meant catcher Jorge Posada had little chance to
throw them out. Posada all but refused to comment Sunday on Irabu's
performance, saying only, ``You saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu is surrounded by teammates like Paul O'Neill, who is
dedicated to getting hits in every at-bat, and David Cone, who is
respected because he competes ferociously even on the days his arm
feels terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said the reliever Jeff Nelson did ask him if all the
pitchers were running Sunday only because of Irabu's performance
Saturday, and Stottlemyre assured him that recent fundamental
mistakes had contributed to the convening of the one-day boot camp
as well. Other than that, ``I haven't heard anything from the
players'' directly about Irabu, Stottlemyre said. ``But I don't
need to. They're a demanding bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu is mostly a loner on this team. Without established
relationships, teammates do not view his outings through the prism
of some personality trait. O'Neill throws a bat and teammates chalk
that up to his intensity. Andy Pettitte struggled last spring and
others figured he was worried about his pregnant wife. If something
is bothering Irabu _ and he said no personal issues were nagging at
him _ nobody will know it.
</P>
<P>
   His second-half slump last year drew down his reservoir of good
will with teammates, and now many judge him strictly on what he
does on the field. On Saturday, they did not like what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hopefully a one-day setback,'' Stottlemyre said,
``from where he was before.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jackson, the Hall of Fame slugger, who had a falling-out
with the Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner, last week,
was here Sunday and met with Steinbrenner, in a first step to
normalize relations. ... Andy Pettitte pitched two shutout innings
in a Class AAA exhibition Sunday, his latest push toward a return
to the big leagues. Pettitte, coming back from a strained elbow,
will probably pitch in a minor-league exhibition Thursday and open
the season on the disabled list. ... David Cone pitched five
innings and Orlando Hernandez four in the Yankees' 8-5 exhibition
loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. Both Cone and Hernandez struggled
with their command at times. ... The Yankees gave outfielder Jerome
Walton his unconditional release and assigned a highly touted
prospect, Alfonso Soriano, to their minor-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
