<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS MAY CHANGE HANDS, BUT STORE'S BEEN AVENUE FOR 25 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Changing Hands Bookstore has lasted longer than
most marriages and some countries.
</P>
<P>
   It has witnessed book trends from home improvement to
self-improvement, from Eastern philosophy to neurolinguistic
programming.
</P>
<P>
   It has survived the onslaught of big chains and urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   With a philosophy of customer service and community involvement,
Changing Hands endures in a world beset by retail metamorphosis. On
Thursday, the Tempe landmark will celebrate its 25th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   That news may make some faithful customers feel a little ancient
themselves. Has it really been a quarter of a century since a
cubbyhole on Fifth Street opened its door to bibliophiles seeking a
reading refuge?
</P>
<P>
   Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the store survived, it has become something of a
minichain itself. Last year, a second store opened at 6428 S.
McClintock Drive in Tempe as a sister to the 414 Mill Ave. store,
which replaced the original location in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more surprised with the store's longevity than its
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was going to last,'' says Gayle Shanks, who
launched Changing Hands with husband Bob Sommer and their friend,
Tom Broderson. ``I didn't see 25 years in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Sommer says, ``The moment I got into the bookstore, I felt
I'd come home.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments are echoed by long-time customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a place of nostalgia in terms of my roots
here,'' says Walt Richardson, lead singer of the Tempe-based
Morning Star Band and Tempe resident since 1974. ``Changing Hands
has always been a landmark where people would meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Carla Elling, director of the Creative Writing program at
Arizona State University, has been a Changing Hands loyalist since
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been captivated by the wild seat-of-the-pants
energy and ingenuity of their co-op beginnings, their amazing
growth as a business and as an extended community/family of book
lovers,'' Elling says.
</P>
<P>
   Those legions of book lovers have increased from a trickle to a
flood. In the beginning, Changing Hands clerks were lucky to see
three customers a day. By 1998, the number was up to about 160,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   In 25 years, millions of books have sold, and rent has risen
from $125 a month to an astounding $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophy of the shop remains the same: Keep the customer
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always willing to go out of our way to order a book,
even if we don't make a profit on it,'' Sommer says.
</P>
<P>
   Such notions would send shivers through a conventional
corporation. Changing Hands has never been conventional.
</P>
<P>
   Flip back through the pages of the Changing Hands biography and
you find the story of three hippies who made good turning their
passion for reading into an American enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Sommer and Shanks were married and living in converted
Army barracks, where they paid $55 a month in rent and tended a
small garden in their back yard. Shanks was finishing her teaching
certificate at ASU, while Sommer taught math there and ran a
hand-loom workshop, crafting looms for local weavers.
</P>
<P>
   The three twentysomething friends also were teaching at an
alterative school called the Free Learners Society at Third Avenue
and Roosevelt Street in Phoenix. After school let out, they would
sit on the porch and daydream about opening a bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy seemed like nirvana _ becoming intimate with the
bestseller list, rubbing elbows with famous authors. Tempe needed
another bookstore, they believed. The neighborhood had only Hill's
at the Tempe Center and nearby Books, Etc.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny bookstore on Mill Avenue, Caveat Emptor, was faltering.
Broderson, who had finished high school but was not in college,
seized the opportunity. With $500 borrowed from his father, he
bought the store lock, stock and paperback and watched the former
owner grab his check and gleefully race out the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Broderson had himself a bookstore. But it seemed doomed.
</P>
<P>
   With rent scheduled to increase to $300 from $125 a month, he
hung on through the next Mill Avenue Fair with help from Shanks,
then closed the business. Shanks helped him cart the leftover books
to his parents' house in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before Broderson showed up at Sommer and Shank's
house and interrupted their gardening to ask a favor: Would they go
into the book business with him? He had found a new building at 9
E. Fifth St. where he could sublease 500 square feet of affordable
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said yes,'' Shanks says. ``It took me 12 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer remained committed to his teaching and his loom workshop
but joined the book business the next year.
</P>
<P>
   With an additional $300 borrowed from Broderson's father and a
$1,500 loan from First National Bank, Broderson and Shanks went to
work building book shelves and ordering books.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular titles then were signs of the times: ``The
Whole Earth'' ``Catalog, Finding and Buying Your Place in the
Country, Zen Mind Beginner's'' ``Mind''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Because many of the books were used, recycled and traded,
Broderson gave the store its appropriate name. Changing Hands
opened April 1, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one came in, that's my memory,'' Shanks says with a laugh
about their first day of business.
</P>
<P>
   Those slow days gave her time to read, weave textiles on a small
loom and chat with friends. She rode her bike to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But fun didn't pay the bills. The store didn't turn a profit for
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Success came gradually. Broderson and Shanks expanded their
stock, buying much of it at swap meets. They began carrying more
new books, heeding customer requests.
</P>
<P>
   Early customers were denizens of the Age of Aquarius. They ate
sprouts, defied authority, preserved the environment and expanded
their consciousness. They wore love beads and Birkenstock sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Shanks looks down at her own feet and laughs. She's still
wearing Birkenstocks.
</P>
<P>
   A list of Changing Hands' first neighbors is a blast from the
past: The Armadillo Wax Shop (candles), the original Gentle
Strength co-op (wheat germ), Earthen Joy (whole-grain sandwiches),
Happy Trails head shop (water pipes).
</P>
<P>
   Tempe officials welcomed Changing Hands. When the city began
downtown redevelopment in 1978, architects designed the space at
414 E. Mill with the store in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep them there,'' says Harry Mitchell, who was
Tempe mayor from 1978 to 1994 and a City Council member for eight
years before that. ``Changing Hands symbolizes what we've tried to
do in downtown Tempe - businesses that are unique.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU professors sent their students to the store, which carried
texts assigned in Creative Writing classes and the then-new Women's
Studies program. One customer set up a subsection on feminist works
and non-sexist books for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, Changing Hands was the only bookstore in the Valley
that took women's literature and feminist studies seriously,'' says
Mary Rothschild, director of Women's Studies at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   By May 1978, Changing Hands had outgrown its little Fifth Street
location and abandoned it for the location on Mill. Boxes of books
were transported via a human chain of 50 friends, family, customers
and ASU professors that stretched 500 feet between the two stores.
</P>
<P>
   Workers stocking the new shelves ate pizza and sang an African
chant, ````Dumaah abutay,'''' recalls Pinna Joseph, who came on
board just before the relocation. Joseph now is a partner and
director of marketing and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just ecstatic,'' Shanks says. ``We thought we were in
heaven. It was three times the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, they outgrew that space, too. By 1983, says Susie
Brazil, partner and manager of the McClintock store, ``we had no
room; there was no space where we could even set a card rack.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same week that Sommer and Shanks received notice that
their soon-to-be-adopted son had been born, they were knocking down
walls and expanding to the south.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, they expanded north.
</P>
<P>
   Broderson had left the business by then to open a bookstore in
Prescott called the Satisfied Mind. He still leases a small section
of the Mill Avenue store, offering out-of-print and collectible
books.
</P>
<P>
   Though Changing Hands continues to thrive, downtown Tempe has
changed around it, shifting focus from retail businesses to
entertainment. Restaurants and bars attract a younger crowd that
would rather hang out than shop.
</P>
<P>
   New parking procedures can be frustrating. Walk-by traffic has
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Changing Hands hopes to ride out the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If rent stays reasonable, we will stay on Mill,'' Sommer says.
</P>
<P>
   Store owners are hedging their bets with the McClintock
location, situated in a strip mall. The Mill Avenue store is
returning to its used-book roots and reducing its size by a third.
</P>
<P>
   Changing Hands faithful need not despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a return to our roots in a positive way,'' Shanks says.
``It's a huge challenge. We are so committed to staying downtown
and being a community bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   The McClintock outlet is a big, beautiful shop filled with new
and used books, cards, candles and gift items and staffed by clerks
who know and love books.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, the Wildflower Bread Co. moves in next door with
access to Changing Hands, giving readers something to snack on
after they've selected their reading material.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that won't change is the Changing Hands philosophy. As
they once hoed their garden of tomatoes, broccoli and lettuce,
Sommer, Shanks and now Joseph and Brazil say they continue to
cultivate a clientele that shares their passion for literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Sommer says of his work. ``It's great when you
order a book and then you shelve it, and you show a customer the
book and you recommend it. Then you meet the author. You've felt
the complete cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually feels like you're doing the right thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
