<HEADLINE>
ROCKET BOY WINS FAVOR OF SPACE ENTHUSIASTS, WHO SLAM SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The ``Rocket Boy'' of the Phoenix's Deer Valley School
District is quickly becoming a cult figure among space wonks around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen-year-old David Silverstein, a seventh-grader who was
suspended for the rest of the school year for bringing a homemade
rocket to Desert Sky Middle School, has caught the attention of
scientists, a Ph.D. from the Jet Propulsion Laboratory and just
plain folks who were surprised that school officials would take
such drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   David's parents, who will home-school their son, are in the
process of appealing the suspension. The matter likely will come up
during an April 13 school board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The groundswell of support for David began with NASA engineer
Homer Hickam. Hickam's high school interest in rocketry is
portrayed in the movie ``October'' ``Sky,'' which inspired David to
build his rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster last &UR; week accepted an invitation from Space
Adventures to attend an Astronaut Rocketry Workshop in Washington,
D.C., over the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Applying my creativity without breaking the rules is great and
being able to build a rocket that might really work is a fantastic
dream come true,'' David said in responding to the Space
Adventures' offer.
</P>
<P>
   David acknowledges that he showed bad judgment in bringing the
rocket to school, but his plea didn't sway the district hearing
officer. The hearing officer refused to comment on the case, as did
the vice principal who ordered the locker search at the school.
</P>
<P>
   But people around the country haven't been so reticent, starting
with Hickam, who called and sent an e-mail to David. His advice to
the school board: ``Lighten up.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that David join a rocket club and invite the
school's principal and assistant principal to the first launching.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the business chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about this nonsense concerning this kid and his rocket
and the aftermath,'' said Frank Sietzen, editor in chief of ``Ad
Astra'' magazine in Washington. It's published by the National
Space Society, the world's oldest space education and advocacy
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a week goes by when I don't get a message from somebody
telling me that we need more education for kids about the promise
of spaceflight and space technology in their lives. Not only their
life today but their future. How in some communities the economic
boom has busted and school dropout rates in some locales are
soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we expect to keep our future's promise intact if we
slap down kids like this every time they demonstrate a little bit
of initiative?''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Walker, a former astronaut and mission commander, suggested
that school authorities could be flexible and give David
``penance,'' such as demonstrating his rockets for other students.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case,'' he said, ``I hope David realizes that
intellectual curiousity leads to knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines of the school district, the rocket was
classified as a firearm, a major violation in its zero-tolerance
policy.
</P>
<P>
   School officials have maintained that they had no option but to
suspend David. &QL; 
Jim Gintonio can be reached at 444-7125 or at
jim.gintonio(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
