<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ARIZONA'S SEN. JOHN McCAIN TALKS OF REAGAN-STYLE PRESIDENTIAL (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain is planning to announce early next
month that he is launching a full-blown campaign for the White
House that will draw upon former President Reagan's advisers and
Reagan's ``feel good'' brand of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reagan, the Arizona Republican is banking that his personal
appeal, enhanced by his war hero status and a reputation as a
political maverick, can elevate him above the Republican field.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will formalize his candidacy in early April with a
three-day tour that illustrates some of the states he plans to
emphasize. He will make tour stops in New Hampshire, South
Carolina, Arizona, California, Utah and Massachusetts. He plans to
begin the tour with a breakfast with Naval Academy midshipmen in
Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   He will visit Iowa later in April.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seeking a niche within the GOP, McCain, 62, is
seeking to pull in backers from all wings of the party, as Reagan
did, based as much on personality as on ideology. His strategy
suggests the third-term senator will not be courting the party's
religious conservatives the way some other Republicans historically
have in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain formed an exploratory presidential committee in December,
enabling him to raise funds and set up a campaign office in an old
printing shop in suburban Alexandria, Va. Some supporters have
already printed up some bumper stickers and sent them to McCain.
``McVote for McCain,'' says one.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares now to formally enter the race, McCain
acknowledged that he and the rest of the field trail Texas Gov.
George W. Bush in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was convinced that he (Bush) would be the odds-on
front-runner, and in many respects he deserves to be,'' McCain said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain insists he's not intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain says his own campaign _ emphasizing, as it will,
the overhaul of campaign finance laws and curbing government
``pork'' projects _ will fare just fine as a reform-minded,
underdog alternative. ``I think, with the appeal that we would
have, we'd be far better off not to campaign in the lead,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   So who will vote for McCain? Leaning back in a chair in his
Senate office, the white-haired senator ticks off a list of issues
and groups to which he can lay claim: ``National defense, veterans,
reformers, independent-minded (voters).''
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that McCain's core of campaign advisers
during this interim period has included Ken Duberstein, a former
chief of staff in the Reagan White House, and Michael Deaver, a
Reagn adviser and spinmaster.
</P>
<P>
   While Reagan made Americans feel good about themselves in his
1980s speeches, McCain will bill himself as a political reformer
and a Vietnam veteran who twice escaped death, first aboard an
aircraft carrier engulfed in flames, and then in a Hanoi prison
camp.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign, like Reagan's, is designed to appeal directly
to the gut.
</P>
<P>
   It's a message intended to elevate McCain above the realm of
politics and to make his rival candidates seem mundane by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think being a war hero has given him the inward strength to
do things that the ordinary politician wouldn't do,'' former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger said in a McCain profile
televised recently by the A&AMP;E Network as part of its ``Biography''
series.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger's quote could practically serve as McCain's campaign
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   The program contained footage of McCain scrambling out of a
plane in 1967 after it was hit by a rocket that misfired on the
deck of the USS Forrestal. McCain is also shown lying, critically
wounded, in a Hanoi prison camp after his plane was shot out of the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that McCain's campaign mailed thousands of
postcards to friends and potential donors alerting them to the
program, which premiered Feb. 10. His former Naval Academy
classmates, some of whom are now volunteering for his campaign,
held a reception for McCain on the evening of the broadcast. His
presidential committee Web site on the Internet
(www.mccainforpresident.org) invites supporters to contact the
staff to obtain a videotape of the program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McCain and aide Mark Salter are collaborating on a
book about the senator, his father and grandfather, who were both
admirals. The book ends with McCain returning home from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation tired of White House campaign finance and sex
scandals, McCain believes the time is right for a campaign based
largely on character.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things in my campaign is to restore respect to the
office of the presidency and the institutions of government, which
I think this administration debased in '96 with their campaign
finance violations,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain knows he faces a risk.
</P>
<P>
   Jabs at President Clinton's leadership could be delicate at
times for McCain who, like the president, has been accused of
marital infidelity in his past. McCain has not denied that he
wrecked his first marriage with ``inappropriate'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   McCain may also be subject to renewed barbs for his rebuke by a
Senate ethics panel for exercising ``poor judgment'' in his
relationship with former Phoenix financier Charles H Keating Jr.,
who became a symbol of reckless investments by the savings and loan
industry during the 1980s. McCain took campaign contributions from
Keating (later returned) and vacationed with him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he is counseling fellow Republican candidates to
avoid personal attacks _ not to protect his own image, but because
negative campaigning hurts the party's prospects of regaining the
White House in the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain said he had decided to borrow from Reagan's
legacy in part because Reagan made people feel positive and
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked at length about some of the difficulties that
the Republican Party is experiencing, and it's not so much got to
do with the message we're sending, but how we send the message,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan had this great ability to sound and act
inclusive. And even though people may disagree on specific issues,
he was an inclusionary president. He'd display kind of a gentleness
about him and project an image of pleasantness rather than having a
hard edge about him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the areas where I've tried to be more like
Ronald Reagan, sending out an inclusive message rather than an
exclusive message.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for McCain: raising about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to find 14,000 or 15,000 of my closest
friends. When you combine that with about $5 million in (federal)
matching funds, I think you could do it for $20 million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While this will be McCain's first run for president, he was
seriously considered in 1996 to be Bob Dole's running mate. Dole
eventually chose Jack Kemp instead.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, McCain said he is convinced he doesn't want to
be anybody's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   It is standard for presidential contenders to disavow interest
in the No. 2 spot for fear of trivializing their White House
ambitions. Still, McCain's dismissal of the vice presidency seems
to go further than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through that kind of routine and got together all of
our background and tax returns and all that stuff, and so I had
time to think about it then (in 1996),'' McCain said. ``I'm
convinced that I would not want to do that. It would mean moving my
family to Washington. Remember, I would be 64 years old by the time
that took place. I would much rather serve in the Senate and be
chairman of the Commerce Committee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who wins, McCain said, the nomination is likely to be
wrapped up in less than a year. McCain is already looking ahead to
such early primary states as New Hampshire, Iowa, South Carolina
and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``California, on March 7, is really going to be almost of
transcendent importance, because we've got one-fifth of the
delegates elected from one state on the same day,'' he said. ``For
all intents and purposes, from what I can see now on March 7 in the
year 2000, it's over. The nominee is decided.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
