u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-CRIME-300&AMP;A     03-29 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-CRIME-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS DROP AND SHOOTINGS RISE AS THE POLICE, GIULIANI SAYS, ARE
DISTRACTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With police statistics showing the rate of violent
crime creeping up again in New York City, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
suggested Sunday that the trend might be the result of a less
active police force distracted by the uproar over the killing of
Amadou Diallo seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters on the first day that officers in the
department's embattled Street Crime Unit reported for duty in
uniform _ one of several changes imposed on the unit by
Commissioner Howard Safir in the wake of the shooting _ Giuliani
said: ``The street crime arrests are down 62 percent since the
concentration on the Diallo case. And here's what we have to be
concerned about: in the places that street crime arrests are down,
shootings and murders are up.
</P>
<P>
   ``While everyone else in the media is concentrating just on one
shooting in New York City for the last two months,'' the mayor
said, ``I have to concentrate on 130 other people who died and were
killed and try to find a way to reduce that. So I have asked the
police commissioner and the Police Department not to be distracted,
to keep its focus on how we save lives in New York City and how
people are actually murdered and killed in the vast majority of
times in the city are by other citizens of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was citing statistics released by Safir on Friday
showing that from Feb. 4 to March 24, officers from the Street
Crime Unit made 291 arrests, down from 705 arrests during the same
period in 1998 and 775 in 1997. The number of stop-and-frisk
reports filled out by officers from the unit has also fallen
precipitously. The unit stopped and frisked 18,023 people in 1997
and 27,061 last year, the police said. Through March 14, though,
the unit has stopped and frisked 3,502 people, putting it on pace
to end the year with many fewer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The number of shooting incidents and shooting victims,
meanwhile, is creeping up in neighborhoods usually policed by the
Street Crime Unit, statistics show. There have been increases in
the 47th Precinct in the Eastchester section of the Bronx, the 46th
precinct in upper Manhattan, the 113th Precinct in Jamaica, Queens,
and the 110th Precinct in Elmhurst, Queens, among other areas.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent statistics show that through March 21, there
were 136 homicides in the city, up 8 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing meaningful conclusions from these statistics is
difficult, given the brief span of time involved, said Dr. Andrew
Karmen, a criminologist and sociologist at the John Jay College of
Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that on March 7, when homicides were reported to
be up by 5 percent during the first nine weeks of this year
compared with the same period last year, the police said that the
biggest jump was in homicides stemming from domestic disputes. At
that time, Safir said there was no way to know whether the citywide
increase was statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to really know what these shootings are about,''
Karmen said. ``If they're domestic shootings, that's something the
street crime unit can't do much about.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmen said that it appeared that the police might be trying to
lay the groundwork for an explanation for a broader increase in
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're seeing that crime is bottoming out,'' he said,
``and they're preparing for criticism by developing this
fingerpointing argument, that you the critics have ruined
everything and caused crime to go back up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Safir attributed the increase in shootings to a drop
in morale amid relentless media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speculate to the fact that the individuals in
Street Crime are concerned about taking enforcement action for
being criticized,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Hispanic officers dismissed that contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been telling the commissioner for years that street
crimes has been just searching people at will, all in minority
neighborhoods,'' said Detective Terrance Wansley, of 100 Blacks in
Law Enforcement. ``The reason the arrests are going down is that
all of a sudden, they have to play by the same rules as everyone
else. The Constitution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
