<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TMS-COMMENTARY-TE     03-29 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS' THIRD TRY REFRESHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ This time there wasn't an opening-lap
fender-fest, or a mind-numbing rain delay, or three dozen drivers
complaining about the state of the speedway's asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was simply a race, a race with a Texas-sized
ending. This time, the Terry Labontes, the Dale Jarretts and the
Ward Burtons of the world finally showed us what this fuss called
NASCAR was all about.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there have been better Winston Cup races. But none
heretofore in this neighborhood come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch duel between Labonte and Jarrett, on the heels of
Jeff Gordon crashing, of Burton pitting two laps early and of
whatever other histrionics the day could muster, made for an
afternoon at Texas Motor Speedway unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over, the winner, Labonte, did a most amazing
thing. He praised the day, instead of calling for the bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day for us,'' said the Corpus Christi native,
after his 21st career Winston Cup victory. ``To me, this is the
biggest race I've ever won. To be able to come down here to Texas
and win _ I was just thankful. I was just happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they complained about Turn 2. Too tight. And they bemoaned
the lack of a second groove to race in.
</P>
<P>
   Few drivers ever traveled two abreast. And passing opponents is
still somewhat of an Indiana Jones adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't spoil the show. Rather, let me suggest, the
track's contrariness enhanced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes they've made here were a big improvement,''
Labonte said. ``You saw people race real good today, compared to
what we saw the first two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The layout of the TMS track, pre-$3-million facelift, had
invited caution. But yesterday the field raced at 180 mph through
an incident-free first 30 laps and the NASCAR equivalent of a TV
timeout had to be called _ a mandatory caution flag.
</P>
<P>
   The next 200 miles produced mostly a long, single-file conga
line, but so be it. Lapped cars add obstacles. Pit stops under a
green flag add drama.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's misfortune hinted at the early indecision that was
taking place in the pits. The sport's biggest name had a right
front tire cut down and veered into the Turn 4 wall with a
molar-jarring thud. The intermittent tire problems prompted
Goodyear people to remind pit crews of the tires' recommended air
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in other words, this baby is growing up. Two years ago,
one of its larger ``problems'' was that the delivery men picked up
the grand piano but not the world-class pianist.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, with Gordon suddenly whisked from the spectacle, we
were reminded that the show goes on.
</P>
<P>
   There was Burton, whose No. 22 Caterpillar Pontiac looked like a
winner for 56 of the day's laps. His crew made the costly decision
to pit on Lap 214 under a green flag _ the yellow flag brought
things to a crawl just three laps later. Burton never could make up
the missing lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were as good as anybody out there,'' he said later. ``Were
we good enough to win the race? Shoot, yeah. We were racing winning
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to pick up the paper in the morning and think
we had a bad day. But we know that, except for one break, we had a
heck of a run. Give us one more shot. I think we'd win this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The show went on. There was Martin, who had laid down his own
personal driving groove into the TMS winner's circle. A tire
problem sent him, too, into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, it was Jarrett and the two Texas Labontes, Terry
and Bobby. Among them, there were a combined 45 Winston Cup
first-place trophies and 23 top-10 series finishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac pit, a mini-drama
played itself out. Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder in
practice at Darlington (S.C.) Raceway a little more than a week
ago, didn't know how long he was going to be able to drive.
Designated driver Matt Kenseth was ready to take over at any time.
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Labonte never relinquished the wheel. ``I've got
this big ol' coconut shell \Ra cast\S on my back, and it's pretty
sore right now,'' Bobby Labonte said. ``It just didn't lay right
with me for the most part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more or less giving out at the end. My neck was hurting
because we had changed some stuff in the seat, and it wasn't
normal. I've never been this uncomfortable before.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the threesome rolled on to the end, weaving and darting
past lapped cars, ignoring the gray clouds, not worried about the
track or who sang the Anthem, but focused only on the checkered
flag.
</P>
<P>
   It made for an engaging finish. It reminded us, in this third
try, that a NASCAR Winston Cup race is more than a week-long
gripe-fest and a four-hour traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there have been better stock car races. But not here.
</P>
<P>
   The change was more than refreshing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7628 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-FIX-LEBRETON-COLU     03-29 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FIX-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS' THIRD TRY REFRESHING
</HEADLINE>
 
( changes byline from Gonzalez to LeBreton) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ This time there wasn't an opening-lap
fender-fest, or a mind-numbing rain delay, or three dozen drivers
complaining about the state of the speedway's asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was simply a race, a race with a Texas-sized
ending. This time, the Terry Labontes, the Dale Jarretts and the
Ward Burtons of the world finally showed us what this fuss called
NASCAR was all about.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there have been better Winston Cup races. But none
heretofore in this neighborhood come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch duel between Labonte and Jarrett, on the heels of
Jeff Gordon crashing, of Burton pitting two laps early and of
whatever other histrionics the day could muster, made for an
afternoon at Texas Motor Speedway unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over, the winner, Labonte, did a most amazing
thing. He praised the day, instead of calling for the bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day for us,'' said the Corpus Christi native,
