</P>
<P>
   There was Burton, whose No. 22 Caterpillar Pontiac looked like a
winner for 56 of the day's laps. His crew made the costly decision
to pit on Lap 214 under a green flag _ the yellow flag brought
things to a crawl just three laps later. Burton never could make up
the missing lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were as good as anybody out there,'' he said later. ``Were
we good enough to win the race? Shoot, yeah. We were racing winning
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to pick up the paper in the morning and think
we had a bad day. But we know that, except for one break, we had a
heck of a run. Give us one more shot. I think we'd win this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The show went on. There was Martin, who had laid down his own
personal driving groove into the TMS winner's circle. A tire
problem sent him, too, into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, it was Jarrett and the two Texas Labontes, Terry
and Bobby. Among them, there were a combined 45 Winston Cup
first-place trophies and 23 top-10 series finishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac pit, a mini-drama
played itself out. Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder in
practice at Darlington (S.C.) Raceway a little more than a week
ago, didn't know how long he was going to be able to drive.
Designated driver Matt Kenseth was ready to take over at any time.
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Labonte never relinquished the wheel. ``I've got
this big ol' coconut shell \Ra cast\S on my back, and it's pretty
sore right now,'' Bobby Labonte said. ``It just didn't lay right
with me for the most part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more or less giving out at the end. My neck was hurting
because we had changed some stuff in the seat, and it wasn't
normal. I've never been this uncomfortable before.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the threesome rolled on to the end, weaving and darting
past lapped cars, ignoring the gray clouds, not worried about the
track or who sang the Anthem, but focused only on the checkered
flag.
</P>
<P>
   It made for an engaging finish. It reminded us, in this third
try, that a NASCAR Winston Cup race is more than a week-long
gripe-fest and a four-hour traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there have been better stock car races. But not here.
</P>
<P>
   The change was more than refreshing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
