<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7629 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TPC-HNS &LR;      03-29 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ After nearly a year of chasing Tiger
Woods for the honor of being the top-ranked golfer on the planet,
David Duval finally ascends to No. 1 in the world, then has to
fight to claim No. 1 in his family.
</P>
<P>
   Duval on Sunday won the tournament he grew up watching as a kid.
And even though he didn't win The Players Championship as much as
he survived it better than anybody else, Duval's greatness rubbed
off on his father, who was winning the Emerald Coast Classic on the
other end of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Duval's victory near Pensacola, Fla., meant the Duvals
became the first father-son combination to win PGA Tour events on
the same weekend. All that's left now is for David's mom to go out
and win on the LPGA circuit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a banner day for the younger Duval, whose perseverance
was crucial in shooting a 1-over-par 73 that gave him a 3-under 285
total for the tournament, two shots ahead of runner-up Scott Gump.
He secured the victory with a pinpoint wedge shot to the island
green on the par-3 17th. His eight-foot birdie putt gave him a
two-stroke margin for error on the treacherous 18th, which he
parred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful week,'' Duval said. ``I'm very proud of
myself for the way I played. I'm kind of anxious to watch the tape
of this tournament. It must have looked brutal out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass was a beast.
But after he was done, Duval knew he not only had beaten one of the
strongest fields ever assembled but also a course that was
heartless during a weekend when only one round below 70 was posted.
</P>
<P>
   His win, coupled with Woods finishing in a tie for 10th, meant
Duval will be elevated today to the top of the official World Golf
Rankings. Woods' reign of 41 consecutive weeks on top is over.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Duval also won his third tournament of the year.
It's the third consecutive year he has won at least three, a feat
that hadn't been done since Tom Watson won three or more each year
from 1977-82.
</P>
<P>
   As has been his custom, Duval deflected talk about being the
best player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be No. 1, but it's not a concern of mine,'' he
said. ``I'm the best this week. Maybe not next week. But this week,
yep.''
</P>
<P>
   That Duval was able to ascend to No. 1, pair with his father to
win on the same weekend and get his 10th career victory at The
Players was all the more sweet. Duval, 27, estimated he has been
coming to the tournament for at least 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born and raised in Jacksonville, and we moved out to the
beach when I was a junior in high school,'' Duval said. ``My dad
used to work in the scorer's tent on Saturdays. I always had a hat
for him, and all the players would sign it when they got done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know if I ever thought I was going to win here.
Obviously, I dreamed about it and thought about it. But I don't
know if I ever really thought it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened, he said, because of a combination of things. Duval
took three weeks off before the tournament and also practiced a lot
the week before the event. He knew he was playing well and putting
well. And when the course was set up so difficult, with hard, fast
greens and dicey rough, he knew he would be comfortable in the
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that there would be some bogeys,'' he said. ``And I
knew I would make a few birdies. I didn't make a double bogey all
week, which is a pretty good stat.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 players in the field avoided making at least one double
bogey or worse during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The key to victory for Duval, who started the day with a
one-shot lead over Skip Kendall and Phil Mickelson, came when he
hit a bunker shot into the cup on No. 9 for birdie. Earlier, it
looked like he might be headed for a much higher score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was swinging OK, but I was probably being a little tentative
up to then,'' he said. ``I had 100 yards to the front of the green,
and the ball was in the first cut of rough. I had to kind of go
under one tree and over another one. The gap was right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my caddie and told him there were two plays. We
could either go sideways and punch out or try to hit the gap and go
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided it was time to play golf. If I didn't make that
shot, I could have made double or triple bogey easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval hit the gap and put the ball in the pot bunker just to the
right of the green. His blast rolled into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a lot of players who live here can attest, I put in a lot
of time in the bunkers here, and it paid off,'' he said. ``I hit a
great little shot. That really kind of settled me down.''
</P>
<P>
   It also got him to 3 under par, which put him back in the lead,
a position he would not surrender the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hung in there,'' Duval said. ``I knew that if I could
make 18 pars, I'd win for sure, unless they soaked the greens
(which they didn't). I knew everybody was going to make some
bogeys. It's impossible to avoid them in these conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The only player who made a serious charge on the back nine was
Gump, who actually made a move by merely staying at 1 under par
over the last eight holes, overcoming a double bogey at the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Duval birdied the 12th but bogeyed the 14th and 15th,
coincidentally, after finding out in the 14th fairway that his
father had just won his tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's second bogey cut his lead to one shot over Gump. But he
clinched the tournament with his gutsy shot at the 17th.
</P>
</TEXT>
