<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOHAND-AZR &LR;      03-29 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOHAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD OF ADVERSITY: BOY RESILIENT DESPITE INJURY, HARDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ P.J. Constance's right arm ends just below his elbow,
chopped off piece by piece by doctors after he snapped his forearm
falling 20 feet into a stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lives in a tough neighborhood where gunshots ring out
regularly on weekend nights, it was a seemingly routine childhood
injury _ a broken arm _ that so barbarously interrupted his life.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a little boy who has grown up in adversity and knows
nothing else. So, he takes it well.
</P>
<P>
   He had been homeless, living in a shelter for a year and a half
before moving with his father, two sisters, brother and uncle into
his grandmother's humble but immaculate two-bedroom Phoenix
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Cater-cornered from that apartment near 16th Street and McDowell
Road is Resurrection Lutheran, the red-brick church where P.J. was
playing Nov. 29 when he fell into an outdoor stairwell. His friends
scattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard my arm crack,'' the 8-year-old says.
</P>
<P>
   An elder at the church heard crying and followed the sound to
P.J. A former emergency medical technician, he put a splint on
P.J.'s arm. Pastor Ted Bodjanac called 911.
</P>
<P>
   At Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center, doctors put a cast on
the arm. The radius and ulna had snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, his family took him back to the hospital. His
entire right hand had turned black, blue and red. He was
transferred to St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center, where the
state's unit for children's rehabilitative services is based.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Del Worthington, the orthopedic surgeon who heads pediatric
orthopedics there, knew the boy was in bad shape as soon as he saw
him. P.J. had somehow contracted streptococcus _ a dangerous,
flesh-eating bacteria that can lead to gangrene.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Worthington removed the tips of P.J.'s fingers.
Two days after that, he cut off more. And a little more.
</P>
<P>
   In all, P.J. had 13 surgeries. He left the hospital Christmas
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' P.J. whispers, ``my arm feels like it's still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gangrene is relatively common, Worthington says, especially
among diabetics and people whose blood vessels are damaged by
smoking. It is not so usual in children.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling whether P.J.'s arm _ or more of it _ could
have been saved if he had been brought back to the hospital sooner,
Worthington says. The bacterium is so aggressive that he has known
two people who died of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had waited any longer, it would have killed him,''
Worthington says.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. was just 6 when Karen Ryan met him at a homeless shelter in
Sunnyslope. She is his mentor through a program run by the Mental
Health Association of Arizona. She sees the boy at least once a
week, taking him to doctor's appointments, swimming and to
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look in P.J.'s face, you can see he's lived more
lives than a lot of adults,'' Ryan says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; P.J.'s mother hasn't been around in more than a year. His
parents' separation has been ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been up and down with his folks' problems,'' Ryan says.
``Now, he has this one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a heavy load for one little boy.
</P>
<P>
   But, already, his Uncle Freddie has taught him to wrestle, and
P.J. can take down his brother, 6-year-old Marc, with one arm.
</P>
<P>
   His father taught his once right-handed son to flick a yo-yo
with his left.
</P>
<P>
   And someone else in the neighborhood taught him to do one-handed
wheelies on his bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to be strong,'' P.J.'s uncle, Alfredo Hernandez,
22, says.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was hit by a car when he was almost 3, his right arm
crushed and put back together with metal pins and skin grafts. He
remembers being taunted as a kid and doesn't want that for his
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   This family has been through hard times, including the shooting
of one of P.J.'s uncles, who accidentally walked into a
neighborhood dispute. He was hit in the head but survived.
</P>
<P>
   P.J., too, will survive, says his maternal grandmother, Maria
Hernandez. She adds, ``He has a lot of family, and everyone loves
him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the doctor's office a month ago, P.J. had his pick of
prostheses. On the table were a hand-shaped piece of pink rubber
and a metallic hook.
</P>
<P>
   While Ryan and his father talked with the doctor, P.J. picked up
the metal hook and studied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will this hold onto the monkey bars?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably be a few more weeks before his arm is healed
enough to wear the prosthesis. Without it, P.J. already has learned
to write, dress and eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be better at cooking,'' his sister, Monica, 11,
says. ``He can still make Top Ramen, but he needs help for macaroni
and cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. missed a month of classes at Squaw Peak Elementary School,
but he is catching up with the help of a tutor. He also gets
counseling and physical therapy there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's OK if the kids at school call me handicapped
because I am,'' P.J. says.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely looks at his stump of an arm. He bathes each night
with it covered by a white cotton stocking. Afterward, his father
cleans and rebandages it.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.J. was real afraid of people not accepting him for what he
was,'' says his father, Paul Constance, 36. ``At the hospital, he
had gone so far to say he didn't want to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't talk like that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.J.'s known from the start that he didn't lose his hand,''
Constance says. ``He kept his life.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits that P.J.'s life _ all of the children's lives, really
_ have been turbulent with frequent moves, financial struggles and
spells away from their parents. But Constance says what happened to
P.J. has made him a better, more devoted father.
</P>
<P>
   It was Constance, Worthington says, who sat endlessly by his
son's bedside, taking a leave from his job at an automotive
air-conditioning business.
</P>
<P>
   These days, P.J. spends his afternoons riding his bike and
flying his kite. On Sundays, he goes to church. He likes pizza and
says that girls have cooties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I want to be when I grow up, but I can be
whatever I want,'' he says, climbing onto the hood of a parked car
and settling next to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The boy could need more surgery as he grows, though nothing
compared to what he has already been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you wanted to be an FBI agent,'' Constance says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' P.J. says, grabbing his little brother in a
headlock. ``An FBI agent.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
