<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILKO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TOUR BRINGING HER ALDED AUTHOR LESLIE MAR MON SILKO TO PHOENIX
AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The rain-washed air of Durango, Colo., was refreshing
for Tucson author Leslie Marmon Silko last week after months of
choking on Arizona dust left by a dry winter.
</P>
<P>
   Silko had driven to Colorado from Flagstaff, Ariz., for a book
signing of her long-awaited novel, ``Gardens in the Dunes.'' Just
days before, she had been at the Northern Arizona Book Festival
alongside famous authors from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   A full-blown book tour is under way. On April 6, Silko will
appear at Changing Hands Bookstore in Tempe. On April 10, she will
appear at the Arizona Book Festival in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is familiar,'' she said of Durango's St. Lewis College,
where she spoke to an audience that includes many of the young
Native Americans who make up much of the student body. It is her
third visit to the college since she began writing almost 30 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although Silko herself is Native American, reared on the Laguna
Pueblo Reservation in New Mexico, her readers are multicultural and
span a wide age range. Senior citizens, she said, especially enjoy
her ``heartfelt, serious stories.'' They flock to her readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have inquisitive minds,'' she said. ``They are really
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   To call Silko simply a Native American writer is to diminish an
author whose style and themes transcend genre fiction. ``Gardens in
the Dunes,'' her third novel, is being compared to Henry James in
its scope, though it does not replicate his ponderous style.
</P>
<P>
   Modern readers will applaud that. Silko's prose is lyrical and
richly detailed. ``Gardens'' is the story of two sisters, their
mother and their Grandma Fleet. It begins at the turn of the
century in the ancestral gardens of their tribe and then travels
from America to Europe _ such a Jamesian locale and time period.
</P>
<P>
   Although Silko's previous novel, 1991's highly praised ``Almanac
of the Dead,'' took a laborious 10 years to write, she spent a
relatively speedy four years writing ``Garden,'' resisting pressure
from her publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster, to write faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers want a book 18 months after the ink dries on the
contract,'' Silko said by phone from a Durango bed and breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Fans also were eagerly waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by her agent and her editor, Silko managed to hold the
howling wolves at bay long enough to write her novel the way she
wanted, crafting it so meticulously that she was still editing it
in her mind after publication.
</P>
<P>
   She's pleased with the results and with the reviews she has seen
so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different,'' she said. ``I like to do different things.
It goes so many places.''
</P>
<P>
   Silko's grandfather, Grandpa Hank, inspired the novel, she said.
As a boy, Grandpa had attended a White-run Indian school in
Riverside, Calif., which educated many Hopi and Pueblo Indian
children.
</P>
<P>
   Silko began to think about a student mentored by a teacher and
destined for greater things than normally is planned for Native
American children. In ``Gardens in the Dunes,'' such a child is a
girl named Indigo.
</P>
<P>
   Silko's own life and work were shaped by the Laguna Pueblo and a
teacher who sparked her creativity. The nurturing environment in
which she was reared fostered the love of storytelling that would
become her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surrounded, maybe even in the womb, with a community
that maintains itself and its continuity in the spoken word and a
delight in the narrative,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth grade provided an epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   Silko was transferred from a reservation school to a small,
private Anglo school in Albuquerque. Embarrassed to discover she
was behind the other students in math and science, she withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   But one day her teacher, a war bride from England who might have
empathized with the girl who was feeling like a foreigner, assigned
the class to use their spelling list to write a story.
</P>
<P>
   Silko came alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I escaped the unhappiness of school and being behind,'' she
said. ``That was the big breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   By eighth grade, she was writing poems and stories for Sister
Mary Agnes in a Catholic school where her Native American religion
was tolerated and her writing was encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from the University of New Mexico and taught
college English and fiction writing before returning to her
heritage of storytelling. In 1977, after publishing several short
stories and poems, she wrote her first novel, ``Ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics loved it. But the pigeonholing also had begun. The ``New
York Times''labeled her as the ``most accomplished Indian writer of
her generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Silko is not so much offended by labeling as she is weary of it
_ for herself and other marginalized writers _ gay writers, lesbian
writers, Black writers, women writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes the 21st century; maybe we could just talk about
`writers,' '' she said. ``We're such a multicultural society.
People on the street are far away from that (stereotyping).
Marketeers are behind the times.''
</P>
<P>
   She is perhaps ahead of her times and doesn't always like what
she sees. Silko, a human-rights activist in Tucson, said she
believes she is seeing an increase in infringement on civil
liberties by agents involved with the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, their tactics hit home. Silko and a friend were
pulled over in Tucson by officers who said their car had faulty
headlights. She said that when the officers saw that she was
Indian, several additional units were called, including a canine
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Silko's friend, an Anglo man, was taken away with his car,
leaving Silko alone on a dark Tucson road, she said. She found
assistance at a Circle K.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, Silko said, turned out to be federal Border Patrol
agents who keep an eye on southern Arizona near Mexico. The
incident, she said, is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Silko, 51, speaks out for all oppressed Americans, not just
Indians. Her heart aches for displaced war veterans who roam the
streets. She fights for the rights of women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But her greatest enmity is reserved for the folks who patrol the
U.S.-Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way the powerful and the rich trample the Earth and
all people, women and people of color, . . .'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know something Gestapo is going on in the
Southwest. The rights of Americans are being eroded.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
