<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL STARTS MONDAY FOR KITNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Jon Kitna is about to embark on a journey. His
ultimate destination is NFL stardom. His vehicle is the
quarterback-friendly offense of new Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   But Kitna must begin by taking small steps, starting with
Monday's first practice in the team's four-day quarterback camp.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon workout will provide the first opportunity for
Holmgren, offensive coordinator Mike Sherman and quarterbacks coach
Mike Sheppard to see Kitna operate the pass-oriented attack that
was made famous by Joe Montana and Steve Young in San Francisco and
helped Brett Favre achieve fame in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The six practices this week also will be Kitna's initial chance
to show he can take the potential that has prompted comparisons to
Favre and Young in their NFL infancy and parlay it into
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy:
</P>
<P>
   For Kitna, who has started six games in his first three seasons
with the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   For new backup Glenn Foley, who was obtained 10 days ago in a
trade with the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   For Holmgren or his top offensive assistants, who also find
themselves in new roles _ Sherman becoming the coordinator after
two seasons as Holmgren's tight end coach in Green Bay; Sheppard as
the quarterbacks coach after being the offensive coordinator in San
Diego last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand the offense, you have to be smart. It can be
overwhelming,'' Kitna said. ``I read Brett Favre's book, and he
said it took him two years to really get a grasp of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren continually refers to his offense as quarterback
friendly, but agrees that Favre's assessment is not only fair, it
is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not brain surgery. But you've got to concentrate, and
you've got to be pretty heads up because it puts a lot on the
quarterback's shoulders,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have broad shoulders, not to mention a reinforced
resolve and skin thick enough to endure a Green Bay winter.
</P>
<P>
   Running Holmgren's offense is not as easy as Favre made it look
in being named league MVP in 1995, 1996 and 1997, when he threw for
112 TDs and more than 12,000 yards in leading the Packers to
back-to-back Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Brett coming up after a big win and sitting next to
me on the plane,'' Holmgren said, recalling a road game in 1994.
``He was really excited. He said, `I got it. It hit. Things are
slower. I see things better.'''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren breaks into a smile just recounting the episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you get from Point A to that point,'' he quickly added,
``you're going to have your moments where you couldn't make the
decision fast enough because you don't have enough experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna is at Point A. That's A as in angst, but also anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time to learn the system. There will
be some little bumps along the way,'' he said, ``but I can't wait
to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   The best place to start understanding Holmgren's offense is at
the beginning. It is rooted in the 49ers attack he learned as an
assistant coach under Bill Walsh, but has branched out to include a
power running game; one-back, four-receiver sets; and a
preponderance of screen passes.
</P>
<P>
   The pass patterns Holmgren uses are not revolutionary. The
combinations in which he uses them and the formations from which he
deploys them are.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren says it takes three things to play quarterback in his
system:
</P>
<P>
   -- Accuracy. Holmgren prefers a short pass to a running play
because it is easier to gain 6 yards through the air than on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, not even Barry Sanders, averages 6 yards a carry,''
said Holmgren, aware that Denver's Terrell Davis and San
Francisco's Garrison Hearst led the league last year by averaging
5.1 yards per carry, both in offenses similar to his.
</P>
<P>
   ``So a lot of times a short pass will be substituted for another
running play. It's easier,'' he said. ``But you have to have the
quarterback. You've got to have the guy so he's making good
decisions most of the time, and he's pretty accurate. If you don't
have that, then you might as well run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Agility. Not that all-out scrambling ability of Young, but
the necessary foot movement to avoid the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when the play breaks down, you have to be able to make
plays,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Acceptance. Call this one ``Coach knows best,'' even when it
might not look that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be willing to accept and believe what you're
telling them, even if it's not real logical in the beginning,''
Holmgren said. ``If I say this works, this will work. But even
Steve and Brett would look at me in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense has become synonymous with spawning great
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the guys who have succeeded in the offense,'' Kitna
said. ``Obviously you have to have tools. Those guys have tools.
But I tend to think I have a lot of those traits, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
