<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PISTONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS LAY PATCH ON PEP-LESS SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ If the Sonics were a soap opera _ and this
has been one dramatic season _ an apt show title could be the ``As
the Sonics Turn.''
</P>
<P>
   One day they are an interesting and lively bunch, the next they
are a dull flashback that makes you want to turn the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at the Palace of Auburn Hills, the Sonics were tuned out
before NBC viewers barely could tune in the nationally broadcast
game against the Detroit Pistons. After a disturbing 104-87 loss,
Sonics coach Paul Westphal did not mince words in describing his
team's fourth loss in six games. To Westphal, the Sonics were ``The
Old and the Slumberous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sluggish. We looked old and tired and slow. And the
Pistons took advantage of it,'' Westphal said. ``They did whatever
they wanted to in the first half, and the game was pretty much
over.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not how the Sonics wanted to start their toughest
stretch of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of bringing fire and enthusiasm into the first of five
road games in six nights, the Sonics brought only their luggage
into Detroit. From the start, the team looked weary, as though it
was at the end of this trip.
</P>
<P>
   But they must try to rebound against Dallas tonight before
taking on San Antonio Tuesday, Denver on Thursday and Portland on
Friday. The Sonics now have lost nine of the 12 games they've
played on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have individuals step up,'' Dale Ellis said. ``We
can't rely on Gary (Payton) to get it done for us every night. We
have to be more consistent as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished with 10 points and seven assists in 32 minutes.
Detlef Schrempf shared a team-high 12 points with rookie Jelani
McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Sonics were doomed by a poor first quarter. They
fell behind 28-8 in the first 10 minutes and trailed by 20 points
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   By the 4:29 mark in the third quarter, the Sonics were down 22
points, and Westphal went with his Sonic 2000 team. McCoy, Drew
Barry, Aaron Williams, Rashard Lewis and John Crotty played the
entire fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only bright spot was that our young guys played in the
fourth quarter and did a nice job. They played with some energy,''
Westphal said. `` ... We'll keep looking for something that works,
that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other good that came out of the loss was that the
Sonics managed to rest their top seven players. Payton played the
most minutes of any starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they'll be ready to play (at Dallas tonight),''
Westphal said. ``... We have too many (slow starts) that's for
sure. We have to ask ourselves if we're not good enough. Maybe
we're not good enough. Maybe that's the reason we're having slow
starts. There's no reason to not be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, who never led, missed 13 of their first 17 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, meanwhile, benefited from Lindsey Hunter's hot hand
early. Hunter, who scored a game-high 20 points, made his first six
shots and finished with 13 points in the opening quarter. He mostly
picked apart the Sonics' trapping defense, which they use more with
the smaller lineup now that Vin Baker is sidelined with a torn
ligament in his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   With Baker out, Payton must carry more of an offensive load. But
the Pistons took away Payton's post-up opportunities. They also
outran the Sonics up and down the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored a lot of easy baskets on us by making simple
basketball plays,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   What Ellis referred to were the Pistons screening for each
other, cutting through the lane and making extra passes. The Sonics
were not as patient when they had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we stop fighting ourselves we'll be all right,'' center
Olden Polynice said. ``We're not playing together. We're not
working as a unit, and it frustrates everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do that at home. When we come on the road, we fight
each other. We're a better team than that. We should know how to
play together. We've got to play to each other's strengths, but we
bring each other's weaknesses out.''
</P>
<P>
   The stress of Sunday's game got to Payton just before halftime
when he was whistled for a technical foul. After being charged with
an obvious offensive foul, Payton unleashed a tirade at referee
Jess Kersey.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit went ahead 52-30 when Jerry Stackhouse made the free
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who has refused to talk to reporters after games for the
past several weeks, left again without comment.
</P>
<P>
   It is to the point, though, where there is little else to say.
The questions are the same. The answers seem simple enough. But the
Sonics are still a 1,000-piece puzzle spread about the court every
other night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of the mysteries of basketball,'' Polynice said.
``We've tried so many things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
