<HEADER>
A7642 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     03-29 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN BRAWLGAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A team disoriented by rapid change, distraught by a
spate of losses and in desperate search of an identity found one at
last Sunday. The Lakers became the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   All the elements of an Eastern Conference playoffs rumble
between the New York Knicks and the Heat were on display at the
Forum. And the Lakers relished playing the role of bruising
provocateur.
</P>
<P>
   Elbows and various limbs flew in all directions beneath the
baskets. Bodies were slammed. A face was mashed. A ball became a
projectile. Two near-brawls erupted. Ejections and technical fouls
were handed out in batches, like cheap door prizes.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers, copping their best East Coast 'tude, muscled up,
stayed cool and pulled out a bruising 99-91 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big ballgame, it was a tough ballgame, and I like the
aggression that our guys played with,'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a two-game losing skid figured to take a gut check or
two. The Knicks provided the Lakers with a few dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing dealt Derek Fisher an elbow and a bruised
cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Thomas wrapped up Dennis Rodman's head and threw him to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal jammed a thunderous dunk over Chris Dudley,
landed on him, then shoved him into a row of photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley tossed a changeup halfway down the court, the ball
harmlessly dinking O'Neal's leg.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell . . . well, he didn't hurt anyone unless you
count the team-high 25 points he scored against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The final mayhem tally: 51 fouls, five technicals, one type-two
flagrant, and ejections for Thomas in the third quarter and Dudley
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the Lakers baited and banged but managed to
avoid self-destructing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a lot of character,'' Kobe Bryant said, ``because
there's been a lot of quote-unquote distractions going around this
week. Coming out here and playing a smart basketball game, playing
a physical basketball game, and still keeping our cool and winning,
I think it shows a lot of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Glen Rice aptly put it: ``We were able to handle what they
were dishing out, and dish it out ourselves. We weren't going to
back down, and we stepped up to the challenge and got the win.''
</P>
<P>
   They did so _ and avoided their first three-game home losing
streak in five years _ with the kind of consistent aggression on
defense and movement on offense that Rambis has been pushing.
</P>
<P>
   When it all came together, the results were anything but
aesthetic. Just effective. They shot 48.6 percent and committed
just 12 turnovers. They disrupted New York with five blocked shots
and eight steals, held Ewing to 9-of-25 shooting and held the
Knicks to 15 points in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And their three big guns all fired _ Bryant delivering a
game-high 29 points, complemented by 21 from O'Neal and 19 from
Rice, who's finding his touch and his place in the crowded Lakers
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as of lately, I've been able to get into it a little
bit more,'' said Rice, who scored 11 points in a crucial
second-quarter run that expanded the Lakers' lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had scored 14 in the first quarter, but the Lakers still
trailed by six heading into the second period. But Rice and Rick
Fox (eight points) paced a surge that gave the Lakers as much as a
14-point lead in the second quarter, and the Knicks didn't threaten
again until late in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A Sprewell 3-pointer cut the gap to 78-75, but the Knicks came
unglued after that, as O'Neal slammed over Dudley, landed on him
like a stunt cowboy on a steed, then tossed him aside. O'Neal only
drew a technical foul, but Dudley was ejected after throwing the
ball. Rice scored three straight points and Derek Harper hit
back-to-back 3-pointers, and the Knicks were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always get up for the big teams, so I'm not surprised,''
O'Neal said. ``We matched their intensity and we played well. We
knew we needed this one today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
