<HEADLINE>
MONAHAN TO START SEASON AT CLASS AAA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ A sloppy day-night doubleheader was three outs
from expiring Friday, and there was Shane Monahan, fouling off
fastball after fastball, shouting at himself when he missed his
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Monahan got a breaking ball from Colorado's Jerry
Dipoto and rapped it through the right side for his fourth hit of
the game. He came around to score, pumping his fists as he charged
across the plate to send the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Monahan took his .326 spring average and cleaned out his
locker. He was optioned to Class AAA Tacoma, where he will play
regularly. Monahan, whose 43 at-bats this spring were more than
twice last spring's total, said he will take this demotion better
than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I went down and had a crummy year in Triple-A
because I didn't want to be there,'' Monahan said. ``I felt like I
didn't really get a shot. But that was the wrong attitude to have.
I'm a year older, and you look back at last year and say, `God,
that was a wasted year until I got to the big leagues.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to cry about it. I'll go to Triple-A and handle
my business. Whatever happens, happens. I'm coming down full of
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Monahan, who hit .242 after his midseason call-up to Seattle
last year, was a long shot to make the team after the M's acquired
veteran outfielders Butch Huskey, John Mabry and Matt Mieske. But
barring any trades, two young outfielders will survive: Charles
Gipson and Raul Ibanez.
</P>
<P>
   Those players fill more specific needs than Monahan _ Gipson as
a backup center fielder and shortstop with speed; Ibanez, who is
out of options, as a third catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like him,'' manager Lou Piniella said of Monahan. ``But
it's a numbers game with him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' spring roster stands at 33, and Piniella expects
it to be finalized on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA'S HOT: Right-hander Freddy Garcia earned his spot in the
rotation a week ago, and he's done nothing to make Piniella
second-guess himself. Garcia improved to 4-0 and lowered his earned
run average to 2.03 in Sunday's 4-2 win over the San Diego Padres.
Garcia struck out eight and allowed three hits in six shutout
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as good a pitched game as I've seen this spring,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's fastball hit 96 mph, but the Mariners knew he threw
hard. They've been hoping to see him use his changeup more
effectively, and Sunday he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more comfortable (with the pitch),'' Garcia said. ``When I
get behind in the count, I can throw the changeup for strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   FASSERO LOOKS SAFE: Although it seems unlikely the Mariners will
sign left-hander Jeff Fassero to a contract extension before
opening day, it's not because of his performance on Friday, when he
allowed 11 earned runs in 22/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're worried about him,'' said Lee Pelekoudas,
M's vice president for baseball administration. ``He'll be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets have shown interest in trading for Fassero,
but the Mariners have shown no indications of shopping their
opening-day starter.
</P>
<P>
   BULLPEN QUANDARY: Piniella said he's more concerned with the
bullpen void left by Mark Leiter than he is about who will be his
fifth starter. He stopped short, however, of saying that Leiter's
injury makes Bobby Ayala more valuable to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who figured to be a setup reliever, will start the
season on the 15-day disabled list with shoulder tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the experience,'' Piniella said of Ayala, who allowed
his first spring homer Sunday. ``He's pitched in that role before.
At the same time, it's a complicated situation for us, because we
basically had it mapped out. We've got to fill that spot, and we're
not exactly sure where that piece is coming from. It's here, it's
just a question of how to juggle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-handers Rafael Carmona and Eric Weaver are still in camp,
but Brett Hinchliffe is the favorite to assume Leiter's role.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Right-hander Bill Swift, who still has an
outside chance to make the M's rotation, struck out 11 and walked
none over five innings in a minor league game Sunday. Pitching
coach Stan Williams said Swift ``looked like the old Billy.'' Swift
could make the rotation if Ken Cloude does not improve and
Hinchliffe works in relief. ... Roger Jongewaard, M's vice
president for scouting and player development, was in attendance
when the Baltimore Orioles played the Cuban national team
yesterday. ... What's the going rate on a souvenir T-shirt of a
non-roster outfielder batting .059? Thirty dollars. Garth Brooks,
whose No. 77 mock jersey is the hottest-selling item at Peoria
Stadium, struck out against Greg McCarthy to end yesterday's game.
The country singer is now 1-for-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
