<HEADLINE>
COUCH POTATOES PULL IN HISTORY LESSON ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Saturday was yard day. Sunday was vegetable day.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not referring to the Sonic offense.
</P>
<P>
   For a sports follower, history came in torrents out of the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena Williams became the first sisters to play for a
pro tennis tournament title in 115 years. David and Bob Duval
became the first father and son to win PGA and Senior PGA tourneys
on the same day. And a major league team played a baseball game in
Cuba for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   If you foolishly made Sunday yard day, you were all wet on
several counts. Here's some of what was missed, as well as some
rain for others' parades:
</P>
<P>
   -- The all-Williams, all-day matchup at the Lipton Championships
in Key Biscayne, Fla., was a splendid stunner on multiple fronts:
Family, skill, athleticism, race, freshness, tautness, beads.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup's potential had been possible for awhile, but Serena
had to beat three top-10 opponents to get to her sister, 15 months
her senior. Venus and Serena have knocked tennis upon its Wimbledon
whites in ways unseen since McEnroe, Connors, Navratilova and Evert
consumed newsprint by the forest.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Orioles nearly endured an exploding Cuban cigar before
beating their hosts 3-2 in 11 innings, once again making the world
safe for democracy and the American way. The success of the
breakthrough sports contest has inspired the NBA. Commissioner
David Stern is expected to send an NBA team to play at the Los
Angeles Sports Arena, which has not seen professional basketball in
nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sitting side by side at the game in Havana were Fidel Castro,
the dictator who hijacked a nation in 1959, and baseball
commissioner Bud Selig, the used-car salesman who hijacked the
Seattle Pilots in 1970. Have there ever been two men who have
ascended so dubiously, accomplished so little, and stayed in power
so long?
</P>
<P>
   -- If there was debate about the world's hottest athlete, David
Duval chilled it when he won the Players Championship in Ponte
Vedra Beach, Fla. _ the 10th win in his last 33 tourney
appearances. Just to make sure it wasn't easy, the tourney had 49
of the world's 50 highest-ranked golfers, only two of whom finished
under par. The field Sunday put 18 balls in the water that
surrounds the diabolical island green of No.17, making the movie
``Tin Cup'' come to life for the whole PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   When Duval's father, Bob, a few hours earlier won the Senior
Tour event in Milton, Fla., the Duvals drained whatever was left
over in the national well of sports cuteness after the Williams
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   -- From the poignant to the pathetic: Mariner Ken Cloude's
spring-training flop puts him on the verge of winning the club's
Fleming/Wolcott Award for the annual squandering of youthful
pitching promise. Still intact is Mark Langston's claim to be the
Mariners' last farm-developed pitcher who was a major contributor
in Seattle. For kids who don't remember Langston, he pitched
shortly after Cy Young, and would be a nice fit for the Mariner
roster sometime this season. It would give the Mariners the oldest
staff since the one Moses took up the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   -- Longtime P-I baseball scribe Jim Street leaves shortly to
become public relations director for USA Baseball, the national
federation for the U.S. Olympic team and international amateur
teams. Not only does the job include baseball, but international
travel and year-round residence at federation headquarters in
Tucson, Ariz. It's a great job for a great guy, and here's the best
part: Street has volunteered to set up all future tee times and
pick up all bar tabs for Seattle-area rainbirds visiting spring
training. (Might as well put him on the spot. What's he going to
do: Claim his old newspaper misquoted him?)
</P>
<P>
   -- To all the column correspondents who skewered me for my
criticism of Bob Bender's coaching in Washington's NCAA tourney
loss to Miami of Ohio: I said he coached a bad game, I didn't say
he was a bad coach. Lots of coaches can look bad in the tourney.
I'm certain that next time, Bender will defend a Wally
Szczerbiak-type player as well as I can spell him.
</P>
<P>
   What isn't as certain is whether Bender can restore the UW's
reputation as a place for state high school stars. Since the forced
resignation of Marv Harshman, the Huskies haven't recovered the
in-state edge.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga star forward Casey Calvary, of Tacoma's Bellarmine, was
a steady attendee of the Husky basketball camps, yet was overlooked
in recruiting. This season, Grant Leep of Mount Vernon wasted his
freshman year with a five-minute average when he could have
redshirted. Mistakes like these leave indelible impressions on high
school coaches.
</P>
<P>
   -- Did the Sonics finish a five-games-in-six-days road trip
Sunday, or start one? By the looks of the 23-6 lead the Pistons
took in the opening minutes in Detroit, the Sonics have the guts of
Barney Fife and the leadership of Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dismay over the disclosure that new Husky football coach Rick
Neuheisel was seen partying at the L.A. home of a convicted mobster
not only is unfounded, the act should be seen as encouraging. Given
how severely the Huskies have been out-recruited in recent years,
UW fans should be heartened that Neuheisel may be getting tips from
an expert, Dominick ``Donny Shacks'' Montemanaro, on how to make
offers that can't be refused.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
