<HEADLINE>
IN STREET FIGHT, RODMAN'S YOUR MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ This is why the Lakers need Dennis Rodman, warts and
all.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman got under the New York Knicks' skin like an ingrown hair
on Sunday afternoon. He left a rash of raw and irritated Knicks
bodies in his furrow while staying admirably above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, with Rodman showing them the way to improved
physical phatness, prevailed 99-91 in front of a sellout Forum
crowd and a national television audience in the kind of game that
has given the team fits in the past. Or had you conveniently
forgotten those two really ugly marks on last year's record, 83-106
at Miami and 89-101 at New York?
</P>
<P>
   When they put the floor down for this one, the Forum workers
should have kept the hockey penalty boxes. Knicks center Patrick
Ewing deserved two minutes for elbowing Lakers point guard Derek
Fisher midway through the second quarter and Chris Dudley did
receive the hoops equivalent of a game misconduct midway through
the fourth for throwing the basketball at Lakers center Shaquille
O'Neal's backside after O'Neal dropped Dudley like a bath towel on
his way to a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of it occurred in the waning seconds of the third when
the Knicks' Kurt Thomas, in a pretty good goon impression,
clotheslined Rodman underneath the Knicks' basket (and then tried
to undress him) after he and Rodman had scuffled over a rebound of
a Ewing miss.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas won that battle but lost the war, his cool having
completely deserted him by that point. He made the follow to cut
the Lakers' lead to 71-64 and as part of his follow-through flung
Rodman to the ground and tried vigorously to separate the Lakers
forward from his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   For a split second it looked like a bench-clearing brawl might
ensue. O'Neal would later admit he thought about being the third
man in, but Rodman wasn't retaliating so O'Neal figured neither
should he.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis did a pretty good job of not reacting,'' O'Neal said.
``I don't know if I would have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy also showed more restraint than he
has in the past, somehow stopping himself from flinging himself
onto the court in protest and clinging on to Rodman like one of
those feather boas the flamboyant Lakers forward is fond of
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Van Gundy wasn't fuming. Afterward, he called
Rodman a ``dirty'' player. Which begs the question, what does that
make Thomas, downright filthy?
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazes me,'' Van Gundy groused, ``that (Dennis) is
always the one involved, but it's always the other players that get
picked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, sometimes you're the bruise and sometimes you're the fist.
As Rodman later reasoned: ``It's a game of wits. You just have to
be a lot smarter and a lot more cunning.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear early on that the recalcitrant Rodman had decided
to test the patience of a team other than the Lakers for a change.
Poor Patrick. For a player, Ewing looked like a pretty good union
president by the time Rodman and O'Neal were through with him.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, whose leadership during the protracted lockout was
harshly critiqued by O'Neal last week, missed 14 of his final 19
shots, fouling out in the final minute with 20 points. He had 13
rebounds, but he got six of his 12 defensive boards in the first
quarter, leaving the Lakers plenty of time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they did, worked. O'Neal appeared to raise his
defensive intensity a notch in the second quarter, coming out to
the high post to meet him. And Rodman and Glen Rice did a nice job
of boxing out.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Ewing had zero rebounds and zero points in the
second quarter as the Lakers turned a six-point deficit into a
14-point lead in a matter of 10 minutes. The Knicks chipped away at
the advantage, closing to 50-42 at the half. The closest they came
to the Lakers after that was 78-75 on a Latrell Sprewell 3-pointer
with 6:39 remaining in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans could have been forgiven for worrying that the other
shoe was about to drop. Instead, O'Neal dropped a definitive dunk
on Dudley and Dudley retaliated with the half-court throw that
turned out to be the stake in his team's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw it, I got frustrated, I threw the ball,'' Dudley said.
``It was a physical game and it got a little out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   As the game got wilder and weirder, Rodman got more repressed.
Go figure. He drew fouls twice in the closing two-and-a-half
minutes and sedately sank all four attempts to keep the Knicks at
bay. He finished with seven points and 12 rebounds, making everyone
forget his no-show at practice the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's time to hit the big shot, the big free throw, I'm
always there,'' he said. ``I am always ready.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
