<HEADLINE>
BRAND IS THE NAME OF DUKE'S GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ With Elton Brand, you measure the size of
the hands as well as the heart. The frame already is apparent; it's
three-car-garage wide.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as Michigan State discovered, the frame moves and
catches, collecting passes, points and rebounds. The national
player of the year is expected to lead Duke to the national
championship Monday night when the Blue Devils take on the
Connecticut Huskies at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Brand brought out more curiosity seekers than usual
after decimating Michigan State in one of Saturday's Final Four
semifinal games. The Spartans entered the game as supposed
scrappers who scratch, claw and like to get dirty. Essentially,
Brand rubbed their noses in it with 18 points and 15 rebounds,
carrying Duke to a 68-62 victory.
</P>
<P>
   If they are hoping for anything different, the Huskies won't
experience a Brand new ballgame _ it will be the same as always,
this unstoppable wall using his muscular body, active feet and soft
hands to floor his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut plans to hamper him with foul-prone Jake Voskuhl and
a variety of double-teams sent from different directions. That's
exactly what Brand expects and encourages.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see a man-to-man match-up, my eyes light up,'' Brand
said. ``But sometimes a double-team puts a team at a disadvantage.
I don't know if it's a good strategy or not. I just have to adjust
and play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   If doubled, Brand plans to kick the ball out to the perimeter,
where Trajan Langdon and William Avery await for open 3-point
shots.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun said: ``You have to pick your
poison.'' Aside from that one aberration in Alaska when the Blue
Devils lost to Cincinnati in December, all options are fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation Sunday was that since Voskuhl is 6-foot-11 and 245
pounds, he might be better equipped to handle the 6-8, 260-pound
Brand. But Voskuhl is like ex-Sonic Jim McIlvaine in that neither
can avoid contact or a referee's whistle and usually end up on the
bench. Nonetheless, this is Connecticut's best shot even though
Voskuhl sounded helpless Sunday when asked about Brand's patented
post-up move, simultaneously lowering the shoulder and the boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to really try to bully people with that move,''
Voskuhl said. ``No one's seemed to stop it yet. It's hard to defend
something like that. You could try to take a charge, but with his
footwork and control of his body, you can't really do that. If you
fall down, he stops and shoots a layup.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand hopes to see the tall blond in front of him Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tougher when someone's that big,'' he said.
``But I'll use my quickness and dribbling to go around him.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be Brand's final game at Duke. The sophomore was
asked Sunday about the possibility of playing in the NBA next year
and said he had not yet made a decision. If he leaves early, Brand
would be the first Duke player to turn pro before using up his
college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   As an NBA player, he will be compared to Charles Barkley. Listed
at 6-8, he is more like 6-6. He plays with ferocity. He looks angry
and focused on the court, but is affable elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   During his interview with the media Sunday, Brand spoke through
a constant smile. He is an articulate young man who grew up in
Peekskill, N.Y., building body mass and confidence while developing
a reputation for toughness.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first games as a freshman in high school, Brand
took an elbow to the head that knocked a tooth into the roof of his
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know where it was,'' he said. ``I was bleeding when I
came over to the bench. Then I found it and straightened it out.
They wanted to take me to the dentist, but I wouldn't let them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand returned to the game, grabbed a few more rebounds and
dislodged the opponent with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at Duke, Brand fractured a bone in his left foot. He
was supposed to be out for four months. Brand returned in eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Resilient, he is also unusual. Besides the nimble manner for a
player his size, Brand has hands that match the size of the
foundation. From the base of his palm to the end of his middle
finger, Brand's hand is 10 inches long, a quarter-inch longer than
Michael Jordan's. A Raleigh, N.C., surgeon says the average male's
hand is 7{ inches long. Brand's hands are like a first baseman's
mitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help me getting rebounds, in trying to get steals and in
blocking shots,'' Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has given him some special gifts,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski. ``He has a huge body, but he's very much finesse. He
has huge hands, he has long arms.''
</P>
<P>
   He has given the Huskies a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to stick our chests out there and let him know
we're not going to be moved,'' said forward Kevin Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has ever come up against anyone as big and quick as
he is, Brand said: ``I don't think so ... I'm getting a little
cocky right there.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cameron Indoor Stadium, Duke fans hold up signs that say:
``Branded for Life,'' and you get the feeling that Connecticut
could become fodder for slaughter Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
