<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     03-29 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS AFFAIR NOT TO REMEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano was all but tarred and
feathered for attacking the way Chicago counter-attacked its way to
an MLS championship last season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he would love to bite his tongue and stay away from
this topic _ he can't. Not after Sunday's 1-0 shootout victory over
the Burn after the two teams failed to score in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones, Clint Mathis and Greg Vanney provided enough scoring
punch in the shootout to give L.A. a 3-2 edge and improve to 2-0 _
but it was hardly a positive result considering the Galaxy lost
four valuable points by failing to win in regulation in its first
two games at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The boring showing by both teams raised a philosophical debate
amongst the two coaches afterward. Of course, both Zambrano and
Dallas' Dave Dir claimed the other was responsible for most of the
boos from the 27,034 in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attacking Dallas directly the way he did Chicago,
Zambrano chose a more careful approach this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at games in this league and I can tell you that
defending is the priority and that's a fact,'' Zambrano said. ``I
think it's different in years past when teams played open soccer.
But now most of them are falling back and defending. That's just
the way it is, unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   There were hardly any chances on either side. The Galaxy managed
only two shots on goal to the Burn's one, prompting Zambrano to
admit the game lacked character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it boring? Without a doubt,'' Zambrano said. ``If you
examine the game of soccer, the attack-minded philosophy should
prevail for the game to be attractive. If you have a
defensive-minded mentality, it won't be pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Dir, however, claimed the Galaxy plays a bigger
counter-attacking role than Zambrano admits. And despite the fact
L.A. shattered every scoring record imaginable last season, Dir
said the Galaxy does as much counter-attacking as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that whenever Octavio loses he talks about the same
thing,'' Dir said. ``When he wins he's fine with packing it in and
counter-attacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not God's gift to soccer, but they (the Galaxy) pack it in
more than anybody. They make every attempt to win the ball behind
you when your player is in a good position. They use a lot of
elbows and they love to spring their guys with speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, on the other hand, like to play possession, knock the ball
around and create good chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones gave his own objective look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is always attractive as long as you're winning,'' he
said. ``If you play attractive as (heck) and lose all your games,
you're going to have zero fans out there. That's just the way it
is. It's a catch-22.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
