<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-REBOUND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR GIVES TMS RESOUNDING THUMBS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After a relatively incident-free and
complaint-free racing weekend, NASCAR official Mike Helton said
Texas Motor Speedway has passed its final exam.
</P>
<P>
   Helton said TMS has fixed the water seepage problem that plagued
the racetrack a year ago. But minor concerns remain about a
``transition'' in the pavement in Turn 2 and traffic flow have been
brought to his attention, Helton said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not as much complaining this year about the
racetrack,'' said Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief
operating officer. ``The issue where the water was seeping up
through the track, all indications are that's been corrected. We
still have issues with traffic in Texas, and Atlanta, for that
matter. But the specific issues addressed last year, they
\Rmanagement\S have worked on and have gotten much closer to the
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a weekend plagued by water seepage in Turn 1 and
chunking pavement in Turn 4 last April, NASCAR president Bill
France Jr., informed TMS developer Bruton Smith that he wanted the
glitches repaired before the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series visited
for a night race in June.
</P>
<P>
   Smith responded with a $3 million renovation that included
installation of an elaborate drainage system, reconfiguring of the
entrance into Turn 1 and the exit of Turn 4 and a complete
repaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Motor Speedway is a grand facility, by even Texas
standards,'' said Helton, who assumed day-to-day operations of
NASCAR from France in February. ``The problem we had here last year
was water coming from underneath up. The problem we got this year
is water coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to Saturday's rain-shortened Coca-Cola 300
Busch Grand National race. Showers also washed out the final
Winston Cup ``Happy Hour'' practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In regards to the transitions in Turn 4 and those things the
drivers commented about the first couple of years, the drivers are
a bit more comfortable now,'' Helton said. ``They talk about a
`transition' that might now exist in Turn 2. It might be a bump or
it might be from the fix the track went through last year _ having
left a little bit of a difference from the Turn 2 that existed the
first two years. We don't necessarily see that as a big issue,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, who finished second in yesterday's race, said the
track was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe track\S allows us to race hard, it allowed us to race
side-by-side at times,'' Jarrett said. ``They did improve the
track. It was much better and it will continue to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton said he also heard an earful about traffic, specifically
about a problem with crew members trying to exit the track at the
end of their work day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday night, for example, it took an hour and a half to get
out of the infield,'' Helton said. ``Traffic is an issue, and has
to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for TMS getting its much-desired second Winston Cup date,
Helton maintained the posture that NASCAR is looking to expand into
new markets before adding race dates to existing markets.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, Eddie Gossage, TMS vice-president
and general manager said this was a positive step for the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been better, but this was definitely a turning
point for Texas Motor Speedway,'' Gossage said. ``Race-wise, it
looked like a typical Winston Cup race, which is what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   As for getting a second date, Gossage added: ``Nothing was
discussed \Rtoday\S about the second date. Do we go knocking on the
door tomorrow for a second date? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage also said TMS would make a ``concerted effort'' to land
a second Busch Grand National race. Saturday's Coca-Cola 300 drew
an estimated 115,000 fans, the largest crowd ever for a Busch
race.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
