<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIENFUEGOS' L.A. FINALE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- If you listen to his agent, Corey Clemetson,
Sunday's 1-0 shootout victory over Dallas may have been the last
game for midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos -- at least in a
Los Angeles uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, 31, agreed last week to end his holdout with Major
League Soccer following a friendly breakfast with MLS commissioner
Doug Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos has been at odds with the league over his contract
and told Logan last Saturday he would give the league 10 days to
make a reasonable offer. With Wednesday's target date approaching,
Clemetson said Cienfuegos could be on his way to El Salvador if
nothing changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me on Friday he would like to have Doug Logan promise
to be out here at the end of negotiations if thing's aren't going
well. At this point, they aren't going that well,'' said Clemetson.
``We are going to do what we can but as far as I know the deadline
Wednesday still stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson says the two sides are no closer than they were a week
ago, although some progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialogue has been good and cordial but that's about it,''
Clemetson said. ``We haven't had much movement at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Greg Vanney scored the deciding goal in Saturday's 3-2
shootout victory. He has had his share of good and bad luck as the
team's fifth kicker.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Western Conference final against Chicago,
however, it was Vanney who missed L.A.'s final attempt, allowing
the Fire to reach the MLS championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice when you win and I'm not afraid of going
fifth. I think it's an advantage despite the pressure,'' said
Vanney. ``When you go fifth you get to see what their goalkeeper
does in the earlier rounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
