<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-KINGS-HNS     03-29 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-KINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Having learned Kings star Chris Webber would
be out with the flu Sunday, Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich fretted
that it was the worst news for his team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kings would rally behind the loss of their leader. Someone
would have a career night. The Rockets, playing their fourth game
in five nights, could easily be suckered.
</P>
<P>
   He was right, too. But the Rockets answered in a way he never
would have dared consider. The Rockets rallied around the loss of
their own star power forward, surged past the Kings and then
brought Charles Barkley back to put away their eighth consecutive
win with a 107-93 knockout of the Kings at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles was suffering,'' Rockets forward Scottie Pippen said.
``But we really wanted to come out and maintain what we've been
building the last week and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last week and a half, the Rockets have appeared
unbeatable, rallying from 19 points down in the second half to beat
the Warriors on Saturday, then a night later whipping the Kings
with Barkley playing just 10 second-half minutes in obvious back
pain.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Rockets left Houston as the NBA's hottest team, a
weekend in Northern California more than validated that streak: It
returned the Rockets to the ranks of the league's power teams. With
an eight-game winning streak and victories in 11 of their past 12,
the Rockets get a day off in Los Angeles to consider their sudden
place in the NBA standings. Just three weeks after they were sixth
in the Western Conference, they wake this morning tied for the
fourth-best record in the NBA, just one game behind the Utah Jazz
in the Midwest Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really got it going,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We just have
to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's the rub. Barkley said he badly strained his back
when he overcompensated for an aching left knee. He had
arthroscopic surgery Feb. 4, and though he has gotten stronger, the
back has grown worse each of the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back is killing me,'' Barkley said. ``I'm in pain right
now, but as long as we win, the pain hurts less.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets came up with that analgesic with an
often-spectacular second half, rallying around the loss of Barkley
in the third quarter and then hopping on that sore back in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had left the court with 3:24 remaining in the first half
and stayed in the training room for the start of the second half to
continue treatments. The decision to hold him out of the start of
the second half was based on the thought that if he started the
half, the back would stiffen when he had to leave the game. The
hope was that once in the game he could continue to play without
tightening up when resting.
</P>
<P>
   With Barkley out, Othella Harrington took care of the third
quarter until Barkley returned to start to the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington shut down Lawrence Funderburke _ who had a
career-high 18 points in Webber's place _ and made four of five
shots for nine points in the quarter. He even added, of all things,
a nifty behind-the-back bounce pass to Hakeem Olajuwon for a dunk.
After a 12-point first half, largely against the pained Barkley,
Funderburke had just two points in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew with Charles out I had to give a lift, and especially
try to slow down Lawrence a bit,'' Harrington said. ``I was
disappointed in myself at Golden State, missing all those free
throws (he made three of eight). I wanted to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Barkley returned, the Rockets had withstood a
shooting barrage from Kings rookie Jason Williams and answered with
a run of their own. When Williams scored on one of his one-handed
high floaters, he had given the Kings a 61-60 lead midway through
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets immediately regained the lead, Olajuwon scoring
on the Harrington pass as the Rockets closed out the quarter with a
14-4 run. When Cuttino Mobley ended the quarter by just beating the
shot clock with a 3, the Rockets had their largest lead, 75-66.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Barkley went to work. After a Matt Bullard jumper,
Barkley took a pass from Brent Price to a three-point play, then
hit a turnaround jumper. Having forced the Kings to double-team
him, he passed to Price at the 3-point line, and Price gave the
Rockets an 85-72 lead with 9:33 left.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley followed a Price miss with a layup, passed to Pippen for
a dunk and then beat Funderburke inside for two more layups, even
helping the fallen Funderburke up after driving past him on the
second. He had 11 points in five minutes, the pain never leaving
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles was heroic,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I would think that
would have a very positive effect on a team. It had an effect on
me. I think the guy is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Dickerson nailed a 3 with 6:20 left, the Rockets
led 96-80 and began to cruise. But as has so often been the case,
they cruised too soon. They made just one of their next eight
shots, and the Kings went on an 11-2 run to within 98-91 with two
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   But just as he had Saturday at Golden State, Pippen put the win
away with a 3, taking a pass from Olajuwon to push the lead to
101-91 with 1:33 left. Olajuwon hit a 3 at the buzzer to give him
24 points. Pippen had 17, and Barkley added 15 points and 11
rebounds in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worn out,'' Tomjanovich said. ``That's four games in
five nights. We really need an off day bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But winning under such circumstances, Olajuwon said, ``is the
sign of a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going, good might be an understatement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
