<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-HNS     03-29 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It was just a matter of time before the Los
Angeles Lakers or the visting New York Knicks cracked under the
pressure their disappointing seasons.
<TEXT>
<P>
   RodmanTurns out it was the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and the Knicks, both in the process of being
undermined by chemistry problems, duked it out _ almost literally _
at the Great Western Forum on Sunday, the Lakers walking off the
floor with a 99-91 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights will show the key plays _ Derek Harper's two huge
3-pointers in the final four minutes to stave off a Knicks rally,
Kobe Bryant's graceful spin move in the lane with 49 seconds to
play, capping a brilliant 29-point performance, and all of
Shaquille O'Neal's dunks in a 21-point game.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to the Lakers' 20th win was they were able to shove
aside Dennis Rodman's relentless sideshow while the Knicks were
not. The Knicks, faltering under their internal pressures, were
unable to deal with the throbbing headache that is Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   And Rodman mined that for all it was worth.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, everyone, the 17,505 in attendance and the honchos at
NBC, went home happy because the game was spiced with several
obligatory Rodman incidents, from the usual jersey-grabbing and
elbow-throwing to an all-out wrestling match with the Knicks' Kurt
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered and the New York bench griped every time he
elicited a response from the Knicks, so it was understandable most
of the postgame discussions focused on Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you understand the game, you ignore all the stuff Dennis
does,'' said the Lakers' Robert Horry. ``I know when I played
against him when he was in San Antonio, you just ignore him. A lot
of people get mad at the things he does, but you have to ignore it
and keep going. You have to be smarter. I'm surprised he still gets
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also surprised was Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, who minced few
words when describing Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a dirty player,'' Van Gundy said. ``I mean he's a great
player, but he plays dirty. It always amazes me that he's always
the one involved but it's always the other players that get picked
on (by the officials).''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say Van Gundy has been feeling a bit picked on
himself these days. About the only thing thinner than Van Gundy's
hairline is the ice on which he has been skating the past couple of
weeks with New York management. After sweeping changes to their
roster during the offseason, the Knicks thought they were going to
be among the Eastern Conference's elite.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sunday's loss to the Lakers dropped them to 16-14, and
supposedly a step closer to a pink slip for Van Gundy, who has been
battling his team as well as opponents.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest fight remains Latrell Sprewell, who is quietly being
called ``Me-well'' by teammates because of his selfish play.
Sprewell is unhappy with his role as sixth man and wants to start,
a conflict that led to a meeting with Van Gundy last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell led the Knicks with 25 points Sunday, but threw up
several ill-advised shots and often missed a wide-open Patrick
Ewing, who would finish with 20 points and 13 rebounds before
fouling out with 23.4 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in many ways, Sunday's game represented a Twilight
Zone-like cautionary tale about being careful about what you wish
for. The Lakers and Knicks wanted to reinvent themselves, and went
to great _ and somewhat controversial _ lengths to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' problems with Rodman have been well-documented _ his
trip to Las Vegas, refusing to report back in for the fourth
quarter Friday in what turned out to be a loss to the Sacramento
Kings and then being 75 minutes late to practice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one said it was going to be easy,'' said Lakers coach Kurt
Rambis of dealing with Rodman. ``I look forward to him being here,
being productive and focused on all the things we are doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sunday, when the ``good'' Dennis Rodman showed up. He
finished with seven points and a team-high 12 rebounds, even
knocking down four straight free throws in the final 2:35.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys always try to count me out of the free throws,''
Rodman said. ``At the beginning of the game I may screw around, but
when it is time to hit the big shot, the big free throw, I am
always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like he always seems to be there when there's a bit of
extracurricular activity. Rodman's one true gift is his ability to
tap into an opponent's frustrations and mine them for his own
purposes, as he did in his tussle with Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game of wits,'' Rodman said. ``You've got to know when
to be aggressive and when not to. You show your aggression during
the play, but you do not show your aggression after the play. You
just have to be smarter and more cunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Something the Knicks were not.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Thomas tossed for his set-to with Rodman, but Chris
Dudley was ejected with 6:13 left in the game for throwing the ball
at O'Neal after the 7-1, 325-pound center dunked over him and then
flipped Dudley aside with a twitch of his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what happened,'' said O'Neal, grinning.
``There was so much power in my body that I didn't even feel it
(when the ball hit him in the backside).
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Dudley) just grabbed me. He was under me, and I just had
to get him off me. You know how it is with those Knicks guys _ you
don't know what their intention is, so I had to get him off me.''
</P>
<P>
   Could have been worse. It could have been Rodman under him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-PRIMESTAR5     03-29 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-PRIMESTAR500-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
FORT WORTH _ Terry Labonte has an impressive list of
accomplishments in his NASCAR career, including two Winston Cup
championships and earnings of more than $19 million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 42-year-old Corpus Christi native has reached most of the
goals he hoped to achieve in his 21 seasons on the circuit, but one
thing that had eluded him was winning a race in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who now resides in North Carolina, finally grabbed a
checkered flag in Texas when he guided the Kellogg's Chevrolet to
victory Sunday in the Primestar 500 in front of a Texas Motor
Speedway-record crowd of 221,861.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the biggest race I've ever won,'' said Labonte,
who has 21 victories in his career. ``To come here and win at home
is great. I looked up and saw the crowd standing at the end, and it
was an awesome feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a perfect day for the Labonte family. Younger
brother Bobby _ driving with a broken right shoulder blade _
finished third in the Interstate Batteries Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a big coconut shell on my back,'' Bobby
Labonte, 34, said. ``It's pretty sore right now. I've never been
that uncomfortable in the car. But it was fun racing with Terry
most of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett finished between the Labonte brothers as the race
ended under caution after Jimmy Spencer hit the wall on the
frontstretch with four laps remaining in the 334-lap event.
Teammates Rusty Wallace and Jeremy Mayfield were fourth and fifth,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte, who led 124 laps, took the lead for good with 10
laps remaining when he managed to squeeze past Jarrett, who got to
the front thanks to an off-sequence pit stop late in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett kept Labonte behind him for 17 laps, but Labonte finally
got around him _ with a little help from Chad Little _ by going
outside at the start of lap 324.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett had to slow down just a bit in the Quality Care Ford as
the two cars came up on Little, who was trying to stay on the lead
lap. Labonte made it past Little in turn 1, but Little stayed in
front of Jarrett for half a lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to figure out how to pass Dale,'' Labonte said.
``I tried inside, and I couldn't do it, but I found out I could go
outside and get some grip.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was six car lengths ahead of Jarrett when the yellow
flag came out with three laps to go, so it was unlikely Jarrett was
going to catch him had the race ended under a green flag.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte and Jarrett battled the last time Labonte won a race, in
Richmond, Va., last June. Labonte bumped Jarrett from behind to
force his way to the front with two laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I didn't want to do today was run into Dale, and
almost did once,'' Labonte said. ``I had to get out of the gas and
try again the next lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was angry at Richmond when Labonte tapped him from
behind, but he had no complaints this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry made a good, smart, clean pass today,'' Jarrett said.
``I had to get off the gas a little when he got by me, but he had
the better car. I wasn't going to catch him at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett said he was happy he was able to stay in front of Bobby
Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how tough Bobby is, so it didn't surprise me he went
the distance today with that injury,'' Jarrett said. ``He has that
determination and desire to compete. It shows the strong will and
mental strength he has to go through what he did out there and
finish third.
</P>
<P>
   ``But second was great for us if you look at the big picture. We
gained a lot of (championship) points on guys ahead of us (entering
the race) that had trouble today.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte earned $376,840 for the victory and moved up from
ninth to fifth in the Winston Cup points standings. The money and
the points are important to Labonte, but he said winning in Texas
is something he always will remember.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte raced three times at the start of his career (1979-81)
at Texas World Speedway before NASCAR stopped running at the
College Station track. He had to wait 16 years to get another
chance at a Texas victory, and he came close in his first two trips
to TMS. Labonte was third in 1997 and sixth last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of effort into trying to win here this year,''
Labonte said. ``We tested two cars here. Before the season started,
we wrote down some things we wanted to accomplish. Winning here was
near the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   The only major goal that has eluded Labonte is a victory in the
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten Daytona yet, but we got the second-most
meaningful race for us,'' said Andy Graves, Labonte's crew chief.
``Terry doesn't always show how he feels, but I know how much it
means to him to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, who has finished in the top 10 in all three TMS
races, hopes he can join Terry someday as a Texas winner. But Bobby
said he knew early in the race Sunday that his big brother was on a
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry was driving his heart out today,'' Bobby said. ``It's
never easy to pass that 88 car (Jarrett), but Terry was not going
to be denied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
