<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7662 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ They come in assorted sizes and all kinds of
packages, the ones who can take a routine ending to a predictable
season and turn it on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are Danny Manning, an All-American in pedigree,
who can hoist an entire underdog team from Kansas onto his
shoulders with 31 points and 18 rebounds to knock off cocky
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are Harold Jensen, an unassuming reserve, who can
pop up off the bench for Villanova and shoot a perfect 5-for-5 from
the field to take down snarling, powerful Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are even Lorenzo Charles, who can become a folk
hero merely by standing in the right place at the right time,
turning a miss into a miracle as North Carolina State shocks
leaping, soaring, strutting, slam-dunking Houston and the world.
</P>
<P>
   They are the difference-makers, and you never seem to know their
names or what shape they'll take. But if it happens tonight for
Connecticut against mighty Duke in the NCAA championship game, the
most likely candidate will be a point guard who looks like the
product of a mating dance between a Cabbage Patch doll and one of
the Teletubbies.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin is a well-rounded player, a well-rounded person
and, well, rounded. He is to the image of hummingbird-quick guard
what chicken fried streak (extra gravy) is to health food.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's idea of a six-pack is not a well-defined set of
stomach muscles but something you drink while resting the plate
with the burger and chips on your stomach. He's a muffin with legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I do eat a lot,'' he said. ``That's not a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Not at 5-10 and 205 pounds. And certainly no secret to the
basketball world as the Huskies have posted a 65-7 record in the
two seasons since he joined the team.
</P>
<P>
   Fans at visiting arenas have called him ``Pillsbury Doughboy.''
They wave Domino's Pizza boxes at him when he's in the layup line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been small, always had this kind of body, and I
like it,'' El-Amin said. ``I know I don't look like your average
point guard. Which is why, I think, the out-of-shape segment of the
population takes me and embraces me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's it. He's a hero to the majority in the
soft-around-the-edges segment of society, the bunch of us who
figure we could jump up off the sofa and dribble the ball down the
court on the fast break and stick the jumper like the little
roly-poly dude, if only we'd remember to lick the nacho cheese off
our fingers first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Barkley doesn't have the shape or size of your
big-time power forward in the league, but he's done all right,''
El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   He's a miniature Chuckster, motor mouth and all.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that he is a special kind of athlete,
possessing an unorthodox body and yet extraordinary skills to
succeed and a cocksure attitude. Which is why if Connecticut has
hope tonight, he is it. Not simply because El-Amin scored 18 points
against Ohio State and dealt six assists _ including that nifty
behind-the-back pass to Kevin Freeman _ but because he believes he
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had fear of anybody on a basketball court,'' he
said. ``So I know I won't be afraid of Duke. If pressure got to me,
I wouldn't be who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, the kid who started playing the game at age 4 in
Minneapolis when his father hung up a hoop over the garage for
Khalid and his older brother Makram and was always the smallest one
in every game. When he was in second grade, El-Amin was playing on
a seventh-grade team at a place called the Hospitality House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start, but I got my minutes,'' he said. ``They knew I
was there.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of what UConn All-America guard Richard
Hamilton and center Jake Voskuhl must do for the Huskies to have a
fighting chance against Duke, El-Amin is precisely the kind of
player, the kind of hug-the-spotlight personality, who could feel
the heat and thrive.
</P>
<P>
   If you let yourself believe in the tooth fairy and all of those
past NCAA Monday nights, there is something about him that tells
you he is the kind of figure who could make things as interesting
as his own life.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin is an orthodox Muslim who married at age 16, fathered a
daughter out of wedlock at 17 and now, two years later, has an
infant son with his wife. He prays five times a day. He is mouthy
yet devout. He is small yet plays big. He looks like a marshmallow
yet has 6 percent body fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's about 15 years old to 35, depending on the subject matter
and the moment,'' said UConn coach Jim Calhoun. ``But we wouldn't
be here without him.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the Huskies' heart, their soul, their hunger, maybe their
entree to another March miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   Which, El-Amin will tell you, is different than no chance at
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
