<SLUG> BC-BKW-DUKE-PURDUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE CAN'T KEEP UP WITH PURDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Purdue Boilermakers ended an almost
perfect season on an almost perfect note Sunday night, as they
defeated Duke, 62-45, in the NCAA Tournament final at San Jose
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time Purdue (34-1) took home the national
championship in 10 trips to the tournament, and the first time a
Big Ten team won the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' said a beaming Purdue coach, Carolyn Peck, after the
game. ``I guess that's the best way to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrill was in the result but not the execution. It had the
dubious distinction of being the lowest-scoring championship game
in NCAA history (Louisiana Tech and Auburn totaled 110 points in
1988), and had the fewest first-half points (39, compared to 50 in
the '88 game). Purdue's 17 first-half points were also the lowest
total.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (29-7) has been to the tournament for the past five years
but never had gotten as far as the Final Four. It defeated
three-time defending champion Tennessee in the East Regional and
Georgia Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come such a long way, and we've been playing our best
basketball,'' said Duke coach Gail Goestenkors. ``So this is very
disappointing. This is certainly not the way we envisioned the end
of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, which had a very un-Purduelike first half, rebounded to
show why it suffered only one loss, to Stanford, all season. With
the game tied at 30, the Boilermakers went on a 10-1 run. Even
though Duke tried to come back with a 3-pointer by senior guard
Nicole Erickson (8 points), and two layups by Michele VanGorp, it
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   When a 3-pointer by Katie Douglas landed to give the
Boilermakers a 45-38 lead, she jumped and raised her fist in the
air as the sellout crowd of 17,773 cheered. With six minutes to go,
Duke suffered a scoring drought, and 12 free throws in a row by
Purdue put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ukari Figgs scored a game-high 18 points for Purdue, while
Camille Cooper and Douglas had 13 ach. Stephanie White-McCarty
added 12, but with four minutes left she severely sprained her
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, fans must have rubbed their eyes and wondered who they
were watching. Was this really top-ranked Purdue playing No. 10
Duke?
</P>
<P>
   In the first 7:10, the teams accounted for just 10 points. Duke
turned the ball over again and again (20 in the game), and was
charged with eight fouls. The Blue Devils shot 39.1 percent from
the floor in the first half, Purdue 28.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The half ended with Duke in front, 22-17.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who scored just 3 of her 18 points in the first half,
said, ``We were going for outside shots, and our outside shots
weren't falling. So in the second half we started attacking the
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp, Duke's 6-foot-6-inch senior, who was held to just 4
first-half points, said her team wasn't executing on offense. Added
Hilary Howard, ``They play good pressure defense and we didn't make
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   But Purdue made all the adjustments it had to, and when the
buzzer sounded, it had the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't think of a better moment,'' Peck said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
