A7664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NOR     03-29 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NORTHDAKOTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE'S NO CROWD IN FROZEN FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Hockey East is headed West. And Boston College
goalie Scott Clemmensen is ready for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   BC, playing tough defense once again, knocked off top-seeded and
No. 1-ranked North Dakota, 3-1, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the Dane County
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles made it a Hockey East sweep of the rest of the
college hockey world.
</P>
<P>
   Three Hockey East teams _ BC, New Hampshire, and Maine _ made
the field and all three advanced to the NCAA's Frozen Four that
starts Thursday in Anaheim. It's the first time in the league's
15-year history that three teams have made it to the final round.
</P>
<P>
   BC and Maine square off in a rubber match in one semifinal. UNH
faces Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, high-flying all year, did it with defense just like
they did Saturday night against Northern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen and the Eagles shut down the Fighting Sioux, who
averaged five goals a game and were top-rated in the country most
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one more thing to say,'' Clemmensen said in a news
conference. ``I didn't pack my shorts for nothing on this trip. I
was real confident we were going on to Anaheim.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was a big part of the reason the Eagles will fly West
Tuesday instead of East this morning.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, Clemmensen allowed a single goal.
He had 31 saves, including 15 in the third period, as the Sioux
tried to cut into a 2-1 BC lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first period, BC built the lead in a fast and
furious second. Senior Chris Masters opened the scoring, banging in
a rebound of a Mike Lephart shot that went off the crossbar for a
power-play goal at 10:26.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota matched that one at 13:47 when Lee Goren held off
BC defenseman Mike Mottau and beat Clemmensen high, also on the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   BC freshman Jeff Giuliano scored his fifth goal of the year at
17:45 for 2-1 lead. Jeff Farkas, who was everywhere, and defenseman
Brooks Orpik assisted.
</P>
<P>
   The puck popped out front to Giuliano, and he blasted it past
North Dakota goalie Karl Goehring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches had been saying shoot high, over his glove or
blocker, because he had been going down early,'' Giuliano said.
</P>
<P>
   So he did. And got the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen and the defense bore down and made the goal stand the
rest of the way. Clemmensen held his ground while the Sioux tried
to jam the puck in at the eight-minute mark of the third. He
stopped David Hoogsteen midway through the period. And slid across
and made a super save on Brad Williamson with two minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, North Dakota had a chance to pull Goehring with time
running out.
</P>
<P>
   And soon, Brian Gionta pounced on the puck at mid-ice, skated
towards the boards, and fired it into the open net. With 15 seconds
left, BC had sealed the win.
</P>
<P>
   And its trip West. Seconds later the game ended. A couple of red
and yellow streamers _ hey, maroon and gold aren't in heavy supply
around here _ rained down into the rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey East rules,'' yelled a lone voice in a sparse crowd of
largely North Dakota fans.
</P>
<P>
   For this weekend, it certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   BC, given the toughest draw by being sent here to begin with,
more than did its share.
</P>
<P>
   And did it in a different manner than maybe many expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as coaches thought going in it would be a 5-4 type game,''
said BC coach Jerry York. ``It's awfully hard to hold us down as a
team. The same goes for North Dakota. But it was a case of good
pitching in baseball. There was good goaltending on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Sioux coach Dean Blais tipped his hat to BC.
</P>
<P>
   When his team got its only goal, he was looking for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a little momentum switch,'' Blais said.
``Usually when we score, we score in bunches. And usually we
generate things in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles, he said, limited that part of the game. And kept
the Sioux forwards from doing damage anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did not get those opportunities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And because of it Clemmensen and the Eagles are headed West.
With a couple of their Hockey East rivals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
