</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS CLAIMS FAMILY FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Not yet, little sister.
</P>
<P>
   Sisterly love was not evident Sunday within the prize ring,
actually a 78-by-36 foot asphalt tennis rectangle baked in high
noon sun, where Venus and Serena Williams threw brutal Sunday
punches at each other for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Then the historic encounter was over, both still standing,
quickly hugging. Winner and yet champion at The Lipton by a
decision was big sister, Venus, 6-1, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Female siblings have rivaled throughout the 123 years of the
tournament game. During the early days of the century it was said
in Southern California (where Venus and Serena originated): ``It
takes a Sutton to beat a Sutton.'' All four of them _ May, Violet,
Florence, Ethel _ were nationally prominent, and May, in 1905, was
the first foreigner to win Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever finals embraced them couldn't have enjoyed the
magnitude of Venus and Serena Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even the last (and only) collision of sisters, the English
Watsons, in a major title bout _ Maud over Lillian at Wimbledon,
1884 _ wouldn't have rippled much beyond London.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome that absorbed a full-house
congregation of 14,000 at Crandon Park plus planetary TV
eavesdroppers, the Williams beat went on. Although little sister
Serena, 17, hit the wall with her 16-match streak, Venus, 18,
extended hers to 10.
</P>
<P>
   It's becoming clear that the initials WTA (Women's Tennis
Association) may soon stand for Williamses Take All.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more finals for the two of us,'' said Venus, who
stays at No. 6 in the universe, while Serena rises five levels to a
personal zenith of No. 11. But does big sister (3-0 in their
professional faceoffs) give little sister the whammies?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, believes Rick Macci, their coach of early formative teen
years. ``This is an unusual sister relationship, very, very close,
like two peas in a pod. It will be a while before Serena will be
able to fight all-out against Venus. But I think it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While this was a much better performance from both kids than the
two previous in 1998, won in straight sets by Venus at the
Australian and Italian Opens, both had sinking spells. And Serena's
came at the worst place, at the wire, after seizing big sister's
serve to get even at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for too much at the end, rushed my shots,'' sighed
Serena, loser of the last 6 points, 8 of the closing 9, 7 of them
on unforcederrors. Her error count unhappily outweighed Venus's,
66-41.
</P>
<P>
   The man who put rackets in their hands when each was 4, papa
Richard Williams, said, ``I think maybe they both focus more
intensely when they play other opponents. They can both play a lot
better. Serena got shaky because Venus ran down so many balls.
Nobody else can do that against her.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while he flashed handwritten signs (like ``Come on,
Serena!'') at TV cameras, but said he then had to leave his seat
``because I worried I was gonna cry. It was going through my mind
all the difficulties of getting out of the ghetto in Compton
(Calif.) and . . . to arrive at this with both my daughters in this
final . . . I could feel the tears coming.''
</P>
<P>
   He frowned at the suggestion that big sister had taken it easy
on beloved little sister just when it seemed the title was hers
with a winning 4-3 lead in the second. Venus faded inexplicably, as
Serena took three games to square it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been raised to win, not just be here, and I believe
they will be 1-2 in the world in time. I've always believed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus also frowned. ``I just lost it at 4-3. It happens. I don't
let up on anybody. I know how Serena comes back, and I didn't want
to be her victim like Martina Hingis was. It gives me great
satisfaction to have survived her onslaught.''
</P>
<P>
   Good choice of words _ the Sisters Sledgehammer did lay on
onslaughts. ``We try to kill each other,'' Venus said. It looked
that way. Never have two females on a tennis court combined such
awesome power and cheetah-like speed. Only the most severely
bludgeoned balls outdistanced them to become winners.
</P>
<P>
   Little sister and big sister pooh-poohed the psychological
aspect. ``I play the ball, not the opponent. But I've always
dreamed of a day like this,'' said Serena. ``I think you people
(reporters) attached more emotion to it than us. It's a game. We go
home and live life. The competition doesn't affect our
relationship. Family comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto, pretty much for Venus, although, ``Of course I know it's
my sister over there. We've played so many times. We know what the
other's gonna do.''
</P>
<P>
   So do we, now that these relatively inexperienced phenoms are
leaning on the tour inexorably, stylish stormers reaching for the
top. Little sister's time will come, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
