</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITING TAKES ALL-AROUND SKILL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Jim Calhoun sat proudly on the podium
facing the national media for the off-day NCAA championship game
press conference Sunday. Seated to his immediate left were young
men _ the ``student-athletes'' as the NCAA insists they be called _
from Katy, Texas, (Jake Voskuhl); Augusta, Ga., (Ricky Moore);
Coatesville, Pa., (Richard Hamilton); Springfield, Mass., (Kevin
Freeman, who made a senior-year stop at Paterson, N.J.); and
Minneapolis (Khalid El-Amin).
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this was not Art Quimby's kind of UConn Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the first Eisenhower Administration, when young Mr.
Quimby twice was leading the nation by routinely hauling in more
than 20 rebounds a game, the Connecticut Huskies were like some
Appalachian families; i.e. seriously inbred. Connecticut basketball
pretty much meant just that, and if it had any remotely broader
scope, it meant New York or New Jersey. In Quimby's sophomore year
of 1952-53, for example, he was one of 12 Connecticut high school
products. The other three members of the team came from Brooklyn,
Yonkers, and Belmont, Mass. Throughout the 60s, 70s, and early 80s,
the Huskies really were Connecticut's team.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why Calhoun will be taking a 33-2 UConn
team into Monday night's championship game against Duke (37-1), but
foremost among them is the fact that he has a true national
program. The typical Husky no longer comes from New Haven,
Hartford, Bridgeport, Waterbury, or, like Art Quimby, New London.
In the Calhoun era a Husky can come from South Carolina (Ray
Allen), Arizona (Brian Fair), Federal City, Wash., (Donny
Marshall), Los Angeles (Kevin Ollie), or Sandy, Utah (Travis
Knight). If a Chris Smith (Bridgeport) or Scott Burrell (Hamden) or
Edmund Saunders (Waterbury) wants to come, that's great, too.
Calhoun always will solicit the very best the Nutmeg State has to
offer. But he never will make the mistake of depending on it,
unless getting a National Invitation Tournament invitation is the
new goal of the UConn athletic program.
</P>
<P>
   Dom Perno, Calhoun's predecessor, already had figured things
out. He brought in such out-of-staters as Tim Coles (Baltimore) and
Ray Braxton (Daytona Beach), and his 1985 recruiting class featured
Jeff King (Lansing, Mich.), Eddie Williams (Magnolia, N.C.), and
future NBA mainstay Cliff Robinson (Buffalo). But he never got to
reap the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   When Calhoun coached at Northeastern, his idea of exotic
recruiting was to establish strong ties in Pittsburgh and the
Washington D.C./Baltimore areas. You didn't see Sun Belt kids
flocking to Huntington Ave. Arriving at Storrs in 1986, he knew
he'd have to broaden his recruiting horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say to (former assistant coach) Howie Dickenman, `Who are
we involved with?' and he'd tell me it was the sixth-best kid in
New Jersey, the seventh-best kid in New York, or the 10th-best kid
in Philadelphia. I said, `Men, we're sure going to have to coach
'em up a lot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So the decision was made: UConn was going to start competing for
the best kids, period. But what exactly did UConn have to offer?
Calhoun wouldn't have had the job if anything good was going on in
Storrs (50-62 the four previous seasons).
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, a) we will go after the best athletes we can get and
b) we will sell the Big East first and UConn second,'' Calhoun
reveals. ``We'd say, `Would you like to play against Alonzo
Mourning? Would you like to play in the Carrier Dome?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun bagged a 6-foot-5-inch defensive specialist he still
raves about by the name of Lyman DePriest out of Detroit in 1987.
He got Rod Sellers from Florence, S.C., the following year. He went
international with Israel's Nadav Henefeld in '89 (along with
in-state bonanzas Smith and Burrell).
</P>
<P>
   The huge breakthrough came in 1991. Jim Calhoun, the kid whose
own game had been honed at French's Common in Braintree and who had
been the King of Huntington Ave. for 14 years, injected himself
forever into the national picture with a colossal six-man
recruiting class consisting of Ollie, Fair, Donny Marshall, Donyell
Marshall (Reading, Pa.), Rudy Johnson (Jacksonville), and Natambu
Willingham (Atlanta). Little ol' Storrs was now a place with true
cachet.
</P>
<P>
   Ollie was said to be the Player of the Year in LA and Fair was
the equivalent guy in Arizona, but the key player in this group,
according to Calhoun was Donyell Marshall, a 6-8 seriously big-time
All-American. ``Getting him gave us true national credibility,''
Calhoun maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the mentor knows whereof he speaks. ``I never
thought of Connecticut until Donyell Marshall went there,'' says
Hamilton, the feathery 6-6 scoring machine whose 24 points on
Saturday helped send Ohio State home. ``He lived about 20 or 30
minutes from my house in Coatesville, and I saw that if he could
fit in there and be happy, I could, too. I thought if I had the
opportunity I could go there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest X and O men still need players. The greatest
motivators still need players. No one is more acutely aware of this
than Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, whose own talent core includes
kids from Georgia (William Avery), Alaska (Trajan Langdon), New
York (Elton Brand), Michigan (Shane Battier), Missouri (Chris
Carrawell), Illinois (Corey Maggette), California (Chris Burgess),
Washington, D.C. (Nate James), and New Mexico (Taymon Domzalski).
</P>
<P>
   You gotta do what you gotta do _ within the rules, of course.
``Coach K would fly 3,000 miles to see me in a pickup game,''
recalls ESPN commentator Jay Bilas (Duke '86), a Los Angeles native
and member of Coach K's first great Blue Devil recruiting class.
``I can still see him sitting on the steps of one of those portable
classrooms watching us on our outdoor court,'' he says. ``Of
course, now he wouldn't do that. If it were still legal, he'd send
an assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Calhoun, I'm sure, would go himself. I mean, Coach K already
has won two national titles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
