<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BEGIN WITH SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Walter Zenga still seems to have his
magic touch. Zenga stopped a penalty kick and stifled the Miami
Fusion for 88 minutes before Tyrone Marshall's goal spoiled the
Revolution's Major League Soccer season-opener Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The score finished 1-1 in regulation time, and the Fusion won
the shootout, 4-3, to earn their first point in two games. The
Revolution, who concluded last season with four shutouts in their
final six games under Zenga's coaching, visit Kansas City Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, returning as player-coach after a year of retirement from
goalkeeping, had his team prepared, and the Revolution's Giovanni
Savarese set a league record with a goal 22 seconds after the
opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution continued to threaten offensively in the first
half, but by the second half had retreated into a defensive mode,
eventually succumbing to the Fusion's pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the world but it would have been better to
start with 3 points,'' Zenga said. ``I feel good about myself and
how the team played in front of me. We know our problems and we
will work to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution displayed a compact defensive scheme, impeding
the effectiveness of Fusion fullbacks Mario Gori and Jay Heaps, and
using former Fusion midfielder Kris Kelderman to shadow Carlos
Valderrama. They showed that they will emphasize defense, but
judging by the speed of the opening goal, will try not to ignore
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga noted that the formation included two strikers, along with
Joe-Max Moore, whose role was intended to be a withdrawn striker.
And pressure by the Revolution led to a misplay by Heaps on the
edge of the penalty area that Moore pilfered and shot off the left
post. Savarese roofed the rebound into the far right corner of the
net for his 42d MLS goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution failed to generate attacks from midfield
after the opening minutes, and their second-half counterattack
attempts failed, despite the addition of forward Carlos Rocha, who
was cautioned for dissent by referee Noel Kenny in the 82d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Fusion coach Ivo Wortmann made two key substitutions in the
second half, adding Tyrone Marshall and Nelson Vargas, as Miami's
sense of urgency increased. Vargas added a dimension of creativity
and, along with Valderrama and Henry Gutierrez, helped Miami
dominate midfield possession.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after the Revolution's Richard Goulooze surrendered a
penalty in a clash with Diego Serna in the 81st minute, Vargas
squandered the penalty kick. Then, the Revolution seemed destined
to win, as Zenga's save climaxed a spectacular performance in his
first competitive game since October, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga had stopped Vargas twice in the opening minutes of the
second half, and midway through the half had stymied Marshall from
point-blank range, and collected Carlos Parra's point-blank
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   But with four minutes remaining in a 92-minute contest, the
Revolution failed to clear a corner, and Valderrama chipped to the
far post, where both Gori and Marshall were unmarked, and Marshall
tapped a header inside the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, playing without three starters _ Imad Baba
(groin), Edwin Gorter (suspended), and John Harkes (knee) _ went
into a defensive formation after defender Brian Dunseth replaced
Johnny Torres seven minutes into the second half and Mike Burns
moved into midfield.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy could be justified, since this was the Revolution's
opening match and the team needed to boost morale after a
disastrous 1998 season. And it might have succeeded, but the
85-degree heat and the size of one of the country's best playing
surfaces were to Miami's advantage. And, after Jair suffered an
ankle injury after being taken down from behind by Gutierrez in the
72d minute, the Revolution's midfield creativity diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Italy, we would say that a tie was the right result,''
Zenga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
