u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANALYSIS-     03-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER STAR IS NOW BIRD OF PREY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some things do change. Whoever thought you'd see the
day when Larry Bird showed up for a game wearing lavender?
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going for his former franchise, he could show
up in Boston wearing an Old Navy ensemble, cargo pants, or one of
those hideous golf shirts (``they're free!'') he used to wear and
it wouldn't matter. Beating the Celtics is a requirement if you
play for the Pacers. The alternative is, well, still unknown
because Bird is now 6-0 against the team that let him slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a must win for us,'' Reggie Miller said after the
Pacers had executed an efficient 101-93 decision over the Celtics
Sunday. ``We know that. It's the Finals, Game 7, you name it. We're
no fools. I know that someday they're going to beat us, but I just
hope that comes when I'm retired and he's not coaching anymore.
He's not a man of many words, but I can just imagine what he'd
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was a lot like the previous five with Bird's boys,
games that were decided by 6, 4, 7, 7, and 3 points. The Celtics
always seem to play Indiana hard, and to the end, but the result is
the same. That's Indiana's persona.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Pacers' 20 wins, almost half _ nine _ are by 5 or fewer
points. Thirteen are by 8 points or fewer, including both Celtics
conquests. They don't really have that blowout mentality, only two
of their wins have been by 15 or more, which should make them an
NBC favorite because they retain viewers. (The Celtics, by
contrast, have won games by 32 and 34 points.)
</P>
<P>
   Bird, of course, makes no pretense about how much he enjoys
sticking it to the team he once led and carried. They thought
enough of him to go out and court potential head coaches. They
didn't think enough of him to turn the whole enterprise over to him
and let him run it. We had M.L. Carr for that.
</P>
<P>
   All he's done since leaving town is preside over an Indiana
resurgence. The Pacers were within one jump ball of the NBA Finals
last year. This year, picked as the favorite and expected to win,
they are doing just that. They are 20-8 and battling Miami and
Orlando for Eastern Conference muscle-flexing rights.
</P>
<P>
   And Bird? He is 78-32 as a head coach. The six Ws against the
Celtics are easily the sweetest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to lose to anybody _ especially those guys,'' he
said. Asked later how it felt to be 6-0 against Pitino, he said,
``I don't care who's coaching that team. I just want to beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He still insists he'd have trouble if the Celtics were playing
in the Garden. That was his place and there are too many musty
memories, too many things he could identify with, like obstructed
view seats, the 1920s locker rooms, the lack of air conditioning,
the smell of circus animals, the exit ramp that always looked like
it was going to collapse. They paved paradise and put in a parking
lot is what Joni Mitchell once wrote. That's how Bird felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough coming back here,'' he said. ``Thank God I'm in
this building. I honestly think that if the Boston Garden was still
standing, I wouldn't want to go in there and coach in that
building.''
</P>
<P>
   He sensed trouble for this one. He arrived in town after a good
win in New Jersey and picked up all the turmoil talk surrounding
the Celtics. He and eight of his closest friends dined in the North
End Saturday, but there were no visits to Clarke's or any of his
former hangouts. He's almost boring these days (lavender?) although
he did get a good yuk when he said that Rick Robey was his mentor
as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, meanwhile, finally had gotten a road win in
Philadelphia. They are more athletic than Indiana, they press, they
were hungry, and with national television and the Pacers as the
opponent, well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd be in for a bloodbath,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was concerned about all the extracurricular stuff
going on with the Celtics, Bird said he was. He talked it over with
his team. He needn't have bothered. By now, his players know that
there are some select regular-season games that matter to their
coach, like the ones where he gets a five-minute standing ovation
and fans still chant his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big thing. We all know how much this means to him,''
Jalen Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much hype over these games,'' Miller said, ``but
we're the ones out there playing. As it is, we have to come here
one more time. That's scary enough.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Patriots Day, Reg. The little guys won that day.
Just make sure Bird doesn't show up wearing a red coat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
