<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-PIERCE-BO     03-29 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PIERCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE PERKS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It happens all too often in the NBA. A newcomer gets
off to an exceptional start, making himself an early candidate for
rookie of the year. Then comes the initial setback: Perhaps the
folks who make a living discovering players' weaknesses target his.
Or maybe it's an injury, or a slump, or something that damages his
confidence. How the young player responds will determine whether he
has a solid future for the season or if he's merely a one-month
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics rookie Paul Pierce is trying to overcome a March filled
with setbacks, which followed a February in which he earned rookie
of the month honors and was considered among the leading candidates
for rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston's 101-93 loss to Indiana Sunday, Pierce had his best
game in weeks, scoring 18 points on 5-for-11 shooting in helping
the Celtics stay close before the Pacers pulled away down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Sunday scored more points in the second half (12) than
any of his single-game totals over the previous five contests.
</P>
<P>
   He had a team-high 9 points in the third quarter to help the
Celtics, who trailed, 51-42, at halftime, pull within 3 before
trailing after the third, 79-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last five to six games, I haven't been aggressive on
offense. Hopefully, I can get back in the right direction now,''
said Pierce. ``(Sunday) was the best I've played for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play aggressively, I play better on the offensive end
and the defensive end. Finally, I scored in the second half. I
looked at the past two or three games and I didn't even score in
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce entered Sunday's contest tops among NBA rookies in
rebounding, second in points per game, steals, and 3-point field
goal percentage, and third in blocked shots. His averages of 20.4
points, 7.1 rebounds, and 2.7 steals in February earned him rookie
of the month honors.
</P>
<P>
   Then came March 1, when Pierce missed two free throws in the
closing seconds of Boston's 99-97 loss to New Jersey. Though he
Sunday denied reports coach Rick Pitino criticized him for costing
the team the game, Pierce did admit the misfires damaged his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   On March 9, against Charlotte, he sprained his right ankle in
the first half and did not return. He missed the next two games. In
his return from the injury, Pierce scored 15 points on 5-for-8
shooting against Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   But then he began struggling. He said since the ankle injury, he
has been reticent to drive to the hoop and added the opposition is
working harder to shut down his game, playing him more aggressively
and often double-teaming him.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday that wasn't a problem. Over the last 3:17 of the third
quarter, Pierce scored 6 points _ a 2-foot jumper and four free
throws. Pierce's other 3 points in the quarter came on a 3-foot
jumper and a free throw. Against tougher defenses, he spent the
quarter attacking the glass and either got a basket or went to the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to get my head back to where it was at the
beginning of the season,'' said Pierce, who said the ankle is no
longer a problem. ``I've been looking at tape, and I see a lot of
things I do offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses are picking up on me on my drives. On my first step,
I'm seeing a lot of double-teams and they're really coming at me.
When I dribble into the middle, I can see another guy running at me
and a post man getting down getting ready to block shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game of adjustments, and if I can adjust and recognize
that, and find my open teammates and swing the ball and do the
little things to help this team win, I can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said he believes the adjustments will make him a smarter
player, one who could last after other newcomers have faded. ``I
know teams aren't going to give me the same thing they gave me the
last game, and I have to recognize that and adjust to it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning process for me. I think I'm going to be in
this league a long time, so it's something I have to adjust to,
especially during the first couple of years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
