<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NIXON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX' TROT IS HOT TO SUCCEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He was so upset when he popped out against
the kids from Boston College _ in the second exhibition of spring _
that he marched through the clubhouse and went straight to the
weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams has called him in for a soothing chat. So has
bench coach Grady Little. His dad called from home, with some tips
on what he was doing wrong at the plate. So did his brother. The
guys he played with at Pawtucket, Donnie Sadler and Lou Merloni,
they weighed in, too. That's in addition to the daily sessions with
Jim Rice, the batting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the day John Valentin pulled him aside and said
that if he doesn't start to take it a little easier, it will be a
long season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm so much of a doggone perfectionist,'' Trot Nixon said
Sunday, ``it will be a long season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get a hit on every at-bat. I want to make every
play.''
</P>
<P>
   A week from Monday, the Red Sox season begins in earnest, as
they like to say in the sports pages. Nixon, rookie right fielder,
hardly will notice the difference. A practice game in Florida in
March, Opening Day in Kansas City in April, a game of Wiffle Ball
in the backyard with his wife, Kathryn. It's pretty much all the
same to Nixon, the 24-year-old North Carolinian bent on proving to
God, family, and Red Sox Nation that he has earned the right to be
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player,'' Williams said Sunday. ``He knows we like
him. He's doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had a nice game in Sunday's 9-8 win over the Minnesota
Twins. A single over the second baseman's head to drive in a run in
the second. A hit-and-run single through the vacated left side in a
textbook three-run fourth inning. A lovely bunt to move the runners
over in a four-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied with his afternoon? ``If I hadn't gotten that bunt
down, I would have been upset with myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Which would have placed him right back where he was last week,
when he was in the midst of a 1-for-19 slide that had dropped his
average to .205 entering the weekend. Until Sunday, Nixon had
collected as many as two hits in a game just once this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week ago,'' he said, ``I wasn't feeling comfortable at all.
I was doing a lot of thinking about what I was doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough he figured it out, with the help of family, friends,
and Rice. ``I was falling back, instead of shifting my weight
forward,'' he said. ``I'd start forward, then go back.'' The effect
was to produce an awkward uppercut that wasn't producing the home
runs Nixon was trying to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were few times,'' he said, ``that I wanted to jack the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice finally suggested that Nixon slide his hands about an inch
up the handle of his 35-inch, 32-ounce bat. ``Stupid me, that I
didn't think of it myself,'' Nixon said. ``When I was going bad in
Pawtucket in '97, I choked up, and it turned my whole season
around.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll leave the hands up, he said, until he is satisfied that
he's back to swinging down on the ball, generating line drives.
``Then I'll slide my hands back, so I can use all 35 inches,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon has found ways to contribute even when he wasn't hitting.
He made a diving catch here after a long run to the foul line last
week, and Friday in Port Charlotte scored from second base on a
sacrifice fly, a rare feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be times when he struggles,'' general manager Dan
Duquette said that day in Port Charlotte. ``All rookies do. But
he's making the adjustments. He's going to help our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Nixon might be the last person to believe that. His
locker here is adorned with handwritten signs, which feature the
liberal use of exclamation points. Dare to Be Great! says one.
Don't Give Away Any At-Bats! says another. And a third: It's Time
to Make Baseball More Important Than Your Workouts! Get Focused!!
Have a Nice Day!!
</P>
<P>
   The signs come courtesy of Rich Zawacki, the team's physical
therapist. It started out as fooling around, Nixon said. It has
come to mean more. He knows now where he can go when he needs a
pick-me-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to contribute,'' he said. ``I want the guys on this
team to say, `He can hit.' I don't want to go up there in a
pressure situation and guys thinking, `Oh, no. Game's over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that in baseball, especially, where failure is
built-in, to impose such unrelenting pressure on himself can be
highly flammable. Yet at the same time, it's what has driven him to
reach the level he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can change it,'' he said. ``But I can't change it all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggles he endured in the minors have made him more
accepting of setbacks, he said. ``It helped me learn how to deal
with it,'' he said, ``but I wish I didn't have to deal with so much
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, when I was hitting .230, .240., .250, I questioned
myself. There's no way I can be this bad. I wasn't having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nixon, the fun comes only in excelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to prove myself every day,'' he said. ``Not just to
these guys, but to prove I can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
