<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ARE INTO SELF-HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before their game even started against the Maple Leafs
in Toronto Saturday night, the Bruins already knew that the New
York Rangers had been defeated by the Philadelphia Flyers, further
dimming the league's chances for a Manhattan entry come the start
of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is the time of year for scoreboard watching,
with the Bruins having 10 games remaining, Boston players say they
don't care what the Rangers or Florida Panthers are doing, though
it's impossible not to be tempted to look up at the out-of-town
results. The bottom line is if the Rangers or Panthers are going to
get in, they need help from others. Boston, in sole possession of
the eighth and final Eastern Conference spot, only has to help
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing I don't like to do is look to see if the
Rangers lose,'' said defenseman Kyle McLaren. ``I like to win
ourselves and take care of things. When (coach Pat Burns) said the
Rangers lost, guys wanted to win. Guys always want to win and it
gives a little more incentive to win and push more in front of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That incentive was certainly evident for the first 52 of the 60
minutes of regulation against Toronto. The Bruins had built a 2-0
lead with stifling defense and opportunistic offense and looked on
track to play a nearly flawless road game. But the wheels fell off
in the third and Boston had to settle for a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive deadlock for Boston and what made
it most aggravating is that the Bruins gave up leads late in the
game. They were ahead, 3-2, Thursday against the Blackhawks in the
third period but Chicago tied it with 1:24 left in regulation. The
Bruins had a two-goal lead against the Maple Leafs heading into the
third. After surrendering a goal with 7:18 left, they couldn't hang
on and watched the lead evaporate with just under a minute left as
the Leafs pulled goalie Curtis Joseph for an extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be disappointed with the point we lost but I'm
satisfied with the point we got,'' said Burns. ``On their tying
goal, we can't puck-watch. Everybody was puck-watching, but they're
young, they're going to make mistakes like that. We have to live
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Steve Heinze said what was most frustrating was just how
close the Bruins came not only to a victory but to a shutout of the
highest-scoring team in the league. Once the Leafs got a sniff that
they could come back, they did with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it all by the book, all the way everyone was supposed
to play,'' said Heinze. ``Chipping it in, chipping it out. Simple
stuff, patient. Then it just wasn't our game in the third period.
We pride ourselves on not giving away leads and that's exactly what
we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every point is huge for us right now, but that's a sour way to
tie a team like that when you have them down by two. It's like
you've got them so frustrated and they're thinking, `We can't
score, we can't score' and then it's `Oh, geez, we got one. We can
score.' It gives them a little boost, puts us back on our heels, we
tighten up, and they took it to us and got that second one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who had Sunday off, finished playing five games in
eight days, a tall order. But the good news is they finished
unbeaten in that span with a record of 2-0-3, earning 7 of a
possible 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win, we need to win,'' said McLaren. ``We need
points at this time of year. It doesn't matter to me what other
teams do, it might matter to some guys to get them going. But we
need points no matter what. We're not going to change our style if
they lose or win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be looking that there are 10 games left. We want to
do it now, in the next five games, and make sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, and many of his teammates, said the
five-games-in-eight-nights excuse doesn't hold any water in terms
of explaining why they finished the way they did the last two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Leafs played the night before and got home late,'' he
said. ``I think we're in pretty good shape as a team. We have
pretty tough practices that keep us on our toes. Conditioning
shouldn't be a factor. If anything, we should outplay teams in the
third period.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren said he thought it was less the Bruins collapsing in the
final seven-plus minutes and more the fact that Toronto turned up
the heat after the club was able to score its first one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, I give them credit for battling back and
coming on strong,'' he said. ``I think our guys played a hell of a
game. We played our system to a T for 50 minutes. The puck was
bouncing our way, and for the last 10 it wasn't, and those are the
breaks sometimes you get. Any time you have a 2-0 lead on any team,
you want to close the door and take the 2 points home. Guys are a
little bit disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's disappointing to get a 2-2 tie but it's a point and
it moves us up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ticket strips for the first two rounds of home playoff games
(eight potential games) go on sale to the public Monday morning at
11 at the FleetCenter box office only. From Monday through
Thursday, only playoff strip packages will be available. Individual
game tickets for the first two home playoff games will go on sale
Friday at 11 a.m. at the FleetCenter box office, all TicketMaster
outlets, and through TicketMaster phone charge (508/617) 931-2222.
Ticket prices are the same as regular-season games.
</P>
</TEXT>
