</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVALS HISTORIC TWOSOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ They reside in Duval County, which
encompasses the nearby city of Jacksonville, but Sunday they could
claim they did what they did for all of golf in the Sunshine State.
Bob Duval won the PGA Senior Tour's Emerald Coast Classic in
Pensacola, and son David followed the lead to win The Players
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   He did it with a heroic finish on the final two holes at the TPC
at Sawgrass, knocking his tee shot on the par-3 island hole to 6
feet and fluffing a wedge shot from the back of the green on the
18th to within 1 foot to lock up a two-shot victory over Scott Gump
with the highest winning score (73_285) since the tournament moved
here 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The double victory was the first time a father and a son won on
the same weekend. Dave Stockton Sr. and son Dave nearly did it four
years ago. The father won that Sunday in the Senior TPC
Championship at the TPC of Michigan, and son Dave finished tied for
second in the Greater Hartford Open. This time it happened on a
course where a teenage David Duval watched the tournaments and
dreamed his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only a couple of events I'd rather win,'' said Duval,
who finished at 3 under par and climbed to the No. 1 world ranking
over Tiger Woods with his 10th win in the last 18 months on the PGA
Tour, and third win this season. Duval closed with a remarkable 59
to win the Bob Hope Classic Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is turning into a dream year already,'' said Duval, ``and
it's only March.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the conclusion of an arduous weekend in a competition
that included 49 of the top 50 players in the world rankings. It
was a test of survival with Saturday winds, rock-hard greens, and
difficult rough around the greens that had players grumbling. Fred
Couples shot the low round of the day (68) and vaulted from a tie
for 40th into a tie for fourth. Nick Price (73_288) was solo third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was survival of the fittest,'' said Gump, whose 71_287 was
one of just five rounds below par-72. He was in contention until he
saw his 8-iron shot on the par-3 17th go into the water. He revived
with a 5-iron to 15 feet on the 18th to set up a birdie and
squarely put the pressure on Duval, who had the 17th and 18th holes
left to play.
</P>
<P>
   The wedge Duval hit on the 17th was the shot of the tournament.
It settled within 6 feet of the pin, and he made it. The tee shot
was so demanding, Duval said he remembered the year Price won and
just walked up to the shot and hit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just walked up, grabbed his club, and hit it,'' said Duval.
``I kept that in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval's birdie at 17 gave him a two-shot lead and all he had to
do was stay away from the water that cuts into the fairway on the
left side of the green at 18. Duval's tee shot kicked into the
light cut of rough, his second shot rolled off the back side of the
green, and he hit a soft, lofted wedge to within 1 foot to the
roars of the partisan crowd cheering for the neighborhood kid.
</P>
<P>
   It was Duval's to win or lose, and as he played out the 14th
hole to the first of two consecutive bogeys, somebody informed him
his father had won the Emerald Coast Classic. Now it was the son's
turn to perform on the First Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him last night,'' said Duval, ``and I told him not
to think about winning. You're going to think about that tomorrow
so don't waste energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming to this tournament for years. I've played in
it five times. I was born and raised in Jacksonville. We moved out
to the beach when I was a junior in high school. I've been here as
a spectator for 15 years, and my dad used to work in the scoring
tents. I'd always have a hat for him, and he'd have the players
sign it when they finished with the scorecards. I dreamt about
winning it, but I don't know if I ever thought I was going to win
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval won because he survived, holing out from a trap on the
par-4 ninth to set things in motion after missing the green on the
par-3 eighth and making a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out a little tentative,'' he said after yanking his
first two tee shots to the left and starting out with a bogey. ``I
said, `I have two options. I just said it's time to play golf and
let's go and see what happens.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The $900,000 first-prize money lifted his earnings for the year
to more than $2.1 million and he became No. 1 on the world list
after Woods held the ranking for the last 41 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew starting out that if I made 18 pars I'd win for sure,''
said Duval who at one point Saturday led by five shots before the
severity of the course set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were nerves all day, but I think you just learn to know
what they feel like and accept them and move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
