<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7677 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-PURDUE-DUKE-HNS &LR;      03-29 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-DUKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Quite often, even a veteran actor or actress
can come a little unraveled when the curtain goes up.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Purdue, in its first trip to an NCAA Tournament
championship, can empathize.
</P>
<P>
   After playing tentatively and being unable to put the ball in
the basket through the first 20 minutes, the Boilermakers were
taking curtain calls Sunday night after a 62-45 victory over the
Duke Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   They had rebounded from the most dismal performance in a half in
the 17-year-old tournament to claim the first NCAA women's title
for the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Purdue accomplished that feat playing the final 4:01
without its star player, All-American Stephanie White-McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   The senior from West Lebanon, Ind., was helped off the floor
after spraining her left ankle during a fight for a rebound under
the Purdue basket. She left on crutches after the game but paused
before leaving San Jose Arena long enough to express joy over
finishing her collegiate career a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're just really excited,'' she said. ``I'm so happy
for this team. We've come so far. Everybody just stepped up. And
Ukari (Figgs) carried us.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who had only four points during a first half in which the
Boilermakers shot 28.6 percent and scored a tournament-record-low
17 points, broke out for 14 points in the second half as Purdue
outscored Duke 45-23.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who had 24 points in a 77-63 semifinal win over Louisiana
Tech on Friday, was named the Most Outstanding Player of the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew in the first half I was tentative going to the
basket,'' she said. ``I was settling for outside shots. But I came
out more aggressively in the second half because I just wanted us
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgs and White-McCarty have become close friends over the past
three years. With her chum sitting on the sideline nursing the
ankle sprain, Figgs went over during a timeout and delivered a
short inspirational speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told her, `We've been through this before. I'm just
going to go out and put everything on the line for us,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Sunday's victory came on the same arena floor where
the Boilermakers (34-1) suffered their only defeat, 73-72 to
Stanford in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue might not have gotten to the winner's circle had it not
been for Figgs, Katie Douglas (13 points, five rebounds) and a
solid defensive effort that held Duke in check.
</P>
<P>
   But sophomore center Camille Cooper's steady play was crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camille played very big for us,'' said Figgs. ``She knew she
had a big assignment going up against (6-6) Michele VanGorp, a
sophomore going against an All-American. But she played well for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was 5-for-9 for the night and had 13 points, seven
rebounds and a blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   As might have been expected, the Blue Devils were on the
opposite end of the emotional spectrum from the Boilermakers by the
end of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed for our team,'' said Duke coach Gail
Goestenkors. ``We'd come such a long way. We had been playing our
best basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's a disappointment when your last game doesn't come up
to what you've been doing before. But it's been a wonderful
journey. I'm very proud for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke finished its most successful season at 29-7.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue broke the game open with a 10-1 run near the start of the
second half. Figgs had six points during the run as Purdue mounted
a 40-31 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the locker room disappointed at halftime,'' said
Figgs. ``I felt like I had let my team down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been tentative; I wasn't attacking the basket. I knew
that I had 20 minutes left to either win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I didn't want to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, also in the national championship round for the first
time, was almost as jittery as Purdue during the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers and missed shots in bunches by both squads probably
had TV viewers channel surfing long before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue was 8-for-28 from the floor in the opening period, Duke
an almost-as-dismal 9-for-23.
</P>
<P>
   But despite that and 11 turnovers, the Blue Devils led 22-17 at
the break.
</P>
<P>
   The combined point total (39) was the lowest for a half in the
history of the tournament, surpassing the 50 by Auburn and
Louisiana Tech in the 1988 title game.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 points by Purdue were a record low, beating the 19 by the
Lady Techsters in '88.
</P>
<P>
   But Figgs caught fire as Purdue broke out of a 30-all tie to go
up 40-31 with 9:53 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers were ahead only 47-42 when White-McCarty was
taken to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   But they used 10 straight free throws and a steal by Figgs in
the final 3:09 to take home the Sears Trophy symbolic of their
national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is just so special,'' said Figgs. ``Any time you win
a championship is special, but this one means so much more because
of the closeness on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody goes down, we rally for them. I think we did that
at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp had 15 points to lead the Blue Devils. No other Duke
player reached double figures.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp was selected to the Final Four first-team squad along
with teammate Nicole Erickson, the team scoring leader who was held
to eight points, and Figgs, Douglas and White-McCarty of Purdue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
