u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAFINAL-BOS     03-29 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN HAS DATE WITH DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 FINAL-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MARK BLAUDSCHUN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Rarely has a college basketball season
had such a tidy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, No. 1 now, No. 1 at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   UConn, No. 1 for 10 consecutive weeks in the middle of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, chasing its third national championship in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   UConn, seeking its first national championship and looking to
become the first New England team since Holy Cross in 1947 to win a
national title.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the teams are an astonishing 70-3. No other team has
been ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at Tropicana Field, the Blue Devils and Huskies
will play for the 1999 NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be any `this' or `that' '', said UConn
forward Kevin Freeman, who appeared tired of hearing all the talk
of Duke's invincibility. ``Duke has 40 minutes to prove it. We have
40 minutes to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, a winner of all its games since losing in the last second
to Cincinnati in a tournament in Alaska in November, is the
favorite, which puts UConn (33-2) in the role of underdog for one
of the few times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Even Huskies coach Jim Calhoun concedes Duke (37-1) deserves the
accolades. ``Clearly, what they've done during the season, by not
only the quantity of wins, but quality of wins and the way they
played, they played as the most dominant team in college basketball
in a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Calhoun is not conceding anything. ``We are 33-2,'' he said.
``We've had a reasonably decent season ourselves. We've been
brilliant at times. We have been pragmatic at times. We've survived
at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke has done more than survive. It has glided over, pushed
through, and run past everyone since that loss to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday someone suggested that carrying the role of a favorite
might have added to the Devils' burden Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it has not been taxing,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski, ``because we don't talk about it. We just talk about
getting better and having fun playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke has done that and done it easily, until Saturday night's
68-62 win over Michigan State in the semifinals. So physical was
the game that Coach K reportedly gave his team Sunday off.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way, Duke's excellence and dominance has energized
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   UConn guard Khalid El-Amin said he has been focused on the
Devils for a long time. ``Ever since the season started, we have
been hoping to have the opportunity to play Duke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders why. If there is a weakness in the Devils' game, no
one has found it. Most people think there will be two key battles.
Underneath, where UConn's Jake Voskuhl and assorted friends will
attempt to handle Duke's Elton Brand, college basketball's Player
of the Year. And in the backcourt, where Duke's William Avery and
UConn's Ricky Moore, high school teammates in Augusta, Ga., could
face off.
</P>
<P>
   It also will be a game of similar styles. Both teams excel at
the transition game. Krzyzewski calls the Huskies the best
offensive transition team in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The odds say Duke will become the first team to win a national
championship with one or no losses since Indiana did it in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The matchups suggest that Duke is a little stronger, a little
quicker, a little more talented.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn, when it plays the way it did against Stanford during
the regular season and against St. John's in the Big East
tournament championship game, has some things going for it in the
tenacity of Moore on defense, the immense skill and smoothness of
Richard Hamilton, and the toughness of El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the season,'' said El-Amin, ``we felt we were
on the road to the national championship. Now we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Duke is waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
