<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-VOSKUHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOSKUHL WILL BE KEY FOR UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ If, as Kevin Freeman suggested, the task
the University of Connecticut's basketball team faces in Monday
night's NCAA championship game against Duke is akin to the blinding
of a cyclops, then it likely will fall upon more than one Husky to
lead the charge against the one Blue Devil who poses the same
threat as the mythical goliath: Elton Brand, a 6-foot-8-inch,
260-pound sophomore center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's like a big cyclops,'' Freeman said, drawing
laughter from the assembled media during Sunday's Final Four press
conference at Tropicana Field, ``and you've got to just try to take
the eye out of him and beat them, the entire team. You can't just
take the head off.''
</P>
<P>
   But who will provide UConn's first line of defense in the
frontcourt?
</P>
<P>
   Who likely will draw the assignment of going eyeball-to-eyeball
against Brand?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   He stands 6-11, weighs 245 pounds, has a disarming smile, a
soft-spoken manner, and blond surfer-boy looks (with a moptop to
match) that belie his Katy, Texas, roots (the same town that
sprouted Roger Clemens). In short, Voskuhl's choirboy image
inspires so little fear in opponents that when he jogs out onto the
court Monday night, Brand will not be inclined to want to run home
to momma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really see any advantages I have over him yet,'' said
Brand of Voskuhl. ``We didn't get a chance to watch any film. I
just watched him two or three times on TV during the season. In the
game (Saturday) night, he was in foul trouble like I was, so he
didn't really play that much. So I have not really had a chance to
look at him as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for Voskuhl. Monday night will be the first time they lay
eyes on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him or even run into him in the halls here,''
said Voskuhl. ``I didn't get a chance to see him a lot (Saturday)
night, but throughout the year they've been on TV so much that I've
seen him a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with a player like him, he's so really good, you can't
really say you're going to stop him and that he's not going to do
anything,'' he added. ``You just try to contain him and hope that
he really doesn't go off on you. But I feel like I'm really
fortunate to have a teammate like Kevin Freeman, who is a great
help defender. So, I'll be counting upon Kevin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Freeman, like the rest of the Huskies, will be counting on
Voskuhl to stay out of foul trouble and play more than the 19
minutes he logged in UConn's 64-58 victory over Ohio State
Saturday. Voskuhl's line vs. the Buckeyes: 2 points, 5 rebounds, 1
assist, 1 turnover, 1 blocked shot, 1 steal and, oh yes, 5 fouls.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Voskuhl's second disqualification of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for me to be out there longer than 19
minutes,'' Voskuhl said. ``I've just got to play smarter, really.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in a game in which he no doubt will have to battle Brand
fiercly, Voskuhl expressed some concern about how flexible the
officials were going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say, with the NCAA Tournament it's like the
officiating is different,'' said Voskuhl, who averages 5.6 points
and 6.5 rebounds, but ranks as the runaway team leader in fouls
(103). ``You really have to try and adjust to the officiating,
because they are all getting watched by everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the year, you normally get the same officials, but
you kind of know how they're going to call it, and they know how
you play. Sometimes we've had the same officials, but it seems like
in the NCAAs things are a little bit different, so it's just a
matter of adjusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl, however, did say there was one Big East official he
hoped to see calling the championship game. ``Tim Higgins,''
Voskuhl said, unabashedly. ``He and I really get along well. I
haven't seen him yet, so maybe he'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand also was plagued by foul trouble in Duke's 68-62 victory
over a physical Michigan State squad, but still scored 18 points
and grabbed 15 rebounds (13 in the first half).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great number, 13 in one half, '' Voskuhl marveled.
``But we just have to try and box him out. I have to play solid.
He's proven he can score on anybody in the country. Just to foul
him is not going to be the most intelligent thing to do. It's
important to make players play both ends of the court. He's kind of
the heart of their team, and when he's playing well they're really
at the top of their game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
