<SLUG> BC-HKC-MICHIGANSTATE-COLORADOCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE STUNS COLORADO COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Live by the quick strike, perish by the quick
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado College rode a three-goals-in-42-seconds explosion to a
first-round win over St. Lawrence in the NCAA hockey tournament
West Regional Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And the Tigers were sent back to Colorado Springs Sunday when
Michigan State pulled a similar trick.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 3-2, with under two minutes left to play, the Spartans
stunned the Tigers with two goals _ both of them reviewed on video
_ in 32 seconds for a 4-3 win in their regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State improved to 29-5-7 and earned a berth in the
Frozen Four in Anaheim. The Spartans take on the University of New
Hampshire in a semifinal game Thursday at Arrowhead Pond. Colorado
headed for home 29-12-1.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Michigan State found success in the NCAA Tournament.
The Spartans are back in the Frozen Four for the first time since
1992. They had lost six straight tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden hasn't been bad for me,'' said Michigan State coach
Ron Mason. ``I've been there lots of times before and had won a
bunch and I won a championship, fortunately they can't say you
can't win the big one. But it's nice for the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden might have been there for them, he said. And it
looked that way from the way the Spartans celebrated on the ice and
as they came off it.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans appeared headed for a seventh straight loss when
Colorado College took a 3-2 lead on a Trent Clark goal with 8:39
left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were still on top when Paul Weaver was called for
interference with 3:01 left, a call CC coach Don Lucia did not
like.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of a series of bad breaks for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   First, Spartan freshman Andrew Hutchinson shot the puck toward
traffic and the net and it beat a screened Jeff Sanger. The play
was reviewed to see if a Spartan was in the crease, and was allowed
to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two seconds later, the Spartans struck again. Freshman
Adam Hall took a shot that bounced off the glove of Sanger and
popped slowly into the net for his second goal of the game. That
score, too, was reviewed to make sure the puck went over the goal
line. It also counted.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Colorado College folks figured it, it was a fitting
end to a tough, injury-filled season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't get any breaks today,'' said senior defenseman
Scott Swanson. ``It's kind of been the way it's been all year. We
haven't gotten key bounces or key calls to go the right way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
