<HEADER>
A7684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-MAINE-BOS &LR;      03-29 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE RELYS ON MICHAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Alfie Michaud's name is not listed on the
Hockey East All-Star team, but more importantly for the University
of Maine junior goaltender, it most definitely is inscribed on a
plane ticket to Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud, who backstopped Maine to a pair of victories over the
weekend, 4-2 over Ohio State and 7-2 over Clarkson in the NCAA
Tournament East Regional in Worcester, is heading west with his
teammates for hockey's Frozen Four and a shot at the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   About Michaud's 22-save performance against Ohio State, which
included a perfect 11 for 11 in the second period when Maine was
nursing a 2-1 lead, Black Bears coach Shawn Walsh noted that
``Alfie made some great saves. He's led the Hockey East Tournament
in save percentage the past two years and he showed why against
Ohio State. He didn't even get a vote for honorable mention (in
Hockey East) and I was stunned at that. But he's a positional
goalie. He doesn't look flashy.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh showed his appreciation for Michaud's play the following
night, when, with the Black Bears in front of Clarkson by five
goals with 90 seconds to play, he took Michaud out so Maine fans
could give him an ovation.
</P>
<P>
   It was well-deserved because Maine was in a tight spot after
Clarkson's Paul Evans beat Michaud on a penalty shot at 16:52 of
the middle period to close the gap to 4-2. Maine still had to kill
two penalties called even before Evans's score.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Michaud stood his ground, blanking Clarkson for the
rest of the period and the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's past is past and I can't change the past. That's been
my thinking all season. There are 3,600 seconds in a hockey game
and 500 more in (regular-season) overtime and all you can do is
play for each moment,'' said Michaud, who as a youngster in
Selkirk, Manitoba, faced some unusual family pressure.
</P>
<P>
   His dad and nine uncles toughened him up by shooting tee-balls
at Alfie in the basement of his home. ``They made me stay in there
even if I cried,'' he recalled with a smile and a bit of a wince,
``and I stayed with it because I wanted to be a goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   When a friend urged him to give junior hockey a try, the pair
traveled to Saskatchewan, where Michaud was his league's rookie of
the year for the Lebret Eagles. A scholarship to Maine soon
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud had a respectable 32-20-5 record at Maine entering this
season, but there were no trips to the NCAA Tournament until this
year. Michaud's save percentage improved from .864 and .890 his
first two years to .906 this season, a reflection of the goalie's
and team's commitment to defense and Michaud's steadier play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played excellent defensively all year. That's been our
backbone,'' said Walsh. Added standout defenseman David Cullen,
``Our defensive style is our bread and butter. We try not to allow
any odd-man rushes and play a smart game. We try to let Alfie make
the long saves and take away the second shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula has worked so well that entering the Frozen Four,
Michaud, whose record this season is 26-6-3 (Maine is 29-6-4), has
been forced to make 30 or more saves only twice this season _ and
he responded well on both occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The first was Jan. 3 at Colorado when his 33 stops were key in a
3-3 overtime tie. The second came five days later as Michaud's 38
saves were the difference in a 2-1 victory at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to the big games and now the tournament games are what
you play hockey for,'' he said. ``Listening to tapes on mental
toughness have helped me. Last year, I was very inconsistent. I'd
lose my confidence quick and it was like being on a roller-coaster
ride. Now nothing gets to me. I really take it one second at a
time. I'm enjoying the game. I'm playing for the moment. I listened
to the tapes before I went to bed the night before the (Clarkson)
game and twice before it and that helped me relax and focus at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a rough start last year, but now he's the epitome of
consistency,'' said Walsh. ``And he's able to bounce back. When we
beat UNH (4-3) in February, Alfie gave up two questionable goals.
But when it was a 3-3 game in the third period, he made two
scintillating saves. He's getting better and somebody's going to
enjoy picking him and I hope he gets a shot (in the pros) after
college because he's such a wonderful kid. I want whatever's best
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But as calm and cool as Michaud was during the regionals, there
was a moment of personal emotion immediately after the Clarkson
game.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud's immediate thoughts were of Rich Britt, the team's
assistant trainer and equipment manager, who died last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dickie said the week before he passed away that his dream was
for the team to get to Anaheim and we wanted to get there for him.
I think he was looking down on us and smiling on us tonight,''
Michaud said with a shaky voice. Michaud helped set the tone for
the victory when he spread-eagled in the first minute to snag a
Clarkson drive with his glove 6 inches off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud expects his immediate family, which drove 22 hours to
Denver in January to see him play, to hop in the car for the
Manitoba-to-California trip this week. ``But,'' he said with a
laugh, ``it's a long ride, 10 hours more than to Denver. They're
probably in the car now.''
</P>
<P>
   With some tee-balls in the trunk, just in case Michaud wants
some extra practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
