<SLUG> BC-HKW-WHCA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD REVELS IN TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
 FINAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ For the 24 new national champs, the night had been
too short to fit in all the joy; too fleeting to replay all the
special moments; too brief to accommodate that much happiness.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Crimson needed overtime to defeat the University of
New Hampshire, 6-5, Saturday night to win the American Women's
College Hockey Alliance Division 1 title in a game that didn't end
until 11:18 EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just eight bleary hours later, they and their coaches were
settling into their seats on Northwest Airlines Flight 720, its
overhead racks bursting with bouquets and a treasured trophy
ensconced safely, and appropriately, in First Class.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep? ``Not a wink,'' said A.J. Mleczko, who ended her Harvard
career with an assist on Jen Botterill's game-winning goal. ``I
don't think any of us did. We had a lot of celebrating to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Which they went about doing until 20 minutes before the buses
left for the airport, thanks to a party thrown by the same local
Harvard Club that feted the men's hockey team when it won the NCAA
title in St. Paul 10 years ago. Even the pep band got in the act,
until the nice people at the Radisson Metrodome had to invoke a
trumpet curfew.
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting the party go on all night: There was a lot
to celebrate in a season that not only saw Harvard win its first
conference tournament game in the 20-year-old program, but go on to
win the ECAC tournament and national title after winning a
team-record 33 games (the previous best was 19) and scoring more
goals (218) in a season than any previous Crimson squad, men's
(191) or women's (118).
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had the foundation,'' said coach Katey Stone of her
team, which went 14-16 last season for the most wins in nine years.
``I knew we could make a run for the national championship. To say
we'd be 33-1? No.''
</P>
<P>
   But to that foundation returned Mleczko, back from a two-year
absence training for the 1998 US Olympic team, and Tammy Shewchuk,
a Canadian national team member who just missed making that
nation's Olympic team. Add to that incoming freshmen Botterill, a
Canadian Olympic-team forward, and Angela Ruggiero, an intimidating
defenseman for the US squad, and you've got, well, you've got the
new national champions. Of the nation's top six scorers, Mleczko,
Shewchuk, Botterill, and Ruggiero went 1,2,3,6.
</P>
<P>
   In that company, sophomore winger Angie Francisco often was
overlooked, even though she, too, cracks the Top 10. ``Angie's
clutch,'' said Stone after Francisco came through with a hat trick
and an assist in the title game. ``She's a bulldog.''
</P>
<P>
   All season, Stone had emphasized that the Crimson were more than
just the Fab Four, and on Saturday night they proved it again _
again, because in the first round of the ECAC playoffs, they beat
Cornell, 3-2, without either Ruggiero or Botterill, who were
playing for their national teams in the Women's World Championship
_ when Francisco and backup goaltender, freshman Alison Kuusisto,
shared the spotlight. Kuusisto was playing in place of Crystal
Springer, who Friday night against Brown broke the same collarbone
that kept her out for six weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, because it puts a punctuation mark on everything
we tried to tell the kids and convince them of,'' said Stone, who
still barely had snoozed late Sunday afternoon. ``The egos were
parked at the door, and it was all about team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
