<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLDFIGURESKATING-BO     03-29 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SKATERS NEED TO GET SHARPER 
</HEADLINE>
 FIGURE SKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI _ They came here during slush-and-gravel season with
modest expectations. Tara Lipinski is a pro. Todd Eldredge is on
``active rest'' and was here purely as a spectator. Last year's top
pair and dance couples have split up or moved on.
</P>
<P>
   The US figure skating team was filled with rookies and a
13-year-old who made the roster through a loophole. In other words,
the usual post-Olympic reconstruction project. ``This was a
developing team,'' said Audrey Weisiger, who coaches Michael Weiss.
And with the Winter Games in Salt Lake City still three years off,
the Americans are still a hardhat zone.
</P>
<P>
   When the world championships ended here Saturday night, the US
had won two medals but golden girl Michelle Kwan had lost her crown
to 26-year-old Maria Butyrskaya. And the Russians had the best week
that they or anybody else have had at this annual all-skate.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first to win all four events, going 1-2 in men's
with teenagers Alexei Yagudin and Evgeni Plushenko and 1-3 in
women's with Butyrskaya and 17-year-old Julia Soldatova.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks, who failed to win a gold medal for the first time in
four years, could only observe that three of the four Russian
champions were made, or at least polished, in America. Yagudin and
the pair of Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze train in New
Jersey, dancers Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsyannikov in Delaware.
Maybe some of the Russian gold dust will rub off on their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   For consolation prizes the Americans had Kwan's silver and
Weiss's bronze, but they weren't as concerned about winning medals
as they were about losing spots for next year's championships in
Brisbane. All but four of their 16 skaters were either here for the
first time or came with new partners. But when the count was done,
the slippage wasn't as bad as feared.
</P>
<P>
   Though the US dropped from three to two entries in men's and
pairs as expected, it retained two in dance when Naomi Lang and
Peter Tchernyshev cracked the top 10. And the women, who were on
the bubble after Kwan crashed in the short program, pulled through
when 13-year-old Sarah Hughes, the youngest skater in the field,
finished a serendipitous seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than I ever could have imagined,'' said Hughes,
who's two years under the age limit but qualified because she's a
world junior medalist. ``It was just so much fun. I don't know what
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes and fellow 13-year-old Naomi Nari Nam, who beat her at
the US championships but isn't a world junior medalist, are both
good enough to make the 2002 Olympic team. The question is how long
the 18-year-old Kwan will stick around. ``She's never said one word
about stopping,'' says coach Frank Carroll. But Kwan is planning on
starting college in the fall and will be hearing this week from
Harvard, Stanford, Cal-Berkeley, and UCLA, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan insists she'll be able to balance skating and academics.
``I will compete,'' she says. ``I can't walk out of the rink and
not want to go back. This is what I love doing. I love the
pressure. I love the stress. I love going backstage after the
warmup and going `arrrgghhh.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But can Kwan be a full-time coed and still keep her skills at an
Olympian level? It's a hazy forecast all around for the Yanks. Will
the 27-year-old Eldredge, the former world and five-time US champ,
come back? Or will he decide that he no longer fits in a world
where men are doing a quadruple jump in the short program and two
in the long?
</P>
<P>
   Will Weiss be able to juggle fatherhood and skating for three
more winters? Will 18-year-old Tim Goebel, who landed the first
quad salchow-triple toe combination at a world event, develop the
artistry he needs to be a global contender? Can the pairs and
dancers get anywhere near a podium before Salt Lake comes around?
</P>
<P>
   For the rebuilding Yanks, last week was an introduction to the
ozone _ and an initiation. ``This is big,'' concluded Danielle
Hartsell after she and brother Steve, the new US pairs titlists,
finished 10th in their world debut. ``But we have one under our
belt now. Next year, we'll know what to expect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
