   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Allied warplanes braved bad weather
Sunday night to step up attacks on Yugoslav troops while NATO
officials repeatedly accused Serbian forces of large-scale
atrocities in Kosovo. On both sides of the Atlantic, officials were
being asked what they would do if air power failed to halt the
violence against Kosovo's Albanians. Clinton administration
officials, as well as those at NATO headquarters, insisted they had
no intention of committing ground troops. By Adam Clymer. With
attack sites map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Defiant as ever and
proud of his nation's resistance to NATO's air attacks, Slobodan
Milosevic staged an eerie celebration Sunday: a rock concert in the
center of Belgrade to show solidarity with the soldiers facing down
the allied assaults. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BASEBALL-FANS (Havana, Cuba) _ It was a sunny event laced
with nationalism and patriotic feeling, but in the end, the
historic game between the Baltimore Orioles and a team of Cuban
stars played here Sunday was about baseball, and the 50,000 Cubans
who attended walked out with their heads high. By James McKinley.
With photo. (Also moved in ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana, Albania) _ Their Kosovo villages in
flames behind them, tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians were
hounded by Serb forces into Albania in long lines of battered cars
and tractors and on foot, threatening to overwhelm the scant
resources of this desperately poor country and the hasty efforts of
Western aid workers. By John Kifner. With map of refugee movements
out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-PILOT-RESCUE (Washington) _ Shortly after 8:45 p.m.
Saturday in the Balkans, a secretive search-and-rescue team based
with American forces in Bosnia received an urgent phone call: An
F-117 stealth fighter, the premier attack plane in America's
arsenal, was down in Yugoslavia. The fate of the pilot was unknown.
Within minutes, a recovery mission was underway, tapping the
talents of an elite special operations unit poised to pluck downed
pilots from storming seas or from behind enemy lines. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUDAPEST (Budapest, Hungary) _ Warning that NATO's
bombing of Yugoslavia had severely damaged Russia's reationship
with the United States, a Russian delegation met here Sunday with
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke before attempting to travel by
road to neighboring Yugoslavia to present a peace plan to President
Slobodan Milosevic. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB-TV (Undated) _ For Serbs watching
government-controlled Serbian television, the world of the Balkans
is not complex and conflicted, but crystal clear: NATO attacked
Serbia because of a longstanding criminal conspiracy by the West.
Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo are terrorists. And Serbia, above all,
will fight to the last man. By Anthony Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EMAIL (Undated) _ This is the first instance of warfare
where a small but significant slice of the population has Internet
access. The Yugoslavs, a technically savvy group for decades, have
used the Web to create an entire news network consisting of e-mail
exchanges, chat rooms and bulletin boards _ where no rumor is too
small to dissect at length and almost no hamlet too remote to
mention. By Neil MacFarquhhar.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HOOPER (Washington) _ The first NATO missiles and bombs
were only a few hours from striking Yugoslavia when James Hooper,
once the State Department's senior dissenter on Balkan policy,
sipped his coffee a few blocks from the White House and talked of
ground troops likely to follow. It has been two years since Hooper,
the very model of an earnest Foreign Service careerist, quit the
government in frustration after 26 years of toiling at diplomacy.
He joined a handful of pioneer State Department dissenters who left
across two administrations protesting Balkan policy. By Francis X.
Clines. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEDIA (Undated) _ As NATO bombers pummel Yugoslavia,
President Slobodan Milosevic pummels the country's independent
press. Seeking to tighten an official near-monopoly on what Serbs
are told about the war, Milosevic responded to the bombing by
shutting down virtually all the independent newspapers and
silencing the nation's most prominent independent radio station,
B-92. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA (Tetovo) _ Macedonia is now the only former Yugoslav
republic that has peacefully retained an ethnically-mixed society.
The war in Kosovo, waged at Macedonia's borders, is harshly testing
the country's ability to keep itself intact. By Alessandra Stanley.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Ohrid, Macedonia) _ The separatist rebels in
Kosovo are holding out surprisingly well against an apparent major
Serbian offensive in Kosovo, despite losses and a shortage of
ammunition, foreign military observers here say. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CAPETOWN-WAR (Capetown, South Africa) _ Cape Town is in a
three-way war between criminal gangs, the police and a Muslim
anti-crime group calling itself People Against Gangsterism and
Drugs. Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SHEEP-SACRIFICE (Cairo) _ At the start the Eid al-Adha, the
feast of sacrifice, one of the most important festivals on the
Islamic calendar, it's a bad time to be a sheep. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISTS-KILLED (Montego Bay, Jamaica) _ As dictatorships
disappear from the map of Latin America, leaving Cuba as a holdout,
violence against reporters has dropped correspondingly, to 23
journalists killed last year from 41 in 1989. At the same time, as
democratic institutions have taken root in Latin America's big
cities, violence against reporters has shifted to the rural areas,
according to advocates for press freedom gathered here for a
meeting of the Inter American Press Association. By James Brooke.
With graphic.
</P>
