<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-DUKE-PURDUE-600&AMP;A     03-29 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-DUKE-PURDUE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOILERMAKERS DEFEAT DUKE FOR FIRST TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete writethru to reflect final score.)  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ As Purdue's Ukari Figgs and Stephanie
White-McCarty hugged with tears in their eyes at one end of the
court, a similar embrace was taking place several feet away in
front of the Duke bench.
</P>
<P>
   There, a tearful Nicole Erickson and Michele VanGorp _ teammates
of Figgs and White-McCarty before transferring from Purdue to Duke
two years ago _ met. Arm in arm, the two Duke seniors then turned
and left the San Jose Arena court.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs and White-McCarty, who was on crutches because of an ankle
sprain, remained to celebrate Purdue's first National Collegiate
Athletic Association women's basketball championship, a product of
a 62-45 victory over Duke in Sunday night's title game.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited game that reflected both the championship stakes
and the unique personal history between the teams, top-ranked
Purdue overcame White-McCarty's late injury with a second-half
surge.
</P>
<P>
   The total points in the game (107) was the lowest for a women's
NCAA final. In 1988, Louisiana Tech and Auburn combined for 110
points.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's victory also means the Duke men's and women's
basketball teams will not win a double championship, something that
has never happened in Division I college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to White-McCarty, which occurred after she missed a
turnaround jumper near the foul line with four minutes left in the
game, actually appeared to spark Purdue, which scored the next 13
points to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   As White-McCarty _ an all-American and a player of legendary
status in Indiana _ was helped from the court before a hushed
Purdue bench and cheering section, Duke Coach Gail Goestenkors knew
the game had reached a pivotal stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `O.K., this is it,' '' Goestenkors said. ``It's going
to go one way or the other right now. And they tend to rally around
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Purdue bench, there were a few seconds when things
appeared to be in disarray. White-McCarty's face was twisted with
pain and her teammates were in a circle trying to console her. But
Purdue's players said they soon found a resolve to close out the
game and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steph means so much for this program and to all of us,''
Camille Cooper said. ``When she went down, we all knew right there
that we can't lose this ball game now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Duke had led by 5 points at halftime, Figgs, who would
score all of her game-high 18 points in the second half, rallied
Purdue to a 47-39 lead just before White-McCarty slumped to the
court.
</P>
<P>
   But as White-McCarty lay on the court, Duke's Hilary Howard sank
a 3-point shot at the other end. Duke's players, who appeared out
of sync for most of the second half, could sense this might be
their last opportunity to keep Purdue from its 32nd consecutive
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the emotion on the court at that point,'' Howard
said. ``Their star was down, we were making a little run. I was
hoping we get it together for a last, good stretch. But it didn't
happen that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Duke wouldn't score again until the game was one minute
from ending, and by then Purdue had a 60-45 lead. In that stretch,
Purdue made 12 consecutive free throws and 15 of 17 it attempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed because we've come such a long way,'' said
Goestenkors, whose team burst into the college basketball national
spotlight with its upset of Tennessee in the East Regional final
last week. ``It wasn't even close to one of our best games so it's
not the way we envisioned the season ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a wonderful journey.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Purdue Coach Carolyn Peck, who is resigning from Purdue to
become coach and general manager of the Orlando franchise in the
Women's National Basketball Association, said Sunday's victory
would have a big impact on her school's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our first national championship and the first national
championship for a women's Big Ten program,'' Peck said. ``Those
are nice accomplishments. Back home on campus, we have a picture
frame we've been reserving for Purdue's first national championship
team. And these players are going in that picture frame.''
</P>
<P>
   White-McCarty said: ``This is what we stayed for, we stayed for
the opportunity. The group we have on this team makes it special.
It's been a lot of fun and it means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tip, each team played with a fervor that seemed
the byproduct of the closeness of the most pivotal players on the
court _ White-McCarty, Figgs, Erickson and VanGorp.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the intensity was the impact of the game on each
school's program. Neither Duke nor Purdue had ever played in the
national championship game of women's college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But all this led to some nervous play and sloppy basketball.
Halfway through the first half, Duke led, 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke guards were harassed and appeared disorganized as they
attempted to run their offense.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue had larger guards, and the 6-foot-1-inch forward Katie
Douglas, an unsung star of Purdue's defense, also seemed to be
causing size problems for Duke's hottest player in the tournament,
Erickson, who is 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever problems Erickson was having, they were not as
noticeable as the troubles Figgs was having in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who led Purdue with 24 points in its semifinal victory
over Louisiana Tech, was 0 for 7.
</P>
<P>
   The game officials contributed to the helter-skelter nature of
the first half when they called 15 fouls on the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her struggles in the first half, Figgs sparked Purdue's
rally at the midpoint of the second half, scoring 8 points during a
12-1 run that gave the Boilermakers a 40-31 lead.
</P>
<P>
   During this span, Duke turned the ball over on three consecutive
trips down the court as Purdue pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-point shot by Erickson and two strong post moves by VanGorp
that led to easy baskets cut Purdue's lead to 42-38 with eight
minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas sank a 3-point basket from the wing that extended
Purdue's lead to 7 points. Peppi Browne made one of two free
throws, but Purdue's Cooper converted a short jumper to increase
its lead to 47-39 with 4:29 to play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
