<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     03-29 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA, SELANNE SPARK DUCKS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Mighty Ducks are more of a team than they have
ever been, but there's no doubt that as Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne go, so go the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the two Anaheim stars are going pretty good. Two
nights after combining for three goals and seven points in a win
over Dallas, Kariya and Selanne combined for three more goals and
seven points in a 5-1 win over the Calgary Flames before 15,975 at
the Pond on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line has been excellent, especially in the last two
games,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg. ``They have been playing
a great team game and are being rewarded. They aren't cheating for
chances. They are forcing mistakes and turning them into goals.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four games, Kariya and Selanne have combined for 21
points _ 11 by Selanne and 10 by Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Two victories, after a 1-3-2 slump, give the fifth-place Ducks a
four-point cushion on sixth-place St. Louis and move them six in
front of San Jose. The Ducks' 100th win at the Pond also moves them
five games over .500 (33-28-5) for the second time in franchise
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a huge two points for us,'' said Hartsburg. ``With
the win we are 10 (ahead of the eighth-place Flames, who are
battling Edmonton for the final Western Conference playoff spot),
otherwise we'd only be six ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   With a rugged five-game road trip around the corner, the Ducks
gladly took advantage of a tired Calgary team that played Saturday
night in Phoenix, just as they took advantage of a Dallas club that
played the Kings the evening before coming to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were tired, we wanted to keep the tempo up,''
Selanne said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored the first goal of the game when Selanne set up
Kariya at 15:25 of the first period. Kariya got just enough on his
shot from the slot to beat Fred Brathwaite on the stick side for
his 32nd goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks needed nine minutes to record a shot in the second
period, but they needed only a club-record 12 seconds to score
twice and take a 3-0 lead into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne scored his NHL-leading 43rd goal of the year when he
turned defenseman Tommy Albelin inside out and ripped a slap shot
past the helpless Brathwaite at 18:07.
</P>
<P>
   Albelin then was victimized by Kariya, who beat him to the puck
behind the net and centered to Jeff Nielsen. Alone in the slot,
Nielsen had little trouble beating Brathwaite for his fourth of the
season at 18:19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously that was huge,'' Selanne said. ``Right now it's just
nice to be playing with the chemistry clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   After Selanne set up Kariya for a breakaway goal at 7:10, the
Flames seemed determined to go after the Anaheim winger.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne was hit hard twice before Hartsburg countered by putting
Stu Grimson on the ice. Grimson had one thing on his mind, and that
was goading Dave Roche into a fight. A slash by the Ducks enforcer
finally did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Grimson picked up an extra two minutes on the play and when Ted
Drury received a double-minor for high sticking the Ducks were two
men down, and Guy Hebert's shutout was in jeopardy. Anaheim killed
off all but four seconds of the two-man disadvantage before Valeri
Bure beat Hebert with a shot that bounced off the post and in.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert lost his shutout, but his 29th victory of the season tied
his own club record set in the 1996-97 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
