<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7800 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-REVIEW-9     03-29 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-REVIEW-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUESSES THAT TURNED OUT WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ If anyone has ever wondered how wars begin,
they begin like this: Two sides, starting from different principles
and world views, back one another into a trap of their own rhetoric
and mythologies.
</P>
<P>
   If the West miscalculated President Slobodan Milosevic's
willingness to invite NATO-led troops into Kosovo, the southern
Serb province, the Yugoslav leader may at the same time have
miscalculated his own freedom to solve the problem he created.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic rose to power on the issue of the minority Serbs in
Kosovo, the province from which Serbs derive their defining myths
of nationalism, victimization and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he promised Kosovo's Serbs that ``no one will be
allowed to beat you'' and that Kosovo would remain in Serbia
forever. When he did that, said Slavko Curuvija, a Yugoslav
journalist who was standing next to a shaking Milosevic at the
time, ``he suddenly became the leader of all Serbs and the Serb
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But that path led Milosevic and the Serbs toward widespread
ethnic cleansing and killing through much of what once made up
Yugoslavia. The Serbs certainly misjudged how much revulsion this
would stir in the West. On the other hand, the notion of martyrdom
in Kosovo is so deeply ingrained in Serbian mythology that the West
likewise seems to have miscalculated Milosevic's ability to walk
away from Kosovo once the battle there had been joined.
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs, Kosovo is their Jerusalem, the holy touchstone
and center of their existence as a nation despite all the defeats
and travails of history. It was in Kosovo, in 1389, on the Field of
Blackbirds, that Serb forces lost a mighty battle to the Ottoman
Turks, who then ruled Serbia for the next 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbs regard themselves as having kept the flame of
their nation alive, with Kosovo as its bleeding heart. They
regained Kosovo by force in 1912, in the First Balkan War, when the
crumbling Ottoman empire was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Serb nationalism was the distant spark that touched off World
War I, and the Serbian nation that resurfaced in this century still
has enormous complexes. Serbs still consider themselves a
misunderstood Christian nation on the edges of Western
civilization, patronized, mistreated and pushed around by more
powerful states, even as they bravely draw the line today against a
new Muslim expansionism in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's current bombing campaign to protect Kosovo's Albanians
feeds into all those Serb mythologies, and for now, at least, has
strengthened Milosevic's support at home. Again and again over the
last week, Serbs of widely differing backgrounds have said they
have no great love for Milosevic, who is bringing destruction to
the country, but that they support his refusal to allow foreign
troops into Kosovo as an intolerable infringement of Serbia's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Milosevic has drawn the wagons more closely around
himself, firing critics in the army and elsewhere who express
dissent even privately, and not always getting the best
information, Western negotiators and Yugoslav officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not have believed until the end that NATO really meant
to bomb him,'' said a Yugoslav official with ties to the
presidency. ``But Kosovo is too big a prize for him and for all of
us, and the West really offered us nothing in return, only this
pretense that we would remain legally sovereign.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. negotiator long involved with the effort to
negotiate a peaceful solution for Kosovo expressed some wonderment
when the final visit to Milosevic by the U.S. diplomat Richard
Holbrooke produced no movement. ``We thought that faced with the
choice of having NATO-led troops in Kosovo and getting bombed, that
he would prefer the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   This miscalculation was a part of the larger U.S. assumption
about Milosevic, based on the experience in Bosnia, that he would
always bend to superior force to preserve his power. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright has long argued that ``the only language
Milosevic understands is force.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was able to walk away from Sarajevo when it was
included in the Bosnian Muslim zone under the Dayton accords of
1995, and he could survive the cleansing of Serbs from the Krajina
region when Croatia's forces drove them out earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo is different. Bosnia was never an integral part of
the Serb nation or myth, as Kosovo is, and it was independent, as
Kosovo is not. The Serbs were losing anyway by the time the
Americans got around to trying to stop that war in 1995, and
Milosevic had a lot to gain by suddenly turning into the West's
crucial partner in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic may yet bend, says a Yugoslav analyst, Bratislav
Grubacic, who has close ties to part of the regime. But he notes
that Milosevic's wife, Mira Markovic, is a more nationalistic and
ideological figure than her husband and is fond of saying, ``You
can defeat us, but you cannot convince us.''
</P>
<P>
   Her logic, which Milosevic seems to accept, is that to
effectively give away Kosovo by signing the peace accords would
destroy their claim to leadership, Grubacic said. ``But if we lose
Kosovo in a war, we have the legal basis to reconquer it in 100
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yugoslav army is doing its best to destroy the
Kosovo Liberation Army and leave ethnic Albanians a calling card
they will long remember.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Milosevic may have outsmarted himself, Curuvija suggested.
Having ridden Kosovo to power and having set that genie free, it
may have turned out to be his captor. ``After all Milosevic has
said and done since 1987 to bind Kosovo to Serbia, if now he said,
`To hell with all that,' and signed the deal, he'd be dead,''
Curuvija said. ``I told American officials that a policy intended
to push Milosevic to the wall over Kosovo, to act as they want or
to be killed, is the worst policy, that they had to find another
way with him, to find a way to make him a partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, says Grubacic, the West has pushed Milosevic into
embracing his isolation to preserve his power at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a suicidal policy, and he may finish like Hitler in the
bunker,'' Grubacic said. ``But he will be remembered in Serb
mythology history as someone who said `no' to the dissolution of
the nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
