<HEADER>
A7802 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CAMPAIGN-CONDUCT-RE     03-29 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CAMPAIGN-CONDUCT-REVIEW-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRINNING WITH THE ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the candidates are to be believed, the unfolding
presidential campaign will be a high-toned, polite affair.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, in a mailing to
prospective supporters, pledged never to lambaste ``my friends and
colleagues'' in the race. Former Vice President Dan Quayle made the
same vow. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said he has never run an
attack commercial _ and is not about to start now. Among Democrats,
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey has no plans to resort to
biting rebukes to catch up to the favorite, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Will debates, therefore, more resemble tea parties? Instead of
those commercials featuring grainy, villainous images of their
rivals, will politicians promote themselves frolicking through
clover?
</P>
<P>
   Don't put away your television clicker just yet.
</P>
<P>
   While candidates sense that people are repulsed by the vitriolic
discourse in Washington _ and pollsters warn that attacks can
boomerang _ virtually no one in politics believes that the days of
dark, dirty presidential campaigns are over. There will always be
one candidate who is winning and one candidate who is losing. And
the candidate who is behind almost invariably will seek to alter
the dynamic by discrediting his or her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the impeachment imbroglio, politicians are
especially sensitive to the accusation that they would rather
slaughter their enemies than save the republic. So the trick now is
to deploy attack strategies without seeming to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
recently warned his party's contenders that they risk ``a
bloodbath'' unless they abide Ronald Reagan's 11th Commandment:
``Thou shalt not speak ill of a fellow Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Axelrod, a veteran Democratic strategist in Chicago,
said that may be for naught. ``We've heard about the 11th
Commandment for a decade,'' he said, ``but the First Commandment of
politics is: `Thou shall not lose!'''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians can promise not to go negative and then go negative
anyway because they hold divergent views of what constitutes an
out-of-bounds remark or advertisement. Asked to define negative
campaigning, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, who is seeking the
Republican nomination, was not entirely joking last week when he
replied, ``Any attacks made on me!''
</P>
<P>
   No candidate, of course, likes to fess up to going too far after
an opponent. A prime example is Steve Forbes, who pumped roughly
$35 million of his personal fortune into commercials that bashed
his opponents in 1996. His attacks were so thermonuclear that his
brief burst of support in the polls began to hemorrhage, leaving
opponents (using his given name) to deride Forbes as ``Malcolm the
Mudslinger.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire in February 1996, Forbes conceded that he had
``spent too much time talking about the inconsistencies and
shortcomings of my opponents.'' He added, ``When you make a
mistake, you learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week Forbes, who is making a second try for the
nomination, was at it again: He began running radio commercials in
the pivotal states of Iowa and New Hampshire, accusing Gore of
``hiding while his liberal friends do his dirty work'' _ attacking
Republicans on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Upon reflection, Forbes insisted that he was not out of line
last time. ``To me, the 11th Commandment means no personal attacks,
talking about rumors, drinking, that sort of thing,'' he said.
``Our ads were about issues, particularly the tax issue. And unlike
other campaigns, which should remain nameless, we never did phone
calls in the middle of the night, `If you vote for Mr. X, you know
he poisons cats.''' (Forbes' commercials also delved into such
matters as raising questions about the financial practices of his
opponents.)
</P>
<P>
   While Kasich said he would never make personal attacks, he
pleaded ignorance when asked whether the Forbes commercials in 1996
were appropriate. ``What my problem is, is I don't watch a lot of
television,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain argued that Forbes served as a case study in negative
campaigning. ``What's the definition of a negative ad?'' he asked.
``I remember the Forbes campaign commercials: `August something,
1991. Bob Dole voted for a gondola in Idaho!' When asked, the
Forbes campaign said, `Well, that's his voting record.' Well, it
wasn't his voting record. It was an omnibus goddamn appropriations
bill that had nothing to do with the gondola!''
</P>
<P>
   For all of McCain's indignation, Darrell West, a professor of
political science at Brown University, said he was not convinced
that the senator would stay on the high road. ``I'll believe it
when I see it,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling how George Bush ridiculed Michael Dukakis in the 1998
campaign _ and Dukakis never responded _ West said: ``Nobody wants
to get Dukakis-ized. Nobody wants to be the candidate who is
attacked but doesn't respond, because the risk in that situation is
that the negatives will stick.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since elections are inherently comparative exercises, the
question always comes down to how much comparing a candidate should
do. Tone is important, too; Does ominous music transform a
commercial into a negative commercial?
</P>
<P>
   By promising not to engage in negative campaigning, candidates
try to persuade voters that they are above sinking into mud. Former
Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee cultivated such an image, but he
has not ruled out running negative advertisements in his current
campaign, arguing that his failure to respond to attacks cost him
the New Hampshire primary in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander neglects to tell people that he ran the first negative
advertisement in New Hampshire in 1996, attacking then-Gov. Pete
Wilson of California on the radio for increasing taxes and pledging
to serve a second full term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic contest has the potential to get nasty as well.
Gore has a Boy Scout reputation, but he first raised the issue of
Massachusetts' prison furloughs in a debate in the 1988 primaries.
Bush's supporters picked up the idea and cited the furlough of
Willie Horton in perhaps the most devastating commercials against
Dukakis in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McSlarrow, Quayle's campaign chairman, said that maybe
campaigning will be cleaner in 2000. ``All of us watched what
happened to Bob Dole when he was running out of money as he was
getting pounded right and left _ he couldn't get off the mat for
months,'' he said. ``Nobody wants whoever the nominee is to get
wounded again.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who cling to Reagan's approach should be mindful that
he was no shrinking violet. In scathing remarks about President
Gerald Ford's foreign policy in March of 1976, Reagan accused him
of ``a timid, vacillating and divided leadership.'' The father of
the 11th Commandment had violated it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
