<SLUG> BC-R-B52-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD, SLOW AND INDISPENSABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most expensive warplane ever built, the $2
billion B-2 stealth bomber, made its combat debut against
Yugoslavia last week after more than a decade of controversy over
its costs and abilities. But the truly remarkable aircraft taking
part in NATO's strikes was not the newest but the oldest: the B-52.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the long, lumbering B-52H Stratofortress bombers have
been pounding targets across Yugoslavia from a base in England.
Three months ago, B-52s hammered Iraq from the Indian Ocean. During
the Persian Gulf war in 1991, B-52s dropped a third of the total
tonnage of bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven years after the last of them rolled off the
production line, the B-52 remains the workhorse of the Air Force,
old and slow, but still able to deliver a punch. And incredibly,
the last of the 76 B-52s still flying are not expected to retire
until 2044. Those that make it that long will be 82 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the bomber's longevity has been its ability to adapt.
The first of them, known as B-52Bs, entered service in 1955. Their
original mission was to fly high enough to avoid Soviet air
defenses as they waged nuclear war. When the Soviets built missiles
that could shoot them down, later models were adapted to fly low
instead.
</P>
<P>
   The latest and last model _ the B-52H _ has undergone constant
remodeling since being built between 1960 and 1962. These B-52s
have new engines, new avionics, new electronics and, most
important, new weapons. Imagine having a '57 Chevy with all the
latest automotive innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Today's B-52s are outfitted with as many as 20 air-launched
cruise missiles, each weighing a ton. These missiles _ used in last
week's raids _ allow the bombers to attack far from their targets.
</P>
<P>
   That limited role has led some to question the Air Force's plans
to rely on them for another four decades. ``It only works if you
can essentially keep it a couple hundred miles out of harm's way,''
said Michael O'Hanlon, an analyst at the Brookings Institution in
Washington. ``It's a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a day of outrageously expensive projects, B-52s have a
tremendous advantage. Built for only $74 million apiece, they are a
bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0849EST &QL; 
