A7820 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-PIZZA-CRISIS-REVIEW     03-29 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PIZZA-CRISIS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE CRISIS, HOLD THE ANCHOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can you possibly rank national crises? Who's to say, ``Yep,
that one's an eight, but this has got to be a 10''? Do you measure
headline size, count talk-show references, or just throw up your
hands and await history's ruling?
</P>
<P>
   None of the above, to hear Frank Meeks tell it. Just follow the
pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever matters of state overwhelm, matters of the belly must
be dealt with in the quickest, most instantly gratifying way
possible. ``When Washington is in crisis, pizza sales soar,'' said
Meeks, owner of 59 Domino's Pizza stores in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly, on the pizza-crisis meter, are the biggies (not
appetite-adjusted, of course)? Well, the Capitol set its record _
1,500 Domino's pies _ on Impeachment Saturday, Meeks said. And when
the Lewinsky scandal broke, he said, ``things were rocking'' at the
White House _ to the tune of an unrivaled 900 pizzas a day,
compared with 50 on a typical day.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Pentagon set its record: more than 800 pies.
``Right as the bombs went off,'' Meeks said, orders flooded in from
the Pentagon and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But can any trend be spotted in the toppings chosen? Pepperoni
for spicy sex scandals, perhaps, or veggie-only for a health-care
crisis? No, said Meeks, ``but when there's a crisis, they load up
on the toppings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 0922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
