seemed even longer than usual. By the time it was over, the
question of the night was, what were former Sen. John Glenn and
Gen. Colin Powell doing on stage? No one knew.
</P>
<P>
   The big upset was ``Shakespeare in Love,'' beating the
front-runner, ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Miramax, the
quasi-independent company owned by Disney, won 10 Oscars, including
three for Roberto Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful.'' Gwyneth Paltrow
won best actress and Judi Dench best supporting actress for
``Shakespeare in Love,'' and James Coburn was voted best supporting
actor for ``Affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of the awards was more fun than the show itself.
Miramax and Dreamworks continued sniping at one another over how
much money the other spent on its campaign for ``Shakespeare in
Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.'' A photograph in the trade
papers showed the three owners of Dreamworks _ Steven Spielberg,
David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg _ sitting together at a
post-Oscar party, looking somewhat unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   And Fernanda Montenegro, the Brazilian star who was nominated as
best actress for ``Central Station,'' had some blunt comments that
stung because many in Hollywood believed she was on target. She
told a Brazilian television interviewer that neither Ms. Paltrow
nor Benigni were especially worthy of the awards, and called Ms.
Paltrow ``this romantic figure, thin, pure, virginal.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BERNARD WEINRAUB
</P>
<P>
   For Detained Pinochet, A Partial Victory
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet's desire to end his house arrest in
England and return home to Chile got a boost when England's highest
court threw out the bulk of the charges that could be used in the
Spanish effort to extradite him to Madrid to stand trial for crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-year-old former Chilean dictator was arrested in October
and has been detained since then. His lawyers argued that the
lesser charges are not sufficient to hold him any longer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Says, `No Thanks'
</P>
<P>
   Campaign after campaign, supporters of the Rev. Jesse Jackson
greeted the civil rights leader with the rallying cry, ``Run Jesse
Run!''
</P>
<P>
   This time, he could not be enticed. Jackson, who has run twice
for president, announced he would sit out the 2000 contest, saying
he would rather concentrate on persuading corporations to invest in
minority businesses. ``The time spent running for president is time
that cannot be spent doing something else,'' he said. ``I've got so
many issues I want to raise. I've got so many battles left to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Vice President Al Gore with only one rival for the
Democratic nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   At Last, a Balloon Makes It
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bertrand Piccard and Brian Jones became the first
balloonists to circle the world nonstop. They were greeted in
Geneva by a thunderous cheer and a trumpeter playing the
``Triumphal March'' from ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, 41, a Swiss psychiatrist, and his British co-pilot,
Jones, 52, completed a 19-day trip around the world in their
Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon when they flew over an invisible finish
line at 9 degrees 27 minutes west longitude in Mauritania, then
touched down in the soft sands of southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   More than a score of pilots had tried to go around the world in
a balloon before. All failed.
</P>
<P>
   MIT Admits It's Tough on Women
</P>
<P>
   From Harvard to Stanford, top American universities are often
accused of discriminating against their female professors, and
usually respond with defensive denials. The Massachusetts Institute
of Technology took a different, more scientific approach: It
gathered the data, quantified the problem and verified its
existence.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the institute _ the most prestigious science and
technology school in the country _ has responded with an
extraordinary admission from its highest officials that, yes, women
on the faculty have been systematically, though unintentionally,
short-changed. It found pervasive evidence that women came up short
on everything from hiring and tenure to the allocation of critical
resources like research money and lab space.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Line Takes a Plea
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean Cruises pleaded guilty in federal court in Los
Angeles to three counts of making false statements to Coast Guard
inspectors in an attempt to conceal the illegal dumping of oily
waste water into the Pacific Ocean in 1994. Prosecutors believe the
unexpected admission reinforces United States jurisdiction over
foreign cruise ships. Royal Caribbean, the world's second-largest
cruise company, still faces potential dumping charges in New York
and Alaska. The industry is under congressional scrutiny on several
fronts, including whether to alter the tax-free status that saves
foreign ships plying U.S. waters billions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOUGLAS FRANTZ
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Call for Changes in the 737
</P>
<P>
   The rudder system of the Boeing 737 should be changed, the
National Transportation Safety Board said, to meet one of the
simplest principles of aviation: that every crucial part have a
back-up. The recommendation for the world's most popular airliner
was based on investigations of two crashes and several smaller
mishaps, and could be among the most far-reaching the board has
ever made.
</P>
<P>
   The board blamed the crash of USAir flight 427, a 737 that went
down on approach to Pittsburgh in 1994, on the failure of a single
hydraulic valve that it said should be made ``reliably redundant.''
All 132 people aboard that plane died.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD &QR;
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, a Ritual Suicide Strikes a Chord
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese manager shocked the nation when he committed
hara-kiri in a protest of the corporate restructuring that is
starting to take place across the country. Moments before he
slashed his stomach with a 14-inch fish-slicing knife, Masaharu
Nonaka had been in heated talks with the president of Bridgestone
Corp., one of the world's largest tire makers.
</P>
<P>
   The case is extreme, but Nonaka's ritual suicide strikes a deep
chord in Japan, which is suffering from record levels of
unemployment and a recessionary economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL WuDUNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Windfall in the Budget
</P>
<P>
   Deficits have given way to surpluses, but budget politics in
Washington go on. Both the House and the Senate adopted Republican
tax-and-spending plans, putting Congress on a collision course with
the Clinton administration over how to divide the huge fiscal
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to bolster Social Security and provide a big
tax cut. Democrats want to bolster Social Security and split the
rest of the money among Medicare, new spending and a much smaller
tax cut. With the pie as big as it is, there is probably room for
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Possible Clue On Missing Atheist
</P>
<P>
   With a former employee of the missing atheist leader Madalyn
Murray O'Hair in custody, charged with weapons violations,
investigators were hoping for a long-awaited breakthrough in the
perplexing 1995 disappearance of the 77-year-old woman, her son,
her granddaughter and $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, a convicted felon who also pled guilty in 1994
to theft from Ms. O'Hair's organization, American Atheists Inc.,
was arrested after an eight-hour search of his apartment in Austin,
Texas His lawyer told reporters that federal officials considered
Waters a suspect in the possible murder of the three missing
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK LYMAN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Bright Lights, Wrong City
</P>
<P>
   Two buildings, a continent apart, with crowds peppered with
celebrities. But there the similarities ended. At the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles, film stars stepped smilingly in
for the Academy Awards ceremony. And at Police Headquarters in
Manhattan, former mayors, other politicians, union leaders, even a
few actors, gathered day after day to protest the shooting of
Amadou Diallo, the unarmed man who died in a hail of 41 police
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Could that be Police Commissioner Howard Safir
mingling with the Oscar luminaries? The very man who had said he
would have to skip a Monday hearing on the Diallo affair because of
what an aide called ``important, long-scheduled meetings''?
</P>
<P>
   Yes indeed. And Safir had headed west on a Revlon jet, slept in
the swankest-of-the-swank Peninsula Hotel, all as a guest of a
Revlon pal. Once spotted, he hopped the red-eye home and made it to
the hearing after all. An ethics investigation is pending.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Conviction for Kevorkian
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of second-degree murder for
giving a lethal injection to a 52-year-old man with Lou Gehrig's
disease. Kevorkian, who defended himself at the trial in Pontiac,
Mich., could be sentenced to life in prison. It was the 70-year-old
doctor's first murder trial. In the past, he has been charged only
with assisted suicide. He was acquitted three times and a fourth
case resulted in a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   White House Offers China Plan
</P>
<P>
   The White House thought it had a plan to improve relations with
China: Get Beijing into the World Trade Organization, something the
Chinese have sought for more than a decade. But the Chinese never
wanted to pay the price _ lower tariffs on imports, an end to huge
trade barriers and protection for state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Chinese seem willing to play, and negotiations are
becoming furious in the run-up to Prime Minister Zhu Rongji's visit
to Washington on April 8. But in the White House, some are getting
cold feet. Amid charges of spying and human rights violations, some
wonder whether Congress will torpedo the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
