<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7824 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SLAVERY-BOOKS-REVIE     03-29 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SLAVERY-BOOKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAVERY'S TRUTHS (AND TALES) COME FLOCKING HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emancipation was declared in 1863, but it is in this last decade
of the 20th century that historians and writers are writing freely
about the brutality and violence of slavery _ taboo topics that
have silenced families, black and white, for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   A proliferating number of popular and scholarly books about
slavery are stripping away whatever is left of the velvety romance
of benign slaveholders presiding over docile slaves. And they are
emphasizing efforts of the enslaved to escape or rebel and the
punishments they faced that ranged from branding to amputation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the bleaker information emerges from the faded pages of
court records and antebellum divorce petitions. But among the newly
published books are some milder views expressed in the memoirs of
planters' wives, old handwritten diaries and slave narratives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, the taboos have been lifted,'' said Lucinda
MacKethan, an English professor at North Carolina State University,
who helped arrange for the publication of ``Lyddy'' (University of
Georgia Press), an antebellum novel by a planter's wife, and
another wife's memoirs. ``For instance, talking about miscegenation
in families is no longer considered the horrible shaming thing that
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling, she added, ``that we don't know the full
story and we ought to go back and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``We used to keep silent about it because there was a
social stigma attached to those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the burst in publishing about slavery has come in the
1990s, with 53 titles published last year and 16 published so far
this year, according to R.R. Bowker's Books in Print. In previous
decades, the yearly output of titles was less than 12 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the current interest in slavery goes beyond that of
academics and historians. There are also amateur sleuths and
genealogists like Robert Newman, an Ohio civil rights lawyer who
discovered the handwritten memoir of John P. Parker, a former slave
and conductor on the Underground Railroad. Newman, who tracked the
autobiography to a university archive from a footnote in a doctoral
dissertation, used the $75,000 advance from publication of ``His
Promised Land'' (W.W. Norton &AMP; Co.) to purchase the Parker home in
Ripley, Ohio, for a museum.
</P>
<P>
   The National Underground Railroad Freedom Center is scheduled to
open in 2003 in Cincinnati. The $80 million building will include
interactive exhibits enabling visitors to experience what it was
like to be a slave.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a cover off of something that's been covered along
time, then you generate a lot of curiosity,'' said Ed Rigaud, the
president and chief executive of the Cincinnati center. ``We're
taking the cover off.''
</P>
<P>
   The literature on slavery has distinct periods beginning with
the political activism of abolitionists, who after the 1830s
published books describing the mistreatment of slaves. The
publications provoked slaveholders into publishing
counter-narratives that portrayed slaves as intelligent people who
loved being part of the plantation family.
</P>
<P>
   During the Great Depression, workers at the Works Progress
Administration collected the oral histories of aging former slaves,
but the results were bland because white interviewers conducting
the research avoided the painful questions of brutality, violence
and rape.
</P>
<P>
   Those topics were often forbidden for the descendants of slaves
and slaveowners themselves. ``It's a part of history that as a
black I wasn't familiar with myself,'' said Mary Young, an
associate professor of English and Black Studies at the College of
Wooster in Ohio, whose family just didn't talk about slavery. She
has edited two books of slave narratives published by Franklin
Watts, ``All My Trials,'' a collection of histories from women, and
``Testaments of Courage,'' a history of men.
</P>
<P>
   But there are curious gaps in these narratives, Professor Young
said. The women may have talked easily about ``sassing'' their
owners, but they declined to talk about sexual exploitation and
cruelty. She said she had to dig for stories about a slave whose
ear was nailed to a post or a runaway who was punished with the
amputation of a foot.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Runaway Slaves: Rebels on the Plantation'' (Oxford
University Press), historians John Hope Franklin and Loren
Schweninger examined the brutal side of slavery after years of
researching old civil court records, divorce petitions and
newspaper advertisements offering descriptions of runaway slaves.
</P>
<P>
   From the divorce records filed by plantation wives, a picture
emerged that it was ``widespread and not uncommon for slaveholders
to have interracial sex with slaves in their late teens and 20s,''
Schweninger said. The runaway notices often revealed vivid
descriptions of the missing slaves: scars, whip marks, cropped ears
or branding on the forehead or back.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the historians calculated that slaveowners had to
contend with frequent escapes; they estimated that each year more
than 50,000 of the 2 million adult slaves tried to run away either
to the North or deeper into the South to be reunited with relatives
sold to new owners. But few succeeded in their escape, perhaps less
than 5 percent, Schweninger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a group of historians who believe that the vast
majority of slave owners were pious Christian men devoted to their
families,'' Schweninger said. ``I think people are going to take
umbrage at how we explore this, but we use evidence and the
evidence is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Ball, whose book ``Slaves in the Family'' (Farrar, Straus
&AMP; Giroux) won the National Book Award for nonfiction last year,
knows firsthand how difficult it is to probe for information about
slavery. When he inquired into the history of his famous
slaveholding family, one cousin scolded him, saying, ``This will
court anger and it will divide people.'' When he interviewed
descendants of the Balls' slaves, one elderly woman explained the
logic for silence: ``The older parents come under such strain, with
slavery, until they didn't tell the children things they should
have told them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball said his book lectures have turned into miniature town
meetings about race. ``The feeling I get is that people now welcome
the permission to talk about the hard stuff in my book,'' he said.
`` `Slaves in the Family' talks in thorough detail about the
purchase and sale of children, black and white sex, the slave
ships. It means that people want to find a way to talk about this
inheritance and the story I tell seems to help. There's too much
silence about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
