<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-TALK-KAN &LR;      03-29 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TALK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES FROM THE CRYPT AND OTHER VEILED EAVES-DROPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ So my wife and I are walking down a busy street in
this semi-ritzy skiing village, thinking about whether I want a
ski-burger for lunch or a ski-taco, when this small knot of women
passes by us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're well into the middle of some immensely engaging (to
them) conversation, which means that I was privileged to overhear
only a piece of it as they came within earshot and then drifted
away, their voices merging with the surrounding cloud of background
ski-ish noises. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here, however, is what I heard one of those women exclaim: ``But
I was supposed to be dead anyway, so I guess it was all right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to spin around and follow them at a discreet distance
to find out how she was supposed to have died, how she avoided
buying the farm, what was all right about her supposed death and on
and on. But my wife, as well she should, frowns on me shadowing
small packs of women so I can eavesdrop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Furtive doesn't become you,'' she says. At least she'll
realize she says that when she reads it here. (I don't have time to
check all these quotes.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as I took in that ``supposed to be dead'' quote, it occurred
to me that I don't need to track people around for their full
stories. I'm guessing that those stories can't be much better than
ones I can make up about them with no more construction supplies
than a few lines of actual words spoken by a passer-by. (An aside:
Do you, too, sometimes put ``passer-by'' on your resume? Or is that
just me?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I've come to understand that one way to give my mind a
vacation from the tedium of daily routines is to engage it in
altogether different and creative ways when _ as I'm doing here in
Colorado _ I take some time off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I've decided to spend part of today picking up snippets of
real passing conversation and filling in the story myself. As for
the supposed-to-be-dead woman, here is almost certainly the part
that preceded what I heard: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with a critical illness and given 12 days to live, she
proved her doctors wrong by surviving. Although still expecting her
own demise, she finally got a call from her physician, who said:
``The diagnosis was meant for another Elizabeth Lilliquith
Snagglepunk, not you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She rejoiced that night by drinking far too much demon rum and
awoke the next morning feeling as if the Army of Belize had spent
the night doing incompetent and highly irregular maneuvers on her
skull. ``But I was supposed to be dead anyway, so I guess it was
all right,'' she allowed of her morning-after condition, sounding,
frankly, a little unconvinced. The end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a few minutes later, as I walked toward the Vail public
parking garage, two 30-ish men off to my side engaged in this
exchange: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Bob, you remain single.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever been close to getting married?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And just that quickly they were out of hearing. So that forced
me to imagine where this conversation went after that: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me about it, Bob?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, tell me about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind, Bob. I think I see the problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At that point I imagine Bob, a doctor, seeing a woman nearby and
greeting her: ``Elizabeth Lilliquith Snagglepunk! It's great to see
you're not dead.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
