<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN30     03-29 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN30 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ever-ready economy floating on flexibility
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brazil is brimming with coffee beans, iron ore and
sugar. Russia is home to some of the world's most brilliant
scientists. Japan's work force is healthy, hard-working and
well-educated.
</P>
<P>
   But despite such advantages, these countries, like so many
others today, can't find their way out of a tangle of unemployment,
weak currencies and pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the United States, the good times roll: Federal
deficits have dried up, stock prices are setting records, inflation
is tamed, and home sales are booming. Economists say Americans are
enjoying the best business environment in history.
</P>
<P>
   How can so much of the world be cowering under dark economic
clouds while the sun keeps shining so brightly on everything red,
white and blue? Last year, Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan famously warned that with much of the world mired in
economic misery, the United States could not remain ``an oasis of
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet here we are, cool drink in hand, kicking back at the oasis
to soak up more fun. How do we do it?
</P>
<P>
   Economic historians have spent decades trying to pin down the
reasons for ``American exceptionalism,'' a phrase coined in the
1830s by Alexis de Tocqueville, a French social philosopher who
wrote about why this country seemed so different from Europe. The
topic still fascinates. At a global economic conference sponsored
by the Milken Institute _ a California think tank founded by
one-time junk-bond king Michael Milken _ four Nobel prize-winning
economists kicked around ideas about why America has grown so
exceptionally wealthy. And why it's getting even richer.
</P>
<P>
   In general, they agreed with the conventional wisdom that
contributing to our unmatched economic success are: our respect for
laws governing property, contracts and individual liberties; an
emphasis on learning and literacy; an abundance of natural
resources; our large geographical size; and the rapid growth of
population.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most important factor, according to Nobel
laureate Gary Becker, an economist at the University of Chicago, is
that we have been encouraged to be, in the best sense, greedy.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers, mall operators, car salesmen and others constantly
urge us to acquire more goods and services. Enough is never enough
in a popular culture where the Material Girl is a role model. The
promotion of avarice may seem shallow, but it has a positive
economic impact. To fulfill our many desires, we feel compelled to
work harder. That leads to new inventions and higher output, which
stimulate more buying, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   In nations where the government has discouraged individuals from
accumulating personal wealth, the society has remained relatively
poor. That's true even in countries that promote advanced learning,
such as Russia, Cuba and China.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those countries ``invested an awful lot in education ...
and nevertheless had dismal economic development,'' economist
Becker said. Education, like natural resources, won't bring
financial success unless a country also fosters a ``delicate
interdependence'' between skills and greed. The United States has
flourished in the 20th century because ``we gave people the
incentive to use their human capital,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, though Becker's point about the benefits of allowing people
to satisfy their material appetites helps explain why Americans
succeeded up to the 1990s, it doesn't fully account for why we are
now becoming so much richer than even other capitalist countries,
such as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese seem to be like us in many ways. They have respect
for laws, a democratic government, a well-educated work force and a
culture that encourages young people to try to get rich. Yet our
economy is vastly outpacing theirs. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Douglass North, a Nobel laureate from Washington University in
St. Louis who also spoke at the Milken Institute conference, said
the difference can be summarized in a word: ``flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Japanese business leaders, Americans are quick to lay off
workers, close plants, change banking practices or do whatever else
is necessary to survive. North said our free-wheeling economy keeps
replacing products and practices that don't work well with whatever
will.
</P>
<P>
   And labor is nearly as flexible as capital in this country. A
worker who gets laid off in Connecticut will readily switch to a
job in Atlanta. Or Los Angeles. Or Seattle. Even though the
distances are enormous, it's all one country with excellent
transportation and communication links.
</P>
<P>
   Life couldn't be more different in Europe. For example, a
laid-off German autoworker would dread moving to Portugal where
unemployment is much lower, even though both Germany and Portugal
are members of the European Union. Language, patriotism and family
ties make Europeans extremely reluctant to hop from one location to
another.
</P>
<P>
   Of course in human terms, American flexibility has its downside.
A South Georgia farmer who is losing his land and moving to Atlanta
to start a landscaping business might be heartbroken about the
change. But ultimately, both he and the economy will be better off
when his labor gets shifted to where it is most needed.
</P>
<P>
   This flexibility also helps explain why in 1998 _ when the U.S.
unemployment rate averaged just 4.5 percent _ more than a million
Americans were laid off, according to the Labor Department. Even
though times were good, companies were furiously closing plants,
installing equipment to replace workers and pursuing mergers to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, our national character helps us through these
upheavals. As a nation of immigrants, we have a long tradition of
picking up and starting over. ``Go West, young man!'' has resonated
with Americans for generations; we're willing to keep looking for
that pot of gold.
</P>
<P>
   And that can-do spirit fuels our optimism. This month, KPMG, a
business consulting firm in New York, polled college students via
its Web site. Of the 281 students who responded to the question,
``Do you think you are going to be a millionaire in your
lifetime?'' more than three-quarters answered ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Will today's level of optimism and flexibility allow the United
States to remain the world's one true superpower forever? Economic
historians say we are entering the 21st century with a good head of
steam but note that no great power has dominated for eternity. The
once-mighty leaders of Egypt, Rome, China and Spain all faded
eventually. Perhaps by the end of the next century, China, with its
massive population and resources, will re-emerge as the most
powerful nation.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, our country is on top of the world. On New Year's
Eve 1999, there will be no better place to party at midnight than
at the oasis.
</P>
<P>
   This is a weekly report by Atlanta Constitution editorial writer
Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by the coming of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
