<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Ma and Pa go to town
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When I was a child growing up on a farm in the
Midwest, our family went to town once a week. We all piled into the
car and drove the seven miles to stock up on supplies. It was the
highlight of our week.
</P>
<P>
   We went to the feed store first to get chick feed, brush killer,
salt blocks and the like. Then we'd go to the square, where our
stately courthouse was surrounded on all sides by store after
store. Mom would go into JC Penney's and buy a $3 cotton shirtdress
and get dad some new handerkerchiefs and socks.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'd go to the dime store, truly heaven on earth for kids.
We'd amble down the aisles marveling at the gadgets and goodies
laid out before us. We never bought much, but we could look. Mom
usually headed straight to the back of the store where the fabrics
were to get her sewing supplies. We lingered over the jacks and
rubber balls, Barbie clothes, colored pencils and pens, Nancy Drew
paperbacks and the cornucopia of candy.
</P>
<P>
   Then we'd go to the grocery store and fill up on the needs of
our family of five for a week. Of course, most of what we ate on
the farm we grew or raised ourselves. We were in town for the
staples: sugar, salt, flour, coffee, soap, detergent and such.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of our trip, if we had been really good, we might get
to go back up to the square to park and watch people go by. Any
wonder so many of us left for the city as soon as we could?
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, town squares have been replaced by superstores _
sprawling retail centers that offer everything from garden supplies
to golf balls, banking to beauty salons, pet food to Preparation H,
all under one endless roof.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, my husband and I found ourselves in one
such superstore _ not a regular destination for a couple of
anti-shoppers like us. We needed just a couple of things and
thought we'd pop in to get them. You never just ``pop in'' to one
of these places. Finding a parking space and getting to the front
door can take a good 30 minutes. Once inside, something happens.
</P>
<P>
   You step through that door and look up to see _ everything. It's
the dime store of my youth ad infinitum. No matter how focused you
were before that automatic door opened, you are overwhelmed as soon
as it shushes to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Something insidious overtakes you. Suddenly you realize you need
some hand towels for the kitchen, and you might as well stock up on
tuna fish while you're here. Oh, and look, they've got socks on
sale, a package of 10 for $6.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, you're pushing two cartloads to the checkout
counter and have nickeled and dimed yourself into the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Ma and Pa Kettle Go to Town.'' It's the Waltons stopping
by the general store to pick up the mail and being seduced by the
gumballs. I don't care where we live, it's the country folks being
sucked in by the lure of the big city and all its marvels. If it's
there, we must want it.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I stumbled out of the store two hours later with
more bags than we could carry. We got home and found we'd bought
things we had no idea we needed _ and didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the daze lifted. Like coming out of anesthesia, we
blinked several times, gulped and began making a return pile.
</P>
<P>
   The trauma of this experience has led me to a conclusion: We
need help. And so do others like us. We need to start a support
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Vicki, and I am a superstore addict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Vicki, we're with you!''
</P>
<P>
   We can meet weekly at the food court. Oh, and don't let me
forget to pick up some miniblinds and mayonnaise after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
