<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX     03-29 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wedding plans prompt some soul-searching
 &HT;    Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ For over 40 years, I've been working on an
advanced degree in curmudgeonry. Although not a new field, it is
rather an obscure one, requiring far more scholarly dedication than
throw-away subjects like biophysics and brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And now, just as I was about to be ushered into the hallowed
halls of the truly cantankerous, the unthinkable happens. My son
Kristofor brings home his lovely Amy and tells me they're getting
married.
</P>
<P>
   My reaction is like that of any devoted mother. I hug Kristofor,
check Amy's teeth, and give the union my blessing. Then I ask when
they're going to elope. The children eye one another briefly as my
son breaks the news. Sorry, Mom, no elopement. We're planning a
garden wedding with guests, crying mothers, and a
</P>
<P>
   string quartet. The whole meatball.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment our history, Kristofor's and mine, flashes before
me like a drowning person. Specters of overflowing diaper pails,
emergency rooms, and spit-up carrots, loom larger than life. The
countless boo boos I had kissed, and two years of driving
kindergarten carpool with a gaggle of four- and five-year-olds
pouring Orange Crush in each other's hair, swims before my
</P>
<P>
   eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I even recall the time he invited me up to his treehouse to
discuss the meaning of life. My words were less than profound, but
adequate, I thought. ``You grow up, go to college, work at
something you love doing, meet the lady of your dreams, and
elope.''
</P>
<P>
   Blatant brainwashing, I admit, but it was for his own
</P>
<P>
   good _ and mine _ because for decades now, I have politely
refused invitations to weddings, christenings, graduations, bar
mitzvahs, circumcisions, and showers of all kinds (tedious
gatherings where a bunch of women get together to see how many
words they can make out of ``can opener'' before anybody's allowed
to order a drink). In time, true friends came to understand my odd
ways. ``Oh, that's just Elizabeth,'' I've heard them explain to the
uninitiated.
</P>
<P>
   So much for unrepentant churlishness. I'm going to have to get
over it, for the time being anyway, and behave myself. I have vowed
to brush up on small talk, practice agreeing with everything, and
to follow the advice of a couple of my friends who've already been
where I'm heading. ``Wear beige and smile _
</P>
<P>
   with your mouth CLOSED.''
</P>
<P>
   And buy a new dress.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to another problem. There are three things I
absolutely do NOT do. I do not wash cars, mow lawns, or shop. So
far, it's worked out to my satisfaction. I've jobbed out the car
washing and lawn mowing, and simply stayed out of stores. But now I
need a dress.
</P>
<P>
   I started thumbing through catalogues but soon realized that
while L.L.Bean is great, I can't wear a sleeping bag to a garden
wedding. Not even with kid gloves.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, I walked up to the drug store and picked up a
fashion magazine _ I didn't buy it, mind you, I just picked it up
and looked at it. Inside the cover is a two-page layout for a well
known peddler of the ultimate in chic. Unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   The photo is of a young guy wearing a wet T-shirt with a
drooping pocket and a stretched-out neck. His shirttail half-hangs
out of a pair of oversize cargo pants (the ones with a pocket on
each leg big enough to garage a Moped), and he is pouting like
someone has just swiped his half-full bottle of muscatel. Over it
all, he wears a trench coat that even Columbo would have
</P>
<P>
   turned down. If I hadn't recognized the designer's name, I would
have sworn it was an ad warning derelicts to repent.
</P>
<P>
   Two pages back, a pre-pubescent waif wearing only what appears
to be a babushka with spaghetti straps stares at me over circles
under her eyes so dark they can mean only one thing _ she's either
just out of, or on her way into, rehab.
</P>
<P>
   I dropped the magazine back on the rack, went home and called my
high-school-and-forever friend, Jeanne. She's married off two sons,
gracefully, so if anybody can pull me through this, she can.
</P>
<P>
   We're going shopping.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
