<HEADER>
A7877 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN30-COX     03-29 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Cheap_o wine signals new trouble spots
 &HT;    By MARK LANE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I was tipped off well ahead of time to the
crisis in the region formerly known as Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't read State Department cables, Central European
newspapers, exotic Web sites or even watch CNN. I saw it at the
liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   My intelligence about the region comes from a source ignored by
the foreign_policy establishment, unnoted by pundits and unanalyzed
by analysts. Look for this indicator and you, too, can be a foreign
policy prognosticator. Here it is: impending political calamity
creates cheap wine.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, when Slovenian Sauvignon and something dark
and tongue_staining from Montenegro dropped below the benchmark
$3.00_a_bottle level, I started looking at cruise_missile futures.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered this pattern many years ago. Back when I first
realized that my sense of taste was too crude and uneducable to
merit spending much on wine. I would buy something cheap and exotic
from the back shelves of the store and three months later, the
place on the label would appear in 38_point type on newspaper
international pages. Once you see a country's name on a two_buck
bottle of wine, you can count on Christiane Amanpour being there
within six months.
</P>
<P>
   I fondly recall the last time I bought a 99_cent bottle of wine.
It came from Algeria at just about the time Col. Houari Boumedienne
had died and colonials and commies were divvying up the government.
The wine was _oh, how do the food writers say it? _ a robust
vintage, an earthy wine, a wine that speaks of fruit and tractor
parts, that slaps you on the back, belches and calls for another
round. Equally good as an aperitif or for tie-dying shirts. I loved
it.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Algeria stabilized and the wine left the bargain rack. I
thought I'd never see it again. Then, in the early 1990s, it
reappeared in $1.99-a-bottle version. Sure enough, within months,
militant Islamic fundamentalists won parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   The system works.
</P>
<P>
   Years before the global economy became a Sunday editorial
buzzword, the wine scavenger was well aware of how closely we are
all connected. How a few bad elections, an ethnic insurgency or a
sucker bet on industrial policy could take the proud, sun-ripened
product of a distant land and slap a ``$2.99'' sticker on it.
</P>
<P>
   The world of the wine cheapskate is one of international
intrigue, currency devaluations, fiscal crisis, armed insurrection,
religious strife and collapsing dictatorships in temperate
climates. We see the dark side of the world economy and drink it
in.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes we strain it through a coffee filter first.
</P>
<P>
   It makes me read international stories a whole different way. I
note with pleasure the ascendance of right-wing kooks in French
elections. Smile at the slide of the Euro. Too late for this year's
Beaujolais Nouveau, but it has potential.
</P>
<P>
   The wine scavenger, however, is no pessimist. We know too well
that crises come and go.
</P>
<P>
   The march of democracy continually clears the bargain shelf and
we must find the next troubled region. A stable, democratically
elected government with a central bank that does not operate out of
a suitcase hikes the cost of a bottle by at least a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine hyperinflation brought us Cabernet Sauvignons more
intense than the same three bucks would buy you from mellow
California. But the transition to democracy and stabilization of
the peso moved the product to parts of the store I just see on the
way in.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's move from military dictatorship to democracy to
full-blown part of Europe has made its jug wine less of a deal
every year. They even started filtering the chunky stuff out before
they bottle it. They're no fun anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So if our smart bombs are really smart, they will spare coastal
vineyards of Montenegro and the peacekeepers will step around the
fields in Macedonia. A three-buck red wine could be their first
timid step toward becoming a normal country.
</P>
<P>
   Don't accuse me of enjoying the world's misfortunes. I am
helping developing economies join the community of nations. That's
a lot to ask a browser in a liquor store, but with enough time on a
Friday night, I'm up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at
</P>
<P>
   marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
