<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7878 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAC-REPORT30-COX     03-29 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Popular iMac serves as bait for game developers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bait is an iridescent gumdrop of computer. The prey? Game
developers, many of whom stopped publishing for the Mac years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer is hoping its popular new iMac computer will lure
developers back to the Mac platform.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell whether developers are taking the bait,
but Apple Computer should get an A for effort. The company is
pulling out the stops to win over game developers, seeing them as
key to an effort to win a greater share of the home market.
</P>
<P>
   Some developers are expressing renewed interest in the Mac.
What's caught their fancy is twofold. The iMac has been a
commercial success, the best-selling single computer, and it was
designed for games.
</P>
<P>
   iMacs include technologies that developers like. For example,
there's a strong, if not state of the art, graphics accelerator.
This technology enables graphically detailed games to run faster.
</P>
<P>
   These computers also use a new standard for peripherals called
Universal Serial Bus, which is favored by many developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' Matthew Manuel, a senior Disney Interactive
programmer, recently told MacWeek magazine. ``The iMacs are sort of
like game consoles. They're much easier to optimize for games.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer's campaign to win over game developers involves
more than just new technology. The company is going out of its way
to schmooze them.
</P>
<P>
   The company turned out in force at the recent Game Developers
Conference in San Jose, Calif. It had a large booth featuring iMacs
and its new blue-and-white iridescent G3 computers.
</P>
<P>
   Running on these computers were some of the top games, including
``Myst II'' and ``Quake II.'' It was an impressive display that
attracted a crowd of developers all day long.
</P>
<P>
   And, to sweeten the pot, Apple Computer gave every developer
attending the conference a free package of software development
tools for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Apple Computer's effort is not overwhelming so
far, but it is beginning to win back some important developers that
were on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Maxis, for example, was uncertain about whether it was going to
publish a Mac version of its latest version of ``SimCity'' a year
ago. Now, a Mac version has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
