<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7880 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH30-COX     03-29 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadband is coming, and you might like it
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is broadband. This is the way.
</P>
<P>
   That's the slogan of MediaOne, the cable company recently
purchased by fellow cable operator Comcast for $55.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In MediaOne locations, this phrase hasn't really caught on.
``Get the cable thing right first,'' frustrated subscribers have
been known to bark at MediaOne salespeople trying to sell them on
the broadband future.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's unfair to single MediaOne out as the sole source
of cable consumer wrath. There are few American cable subscribers
who can't relate to tales of waiting for repairmen, hearing a
disembodied voice endlessly repeat the phrase, ``Please stay on the
line; your call is important to us,'' or muttering incredulously,
``They want how much for HBO?''
</P>
<P>
   But _ kidding aside _ broadband is coming, and it's going to
make your current dial-up Internet service as outdated as an old PC
left over from the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   But these same cable operators are also offering one of the
major on-ramps to the future of the Internet _ the high-speed world
of cable modems. For about $49 per month plus installation, most
cable operators are ready to bring the world of high-speed Web
access into your home, not in 2004 as the analysts were predicting,
but right now, today, this very minute.
</P>
<P>
   My personal instinct is to be leery of anybody who wants to come
in and fiddle with my home computer _ especially cable companies
that usually have to drop by three or four times to figure out why
the cable works in the living room but not in the den.
</P>
<P>
   My professional instinct has been to say a polite ``no thanks''
to the cable modem and high-speed telephone access. Speed for its
own sake means nothing. High-speed access will let me download the
new Internet Explorer browser in a matter of minutes instead of the
countless hours it would take with my teensy telephone connection.
But the question remains: What else can you get with all this speed
that you can't get with traditional dial-up access?
</P>
<P>
   There are a few companies beginning to develop Web sites for the
high-speed world. This week, Web portal Snap (www.snap.com)
introduced a high-speed version of its service, temporarily dubbed
``Snap.com for Higher Speed Users.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does define a different experience for high-speed
users,'' says Snap Chief Operating Officer Edmond Sanctis. Snap has
already made deals to offer the customized versions of high-speed
Snap with several cable and phone companies including Cable and
Wireless USA, Bell Atlantic and SBC. However, the faster portal
service is also available to users with T1 lines, which would
include almost anybody who logs on to the Web from work. Having
this rich media content at the office really does whet the appetite
for installing the same kind of service at home.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Snap's high-speed service via a T1 connection is a
different Internet experience. Users can surf the site the way they
always have to hunt for information, check stock prices and read
news headlines, or they can watch live news reports from Bloomberg
TV, catch movie star interviews from E! online or check out an
infinite number of ``South Park'' videos.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed Snap is a multimedia version of dial-up Snap,
with more audio video and music links. ``The thing I didn't want to
do was gratuitous video,'' Sanctis says. ``It truly does bring the
best of what works on a portal with a richer, more television-like
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is BellSouth.net's new Web portal service, available
in each of the markets in its nine-state service area. While
portals may seem like an old-fashioned narrowband idea, the
BellSouth.net portal offers a link to its Yellow Pages service,
which Vice President Donna LaChance says is the most updated
version of the BellSouth Yellow Pages there is.
</P>
<P>
   While directory assistance operators are often unable to help
you if you only know half a company's name or aren't really sure if
the business is in the city or the suburbs, the BellSouth online
Yellow Pages is able work with any kind of mangled information you
throw at it and return the exact business you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   For today's dial-up Internet customers, logging onto the
Internet to find the phone number of the local pizza joint might be
more bother than it's worth. But over the next few years, when
MediaOne/Comcast, BellSouth and others offer ``always on''
high-speed phone and cable modem access puts the Internet at more
and more fingertips, multimedia portals and online Yellow Pages
might become broadband's killer applications. And it might be
enough for skeptics to seriously consider letting the cable or
phone company come over and wire them for speed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
