<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MEDIA30-COX     03-29 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo! devotes issue to music, Net
 &HT;    By Charles Hadaad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet is becoming an increasingly big part in both the
marketing and distribution of music. Read what rocker David Bowie
has to say about music and the Internet in the April issue of
Yahoo! Internet Life. Says Bowie of the Net, ``This is for real. It
will change everything that we know _ absolutely everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowie is just one element in Yahoo!'s April issue, which is
devoted to music and the Internet. Other articles include a look at
the war between the music industry and a group of upstarts trying
to set the standard for how music is distributed through the Net.
Many music publishers and distributors think the Net will forever
change the way you buy recordings, because it is fast and it also
does something marketers like _ encourages impulse buying.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Tonka cars, the favorite of many a kid, have gone digital. The
company now offers a computer CD version of its cars. In ``Tonka
Garage,'' kids can build their own cars and crash them. You can
also convert images of cars to trading cards, decals and other
things that can be printed out.
</P>
<P>
   A companion game, ``Tonka Raceway,'' lets you create racetracks
and then race the cars you've created. Or you can pick cars and
trucks to race from a list of 30 already created for the game.
Published by Hasbro Interactive, these games are available only for
PCs running Windows 95 or a higher version of the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Need help with your taxes? Now you can turn to the Web for
everything from advice to forms. Some sites provide information on
the latest changes in the tax code. Others let you print out
worksheets to help calculate your return. Still others let you fill
out and file your return electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of sites worth check out. Start with Deloitte
&AMP; Touche Online at www
</P>
<P>
   .dtonline.com, then cruise to ABCNews.com at www.abcnews
</P>
<P>
   .go.com/sections/business
</P>
<P>
   .taxes98. Finally, if you want to do your taxes online, take a
look at Turbotax.com at www
</P>
<P>
   .turbotax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7885 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REMOTE30-COX     03-29 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REMOTE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remote eliminates confusing forest of buttons
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're like most people, your home
entertainment equipment includes remote controls. But you don't
necessarily know where the remote controls are, and the ones you
can put your hands on may not work the way you'd like them to.
</P>
<P>
   I have eight home entertainment devices that were sold with
remote control units. Only two original remote controls are in
active use.
</P>
<P>
   I use two replacement remotes that are supposed to combine the
functions of several remotes but really don't. They don't have slow
motion, or frame-by-frame buttons for the VCRs, for example.
</P>
<P>
   One device, a compact stereo, sits close enough to the side of
the bed that it's easier to push the buttons than to use the
remote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would be nice to have a single remote control that
handles all the functions of the remotes that came with the
devices. It would be even nicer if the remote control was easy to
use and didn't cost as much as the equipment it operates.
</P>
<P>
   Several omnibus remote controls are on the market, and it's up
to you to decide if they meet your criteria for a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more sophisticated units is the Take Control system
from audiovisual manufacturer Harman/Kardon. Harman/Kardon claims
Take Control is so simple to use it's actually fun to operate, and
they say it's the most versatile remote control ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a series of buttons as found on most remote controls,
Take Control has a few buttons and a touch-sensitive screen.
</P>
<P>
   The user programs the device to create various ``activity
screen'' displays that can be called up to handle particular
functions. The ``watch TV'' activity screen, for instance, combines
controls for an audiovisual receiver, video controls for the
television, channel selection from a cable box and controls for a
VCR or DVD player.
</P>
<P>
   Take Control comes with CD-ROM software that allows users to
customize the remote control with their personal computers. This
feature lets users create macro commands that trigger functions of
several components with the touch of one button.
</P>
<P>
   Take Control carries a manufacturer's retail price of $349.
</P>
<P>
   It is available where Harman/Kardon components are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TOOLS30-COX     03-29 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC Camera refuses to take a trip on Serial Bus
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is an account of a well-meaning attempt to review a $100
computer gadget. It turned into a saga we'll call ``Oklahoma Warner
and the Bus of Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philips USB PC Camera is one of those little egg-shaped
devices that sits on the desktop and transmits moving pictures to
your computer. The interesting thing is it uses the Universal
Serial Bus, or USB, connection, an appendage with which all
up-to-date computers are equipped. Having never used my USB, it
seemed a good thing on which to report.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was the first mistake. First times never work
for me.
</P>
<P>
   The documentation, actually, provided a fair omen. It consists
of a printed manual with setup instructions in six languages and a
separate yellow card with a big red STOP sign that says to ignore
the manual and do it this way instead.
</P>
<P>
   It took both sides of this 4x8-inch card to go through the 31
steps for installing the camera and its software. It is very hard
to do 31 consecutive things right. I found the best procedure was
to accomplish the first 15, then take a nice long nap before
assaying the final 16.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, all the little devices showed up in the right places in
the Device Manager, and it came time to set up the software for the
camera. The software, of course, said the camera wasn't correctly
attached and wasn't responding.
</P>
<P>
   Rebooting seemed like a wise thing to do, but it wasn't. The
computer wouldn't reboot. It would get a little way along the route
to daylight and then quit. Worst of all, when it reached that
point, it would not allow itself to be turned off. Pushing the
on-off button had no effect at all; it had to be unplugged. Upon
detaching the camera, the problem went away.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the bottom of the yellow card, below the 31st step, it
says if the computer won't start when the camera is connected, ``It
is very likely that your BIOS is not compatible with the USB
standard.'' Why my BIOS would have a USB and not be compatible with
its standard is one of those imponderables like the meaning of life
or income tax codes.
</P>
<P>
   So I called tech support at Gateway. This is an operation in
constant flux; it never works the same way for more than a month at
a time. After pressing numerous buttons, a recording basically told
me everyone was busy and I should go away and quit bothering them.
It shunted me into something called Automated Tech Support, where a
recorded voice said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are running Windows 95 on your desktop computer, press
1. If you are running a laptop computer, press 2. If you are
running a Destination computer, press 3.'' I'm doing none of the
above. I'm running Windows 98. A patient man would no doubt have
tried No. 1, but I decided to take another nap.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arising, I went to Gateway's site on the Web and found the
BIOS updates which are, allegedly, the right ones for my computer.
There are two of them. Why two? I only need one. Which one? Ah,
wouldn't life be dull without these little mysteries? I downloaded
both, and opened up one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions for upgrading the BIOS don't run to 31 steps,
but they involve changing jumpers back and forth on the motherboard
and warn you if you do this wrong, you will have performed a
frontal lobotomy on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, standing here in the cave, I have to grab the
idol off the pedestal and replace it with another so swiftly that
the secret mechanism won't drop the ceiling on me. The howls of
outraged natives echo from the mouth of the cave.
</P>
<P>
   I'd better have another nap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
