<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7891 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-HEADSET30-COX     03-29 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HEADSET30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't hold the phone: Headset phones growing popular at home
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Homemaker Lori Mackintosh doesn't have five or 10
minutes to spend standing around with a phone pressed to her ear
listening to elevator music while waiting to be taken off hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have kids at home, you need your hands free, and you
need to be able to move around,'' said Mackintosh, who lives in
Washington Twp., Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The solution for Mackintosh and for a growing number of
telephone users has been to buy a headset for her home telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Headsets traditionally have been associated with switchboard
operators, workers who spend their entire days making phone
connections. More recently, headset use has spread to other office
workers who need to type, take notes or shuffle papers while
talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Now the big push is toward headsets at home.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Small, director of residential phone marketing for
Ameritech Corp., said the growth of headset phones at home is
connected to consumer demands for mobility. He said cordless phones
went from virtually nonexistent to being in 70 percent of all homes
within the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Cordless phones have freed people from the need to be close to
the place where the phone is plugged in. Headsets connected to
cordless phones let the user keep working around the house or home
office while talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely where we're going,'' Small said. ``We expect
phones with headsets to represent about 30 to 40 percent of the new
phone market.''
</P>
<P>
   About 25 readers contacted the Dayton Daily News after the paper
ran a short item asking for comments from people who use headsets
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who called or e-mailed were women who found
headsets more comfortable and convenient to use at home than the
traditional handset.
</P>
<P>
   Most people at one time or another have pinned telephone
handsets between their ears and shoulders by crooking their necks
so they could use both hands while talking on the phone. But
holding that position on a regular basis can be extremely
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I don't use a headset it hurts my back too much,'' said
Patty Boeckman of Englewood, Ohio. ``If I try to hold a handset
phone on my shoulder it runs pains through the right side of my
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeckman started using a headset while working full time as a
travel agent. She still works as a travel agent, but since July has
split her time between working in an office and working from her
home.
</P>
<P>
   She bought a Radio Shack system that has a headset attached to a
dial pad. The phone doesn't have a handset.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami University ergonomist said Boeckman's complaints are not
unusual. Marvin Dainoff is a professor of psychology and director
of Miami's Center for Ergonomic Research. He has written or
co-written several books and advocates ``guerrilla ergonomics'':
achieving fit and comfort with inexpensive, easy-to-find solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cradling a phone on your shoulder has a high likelihood of
causing problems,'' Dainoff said. ``Especially if you're working at
a desk, a headset makes a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Dainoff and Small both said the key to choosing a headset is to
try it on in the store before making a purchase. Headsets are more
delicate than handsets and tend to be in use longer, so durability
is a major consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the headband first. It must be rugged and should be
adjustable to give a firm but not tight fit. The microphone should
be held comfortably in front of your mouth when in the active
position.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer an earpiece clip instead of a headband, be sure
the earpiece holds the phone comfortably and securely even when you
pivot your head rapidly from side to side.
</P>
<P>
   Look on the package for assurances that the phone cord is
shielded. Unshielded telephone cords can pick up radio signals that
interfere with reception.
</P>
<P>
   The highest quality headset phones have noise cancellation
features. These are electronic components that reduce the amount of
background noise the headset microphone picks up.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, led by Radio Shack and Plantronic, make
stand-alone headset phones _ that is, phones that have no handsets.
</P>
<P>
   But more common are headsets designed to use with cordless or
cellular phones. Small said almost all cordless phones currently
being made have 2.5 millimeter jacks built in that are designed to
accept headsets.
</P>
<P>
   People using them usually carry the cordless or cellular phone
unit in a pocket or clipped to a belt with the headset in place on
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Small said Ameritech plans to introduce a headset phone that
doesn't need a cord to connect it to the body of a cordless phone.
</P>
<P>
   The phone, now in the prototype stage, has a dial pad on a unit
about the size of a credit card that can be slipped into a shirt
pocket. Signals pass between the dial pad and headset using
infrared light.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone is enamored with the idea of headsets.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Perenic, an engineer who works as a support contractor to
the Aeronautical Systems Center at Wright Patterson Air Force Base,
complains that phone engineering may have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   He said phones, particularly cellular phones, have been
miniaturized to the point that they're too small to hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that given enough time we could probably make
telephones the size of a sugar cube. But why would you want to,
other than to prove that you could?'' Perenic asked. ``Now most
people would probably say, `Oh, don't be silly, they'd never make
it that small!' Well, maybe, but I never thought they'd make most
phones the size of a pickle either and then make me wear Spaceman
Spiff headphones to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A headset solves a lot of problems, but there's an axiom that
every ergonomic solution creates a few new problems,'' Dainoff
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when you wear a headset, people around you are
never sure whether you're on the phone or not. ``Holding a handset
to your ear is a clear visible signal that you're talking; wearing
a headset is not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dainoff said he owned a headset a few years ago but got rid of
it because people he talked to complained that they couldn't hear
him as well as they did when he used a headset.
</P>
<P>
   Phone equipment has improved rapidly and sound quality problems
are less prevalent than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   But Dainoff said men in particular still are resistant to the
headset idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of image is not trivial,'' he said. ``The people we
traditionally associate with headphones are telephone operators,
and they were almost all women.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how practical headsets are, they have to overcome
that image before most men will wear them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
