<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC Camera refuses to take a trip on Serial Bus
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is an account of a well-meaning attempt to review a $100
computer gadget. It turned into a saga we'll call ``Oklahoma Warner
and the Bus of Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philips USB PC Camera is one of those little egg-shaped
devices that sits on the desktop and transmits moving pictures to
your computer. The interesting thing is it uses the Universal
Serial Bus, or USB, connection, an appendage with which all
up-to-date computers are equipped. Having never used my USB, it
seemed a good thing on which to report.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was the first mistake. First times never work
for me.
</P>
<P>
   The documentation, actually, provided a fair omen. It consists
of a printed manual with setup instructions in six languages and a
separate yellow card with a big red STOP sign that says to ignore
the manual and do it this way instead.
</P>
<P>
   It took both sides of this 4x8-inch card to go through the 31
steps for installing the camera and its software. It is very hard
to do 31 consecutive things right. I found the best procedure was
to accomplish the first 15, then take a nice long nap before
assaying the final 16.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, all the little devices showed up in the right places in
the Device Manager, and it came time to set up the software for the
camera. The software, of course, said the camera wasn't correctly
attached and wasn't responding.
</P>
<P>
   Rebooting seemed like a wise thing to do, but it wasn't. The
computer wouldn't reboot. It would get a little way along the route
to daylight and then quit. Worst of all, when it reached that
point, it would not allow itself to be turned off. Pushing the
on-off button had no effect at all; it had to be unplugged. Upon
detaching the camera, the problem went away.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the bottom of the yellow card, below the 31st step, it
says if the computer won't start when the camera is connected, ``It
is very likely that your BIOS is not compatible with the USB
standard.'' Why my BIOS would have a USB and not be compatible with
its standard is one of those imponderables like the meaning of life
or income tax codes.
</P>
<P>
   So I called tech support at Gateway. This is an operation in
constant flux; it never works the same way for more than a month at
a time. After pressing numerous buttons, a recording basically told
me everyone was busy and I should go away and quit bothering them.
It shunted me into something called Automated Tech Support, where a
recorded voice said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are running Windows 95 on your desktop computer, press
1. If you are running a laptop computer, press 2. If you are
running a Destination computer, press 3.'' I'm doing none of the
above. I'm running Windows 98. A patient man would no doubt have
tried No. 1, but I decided to take another nap.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arising, I went to Gateway's site on the Web and found the
BIOS updates which are, allegedly, the right ones for my computer.
There are two of them. Why two? I only need one. Which one? Ah,
wouldn't life be dull without these little mysteries? I downloaded
both, and opened up one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions for upgrading the BIOS don't run to 31 steps,
but they involve changing jumpers back and forth on the motherboard
and warn you if you do this wrong, you will have performed a
frontal lobotomy on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, standing here in the cave, I have to grab the
idol off the pedestal and replace it with another so swiftly that
the secret mechanism won't drop the ceiling on me. The howls of
outraged natives echo from the mouth of the cave.
</P>
<P>
   I'd better have another nap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
