<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting online buying to the test
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks at Yahoo! Internet Life have a standing feature that
takes a look at whether electronic commerce (which is just a nice
way of saying ``buying things on the Web'') is really the wave of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   The piece in the April issue discusses the question of whether
it is easier to buy something on the Internet or the old-fashioned
way.
</P>
<P>
   The first comparison looks at bagel buying. The old way, in this
case, is heading to the neighborhood bagel store. Total time and
cost for 24 bagels and cream cheese: 24 minutes, $26.50.
</P>
<P>
   The new way involved searching for a bagel store online. A site
called bageloasis.com delivered overnight: cost $59, plus delivery.
Time: Eleven minutes to find a site and order, one day to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion: The old way is better (assuming you live near a
bagel store).
</P>
<P>
   A more apt comparison looks at book buying. Amazon.com and
Barnes and Noble have received a lot of attention for the prices at
their retail book sites, but lesser-known sites such as
www.buybooks.com and www.spree.com have even cheaper prices. Tom
Wolfe's ``A Man in Full,'' the book used in the comparison, sold
for $14.48 at BuyBooks. Traditional retailers, such as Crown Books,
offered the same book at $17.37.
</P>
<P>
   The piece concluded by saying that online sites, once you add
shipping costs, are more expensive than Crown's prices, but
shopping for books online takes very little time and no gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The April issue also gives fanatics a chance to locate the grave
sites of the rich, famous or interesting. The site,
www.findagrave.com, lets you search by location, name or claim to
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the listings include directions to the cemetery. For
some, including Duane Allman's, pictures of the grave site are
included.
</P>
<P>
   Site helps connect your business with money
</P>
<P>
   An online site for venture capital could become a one-stop
shopping site for companies looking for growth tips and growth
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capital Online, www
</P>
<P>
   .vcapital.com, is a Chicago- and San Francisco-based company
with a Web site that connects growing companies with money. Venture
capital is money invested in young companies. Investors in
early-stage companies get a larger stake. The companies, in turn,
get money that lets them develop product and hire employees. In
return for their money, early investors often take an active role
in the day-to-day running of the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The site was launched in January by Len Batterson, a Chicago
venture capitalist and an original investor in America Online.
Batterson created the site to speed up the early stages of picking
and choosing. The site claims it can cut the early
information-gathering stages from an average of 20 weeks to four.
</P>
<P>
   The funds, while open to all companies, will focus on the
Southeast, Midwest, Southwest and Southern California. Venture
Capital Online said those areas have the potential to blossom into
another Silicon Valley or Route 128 near Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capital Online is a network of 26 venture capital firms
that manage more than $3 billion in assets, including Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist, Apex Investment Partners, Tribune Ventures, Kline Hawkes and
Technology Funding.
</P>
<P>
   A feature called ``Venture Capital Clearinghouse'' screens the
entrepreneur's request for money, matching it with venture
capitalists based on their likes and dislikes, and provides a
summary of your business plan.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term plan is to turn the site into a kind of online
community of people running start-up companies and the people that
help fund them, including market research, educational information,
multimedia features and live chats.
</P>
<P>
   Until March 31, the site charges a $99 fee to refer a business
plan to venture a capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
