<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handle perfumes appropriately to make them last longer
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How long do perfumes last? Do they go bad after awhile? Can
anything be done to make them last longer?
</P>
<P>
   _Stephanie Coates
</P>
<P>
   A: Perfume longevity depends on storage. Once a bottle is
opened, it is meant to be used, say the scent gurus at the
Fragrance Foundation. Exposure to sunlight or extremes of
temperature change a perfume's scent and quality.
</P>
<P>
   Colognes and toilet water can be kept in the refrigerator to
invigorate the scent. Perfume should be stored in its box in a
cool, dry place away from sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Someone left a Bible where I work and no one has claimed it.
Any idea what to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   _Jake Guzman
</P>
<P>
   A. Is it in fairly good shape? Donate the Bible to a nearby
church.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bible is no longer usable (binding coming apart, pages
soiled), that is another matter. According to Helen Osmanat the
Catholic Diocese of Austin,a blessed or consecrated Bible is sacred
(these volumes are often inscribed) and should be buried or burned.
If the Bible has not been blessed, disposition is up to your
discretion.Q: You enlightened us with the origin of ``stat.'' How
about the origin of ``stet,'' the editor's mark meaning ``ignore my
other marks and leave as is''? Being a newspaper columnist, I'm
sure you have some experience with this.
</P>
<P>
   A: Break out the Latin dictionary _ this is the third person
singular, present subjunctive of ``stare'' meaning ``to
stand.''Looks like Latin is more than a source for answers in The
New York Times crossword puzzle. My old Latin teacher, Sister
Cecilia, would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife flies to Korea in April and will return in May. Can
you give us the preparations used to minimize jet lag on both
trips?
</P>
<P>
   _R.D.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Even jet-setting has a down side.
</P>
<P>
   Body time and local time at war? Sandy McDonough of Austin
Diagnostic Center's Travel Clinicsays a little common sense goes a
long way: Get adequate rest before traveling, reduce smoking and
avoid alcohol and caffeine, carry healthy snacks and avoid heavy
meals, increase fluid intake (eight ounces per hour during flight),
exercise (in-seat flexes, walking around), sleep as much as
possible on the plane (request pillow and blankets and bring ear
plugs and eye cover, shower or wash hands and face at stops.
</P>
<P>
   So skip the free champagne, grab some shut-eye and drink water
like a fish. McDonough adds sleeping pills are not recommended, as
they interrupt normal sleep patterns. Upon arrival, do not
immediately sleep. Get some sunshine if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What is the deal with the new quarters? Is there something
behind them or is the government just issuing new quarters?
</P>
<P>
   _J. Wilson
</P>
<P>
   A:Beginning this year, the U.S. Mint is starting a ten-year
celebration of the 50 states. Each year five new quarters will be
issued, celebrating each state in turn _ according to the date it
was admitted to the union. The first five quarters (check your
pockets) honor Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Georgia or
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first change to the quarter since the bicentennial
quarter was issued in 1975-76. The familiar George Washington
silhouette replaced Lady Liberty on the obverse of the quarter in
1932. Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O.
Box 670, Austin 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
