<HEADER>
A7908 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-FEATURE30-COX     03-29 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS: Christian, Jews prepare to celebrate
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your family may celebrate one of two religious holidays this
week. If you're Jewish, you'll probably begin the eight-day
celebration of Passover on Wednesday evening. And if you're
Christian, you're likely to celebrate Easter this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though these two holidays remember different events for these
religions, they have some links.
</P>
<P>
   Passover celebrates the escape of the Jews from slavery in Egypt
nearly 3,500 years ago. The story of the escape and their 40-year
journey to the land that is now Israel, is told in Exodus. Exodus
is the second book of the Old Testament in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Christians believe Jesus, who was Jewish, is the son of God,
whose resurrection from the dead is celebrated on Easter. The story
of Jesus' life, death and resurrection is written in the Gospels of
the New Testament in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The Seder and the Last Supper
</P>
<P>
   The Gospels say the Last Supper eaten by Jesus and his 12
followers before his death was a Seder. The Seder is a symbolic
meal served on the first night of Passover. This year, Passover
falls between Palm Sunday and Easter, just as it did 2,000 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Jesus broke the bread and told his disciples to eat it in
his memory, he was holding a piece of matzo, an unrisen bread. The
wine he blessed and offered to them was the wine in the Seder cup.
</P>
<P>
   The bread and wine were adopted by the Christian religion as
part of its own rituals. A round wafer of flat bread or a piece of
real bread is eaten and a chalice of red wine drunk at Holy
Communion. Communion is central to Christian worship.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Passover
</P>
<P>
   Hebrews, who became known as Jews, settled in Egypt around 1500
B.C. but later were enslaved.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th century B.C., a Jewish leader named Moses encouraged
his people to seek freedom. (The story of his youth is told in the
movie ``The Prince of Egypt.'') According to the Bible, the pharaoh
Ramses II refused to release them, and God punished the Egyptians.
God sent 10 plagues, including livestock disease, hail and swarms
of locusts. After each disaster, the pharaoh agreed to release the
Jews, then went back on his word.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Moses called for the 10th and most terrible plague: the
death of firstborn children of Egyptian families. On the night
Moses had predicted, the Bible says, God sent the Angel of Death to
kill the oldest child of each Egyptian household.
</P>
<P>
   The Jews were told to slaughter a lamb and mark their doors with
its blood so the angel would know to pass over their houses. That
is how the holiday got its name.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of town
</P>
<P>
   After he called down the last plague, Moses told his people to
be ready to leave at any time. That night was the one before
families did their weekly baking, so the women did not set out the
bread dough for its overnight rising. They mixed the dough without
yeast (so it would keep on the journey) and packed it. When they
stopped to rest, they laid out flat pieces of dough on the hot
desert rocks to bake in the sun. The baked dough was called matzo _
unrisen bread. Made of flour and water, it looks and tastes like a
cracker.
</P>
<P>
   The Seder
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Passover meal begins with the ritual of the Seder, a
word that means ``order.'' During the Seder, the Exodus story is
retold and foods that symbolize the Passover events are eaten.
</P>
<P>
   The book of prayers, stories and procedures for Passover is the
Haggadah. The foods on the Passover plate are:
</P>
<P>
   Maror (MA-ror): bitter herbs (horseradish) for the bitterness of
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Karpas (KAR-pas): a green vegetable (parsley, lettuce,
watercress) symbolic of spring. It is dipped in salt water to
recall the tears shed in slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Charoseth (ha-RO-seth): a mixture of chopped apples, spice, nuts
and wine, for the mortar that bound the stones of the Pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   Zeroa (ze-RO-ah): a roasted leg bone, for the lamb whose blood
ensured freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Beitzah (bay-TZAH): an egg, hard-boiled and then oven-roasted,
for the Egyptian children who died so near the start of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Chazeret (ha-ZER-et): an optional bitter vegetable such as a
parsnip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
