 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2531 - March 29, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2531 -- March 29, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BOMBING YUGOSLAVIA : DANGEROUS AND COUNTERPRODUCTIVE The
decision of the United States and its NATO allies to strike
Yugoslavia is a very dangerous step fraught with unpredictable
consequences not only for Europe but for the whole world, writes
Mikhail Gorbachev in this article. ``Let us call a spade a spade;
it's an aggression.'' 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________ 2. THE
OUTSIDER Yitzhak Mordechai, an Iraqi-born Kurdish Jew, is running
for prime minister on the ticket of the Centre Party, an inchoate
political refugee camp for those fed up with Israeli politics as
usual. By Deborah Sontag. From The New York Times Magazine. 3,000
words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE MAKING OF A FUGITIVE Wanted in connection with the murder of
Dr. Barnett Slepian, the anti-abortion militant James Charles Kopp
inhabited a world of would-be saints and cold-blooded killers. By
David Samuels. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
FIGHTING A HIDDEN KILLER The millions of Americans infected with
hepatitis C face an agonizing uncertainty. The virus may stay
forever dormant, or it may kill them. By Sally West Johnson. From
The Boston Globe Magazine. Full-length (3,700 words) + edited
article available.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
MANY WITH PSYCHIATRIC DISORDERS PASS THROUGH
</P>
<P>
   COURTS UNDETECTED Many people arrested for a variety of
offences, some petty and some grave, have serious psychiatric
disorders. As a result, many court systems have now set up
``diversion'' programs aimed at identifying these people so they
can be referred for treatment. But just how good are these programs
at identifying people who need help? Researchers found that one
such program in Britain missed the vast majority of people with
serious psychiatric disorders. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News
Service. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
DEBATE : GLOBAL RIGHTS Can the new international court of justice
help prevent crimes against humanity? Or is it a pious sham? By
A.C. Grayling and David Rieff. From Prospect magazine. 2,000 words.
(N/A U.K.) 
____________________________________________________________________
__________ 7. FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain.)
Embargo 19h00 GMT March 31
</P>
<P>
   A. THE TRIALS OF TRICLOSAN Cosmetics, toothpaste, carpets,
childrens' toys and plastic kitchenware may all have been
impregnated with triclosan. This substance is a potent killer of
bacteria and fungi. But the discovery that it has a specific mode
of action adds to concern that microbes could soon evolve that are
resistant to what might otherwise be a promising therapeutic agent.
By Henry Gee. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. FLASH, BANG, BUBBLE Tiny bubbles bursting in beakers of water
have the potential to unleash the power of the stars - and might
possibly contain the secrets for accessible thermonuclear fusion.
By Henry Gee. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. STRESS BRINGS ON STICKY SITUATIONS Having a hip replaced, a
new heart valve installed or a joint pinned is, like any operation,
stressful. But that stress could itself affect the way that the
human body reacts to synthetic implants and thus the outcome of
such operations. By Sara Abdulla. 250 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
CULTURE COMES HOME Anthropology began life in the colonial era as
the ``science of difference.'' Does it still have a place now that
difference is celebrated and everything has a ``culture?'' Its new
role may be to act as a counterweight to evolutionary psychology's
stress on the fixity of human nature. Can it mediate clashes
between civilisations? By Nancy Hynes. From Prospect magazine. (N/A
U.K.) 2,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 9.
CHINA PUSHES ITS PAWNS SOUTHWARD Beijing has been gradually taking
control of strategically important maritime routes and air space in
the South China Sea, as well as of the region's oil-producing
potential. Through its rapprochement with Cambodia, it is
strengthening its grip on Vietnam, which has historically barred
its way to the south. By Francis Deron. From Le Monde. (English
translation available.) 800 words.
