<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERMOT-MULRONEY-IN-GOODBYE-LOVER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERMOT MULRONEY WANTS HIS NAME BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Dermot Mulroney with Patricia Arquette in
a scene from ``Goodbye Lover.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Dermot Mulroney is not a lawyer. And he doesn't play one on
television, either.
 &HT;    Just the other day a female fan told Mulroney, ``I love you in
that TV show, `The Practice.'''
 &HT;    Another fan once told him, ```In the Line of Fire' was such a
cool movie. You had great chemistry with Clint Eastwood.'''
 &HT;    Mulroney just nodded and smiled. Explaining takes too much
trouble.
 &HT;    He doesn't have a television series. He didn't star in that 1993
Eastwood hit. That was Dylan McDermott.
 &HT;    For years, the industry and fans have mixed up the two actors,
and things are only getting worse. The 34-year-old Mulroney's
biggest hit was ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' (1997), which
co-starred Julia Roberts _ who in real life was once engaged to ...
Dylan McDermott.
 &HT;    ``It boggles the mind,'' the good-natured Mulroney says over
breakfast at the Four Seasons Hotel in Los Angeles, reed-slim and
relaxed in blue jeans and a black sweater. ``Hey, between us, we
have an incredible resume.''
 &HT;    There is one sure way to tell the actors apart, he adds.
 &HT;    ``I have a scar on my face from when I was a kid and fell on a
broken dish while trying to feed some rabbits,'' he says. ``Now I'm
glad I have the scar _ it sets me apart.''
 &HT;    Another way: Mulroney is the one starring in ``Goodbye, Lover,''
the noirish thriller/comedy opening nationwide on April 16 and
co-starring Patricia Arquette and Don Johnson.
 &HT;    ``It's a significantly different comedy,'' Mulroney says.
``Basically, Patricia and I are plotting to murder my brother,
played by Don. This is a very serious dark comedy that reveals
itself slowly.
 &HT;    ``So few movies allow the audience a chance to figure it out for
themselves,'' he adds. ``Frankly, I'm sick of movies that don't
have a script, but they're wrapped up in this attitude. Most movies
today are just palatable _ they don't excite the mind.''
 &HT;    ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' excited minds to the tune of more
than $100 million at the box office, but Mulroney is under no
illusion that he was its drawing card.
 &HT;    ``I think that movie is the ultimate comedy,'' he says,
``because here you had characters played by Julia Roberts and
Cameron Diaz fighting over me. I swear when I got the part, I told
my wife, `I've got to lie down, honey. Send me a damp towel. This
is really too much.'
 &HT;    ``She said, `Yes, dear. The film is clearly a fantasy.'''
 &HT;    The film's success led to some new opportunities for Mulroney,
but the actor _ who has been on and off the hot list for a decade _
wasn't impressed.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I've certainly heard it all before,'' he says. ``I've
heard, `You're going to be the hottest thing alive,' and then it
doesn't happen. Then you're chilly cold and have to wait for a
thaw. So those little tags don't carry much weight with me anymore.
I don't put any stock in one film _ I have a wait-and-see attitude,
because I've been disappointed a few times.
 &HT;    ``In fact,'' he adds, ``the only difference I noticed with `My
Best Friend's Wedding' is that the film had a lot of promotion.
It's sad, but Hollywood now is really about how much they spend on
your movie after you make it.''
 &HT;    Mulroney's resume reflects quality films that haven't made much
money, including ``Kansas City'' (1996), ``The Trigger Effect''
(1997) and ``How to Make an American Quilt'' (1997). His more
commercial efforts, such as ``Point of No Return'' (1993) and the
western ``Bad Girls'' (1994), didn't pan out, and before ``My Best
Friend's Wedding'' his last real hit had been ``Young Guns''
(1988).
 &HT;    Nevertheless, he's been working steadily for 13 years, which he
says is enough.
 &HT;    ``For me, the fame doesn't matter,'' he says. ``I don't care if
my name is above the title.''
 &HT;    Even if he could, Mulroney says, he wouldn't want to achieve Tom
Cruise's level of stardom.
 &HT;    ``I don't think the big stars have a lot of control over their
lives,'' he says. ``It's not my style to splash around the cover of
magazines.
 &HT;    ``Of course, the one good thing about being Tom Cruise is that
people do go to see all of your movies. So it's a real Catch-22.''
 &HT;    Mulroney grew up far from the Hollywood glitter, as the middle
child in a family of five in suburban Alexandria, Va. It was his
mother Ellen, a former actress, who first suggested that he try
acting.
 &HT;    He did, and liked it. Various community-theater efforts led him
to Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., where he majored in
film.
 &HT;    ``I thought I'd get a job on a movie set pulling cable,'' he
says. ``I didn't have lofty plans.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he took a chance when a William Morris agent
visited the campus during Mulroney's senior year.
 &HT;    ``He put a sign-up sheet on the wall and said, `Anybody
graduating is welcome to audition for an agent,''' Mulroney
recalls. ``I signed up. It was unexpectedly easy to get going in
this business.''
 &HT;    His first role was as Bill Bixby's son in the television movie
``Sin of Innocence'' (1986), a family divorce drama he calls ```The
Brady Bunch' with sex.'''
 &HT;    That led to a series of television movies and low-budget
features. It was while making one of the latter in 1988 that he met
his wife of eight years, actress Catherine Keener. According to
her, he made a good first impression by saving her life.
 &HT;    ``The movie `Survival Quest' was about this Outward Bound
group,'' she says in a separate interview. ``The tag line was, `In
the wilderness, you can't call 911.'''
 &HT;    As it turns out, the tag line had a point.
 &HT;    ``One day while shooting in a national park, I began to drown,''
she recalls. ``I'm getting carried down a river, and Dermot was the
only man who would jump in to save me. I swear, there were a
hundred crew guys who couldn't inconvenience themselves.
 &HT;    ``Dermot jumps in this raging river, and we're carried two miles
down by this horrible current,'' she says. ``At that moment I fell
in love with him, although we were both with other people at the
time.''
 &HT;    One thing led to another, however, and in 1991 they married.
 &HT;    ``We were best friends before we got married,'' Mulroney adds,
``which is the perfect place to start.''
 &HT;    Mulroney and his brother Shaun are also entrepreneurs, owning
the Double Door, a Chicago bar which showcases rock bands. Big-name
bands such as Smashing Pumpkins, Oasis and Bush have jammed there,
as has the actor's own band, The Low and Sweet Orchestra, which
released its first album, ``Goodbye to All That,'' two years ago.
 &HT;    ``I play cello and mandolin in a rock band,'' he says, shaking
his head. ``You figure it out.''
 &HT;    His fame probably gives the band some extra pull, but even that
has its complications. Shaun Mulroney has told his brother that
people wonder when ``that guy from `The Practice' will be
playing.'''
 &HT;    Mulroney sighs.
 &HT;    ``You know, one day I'll have to star in a movie with Dylan
McDermott,'' he says. ``It would be the ultimate way to confuse
America.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
