<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7936 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELINA-KANAKAREDES-IN     03-29 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELINA-KANAKAREDES-IN-PROVIDENCE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELINA KANAKAREDES: DIVINE `PROVIDENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Melina Kanakaredes in a scene from
``Providence.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It isn't hard to tell when you're suddenly famous.
 &HT;    ``I was in New York City for the premiere of `Providence,'''
says Melina Kanakaredes, the ebullient star of NBC's surprise
midseason hit. ``We were going down Broadway, and there was my
face, on a billboard!
 &HT;    ``I'd never seen my face that big before,'' she says, still
amazed. ``My mother nearly stopped everybody on the street to say,
`That's my baby!' It was so bizarre to see her all excited.
 &HT;    ``I was like, `Oh my God, this is very strange,''' the actress
recalls. ``I remembered back to when I graduated from college and
moved to New York. I barely made 200 bucks a month doing
off-off-off Broadway.
 &HT;    ``And now there was my head on this wall.''
 &HT;    The excitement was just beginning. That evening ``Providence's''
debut episode captured the attention of nearly 20 million viewers.
 &HT;    Kanakaredes, a Greek-American beauty who's all slate-gray eyes
and cascading curls, awoke the next morning as Hollywood's latest
overnight success.
 &HT;    ``Every teacher in every school, during roll call on that first
day, would say `Melina Ka ... Kana ... ,''' she says with a laugh
during a telephone call from her rented home in Los Angeles. ``Now,
to have Jay Leno say, `And next, Melina Kanakaredes,' is
incredible.''
 &HT;    Kanakaredes is actually far from an overnight success. She's 31
and has been kicking around stage, television and movie circles for
years. Her credits include a four-year stint on the soap opera
``Guiding Light,'' the television series ``NYPD Blue'' (as Jimmy
Smits' girlfriend), ``New York News'' and ``Leaving L.A,'' plus
such films as ``The Long Kiss Goodbye'' (1996) and ``Rounders''
(1998).
 &HT;    NBC recognized her talent _ she projects genuine earthiness _
and inked her to a production deal. Kanakaredes passed on several
proposed projects, including a new cop drama and a role on ``Law
and Order,'' until the ``Providence'' script arrived for her
consideration.
 &HT;    The show would follow the joys and sorrows of the Hansen family
of Providence, R.I., with Kanakaredes in the pivotal role of
Sydney, the oldest and most sensible Hansen sibling. In the pilot,
Mom Hansen (Concetta Tomei) dies in the middle of a wedding,
prompting disenchanted plastic surgeon Sydney to remain in
Providence with her veterinarian father (Mike Farrell), troublesome
brother (Seth Peterson) and pregnant sister (Paula Cale).
 &HT;    ``I honestly thought `Providence' might catch on,'' Kanakaredes
says. ``As usual, I had to judge an entire series on one pilot
script. I had no idea what would happen after the pilot, but I was
so taken with the characters and the way it was written, with all
those bizarre twists and turns.
 &HT;    ``I really liked Sydney, and I attached myself to her,'' the
actress says. ``I decided to do it, thinking, `Whatever happens,
it'll be something I really enjoy doing. If it doesn't go to
series, I'll have an hour of material to put on my clip reel.'
 &HT;    ``The other scripts I read reminded me of other shows on
television,'' she adds. ```Providence' struck me as something new
and different. Family drama is not new, but it hasn't been done in
this way, in this venue, with our quirkiness.
 &HT;    ``So far I haven't been proved wrong.''
 &HT;    Critics tore into ``Providence'' with a vengeance. Some declared
the show cloying or syrupy, others deemed it contrived or downright
silly.
 &HT;    Almost every reviewer detested the show's trademark device:
Sydney's dead mom comes to her in dreams, bitching about life and
death, complaining about Sydney's choice in men and chain-smoking
like Denis Leary in drag.
 &HT;    Kanakaredes took it all in stride.
 &HT;    ``I always say I love constructive criticism, and that's because
a television show can take it to heart, adjust certain elements and
make it better,'' the actress says. ``In many cases, the criticism
of `Providence' was not constructive.
 &HT;    ``In those instances I went, `Apple pie, cherry pie.' Some
people love `Providence' and some don't. That's fine,'' she says.
``The validation is that the audience really loves it. Also, the
critics tooled on the show, but they weren't so bad to me.''
 &HT;    Kanakaredes laughs.
 &HT;    ``I'm thankful,'' she says, ``for the little miracles.''
 &HT;    Right now, with its audience growing, ``Providence'' seems
primed for a lengthy run. Such a prospect hardly daunts
Kanakaredes, who calls Brooklyn, N.Y., her home and only rents her
place in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    ``It's always a roller-coaster ride, and you never know what's
going to happen tomorrow,'' she says. ``We all just want to
continue to raise the bar on the material, make the best show we
can and enjoy ourselves in the process.
 &HT;    ``If it goes five or six years, I guess I'm ready for that,''
Kanakaredes says. ``You sign on for that _ I've got a five-year
contract.
 &HT;    ``This year just flew by, and I hope it will continue like
that,'' she says. ``We have a great group of people, cast and crew.
I'm sure actors say that all the time, but we do, and I couldn't
ask for the experience to be any better.''
 &HT;    A native of Akron, Ohio, Kanakaredes knew early on that acting
was her destiny. She jokes that she's been performing for ages _
albeit for much of that time without pay.
 &HT;    ``I'm the youngest of three girls,'' she says. ``My sisters did
a lot of musical theater growing up, so I started singing and
dancing.
 &HT;    ``I said to my parents, `I want to be an actress,' and they
said, `Well, OK, just make sure your grades are good and that you
have something to fall back on.'
 &HT;    ``Right into college I just kept on acting,'' Kanakaredes says.
``I never worried about making a living from it, because the
worst-case scenario was to go home and work in my family's candy
business.
 &HT;    ``I continue to love what I do,'' the actress says cheerfully.
``It's fun to leave yourself and jump into somebody else's skin for
a while. To do that you have to collaborate so much with other
people, all of whom bring their own talent to the show or movie.
 &HT;    ``When it all comes together, it can be magical.''
 &HT;    Magical and life-altering. Not only can Jay Leno now pronounce
her name, but fans recognize Kanakaredes in the streets and
producers are calling with movie offers.
 &HT;    It's a decidedly heady time, but the actress has her family _
most notably her sisters and her husband of six years, New York
chef Peter Constantinides _ to help keep her feet on the ground and
her ego in check.
 &HT;    ``My sanity is my family,'' she says. ``Actually, my sanity and
my insanity is my family. We see each other as much as we can, even
though we're often on different coasts.
 &HT;    ``I'm Greek, and togetherness is a big part of our culture,''
she adds. ``My husband is of the same background.
 &HT;    ``My attitude is I love what I do, but it's not 100 percent of
who I am,'' Kanakaredes says. ``Being with my family puts
everything in perspective, and I don't care as much about the crazy
stuff _ the publicity and the recognition _ that's going on.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
