<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTRESS-GWEN-VERDON-S     03-29 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTRESS-GWEN-VERDON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWEN VERDON STILL HEARS THE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Gwen Verdon with Ann Reinking during
rehearsals for ``Fosse.'' 
 By MICHAEL J. BANDLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I just back up into everything,'' Gwen Verdon says.
 &HT;    That's the secret behind her more than a half-century as an
entertainer, she says. It accounts for success on stage, in films
and on television, not to mention an armful of Tony Awards and,
most recently, the National Medal of the Arts.
 &HT;    Along the way, she's taught Marilyn Monroe how to walk, served
as muse to arguably the century's greatest choreographer and, most
notably, sang and danced up a storm in such Broadway hits as ``Damn
Yankees'' (1955), ``New Girl in Town'' (1957), ``Sweet Charity''
(1966) and ``Chicago'' (1975).
 &HT;    And she isn't through yet. The hit new revue ``Fosse'' _
celebrating her late husband, director/choreographer Bob Fosse _
brought her back to Broadway as its artistic adviser. She has two
movies in the can. And her daughter, Nicole Fosse, recently gave
birth to Verdon's fifth grandchild _ perhaps the best treat of all
for the 74-year-old, who is already a great-grandmother as well.
 &HT;    But don't count on Verdon doing much babysitting. She recently
taped an episode of ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' with more film and
television work to come.
 &HT;    It's rare for musical performers to find work after they pass
song-and-dance age, but when Verdon hung up her dancing shoes she
quickly found work with such prestigious directors as Francis Ford
Coppola (1984's ``The Cotton Club'') and Ron Howard (1985's
``Cocoon''). By the time she finished working with them, her new
career was well underway.
 &HT;    Verdon knew something about brilliant directors through her
years with Fosse. The mercurial dance innovator was her
professional partner from 1955 until his death in 1987, and the two
married in 1960. They separated in the early 1970s but never
divorced, even as he moved on to other women _ including Ann
Reinking, who later became a close friend of Verdon and co-directed
``Fosse.''
 &HT;    Even when she wasn't in a Fosse production, Verdon says, she was
always around, working with dancers, offering the director an
objective eye and even tracking down a gorilla suit for the 1972
movie version of ``Cabaret.''
 &HT;    ``We were always together,'' Verdon says during a conversation
at Sardi's, the legendary Manhattan theater-themed restaurant where
her caricature has hung prominently for decades. ``I just accept it
_ that was my life. I can't imagine not belonging to him.
 &HT;    ``We were great if we didn't have to live together and deal with
mundane things,'' she adds. ``It was mundane things that drove us
nuts. I never wished him, and he never wished me, an unhappy life.
If you really examine a person and admire him, that feeling doesn't
go away.''
 &HT;    Since Fosse's death Verdon has seen herself as a keeper of the
flame, helping to create a Fosse archive at the Library of
Congress, establishing a scholarship to train dancers in the Fosse
style and, of course, working with Reinking and others to create
``Fosse.''
 &HT;    ``I was determined that Bob's work somehow would be seen
again,'' she says. ``It deserved it. And audiences deserved to see
not just those dance numbers, but his point of view about theater _
his use of the stage and the levels of the stage. No one else has
approached theater and dance the way Bob did.
 &HT;    ``He could not be categorized, either in his work or in his
character,'' she says. ``He truly was very interesting, very unique
_ and always a surprise.''
 &HT;    The daughter of an MGM gaffer who worked on Greta Garbo movies
and the ``Tarzan'' series _ ``Johnny Weismuller taught me the
backstroke, his specialty,'' she recalls _ Gwyneth Verdon was born
with rickets, which was then usually treated by breaking the legs
and letting the bones realign.
 &HT;    But her mother, a dancer, chose her own method _ corrective
shoes and dance exercises.
 &HT;    ``I did them completely wrong, with my feet turned in,
pigeon-toed and knock-kneed,'' she says, laughing. ``I think that's
why it was so easy to dance for Bob Fosse.''
 &HT;    Verdon was a trouper from the outset. As a teen she danced with
several professional companies and modeled bathing suits. At 17 she
married Jim Henaghan, a columnist for The Hollywood Reporter, and
nine months later gave birth to her first child, James. The
marriage, troubled by Henaghan's alcoholism, lasted only five
years.
 &HT;    One night when her husband was ``on one of his big drunks,''
Verdon took over his assignment to cover a nightclub show. There
she encountered the Afro-Cuban jazz style of Jack Cole, and was
mesmerized. Going backstage, she asked to work with him, and for
the next couple of years assisted Cole on Broadway projects and
then in Hollywood. She performed as a ``specialty dancer'' in
movies such as ``David and Bathsheba'' (1952) and ``The Merry
Widow'' (1952), and worked behind the scenes teaching actresses
such as Marilyn Monroe and Jane Russell how to move.
 &HT;    ``Marilyn would wiggle so much she could never get someplace,''
Verdon recalls, ``so I would have to calm her down. And I had to
teach Jane not to act so tough. She was sort of clod-walking. I got
her to believe she was only 5-feet-4, instead of 6 feet tall.''
 &HT;    One day choreographer Michael Kidd saw Verdon perform, which led
to her Broadway debut in a small role in Kidd's ``Can-Can'' (1953)
_ and with it a name change so she'd fit on a marquee.
 &HT;    The opening night was the stuff of Broadway legend. Though she
wasn't the star, the audience rose and summoned Verdon for a
curtain call. Kidd had to all but drag her onstage from her
dressing room.
 &HT;    ``They wouldn't stop applauding,'' she recalls dreamily.
 &HT;    That role won her first Tony award. Two years later, in Fosse's
``Damn Yankees,'' she won a second Tony and etched herself
indelibly in Broadway history with her playfully sultry ``Whatever
Lola Wants, Lola Gets,'' recreating the role for the 1958 film.
 &HT;    ``New Girl in Town'' and ``Redhead'' (1959) followed, each
winning another Tony.
 &HT;    Even Nicole's birth didn't slow her down much _ she was back on
Broadway three years later in ``Sweet Charity,'' and then again in
1975 for ``Chicago.''
 &HT;    Verdon's shift to nonmusical acting wasn't a shock _ even during
the peak of her musical stardom she'd been studying with acting
guru Sanford Meisner _ but she admits that it was a difficult
transition, Tony Awards notwithstanding.
 &HT;    ``People don't think of you as an actor,'' she says with a
shrug.
 &HT;   By now, however, people do. Specializing in
eccentric-but-vigorous oldsters, she'll be seen as Ellen Burstyn's
nosy next-door neighbor in the upcoming ``Walking Across Egypt''
and as an agoraphobic woman who shares her house with a Great Dane
in ``Bruno.'' The latter film is being directed by Shirley
MacLaine, another Fosse veteran _ she won Verdon's part for the
1969 film version of ``Sweet Charity,'' but Verdon didn't hold a
grudge and even helped her learn the dances.
 &HT;    One day last fall, out of the blue, the actress got a call
informing her that she had been selected to receive the National
Medal of the Arts. On a bright November morning, under a glistening
white tent on the south lawn of the White House, Verdon received
her award from President Clinton, in the company of such fellow
honorees as film star Gregory Peck and opera singer Roberta Peters.
 &HT;    Saluting her, the president observed that ``this famous redhead
is showing us all that she is still alive and kicking.''
 &HT;    Indeed she is. At an age when many people have long since
retired, Verdon volunteers that she'd love the chance to appear in
a costume drama like ``Elizabeth'' or ``Shakespeare in Love.''
 &HT;    Or even a western, she adds.
 &HT;    ``I could always be the lady who runs the whorehouse!''
 c.1999 Michael J. Bandler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael J. Bandler is a Silver Spring, Md.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
