A7941 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSEY-GRAMMER-IN-FRA     03-29 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSEY-GRAMMER-IN-FRASIER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELSEY GRAMMER'S SHRINK RAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kelsey Grammer in a scene from
``Frasier.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the very best of times for ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to Thursday nights in September 1998, the show has
thrived. Most weeks it notches even higher ratings than its
timeslot predecessor, ``Seinfeld.'' After five years of slugging it
out on Tuesdays, ``Frasier'' has settled into NBC's Thursday-night
lineup for what would appear to be an extended run _ and few people
are more surprised than Kelsey Grammer, Frasier Crane himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it sounds extremely odd for me to say out loud
that I've been playing Frasier for 16 years now,'' says the genial
Grammer, who first played the pompous shrink on ``Cheers'' way back
in 1983. ``But this has been an extremely gratifying year for us,
for all of us. It's a message to us that all our hard work is
paying off. These are the best of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Grammer's onscreen compatriot David Hyde Pierce, who
plays Frasier's stuffy brother Niles, feels fully vindicated by the
show's resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were _ and are _ a really good show,'' Pierce says. ``This
has been an amazing season for us _ we've had some of our very best
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact we're in syndication, too, has helped our
ratings,'' he adds. ``Instead of just people who know about the
show sitting down to watch once a week, suddenly people come home
from work, flick on the TV and realize, `That's ``Frasier?'' Hey,
it's a pretty funny show.'''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for ``Frasier's'' most successful season ever
has to go to Grammer, Pierce and their collective onscreen
chemistry. There's also a lot to be said for co-stars Jane Leeves,
John Mahoney and Peri Gilpin. But there are other factors, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the compliments our show always gets, which I hate, is
that we're so intelligent, so highbrow,'' Pierce says. ``That's so
unfair. We have the broadest physical comedy _ we do everything on
this show. There happen to be two very intellectual characters in
it, but the things they go through are the same things we all go
through _ wanting to be liked, wanting to find love and all that
other stuff. Our writers know how to make these two snobby guys
very human.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the writers on ``Frasier,'' who have collected
three Emmys to date, are fearless. It took nerve, for example, to
lead off this season with a story line that saw Frasier ousted from
his radio career and sunk in general depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got nine shows out of it,'' Grammer says with a shrug. ``It
was an interesting journey for Frasier, but we always knew he'd go
back to the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it made the audience uncomfortable, because Frasier's
confidence was completely shot,'' he says. ``It's interesting,
because he's often lacking in confidence. But if Frasier is in real
despair, it makes the comedy a little harder. I mean, a guy who's
pompous and out of work is a little hard to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of the game, Grammer says, he and the writers are
hesitant to drop another full-time cast member into the mix.
There's still room for the occasional recurring character, such as
Canadian actor Saul Rubinek as Donny, Niles's sleazy lawyer who
also has designs on Daphne.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect any new additions to the regular cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried that,'' Grammer says, wincing. ``A few years ago, we
added Mercedes Ruehl as the station manager, and we thought about
making her full-time. We got, like, five shows out of it, and that
seemed sufficient _ that seemed like the limit to what we had
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which would seem to rule out a regular girlfriend for Frasier,
though the possibility is always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope so,'' Pierce says jokingly. ``Don't you think
he's suffered enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Frasier's previous pairings _ with women played by JoBeth
Williams, Virginia Madsen, Linda Hamilton and other comely
actresses _ have all ended badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Frasier is still looking for love,'' Grammer says
with a sigh. ``We may yet find a comfortable relationship for him.
If it was filled with humor and autonomy and parity and real love,
I think it would be a wonderful thing to have.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more personal level, Grammer says that he's finally come to
terms with his own success. After a miserable and violent childhood
_ both his father and his sister were murdered _ the actor's early
years in Hollywood were marred by drunken-driving incidents and
self-admitted problems with alcohol, as well as two failed
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   All that is in the past, he says now. He's off the bottle, and
with his wife Camille _ the two married last year _ he says he's
finally able to accept his own happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did an interview with Details magazine where they asked me
what was my most `mondo' year,'' he says. ``And this year has been
the best year of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the past two or three years have been
extraordinary,'' he says thoughtfully. ``It's sometimes hard for me
to believe that I can be functionally this happy all the time _ and
still be miserable when I need to be. There's this factor in me
that needs something to be wrong, or I just don't feel that I'm
alive. But things are very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his continuing commitment to ``Frasier,'' Grammer would
like to make another ``appearance'' on ``The Simpsons,'' where he
has voiced the malevolent Sideshow Bob in several episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, I'd love to do another one,'' he says enthusiastically.
``The last time Bob was a good guy, but he was wrongly sent back to
jail, which is really going to piss him off. I suspect when `The
Simpsons' plan their final episode, they'll have Sideshow Bob
return and finally destroy that wretched little town.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, ``Frasier'' should keep Grammer busy.
He's signed for three more years after this season, which would
make almost two decades of playing the same character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it bother me having played the exact same person for 19
years? Not at all,'' he says, smiling broadly. ``I think Frasier's
a pretty grand guy. Don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
