<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _Economic historians have spent decades trying
to pin down the reasons for ``American exceptionalism,'' a phrase
coined in the 1830s by Alexis de Tocqueville, a French social
philosopher who wrote about why this country seemed so different
from Europe. The topic still fascinates. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ Just as I was about to be ushered into the
hallowed halls of the truly cantankerous, the unthinkable happens.
My son Kristofor brings home his lovely Amy and tells me they're
getting married. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _On a recent Saturday, my husband and
I found ourselves in a superstore _ not a regular destination for a
couple of anti-shoppers like us. You step through that door and
look up to see _ everything. It's the dime store of my youth ad
infinitum. Something insidious overtakes you. Pretty soon, you're
pushing two cartloads to the checkout counter and have nickeled and
dimed yourself into the hundreds. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I was
tipped off well ahead of time to the crisis in the region formerly
known as Yugoslavia. No, I don't read State Department cables,
Central European newspapers, exotic Web sites or even watch CNN. I
saw it at the liquor store. My intelligence about the region comes
from a source ignored by the foreign_policy establishment, unnoted
by pundits and unanalyzed by analysts. Look for this indicator and
you, too, can be a foreign policy prognosticator. Here it is:
impending political calamity creates cheap wine. (Lane, Daytona
Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
