<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, March 30,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET- PERSONAL-TECHNOLOGY 0326 _ The PalmPilot, a hand-held
computer, has sold nearly 3 million units, and its success has
awakened the giant in Redmond, Wash., known as Microsoft.
Microsoft's entry into the market has spawned scores of new
hand-held computers, powered by a light version of its Windows
operating system. Today, there are plenty of models, and they come
in all sizes, colors and configurations. But don't be fooled.
There's less variety than meets the eye. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes two 2-column color photos of
hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Hand-held computers at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE DIVERSITY _ The Internet's ability to turn people into
voices without faces makes it hard to see that the Net is becoming
more diverse. According to a new study by Forrester Research Inc.,
minorities are getting onto the Internet at an enormously
increasing rate. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR WARS'' REVIEW _ ``Star Wars'' fans clamoring for
information about the highly anticipated first prequel, ``The
Phantom Menace,'' can find clues and answers only a mouse click
away with ``Star Wars: Behind the Magic,'' a two CD-ROM set for PCs
from LucasArts. (Larsen, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 1-column
color photo of ``Star Wars'' character Princess Leia taken from the
CD.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ General Motors, the granddaddy of the automakers,
has stepped onto the Internet retail sales floor. The company has
unveiled its online shopping site, GM BuyPower. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-column color photo of web
site.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ As a kid, we tortured engines to get the most out
of them, even though we knew that shortened their life span. The
same thing happens with hopped-up computer chips: They live a short
but exciting life. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes 1 column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE _ Headsets are becoming more popular at home,
with their ability to let users get more mobility while talking.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ In honor of spring, we'll do some cleaning that
could save you money and will surely make your computer last
longer. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ A well-meaning attempt to review a $100 computer
gadget turned into a saga we'll call ``Oklahoma Warner and the Bus
of Doom.'' (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ Broadband is coming, and it's going to make your
current dial-up Internet service as outdated as an old PC left over
from the '80s. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ One of the most important uses of the Web must be
getting horoscopes. Otherwise, why would there be so many different
horoscope sites? (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ The Internet is becoming an increasingly big part
in both the marketing and distribution of music. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ Apple Computer is hoping its popular new iMac
computer will lure developers back to the Mac platform. (Haddad ,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ The folks at Yahoo! Internet Life have a standing
feature that takes a look at whether electronic commerce is really
the wave of the future. The piece in the April issue discusses the
question of whether it is easier to buy something on the Internet
or the old-fashioned way. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-TECH _ Anyone who has ever carried around a laptop
computer knows even the lightest machine becomes a heavyweight over
time. That's why AlphaSmart's such a nifty item. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REMOTES _ Harman/Kardon's Take Control remote promises to
be the easiest-to-use yet. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HEADSET _ Headsets are becoming more popular at home, with
their ability to let users get more mobility while talking.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ There's a place to turn to if you have
questions about anything. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ The United States and its allies began bombing
Yugoslavia last week, trying to bring peace to Kosovo. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-FEATURE _ Your family may celebrate one of two religious
holidays this week. If you're Jewish, you'll probably begin the
eight-day celebration of Passover on Wednesday evening. And if
you're Christian, you're likely to celebrate Easter this Sunday.
Though these two holidays remember different events for these
religions, they have some links. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-WRESTLING _ Hollywood producers are seeking new action
heroes to star in its movies, and they have their eyes on wrestling
shows, like TNT's ``WCW Monday Nitro'' and the USA Network's ``Raw
Is War.'' (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. How long do perfumes
last? Perfume longevity depends on storage. Once a bottle is
opened, it is meant to be used, say scent gurus. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-ASSISTANCE _ Georgia's AIDS Drug Assistance Program has the
longest waiting list of all the ADAP programs in the U.S., and it
also falls short in a number of other areas, according to a new
report by the Kaiser Family Foundation. ADAP is the safety net for
HIV-positive people who aren't quite poor enough to qualify for
Medicaid but can't afford the $10,000-$15,000 a year that anti-HIV
drugs cost. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
