<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8009 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     03-29 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, March 29, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA (Albany, N.Y.) _ When Viagra hit the pharmacy shelves one
year ago, it was love at first sight. The excitement has calmed
somewhat, although not on Wall Street. We assess the drug after its
first year of use. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   CHEATING-INTERNET (Albany, N.Y.) _ The good news about higher
education is that the classics are still being taught in
universities throughout the nation. The bad news is that a lot of
students aren't reading them. But with as many as 70 Web sites
offering term papers for as much as $200 each, the procrastinators
are now finding that on-line cheating is easy. By ANDREW
BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-KILLINGS (Sonora, Calif.) _ While the FBI has imported
a team of professional profilers to narrow its search for the
killers of three tourists, there are plenty of amateur profilers in
the Sierra Nevada foothills here, where the bodies of the women
were found. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-KITCHENS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The sturdy, reliable stoves of
yesteryear are back in style. And at least two companies, one in
Massachusetts and one in Canada, offer reproductions or restored
old stoves that are updated for today's modern kitchen. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ A company called EASE Simulation
manufactures a product called AutoWatch, which is essentially a way
to spy on how your teen-agers (or your employees) drive. It's the
car equivalent of the ``black box'' flight recorder on airplanes.
By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-EXPERT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Victor Porlier, a local resident,
recently published a book called ``Y2K: An Action Plan for Jan. 1,
2000,'' a user-friendly manual for preparing for computerdom's
worst-case scenarios. Now he's become a Y2K spokesman in demand
across the country. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   ETRADE-LAWSUITS (San Francisco) _ Thousands of consumers have
been hurt by recent system crashes and delays that are plaguing
on-line brokerages. Two class-action lawsuits filed against ETrade
Group Inc. highlight the growing pains of the young Internet
brokerage industry,. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ More and more baby boomers in their
early to mid-50s are opting to leave their steady jobs and move on
to new ventures _ whether that means volunteering full time or
launching their own business. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ A few months ago, I went gaga over
Netscape Communications' latest Web-surfing software, Communicator
4.5. While it was an incremental upgrade, it was enough of a leap
to push it past Internet Explorer 4.0. But now I've found a new
love: the Windows 98 version of Internet Explorer 5.0. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-Y2K (Undated) _ For many of us, the year 2000
computer problem is a scary notion looming on the horizon; but for
the nerds and technogeeks who understand the ramifications of
what's going to happen, it's the ultimate hack. One can only hope
that some of these nerds have a benevolent streak of those in the
gang that Mark Joseph describes in his novel, ``Deadline Y2K'' (St.
Martin's Press, $24.95). By HARRY THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-KILBORN (San Francisco) _ When Craig Kilborn walks onstage
Tuesday night as the host of ``The Late, Late Show,'' it's not just
going to be a ceremonial passing of the baton from Tom Snyder to
the new kid on the block. It's going to be a historic exchange _
the hip, wired age breaking away from the industrial era as the
millennium approaches. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ It is striking how much debate
followed the NATO aerial assault on Yugoslavia compared with how
little preceded the fateful decision. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It was a perfect afternoon and I
tried to find someone who cared about the war against Serbia. No
luck in my household. ``It's another Clinton thing,'' said my wife,
who is as cynical and isolationist as any American. ``I won't care
until the bombs start falling in my back yard.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ To say that I have mixed
feelings about the nasty fight between the Catholic Archdiocese and
the nuns-in-drag charity troupe, the Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence, is like saying that it isn't always easy to be a
Christian. Some of my very best friends are gay and some are nuns
and priests. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
