<P>
   For the Aztecs, human sacrifices were ironically the stuff of
life. Only human blood, they told Spanish priests, could give the
sun strength for its daily climb from the underworld. Yet for all
the grisly accounts of the early Spanish chroniclers,
archaeologists have exhumed surprisingly little evidence of these
rituals. That is until archaeologist Steve Bourget began digging at
the Pyramid of the Moon in Peru, where he unearthed a real
sacrificial site belonging to a lesser-known Andean people, the
Moche. Heather Pringle is the author of ``In Search of Ancient
North America.''
</P>
