<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEMPLES-OF-DOOM-NYTSF     03-29 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLES-OF-DOOM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLES OF DOOM  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FIVE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HEATHER PRINGLE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For the Aztecs, human sacrifices were ironically the stuff of
life. Only human blood, they told Spanish priests, could give the
sun strength for its daily climb from the underworld.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the grisly accounts of the early Spanish
chroniclers, archeologists have exhumed surprisingly little
evidence of these rituals. But thanks to a series of stunning
archeological discoveries, researchers are now gaining a clearer
glimpse of these ancient rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The picture emerges not from the most famous civilizations, but
from a much earlier and lesser known Andean people _ the Moche of
Peru's northern coastal desert. They flourished from A.D. 100 to
800 in the river valleys from the Andes to the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, archeologists puzzled over the paintings on Moche
pots. Many portrayed knife-wielding gods holding human heads and
owl-headed priests presiding over human sacrifices, but few
researchers believed they reflected actual practices. But
researchers are uncovering startling forensic evidence of human
sacrifice _ from mass graves to giant wall murals incorporating
butchered human bones.
</P>
<P>
   These new discoveries raise a host of questions, not the least
of which is why the Moche performed human sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Canadian archeologist Steve Bourget began
searching for sites where the Moche performed their slaughter.
Bourget, who had just finished his Ph.D. dissertation on Moche art
and sacred geography, found depictions of mountaintop rituals in
which priests seemed to fling humans to their death down steep
slopes. If the Moche pots showed real events, reasoned Bourget,
then the sacrifices could have taken place near Moche temples
situated at the feet of small mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Bourget began poring over Moche depictions of a different
sacrifice ritual, one that had been studied by Christopher Donnan,
an archeologist at UCLA. The gruesome ritual, which Donnan called
the warrior narrative, was a favorite theme of Moche artists,
appearing on ancient pots and wall murals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with Moche warriors going off to combat,'' Donnan
explains. ``Then some of the warriors are captured. All their
weapons, ornaments and clothing are taken from them. What follows
is a stage where the captors ... slap their faces and tear the
warriors' nose ornaments out. They put ropes around their necks and
parade them. The sacrifice follows.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, like other Moche experts, assumed that the warrior
narrative owed more to fiction than fact. But in 1987, Peruvian
archeologist Walter Alva exhumed the body of a great Moche lord,
dating to approximately A.D. 300. The man wore large circular
earspools and an immense gold headdress, a nose ornament and a back
flap, all crescent-shaped like the blade of a sacrificial knife. By
his side lay a scepter with a bladelike handle. These were the
insignia of the warrior priest.
</P>
<P>
   But if the sacrifices were actual events, where were all the
victims? Bourget studied depictions of the warrior narrative for
clues. And in 1995, he assembled a research team to excavate the
plaza at the Pyramid of the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Peeling back layers of sediment, he was soon surrounded by
whitened human skeletons. Bourget was jubilant. ``For the first
time, we could really see how the Moche performed human
sacrifice,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Such a rare and complex burial site called for a specialist.
John Verano, a physical anthropologist and osteologist who had
worked with archeological teams on Peru's north coast, was
summoned. He set up an impromptu morgue in the Archeology Museum at
the University of Trujillo where he examined the collection of
human remains.
</P>
<P>
   Verano found that all the corpses who could be identified
belonged to a select demographic group: young, healthy, physically
active males. Indeed, the mean age at death was just 23. Many, it
turned out, were old hands at combat. One in every four bore healed
rib, arm, leg and skull fractures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many of the men had fractures just beginning to
knit at the time of death. These confirmed the story, corresponding
eerily to scenes from the warrior narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Moche art,'' Verano says, ``the artists often show
prisoners being smacked on the nose so their noses will bleed, and
that's often done at the time of capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the healing of wounds, the battered men survived
for nearly two weeks after their capture, their last weeks mired in
misery. Death, when it finally arrived, came swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Verano's data suggests that the bodies at the Pyramid of the
Moon belonged to Moche warriors wounded and captured on the field
of battle. It is entirely possible, he says, that the ancient
desert dwellers, like the Aztecs, fought at least some battles
specifically to capture young males for sacrifice. Just how often
the Moche conducted sacrifices and how many lives they took has yet
to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Verano discovered something strange about an
enormous mural on the site. The pre-Columbian mural, painted in
crimson and electric yellow, shows a row of Moche nobles dancing
above the heads of war captives. While studying the mural,
researchers found a fallen chunk of mud plaster from one of the
dancer's feet. A piece of bone protruded from one end. Verano could
see that it was the rounded end of a human femur. It had been
chopped from a cadaver, stripped of flesh, and incorporated into
the giant mural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dancers are stepping on the bones of their enemies,'' he
says, ``or their victims.''
</P>
<P>
   While new evidence explains much about how sacrifices were
performed, it falls far short of answering why. Researchers such as
Elizabeth Benson have traced an intimate link between the offering
of human lives and agricultural fertility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, people thought they could change the world by
ritual,'' Benson says. ``This was how you controlled the world, how
you had enough food for your people. And a human being was the most
important offering you could make.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDEBAR: WHY DID THE GODS DEMAND BLOOD? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To the people who say the Moche or the Aztecs did sacrifices
because their gods demanded it, I would say, Why did their gods
demand it and other peoples' gods did not?'' observes Michael
Winkelman, an anthropologist at Arizona State University in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Winkelman studied scientific accounts of 45 societies worldwide
and came up with seven sacrifice performing societies, from the
Marquesans of the South Pacific to the Romans. He detected several
common, distinguishing traits: nearly all suffered from high
population densities and fought wars over land and scarce
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, all the sacrificing societies were ruled locally by a
leader from a powerful family; in such a system, treachery and
betrayal were constant threats. To intimidate those contemplating
betrayal, Winkelman says, leaders naturally gravitated toward human
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Moche experts call Winkelman's work thought-provoking, but few
are ready to accept that his analyses apply to the Moche, because
not enough is known about their population density or political
organization.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Heather Pringle lives in Vancouver, British Columbia, and
specializes in writing about archeology. She is the author of ``In
Search of Ancient North America.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
