<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-KITCHENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOVES OF YESTERYEAR COME WITH MODERN TOUCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ By the turn of the century, the summer kitchen
was common in many houses. The summer kitchen could be either a
separate room or even a porch, providing a cooler space in which to
prepare family meals.
</P>
<P>
   While the kitchen stove of today quickly cools after cooking,
the cookstoves of the 1880s were made of cast iron, or cast iron
with soapstone inserts. They burned wood or coal and not only
produced a slow steady heat but kept the room warm for hours after
the meal was consumed.
</P>
<P>
   This period was also the height of the American stove industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stove makers took great pride in the craftsmanship of these
cast-iron beauties, producing them in a variety of styles that
included nickel trim and other ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   The stoves were made so well and were so serviceable that they
lasted for decades, unlike many of today's cookstoves, which have
obsolescence built into them.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with the modern kitchen of the 1920s, enamel stoves
became popular, giving the cook a choice of colors, plus the
convenience of cleaning the stove with a damp cloth, according to
the Good Time Stove Co., in Goshen, Mass. Beige, white, gray green
and a popular blue were typical colors.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, Good Time Stove Co. has been rescuing and restoring
these the old workhorses, which not only supplied heat to adjoining
rooms, but heated household water.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a restored cast-iron or enamel range, adapted for
electric or gas heat, or a combination of the two, from Good Time
Stove are $2,850 to $7,650.
</P>
<P>
   Because these stoves are considered works of art, Elmira Stove
Works in Waterloo, Ontario, has been in business for 20 years
making new stoves with the latest technology, but designed to look
like models from the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   These feature gas or electric cooktops and self-cleaning ovens.
A convection oven is only available on electric models.
</P>
<P>
   Elmira stoves, which cost from $3,650 to $6,000, feature
matching microwave and wall ovens and refrigerators in a variety of
six jewel-tone colors with a choice of nickel, brass or copper
trim.
</P>
<P>
   Oil, gas and electrical stoves replaced original cast-iron range
by the 1930s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
