<HEADLINE>
`BLACK BOX' FOR CAR CAN HELP TRACK LEAD FOOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Phone numbers, Web site CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A company called EASE Simulation manufactures a product called
AutoWatch, which is essentially a way to spy on how your teen-agers
(or your employees) drive. It's the car equivalent of the ``black
box'' flight recorder on airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   After using a home computer to set limits such as maximum speed,
throttle position and RPMs, hook AutoWatch up to your vehicle's
diagnostic wiring. After a drive, use the PC to download printed
proof of, for example, the fact that the car was driven at 87 mph
for six minutes at 3 p.m. on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A battery backup even will tell you if AutoWatch has been
tampered with or the car's battery has been disconnected, and for
how long. The $300 device works on vehicles made since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For information or to order, call 888-366-3273 or visit
http://www.easesim.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STAND-UP STUFF: Beanie Babies don't break, even if you toss 'em
at your loved ones. But other collectibles _ Hummels, for example,
or glass figurines _ are more fragile.
</P>
<P>
   A gust of wind or a jostle or a thump can cause a chip or knock
the noggin right off that porcelain cherubim. To the rescue comes a
trio of products designed to keep collectibles from falling over _
Museum Putty, Museum Wax and Museum Gel, all of which we find in a
catalog of household goods called Practica.
</P>
<P>
   Slap a glob of the stuff on the bottom of the valuable to keep
it upright, even during an earthquake, according to the catalog.
Use the restickable putty for pieces you move frequently, the wax
for objects that stay put, the clear-drying and re-usable gel on
glass shelves or beneath crystal.
</P>
<P>
   The products, priced at about $10 each, are available by calling
800-863-5613.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN SCENE: A statue called The Bird Girl once stood in a
cemetery in Savannah, Ga., until author John Berendt came along,
wrote a book called ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' and
put a picture of the statue on the cover of the millions-selling
volume.
</P>
<P>
   So many people visited the city as a result of the book, and
tramped all over the graveyard, that the statue was moved to a
museum. Now you can have your own 2-foot version, courtesy of
Ballard Designs.
</P>
<P>
   The company says nothing about whether your house will be
overrun by visitors should you choose to add it to your decor.
Order the bronze-looking resin statue ($240 with base, $185
without) by calling 800-367-2775. Find Berendt's gripping tale in
bookstores, but never, ever rent the movie version, which Clint
Eastwood directed at a stupefying pace.
</P>
</TEXT>
