<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVEL BRINGS Y2K PROBLEM TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY THOMAS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This millennium actually ends on Dec. 31, 2000, but the Y2K
computer problem will hit a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of computers, programs, critical systems and
established ways of life will come to a grinding halt, we're told.
Yet who knows what will really happen?
</P>
<P>
   For many of us, it's a scary notion looming on the horizon; but
for those who understand the ramifications of what's going to
happen, the nerds and technogeeks who write the software and build
the chips, it's the ultimate hack. They will come to rule the Earth
because they are the only ones who know how big the problem is and
what it will take to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that some of these nerds have a benevolent
streak, such as those in the gang that Mark Joseph describes in his
novel, ``Deadline Y2K'' (St. Martin's Press, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Headed by a computer genius named Doc, a group of hackers called
the Midnight Club concocts a plan to keep Manhattan running when
the rest of the world self-destructs as the clocks strike midnight
on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, the Midnight Club must hack into the major systems
that keep the city running on a pre-Y2K basis and replace them with
their own. They know there is no way that they can keep everyone
on-line, but they hope to prevent anarchy in the world's most
important financial center.
</P>
<P>
   Doc also has to thwart the unscrupulous plans of his boss,
Donald Copeland, who is determined to use the impending crisis to
steal millions from unsuspecting banks who will have no knowledge
of his crime.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium bug sweeps across the planet, chaos ensues.
Companies that spent billions on Y2K measures still find themselves
brought down by overlooked systems; governments have to deal with
angry and cold citizens as the world's nuclear reactors and power
plants are forced to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Planes crash, banks fail, cities burn.
</P>
<P>
   The timeline moves inexorably westward, and Doc's team is still
missing some important passwords that will make their plan a
success. The tension builds as the zero hour approaches America's
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph does something here that most other books and news
articles on Y2K haven't done: He makes the problem comprehensible
to the layperson. His good characters are laid back and likable; he
demonstrates a strong feel for the intertwined worlds of the geek
and the Wall Street businessman.
</P>
<P>
   But the bad guy, Copeland, is too one-dimensional, his fate
almost an anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   The real tension in the novel is based on the realization of how
connected to computers our current technological society is. Joseph
wryly notes that the Third World countries will fare best during
the crisis because they aren't dependent on technology as we are.
</P>
<P>
   If only 10 percent of what Joseph portrays in ``Deadline Y2K''
comes true, we're in for a hard year on Planet Earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
