<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS TOSS OFF DAILY GRIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By L.M. SIXEL  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It always takes courage to make a sea change in
midlife _ especially if that means giving up a regular paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   That's something Saadat Syal discovered when he decided to chuck
his 16-year career of wooing companies to town as vice president of
economic development for the Greater Houston Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Syal, 53, gave it up for the real estate development business.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family have been buying property in inner Houston
over the past several years and they want to build houses and town
houses on the vacant turf. He also has family business in Pakistan
that needs tending.
</P>
<P>
   And he's looking forward to doing volunteer work that he never
had time for. For instance, he spent the past week handling several
mediation cases for neighboring Fort Bend County.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to give up the daily grind, he said about his years
with the Partnership. He wanted a career that gave him more
flexibility and an opportunity to use the skills he has picked up
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   More and more baby boomers in their early to mid-50s are opting
to leave their steady jobs and move on to new ventures _ whether
that means joining the Peace Corps, volunteering full time or
launching their own business.
</P>
<P>
   There just seems to be a general mood of restlessness, Syal
said, speaking of his contemporaries. People have worked hard,
acquired lots of accouterments and now want something more out of
life.
</P>
<P>
   And it was really now or never, Syal said, since the economy is
so good right now.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an overnight decision but more of an evolutionary
process, Syal said. He said he carefully planned his new real
estate venture for several years before setting out.
</P>
<P>
   Many baby boomers are feeling that same itch because the whole
concept of work has changed. People are healthier and live longer
and many can't fathom the idea of putting up their feet when they
hit 65, said Cheryl Matherly, director of the Career Services
Center at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   People who are reaching the age of 40, 45, 50 are thinking about
all the productive years they've got left and wondering if they
want to keep doing what they've been doing, said Matherly, who
recalled a 60-year-old alum who came in and took some career tests
because he was looking for a change in direction.
</P>
<P>
   Many boomers can afford to sing the tune Johnny Paycheck made
famous, ``Take This Job and Shove It,'' because they've done well
in the stock market. They can afford to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Syal said he and his wife always lived below their means. They
bought less house than they could have, they didn't take elaborate
vacations and didn't accumulate any credit card debt.
</P>
<P>
   But while some boomers may have the assets to go out on a limb,
it's not always an easy decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Boynton said he sees a lot of senior executives who
develop a sense of wanderlust, but many don't have the nerve to
leave their organization and go out on their own.
</P>
<P>
   It's not because they lack courage. Rather, it's a reluctance to
move out of the comfort zone of the authority and infrastructure
that they've developed in their organization, said Boynton,
president of the Morganstern Co., an executive outplacement company
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When you're out on your own you have to make your own coffee and
answer your own phone, Boynton said.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Miller also sees nervousness among midcareer folks who
might be thinking about jumping into a new career.
</P>
<P>
   They may be tired of their jobs but they're comfortable and it
provides a steady income, said Miller, chairman of the Houston
chapter of the Service Corps of Retired Executives. High-tech
employees seem to be an exception, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They seem a little more adveNt\97us and sure of themselves, he
said. And many have seen their friends' start-ups strike it big.
</P>
<P>
   Downsizing also appears to spawn entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a month, SCORE conducts seminars on how to start a
business. When the economy is suffering, attendance at the seminars
soar, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Syal said he is already enjoying his new life. The volunteering
has been enjoyable and he is looking forward to lining up his first
real estate development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day should be an adventure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or
call 713-220-2000 and enter access code 1002.)
</P>
</TEXT>
