<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-Q&AMP;A-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU RECEIVE `PASS IT ON' E-MAIL, YOU'D BE WELL ADVISED TO PASS
ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have been getting e-mails from my friends that include a
warning that Congress is about to pass legislation in two weeks
that will force everyone to pay for Internet access by the minute,
like a long-distance call. Since I've been getting this ``in the
next two weeks'' message over several months' time, I presume it's
a hoax. Am I right?
</P>
<P>
   A: You are, although recent events at another governmental body
_ the Federal Communications Commission _ gave momentary credence
to what is actually a variation of an old, old online hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The message you are receiving probably reads something like
this: ``Guess we realized the government would sooner or later find
a way to tax us for using the Internet. Congress will be voting in
less than two weeks. CNN stated that the government would, in two
weeks time, decide to allow or not allow a charge to your phone
bill equal to a long distance call EACH time you access the
Internet. The address is www.house.gov/writerep/. If you choose,
visit the address above and fill out the necessary form. If EACH
one of us forwards this message on to others in a hurry, we may be
able to prevent this injustice from happening! Please Pass This
ON.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the direct descendant of an old hoax that began on
computer bulletin boards, prior to the popularity of the Internet,
of a ``modem tax.'' It was bogus then, and it's bogus now.
</P>
<P>
   However, several weeks ago the Federal Communications Commission
ruled that calls via Internet service providers to the Net could be
considered long-distance calls, since the Internet is a global
network. The FCC's chairman, however, was quick to point out that
it does not mean consumers will be charged as though the calls were
long-distance, but it may change the financial relationship between
providers and the phone companies on which they rely.
</P>
<P>
   In general, anytime you see some kind of dire warning that urges
you to ``pass it on,'' it's probably not worth passing on. But how
can you tell if something's phony or not? Try doing a search for
the words ``virus hoax'' at Yahoo (www.yahoo.com), where you'll
find several pages devoted to debunking hoaxes. One of my favorites
is the Stiller Research Virus Hoax News at
www.stiller.com/hoaxes.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Somebody just sent me an e-mail, and then there was a
separate piece of mail from the same person with just an attachment
called Happy99.exe.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't run it, because I know better than to run programs
received as attachments, but I have heard this is a virus. Is this
true, or just another hoax?
</P>
<P>
   A: In this case, Happy99 is real. Most people who spread it
don't even know they're doing so.
</P>
<P>
   If you had run Happy99, you would have seen a pretty display of
fireworks on your screen. While you were enjoying the show, the
program _ which is technically not a virus, but a kind of Trojan
horse known as a worm _ would have been altering some of the key
files your computer uses to connect you to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, every time you post a message to a Usenet news group, or
send e-mail to someone, it sends a copy of itself along with that
mail, as a separate piece of mail with an attachment.
</P>
<P>
   If you receive it, simply delete it. Your computer is not
affected unless you run the program.
</P>
<P>
   If you have made the mistake of running it, it's easy to remove.
You can find the steps for doing so at
www.symantec.com/avcenter/venc/data/happy99.worm.html. This article
contains information both about restoring the files Happy99
changes, or _ if you have run it but not yet restarted your
computer _ how to prevent a full infection from taking place.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can
receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000
and enter access code 1001.)
</P>
</TEXT>
