<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8090 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLY-WEEK-PAIN-NYTSF &LR;      03-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLY-WEEK-PAIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY AND PUBLIC PIETY OFFER A HOLY WEEK LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEMPHIS -- For many people, the recent Amtrak crash in Illinois
was just another sad story reported one night and forgotten the
next. For those of us in Memphis, however, the story has lasted
longer.
 &HT;    Memphis was a stop along the train's route. Several local
families had members injured or killed. The most heartrending story
was of two sisters, ages 8 and 10, who died in the sleeping-car
fire.
 &HT;    In the days preceding their funeral, the parents, members of one
of the city's prominent evangelical churches, appeared on numerous
