<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-PASSOVER-BAKERY     03-29 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-PASSOVER-BAKERY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A GRITTY FACTORY, BAKING THE BREAD OF FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   I walked into the supermarket to buy kosher food for the holiday
of Passover and to my amazement there were no less than five brands
of kosher wines and matzoh.
</P>
<P>
   The wines were from Italy, France, Israel, California and
upstate New York. The matzoh display had boxes from Israel,
Cincinnati and New York.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up we would eat special hand-made matzohs for
Passover.
</P>
<P>
   The matzoh was made from only two ingredients, flour and water.
The flour and water must be mixed and kneaded by hand and when the
dough is formed, small lumps of dough are given to a baker who
hand-flattens the dough with small rolling pins.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a special metal roller, with dozens of pins, is rolled
over the flat dough. The dough is shaped and baked in an open, flat
baker's stove -- all within 18 minutes from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Let me describe my first visit to a matzoh bakery before
Passover. I was 8 years old and my Chasidic grandfather, called
Zaydee, called me and said ``Eli, Pesach is coming and we need
shmura matzoh, come bake matzoh.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me try to describe a visit to a strange place in a strange
land. The bakery was located in a dilapidated area of Williamsburg,
in New York. It was an old, red-brick factory with rusty grates on
the windows. It must have been built in the late 1880s. The steps
leading into the building had cracks in the cement from the many
years of use. The heavy iron doors had gigantic hinges.
</P>
<P>
   The place looked like it was from the Dark Ages. I was afraid to
go in. Zaydee, however, had no time for my hesitation. He just held
on to my hand and said ``Sonny boy, come in and perform the mitzvah
of baking matzoh for Pesach.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside I saw an incredible sight. There were men running
back and forth. Some were shouting at other men and women to roll
the rolling pins on the dough quicker. Others were singing songs
and the baker kept on yelling at the top of his voice, ``Le shaim
mitzvas matzoh -- for the sake of the deed of matzoh,'' meaning
that each matzoh was being baked for the express purpose of
fulfilling God's command of having unleavened bread -- matzoh. I
had never seen so many things happening at once.
</P>
<P>
   In one area stood an old man with a long beard and peyos (long
side locks). His only job was to be the water man. He wore a bright
white apron and every once in a while he would take a cup of water
from a 25-gallon jug prepared from the night before and pour it
into a new stainless steel basin.
</P>
<P>
   As he did that a second person would dump a huge cup of the
special flour into the basin while a third strong young man would
begin to mix the flour and water by hand. He would not stop moving
his hands until all the flour was mixed and had turned into dough.
</P>
<P>
   His hands twirled faster and faster like a tornado. It was magic
to me. Then another person would take the dough and make it into
little lumps and give it to workers at the kneading table. There
must have been five tables with eight workers to a table. All of
the workers were moving the rolling pins as fast as possible. The
heavier the person rolling the rolling pin, the flatter the dough
became and the matzohs were thinner.
</P>
<P>
   This answers the long unanswered question of why some hand-made
matzohs are thicker than others.
</P>
<P>
   Each matzoh was then carried to the oven on the rolling pin. The
baker put the matzoh into the oven and after a minute he removed
the baked matzoh. It was then placed on a table to be cooled by a
fan.
</P>
<P>
   The finished matzoh was then carried to the packer, who put
eight matzohs to a pound box.
</P>
<P>
   I remember seeing the people coming and going, the singing, and
the flour mixing with the water. The mixer had the largest muscular
hands I had ever seen. After kneading thousands of batches his
hands were like steel vises.
</P>
<P>
   The women of all ages were dressed, as prescribed by the Jewish
orthodox modesty code, with the hair on their heads completely
covered, their arms covered to the wrists and their dresses worn
over their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Their language was a United Nations of Yiddish, Hungarian,
Hebrew and a little English.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the arms of the men and women bore tattoo numbers from
the Aushwitz concentration death camp. For them, each matzoh baked
was a statement of their faith and good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange but happy world to see all the ages thrown
together for the holiday. Passover commences Wednesday night, March
31 at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Passover is an inspirational one. It tells us how a
whole nation of people were freed from years of tyrany and
enslavement. They experienced total freedom from Egyptian bondage.
</P>
<P>
   The Passover night festive meal, called the seder, symbolizes
the ultimate liberation for all people in all places in all times.
</P>
<P>
   This year when we eat our matzoh we should break off a piece and
share it with our neighbor. telling him that the message of
liberation is for all people. A happy Passover to you all.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
