<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN31-COX     03-29 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: GETTING DROOPY AND GROWING OLD
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ At some point in life we stop growing
older and, instead, start growing old.
</P>
<P>
   You'll know it when it happens. Your doctor will tell you when
you show up for an appointment for some new ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just part of growing old,'' he'll explain with a shrug.
Which is to say, nothing much you can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I hate going to the doctor. I hate hearing what's
newly amiss with me that will never be made right, least wise not
in my lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That's why when my left eye started bothering me at night _
waking me up weeping and aching _ that I put off going to the eye
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead I put on an eye patch and applied some ointment to the
offending eye each night at bedtime. It helped but it didn't heal.
The left eye was still blurring out on me on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I finally sought professional eye doctor help.
</P>
<P>
   He took one long look into my bloodshot baby blues (actually,
they're greezer green) and pronounced judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we call, for lack of a better term . . .'' he began.
</P>
<P>
   I just knew he'd complete the sentence with:
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . black death.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that bad, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . droopy eyelid,'' the doctor concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The corner of my eye, I'm told, has become sort of unraveled. At
night, with that side of my face pressed against the pillow, the
eyelid rubs against the eyeball. (Ah, there's the rub.)
</P>
<P>
   As a result . . . Well, let me use the doctor's precise
terminology:
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like raw meat,'' he advised me.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, there's even something they can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   They can tuck it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very minor surgery,'' the doctor said, which is to me the
magic words.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, there are those who are of the opinion that the
difference between minor and major surgery is whether it's being
done to someone else or to you.)
</P>
<P>
   No matter. I'm all set for next month when a specialist from
Dallas comes visiting the provinces to perform his medical miracles
on country folk.
</P>
<P>
   At this point I'm not sure if they'll do both eyes or just one,
but you'll know next time you see me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll either look like Popeye or Betty Boop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile I'm continuing with the eye patch and ointment. My
doctor, for a fact, couldn't improve on the treatment I'd devised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have taken no telling how many ophthalmologists
probably thousands of work hours to have come up with the same
solution,'' he said, obViously impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Just lucky, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, too, that it's an affliction that can be cured.
</P>
<P>
   Of everything that I have drooping, this is the one thing that
can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's looking at you, kid.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
