A8118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIAGRA-HNS &LR;      03-29 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIAGRA REMAINS A HOT COMMODITY YEAR AFTER APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When Viagra hit the pharmacy shelves last year,
it was love at first sight. Many Americans finally found what
they'd been longing for: an easier way to treat erectile
dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the real excitement and enthusiasm, and all the
floods of phone calls have all calmed down,'' said Dr. Ronald
Kaufman, an assistant professor of surgery at Albany Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill hasn't gone from Wall Street either. Pfizer, the New
York-based manufacturer of the drug, reported sales of $788 million
last year, making it one of the most successful prescription drugs
ever. Stock in the company is up 44 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that 20 million to 30 million American men suffer
from erection problems, demand isn't likely to subside.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any new fling, it's hard to sustain the enthusiasm,
even with former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., promoting
it on television.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings that men with heart conditions should avoid
Viagra, the Food and Drug Administration has received reports of
130 deaths, including 77 from cardiovascular events, such as
strokes and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In France, 10 men died after suspected Viagra use during the
first three months of the drug's availability.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those concerns, Pfizer, in conjunction with the FDA,
revised Viagra's label last year to include a stronger warning.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente and MVP, two health maintenance organizations,
continue not to include Viagra in their prescription plans because
of the potential for problems. Another concern is the cost of
Viagra at about $10 per pill.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even some of those people with no complicating conditions
are now thinking twice about using Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are a little more cautious,'' said Dr. Daniel Finn, a
urologist in Albany. ``We've become very conscious of the fact that
some people have had a bad reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the drug has simply been a disappointment. In early
studies of 4,000 men with varying erectile dysfunction, the drug
worked for only 64 to 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Urologists say they've seen similar results among their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some patients fail, many patients are successful,''
Kaufman said. ``It's unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the disappointment has been caused by hyped expectations
around the drug. For months, men and women waited for the FDA to
approve Viagra. The federal agency approved the drug on March 27,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   As Pfizer's stock soared, so did the hopes of couples affected
by erectile dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra works by acting on an enzyme prevalent in the penis to
boost blood flow. Yet many doctors and therapists warned from the
start that Viagra couldn't solve every bedroom problem, even as it
raised awareness about sexual issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jennifer Berman, a urologist and director of the Women's
Sexual Health Clinic at Boston University, is conducting a study of
the effect of Viagra on postmenopausal women who have arousal
disorders, caused by vaginal dryness, surgery or other
physiological reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have so far shown mixed to disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't treat female sexual dysfunction the same way you
treat male erectile dysfunction,'' Berman said. ``The context in
which a woman experiences her sexuality is as equally as important
as the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Viagra, however, at least people are talking more
these days about the science and psychology of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely making progress,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
