<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN0331-     03-29 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN0331-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hilfiger Internet hoax has too long a life
 &HT;    For release March 31, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An e-mail message last week was addressed to me and 15 others.
At the bottom of the page, I was able to see that the sender, along
with another 15 persons, received it from someone else.
</P>
<P>
   What he passed along to me, and to all those others, was an
extension of a venal hoax. My friend didn't recognize it as such
and, thus, compounded it.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of what he sent began: ``I'm not sure many of you
watched the recent taping of the Oprah Winfrey show where her guest
was Tommy Hilfiger . . .''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a report claiming that clothing designer Tommy
Hilfiger went on Oprah Winfrey's TV show and said he did not make
his clothes for African-Americans, Hispanics, Jews and Asians, that
he made them only for upper-class white people; whereupon Oprah
ordered him off her show.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately upon reading that, more red flags flew in front of
my face than I might see at a May Day rally. If such a thing ever
occurred on TV, especially the Oprah Winfrey show, it would be
front page news and Hilfiger's name, and product, would turn to
instant mud.
</P>
<P>
   That was the apparent goal of the e-mail, to destroy the
Hilfiger name and line. The e-mail demanded a boycott of Hilfiger
products: ``Let's give Mr. Hilfiger what he asked for. Let's not
buy his clothes! Let's spread the word, so others won't buy his
clothes either.''
</P>
<P>
   And spread the word they did.
</P>
<P>
   What a vicious lie it was. And to make matters worse, what my
friend was passing on to me in late March was something that first
appeared on the Web in December and has been denied by both Winfrey
and Hilfiger ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Hilfiger never was on the Winfrey show; they have never
met each other. It did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lie has endured and the appeals to ethnic and racial
knee-jerk reaction remain alive, spreading out to more and more
people.
</P>
<P>
   Where and how did this start? I can't be certain, but surfing
the Web, I was able to track the exact text back to a Web site
called IWW News. It was dated Dec. 23, 1998. I don't know what IWW
News is, other than there are constant references through its Web
site listings to ``revolutionary unionism.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a cause has as much right to the Internet as anyone
else. Eventually, however, there has to be something established to
deal with Internet lies, hoaxes and libels without endangering our
First Amendment rights or, since the Web is worldwide, the rights
of people in other countries. Placing limits on speech is a risky
business.
</P>
<P>
   But what needs to come out of this hoax, cited in the Hilfiger
denial as being the same story spread about designer Liz Claiborne
in 1992, is for the gullible public to realize that what appears on
the Internet ain't, as Ira Gershwin wrote, necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   There have been hoaxes before and will continue to be. In 1997,
a lot of people _ including former JFK press chief Pierre Salinger
_ made fools of themselves abetting the Internet-initiated report
that a U.S. Navy missile took down TWA Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the originator of this unprincipled hoax admitted
what he did was ``reckless and a mistake.'' Indeed!
</P>
<P>
   Don't even accept, unconditionally, the photos you see on the
Internet, or anywhere for that matter, as they can be falsified
with computer software. You want a photo of Meg Ryan out fishing
with Adolf Hitler? Piece of cake!
</P>
<P>
   In the Hilfiger hoax, the knee-jerkers who stand ready and
willing to destroy people and businesses based on an
unsubstantiated report can be most dangerous. I would guess that
thousands of people received the ``Boycott Hilfiger'' e-mail during
the past three months and shamefully did just that.
</P>
<P>
   These are great days for cynics like me; so much to do, so much
to distrust.
</P>
<P>
   We need more cynics and less sheep.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
