<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENIGNI-FILMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENIGNI BEFORE `LIFE' BEGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your appetite has been whetted for more Roberto Benigni
films, here are some videos that can be rented with a bit of
hunting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Down by Law'': Cult director Jim Jarmusch's stubbornly
nonconformist 1986 road comedy is so leisurely, it's like looking
at a series of black-and-white Polaroids. But Benigni, as a
cockeyed Italian optimist who falls in with losers Tom Waits and
John Lurie, gives it a much-needed steroid injection. His refrain
here _ ``It's a sad and beautiful world!'' _ could have been a
dress rehearsal for his Oscar speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night on Earth'': Jarmusch's unhurried style was much better
suited to this 1991 series of vignettes about taxi drivers.
Benigni's bit, in which he plays a Rome cabby who makes an
outrageous impromptu confession to a stunned priest, is hilariously
off-color and easily the movie's most memorable sequence. The
movie's non-English portions are subtitled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Stecchino'': Here's a double dose of Benigni: In this
1992 film, he plays a mild-mannered Roman bus driver who's seduced
into switching identities with a notorious gangster. Italian with
English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son of the Pink Panther'': A big mistake from 1993, this
desperate sequel cast Benigni as the son of Peter Sellers'
Inspector Clouseau _ an Italian playing the son of a French
detective made famous by a Brit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Monster'': More mistaken identity, as Benigni stars as a
bumbling petty thief mistaken for a serial killer. This 1996 film
is one of the highest-grossing films in Italian history. Subtitled.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
