<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSTOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGHT-PROVOKING PLAYTHINGS FROM THE ANNUAL TOY FAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanied by BC-NEWTOYS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KELLY DeGARMO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moms have spoken. They want toys that teach their children while
entertaining them. And toy manufacturers are delivering.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``electronic learning aids,'' or ELAs, today's
electronic brain boosters drill kids about the alphabet, phonics,
animals, colors, numbers, spelling, geography and more.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in the form of plush dolls, mini-laptops or palm-size
toys, these electronic learning aids are activated by the push of a
button. Then the fun begins. Using voice technology, a toy designed
for infants might recite a color, letter or shape; a product for
elementary school-age children may quiz students on state capitals
and simple mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   The ELA products sold last year _ $200 million worth _ was up 20
percent from 1997, according to the Toy Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for consumers is that prices are coming down as
computer technology becomes less expensive, says New York toy
consultant Christopher Byrne, an editor for several trade
publications. Eight years ago, ELAs cost $40 or more; now some can
be had for $20 and under. And with the increasingly cheaper
technology, the field for age 6 months and older is getting
crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Age-appropriate ELAs are a good idea for most kids, but parents
shouldn't go overboard. ``You only need one or two,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   One way to pick an ELA is by brand, said Byrne. Industry leaders
include Educational Insights, VTech, Tiger Electronics, ToyMax,
Mattel and newcomer Leap Frog.
</P>
<P>
   Also, parents will soon be able to choose more ELAs linked to
licensed characters, such as Nickelodeon's popular ``Blue's
Clues.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one of the most challenging parts of these toys is
getting kids to play with one, said Michael Wood, president of Leap
Frog, maker of the hot-selling Hug &AMP; Learn Little Leap. The plush
frog uses interactive games to encourage thinking and reasoning
skills for preschoolers. New this year is Hug &AMP; Learn Baby Tad for
little ones 6 to 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most innovative new product is the Leap Pad ($50),
an electronic reading pad that uses magnetic pen technology to
allow a child to interact with the book while reading it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want kids to be as excited about reading as they are about
Nintendo,'' said Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Eight book titles will be available, including favorites Richard
Scarry and Winnie-the-Pooh. The battery-operated electronic pad
folds up to be portable and comes with a headphone jack for travel.
These, like many of the new ELAs, are compact enough to be
portable, making them ideal companions for car trips, plane trips
and other excursions.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
