<HEADER>
A8145 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-`FUTURAMA'-TEX     03-29 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-`FUTURAMA'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE GLIMPSED THE `FUTURAMA,' AND IT'S BLEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Groening told ``Entertainment Weekly'' that he doesn't want
critics to say that his new animated sitcom, ``Futurama,'' isn't as
good as that other show he created, ``The Simpsons.'' He thinks
that would be an unfair comparison, because ``The Simpsons'' is
perhaps the funniest sitcom ever.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Matt Groening's new show, ``Futurama,'' isn't as good as
``The PJs.'' In fact, judging by its first episode (the only one
sent to critics), ``Futurama'' _ which aired Sunday night and airs
again April 4 before moving to Tuesdays at 7:30 p.m. beginning
April 6 _ could become to Groening what ``Leonard, Part 6'' was to
Bill Cosby: a huge comedy embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Could, but probably won't. One would think that Groening is too
smart and funny to not punch up the sometimes horribly stale jokes
in ``Futurama.'' Like this one: When the hero, Fry, awakes 1,000
years in the future, he's told that his only living relative is his
``Great-great-great-great-great-great-great ...
great-great-nephew.'' His response: ``Great!''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the spotty writing, the overriding problem with
``Futurama'' is that the show really isn't satire. (What are we to
relate to? That the New York Tube System sure is a wacky way to
travel?) It plays more like a man-out-of-his-element movie, most of
which (''Crocodile Dundee,'' ``Stripes'') depend on the charm of
their lead characters to engage us. In this case, Fry (voiced by
``Ren &AMP; Stimpy's'' Billy West), is so whiny and annoying that he
makes us cringe.
</P>
<P>
   The show begins showing us another rotten day in his dreadful
life as a pizza delivery boy. On his way to deliver a pizza (from
crank caller ``I.C. Weiner'' _ the first of several recycled
``Simpsons'' jokes) his bike is stolen and he finds out his
girlfriend is leaving him. The opening is so much like the first 10
minutes of ``Stripes'' you almost expect Fry to yell to his now
ex-lover, ``You can't go! All the plants will die!''
</P>
<P>
   The bogus address leads Fry to a cryogenics chamber, where,
during the New Year's Eve countdown, he inadvertently falls into
one of the chambers that freeze people. His timer is set for 1,000
years. The time-lapse scene out the window behind him offers one of
the few really good sight gags in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Once he's out, it's New Year's Eve, 2999. He meets Leela (Katey
Sagal), a ``Fate Assignment Officer.'' Seems everyone in the future
has their job destiny programmed into a chip and implanted into
their hand. That's why the future's slogan is, ``You gotta do what
you gotta do.'' Fry is scheduled to be a _ don't guess, now; it's
not fair _ a delivery boy! He rebels! He runs away, she follows.
</P>
<P>
   Hilarity does not ensue, though there are a few good lines. The
best such scenes come with the hard-drinking robot buddy Fry finds
when they both end up in a suicide booth together. (Sounds funnier
than it plays.) The robot, Bender, is depressed because his job,
bending girders, is so limiting. Not that he isn't good at it. As
he tells Fry while they're tossing back brews in a pub, ``I could
bend a girder to any angle: 30 degrees, 32 degrees ... (he takes a
swig, pauses, then says wistfully) ... 31.''
</P>
<P>
   That the show has little of the wit or even good crude humor of
``The Simpsons'' is inescapable. Especially because there are
several knowing winks toward the show in ``Futurama,'' including a
sighting of Blinky, the three-eyed fish that lived in the stream
near Mr. Burn's nuclear power plant. But do we really need to see a
guest shot of Leonard Nimoy, who made two such appearances on ``The
Simpsons''? (OK, technically only his animated head appears, but
you get the point.) And why in the world is there an Indian
character (Leela's boss) who speaks just like Apu if Groening is
trying to avoid comparisons?
</P>
<P>
   Groening may not like this, but facts are facts: A decade ago,
he created a brilliant show that began as an idea sketched on a
piece of paper five minutes before his interview with network
executives. Now, with 10 years to think about it, he has tried to
create what he describes as a ``sci-fi epic disguised as a
sitcom.'' It may get much, much better. We can hope. But if the
first episode is an indication, he failed _ it is barely sci-fi,
and a sitcom must have comedy to go with the wacky situations. Matt
Groening loves irony, so even he should appreciate that sometimes
success and riches can dull the impish genius that brought them
about in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
