A8159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      03-29 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Tuesday, March 30, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
day supervisor is Gary E. McCardell; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ The ledeall: NATO says some Albanian
leaders have been executed, announces that it is stepping up
attacks on Serbian troops in Kosovo. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO says Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, seems to be trying to carve out a Serbian republic in
Kosovo, re-engineering the political and population landscape in
advance of any resumption of peace talks. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROTECT (Washington) _ One point of the NATO attack was
to protect ethnic Albanians in Kosovo; now they are worse off than
ever. Did the U.S. anticipate this? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DRONES (Washington) _ The drone, an unmanned aircraft, is
one of the best tools NATO has to learn what is going on in Kosovo.
But drones have not yet been used. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ Which allied units are where and
which would be needed if NATO changed its mind and decided on a
land attack. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The weird scene and the
mood in the beseiged Yugoslav capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Dateline to kum) _ News Analysis: After
likening Milosevic to Hitler, can the United States still sit down
and do business with him, as it did at the Bosnia talks in Dayton,
Ohio. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Primakov, the Russian prime minister,
is going to Belgrade on Tuesday. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONITORS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The international monitors
who pulled out of Kosovo dejectedly reflect on what they might have
done differently, and desperately try to keep in touch with Kosovo.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Somewhere near the Kosovo border) _ Listening
to refugee voices: They tell of methodical, organized, systematic
expulsions by police and paramilitaries. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PILOTS (Aviano, Italy) _ What allied pilots are saying
about their missions over Yugoslavia. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these, we are considering stories on diplomatic
maneuvering among the allies and Russia and a story on the possible
relevance of the international convention on genocide.
</P>
