<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-LEGACY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN CASTS LONG SHADOW OVER GOP HOPEFULS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His mind and body are gripped by Alzheimer's
disease, but former President Ronald Reagan's spirit infuses
Campaign 2000 almost as if he were on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reagan's place in history remains under debate, there's
little doubt about his status as a Republican campaign icon. Nearly
every GOP presidential hopeful is claiming a piece of Reagan's
political legacy. His picture appears on campaign Web sites. His
words are recited in speech after speech.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaire publisher Steve Forbes calls himself ``a Reagan
conservative.'' Sen. John McCain of Arizona boasts that he was `'an
early foot soldier in the Reagan revolution.'' Pat Buchanan, the
conservative firebrand, promises to ``complete the final chapter of
Ronald Reagan's legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who served under George Bush,
a more recent Republican president, says he wants to ``resurrect
Ronald Reagan's vision of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates or likely candidates tout their service in the
Reagan administration. Elizabeth Dole served as Reagan's
transportation secretary after a stint as a White House aide.
Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander's Internet resume says that
he headed Reagan's ``Commission to Celebrate Great Americans
Outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   (News reports from the time indicate that the panel was actually
called the Commission on Americans Outdoors.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the search for another Reagan has led some
Republicans to the one likely candidate who rarely mentions him:
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Many of Bush's boosters contend that he
is the party's best hope for reuniting the coalition of economic
and social conservatives that helped Reagan win two White House
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a phenomenon in California we haven't seen
since Ronald Reagan,'' said California Assemblyman Keith Olberg,
one of a number of recent visitors to the Governor's Mansion in
Austin. ``He understands what America is all about, what the
founding of this country is all about. He's absolutely,
passionately committed to it. People get that from him.''
</P>
<P>
   But comparisons to Reagan cut both ways for Bush, whose father
was never fully trusted by some Reagan conservatives. Conservative
activist Brent Bozell III, who is backing Forbes, said Bush's quest
for the Republican nomination will hinge on his ability to prove
himself a worthy Reagan heir.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush were to make a determined and believable appeal to the
conservative base, it would be very difficult for anybody to beat
him,'' Bozell said. ``He's putting a lot of people in his camp who
never understood the conservative movement. To the degree that he
listens to them, he will find himself in trouble very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who often jokes that he inherited half his father's
friends and all his enemies, speaks of his parents with obvious
affection. At the same time, he has made it clear that his personal
devotion does not mean he walks in lock step with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the candidate. I am,'' Bush told the national news
media in declaring his interest in the White House and forming an
exploratory committee for a possible presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   When asked in an interview to name three political heroes
besides his father, Bush put Reagan at the top of the list, in
front of Winston Churchill and Theodore Roosevelt. He said Reagan
played a pivotal role in ending the era of big government that
began with Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan was president in a defining moment in history,''
Bush said. ``He ended the Rooseveltian era (by) putting government
in its proper perspective. The government's role is to herald the
individual and encourage individuals to reach their fullest
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reagan's legacy means different things to different people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something of a Rorschach _ you see in it what you want,''
said Rod Hart, an expert on political communication at the
University of Texas at Austin. ``I don't think they mean they want
soaring deficits and break-the-back expenditures from the federal
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Reagan's admirers acknowledge that his accomplishments
sometimes fell short of his goals. He was an outspoken foe of big
government who watched the federal deficit balloon to record levels
during his eight years in office. He was an outspoken foe of
abortion who failed to win any significant victories for his
anti-abortion allies.
</P>
<P>
   His record on defense was more clear-cut. By almost any
yardstick, Reagan delivered on his promise to beef up the nation's
military. Conservatives also credit his hard-line approach with
hastening the breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   And even Reagan's harshest critics acknowledge the skills that
earned him the nickname The Great Communicator. Reagan, who turned
88 in February, is spending his final years in virtual seclusion,
but he remains a beloved figure for many Americans who identified
with his cheerful optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed in the American spirit. He believed in freedom. He
believed in the goodness of the American people,'' Forbes said in
an interview. ``No one can imitate Ronald Reagan. People would see
through that, but the spirit of Ronald Reagan is what people are
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Jay Root in Austin contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
