<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR KEEPS HIS EYE ON THE Y2K CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Victor Porlier still remembers a cocktail party,
many years before anyone would coin the term Y2K, when he got his
first premonition of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   It was around 1968, and Porlier was helping to set up a
mainframe computer for the U.S. Agency for Economic Development. At
the party, someone told him how the high-tech IBM system would not
recognize the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing this is going to be fixed by the next
century,'' the man told Porlier. ``Otherwise it'll be hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's not hell. But it is expensive. The cost of solving
the so-called year 2000 problem is expected to climb into the
hundreds of billions of dollars, or higher, and all work may not be
done by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Porlier (pronounced ``Por-lee-ay''), who lives near Albany
in upstate New York. Thirty years after that cocktail party
conversation, the former investment specialist and college
professor has become a Y2K guru. He recently published the book
Y2K: ``An Action Plan for Jan. 1, 2000,'' a manual for preparing
for Y2K's worst-case scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Computer specialists fear that many computers originally
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year will
fail or malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume
it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, Porlier has gone from founder of the
nonprofit Center for Civic Renewal to a Y2K spokesman in demand
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that spreading his message on Y2K consumes about 25
percent of his frenetic work schedule. And that message, he says,
is ``be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now clear that this is a real problem,'' Porlier said.
``It is not hype. And there is very deep concern all over the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem also affects computer chips in factories and
machinery all over the world, although many say the problem will be
fixed in time for next year.
</P>
<P>
   What scares some people is the idea that crashing computers will
have a domino effect. Though many technology specialists disagree,
some believe Y2K crashes could cause power blackouts, shipping
problems, food and medicine shortages and perhaps even a
stock-market crash _ in short, a disaster on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   Porlier's book is like a giant list: what kind of food to stock
up on, how to get your finances in order, how to make sure your
family is safe and can stay warm and remain in good spirits if the
power goes out.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher, HarperCollins, has printed 100,000 and will soon
print a second batch.
</P>
<P>
   Porlier, 61, makes no recommendation for how much food to
stockpile. Instead, the book lists the type of food that stocks
well and how to be ready to cook it and eat it while staying
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people aren't doing anything and some are heading for the
wilderness,'' he said. ``Each person has to make their own judgment
call.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Porlier first realized how serious Y2K was. He was at a
seminar at Cambridge and Oxford universities and spent nearly every
night on the Internet. He was amazed how many Web sites were
dedicated to Y2K, and most of them spoke of bad things to come.
Porlier started to research the problem. In February 1998 he began
writing a weekly column for John Westergaard's Year 2000 Web page
(http://www.y2ktimebomb.com) one of the oldest and most popular Y2K
sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   People were starting to pay attention. Porlier received from 40
to 60 electronic mail messages a day from readers, many asking how
they should prepare. Finally, he decided to write the book,
reprinting some columns and adding new information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's done an excellent job,'' said Norman Kurland, a
member of the group Computer Professionals for Social
Responsibility. The group is dedicated to keeping people from
panicking about Y2K and other technology issues. But not everyone
shares Porlier's pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a more extreme approach than is probably necessary,''
said Cliff Kurtzman, president and chief executive of Houston-based
Internet marketing company Tenagra Corp. ``The amount of stocking
up you would reasonably do to support Y2K isn't too much different
than what you might do for a blizzard, or a three-day holiday
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenagra publishes the popular Y2K Web page run by Peter de
Jager, a Canadian computer specialist who helped bring Y2K to the
forefront. On March 1, de Jager announced that Y2K doomsday had
been avoided because so many countries were finally paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've broken the back of Y2K,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Meyer, a spokesman for the U.S. Senate's Y2K committee, said
the committee advocated that people speak to doctors, pharmacists,
bankers and others before determining how much, if any, Y2K
preparations are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not of the mind-set that people need to stockpile for a
long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency says three days supply
of food and supplies is enough to weather any Y2K problems. The
American Red Cross says a week, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police
advocate two weeks and certain hurricane-prone municipalities in
Florida are saying even longer.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own family, Porlier says he has enough of a cache to
keep him and his wife, Lois, warm and fed for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Porlier's own New Year won't be too exciting. He plans to sit by
a short-wave radio, listening to reports all over the world about
what's happening as the day progresses.
</P>
<P>
   And if Y2K turns out to be nothing but hype? That'll make up the
subject of Porlier's next book: ``What we've learned from this, and
what we should do in the future,'' he said. ``There'll be a lot of
postmortems on this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
