<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KILBORN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT TOO LATE FOR THE `LATE, LATE SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Craig Kilborn walks onstage Tuesday night
as the host of CBS' ``The Late, Late Show,'' it's not just going to
be a ceremonial passing of the baton from Tom Snyder to the new kid
on the block.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a historic exchange _ the hip, wired age
breaking away from the industrial era as the millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn and Snyder offer two very different styles.
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn has more potential than many people give him credit for,
a man who could not only be ``the next Letterman,'' but the brand
new model of the 21st century talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, he's closer to Snyder than anyone imagined
because both are originals.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is an odd, fascinating man on his own _ often more so
than the people he interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, when he hosted a throwaway programming idea called
``The Tomorrow Show,'' he was an eye-opener. The hair, the
eyebrows, the mannerisms, the vocal tics, the homespun personal
view of television and its connection to the people on the other
side of the screen _ a trademark right up until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder has always been a sort of misunderstood visionary, a guy
who could talk your ear off and simultaneously keep you interested,
then as you drifted back to your inner thoughts as he kept yakking,
you'd say, ``This guy is unbelievable.'' His style kept people
watching.
</P>
<P>
   But talk has gone in many directions since Snyder's debut.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Carson became king because he made everything fun without
getting overly cerebral. He was a master at controlling the
interview and the audience simultaneously, a feat that hasn't yet
been equalled.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been amusing and erudite, like Dick Cavett. And then
we got a latter-day combination of Cavett and Snyder in the talky
Charlie Rose, but that was to be expected on PBS. Network
television evolved to a smoother, snarkier area with David
Letterman and Jay Leno, Arsenio Hall, Joan Rivers and Conan
O'Brien. They made Snyder more than a retro curiosity, they made
him nearly extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Newer viewers were used to a lot of sass and a considerable
dollop of irony with their talk. For them, to watch Snyder sit down
with a single guest and not have any Stupid Pet Tricks or video
shenanigans was tantamount to watching a silent movie.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the beauty of Snyder. He was and always will be the
old car that feels better, looks better and was more fun to drive
than this year's model.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, takes nothing away from Kilborn. Despite the
popularity of Nick At Nite and TV Land, television is not about
nostalgia, it's about moving forward, about digging the new breed.
And for all the hype about Jon Stewart being the Next Big Thing,
there's no question the future belongs to Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   Provided, of course, he can harness his own immense potential
and craft it into a niche that people will not only love, but will
return to year after year. Give Conan credit for beating back death
and creating his own distinctive humor. Now it's Kilborn's turn,
and just watching this guy go under a spotlight as bright as ``The
Late, Late Show'' ought to provide fascinating viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Kilborn once stand out as the smarmy guy on ESPN's
benchmark sports highlight show, ``SportsCenter,'' his faux-smug
personality and his brand of thickly-dipped-in-irony humor
enlivened ``The Daily Show'' on Comedy Central. Granted, he can
alienate people who don't get the act and he's not above shooting
off his mouth in eye-popping ways, but Kilborn is a rollercoaster
ride of fun when he's on.
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't will he be on, but how soon. Here's a guy who
has worked in cable his whole life and is now going network on us _
to the most staid of them, CBS. Detractors may say that he can't
handle interview duties on his own, that he has the potential to
turn off more celebrities than Letterman (without the built-in fear
that they have to appear on the show or else).
</P>
<P>
   But forget about that. Look to Kilborn as an incredibly talented
new basketball star trying to make a name for himself in the
post-Michael Jordan landscape. Viewers may be sentimental and old
school at first, but time will tell them that the next generation
is upon us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
