<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-29 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A TANGLED WIRE WEB WE WEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There's a problem with our wired world: wires.
</P>
<P>
   This fact was pointed out to me the other day by my wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that pile of junk down there?'' she asked, as we slid
my computer table away from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, wires,'' I answered, wondering where the conversation was
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this mess,'' she continued. ``Haven't you ever
heard of wire management?''
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that I, too, was a bit amazed at the tangle of
black, gray and white wires that sat, twisted and ugly like some
lazy python, against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   When I set up my computer, I distinctly remember carefully
running each of those wires between various pieces of equipment. I
avoided tangles, and made sure none of the wires wrapped around
anything, like a table leg. I even coiled and lightly bound wires
that were extra long.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, it looked as though a gremlin had done the
wiring job. I couldn't even tell where some wires connected. I'd
start at a plug and work backwards, only to get lost in a jumble of
plastic between the surge protector and my computer.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen?
</P>
<P>
   That's what my wife wanted to know, as we set into position a
nice, new computer table, which, unfortunately, revealed more of
the wire nightmare than the old table.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this connected to?'' Mary asked, gripping a slim black
wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speakers,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really need them?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ack! Of course!'' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   And so my afternoon went.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a week later, I sit at my machine writing this column.
Everything appears to be working OK, which means we got all the
wires plugged back in properly. And, I must admit, ``wire
management'' and a few of those plastic wire ties really made
things look nice.
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps not nice. But better.
</P>
<P>
   How long will the organization last? I'm not sure, but I think I
already hear gremlins giggling . . . &QL; 
 &QL; 
MP3 making lots of noise
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since I last wrote about MP3, the file compression format used
to distribute music via the Internet has really taken off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible. It's astounding,'' said Michael Robertson,
chief executive officer of San Diego-based MP3.com, perhaps the
biggest player in the MP3 music business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I know that Robertson is in business, and it's his job to
talk-up MP3. But he offered statistics and information to back up
his assessment.
</P>
<P>
   First off, MP3.com is signing 125 new bands each day, Robertson
said. The Web site (www.mp3.com) already offers downloadable music
from more than 10,000 bands from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com also is adding new functionality to its site. Last week,
for example, the site unveiled a new search function that allows
visitors to find the hottest bands from any given city. Previously,
searches could only be conducted by genre.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, MP3.com has become a record company _ of sorts.
Via its Digital Automatic Music system, artists can compile a list
of songs that MP3.com will put on CDs and sell. Artists have no
start-up costs, and they get half the CD-sales revenue.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, MP3.com earned a major shot of respectability last
week, when Ted Waitt, chairman, CEO and co-founder of Gateway 2000
Inc., joined the MP3.com board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   What else is in store for the MP3 crowd? Robertson says
enthusiasts should expect ``MP3.com's Guide to MP3,'' a soft-bound
book, to become available next month. Expect sales via MP3.com and
Amazon.com. Retail sales are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Robertson predicted that this summer will see a
host of new MP3 hardware hit the market. He said different
companies are jumping into the business, and the goal is to get MP3
players out that can handle more than an hour's worth of music.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, MP3 lovers don't have much more than the Rio, a $200
Walkman-like portable player that has memory enough for about 60
minutes of music. They're on sale at various electronics stores,
including CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   All is not rosy for MP3, however. Despite legitimate
applications such as those employed by MP3.com, the MP3 technology
is considered by the established music industry to be little more
than organized piracy, because of the ease of which it allows
anyone using free software from the Internet to rip music off
traditional audio CDs, compress them into the MP3 format and
redistribute them via rogue Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent survey by the Recording Industry Association of
America will likely fan the fires of anti-MP3 sentiment. The
survey, released last week, found that 15- to 24-year-olds are
buying less music, something the survey partly blamed on MP3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continuing drop-off in the proportion of purchases
accounted for by 15- to 24-year-olds (32.2 percent in 1996 vs. 28
percent in 1998), once the mainstay of the market, is puzzling,''
the report states. ``Potentially the rise of the Internet as a free
entertainment center, and the accompanying availability of free MP3
music files, could be contributing factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps spurred by such findings, the recording industry
intensified its attack on MP3. Last week, the International
Federation of the Phonographic Industry launched legal proceedings
against the Norwegian partner of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos (www.lycos.com) is a popular U.S.-based search engine
site. Over the past few months, it has launched FAST MP3 Search
(mp3.lycos.com), which can instantly link users with tens or
hundreds of Web sites offering MP3 files for download.
</P>
<P>
   It's my guess that if MP3 continues to grow in popularity and if
the format isn't replaced by something better, the recording
industry will take over and dominate the MP3 distribution business
within a year. It'll be the old ``if you can't beat 'em, join 'em''
thing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
