<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSION CREEP (Washington) _ President Clinton, mindful of the
risks of ``mission creep,'' is resisting mounting pressure to
insert U.S.-led ground forces into Kosovo to stem Yugoslav
reprisals against ethnic Albanians. We look at the recent history
of ``mission creep,'' the expansion of goals in widening warfare.
News Analysis. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ If ground forces are ordered to
fight Slobodan Milosevic's drive to kill or expel ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo, how many troops would be needed, where would they come
from and what strategies would they use? Experts offer some
answers. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Washington) _ Dealing a blow to
affirmative action supporters, the Supreme Court refuses to review
a program once used by the Dallas Fire Department to promote more
blacks, Hispanics and women. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STUDENT-FEES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to
decide whether state-run universities can dedicate a portion of the
activity fees they collect from all students to subsidize groups
that pursue political and ideological goals that some students
oppose. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CUOMO-ALBANY (Washington) _ Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo
discusses the impact of the Republican-approved federal budget on
housing and development projects in and around Albany, N.Y. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Republican congressional
majority left town for a two-week recess patting itself on the back
for reaching a budget agreement. But the thing is a fraud. It
doesn't address the tough question of which domestic programs to
cut and it provides a huge tax cut nobody knows how to pay for. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
