includes news and features from The Arizona Republic, Bloomberg
News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Kansas
City Star, The Los Angeles Daily News, The San Francisco Chronicle,
The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1416EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-29 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY AMERICA SHOULD CARE ABOUT THE WORLD BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It is striking how much debate followed the NATO
aerial assault on Yugoslavia compared to how little preceded the
fateful decision.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings of drastic action, specifically bombing, issued by both
President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair weren't
seriously heeded during weeks of negotiations on some form of
truce.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the lack of debate may have been the natural
consequence of the president frequently invoking the use of force
during the tedious negotiations. Again and again, he threatened
that the European allies, all 19 of them in NATO, would use air
power to force the Serbians in Yugoslavia to accept a compromise
over the future of the province of Kosovo, assuring the cessation
of brutal attacks by the Serbians on the ethnic Albanians who live
there.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the lack of debate may have resulted from the
complexity of the rights and wrongs on either side, and the
difficulty of sorting out grievances of such ancient vintage that
they go back many more years than the United States is old.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that there was only modest discussion and
dispute about whether or why the United States might unleash its
military might against Yugoslavia. There was hardly a political
debate in the halls of Congress, and certainly the American people
were not seen to be caught up in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all that is different. Congress resounds with expressions
of criticism and warnings of failure for a policy that is seen by
presidential critics as ill-defined. Warnings of another Vietnam
abound with questions forcefully posed about now that we are in it,
how do we intend to get out?
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls reflect the uncertainty among the public about the
course upon which this country is embarked, with the president
receiving relatively modest and tentative support for his policy.
</P>
<P>
   In making his best case for the intervention, Clinton painfully
spelled out the details of the situation on the ground, putting it
into the context of the historical role the tempestuous Balkans
have played in the history of this bloodiest of centuries.
</P>
<P>
   He needed to do so, because the American people, in their
aggregate, appeared to know so little about it, and cared even
less.
</P>
<P>
   For that, much of the blame must be borne by the mainstream news
media, electronic and print, which did not much to inform their
viewers and readers about the issues when there was time. It isn't
that there was no reporting, because there was some. Looking back,
with honorable exceptions, it was comparatively modest, nothing
compared to what Monica and Bill received even on a dull day in
their year-long saga.
</P>
<P>
   Peering out from the inside of the media beast, this appears to
be largely the result of marketing strategies that command that the
local news dominate, out of concern that nothing else will interest
the audience. The rubric that ``all politics is local'' has its
clone in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   What this has meant is that local concerns came to dominate
American news, because that is where the audiences are to be found,
and all the good things like popularity and higher profits that
come with it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, happenings in far-off places have received
shrinking attention, even among such publications as the New York
Times. For all this time, foreign news journalists diminished in
number, overseas bureaus were closed or reduced in size, and ever
smaller parts of the daily newspaper paid attention to what was
happening in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions only came when a major crisis flared. Then the
foreign news would fight its way onto the front pages and the leads
of telecasts, just as it has with the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, there has been a great transformation: the foreign
has become the local. American military personnel are dispatched
into combat. The happenings in distant places appear to be much
closer to our local concerns than earlier would seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   It serves this nation little to be self-absorbed and live
indifferently to what transpires in remote parts of the world. It
is an indulgence, in cultural and intellectual terms. It should be
practical to care both about those things that impact us
immediately while not being indifferent to the greater world.
</P>
<P>
   The least we should do for ourselves is to arm ourselves with
the necessary background to give us some awareness of what is
happening and why, before history bites us in the back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
