<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-29 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO CARES ABOUT SERBIA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a perfect afternoon, and I tried to find
someone who cared about the war against Serbia instead of sunshine
or the rising price of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   No luck in my household. ``It's another Clinton thing,'' said my
wife, who is as cynical and isolationist as any American. ``I won't
care until the bombs start falling in my back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   I called the Marine Corps recruiting office to see if kids were
enlisting to fight Serbs. The recruiter told me no one was signing
up for that particular cause.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked to Market Street I heard chanting. ``Peace Now!''
yelled hundreds of people in Hallidie Plaza waving an unfamiliar
foreign flag. Ah, Serbian Americans, I thought. I'll go interview a
few.
</P>
<P>
   As I got closer, I wondered why so many black people were
demonstrating against U.S. intervention in Serbia. Then I got even
closer and read the signs that said, ``Peace in Eritrea.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a demonstration about another war in a place most
Americans don't know much about. Eritrea is a former province of
Ethiopia. The two countries are well-armed and killing thousands of
each other's troops over disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accepted the peace accords and the Ethiopians didn't,''
said Negusee Gidey, one of the marshals who was guiding Eritrean
Americans across traffic.
</P>
<P>
   So many civil wars, so few Americans paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   If America really is policeman to the world, we're not doing a
very good job. The world is a giant bar fight raging around us,
while we try to put the cuffs on one of the bigger creeps.
</P>
<P>
   In the reference room of the main library here, I asked
librarians Dennis Maness and John Nelson if they had an atlas
showing Kosovo and Serbia. They found a 1997 ``World Atlas'' that
had a map of Yugoslavia, but no outlines of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The atlas cost $60 but can't be revised fast enough to keep up
with the world.
</P>
<P>
   The librarians said no one had come in asking where Kosovo is on
the map. The last question they got on Yugoslavia was before the
bombing, when a woman called wanting to be filled in on the history
of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little hard to do, especially over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians are circumspect, but Nelson felt strongly enough to
say, ``It's this new thing, that our government bombs countries
whenever it wants. It's a new American right.''
</P>
<P>
   The government never asked us either. It's as if they're
counting on us not paying attention to these modern high-tech wars
in which no Americans are supposed to die.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's hell and the media to pay if American pilots
are dragged through the streets of countries we can't find on a
map.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked through United Nations Plaza, named for an
organization whose goals seem rather quaint, I talked to a few guys
on a park bench about the war against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been following it. I don't have a TV,'' said one
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a war right here in this plaza, a war with the
police. They started my career in crime,'' he said, ``first
arresting me for sleeping on a bench, then sending me to jail.
There's a lot worse problems in the world than that war.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess when you're living under a bridge, you think a lot more
locally than globally.
</P>
<P>
   At Pioneer Army-Navy store on Market Street, there wasn't a run
on military gear. Most of it is bought by pacifists anyway.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked the bored salesman where they got their stuff, he
said, ``Some war we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope Gulf War desert camouflage isn't joined on the rack
by Kosovo mountain camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   A few storefronts down Market is the office of Swords to
Ploughshares, a veterans' rights group that assists homeless
veterans. Behind the counter, answering the phones, was a man who
cared and knew about what was going on in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hanson, a former helicopter door gunner in Vietnam, spoke
almost Socraticly, posing everything as a question _ which seemed
appropriate when speaking of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if people are fighting a 16th century religious war with
20th century weapons? What are we supposed to do?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do people want America to be the world's policeman or not? We
have 14 carrier groups, what does that mean?'' Hanson wondered
about the different interests of the military, the State
Department, big business and the Clinton administration. It all
seemed to be out of our hands, anyway, we agreed.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of our conversation, the former First Cav door gunner
had to take a call from a veteran with problems. His last words to
me were sympathy for a Yugoslavia torn up by Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real sad that this country which almost made it into the
First World has to have this happen to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I walked out into the sun, where people talked about the high
price of gasoline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1444EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
