<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETRADE-LAWSUITS-HNS &LR;      03-29 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-LAWSUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS LEADS TO TROUBLES FOR ON-LINE BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thousands of consumers have been hurt by recent
system crashes and delays that have plagued on-line brokerages, and
lawsuits filed against ETrade Group Inc. highlight the growing
pains of the young Internet brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Chris Miller, 31, a software developer in
San Francisco. His electronic trading saga turned ugly almost
immediately after opening an account with ETrade Group Inc. in Palo
Alto. Like a kid in a candy shop, he logged on Feb. 4 and bought
$7,700 worth of shares in Intel, Microsoft and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Miller clicked on ETrade's Web site,
looking for his orders _ nothing. He checked his portfolio _
nothing. He looked for an e-mail from ETrade, confirming the orders
_ nothing. He called ETrade, but gave up after waiting on hold for
45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With no sign that his trades had gone through, he replaced the
orders four hours later. The next day, he checked his account. The
shocked Miller discovered his orders had been processed twice _ to
the tune of $15,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite miffed, very mad,'' Miller said. ``It even showed
my account had a negative balance.''
</P>
<P>
   After waiting on the phone for an hour, Miller reached an ETrade
representative, who agreed to cancel his second set of trading
orders.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller was angry enough to join one of two potential
class-action lawsuits filed against ETrade earlier this year in
Santa Clara County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits allege that ETrade's trading system crashes, which
have occurred several times since 1997, have cost its customers
money. The suits also accuse ETrade of misleading consumers in its
$25 million marketing campaign, which promised fast, 24-hour stock
trading via the Internet _ even when ETrade knew its computer and
telephone systems could not handle heavy trading during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``ETrade is a marketing machine that hasn't lived up to its
fiduciary duty to customers,'' said Seth Lesser, a lawyer at
Bernstein, Litowitz, Berger &AMP; Grossmann in New York who represents
Miller. ``I'm convinced that tens of thousands of customers have
lost money.''
</P>
<P>
   ETrade did not return calls for comment on the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every on-line brokerage house _ Charles Schwab Corp. in
San Francisco, Ameritrade Holding Corp. in Omaha, Neb., Datek
Online Brokerage Services Corp. in Iselin, N.J., and others _ has
been troubled by system breakdowns over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   On-line brokerages are revolutionizing Wall Street. Internet
investing used to be the realm of technogeeks and professional
traders, but no more: Personal computers and on-line brokerages
have given every person the power to invest with the click of a
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on-line brokerage accounts grew to 7 million with
$420 billion in assets, according to Piper Jaffray Inc., a
Minneapolis investment firm. Nearly one-third of all trades in
stocks and mutual funds were done on-line.
</P>
<P>
   As customers sign up in droves, technology problems are to be
expected, analysts say. No other on-line businesses are handling
the same rapid growth and volume of transactions as ETrade, Schwab
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally blow other sites away,'' said Larry Tabb, an
electronic commerce expert and group director at Tower Group in
Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   When on-line brokers launched their sites three years ago, they
woefully underestimated the public's interest in Internet trading.
The original technology wasn't designed to handle millions of
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is no good traffic model now, and they're running
out of capacity more quickly than they thought,'' said Rob Enderle,
an on-line analyst at Giga Information Group in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like building a dam and filling it to the brim,'' Enderle
said. ``You can model and test the heck out of it, but you won't
know whether the dam will hold until the water hits the top. ETrade
and Schwab are not used to building dams of this size.''
</P>
<P>
   Scared of bad publicity and losing customers, on-line brokerages
are frantically redesigning their systems. To handle the crush of
new investors, Schwab recently had an IBM mainframe rushed
overnight to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a learning experience,'' Enderle said, ``and they're
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ETrade has found itself in the spotlight because of its
high-profile ad campaign (``Someday, we'll all invest this way'')
and a big series of crashes last month.
</P>
<P>
   For three days _ Feb. 3, 4 and 5 _ ETrade's trading system
conked out for nearly four hours altogether. About 20,000 of
ETrade's 676,000 customers were affected. ETrade engineers blamed a
routine hardware and software upgrade ironically meant to speed up
customers' orders.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, ETrade spokeswoman Lisa Nash said the breakdowns
were glitches _ not major problems. ETrade still can handle up to
170,000 trades a day _ four times its daily average. The brokerage,
which will spend $75 million this year on new technology, also is
opening a third technology center near Atlanta that will triple its
trading capacity.
</P>
<P>
   With lawsuits pending and regulators studying the issue, though,
ETrade is playing it cautious. In a recent filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, ETrade told investors that its
trading system could slow or fail because of software problems,
power failure, human error or heavy stress on the system during
peak trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no assurance that we will be able to prevent an
extended systems failure,'' ETrade wrote. ``Any such systems
failure that interrupts our operations could have a material
adverse effect on our business, financial condition and operating
results.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unknown how many customers have fled electronic brokerages
because of the breakdowns. The crashes have been costly to some
firms, though. During its fiscal first quarter, Ameritrade took a
$3.1 million pretax writeoff to pay customers who lost profits from
delayed on-line trades.
</P>
<P>
   On the consumer and regulatory front, thousands of small
investors have flooded state and federal agencies with complaints
about the Internet brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the SEC, the National Association of Securities
Dealers and the North American Securities Administrators
Association _ the professional group for state securities
regulators _ are looking closely at the on-line brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the on-line brokers are keeping faith
with customers,'' said Mark Beauchamp, a spokesman for the North
American Securities Administrators Association. ``They're growing
very fast and advertising very aggressively, and we want to make
sure they're not promising more than they can deliver.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
