on the Fourth of July, in 1946, to a modest Californian family, by
the mid-1980s he was a billionaire and one of the world's most
feared financiers.
</P>
<P>
   Working for a then modestly-sized investment-banking firm,
Drexel Burnham Lambert, he took on the Wall Street nobs by creating
a market for bonds issued by companies which, before, would have
been barely creditworthy enough to get a bank loan, let alone issue
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   By 1987, the value of these bonds had soared from nearly nothing
to $200 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent investigations into Drexel's activities by an
ambitious young lawyer, Rudolph Giuliani, now New York's mayor,
eventually led Milken to plead guilty to six breaches of securities
law. He was fined over $1 billion and sent to jail, his reputation
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Junk bonds had been heavily bought by savings-and-loan
companies; when junk-bond prices fell, many of these S&AMP;Ls went
bust, leading to a government bail-out that cost taxpayers billions
of dollars. Drexel Burnham Lambert went bust, too.
</P>
<P>
   Blame for much of this was laid at Milken's cell door, and worse
was to follow. Soon after leaving prison he was told he had
prostate cancer, and 18 months to live.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is alive and well enough to joke about looking forward
to watching the Rolling Stones when ``they're 85 and I'm 75.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be as energetic and hard-working as he was in the
1980s, and looks almost as youthful (thanks, in part, to ditching
his ghastly toupee).
</P>
<P>
   This recovery he attributes to meditation (he is, after all, a
Californian) and abandoning a diet as junky as his bonds for one
almost free of fat and meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taste for Living Cookbook: Mike Milken's Favorite Recipes
for Fighting Cancer'' was published last September, with revenues
going to a charity, CaP CURE, for which he has already raised more
than $63 million for research into prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime ban has prevented his returning to the securities
business. But he is developing another fast-growing enterprise,
Knowledge Universe, a ``cradle-to-grave learning company,'' founded
in 1997 with his younger brother, Lowell, and Larry Ellison, the
boss of Oracle, a software company.
</P>
<P>
   Its various activities, which span the largest vocational
training business in Britain, operating elementary schools in
Pennsylvania and LeapFrog educational toys, already generate sales
of $1.2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few weeks, Milken will see if he can still sell
to Wall Street when he tries to float Knowledge Universe's
consulting arm, Nextera Enterprises, for an estimated $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   Were privatization to sweep through education as it has through
health care, business analysts reckon that Knowledge Universe might
well become the dominant brand.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the turnout to hear him at this month's ``global
conference'' at the Milken Institute _ founded in 1991 _ his social
standing has been fully restored, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy capitalists such as Rupert Murdoch and Mort Zuckerman
chewed the low-fat with four Nobel prize-winning economists and a
clutch of politicians in the same Beverly Hills hotel where Milken
once hosted a junk-bond conference called the ``Predators' Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine their European counterparts turning up to
honor a disgraced tycoon _ Ernest Saunders, say, or Jurgen
Schneider. But the Milken Institute is a serious outfit, a
nonprofit think-tank concerned (to quote the website) with ``the
global economy, capital markets...and the role of education and
human capital.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to see Milken's life as a contemporary morality
tale: greedy capitalist bad boy redeems his life by devoting
himself to good works. Intriguingly, Milken does not see himself
that way.
</P>
<P>
   As he tells it, his current and former activities are different
aspects of the same mission he has been on since witnessing the
Watts riots in Los Angeles in 1965. Put simply, this is to extend
capital, in all its forms, to people with too little of it.
</P>
<P>
   He has even come up with an equation to prove the point,
P &QC; FT(HC+SC+RA):
prosperity equals financial technology (of which junk bonds are an
important part) times the sum of human capital (which will rise if
people are better educated, live longer) and social capital (which
the Milken Institute may help increase) and real assets (stocks,
bonds, property, and so on).
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Milken's financial innovations are regarded much more
warmly now than they were in the 1980s. High-yield bonds (no longer
dismissed as junk) are credited with fueling much of America's
rampant economic growth, by enabling companies with bright ideas to
get the money they need to develop them.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Streeters reckon that Milken was jailed on
technicalities, after an investigation that makes Ken Starr's look
halfhearted. Some admirers of Milken even suggest that his
contributions to human well-being exceeded those of, say, Mother
Teresa, even before he switched his attention from finance to
healing the sick and educating the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes America can seem too forgiving, especially of those
who are, or were, rich or famous enough to hire a good lawyer or
public-relations adviser. But Michael Milken shows it can pay not
to keep people down when they fall. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
