<HEADLINE>
HOT HEADS, COLD FEET: WASHINGTON SETTLES FOR TEPID SUPPORT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, TIMELY 1,100-word ``separate buy'' article _ with
a helpful 150-word OPTIONAL TRIM at 750 _ is from the current (week
beginning 27 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS
1,100 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like the overgrown college kid he too often
resembles, Bill Clinton plunged into the Kosovo battle as though he
were cramming for exams.
</P>
<P>
   For months he had done his best to ignore this approaching test
of his leadership, preparing neither public nor Congress for the
possibility of war. Then, with the breakdown of peace talks in
France on March 19, the president scrambled to make up for his past
negligence.
</P>
<P>
   He called a press conference, his first in nine months. He
devoted a speech to Kosovo, even though his audience that day
happened to be a union group. And, in telephone calls, letters and
White House meetings, he pleaded for the sympathy of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   By the eve of Serbia's bombing, he had just about succeeded in
uniting America behind his policy. But only just.
</P>
<P>
   The president's first challenge was a House vote on Kosovo
policy on March 11. For reasons good and bad, the Republican
leadership seemed disinclined to support military action.
</P>
<P>
   Tom DeLay and Dick Armey, still smarting from the impeachment
battle, wanted to score electoral points. Christopher Cox, the most
sophisticated of the senior House Republicans, argued that the
president had not discharged his constitutional obligation to ask
Congress for money for his Balkan plans.
</P>
<P>
   The administration was so worried that it might lose the vote
that it pleaded for its postponement.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a fifth of the House Republicans supported a tepid
resolution approving military involvement in Kosovo, narrowly
saving the administration from humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proved still trickier. On March 19 Clinton invited a
few key senators over to the White House to press his case for
intervention, and on March 23 he did it again. He also wrote a
letter to Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, who had earlier
drafted a resolution that would have barred money for air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it seemed as though Clinton might have waited too
long to launch his charm offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Many senators were already on the record opposing intervention,
on the ground that America should on principle avoid getting
embroiled in civil wars, or that the president had exceeded his
prerogative by planning for war without consulting Congress first.
</P>
<P>
   When the vote came, however, the Senate shrank from pulling the
rug from under him. On March 23 it voted, 58 to 41, to support air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote supporting military intervention was hedged about
with conditions and provisos: it required the president to explain
the precise nature of American interests in Kosovo, the cost of
intervention, his exit strategy, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's support was just as qualified. Senator John McCain,
a Republican presidential aspirant, emphasized that he voted for
air strikes in order to produce unity in crisis, not because he
supported the president's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress and the American people have good reason to fear that
we are heading toward another permanent garrison of Americans in a
Balkan country,'' growled the senator.
</P>
<P>
   The half-support in Congress mirrored the mood in the country. A
Gallup poll taken just after the president's press conference
showed narrow support for air strikes: 46 percent favored them, but
43 percent were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll found that a clear majority (58 percent) believed
America had a moral obligation to help keep the peace in Kosovo,
whereas only a minority (42 percent) was persuaded that America
ought to get involved to protect its national interests.
</P>
<P>
   The striking thing about these findings, however, was the
contrast with the same poll a month earlier. The support for
intervention, and the belief in the various justifications for it,
had all strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, this strengthening was roughly proportional to the
rise in the percentage of respondents saying that they followed the
Kosovo question closely. The more Americans focus on foreign
policy, the more they are willing to accept its risks and costs.
</P>
<P>
   The polling data, together with the shift in favor of the
administration in Congress, pose an obvious question. If Clinton is
able to increase support for his policy by explaining it
energetically, why did he not do so earlier?
</P>
<P>
   The simplest answer is temperament: the president lacks the
discipline to work steadily on big issues, and so is reduced to
last-minute scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a more complicated answer. On some issues, the
president's party and advisers are so divided that firm leadership
is not easy. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such divisions certainly exist on trade, for example. Clinton's
economic team, led by Bob Rubin and Larry Summers at Treasury, is
by and large supportive of trade liberalization, whereas the
labor-union base of the Democratic Party is hostile.
</P>
<P>
   This explains why Clinton never made a convincing case for
fast-track trade-negotiating authority, which Congress consequently
blocked.
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo, too, there are splits. Madeleine Albright, the
secretary of state, is a staunch interventionist. Richard
Holbrooke, the administration's chief negotiator with Serbia, ought
to be an ally, but his personal rivalry with Mrs. Albright gets in
the way.
</P>
<P>
   William Cohen, the defense secretary, plays up the potential
risks of bombing Serbia. The Pentagon top brass hates the idea of
getting embroiled in Kosovo peacekeeping, which it regards as
``social work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than impose unity on these squabbling parties, Clinton
kept his head down _ until crisis obliged him to sit up. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,100 WORDS) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contemplating this chaos, Republican strategists are
increasingly inclined to make foreign policy an election issue.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's China policy has been tarnished by a spy
scandal; its support for Boris Yeltsin has not prevented Russia
from descending into chaos; it hardly pretends any longer to have a
policy on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kosovo crisis ends badly, Republicans reckon that they
have a powerful stick with which to beat Democratic foes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the truth is that Republicans are as divided on foreign
policy as the Democrats. The Senate debate on Kosovo featured
virulent exchanges between Republican interventionists and
stay-at-homers; and most of the party's usual heavyweights ended
the debate sitting inelegantly on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy used to be an election winner for Republicans
because they were clear what they believed in. Now the party wants
to get tough on China but soft on Serbia; it wants to assert
American power, but only if there is a quick way out.
</P>
<P>
   How nice it would be if a change of team at the White House
could be counted upon to bring firmness to American foreign policy.
Alas, it cannot. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent, TIMELY article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
