<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-JUMBO-WAR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN BOEING 747 SURVIVE THE TERROR OF TOULOUSE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article _ WITH TWO HELPFUL
OPTIONAL TRIMS _
 &HT;    is from the current (week beginning 27 March 1999) Economist
magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO USER-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 325 WORDS: AT 450
(125) AND AT 650 (200). TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,325 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TOULOUSE _ When it comes to new products, few businesses are
more perilous than making civil aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes cost billins to develop and are designed to last a
generation. Boeing bet the company when it launched the 747,
spending $2 billion on the project, 2 times the value of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Twice as big and efficient as anything else in the air, the
jumbo jet has earned the Seattle company over $20 billion in
profits since it first flew, 30 years ago almost to the day.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's rivals, Lockheed and McDonnell Douglas, bet heavily too
_ and lost. Their wide-body jets, the Tristar and the DC-10, never
earned a penny.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 Lockheed quit the civil-jet business altogether; two
years ago McDonnell Douglas was taken over by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Had either of them developed a twin-engined wide-body aircraft,
it would have avoided head-on competition with the 747, and might
have prevented Airbus from getting off the ground. Instead, over
the past 20 years the European consortium has encroached on
Boeing's dominant market share.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing used to account for well over two-thirds of orders, but
now it is being challenged in most parts of the market by Airbus.
Boeing reigns supreme only with the largest 747s.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Airbus had been content to attack the 747 from
below, with bigger versions of its long-range A340. The latest,
soon to go into production, can carry 385 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic will have an A340 with bedrooms below the main
deck, where passengers can sleep on the night flight that it is
starting between London and Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   But Airbus, led by Noel Forgeard, hired from the French private
sector last year, is determined also to launch an attack from
above.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard reasons that air traffic is growing by 5 percent a year
and that crowded airport hubs will need bigger aircraft. He reckons
that over the next 20 years there is a market for 1,400
``super-jumbos'' that are equipped to carry 550-660 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 20 airlines, half of them in Asia, are seen as
potential customers and only 10 percent of the total number of
planes would be super-jumbos. But they would be worth 25 percent of
the market, or $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hence Airbus, which is owned by France's Aerospatiale, Germany's
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, British Aerospace and Spain's CASA, is
stepping up work on its super-jumbo, the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the partners and the consortium headquarters in Toulouse
have 1,000 staff working on the design of this huge double-decker.
And Airbus lobbyists are starting to ask their governments for
loans to help launch the aircraft. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 125 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 450) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the $10 billion that it will cost to get the A3XX off the
ground, a third is supposed to come from Airbus; a third from
associates, including Italy's Alenia, Sweden's Saab Aircraft and
(Forgeard hopes) a Japanese company; and the remaining third from
European governments.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement signed with the United States in 1992,
governments can finance up to that proportion of the launch cost of
a new aircraft. In return, indirect government aid to Boeing,
through defense contracts with civilian spin-offs, is meant to be
limited to 3 percent of turnover.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus launch aid is repayable at commercial interest rates
as the aircraft are sold. But it is still a subsidy, because it
would cost Airbus far more to raise finance on the market. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus the paper A3XX could, at last, become real. Forgeard thinks
he will have an aircraft to sell to airlines by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to win the first orders by the end of 2000, at which
point Airbus could start production. But the launch timetable has
slipped, as nervousness about the slump in Asian travel has given
airlines cold feet. The earliest an A3XX could take wing now would
be 2005. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 200 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 650) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the project faces other hurdles. The money-conscious
British and German governments increasingly take the view that
Airbus should fly by itself.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, they would be happier financing Airbus if it had
the clarity of a company, rather than the obscurity of the
groupement d'interet economique (GIE), its current status under
French law.
</P>
<P>
   Conversion was supposed to happen in January, but squabbling
over valuations, shareholdings and control brought the process to
an embarrassing halt in October.
</P>
<P>
   The fault lies mainly with the French partner, Aerospatiale _
though its partial privatization in June, when it is merging into
part of the Lagardere Group, might help.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard is visibly irritated at the delay, but the soonest he
can expect a conversion into a proper company is now the autumn of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only governments who are unhappy. Under the GIE
structure, all partners are jointly liable for all the total risks
assumed by Airbus. The Airbus partners, which will mostly be big
defense aerospace firms once Aerospatiale is part of Lagardere,
might prefer the more certain returns of defense projects to a big
and risky civil bet. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest signs that the A3XX will overcome these
obstacles comes from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The firm believes that air travel is fragmenting, with most
growth coming not on the big trunk routes that connect crowded
hubs, but from long-haul point-to-point services, such as Singapore
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``long, thin routes,'' as they are known, are best served
by 300-400 seaters such as the A340 or Boeing's 777.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Baseler, Boeing's boss of commercial-aircraft
marketing, says that increasingly liberal bilateral air-traffic
deals have boosted these routes. He thinks Pacific air travel may
become like Atlantic travel, where many flights bypass such hubs as
London's Heathrow.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years Boeing has maintained that there was not
enough demand to justify spending $16 billion on a replacement for
the jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   It has dismissed Airbus's forecast for super-jumbos, and cut its
estimate by 100 aircraft, to 350 aircraft over 20 years _ though it
takes a narrower view of the market, counting only demand for
something bigger than the 747. (Airbus, by contrast, sees its A3XX
replacing the 747 too.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite these differences, Boeing is now looking at ways of
stretching and updating the 747. It is also quietly reexamining an
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Boeing touted simple stretch versions of the
747, but airlines were not interested; they wanted an aircraft that
would offer big savings, not just more seats. Now, thanks to
technology that it acquired with McDonnell Douglas, Boeing can use
better wing-aerodynamics to save 7 percent on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Its engineers are looking at a 550-seat 747, which would employ
the fly-by-wire technology pioneered by Airbus. Such a remake would
still cost several billion dollars; but it would be cheaper than a
new aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The best explanation for Boeing's change of heart is the A3XX.
Even Virgin, which has pursued a strategy of creating a network of
thin routes, sees the need for a super-jumbo to ease congestion at
hub airports.
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines are more enthusiastic still. When the Asian
market caused the launch date to slip, Virgin's arch-rival, British
Airways, one of the airlines closest to the A3XX, sought
reassurance from Airbus that the consortium was not about to go
cool on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing needs to boost productivity and repair its margins before
embarking on any big investments. Since it got its factories into a
tangle two years ago Boeing's profits and share price have both
tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing delays in converting Airbus into a proper company
might be just the opportunity it needs. After all, any delay in the
A3XX provides Boeing with more years of near-monopoly profits.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Airbus should bet the company now. The trouble is, it
doesn't have a proper company to bet. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
