<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IGNORANT-US-KOSOVO-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE'RE BOMBING WHERE EXACTLY?': AMERICANS CLUELESS ON KOSOVO  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from March 25 for those needing)   (This TIMELY _ and somewhat alarming _ 750-word``separate buy''
article is from The Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD GREENWICH, CONN. _ Katherine Ellenthal's class of
8-year-olds wanted to know more. Most of them understood that
something unusual was going on and a few had watched President Bill
Clinton talking about it on the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the war have a name?,'' one boy wanted to know. ``I think
we're bombing Siberia,'' offered another.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, President Clinton had suggested that Americans
look for Kosovo in an atlas. And so, like thousands of teachers
across America, Ms. Ellenthal started the school day by reaching
for the map _ one of those multi-colored canvases that rolls down
over the blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was an old one, though, and not tremendously helpful. It had
the former Yugoslavia but no place named Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could blame these children for being a touch vague about
NATO operations in the Balkans. In fact, they measured up fairly
well against some of the adults interviewed Thursday outside.
(Certainly they seemed less confused than the lady heard on the
radio suggesting that Kosovo was a chain of gas stations.)
</P>
<P>
   Most had grasped this: There is someone bad doing bad things a
long way away and America wants to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know its happening around Rome and Greece and people are
getting killed,'' one freckled boy volunteered, his hand in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Another interrupted: ``We're being attacked by an ally and so
we're going to try to get a peace but if that doesn't work we're
going to make a war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to my Dad,'' another boy chimes in. ``He told me
we were bombing them because the were having a war and so we have
declared war too.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone offered this vivid picture (perhaps a little too vivid
for Ms. Ellenthal): ``People have been taken out of their homes and
put in line and told to go on their knees. And then they've been
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the children _ it is a class of boys and girls _
had heard of Slobodan Milosevic (though everyone thought the name
funny). Saddam Hussein they knew _ he has been America's villain
for longer.
</P>
<P>
   And most had trouble with the concept of civil war. ``It's the
North fighting South,'' one boy noted. One of the girls in the
class, then spoke with great authority of Israel and Egypt once
going to war over Sinai. The same girl added that stopping wars is
important because sometimes they spread.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton would have applauded her. He would have been
pleased too that this class had a sense that going into a war can
be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   One boy turned anxiously to this visiting reporter to ask:
``Will they be sending planes here?'' Somebody else was worried
about the distance involved and the fact that U.S. soldiers had to
cross the Atlantic. ``That's where the Titanic sank,'' he reminded
his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Brown is the manager of the gas station just across the
road from the Old Greenwich School. It's a Sunoco station. (I
suggested that maybe it was Sunoco that the lady on the radio had
confused with Kosovo _ or, more likely, Conoco).
</P>
<P>
   He was not much further ahead than the school children on what
was going on. ``I usually try to keep up on it, the news, but you
know...'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he has working shifts from 6 a.m. to 11 p.m. Give him a
map, he said, and he could point to Yugoslavia, but as for... Where
was it again? ``You see I can't even pronounce it.''
</P>
<P>
   Right next to the school is the ``Off Center Barber Shop.''
Behind the counter was Leslie Porter. She had seen most of
President Clinton's address and was more or less convinced that
bombing the Serbs was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a good idea,'' she said. ``But in some aspects
its stinks because people are going to get killed for something
that will never get resolved. Is it going to fix anything?''
</P>
<P>
   As for the president suggesting that she may not know where
Kosovo is, well, he was more or less right, she admitted. ``I heard
about it over the last couple of months, but it wasn't anything
important to me. What's Kosovo going to do for me? I never heard of
any new hairstyles coming out of there!'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY, illuminating 750-word article, it must be
