<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND BELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To say that I have mixed feelings about the
nasty fight between the Catholic Archdiocese here and the
nuns-in-drag charity troupe, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence,
is like saying that it isn't always easy to be a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Or an American.
</P>
<P>
   As a dyed-in-the-wool liberal, I feel blessed to live in the
U.S. city that symbolizes ``tolerance'' to liberals and ``excess''
to conservatives. I'm proud to belong to the ACLU and to call
myself a feminist. The First Amendment is my favorite, and Dr.
Laura's arrogant brand of Old Testament condemnation makes my skin
crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my very best friends are lesbian and gay.
</P>
<P>
   I am also an adult convert to Roman Catholicism. Nobody
``indoctrinated'' me as a child. In my mid-30s, after years of
spiritual searching (and a decade of spiritual torpor), I chose a
path. It led to the Catholic Church, and life has been radically
different _ remarkably beautiful and difficult _ ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my very best friends are nuns and priests.
</P>
<P>
   Like most fights, the one between the Archdiocese and the
Sisters looks simple: This city should allow (and thus partially
finance through police and traffic services) a two-block closure of
Castro Street on Easter Sunday for the Sisters' 20th anniversary
celebration _ or it should not.
</P>
<P>
   But this fight is about as simple as society itself.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents for both sides are dug-in. Both claim exclusive
status as The Victim. Both are lobbying politicians and their own
communities for active support. Both have, despite rhetoric to the
contrary, one-dimensionalized the other.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also have been more than a little disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   After the Archdiocese asked that the Sisters' street permit be
revoked, the group's public image underwent amazing transformation.
The ``nuns'' went from a campy, raunchy guerrilla theater troupe,
which often lends its name and energy to fund-raising projects, to
the collective reincarnation of Florence Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sisters plan to hold a ``Hunky Jesus'' contest this
Easter, have passed out folded condoms as if they were consecrated
wafers, and never miss an opportunity to lambaste Pope John Paul II
or any sacred aspect of the Catholic Church, San Francisco
Supervisor Mark Leno insists, ``They mean no disrespect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archdiocese is equally guilty of minimizing some truths.
</P>
<P>
   In its innocent martyr role (executed best by groups like
Catholics for Truth and Justice), the church is behaving as though
its flock is back in the Roman Forum being ripped up by lions.
While over-reaching to compare the Sisters' offensiveness to that
of Nazis and the Ku Klux Klan, church spokesmen ignore the ominous
power and impact that are part and parcel of their mighty
2,000-year-old institution.
</P>
<P>
   In their hurt and anger over insulted nuns and desecrated holy
symbols, they dismiss the deeply painful insult that the pope
inflicted on every gay man and woman when he classified
homosexuality as ``an objective disorder.'' They discount the
soulful anger that results from his insistence that homosexual acts
_ no matter how loving and monogamous _ ``cannot contribute to the
authentic good of the human person.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many things I've learned on the Catholic path is, when
you have mixed feelings, you try to figure out what Jesus likely
would say or do. While you're figuring, you pray.
</P>
<P>
   So, with everything the church has taught me about the heart of
Jesus, this is my Easter prayer: Please, God, let the Sisters of
Perpetual Indulgence hold their party on Easter but inspire them to
take up a collection to defray the cost to San Francisco taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   After Easter, help the Sisters' supporters to acknowledge the
oceans of AIDS charity that Catholics produce and remind them that
the one-billion-person Catholic Church is not a monolith.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, God, please encourage the Archdiocese to ask the New
York-based Catholic League to withdraw its threatened economic
boycott of San Francisco. Help Archbishop William Levada, the staff
of his weekly newspaper and all angry Catholics to remember that
this is the United States of America where even the
Holocaust-surviving Jews of Skokie, Ill., had to accept real Nazis
_ not drag queens _ marching through their main streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Easter Sunday, turn the attention of all hurting Catholics
away from that little two-block segment of Castro Street and make
them focus on some wise words from the late, great Mother Teresa:
``Never let anything so fill you with sorrow as to make you forget
the joy of the risen Christ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
