<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAU-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Scientist at Work: Dr. Lene
Vestergaard Hau, a teacher at Harvard, has gained a formidable
reputation in a branch of science traditionally dominated by men:
physics. But most of all, she is known as the scientist who slowed
light down to a walk. Perfectly at home with such subjects as
quantum mechanics, Hilbert spaces and Bose-Einstein condensates,
Dr. Hau, at 39, is rapidly reaching the top of her profession, her
colleagues agree. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INDIAN-ECOLOGY (Undated) _ Many experts have abandoned the
concept that Lewis and Clark explored a pristine land of the nature
untouched. In fact, evidence now suggests, Native American peoples
had a profound effect on the land and animals, driving some species
near extinction in vast homeland areas with expert hunting skills.
But in buffer zones between warring tribes, where hunters feared
spending time, game thrived, in effect becoming game preserves
where most species survived in narrow areas between warring
nations. The war-zone theory is laid out in the most recent issue
of the journal Conservation Biology, partly explaining why bison,
elk, deer and bears escaped the fate of other, even bigger North
American animal species that became extinct some 13,000 years ago,
which may have been hunted to extinction in a continentwide
blitzkriegs. By William K. Stevens. (1725 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-SELLING (Undated) _ Patients, doctors and
professional groups around the country are increasingly unsettled
by a trend toward merchandising in medical offices, attributing it
to physicians' desire to supplement incomes that have been squeezed
by managed care. No statistics are available to indicate how
widespread the practice is, but doctors' groups are quietly
drafting policies about when selling items to patients is an
acceptable part of medical practice. By Abigail Zuger. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FOX-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ Experimenters have rushed
evolution to produce a new breed of fox _ one that whines for
attention from human beings without any prior conditioning, licks
its masters' faces, and has even begun to look something like a
domestic dog. In a long-term experiment at a Siberian fur farm,
geneticists have created this new version of Vulpes vulpes _ the
silver fox _ by allowing only the friendliest animals from each
generation to breed. Having selected only the most ``tamable'' of
some 45,000 foxes over 35 generations, the scientists have
compressed into a mere 40 years an evolutionary process that took
thousands of years to transform ancestral wolves into domestic
dogs. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALACTIC-CORES (Undated) _ Before its infrared camera shut
down in November, the Hubble Space Telescope focused on an
assortment of spiral galaxies for some of its last pictures in
those invisible wavelengths, giving astronomers penetrating looks
through thick galactic dust into the glowing hydrogen clouds where
stars are being born. By John Noble Wilford. (440 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHOOSING-MATES (Undated) _ Essay. Evolutionary psychology
and other branches of science explain what people want in terms of
a mate. But in reality, people choose mates (or have them chosen
for them), in myriad ways. Our brains are not designed specifically
to desire this or that, but to weigh the options, and then get down
to the business of having babies. By Meredith Small. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ The Berinmo language of Papua New
Guinea categorizes colors with just five words. This makes the
tribe a good subject for studying a linguistic concept that first
gained wide currency in the 1950's. Called the linguistic
relativity hypothesis, it argues that humans see the world less
with their eyes than with their language. Each language filters
experience differently, and thus there are no universal principles
of meaning. By Henry Fountain. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items on clothing that may absorb
pesticides, pesticides in the water supply and a glowing form of E.
coli used for keep pesticides out of the food chain. (675 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column:
Breast-feeding has enjoyed a well-deserved burst in popularity in
recent decades, when pediatric specialists finally succeeded in
overcoming the commercial pressures on modern women to feed their
babies formula. However, lately the numbers have been dropping from
their peak, and now only about 60 percent of mothers are nursing
their babies when they leave the hospital and only 30 percent are
still nursing six months later. By the end of this year according
to the goals set in Healthy People 2000, the Surgeon General had
hoped that three-fourths of all new mothers would be nursing when
they take their babies home. By Jane E. Brody. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SWEAT-SURGERY (Undated) _ A little-known disease afflicts
more than 200,000 Americans: hyperhidrosis _ the production of
chronic, drenching sweat. People with the disease drip water from
their hands, feet or underarms, and sometimes even their chest or
back. But now an operation called sympathectomy, in which surgeons
snip the sympathetic nerve chain that causes the excess sweating,
eliminates the problem. By Anne Eisenberg. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CONTRACEPTIVE-SPONGE (Undated) _ The contraceptive sponge,
once the most popular nonprescription birth control device for
women, could be available once more on drugstore shelves by fall.
The Today Sponge, a convenient and well-liked contraceptive that
was sold from 1983 until 1995, is scheduled to make a comeback
through the efforts of a small pharmaceutical company which
purchased the rights to the product from the manufacturer that
earlier ceased production of it. By Warren E. Leary) (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EBOLA-VIRUS (Undated) _ The early moments after patients are
infected with the feared Ebola virus may be the most important to
their survival, researchers report this week in the journal Nature
Medicine. By Philip J. Hilts. (675 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers are working on a vaccine combat peanut allergies,
and so far are having success in mice. (420 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Teen-agers fretting over how they look may not be just going
through a phase. Some may be suffering from body dysmorphic
disorder. This often secret and little recognized malady that can
lead to dropping out of school, shunning social contacts and even
suicide, say a Brown University research team. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The researchers found that 3 percent of the men reported
having had nonconsensual sexual experiences as adults, and 5
percent said they had been sexually abused as children.
Surprisingly, when the abuse occurred in adulthood, women were just
as likely to be the perpetrators as men, the researchers found,
while men were the most frequent perpetrators of abuse in children.
(350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HELICOPTER-SKIING (Undated) _ The Novice. Learning what's
commonly called helicopter skiing, in which participants fly by
copter to the mountain peaks and ski in deep powder snow. The skis
are wider and shorter. Important differences also involve turning
methods and basic body stance. By Holcomb B. Noble (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEMURS-MAD-COW (Undated) _ Lemurs at a zoo in France appear
to be dying of mad cow disease. By Sandra Blakeslee. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEN-FERTILITY (Undated) _ A popular technique to help
infertile men become fathers results in an abnormal process of
fertilization, researchers have found. While it is not clear
whether there are any effects on the babies conceived with the
method, the finding is expected to raise troubling questions. The
technique is called ICSI, for intercytoplasmic sperm injection.
Instead of allowing sperm to swim up to an egg and penetrate it on
their own, doctors directly inject a sperm cell into an egg. Now,
researchers have determined that ICSI risks damaging the proteins
that push and pull chromosomes into line before cell division and
that it skews the egg's otherwise orderly removal of proteins from
sperm. By Gina Kolata. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Why are the orbits of the Sun's planets
arranged in a more-or-less flat plane? The planets are believed by
many authorities to have coalesced from a disk-shaped cloud of gas
in the evolution of our solar system, beginning roughly five
billion years ago. (284 words)
</P>
