<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCIPLINE-LIFEBEAT-N     03-29 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCIPLINE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOUR CHURCH SAYS NO
</HEADLINE>
  By CARY MCMULLEN 
 c.1999 New York Time Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent trip to New England, the Rev. Bill Boulet saw an
example of how churches used to discipline their members: it was a
dunking chair. In the days of the Puritans, those who broke the
strict rules of church law were strapped into a chair at the end of
a seesaw-like device at the edge of a pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, everybody who came along was supposed to dunk them,''
said Boulet, pastor of Heritage Baptist Church in Lakeland, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Such measures may seem quaint _ or cruel _ today. In these more
sensitive times, it's hard to imagine any church member standing
for a verbal reprimand, let alone a dunking in an icy pond. It's
not unknown for people kicked out of churches to file lawsuits
alleging defamation of character.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the wake of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, some church
leaders have raised the issue of more stringent accountability for
lay people. Following President Clinton's admission of an improper
relationship with Lewinsky, Southern Baptist Theological Seminary
President Albert Mohler called on Clinton's home church, Immanuel
Baptist Church in Little Rock, Ark., to discipline him.
</P>
<P>
   Mohler wrote in a syndicated column last year, ``How can the
church in which he holds membership ignore what even the secular
world considers scandalous? Southern Baptists will be watching
Immanuel Baptist Church to see if it musters the courage to make
clear its own convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Southern Baptist congregations are autonomous, Mohler's
comments provoked controversy, including retorts that he was
meddling where he had no authority. The Little Rock-based Pulaski
Baptist Association unanimously adopted a resolution of support for
Immanuel Baptist and its pastor, Rex Horne, ``allowing them to
conduct their ministry as they see fit under the direction of God's
Holy Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral dimension of Clinton's conduct raises the question of
how churches deal with errant members, especially if their behavior
has become common knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders generally agree that some sort of discipline
is necessary to maintain moral integrity. E. Brooks Holifield,
professor of church history at Candler School of Theology in
Atlanta, said Christians began to regulate their behavior as early
as the second century and that all Christian denominations have
practiced it.
</P>
<P>
   Into the 19th and early 20th centuries, it was common for
Protestant churches to reprimand or expel their members for
infractions such as angry outbursts or public drunkenness,
Holifield said.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups, such as the Amish and Mennonites, are still noted
for their strict observances. But enforcing discipline became
increasingly difficult for American churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I've discovered about discipline in churches
is that they generally don't do it,'' said the Rev. Greg Champagne,
pastor of First Baptist Church in Brooksville, Fla., who wrote his
doctoral dissertation on the subject. ``It's so thorny, they just
avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Champagne said that because of past abuses, disciplining members
for moral infractions fell out of favor. ``It hasn't been practiced
consistently for 100 years. More and more generations haven't been
trained how to do it,'' he said. ``It's a lost art.''
</P>
<P>
   Most churches have disciplinary procedures. The United Methodist
Church and the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) have rule books that
spell out how to handle misconduct by clergy or laity. In fact,
Methodists call theirs ``The Book of Discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Congregational or independent churches tend to rely on the
pattern spelled out in Matthew 18, where Jesus tells his followers
to begin with private confrontation and, if no repentance is
evident, to involve others in the effort to bring a sinner back to
the fold.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, the offender can be expelled from the church.
Although all churches have members who break one or more of the Ten
Commandments, few get thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Sherouse, pastor of Lakeside Baptist Church in Lakeland,
Fla., said he has never seen it carried that far in any of the
three churches he has served. There were cases, Sherouse said,
involving extramarital affairs in which the initial step was taken
of visiting the people involved, but instead of expulsion, the
members were eventually moved to an inactive or ``watch care''
list.
</P>
<P>
   People on watch care lists are still considered members of a
church, but may not hold positions of responsibility or vote in
congregational meetings. In Southern Baptist churches, it is up to
the board of deacons to decide if a member should be placed on
watch care or restored to full membership.
</P>
<P>
   Boulet saw a church he served in Scranton, Pa., threatened with
a lawsuit because of a vote to ``disfellowship'' a member. He said
the church should exercise discipline not because of delight in
pointing out others' failures but because the church carries a
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most difficult thing to do as a pastor, but
if I see someone playing in traffic, I'm not going to let them get
hit,'' he said. ``If a guy is involved in an extramarital affair,
it's going to destroy his marriage, destroy lives. You have to
confront him with a spirit of meekness and say, TI care for you.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In cases where people are removed from church rolls, Boulet
said, it's not because of the sin committed but because the sinner
refused to admit the problem. ``If you're going to do it for the
sin itself, there wouldn't be anyone left in church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of tough love is always aimed at bringing people back
into the church, not driving them off, pastors unanimously say.
Terry Rayburn, district superintendent of the Assemblies of God's
Peninsular Florida District Council, said, ``Our first response is
always toward reconciliation. We are in the ministry of the gospel
and the crux of that is forgiveness. If we don't practice it, we're
ridiculous hypocrites.''
</P>
<P>
   For Catholics, discipline is usually a matter of individual
conscience and the sacrament of reconciliation, popularly known as
confession. It's all done privately, said Sister Lucy Vazquez,
chancellor of the Diocese of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conscience is our guide, but it should be formed. The hope is
that the church forms people from the time they're young to
recognize when they've fallen short. That motivates us to go to
confession,'' Vazquez said.
</P>
<P>
   In the sacrament, a priest acts as a mediator between the guilty
party and God, hears the confession of wrongdoing and prescribes a
penance _ prayers to be said or some action to correct the wrong.
Then he grants absolution and the offender is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a case such as Clinton's, where a sin has become public
knowledge, a priest wouldn't necessarily seek out the person,
because he might have sought absolution in another parish.
</P>
<P>
   Excommunication _ which cuts off a Catholic from the sacraments
_ is a dramatic measure, but one rarely used, according to Vazquez.
It can be imposed by a bishop, as in cases of heresy, or fall
automatically as the result of certain offenses, like taking the
life of the pope, performing or having an abortion _ and even then
the person must be aware of the penalty beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's reluctance to admit to his affair points to one of the
main obstacles in exercising discipline: the shame factor.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Butler Bass, assistant professor of religion at Rhodes
College in Memphis, said the strict rules observed by the Puritans
were gradually relaxed as settlements expanded and it became easy
to escape the shame of church censure simply by moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peer pressure was the most effective form of discipline, like
shunning people who got divorced, but it was informal pressure
rather than formal censure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom of choice poses the same problem today for church
discipline. A couple facing a reprimand could simply go to another
church that would ask no questions about moving their membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``All church discipline has got to be based on a covenant where
I willingly submit myself to this family,'' Champagne said. ``As
long as it functions within a covenant, discipline can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in a simpler era, in which Methodist, Presbyterian and
Baptist preachers thundered about the evils of drinking, dancing
and card-playing, discipline was only intermittently practiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large genre of American church literature about the
lack of church discipline. Mohler's jeremiad might fit in that,''
said Bass with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The issue represents a struggle between popular culture and
attempts by clergy to reassert control over standards of behavior,
swinging between permissiveness and more restrictive attitudes,
Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular culture,'' she said, ``almost always tends to win
out.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Cary McMullen writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
