<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MORAL-DUTY-NYT     03-29 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MORAL-DUTY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO, A MORAL DUTY TO STOP THE ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ Talking about Kosovo, an unnamed foreign policy adviser
to President Bill Clinton pointed out, ``There are massive
bloodbaths all over the world and we're not intervening in them.
...(But) this one's in the heart of Europe.''
 &HT;    Nobody could say the United States was straining at the leash to
blast Serb forces. Nobody could say that it failed to support an
effort for a political solution or that it charged alone without
full consultation and participation of allies.
 &HT;    In fact, the West's reluctance to resort to force has been made
clear at every step since Slobodan Milosevic launched an armed
campaign against the Kosovars a year ago, so much so that NATO came
under severe criticism for ``bluffing'' on its intention to bomb.
 &HT;    And yet, by any conventional definition of international rules,
the attack is an act of aggression against a sovereign state.
Further, Serbia argues that the West has it all wrong, that
actually Serb troops and police are only putting down rebellious
terrorists within their own borders and, what's more, it's nobody
else's business.
 &HT;    That argument doesn't hold today. The new air strikes do show a
profound change in the Euro-American community, a change in
attitude, analysis and ambition. During the war in Bosnia,
government leaders were ridiculed and maligned for failing to stop
the massacres; repeatedly they vowed to do something, waffled and
backed down.
 &HT;    This time we were told again and again that the Western powers
could not simply sit on their hands and let it happen again. Not to
intervene would be a form of collusion with repression _ with the
scorched-earth, ethnic cleansing policy of Milosevic.
 &HT;    The decision to act, not to tolerate a repetition of Bosnia,
shows the gradual evolution of a sense of responsibility,
humanitarian obligation, political need and moral duty. When the
Serbian parliament learned its only choice was to admit foreign
troops to impose peace in Kosovo or be bombed, a question was
raised: Why bomb?
 &HT;    The answer is that there is a new consensus that limits must be
set on outrageous national behavior. Those limits haven't yet been
strictly defined, but they are being drawn now.
 &HT;    At first, France had insisted that action could be taken only
with a U.N. Security Council mandate. But this was impossible
because Russia, which has a veto, is opposed to any attack on
Serbia. That left the question _ how many civilians have to die to
pass the threshold of circumstance? There have already been too
many, France has concluded, and it announced full participation in
the NATO military plan.
 &HT;    There is currently a kind of interim stage in the understanding
of state relations and the meaning of that somewhat vaporous group
called ``the international community.'' The old rule of ``hands off
the neighbor's affairs'' is no longer acceptable. Likewise, the
axiom that ``you can't keep the peace until belligerents are tired
of fighting and want to quit'' is being rejected.
 &HT;    When and where allied intervention is justified, indeed
required, and how to go about it remain intensely controversial.
There aren't any new rules yet but there is a firm convergence in
judging that Kosovo, now, is a case in point. It will set a
precedent.
 &HT;    There are all kinds of risks, not only military and of widening
the war. Relations with Russia will be seriously set back, and this
will affect pending agreements on nuclear arms control as well as
controversial sales of missiles to Iran. The very fate of NATO is
being challenged.
 &HT;    No doubt Moscow would not have minded seeing NATO weakened by
inaction and internal dispute, but it isn't happening. When they
thought it over, the alliance members fixed on priorities. They
decided that because there is a real feeling of need for minimal
standards of how to treat people in Europe, a reaction must occur
when they are violated.
 &HT;    It doesn't matter that Yugoslavia is not directly threatening
any other recognized state. It is bad for the neighborhood. To
punish Milosovic for that is a big step beyond tradition, and the
decision will cast a serious shadow on the argument about NATO's
new mandate. Nobody likes making America ``the global policeman,''
but neither can Europe ignore troubles in its region.
 &HT;    Why do only European conflicts get the benefit of this new
maturing responsibility for peace? Is it a sign of racism to ignore
those other bloodbaths? Maybe. However, Europe's willingness with
America to act at last is surely a sign that people can change,
that this continent has had its fill of wars. It's a shame to have
to bomb to prove it, but it must be proved.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
