<HEADER>
A8349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEATING-INTERNET-HNS     03-29 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEATING-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPUSES TOIL WITH FOOTNOTE OF INTERNET AGE: TERM PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The good news about higher education is this:
Shakespeare, Euripides and other icons of Western civilization are
still being taught in universities throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that a lot of students aren't reading them.
</P>
<P>
   With as many as 70 Internet Web sites offering term papers for
as much as $200 each, the procrastinators who once scoured
fraternity files or hoarded Cliff Notes are now finding that
cheating comes on-line.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet enablers are not subtle. With names like ``School
Sucks'' or ``The Evil House of Cheat,'' they're not exactly
marketing to members of Mensa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it pretty offensive,'' said Brad Lewis, associate dean
for undergraduate education at Union College in Schenectady, N.Y.
``It shows total contempt for the whole academic enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon will receive its first official study this spring
when the Center for Academic Integrity at Duke University examines
cheating at 12 universities.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers University Professor Donald McCabe, who founded the
center, has previously conducted studies showing that nearly 70
percent of students cheat in college. The ease and anonymity of the
Internet can only have increased that percentage, he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of the Internet for plagiarism purposes is clearly on
the rise,'' McCabe said. ``But I don't think people fully
understand it yet. There's a lot of conversation, but very little
action.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line services vary greatly in quality and price. Some charge
nothing _ simply gathering a class's essays and posting them to
read. Others offer teams of ``experts'' who custom-design papers
and require a credit card to browse. Some employ complex search
engines with offerings as diverse as ``Castration as a Metaphor''
and ``The Epic Poetry of Medieval Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta deadline?'' asks one of the more prosaic sites,
schoolsucks.com. ``Click here for research papers online.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Sahr, the 27-year-old college drop-out who runs the site,
makes little attempt to vouch for the quality of his papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be turning out garbage,'' he said in a telephone
interview from his home in Tel Aviv, Israel. ``If the papers in
schoolsucks are bad, and professors are accepting them, that's a
reflection of our higher education system.''
</P>
<P>
   Academics are divided on how to deal with on-line cheating.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most extreme response came from Boston University,
which filed a federal racketeering lawsuit against five on-line
term paper mills in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Employing a graduate student, BU discovered that these companies
were willing to send papers even when the student made it clear she
would falsely claim the work as her own. Some sent papers tailored
to student's exact specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The case was thrown out by a federal judge in November, but the
university plans to refile at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   Some professors, in an effort to catch cheaters, are employing
the cheat's own high-tech tools. If a phrase seems a little too
witty or too pithy for a particular student, the professor can plug
it into a term paper search engine and find the paper from which it
was taken.
</P>
<P>
   That's how a Union College English professor caught a Web-cheat
last spring. By plugging one phrase into a search engine, the
teacher found the suspect paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took about 15 seconds,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based Glatt Plagiarism Services offers the software
equivalent of a mandatory drug test with a program that copies
student papers with every fifth word missing. Professors can call
their suspect students into the office and ask that they fill in
the missing words.
</P>
<P>
   Most educators, however, have reacted to the Internet
controversy with typical academic introspection. Some blame the
large lecture format, which sometimes offers all of the intimacy of
a rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   If cribbed papers pass muster, observers say, that's a sign that
a professor doesn't know his students _ and therein lies the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students suggest to us that the less personal the relationship
with the professor, the less guilty they feel about cheating,''
McCabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Simon, who runs the Expository Writing Program at Skidmore
College in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., asks her students to submit
several drafts, lists of sources and thesis statements _ procedures
that promote good writing while preventing cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to cheat, the student would have to download it, mess
it up, and then submit it,'' she said. ``By that point, it's almost
worth writing your own paper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
