   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, March 30.
</P>
<P>
   TV-OPRAH-HOLOCAUST (Undated) _ An unlikely Holocaust book
becomes an Oprah Winfrey selection. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ROBBERY (Undated) _ A popular South African singer is
convicted of criminal charges in a bank robbery. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   LOMAN-SUITCASES (Undated) _ Our intrepid reporter, Richard
Sandomir, looks into one of the enduring mysteries of the theater:
What was in Willy Loman's suitcase?
</P>
<P>
   LAMBS-SEQUEL (Undated) _ The sequel to ``Silence of the Lambs''
is finally finished. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHILL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Winston and Clementine: The
Churchill Letters, edited by Mary Soames (Houghton Mifflin).
Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Facing the Truth With
Bill Moyers.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
