<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EXTRACT-BOS &LR;      03-29 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EXTRACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER PART OF JOB FOR ELITE AIR FORCE RESCUE UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their motto _ ``that others may live'' _ may seem a
bit melodramatic. But the elite US Air Force pararescue unit that
penetrated deep behind Serbian lines to rescue the first downed
pilot of NATO's air war against the former Yugoslavia lived up to
the billing.
</P>
<P>
   The secret operation Saturday night transformed a major military
loss _ the first crash in combat of the super-secret F-117 Stealth
fighter _ into an emotional boost for the NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the crash, a team of Air Force special
operations commandos headed into action under the cover of night in
a squadron of fixed-wing aircraft as well as HH-60 Black Hawk and
HH-53 Super Jolly Green helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, which snagged the American pilot within six hours,
signaled the latest achievement for one of the most decorated units
in the US military.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials say that a series of technological advances,
including night-vision devices and the global positioning system,
have enabled the United States to carry out search and rescue
operations unimaginable in previous wars. A pilot can transmit a
radio beacon through one of a number of spy satellites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the capability of learning the precise location of
a downed pilot,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. ``And we
have a bunch of well-trained, brave people willing at a moment's
notice to fly into enemy territory under fire, facing unknown
risks, and succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Pentagon was not releasing any details about the
operation out of concern that it would help the Serbs thwart future
rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second successful rescue of a stranded American in
the Balkans in four years. In June 1995, a US Marine rescue team
plucked Captain Scott O'Grady out of the Bosnian woods and the
clutches of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers at the US Air Force rescue base outside Albuquerque
said they are well aware of the risks in their profession. Members
of the unit have won 10 of the 19 Air Force Crosses awarded, the
highest mark of bravery for the service.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those awarded _ Tim Wilkinson and Scott Fales _ earned
the medals for their work the bloody ambush that killed 18
servicemen in Mogadishu, Somalia in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The commandos were dropped into the middle of a raging gunbattle
in an attempt to administer first aid to a team of US Rangers and
Delta Force commandos, according to Mark Bowden, the author of
Black Hawk Down, an account of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fales was injured early on but he continued to provide first
aid to the others and fight to set up a perimeter,'' Bowden said.
``Wilkinson's training and cool'' contributed to saving the lives
of a number of the Americans, added Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   The latest successes of the unit show how far the Air Force has
come since airpower debuted in World War I. In those days, the best
a downed combat pilot could hope for was a safe life as a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The US Air Force formed its first rescue operation in the summer
of 1943, when 21 people bailed out of a disabled C-46 transport
plane over remote jungle near the Chinese-Burmese border. Three
rescuers dropped out of the skies with first aid kits and tended to
the wounded for more than a month. Among the survivors: newsman
Eric Severeid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a volunteer force,'' said Sergeant Joseph Barnard, an
instructor at the US Air Force rescue center in Albuquerque. ``We
understand we are willing to put our lives on the line for somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When something has gone wrong or someone is in bad shape,''
said Master Sergeant Brian Stephens, the director of the training
center. ``That's when we get the 8 o'clock wake-up call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
