<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YANKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO UNITS WONDER WHEN US TROOPS WILL ARRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ As they wait here for the Serb attack that
may or may not come, NATO commanders and soldiers have one
question: Where are the Yanks?
</P>
<P>
   Of the leading countries that have committed troops to the
Kosovo peace implementation force, only the Americans are not part
of the ground force in neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   As they have engaged in a mutual game of ``chicken'' with Serb
forces dug in just over the border in Kosovo, NATO troops say they
want Americans with them to deter a Serb attack.
</P>
<P>
   European politicians share the frustration of their troops that
as they attempt to stare down Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   While US pilots are at the forefront of airstrikes against the
Serbs, the absence of US ground troops here is raising questions
about the solidarity of the NATO alliance. It also has prompted the
divisive suggestion that there are two sets of rules for NATO
forces: one for the Americans, another for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it would contribute up to 4,000
troops to a 28,000-member peacekeeping force, but insisted on
waiting until the Serbs signed the deal that ethnic Albanians
approved in Paris two weeks ago before deploying them. Now, as the
threat of the conflict spilling over grows, the administration is
seeking congressional approval to get troops here to deter Serb
attacks, or retaliate if they do.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately, NATO officers say that one of their American
colleagues from the Allied Command Europe Rapid Reaction Corps,
based in Germany, arrived in Macedonia with them three weeks ago
but was ordered back by American superiors. ``He was as frustrated
about it as we were,'' said one senior NATO officer.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Clinton said he had authorized the
deployment of 100 Marines to protect the US Embassy here after it
was stormed and heavily damaged by a pro-Serbian mob. Clinton also
said US officers in Germany could join colleagues in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Between 30 and 40 US officers, part of the Allied Command Europe
Rapid Reaction Corps, are expected to arrive here in the next few
days, said Major Jan Joosten, a NATO officer in Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   There also are about 300 US troops who have just finished a UN
mission of guarding the Macedonian border, but Joosten said it was
unclear whether those troops will be put under NATO command here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he would ask Congress for approval to move US
peacekeepers into Macedonia. That those troops are not here already
is a subject of irritation among some 10,000 British, French,
German, Italian, and Dutch soldiers who have been here a month.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Americans were not here already, Joosten, a Dutch
officer, said: ``That is a congressional matter. I can tell you our
American colleagues want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The official NATO line is that Milosevic's troops would be
foolish to fire across the border at NATO troops in Macedonia.
First, it would make moot Milosevic's argument against accepting
the peace plan. Milosevic contends that NATO's insistence that its
troops are needed in Kosovo to enforce the settlement violates his
nation's sovereignty. Firing into Macedonia would violate its
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The situation here is volatile. Unlike UN peacekeepers in
Bosnia, NATO troops operate under rules of engagement that give
them far more leeway to respond if attacked. Put bluntly, if Serb
forces fire across into Macedonia, NATO will unleash a ferocious
counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of the conflict spilling over throughout the Balkans
is serious, underscoring the frustration among European NATO troops
here that the Americans are absent.
</P>
<P>
   There are 4,000 British, 3,000 German, 2,500 French, 800
Italian, and 200 Dutch troops in Macedonia. Interviews with the
troops suggest they believe the Clinton administration is so unsure
of congressional and popular support for its Kosovo policy that it
did not want to risk having troops here vulnerable to retaliation
from the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest the delay is because of an institutional flap
over US troops for the first time being under the direct command of
a European general.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with precedent, US troops here would be under the
command of British General Mike Jackson. The Clinton administration
made that concession in exchange for keeping the US troop level
lower. The British and French will supply the bulk of troops, if
the peacekeeping plan is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Some officers say they understand US sensitivities. They believe
the legacy of Vietnam informs the reluctance to get involved in
foreign conflicts in which US interests are ill-defined. They also
believe Americans do not have a realistic appreciation of the
inherent dangers of military operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British people accept, I think more than Americans, that
this is a dangerous business and soldiers get killed,'' said
Lieutenant Colonel Andrew Venus, a British officer. ``In every year
since the end of World War II, except 1963, British soldiers have
been killed in combat.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is grumbling about the reticence of the Clinton
administration, European officers and soldiers speak with
admiration for US troops, with a grudging acknowledgement that the
Americans make them a far more formidable force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the Americans,'' Joosten said. ``They have equipment
and technology that we don't. They are very much part of this
alliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
