<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ESSAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRAIN THAT TOLD A TALE OF YOUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN LUPO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year is 1965. The place, on the old Orient Express, out of
Milan on its way to Athens via Marshal Tito's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The train cars are old, the dining car windows covered with
thick, plush drapes; the meals are meat and potatoes, as thick as
the midsummer Balkan heat. There are no cold drinks, just bottles
of warm, fruity liquid, too thick, heavy as applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   The toilets have stopped functioning. Peasants sit on the
floors. A chicken roams one car. Yugoslav guards, dressed in dull
brown uniforms with black boots and belts and red stars on their
caps, wander about. They are unsmiling, like caricatures from a
newspaper cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   In an airless compartment containing eight passengers, Yugoslav
citizens ask an American to claim ownership of what they had bought
in Paris, so they would not encounter problems with those
brown-suited guards. What they bought includes an accordion. The
American fears a guard will say, ``This is yours? Play something,''
and the tourist will spend the next two decades in a cell, learning
Balkan folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   The guards, however, do not care about Americans, and the
American tourists never bother to ask if the accordion's owners are
Serbs, Croats, Bosnians, for this was Tito's nation, and he
repressed any hint of ethnic nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now, the successors to the guardians of whatever
remains of Yugoslavia care much about Americans and their allies.
Missiles and bombs these past four days have focused their
attention.
</P>
<P>
   We are at war in the Balkans, which means we are ending the
century pretty much as it started. That fact is fraught with
historic irony, not only because Balkan violence triggered the
Great War, which set the stage for the rest of this century, but
also because at the onset of this century, many Europeans believed
there could be no more war on a continent that had known little
else.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to a 1910 book, ``The Great Illusion,'' by Norman
Angell, which, as historian Barbara Tuchman recounted in her own
work ``The Guns of August,'' contended that war was impossible.
After all, Angell argued, the financial interdependence of nations
meant both winners and losers would suffer equally.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in the belief that the 20th century would be one of
enlightenment and scientific achievement, and one could have
concluded that war was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as we prepare for the 21st century, we marvel at
technological achievement and its promise for the future, we talk
of a global economy, of interdependence. The European Union exists,
a miracle in the light of that continent's history. Yet now, as
then, it seems nobody counted on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost nobody. Late in the last century, Otto von
Bismarck, chancellor of the German Empire, predicted that ``some
damned foolish thing in the Balkans'' would trigger a war.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what happened, when, on June 28, 1914, a
Serbian nationalist killed Austrian Archduke Franz Ferdinand in
Sarajevo, thereby setting off a chain of events that propelled
nations and empires, against the inclinations of their own common
sense, into World War I.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, history is symbolized by what clothes, what music
marked the era. For the Serbs, Croats, Albanians, Montenegrans,
Slovenes, Macedonians, Bosnians, Gypsies, and others in the
Balkans, history is a compendium of centuries of warfare,
repression, revenge, blood feuds, and unredressed grievances.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1936 book ``Inside Europe,'' John Gunther wrote, ``The
basic passion of most Balkan folk is nationalism. Their primitive
and turbulent energies are directed to the preservation of their
own political minority or country, rather than social revolution;
nationalism is the pipe through which their energies are
discharged.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows that phenomenon better than Slobodan Milosevic, the
Serbian strongman. More than a half-century after Gunther's work
appeared, Robert D. Kaplan, in his book ``Balkan Ghosts,'' echoed
the theme as he described Milosevic's secret to retaining power:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only Eastern European Communist leader in the late 1980s
who managed to save himself and his party from collapse did so by
making a direct appeal to racial hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it is again in the Balkans, in Serbia, Croatia, Bosnia, and
now Kosovo, that the renewed optimism of a new century crashes
head-on with a bloodied history of resentment that seems to forever
defy both closure and the forces of enlightenment evident elsewhere
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans are like an ancient, airless railroad car, its
windows to the modern world covered with thick drapes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
