<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ The ledeall: NATO says some Albanian
leaders have been executed, announces that it is stepping up
attacks on Serbian troops in Kosovo. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO says Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, seems to be trying to carve out a Serbian republic in
Kosovo, re-engineering the political and population landscape in
advance of any resumption of peace talks. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROTECT (Washington) _ One point of the NATO attack was
to protect ethnic Albanians in Kosovo; now they are worse off than
ever. Did the U.S. anticipate this? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Belgrade is a city
where people say ``ciao'' and drink espresso, judge the latest
Hollywood movies with asperity and surf the net. But the war is
dragging it farther from Europe, into isolation, uniting the Serbs
behind their soldiers, their Kosovo and even President Slobodan
Milosevic. American movies have been withdrawn from the theaters,
though the Original Levi's Store across from the American Center
was left untrashed by the mobs. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Dateline to kum) _ News Analysis: As reports
of Yugoslav forces killing and evicting the ethnic Albanians emerge
from Kosovo, a critical question has arisen for the West: at what
point does brutality by Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president,
and the increasingly personal attacks on him by the West, make it
impossible to ever negotiate with him again? For now, the political
process that NATO's bombing of Serbia is supposed to bolster is
still built around the involvement of Milosevic. It is designed to
convince the Serbian strongman to sign a peace agreement offering
autonomy to the Albanians and accept the presence of a NATO-led
force in Kosovo to police that accord. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Washington) _ Settlement reached between Russia and
the International Monetary Fund, but for a lot less than Prime
Minister Primakov expected. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
