<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MA-RAT-WAR-BOS &LR;      03-29 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MA-RAT-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S RAT PACK TAKES A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Adecade ago, the city's Central Artery highway project
produced The Great Rat Scare. It was a wondrous thing.
</P>
<P>
   According to this nightmare, millions of enraged rats uprooted
from their subterranean digs by construction would stream through
the North End and Chinatown neighborhoods, pausing to infest City
Hall before moving at warp speed across the Common toward the Back
Bay matrons sipping lapsong souchong at the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   The specter was appalling. And fascinating. It had Hollywood
written all over it. The media loved it. Local news at 6 and 11
salivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The topic became sexier and sexier,'' recalls Bruce Colvin,
who led the rat war from early 1989 until last June, when he was
laid off in a round of cost-cutting. ``We were astounded by the
myths and misinformation floating everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The rat stampede never materialized. For starters, there were
never millions of rats under the Central Artery. More important,
rats are not marathon runners. Like all smart gourmands, they
usually stay within 150 feet of their food source. And,
counterintuitively, they adore construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole media had it backwards,'' notes Colvin.
</P>
<P>
   But not the Big Dig, the massive project to bury the busy
highway that goes through center of the city. Today, Boston is
known for its innovative efforts to keep the Norway rat (Rattus
norvegicus) at bay. Last year, for example, the Chinese government
invited Colvin to lecture on the subject at the august Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been so successful that the consumption of rat
poison in sewers is down almost 95 percent from the start of
hostilities in 1990. Poison consumption, specialists say, is the
best way to gauge success because no one has a clue how many rats
there were at the beginning or are making trouble now.
</P>
<P>
   But chew on this: The gestation period for a female rat is 21
days. A male and female, who produce litters of eight to 10 pups,
will be logarithmically responsible for 15,000 offspring in optimum
conditions over the course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   So the rats can still win this war. The Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority, which now runs the Central Artery project, has cut the
number of rat busters from seven to two. The entire operation is
heading toward extinction early in 2005. What level of effort will
there be in the interim? And what will happen after completion?
</P>
<P>
   Much of the burden has already shifted to the city's
Inspectional Services Department, according to John Eade, who ran
ISD for 4 1/2 years until last November and worked closely with the
Big Dig rat cadre. ``They only have two people left to handle the
whole thing, and we're only halfway through the project. That is
ludicrous,'' says Eade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question,'' he asks, ``is whether the Central Artery is
still committed to making this program work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig says yes. ``We will not, cannot, walk away from the
commitment we made when this project began regarding rodent
control,'' says Big Dig spokesman Andrew Paven. But he would give
no specifics about funding or staffing for future rat control
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will ISD, which faces an increased challenge as the Big
Dig effort declines. Spokeswoman Julie Fothergill simply promises
that the city will meet its obligations to win the rat war.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much for rats to mount a spirited counterattack.
Just relax sanitation enforcement and watch the fun. In fact, you
can look elsewhere in Boston to get a taste of what's ahead if the
Big Dig effort flags. It is mystifying, then, that Boston still
allows residents in areas like the North End, Chinatown, and the
Back Bay to leave their garbage out in plastic bags the night
before pickup three times a week. It's Denny's All You Can Eat for
rats.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, as usual, the rat busters are baiting the sewers.
We're talking five 20-gram paraffin blocks of Talon, the
second-generation anticoagulant that kills rats through internal
bleeding. The rats last three to five days after munching on the
stuff, which is hung on a wire in sewers from manhole covers or
placed in plastic boxes in high-use surface areas. (Not to worry,
the rats go underground to die. This is why Boston is not littered
with their carcasses.)
</P>
<P>
   Poison is tricky stuff. Use too much of it and the results can
be terrifying: Rats can develop a genetic resistance to
anticoagulants, as they did in Chicago in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The second generation of anticoagulant in use here, to the best
of anyone's knowledge, is resistant-proof. So far. Colvin cautions
that European countries now have problems with resistant rats
because of overuse of poison. While there is no evidence yet of
such super rats in the United States, he adds, `No one is tracking
here. The US government eliminated all research in that arena 20
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Rats are also canny. They can become ``trap-shy'' if confronted
with too many such devices. When that happens, they may face the
dreaded glueboard. This eponymous device is to rats what the La
Brea tarpits were to dinosaurs. The rats literally stick to the
glue as they walk across it and die a long, horrible death.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the glueboard, there was the plan. Colvin's team
divided the Big Dig and contiguous zones into six areas stretching
from Charlestown to the South End. Area Four, which includes the
North End, and Area Five, dominated by Chinatown, have always been
where the action is. Both are dense and teeming with restaurants.
(The North End alone has 135 restaurant licenses.) And in the
beginning, both had terrible garbage problems.
</P>
<P>
   The scariest turf, hands down, was Haymarket, the open food
arena in the shadow of City Hall where rats gorged themselves on
the mountains of garbage left by the pushcart operators. One night
in 1991, Colvin sat with a hand counter to document the rat
activity there. In one hour, he clicked 104 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous battle was fought there,'' he says, speaking both
of rodents and politicians. Privately, the rat busters chafed at
the political cover given by the city to the pushcart operators,
Boston tourist icons, whose lax produce-disposal habits contributed
mightily to the rat problem.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Big Dig construction began, Colvin and his team
embarked on a yearlong public information campaign in the
neighborhoods most affected by the project. Garbage was the main
topic. People needed to know that rats are unamused when deprived
of food and will depart for gamier pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The state even bought 900 securely lidded garbage cans for
restaurants and residents at high rat risk located near the
construction corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Then they surveyed accessible sewer manholes that were potential
problems. In the downtown area, baiting began more than six months
before construction in all manholes up to five blocks on either
side of the construction zone. Particular attention was paid to the
old brick sewer pipes less than 2 feet in diameter, which are
favored by rats as their very own central arteries. Before the Big
Dig, Boston had never baited its sewers in a coherent way that
included relentless poisoning, rebaiting, and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the baiting has been done by three local pest-control
companies working for the Big Dig. In theory, the city ISD handles
rat problems in private property near construction, while the Big
Dig has responsibility for public areas. In practice, the two
groups overlap, and the efforts of the city will have to grow if it
is to win the rat war as the scope of the Big Dig effort declines.
</P>
<P>
   The jurisdictional questions can be confusing. ``Once you have a
rat, you can't prove where it comes from,'' says John Meaney, ISD's
chief inspector. ``Is it their rat or our rat?''
</P>
<P>
   The other key part of the end game in the Big Dig rat war will
be the design of the 20-odd acres of green space to be located
above the depressed artery highway. Landscaping, it turns out, has
a lot to do with rat activity. Colvin's team studied 650 sites in
downtown Boston and found that rats love ground cover, the thicker
the better. They also adore juniper and yews, and will vault over
walls from adjacent bushes. What they don't like is open grass.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin and others involved in the rat project say that issues
such as landscaping underscore the need for continued commitment by
the Big Dig and the city to maintain the gains they have made
together. Thus far, the two operations have stayed ahead of the
rats. But brave promises from both groups are running headlong into
funding realities.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the rat busters just keep baiting. ``Dead rats
don't run,'' intones Big Dig environmental biologist Trygve Swift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-29 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAWING A LINE IN THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Time for a new parallel.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 years ago, the world's attention was drawn to the 38th
parallel, dividing South from North Korea. In Vietnam, the line
through the 17th, which divided South from North Vietnam, made Big
Power sense, but none at all to most Vietnamese. Now it's time to
pay some attention to the 44th.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, the line doesn't denote an international
boundary. But south of it, in the lower part of Serbia and into
bleeding Kosovo, the presence of a tank, an artillery piece, or an
armored personnel carrier can only mean one thing _ slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   And as the NATO campaign against Serbia moves into its critical
phase of operations against those weapons, the time has come to
draw the line at that line.
</P>
<P>
   Anything below it _ a Serbian armed unit, a piece of serious
equipment, anything _ should be considered fair game, no
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   That is basically the tacit NATO approach in the second stage of
its air campaign. But a clear public statement, what amounts to an
ultimatum, would focus the attention of both Western opinion and
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The most important word President Clinton has uttered since the
campaign moved beyond its initial focus on air-defense and other
basic elements of the Serb war machine has been ``persevere.'' It
implies no quick fix, because there is none, and readiness for an
effort of considerable duration, because that is almost certainly
required in the absence of Slobodan Milosevic's sudden
capitulation, for which senior US officials no longer entertain
realistic hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Perseverance is also the essential word because a campaign from
the air directed at anything that moves south of the 44th parallel
will make it clear to the Serbs involved that they are not only
targets, but that they can be largely isolated and cut off from
their supply lines from the north.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, perseverance is important in the context of the
possibility of using ground troops. It should be obvious from the
verbal dance by Clinton administration officials that the
introduction of combat forces has not been ruled out and
contingency plans are being worked on.
</P>
<P>
   However, the public hair-splitting about using them misses a
more important point about what is feasible in the weeks ahead.
Senior officials are at pains privately to point out that Kosovo is
no Kuwait _ wide open desert and thus easily accessible for armored
columns. In fact, it is remote and relatively primitive.
</P>
<P>
   There are, for example, only a handful of ways into the province
over bridges that can easily be blown up. Moreover, any
introduction of combat units should be preceded by the kind of
up-close bombing to which NATO is now committed for at least the
next few weeks. The best inside opinion is that it would take a
month or so to prepare to use an invading force, whose size would
have to be staggering (at least 100,000 troops).
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, NATO is capable of inflicting severe, daily
punishment on Serb units in Kosovo from the air, and that effort
has barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   However, that means that the forced evictions of ethnic
Albanians and the wholesale murder will continue, with real threats
to the stability of neighboring Montenegro, Albania, and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But it is preposterous to suggest that NATO's campaign is in any
way responsible for the escalating and spreading violence. The
truth is that the Serbian build-up began last fall, as did the
atrocities; as it continued, the situation in Kosovo worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Kosovar Albanians agreed to sign the peace agreement
that the Serbs had rejected, the only evidence is that the NATO
plans to begin bombing were accelerated as the level of violence
raced out of control. That is why the decision to start was made
even as Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's plane was flying
here, in the full knowledge that he would order its return to
Moscow. It was a gutsy move on President Clinton's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Horrific days lie ahead. But that is why the proper course
should be not only perseverance, but a refusal to rule any action
in or out and a public announcement that anything Serbian south of
the 44th parallel is at mortal risk.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment to oppose any rape of Kosovo was right when
George Bush made it at the beginning of this decade; it was right
when Clinton reaffirmed it; and it was right when NATO acted on it.
</P>
<P>
   And that means that it's right to see it through to success.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
