<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET BALONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans left the nation's capital
for a two-week recess patting themselves on the back for passing a
budget blueprint that expects us to believe in six impossible
things before breakfast, as the white queen demanded of Alice in
Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   This is a small step _ a really small one _ aimed at avoiding
the partisan stalemate that bogged down the Newt Gingrich-era
Congress last year. The impasse led to last-minute budget chaos, in
which the GOP got rolled by President Clinton and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the devil is in the details, as Ross Perot is fond of
saying, and the budget deal doesn't have many. This is a skeleton,
missing the necessary political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement promises to set aside funds for Social Security
(although not Medicare), vastly increase defense spending and
provide fat new tax cuts. Even with a looming surplus, the federal
government cannot afford such financial indulgence without busting
the spending limits Congress has set for itself. Something must
give here.
</P>
<P>
   The message is that the budget will be balanced by cutting
unnecessary, unwanted domestic programs. But the plan does not
specify which ones, or by how much. Why are we not surprised? Every
year Congress goes through this fanciful routine, and every year
it's a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Precedent suggests the targets will be popular, essential
services _ nutrition programs, enforcement of health and safety
rules, drug and border control, Amtrak, the Coast Guard,
environmental protection, park maintenance, space exploration, Head
Start, the State Department and even the FBI. All are vulnerable as
legally unprotected examples of the big government that Republicans
love to bash.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans wish to retain their congressional-majority
status, however, they will not be caught whacking away. Voters
correctly expect government to provide these services, particularly
those that directly improve their daily lives or help the poor, the
elderly and the sick. No, the old shrink-government illusion will
not work.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the bombing of Yugoslavia, a big increase in
defense spending also seems inevitable. No one is in a mood to deny
the Pentagon what it claims to need. President Clinton and Congress
may still argue about what to spend where, but the military will
waggle its expensive Stealth bombers at us and have its way.
</P>
<P>
   As for Social Security and Medicare, neither the GOP
congressional leadership nor President Clinton are prepared to make
the accommodations essential for real reform. Consensus is not
possible until the 2000 elections have settled the next division of
political power.
</P>
<P>
   So there will be a lot of talk about saving the systems for the
elderly that will not necessarily mean much, except that the
politicians will compete to outspend and outpromise each other. No
radical cost-saving there, either.
</P>
<P>
   So if we are to avoid a return to budget deficits it is in the
size of the projected tax cut that things must give.
</P>
<P>
   Some GOP conservatives are still singing the old song about the
absolutely imperative nature of a big break for the pitiful,
overtaxed rich. The right wing would eliminate federal agencies,
downgrade education and pinch domestic spending willy-nilly to pay
for that.
</P>
<P>
   But the message is not a winner in these days of economic
prosperity. With most voters, tax cuts get a lower priority than
improved education and protection of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional budget calls for a tax cut of nearly $800
billion over the next 10 years, beginning slowly but accelerating
rapidly in later years. This would absorb nearly all the projected
budget surplus not set aside for Social Security. It is opposed by
President Clinton and most congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The form these cuts would take is left to the House and Senate
to decide later. Initially the Republican congressional leadership
favored a 10 percent across-the-board cut in income tax rates, but,
despite a campaign push from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, the
concept didn't pass the economic and political smell test.
</P>
<P>
   Far more likely and more responsible are smaller, targeted tax
reductions to which President Clinton can agree and for which both
parties can claim credit.
</P>
<P>
   Budgets are as boring as they are necessary, and easily
manipulated for political points by the few insiders who understand
them. We all know that liars can figure and figures can lie. When
it comes to arithmetic gyrations, most of us are condemned to
function on instinct, common sense and guess-work. Lucky thing for
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MA-RAT-WAR-BOS-1S     03-29 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MA-RAT-WAR-BOS-1ST-LEDE-WRITE-THROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S RAT PACK TAKES A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrrects spacing problem s in first paragraph.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A decade ago, the city's Central Artery highway project
produced The Great Rat Scare. It was a wondrous thing.
</P>
