divided the Big Dig and contiguous zones into six areas stretching
from Charlestown to the South End. Area Four, which includes the
North End, and Area Five, dominated by Chinatown, have always been
where the action is. Both are dense and teeming with restaurants.
(The North End alone has 135 restaurant licenses.) And in the
beginning, both had terrible garbage problems.
</P>
<P>
   The scariest turf, hands down, was Haymarket, the open food
arena in the shadow of City Hall where rats gorged themselves on
the mountains of garbage left by the pushcart operators. One night
in 1991, Colvin sat with a hand counter to document the rat
activity there. In one hour, he clicked 104 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous battle was fought there,'' he says, speaking both
of rodents and politicians. Privately, the rat busters chafed at
the political cover given by the city to the pushcart operators,
Boston tourist icons, whose lax produce-disposal habits contributed
mightily to the rat problem.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Big Dig construction began, Colvin and his team
embarked on a yearlong public information campaign in the
neighborhoods most affected by the project. Garbage was the main
topic. People needed to know that rats are unamused when deprived
of food and will depart for gamier pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The state even bought 900 securely lidded garbage cans for
restaurants and residents at high rat risk located near the
construction corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Then they surveyed accessible sewer manholes that were potential
problems. In the downtown area, baiting began more than six months
before construction in all manholes up to five blocks on either
side of the construction zone. Particular attention was paid to the
old brick sewer pipes less than 2 feet in diameter, which are
favored by rats as their very own central arteries. Before the Big
Dig, Boston had never baited its sewers in a coherent way that
included relentless poisoning, rebaiting, and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the baiting has been done by three local pest-control
companies working for the Big Dig. In theory, the city ISD handles
rat problems in private property near construction, while the Big
Dig has responsibility for public areas. In practice, the two
groups overlap, and the efforts of the city will have to grow if it
is to win the rat war as the scope of the Big Dig effort declines.
</P>
<P>
   The jurisdictional questions can be confusing. ``Once you have a
rat, you can't prove where it comes from,'' says John Meaney, ISD's
chief inspector. ``Is it their rat or our rat?''
</P>
<P>
   The other key part of the end game in the Big Dig rat war will
be the design of the 20-odd acres of green space to be located
above the depressed artery highway. Landscaping, it turns out, has
a lot to do with rat activity. Colvin's team studied 650 sites in
downtown Boston and found that rats love ground cover, the thicker
the better. They also adore juniper and yews, and will vault over
walls from adjacent bushes. What they don't like is open grass.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin and others involved in the rat project say that issues
such as landscaping underscore the need for continued commitment by
the Big Dig and the city to maintain the gains they have made
together. Thus far, the two operations have stayed ahead of the
rats. But brave promises from both groups are running headlong into
funding realities.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the rat busters just keep baiting. ``Dead rats
don't run,'' intones Big Dig environmental biologist Trygve Swift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
