<HEADLINE>
ELITE FBI TEAM SEARCHES FOR KILLERS OF WOMAN, TWO GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 and ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONORA, Calif. _ While the FBI has imported a team of
professional profilers to narrow its search for the killers of a
women and two children, there are plenty of amateur profilers in
the Sierra foothills where the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   The elite FBI Behavioral Science Unit, which worked on the
Unabom investigation and was featured in the 1993 movie ``Silence
of the Lambs,'' develops profiles of possible suspects in violent
crimes or terrorist incidents. Its goal is to answer the anguished
question on the minds of most everybody here: Who could have done
this?
</P>
<P>
   At gas stations, coffee shops, convenience stores and
restaurants, there has been little talk of anything other than the
abduction and killings.
</P>
<P>
   The three disappeared from El Portal, just outside the Yosemite
National Park, on Feb. 15. The bodies of Carole Sund, 42, and
Silvina Pelosso, 16, were found three hours north of the park on
March 18 in the charred remains of a car they rented for their
trip. A third body, Sund's 15-year-old daughter, Julie, was found
Thursday near a vista point in Moccasin, about 32 miles southwest
of where her mother's body was found.
</P>
<P>
   The other significant location for the FBI profilers is Modesto,
where the search for the three turned up the first major piece of
evidence: Carole Sund's billfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet it was an ex-convict, some guy who sat in jail for years
and thought about how much he hates women; who else would do this
evil thing?'' said Judy Shay, an Oakland resident who was staying
at her family's cabin in Tuolumne County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small town and people don't have anything else to do
but talk about it,'' said Louise Guthmiller, who said shed believed
the the woman and two children stopped at her gas station in Sierra
Village the day they disappeared. ``Everybody up here has a theory
about who did it or why they did it or how come they put the bodies
here. But we just can't all be right.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI Agent James Maddock conceded as much last week.
</P>
<P>
   The new task force, dubbed Tournap, now is focusing on analyzing
evidence, developing psychological profiles of the killer or
killers and eliminating possible suspects, according to FBI
spokesman Nick Rossi.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, the FBI and the Tuolumne County
Sheriff's Department have been questioning several former convicts
with records of violence or sexual offenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
