<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8441 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-CHALLENGE-BOS &LR;      03-29 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CHALLENGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS OFFICIALS COUNTING ON A DAUNTING TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year away from Census Day, the largest exercise in US
democracy _ bigger than Election Day or Tax Day _ federal officials
are afraid their carefully planned campaign may well fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an impossible task,'' said Kenneth Prewitt, US Census
Bureau director and commander of the 2000 Census operation, ``but
it is a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is not just the cost, which could soar to $7
billion, or the ongoing fight between Republicans and Democrats in
Congress over who will benefit most from the decennial count. The
census, among many other things, determines how the 435 seats in
the House of Representatives will be divided among the states.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is a matter of how, with any high degree of
accuracy, the Census Bureau locates and counts an estimated US
population of 275 million that has never been as mobile,
multicultural, or mistrustful of government as Americans will be on
April 1, 2000, when the census formally starts.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials, armed with the most elaborately detailed plan
ever, have all sorts of strategies for crossing more than 100
language barriers, for counting children in joint custody, for
tracking down the homeless, the hospitalized, and people who dwell
on houseboats and on remote Hawaiian Islands.
</P>
<P>
   In cities across the country, thousands of census canvassers are
walking block by block, attempting to update a mailing list of 120
million addresses and match them with actual residences. Census
forms, available in only English or Spanish 10 years ago, are being
printed this time in Chinese, Korean, Vietnamese, and Tagalog, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more than 400 Census Bureau field offices have
opened, and the agency has launched an unprecedented marketing
campaign to project a friendly image of the government census to
racial and ethnic minorities. To enhance census awareness, the
agency is ``partnering'' with thousands of grass-roots groups,
distributing lesson plans on the census to public-school teachers
nationwide, and spending $100 million on an advertising campaign
targeted at minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the effort, the bottom line is this: Demography is
not on the side of a successful 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Census Bureau is getting better at what it does, but the
demography of our mobile and multicultural society is moving
against us,'' Prewitt said. ``We're running faster and harder, but
we won't know until after the fact whether we ran hard enough to
stay in place, whether we caught up a few steps, or whether we
slipped behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Anderson, a social historian who studies the census, said
contemporary living arrangements collide with the traditional
assumptions of the US census: that Americans reside in only one
place over some time and are either related to, or at least very
familiar with, everybody else who lives under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things make for interesting census problems in 2000,''
said Anderson, a University of Wisconsin professor. ``One is the
real changes in the way families and households are organized
today. The other is explaining to a very large and diverse pool of
immigrants, with different languages and political traditions, why
you need to do a census.''
</P>
<P>
   Decennial censuses were mandated in the Constitution for the
purposes of apportioning House seats and taxation. The census
numbers also guide political redistricting within states for their
legislatures and determine how nearly $200 billion in annual
federal aid to states and cities gets shared.
</P>
<P>
   The census survey, which seeks data on sex, age, race,
relationship, and home ownership for each member of a household,
also provides a wealth of updated demographics that determine
everything from how many new schools are needed to where a Wal-Mart
will get built.
</P>
<P>
   No US census has ever been totally accurate. President George
Washington, who hand-tabulated the first one, suspected the
reported 1790 population of 3.9 million people was too low.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until the 1940s that statisticians were able to
calculate how far off the census enumeration was and that minority
groups and children were being disproportionately undercounted. In
1980, the US Census estimates it missed 1.2 percent of the
population. By 1990, the count was off by an estimated 1.6 percent;
8.4 million people were missed and 4.4 million were counted twice,
according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau planned to use sampling, or statistical
estimates, to correct for an even higher population undercount _
1.9 percent _ in 2000. But since the Supreme Court ruled in January
that sampling is illegal, at least for apportionment, the bureau
has been scrambling to carry out what Prewitt calls the ``vast
task'' of doing a traditional head count.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's count will start April 1, 2000, with the
largest direct-mail campaign in history. Since trial runs show that
the rate of return of both the long and short form will be a low 60
percent, an army of more than 300,000 census enumerators will be
deployed into the field a month later for a door-to-door canvass of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The census canvass used to come first, but due to demographic
changes _ working women are not home during the day to answer the
door _ the Census Bureau switched in 1970 to the mail-out,
mail-back form. Now the bureau's 2000 problem is that households
are so burdened with junk mail, telephone solicitations, and
instant communications like the fax and e-mail that the ``snail
mail'' census questionnaire has a hard time competing. For the
first time, the bureau is testing Internet responses.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting actual household head counts is even harder. The
problem is partly sociological: Many families are split or
reblended. More people cohabitate or live in group housing. An
increasing number reside in inaccessible high-rises or gated
communities. With a booming economy, people are more mobile,
working longer hours outside the home, and changing jobs and
locations more often.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is also that many people, out of anxiety, anger,
apathy, or ignorance, are not about to cooperate with the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been groups suspicious of the government,
but never at this level of public cynicism and concern,'' Prewitt
said. ``We're a victim of that. Even though we are providing a
service, it's not always experienced that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau guarantees that the forms are confidential and
leans on the Immigration and Naturalization Service to lower its
profile during census-taking time. The agency is also working with
advocates for the homeless and migrant workers to become more
sensitive in 2000 to the fears of these groups.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Dukakis has headed the Census Bureau's New England
regional office since 1970, seeing a stunning growth in the area's
immigrant population. This time, he is preparing by setting up
language-assistance centers for Cape Verdeans in New Bedford,
Cambodians in Lowell, Latinos in Lawrence, and Haitians in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   But Dukakis's biggest headache is the prospect of hiring 25,000
to 30,000 enumerators in a hot labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been difficult, it's been very competitive,'' said
Dukakis, who this past winter hired 3,000 block canvassers at $8.50
to $12.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that is easier this time, Dukakis said, is getting
local officials on board the census bandwagon. It could have
something to do with their worry that an urban undercount would
mean fewer federal dollars coming their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
