</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DOCTORS-ART-2TAKE     03-29 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS' OFFICES TURN INTO SALESROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., Texas, Pa., Fla., Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Gary Pozsik waited in his doctor's examining room last April
for the final results of his yearly physical examination, he knew
he was in for yet another discussion of his high cholesterol and
his treatment options. But when the familiar subject came up,
Pozsik, 48, a radio journalist in Columbia, S.C., was startled by
what he heard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of diet, exercise or one of the half-dozen prescription
medications commonly used to lower blood cholesterol, Pozsik's
doctor encouraged him to try something else: a nonprescription
compound that Pozsik would not find in any pharmacy but instead
could order right there in the doctor's office _ cash, check or
charge _ with his doctor's personal assurances of its safety and
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me, and it bothered me a lot,'' Pozsik said. The
host of a radio talk show focusing on health-related issues, Pozsik
recognized immediately that the supplement was a fiber-based
product whose merits had not been accepted in orthodox medical
circles, and whose sale was netting his doctor a tidy profit.
</P>
<P>
   Pozsik declined to buy the supplement, and although he and his
doctor are still on good terms, the memory of his doctor's brief
transformation from impartial consultant to entrepreneur still
disturbs him. ``I think this is taking advantage of your patients
and it's not the route to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients, doctors and professional groups around the country are
increasingly unsettled by a trend toward merchandising in medical
offices, attributing it to physicians' desire to supplement incomes
that have been squeezed by managed care. No statistics are
available to indicate how widespread the practice is, but doctors'
groups are quietly drafting policies about when selling items to
patients is an acceptable part of medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   State medical boards, the appointed bodies that license and
discipline physicians, have no specific prohibitions against
selling commodities to patients, making it a generally legal part
of medicine, said Dale L. Austin, deputy executive vice president
of the Federation of State Medical Boards.
</P>
<P>
   But these state boards are increasingly concerned about the
ethics of the practice, Austin said, and whether it unfairly
coerces patients into becoming customers.
</P>
<P>
   Selling goods out of medical offices is unquestionably becoming
more common, said Dr. Robert M. Tenery Jr., a Dallas
ophthalmologist who heads the American Medical Association's
Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs. The association has
received repeated complaints from both doctors and patients about
the practice in the last few years, Tenery said.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors disagree so bitterly about the practice that the
association has not been able to adopt an overall policy on it,
despite several years of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Items for sale range from prescription eyeglasses and contact
lenses to vitamins and nutritional supplements to products that
have nothing to do with health care, like mops and magazine
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Little controversy surrounds the items at either end of the
range. Although state policies on doctors' dispensing prescription
drugs and devices vary, the AMA has long held that it is a
generally permissible part of medical practice. Then, in December
1997, the group endorsed a policy that strongly discouraged doctors
from selling goods unrelated to health care, like cleaning
products, pointing out that the practice almost always exploits the
desire of patients to please their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But those products in the gray zone where health, nutrition and
beauty meet _vitamins, dietary supplements, skin care products,
weight-loss aids _ have generated bitter debate about whether
doctors can be objective about their effects on health and sell
them for profit at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the medical association considered adopting a policy
condemning the for-profit sales of these goods out of doctors'
offices, but then rejected it, reflecting doctors' profound
ambivalence on both the science and the ethics behind the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rejected because there are a lot of physicians out
there who really felt that we were denying their patients access to
proper care,'' Tenery said, ``and I think there were also a lot of
physicians out there who are now depending a great deal on income
coming from selling products to their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent editorial in The New England Journal of Medicine,
Dr. Jerome Kassirer called the office marketing of products a
result of doctors' pervasive discontent with the financial and
professional constraints that managed care had brought into their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the last five years, Dr. Fred Vasta, an internist in
Quakertown, Pa., has cut his medical work down to about 18 hours a
week, and has spent the remainder of his time distributing goods
and services through Amway, in which freelance entrepreneurs known
as distributors earn commissions on both their own sales of
products and services, like vitamins, household products and
airline tickets, and those of people they enlist to become
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Vasta said he earned approximately equal incomes from both
halves of his professional life, and with his involvement in a new
Amway Internet venture he is anticipating quitting medicine
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think I went through college and professional school
and professional training and all this to have managed care come
and tell me that I was worth eight cents on the dollar for a
patient each month?'' Vasta said. ``You can't even treat a patient
the way it's supposed to be done anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors say that medical considerations, rather than
financial ones, prompt them to recommend products. Dr. John David
Berryman, an obstetrician-gynecologist in Washington, estimates
that in the last year he has steered almost 500 of his patients to
a line of herbal compounds for weight loss and premenstrual
symptoms, products that are ordered through a member of his office
staff.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He finds that patients who are leery of prescription
medications, like hormone replacement drugs, are often enthusiastic
about these nonprescription alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pick the best product I can and tell patients what it does
and they can make the choice,'' Berryman said. ``I'm not wedded to
them taking it or not taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Berryman carefully distances himself from the actual
transactions as well as the profits. ``I don't make money on
this,'' he said. ``That's unethical as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Starlight International, whose products Berryman uses, is a
direct marketing company with headquarters in Monterey, Calif. The
staff member in the doctor's office who orders products for both
patients and staff members is a Starlight distributor.
</P>
<P>
   One of these companies with the greatest appeal to physicians
has been Rexall Showcase International, with headquarters in Boca
Raton, Fla. Rexall distributes vitamins, diet aids, homeopathic
medicines, skin-care products and home water-filtration systems. A
spokeswoman for the company estimated that about 30 percent of its
distributors were in the health-related professions.
</P>
<P>
   The company has created a distributor recruitment tape
specifically aimed at physicians on which nine doctors, including
board-certified internists, cardiologists and surgeons, deliver
testimonials about the efficacy of a patented fiber-based Rexall
product for lowering blood cholesterol, promoting weight loss and
preventing cancer. On the tape, the product is called ``a gift of
health and a gift of finance'' with a ``fair and lucrative
compensation plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors emphasize that the additional income provided by selling
the products can enable them to practice medicine in a more
thorough fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things in medicine are changing,'' Dr. Franklin L. Murphy, a
cardiologist in Los Angeles, says on the Rexall tape. ``I want to
continue to practice medicine the way I feel it should be
practiced. I don't want to do the HMO medicine, and this provides
me a vehicle, another alternative source of income, where I don't
have to do the HMO medicine and I can do the fee-for-service
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview Murphy said of the Rexall
product, ``I think everyone should be on it.'' But he said he
recommended the product only to patients with elevated cholesterol
as an alternative to standard cholesterol-lowering agents. ``I
don't stock a big line of products in the office,'' he said.
``Patients order them directly from the company, and I get a very
small royalty from their purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexall promotional material indicates that distributors earn 25
percent to 45 percent profits on retail sales and as much as 20
percent commission on the sales of people they enroll in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   None of the physicians on the tape specify their compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vast majority of distributors in direct-selling
organizations like Rexall make relatively little for their efforts,
physician-distributors may net thousands of dollars a year from
their participation. They lend the products they offer for sale an
implicit professional endorsement, and may wind up selling them to
hundreds of patients and recruiting dozens of colleagues to do
likewise.
</P>
<P>
   Medical ethicists have repeatedly noted that in addition to the
perplexing questions about whether herbal preparations and
nutritional supplements do all that is claimed, the marketing of
these agents directly by doctor to patient raises other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a financial conflict of interest,'' said Dr. Donald
E. Saunders Jr., a professor of medicine and bioethicist at the
University of South Carolina in Columbia, ``and it demeans the
practice of medicine. I think this kind of thing really wounds the
trust bond between the physician and the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors always have an unfair advantage in dealing with
patients,'' Saunders said. ``Fundamental to medical ethics is to
curb that power and work against our own interests if that's what
it takes to put the patient first.''
</P>
<P>
   Other physicians maintain that the ethical distinction between
accepting money for services rendered and selling a line of
products is new and artificial. Dermatologists, for example, have
historically made and sold their own skin-care products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more comfort with what my patients are getting from my
office compared with what they may be buying from the pharmacy or
department store,'' wrote Dr. David R. Harris, a dermatologist at
Stanford University in Palo Alto, Calif., in a debate on the
subject in the journal Dermatologic Surgery last July.
</P>
<P>
   Some individual physicians _ often those who have parted ways
with orthodox medicine _ now sponsor substantial product lines. Dr.
Robert Atkins, for instance, who has long advocated the importance
of a low-carbohydrate diet for weight loss and cardiovascular
health, sells more than a hundred products from a Web site and a
store attached to his Manhattan offices. The products range from
sugar-free maple syrup to capsules of the steroid hormone
pregnenolone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me at all,'' said one of Atkins' patients,
Malcolm Varon, a New York photographer who estimated that even with
a 25 percent patient discount he spent more than $200 a month on
Atkins' products. ``You're more likely to get people to take what
you want them to take if you have it right there. It's perfectly
legitimate as a way of promoting what he feels is the preferred way
of treating many diseases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
