<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEANUT-ALLERGY VACCINE CLEARS MICE TEST  
 TEEN'S WORRY COULD BE SIGN OF SOMETHING MORE  
 SEXUALLY ABUSED MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Md., R.I., Great Britain)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jock Roy, 55, a businessman from Hanover, N.H., has suffered
from peanut allergies ever since he bit into a peanut butter
sandwich at a birthday party nearly 50 years ago. He described his
reactions as beginning with a prickly sensation in the mouth and
throat followed by a feeling of sickness and swelling of the throat
and sinuses lasting up to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, about 100 people die from complications associated
with allergic reactions to food, and peanuts and tree nuts are
often the culprits. Now researchers at Johns Hopkins University
School of Medicine have taken the first small step toward
preventing peanut allergy reactions in humans with an oral
vaccination that seems to work on mice. Their findings appear in
the current issue of the journal Nature Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers took the cloned gene for the peanut allergen,
Arah2, combined its DNA with a chemical that aids the delivery of
pharmaceutical agents to the intestines and fed it to mice. The
vaccinated mice were protected from the symptoms of peanut allergen
more efficiently than mice that were just given the DNA by itself
or that were not given any DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the exact mechanism,'' said Krishnendu Roy (no
relation to Jock), a graduate student at the biomedical engineering
department at Johns Hopkins University and lead author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   The only proven treatment for people with the allergy has been
educating them to avoid peanuts. But even the cautious sometimes
accidentally ingest them. According to the report, 50 percent of
peanut allergy patients who are treated annually ingested the
peanuts by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I was at a restaurant and the pink ravioli with a white
wine-based cream sauce I ordered had crushed peanuts in the
sauce,'' said Robert Peters, 34, a sales executive from Hempstead,
N.Y., who suffers from a severe peanut allergy. ``I got two
ravenous bites into my mouth and then I felt the tingling.'' He
said the tingling usually gives way to a swelling in the lower
abdomen, and within an hour he passes out unless he gets to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Roy of Johns Hopkins is unsure about the possibilities of an
oral vaccination for patients like Peters and Roy. ``The study
looked at prevention rather than using this vaccination on someone
who has already had the allergy. We still don't know if the vaccine
will work in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   ADOLESCENCE: A Devastating Disorder, Beyond a Phase
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers fretting over how they look may not be just going
through a phase. Some may be suffering from body dysmorphic
disorder (BDD), a severe preoccupation with an imagined or slight
defect in appearance. This often secret and little recognized
malady can lead sufferers to drop out of school, shun social
contacts and even try suicide, say researchers at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   BDD is similar to anorexia nervosa except that sufferers worry
about any aspect of their appearance, not just weight, explained
Dr. Katharine Phillips, author of ``The Broken Mirror,'' a book on
the disorder. ``They look OK but think they don't,'' she said.
``They worry they will be considered superficial or vain if they
tell people about their concerns, but in reality they suffer
incredibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the April issue of the Journal of the American
Academy of Child &AMP; Adolescent Psychiatry, Dr. Phillips and her
husband, Dr. Ralph Albertini, looked at 33 young people, ages 6 to
17, in whom BDD had been diagnosed. They say that this was the
largest study to date on adolescents with the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the schooling, jobs and social life
of almost all had been disrupted. Twenty-two of them had considered
suicide; seven had tried. Five were were unable to leave their
homes even though what they considered physical defects were either
nonexistent or slight. Most preoccupations were with skin and hair,
but subjects also complained about short legs and gaps between
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   In studies with adults, Dr. Phillips found that one in 50
people, mainly women, may have the disorder. Most of them are in
their 30s, but she believes 70 percent of the cases begin before
age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the disorder is unknown, although biological,
psychological and socio-cultural factors are suspected, Dr.
Phillips said. The disorder is not simply the result of Madison
Avenue's rising power, she added. Relatives suspecting that a child
has BDD should consider it a serious problem, not just a phase, she
urged.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, symptoms were treated through cognitive-behavioral
therapy and antidepressants. A pharmaceutical company helped
support the project, but it was not a drug treatment trial, Dr.
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   More information about this disorder may be found at a Web site,
www.butler.org/bdd.html.
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Sexual Abuse, When Men Are Victims
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have learned a great deal in recent years about
female victims of sexual abuse and its often tragic consequences.
But much less is known about men who are sexually abused. How often
does it happen? And what are its effects?
</P>
<P>
   A British survey, the largest epidemiological study of
nonconsensual sexual experiences in men to date, offers some
preliminary answers. In the study, which appears in the current
issue of The British Medical Journal, professor Michael King and
his colleagues at the Royal Free and University College Medical
School in London used computerized questionnaires to survey 2,474
male patients of 18 general practitioners in England.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that 3 percent of the men reported having
had nonconsensual sexual experiences after reaching age 16, and 5
percent said they had been sexually abused as children.
Surprisingly, when the abuse occurred at age 16 and above, women
were just as likely to be the perpetrators as men, the researchers
found, while men were the most frequent perpetrators of abuse in
children.
</P>
<P>
   Men in the study who had been sexually abused had higher rates
of psychological problems, alcohol misuse and self-destructive
behaviors than men who were not abused, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The British researchers cited two other studies that have
examined sexual abuse in men. One was a 1987 study in Los Angeles,
which reported that 7 percent of 1,480 men were victims of
nonconsensual sex after the age of 16; the other was a British
study of 930 homosexual men, which found that more than 25 percent
had been subjected to nonconsensual sex.
</P>
<P>
   King said the rates of sexual abuse found in the new study might
turn out to be underestimates, because it was often hard to get
people to respond frankly to questions about sexual trauma. ``It's
very difficult to interview men cold about a serious problem in
their lives,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISA TANG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
