<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FERGUSON-BOS &LR;      03-29 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FERGUSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRESH, IF REVISIONIST, LOOK AT THE GREAT WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   World War I is beyond almost anyone's memory, but it remains
vivid in our imagination. The terrible trenches. The poison gas.
The horrible price paid, in blood and treasure, for minimal gains.
The irresistible way big-power politics dragged Europe into war,
disillusionment, depression, and war again.
</P>
<P>
   For decades it has been fixed in historical memory as an
inevitable conflict caused by the rapacious militarism of Germany,
ignited by the hopelessly rigid system of European alliances, and
ending in a harsh peace that did little but bring on Hitler, World
War II, and the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing stays the same forever, not even the past, and now
Niall Ferguson, the enfant terrible of the Oxford history
establishment, has produced the modern revisionism that was, alas,
inevitable even if the war itself was not. His argument is simple:
Everything you thought about the start of the war is wrong, and so
is most of what you thought about how it was fought and how it
ended.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, of course, is that the war was so big, so
devastating, so portentous, and so significant that there is no
single truth about it _ just many truths, banging around like
pinballs in an arcade game, bouncing off one another, landing at
random but adding up to a set of conclusions that we already knew:
It was so unnecessary. Europe's leaders were fools. Europe's people
paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, the author of a well-received book on the Rothschild
banking dynasty, does shatter the display cases of the museum of
World War I. He argues, as any revisionist must, that the war
didn't have to happen, that Germany wasn't an overwhelming threat
to European peace, that the allies who won were far less adept at
the art of war than the Central Powers who lost, and that German
hegemony in Europe wouldn't have been so terrible anyhow, given
that three-quarters of a century later there is a peaceful German
hegemony in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The war, he concludes in this massive and oftentimes persuasive
book, was ``something worse than a tragedy, which is something we
are taught by the theatre to regard as ultimately unavoidable. It
was nothing less than the greatest error of modern history.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson draws his title and his sense of irony from Wilfred
Owen, the World War I poet who spoke of the ``truth untold'': ``the
pity of war.'' He argues in an affecting introduction that World
War I was ``the worst thing the people of my country have ever had
to endure.'' There is no argument there _ twice as many Britons
died as did in World War II _ but the reexamination that follows
his opening caused arguments galore last year in the senior commons
rooms of Oxford and in seminar rooms across the universities of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the Ferguson book is the notion that World War I
wasn't inevitable. Nothing is, of course, so on the surface that's
not much of a revelation. But for decades historians have embraced
the notion that, as David Lloyd George wrote in his ``War
Memoirs,'' ``The nations slithered over the brink into the boiling
cauldron of war.'' Indeed, contemporary British politicians argued
_ as H. H. Asquith, the wartime prime minister, did with an eye on
the suffering Belgians in the early days of the conflict _ that it
was ``impossible for people of our blood and history to stand by .
. . while a big bully sets to work to thrash and trample to the
ground a victim who has given him no provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the other elements of Ferguson's revisionist
view: Militarism was in decline, not on the march, in Europe on the
eve of the war. The principal economic fact of early-20th-century
European life was not the growth of German power but the extent of
British power. Despite the broadly held British view that Germany
(as Eyre Crowe warned in 1907) wanted to play ``a much larger and
more dominant part than she finds allotted to herself,'' the most
significant factor in diplomatic affairs was the fact that Britain
ruled 444 million people in 1914. In sheer military strength,
British warship tonnage was more than twice that of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, according to this theory, the war began not because
of Germany's strength but because of its weakness. ``The key to the
arms race before 1914 is that one side lost it, or believed it was
losing it,'' Ferguson writes. ``It was this belief which persuaded
its leaders to gamble on war before they fell too far behind.''
That country was not Britain, as commonly believed (and taught). It
was Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Germany lurched toward war not because it was thirsting for
conflict but because it was worried that its position in Europe was
deteriorating, Ferguson argues. Some of the figures bear that out.
In the period 1870-1913, Britain devoted 3.1 percent of its net
national product to defense expenditures and France devoted 4.0
percent. Germany devoted 3.2 percent. The resulting calculation:
Together, the nations that Germany ended up fighting in World War I
were spending Berlin into subservience. And though one of the
cliches of the period is the rise of German commercial and
industrial power, the weakness of Germany's economy and the
constraints on its growth were well known in London. And in Berlin,
there was a clear sense of which way the tides of power were
running. ``Prospects could never come better for us,'' said the
German military leader Georg Count Waldersee in July 1914, with an
eye on new armament initiatives in France and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Once the war began, Britain was motivated far less by the peril
that Germany posed to Belgium than by the peril Germany posed to
Britain. It is quaint in this season of scandal to consider that
the essential historical evidence for this is contained in
Asquith's letter to his mistress and in the recollections of Lloyd
George's mistress. But so be it. One of the lessons of this book is
the irony of history, or of historians.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out, according to Ferguson, that Britain's involvement
in the war not only widened it but also widened Germany's war aims.
As early as July 1914, Germany was willing to guarantee the
territorial integrity of both France and Belgium. That fell by the
wayside, and a new notion _ thrusting Russia ``back as far as
possible from Germany's eastern frontier'' _ emerged.
</P>
<P>
   One of the way stations of the Ferguson volume is a disagreeable
digression on the efficiency of war, and he makes the point that
``the Central Powers were at least a third better at mass
slaughter'' than their opponents. That is ghoulish, to be sure,
even though it is impossible to separate war from death. A far more
interesting fact may be this: At no point in the war did the Allies
kill more Germans than the number who turned 18 that year. ``If
attrition really had been the way to win the war,'' Ferguson
writes, ``it still would have been going strong in 1919, with the
German cohort of new recruits at its highest level of any year
since 1914.''
</P>
<P>
   These are all fascinating facts, the building blocks perhaps of
a thesis, but, sad to say, not of themselves a thesis. Even if it
is true, for example, that Germany's national-security position was
better off in 1914 than it would have been in 1915 and 1916, why
does it follow that there had to be a war at all? Even if it is
true that Britain didn't have to go to the aid of Belgium, why
should the historian assume that Britain would abandon one of its
strategic imperatives, the integrity of the low countries?
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Ferguson volume is a significant contribution to
the historiography of the war, asking uncomfortable questions and
drawing uncomfortable conclusions. One uncomfortable set of
questions and conclusions involves the place of Germany in Europe,
with or without the war. Ferguson argues that the German war goals
_ reducing the power of Russia, creating a European customs union,
acquiring French colonies _ ``were all goals which were
complementary to British interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he answers Crowe's critical question: ``Should the war
come, and England stand aside . . . (and) Germany and Austria win,
crush France and humiliate Russia, what will then be the position
of a friendless England?''
</P>
<P>
   Here is Ferguson's answer: ``better than that of an exhausted
England in 1919.'' Ask an uncomfortable question, get an
uncomfortable answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
