<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CONTRACEPTIVE-SPO     03-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CONTRACEPTIVE-SPONGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTRACEPTIVE RETURNS TO THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The contraceptive sponge, once the most popular nonprescription
birth-control device for women, could be available once more on
drugstore shelves by fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Today Sponge, a convenient and well-liked contraceptive that
was sold from 1983 until 1995, is scheduled to make a comeback
through the efforts of a small pharmaceutical company that bought
the rights to the product from the manufacturer that had ceased
production of it.
</P>
<P>
   Allendale Pharmaceuticals Inc., a privately held company in
Allendale, N.J., announced this month that it would resurrect the
contraceptive sponge for use by women in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since word of the return of the Today Sponge has gotten out,
we've heard from not only contraceptive experts but many women as
well,'' said Dr. Robert J. Staab, chairman of Allendale. ``And they
are all saying, `Thank goodness it's coming back.' This product had
a special place in the hearts of many consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponge was popular with many women because its ease of use
and ready availability allowed more spontaneous sexual activity
than with many other contraceptives. Women also favored it because
it had a relatively low risk of adverse side effects and could be
used by those who had problems with hormonal contraceptives like
the birth-control pill.
</P>
<P>
   The device is a soft, disposable polyurethane sponge that is
permeated with the sperm-killing chemical nonoxynol-9. Looking like
a plump, rubbery disk with a deep dimple in the middle, and
measuring one and three-quarters inches in diameter and a half-inch
thick, the sponge is inserted into the vagina before sex and can be
left there for 24 hours of protection. The sponge has a ribbonlike
loop to grasp for removal.
</P>
<P>
   The sponge is believed to work in three ways: inactivating sperm
with the spermicide; absorbing semen, which traps sperm to prevent
them from entering the cervix, and acting as a mechanical barrier,
blocking the opening to the cervix.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in contraception and family planning generally praised
the return of the sponge because there are so few other
over-the-counter birth-control choices that are controlled by
women. These include spermicidal foams, jellies and suppositories,
which can be messy and inconvenient, and the female condom, which
is not widely available and has attracted little interest from
women since being introduced in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough contraceptive methods available to
people, and when you lose one, it is felt,'' said Cynthia A.
Pearson, executive director of the National Women's Health Network.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Burnhill, a vice president of the Planned Parenthood
Federation of America, said in a statement, ``The Today Sponge was
a very good local contraceptive and we would like to consider
returning it to the choices offered at Planned Parenthood.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tew, a spokeswoman for the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a
New York-based not-for-profit organization that advocates family
planning and does research on reproductive issues, said the group
applauded the return of the contraceptive sponge. ``Any
contraceptive method found safe and effective by the Food and Drug
Administration should be made available to women in the United
States,'' Ms. Tew said.
</P>
<P>
   Sterilization and the birth-control pill have long been the main
means of contraception in this country, experts said, followed by
prescription devices like the diaphragm. Although never used by
more than 1 percent of contraceptive users at any time, the sponge
was surprising popular among segments of the population, including
unmarried women who infrequently had intercourse and nursing
mothers who could not use their normal means of birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys by the Guttmacher Institute showed that in 1988, 400,000
women used the sponge, but that dropped to 110,000 in 1995 after
production stopped and supplies dwindled. But over the period the
sponge was available, the institute's data indicate that 6.4
million women used the sponge at least once, representingr 11
percent of all women using contraceptives at the time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Its drawbacks include a relatively high failure rate as a
contraceptive and a lack of protection against sexually transmitted
diseases. Tests showed the sponge had a failure rate of about 10
percent during a year's use when worn properly, similar to that of
condoms, diaphragms and other barrier methods, and about a 15
percent pregnancy rate when improper use was factored in.
</P>
<P>
   While condoms guard against transmission of disease-causing
viruses and bacteria, no such claims can be made for the sponge,
although some studies suggest that the device and its spermicide
may afford some protection. There was once concern that the sponge
could increase the risk of toxic-shock syndrome, but later research
showed that those fears were unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   When the Today Sponge went out of production, it caused a minor
social phenomenon when some users reportedly scrambled to buy and
hoard remaining supplies.
</P>
<P>
   These concerns were chronicled in a popular 1995 episode of the
``Seinfeld'' television series, in which the character Elaine
bought every remaining Today Sponge in New York City and filled a
closet with the favorite contraceptive. Concerned with preserving
her treasured stash, she then judged potential lovers on how
``sponge worthy'' they were.
</P>
<P>
   The sponge, approved by the FDA in April 1983, was invented by
the late Bruce W. Vorhauer, a biomedical engineer, and first
produced by his company, the VLI Corp. The company and sponge were
later bought by Whitehall-Robins Healthcare, part of American Home
Products, which produced the product until withdrawing it from the
market in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The product was not discontinued or recalled for health reasons,
as some consumers believe, but because of manufacturing problems.
The company stopped production after a March 1994 federal
inspection of the only factory making the device found bacterial
contamination of the water used to make the sponge and other
products, and problems with sanitizing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing the costs of modifying the factory to bring it up to
standard, and the likely loss of Today's market by the time
upgrading was finished, the company decided to stop making the
contraceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Detroyer, chief executive of Allendale, said his company
bought all rights to the Today Sponge, as well as manufacturing
equipment, from American Home Products for an undisclosed price.
The drug agency approved the companies' request for the change in
ownership. And because the agency never revoked approval of the
sponge, Detroyer said, it can be re-introduced without further
testing or licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Before sales can resume, Detroyer said, the federal agency must
inspect and approve Allendale's sponge production operations, which
are at a contract pharmaceutical factory outside Philadelphia that
already makes drugs for other companies in compliance with federal
regulations. If production begins this summer, the sponge should be
available nationwide by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Both the sponge and its packaging will be exactly the same as
before, company officials said, and it should first be available in
packs of six. The devices should have a suggested retail price
$1.75 to $2 each, they said.
</P>
<P>
   When the sponge was previously available, some women had
problems learning to insert and remove it. Staab said that
Allendale would provide clearer instructions and would set up a
toll-free telephone service to answer questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
