<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GALACTIC-CORES-AR     03-29 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GALACTIC-CORES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUBBLE'S INFRARED PICTURE SHOW: HOW STARS ARE BORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before its infrared camera shut down in November, the Hubble
Space Telescope focused on an assortment of spiral galaxies for
some of its last pictures in those invisible wavelengths, giving
astronomers penetrating looks through thick galactic dust into the
glowing hydrogen clouds where stars are being born.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Torsten Boeker, an astronomer at the Space Telescope Science
Institute in Baltimore, said the pictures, part of the telescope's
concentrated study of about 100 nearby spiral galaxies, were
particularly useful for investigating the dynamics of
star-formation regions. In visible light, many of these regions are
hidden from view by the very clouds of gas and dust enveloping
them.
</P>
<P>
   The telescope's other camera and instruments are still operating
normally, but its near-infrared camera and multi-object
spectrometer, a single instrument, ran out of coolant and had to be
switched off.
</P>
<P>
   In a service mission scheduled in October, space shuttle
astronauts are to visit the orbiting observatory to install an
improved computer and new set of gyroscopes for stabilizing the
telescope. It will be at least another year before a second shuttle
mission can restore the infrared camera with a new cooling system.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the new pictures, Boeker said that an effort was made
to snap spiral galaxies at all angles, from the classic face-on
view of NGC 5653 to the edge-on shot of NGC 891. Other pictures
showed close-ups of the hubs of galaxies glowing in white light
from the dense concentration of stars.
</P>
<P>
   For all the pictures, filters introduced false colors to
highlight textures and material recorded in infrared wavelengths
that would otherwise be invisible to the human eye. Red, for
example, corresponds to glowing hydrogen, the raw material of star
birth. Blue represents the main galactic structure of spiral arms
composed of young and middle-aged stars. Green is a mixture of the
red and blue images. The galaxy cores are mostly white because of
their concentrations of stars.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, astronomers said, red knots in the spiral arms
pinpointed rich star-forming regions. But the glowing hydrogen
inside the galactic cores, they said, could have several possible
explanations. They could reveal star birth or the radiation from
the vicinity of massive black holes, or a combination of both.
</P>
<P>
   Though galaxies come in many other shapes, like ellipticals and
dwarfs, Boeker said that esthetics largely dictated the Hubble's
picture selection. ``Spirals,'' he said, ``are more beautiful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SWEAT-SURGERY-ART     03-29 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SWEAT-SURGERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SURGICAL TECHNIQUE DRIES OFF HANDS FOR GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corey Makowy of Maryland's Hunt Valley region loved school, but
on square-dancing day the 10-year-old begged his mother to let him
stay home. He knew no one would want to take his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates did not want to touch a basketball or computer
keyboard Corey had used either, because his hands sweated _ sweated
so much that when he went to a friend's home to play video games,
he first had to wrap his hands in paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Corey had a little-known condition known medically as
hyperhidrosis. The condition affects more than 200,000 Americans,
and those who have it sweat excessively, usually from the hands,
feet or underarms, but sometimes from the chest or back. The
sweating results from an overactive sympathetic nervous system,
although doctors are not sure of the underlying cause.
</P>
<P>
   But Corey's hands are warm and dry today, thanks to an operation
called sympathectomy, in which surgeons snip the sympathetic nerve
chain that is linked to the excessive sweating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked,'' Corey said. ``Now I can play Nintendo without
paper towels. And when I draw, the pictures don't smear.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey's surgeon, Dr. Mark Krasna, chief of thoracic surgery at
the University of Maryland Medical Center in Baltimore, is one of a
growing number specialists who treat the condition with a new
minimally invasive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year,'' Krasna said, ``advances make the procedure
quicker and easier on the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Until about a decade ago, the operation was a serious one in
which surgeons typically opened the chest and removed ribs to get
to the nerves that caused the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Krasna makes a small incision _ less than an inch _ just
below the underarm of the anesthetized patient. He inserts
cauterizing scissors and a pencil-sized video camera into the
thoracic cavity. Watching a monitor, Krasna snips the sympathetic
nerve chain, then removes the instrument and closes the wound with
a single, dissolvable suture. Patients are discharged within 23
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got it down from opening patients' chests to three
incisions per side to a single, 1-inch cut,'' Krasna said. ``For
bilateral surgery, the procedure is repeated on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Whyte, head of the thoracic surgery division at
Stanford University Medical Center in Palo Alto, Calif., and an
expert in sympathectomy, said that the operation was safe and
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of palm sweating,'' Whyte said, ``at least 95 percent
of patients have good to excellent results.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation can trigger sweating in other parts of the body, a
common side effect, but in Corey's case this has been all but
unnoticeable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The literature shows that after the operation, 30 to 40
percent of patients tend to have increased sweating in their feet
or trunk,'' Dr. Krasna said, ``but very few of them are bothered by
these less visible instances of sweating.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible side effect of the surgery is Horner's
Syndrome, a drooping of the eyelid, but that has not happened in
the case of any patient of either Whyte or Krasna.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients elect surgery after repeated failures with salves,
drugs, electroshock and injections of Botox, a compound commonly
used to smooth wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried one cure after another,'' said Richard Lloyd, 34, of
Rosedale, Md. ``I work at a PC, and the keys have actual puddles
when I type.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People joke about this condition,'' said Lloyd, who is
scheduled for surgery with Dr. Krasna on April 15, ``but it's no
joke when I know I'm about to shake someone's hand and my hands are
soaked.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure costs $8,000 to $10,000, Krasna said, and is
usually covered by insurance. He advises patients to carefully
weigh the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Corey and his parents discussed the possibility of an operation
for several years. They noticed the condition when Corey was 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept hoping he would grow out of it, that it would go
away,'' said Suzanne Makowy, Corey's mother. ``It was awful to see
him cry because of the way people treated him. Finally, he decided
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Corey is happy. ``I can do anything I want,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He can hold his mother's hand, and he no longer worries about
going to school on the days they have square dancing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
