<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      03-29 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 56 years old and intend to work another six to nine
years. I think my portfolio is a little out of balance. I have five
common stocks worth $300,000, $7,000
</P>
<P>
   in Putnam New Opportunities fund, $4,500 in Janus Worldwide
fund, $3,000 in Franklin Balance Sheet
</P>
<P>
   Investment fund, $21,500 in Vanguard Asset Allocation fund,
$25,000 in Vanguard Index 500, $70,000 in money markets, a similar
amount in CDs, $12,500 in Savings Bonds, and $26,000 in the Thrift
Savings Plan. In the thrift plan, 69 percent is in
</P>
<P>
   an account tracking the Standard and Poor's 500 Index, and the
rest in bonds. I add $1,000 a month to the Vanguard Asset
Allocation account, and $200 a month to the Thrift Savings Plan. I
will have a pension annuity upon retirement. As you can see, the
portfolio is heavily weighted towards large-cap stocks. What
adjustments do you suggest? _ M.G., Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not so terribly worried about the 67 percent of the
portfolio that's in large-cap stocks, but the fact that five
individual stocks represent 55.6 percent of it does bother me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm presuming here that the individual stocks which you don't
identify are large caps. If the positions are roughly equal, a
serious tumble from any one of them could cause you some real pain.
</P>
<P>
   It would be lovely if these common stock holdings were in some
sort of tax-deferred savings plan, which would allow you to make
sales and reinvest the proceeds with no immediate tax consequences.
But it doesn't sound as if that's the case.
</P>
<P>
   All I can suggest is that you analyze the tax implications of
selling some of these shares, and then make whatever sales you can
without unbearable tax implications. If you're not sure about the
tax implications, hiring a tax expert to do the analysis for you
would probably be worth the cost.
</P>
<P>
   But you can also take some steps with your ongoing investments
to get a better portfolio balance. For example, while you might
think of Vanguard Asset Allocation as a vehicle that's giving you
some considerable portfolio diversification, at the time of the
last report on the fund from Morningstar Mutual Funds, it held 80
percent of its assets in a stock portfolio dominated by large cap
domestic issues. If I were you, I would stop contributions to that
fund, establishing positions in Vanguard Specialized Health Care
and Vanguard Small-Cap Index and dividing the $1,000 monthly
contributions among those funds.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Thrift Savings Plan, you could also direct that no
more of your contributions go into the S&AMP;P Index fund, instead
adding to the fixed-income side with that money.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 37-year-old man, single and with no children. Among my
investments is a $2,000 Roth IRA which is evenly divided between
American Century Twentieth Century's Ultra and Vista funds. Should
I roll this over into my company's 403(b) plan when I become
eligible to do so, or should I think about rolling over the money
into another investment? _ R.D., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You certainly don't want to move the Roth IRA money into a
tax-deferred account. Consider this: you sacrificed a tax deduction
that was probably somewhere in the neighborhood of $400 to $620 in
order to get the later tax advantage of the Roth IRA, which is that
the money and all of the earnings that it produces will be tax-free
when withdrawn after age 59 1/2. As for whether you want to change
the investment vehicle, the answer is yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Twentieth Century Ultra is a solid,
above-average large-cap growth fund, and although most of its
above-average rating from Morningstar can be tied to its 23.57
percents record for average annual returns over a decade, its
one-year-, three-year and five-year records are respectable,
although slightly trailing the peer averages for those periods. For
a long-term investment program such as your retirement savings,
it's a solid choice.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Twentieth Century Vista is another Share of
Poos, as the Brits might say in rhyming slang. This mid-cap growth
fund has compiled a miserable record, trailing its peer group in
every time period measured by Morningstar Mutual Funds, from
year-to-date to 10 years. Worse, some of the numbers are truly
awful, such as the one-year loss of 8.57 percent, comparing to a
peer average of 24.76, or the
</P>
<P>
   five-year gain of 5.82 percent, compared to a 15.25 percent peer
average. Morningstar's charts show that the sequence of portfolio
manager changes resemble bullpen calls for the 1962 Mets baseball
team. Big years in 1994 and 1995 built the year-end asset base to a
high of $2.24 billion at the end of 1996. But 1996, 1997 and 1998
brought bottom-quartile performances from the fund, and assets have
slid to $985 million, as of the March 4 report of Lipper Analytical
Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar reports that the latest portfolio manager has
analyzed the portfolio and determined that its problems stem from
buying stocks of companies that were growing fast, but whose
earnings were not necessarily following suit. They are now working
on correcting this.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you, I'd let them do it with someone else's money. Why
not move your investment to a small-cap growth fund. If you want to
keep the entire IRA within American Century Twentieth Century
family, why not try American Century Twentieth Century New
Opportunities fund, which posted a one-year record of 18.47
percent, comparing favorably to a peer average of 10.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
