<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-TAX-KAN &LR;      03-29 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-TAX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECT OF HIGHER FUEL TAXES IN KANSAS WORRIES STATION OPERATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK and JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas _ Kay Cho sees a disaster looming for his busy truck stop
in Kansas City, Kan., just a mile from the Missouri border.
</P>
<P>
   Already gasoline prices have been going up, and now comes the
idea of a 5-cent-a-gallon gas tax increase in Kansas. That, Cho
realizes, would make the Kansas tax 6 cents higher than in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to shut down,'' he said. ``The other side has very
low taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it wouldn't be quite that bad. A variety of considerations
make up the pump price of gasoline, taxes being one of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Cho, part owner of Kansas City Truck Terminal, isn't alone
with his concern. Gasoline and diesel fuel dealers along the Kansas
border watch with apprehension as the Kansas Legislature considers
whether to raise the fuel tax to help finance a new transportation
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of raising motor fuel taxes and other fees may provoke
the political fight of the year in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, with an 18-cent-a-gallon tax, Kansas ranks below the
national average in state gasoline taxes. The Missouri gasoline tax
is 17 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas enacted a 5-cent increase, the state would jump above
the current national average of 19.4 cents and above the current
tax of every neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think a substantive hike in the gas tax would have an
impact on the border counties especially,'' said state Rep. David
Haley, whose Kansas City, Kan., district abuts the state line.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators don't want to increase gasoline taxes, or any
taxes, for highways and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe it is essential that a higher fuel tax, one paid
by everyone who uses the highways, be part of the financing
component of any comprehensive transportation plan.
</P>
<P>
   A key part of the debate swirls around the question that worries
Haley: Will a higher fuel tax in Kansas put the state out of step
with its neighbors, causing motorists to pay higher prices at the
pump in Kansas than elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the answer is yes, said Mike Right, vice
president of public affairs for AAA Missouri and an expert on
gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes aren't the only factor in setting the pump price of
gasoline, he said. But, he added, they are a factor producers and
retailers cannot control, so they are an important factor.
</P>
<P>
   States with higher fuel taxes tend to have higher fuel prices,
Right said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, motor fuel taxes represent a time-honored way of
paying for highways.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas initiated its fuel tax in 1926. Missouri had done so two
years earlier. Today, every state in the nation _ and the federal
government _ levies a fuel tax.
</P>
<P>
   Increases aren't unusual. In the last 20 years, the Kansas
gasoline tax has risen six times.
</P>
<P>
   This year, various states around the country are considering
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Higgins, director of congressional relations for the
American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials
in Washington, said the fuel tax has been the most popular source
of income for road programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your motor fuel tax is something that you call a user fee,''
he said. ``I think it is a little bit easier to explain to the
average voter.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, where current taxes are about the same as Kansas,
legislators have been debating a 3-cent-a-gallon gasoline tax
boost. Oklahoma is considering a 1-cent gasoline tax increase to
raise money for passenger train service. Some legislators in
Oregon, which already has a 24-cent-a-gallon tax, are proposing a
4-cent increase.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the debate in Kansas is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Senate passed a transportation plan calling for
the 5-cent boost in the gasoline tax, higher motor vehicle
registration fees and borrowing through the use of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the House passed a smaller transportation plan that
shunned tax increases and designated new money for highways from
the general state budget.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kansas gasoline tax went up 5 cents, the state would take
in $90.5 million a year in new revenue.
</P>
<P>
   A motorist who drives 16,000 miles a year in a vehicle getting
25 miles a gallon would pay an extra $32 in gasoline taxes. Driving
10,000 miles a year, that same driver would pay an extra $20.
Advocates of the tax increase don't believe that having a higher
gasoline tax than neighboring states will cause serious problems
for Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always some sensitivity,'' said Mary Birch, president
of the Overland Park, Kan., Chamber of Commerce, which endorses a
higher motor fuel tax as one way of paying for highways.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1990, the Kansas fuel tax jumped 4 cents higher than
Missouri. ``We didn't hear complaints,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Johnson Countians both live and work within the county, and
make decisions on where to buy gasoline without regard to the state
line, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side is Tom Palace, executive director of the
350-member Petroleum Marketers and Convenience Store Association of
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys on the borders are screaming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palace is concerned that if motorists get used to driving across
the border to buy fuel, they will establish a habit that will be
hard to break even when prices eventually level out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm on one corner and my gas is 95 cents and the guy across
the street is 92, where are you going to shop?'' Palace asked.
</P>
<P>
   A phased-in gasoline tax increase would be easier to swallow, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the Kansas tax by 5 cents a gallon wouldn't
automatically bring about a 5-cent increase in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   What motorists pay at the pump for gasoline depends on a wide
range of things, including the cost of producing, transporting and
refining petroleum, and the competition among distributors and
service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Areas with the lowest gasoline prices aren't always in states
with the lowest gasoline taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, for example, some of the cheapest pump prices
in the Kansas City region have been in Lawrence, Kan., even though
the Kansas gasoline tax is a penny higher than the Missouri tax.
</P>
<P>
   It appears likely that the Missouri tax will remain lower for a
while. State leaders this year considered, but shelved, a proposal
to spend more money on roads this year.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Fahey of Grandview, Mo., a leader of an organization of
highway industry, civic and business groups that recommended a fuel
tax increase for Missouri, said higher fuel taxes are coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it gets down to is, who's going to do it first,'' said
Fahey, who runs a construction company. ``It's going to have to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
