<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METH-MAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER TRAIL TRAPS `GIANT MONSTER' OF METH DISTRIBUTION 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ The biggest, baddest meth dealer in Jackson
County, Mo., history looked neither big nor bad.
</P>
<P>
   Willi Olsen looked old and tired, with gray hair and weathered
skin the color of ash. He was only 48, but service in Vietnam, a
wound that took much of his stomach, and almost two decades of
snorting methamphetamine had cost him. Standing before a federal
judge, hands manacled, head down, he looked years older than he
was.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a time.
</P>
<P>
   From about 1991 to 1995, the California man got rich selling
hundreds of pounds of meth to Jackson County distributors. He
bought classic cars and real estate, gambled millions in Las Vegas
and gave friends wads of cash.
</P>
<P>
   He made drug history in 1993 when he sent two men to Jackson
County with a new, fast and easy way to cook meth. The recipe
spread quickly, beyond Olsen's control, beyond anyone's control.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Olsen had become so big, so rich, they called him
``giant monster.'' He also had become the object of one of the
biggest meth conspiracy investigations in Jackson County history.
And Jackson County had more meth labs than any other area in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen, court records, police and federal prosecutors told the
story...
</P>
<P>
   Olsen fought in Vietnam and fought well. He was an infantry
point man and won nine medals, including two purple hearts and the
Bronze Star for valor. He also was hit in the stomach by a bullet
that broke his back and shattered a hip. He was 19.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Riverside, Calif., in 1971 he could barely
walk because of his wounds. He took a job driving big trucks. On
long hauls, he kept awake with amphetamines. In about 1977, he
snorted his first meth. There was much of it in California,
produced by labs there or in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He and plenty of others used it, Olsen said. ``People were
always asking me for the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he made more money selling meth than driving a truck.
He also found he could make more still by selling it in the
Midwest. Around late 1991, he started selling to two Jackson County
men.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen paid $16,000 for four pounds in California, added a pound
of filler and sold it in Jackson County for at least $80,000. The
Jackson County distributors added another two pounds of filler and
sold quarter pounds for $6,000. Olsen admitted selling about 300
pounds in Jackson County _ almost $5 million just on his take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing was transporting it,'' Olsen said. He flew
in airliners with it taped to his body or stuffed into the tops of
his cowboy boots. He used false-bottomed suitcases and sometimes
overnight mail.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen decided to eliminate the problem with a new production
method.
</P>
<P>
   Californian Kenny Marsh claimed to be one of the inventors of a
method that could turn a few hundred dollars worth of cold medicine
and common household products into a pound of meth in just eight
hours. It was a preferable process to the three-day cooking method
that created odors and tended to cause explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said two words to Marsh before spreading the new process
to Missouri: ``Show me.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced, Olsen sent Marsh and assistant Hugh Escobar to
Jackson County to cook meth. But Marsh suffered from congestive
heart failure from years of heavy meth use. Within months, he
returned to California and died at age 25.
</P>
<P>
   Escobar broke with Olsen and cooked with others, who taught
others. Labs spread through Jackson County like germs. Demand
spread faster.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1728EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
