<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8522 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METH-MAN2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      03-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METH-MAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER TRAIL TRAPS `GIANT MONSTER' OF METH DISTRIBUTION 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olsen gave up his cooking scheme and hired someone to transport
meth from California to Jackson County. He piled up more money,
gambled some away and bought cars, motorcycles and property in
California and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The money left tracks. And colleagues called Kansas City
Detective Dave Parker one of the best money chasers in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Parker teamed with Independence Detective Mike Skaggs.
For more than two years, they served search warrants, sifted
through garbage, traced fake property deeds and tailed meth users
and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   People said they made an odd pair.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, in his late 40s, was trim, dressed in knits and slacks
and knew everything about chasing money.
</P>
<P>
   Skaggs, in his 30s, was overweight and had long hair that
tumbled past an earring. He was the meth intelligence officer for
the Jackson County Drug Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Both believed a conspiracy was involved in Jackson County's
sudden surge in meth.
</P>
<P>
   But who was behind it?
</P>
<P>
   In late 1994, an informant said a local meth dealer expected 40
pounds from California. The dealer was ``the leg of a giant
monster,'' the informer said.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen, meanwhile, continued his spending and sometimes tooled
around Independence, Mo., in a 60-foot travel bus. An informant
said some big supplier was driving the bus. Skaggs and Parker
learned that a mystery man bought the bus with a suitcase full of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bus disappeared from Independence streets. In spring of
1995, Skaggs got a call from police who had raided a farm Olsen
owned southeast of Independence. They'd found a big bus with some
meth and a gun inside, and they'd confiscated it.
</P>
<P>
   Inside it were stacks of gambling tax forms. The name on them
was that of a California man: Willi H. Olsen.
</P>
<P>
   They'd found the monster.
</P>
<P>
   Months later a federal judge in Des Moines, Iowa, sentenced one
of Olsen's big Jackson County buyers to 20 years for expanding a
meth operation into Iowa. Police learned more about Olsen from that
case.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1996, Olsen was on his motorcycle by his California
home in the San Bernardino area when police cruisers arrived. He
gunned his bike and swerved onto pavement. Police chased him,
caught him and cuffed him.
</P>
<P>
   A drug conviction sent Olsen to prison in California. Then a
Kansas City federal grand jury indicted him on meth charges.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, 1997, Olsen pleaded guilty in federal court to
conspiring to distribute and manufacture meth and to money
laundering. Authorities confiscated his property, cars and cash and
left him with a stark choice: cooperate or go to prison for life.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen talked. So did most of the 15 others indicted with him and
sentenced before him. Escobar, the first meth cook known to use the
advanced technique in Jackson County, was sentenced last summer to
four years and two months on a drug conviction.
</P>
<P>
   As for Olsen, the key question at his sentencing last month was
how much his cooperation was worth. Mark Miller, assistant U.S.
attorney, told federal Judge Howard F. Sachs that Olsen's
information was critical in this case and others in South Dakota
and California.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sachs countered, ``On the other side, he was a big
offender.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a kingpin,'' Miller said, and should get sentenced to
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen's lawyer, John Osgood, noted Olsen's cooperation and that
he was a war hero in poor health. Osgood asked for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs took a short break, returned and peered down at Olsen over
the top of his glasses.
</P>
<P>
   As for Olsen's fine military record, Sachs told him, ``what's
happened since pretty much wipes that out.''
</P>
<P>
   He sentenced Olsen to 10 years and imposed a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. attorneys say Olsen clearly helped create a Jackson County
meth contagion that still rages. Even with Olsen and others in
prison, labs are spreading through the Midwest, and cheaper meth
from Mexico is plentiful in Jackson County.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said education is the only way to stop demand for meth.
He's off the drug and knows its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   He has congestive heart failure, the same disease that killed
Marsh and other chronic meth users.
</P>
<P>
   Police saved his life, Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd kept going the way I was,'' Olsen said, ``I probably
would have joined Kenny Marsh in another couple years.''
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
