<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8552 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CHOOSING-MATES-2T     03-29 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHOOSING-MATES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE WE LOSERS? PUTTING A MATING THEORY TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(kd) 
 By MEREDITH F. SMALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am such a loser. According to a branch of biology known as
evolutionary psychology, the human brain was designed to make
mating decisions that insure an individual's genes will be passed
along to the next generation. As a woman, these researchers
believe, I should look for a man of high status who will invest all
his money and goods in our kids. Knowing this theory, I have
nonetheless chosen to spend the last decade with an artist, a man
with no money and few goods beyond a bunch of paint brushes. Silly
me.
</P>
<P>
   But then he's a loser as well. As a man, the theory suggests, he
should have looked for a young, fertile woman with a tight waist
and big hips, which signal her good health. But no. He has chosen
me, a woman much older than himself, one with low fertility who
hasn't seen a decent hip-to-waist ratio in years.
</P>
<P>
   What were we both thinking? Are we really losers? Or are we a
reality check on a theory that has gotten out of hand? Evolutionary
psychology is the current rubric for researchers who study the
biological basis of human behavior. They believe that the human
mind was shaped during a brief period about one and a half million
years ago when our lineage experienced a major rise in brain
expansion. During this Environment of Evolutionary Adaptiveness, or
EEA, as it is often called, we were hunters and gatherers and so
our minds today reflect this ancient way of life.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion that evolution, or biology, or genes, has a major
impact on human behavior is nothing new. Soon after Charles Darwin
developed the theory of evolution by natural selection, Social
Darwinists used it to justify social inequality. But Social
Darwinists were discredited, and for the next 100 years, hardly
anyone talked about human behavior and evolution in the same
breath.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Edward O. Wilson of Harvard University, proposed a
new discipline, sociobiology, as a theoretical framework for the
biological basis of all animal social behavior, including human
behavior. Although sociobiology was widely accepted in the academy,
and is still the basis of all animal behavior research today, the
public went wild. There were protests of genetic determinism,
screams that Social Darwinism was back. There were also
demonstrations at conferences and wide media coverage of the
confrontation. Sociobiology became a dirty word.
</P>
<P>
   The adherents of evolutionary psychology say that it is
different from sociobiology because it focuses on how the mind
makes decisions, not on actual behavior, although thought and
action are usually linked. They clearly feel the mind is hard-wired
in certain ways, but oddly enough, no one has yelled ``genetic
determinism.'' In fact, the public, and the media, eat this stuff
up. How come?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, I believe, lies with the major preoccupation of many
evolutionary psychologists _ sex _ and the fact that much of this
work reinforces male-female stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of evolutionary psychology is about sex and mating, but
this work never receives the same kind of media coverage. Of course
not. How can it compete with titillating tidbits of evolutionary
psychology such as these: Male brains are designed to want any
number of sexual partners, while women want only one stable guy.
Men want young sexy things while women like older stable guys.
Evolution says it is true.
</P>
<P>
   Who can resist such talk? Well, women, for one thing, and not
just because _as we are often accused _ of emotional or political
reasons. We object because it doesn't sit right. It's hard to
explain to men the oppressive power of hearing all your life that
wanting sex as much as men do makes you a bad person. It makes you
want to keep those thoughts to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Additional resistance is coming from anthropologists and
neuroscientists who are currently taking evolutionary psychology to
task.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't take much to find the holes in evolutionary
psychology. Most disconcerting is its use of questionnaires to
figure out what people think about the ideal mate, the ideal body,
the ideal face and so forth. As most social scientists know
already, people are notorious for lying on paper, especially in
research on sexuality; men typically exaggerate what they think and
do, and women always hide their true selves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also, the choice of research subjects is plain silly: college
kids. Yes, they are convenient, but do they represent the
collective human mind?
</P>
<P>
   More insidious is the tendency for researchers to interpret
their data to fit the ideology. The most cited studies about ideal
mates have been conducted by Dr. David Buss of the University of
Michigan. Buss gives subjects a list of traits to rate when
thinking about a mate. Traits such as ``kind and understanding''
and ``intelligent'' and ``exciting personality'' show up on the top
of the list for both men and women. But Buss is not interested in
those commonalties. Instead, he focuses on traits that appear half
way down the ranking _ physical attractiveness and good earning
capacity _ and the fact men rate looks a bit higher and women
wealth a bit higher.
</P>
<P>
   Buss maintains that these results reflect innate differences in
mate desires by men and women. But that ignores the obvious, and
higher rated, results that men and women surprisingly want the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   When this methodology is applied to a wider sample, the results
are similar, and even more problematic. Men in 37 different
cultures rated attractiveness and youth as more important than
women did, and women rated earning capacity higher than men did.
The problem with this supposedly cross-cultural work, as an astute
undergraduate pointed out to me, is that the sample is across
countries, not cultures.
</P>
<P>
   There are also serious problems with the underlying assumptions
of evolutionary psychology. The idea that the human brain was
molded only during one period of history, the EEA, is misguided; we
have a long evolutionary path during which our brains and bodies
adapted, and are still adapting.
</P>
<P>
   And the notion that our thoughts about the ideal mate represent
some truth that is unsullied by cultural influences is ridiculous.
Culture in the form of family, religion and tradition impinges on
just about everything about sex, and clearly directs mate choices.
Women have to look for status in men because they can't get it
alone. And given the choice between an old wealthy guy of high
status and a young one, any sane woman would take the young one.
</P>
<P>
   And what person wouldn't want a partner who is judged ideal by
cultural standards? At the moment, skinny girls are offered up as
the ideal, and so men want that type. But in the real world, men
don't get anything close to a culturally manufactured ideal, and
they know it.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares about fantasies anyway? Genes are passed along in
the real world where attraction, love, mating and marriage are not
always linked. In reality, people choose mates (or have them chosen
for them), in myriad ways. Our brains are not designed specifically
to desire this or that, but to weigh the options, and then get down
to the business of having babies.
</P>
<P>
   Given that scenario, my partner and I are not anomalous; we're
typical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
