</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUGGED PAIR OF JEANS  
 GROUNDWATER CHEMICALS  
 BACTERIA THAT GLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wis., Del.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disposable synthetic clothing designed to protect the skin from
hazardous chemicals is no one's idea of casual wear. The same
qualities that keep harmful compounds away from the body can keep
heat and moisture in, making such garments uncomfortable at best.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers at the University of California at Davis have
developed a process that could make protective clothing as
comfortable as an old pair of blue jeans. In fact, with their
process, protective clothing might even be an old pair of blue
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The research, reported at a meeting last week of the American
Chemical Society, is intended to protect farm workers from the
pesticides they encounter in the field. Rather than trying to block
the chemicals, the goal is to destroy them, by incorporating into
the surface of ordinary cotton-polyester fabric a compound that
breaks down the harmful chemicals on contact. By wearing clothes
made from the treated fabric, a farm worker would become a walking
detoxification plant, rendering a pesticide harmless before it
reached the skin.
</P>
<P>
   The compound used, called a hydantoin, needs to be activated by
the addition of a chlorine atom. And that leads to another
advantage of the process: Simply by washing the clothes in bleach,
their pesticide-destroying capabilities are renewed.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the fabric destroyed up to 99 percent
of some kinds of pesticides. They caution, however, that the
treatment has not been tested with organophosphates like malathion,
which account for a large portion of the total pesticides in use.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical Concoctions
</P>
<P>
   Once a pesticide seeps from the field into groundwater,
protecting against it is a different matter. Even low levels of the
chemicals in water can have health effects, as studies have shown.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those studies have looked at one chemical in
isolation. Groundwater in agricultural areas contains a mix of
compounds _ insecticides, herbicides and fertilizer. Might the
effects of this chemical cocktail be different from that of each of
the ingredients alone?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, say researchers at the University of Wisconsin. After a
five-year study, they suggest that combinations of agricultural
chemicals can influence the immune, endocrine and nervous systems.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers gave mice drinking water with various
combinations of chemicals at concentrations equal to those often
found in groundwater. The most pronounced effects were found when
one pesticide _ either an herbicide or an insecticide _ was
combined with nitrate fertilizer. The results were reported in the
current issue of the journal Toxicology and Industrial Health.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that current testing methods for most
agricultural chemicals are flawed, both because they focus on the
chemical in isolation, and because they mainly look for
carcinogenic effects rather than systemic impact.
</P>
<P>
   A Glow for E. Coli
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid pesticides is to keep them out of the food
chain. Researchers at the University of Delaware and Du Pont Co.
have figured out a way to do that, at least for chicken feed.
</P>
<P>
   The technique uses a genetically engineered strain of E. coli
that acts as a biosensor, glowing in the presence of certain kinds
of chemicals, including pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   When normal E. coli encounters a damaging compound in its
environment, it responds by making proteins. The researchers fused
genetic material from a bioluminescent bacteria with E. coli,
creating a form of E. coli that responds to environmental stress by
making glow-in-the-dark proteins.
</P>
<P>
   By adding the bacteria to poultry feed and then measuring the
bioluminescent response, the scientists were able to detect a
variety of compounds like the herbicide known as 2-4D and aflatoxin
B1, a carcinogen that can kill chickens. The researchers foresee a
day when a farmer can use a hand-held light detector to screen feed
for harmful compounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
