<HEADER>
A8558 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HELICOPTER-SKIING     03-29 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HELICOPTER-SKIING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE SKIS, HELICOPTER, AWE AND TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back a thousand years ago, as a fearless beginner on the
groomed, hard-packed slopes of the Northeast, I seemed to favor the
point-the-skis-downhill-and-crash-at-the-bottom approach.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, after a moderately undistinguished
college-racing career, that basic style remained intact with a
brief, and aborted, attempt at an entirely new discipline in the
Austrian Alps: deep-powder skiing. That attempt ended with a crash
at the top of the mountain, not the bottom, and two broken skis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, lured by the promise of warm spring sun, in high pure,
untouched virgin snow, attracted as well by the idea of soaring
with ease by helicopter up among the remote spires of the Canadian
Rockies set in the greatest of imagined beauty, I ventured, several
decades after that, to try again.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day skiing adventure began the day before skis
actually touched snow with two very important lessons of survival.
Forty of us were assembled in the unfancy Gothics lodge, in an
abandoned gold-mining camp, one of 11 ski areas run by Canadian
Mountain Holidays over some 11,000 square miles of mountains in
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Our instructors first offered a set of specific instructions on
precisely how to board and get out of the helicopter. Then we
learned how to use the radio transmitter-receivers provided by the
company to tune in and locate the transmitters strapped to the
bodies of other members of the group, should they be buried in an
avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Our first day on the snow was a rousing success _ depending on
how you define success. It was actually closer to a disaster, but
no one was decapitated by helicopter blades, buried in an
avalanche, and I did not fall up to the neck more than 20 times in
the hip-deep powder.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the day, in heavy snowfall, 10 of us kneel in a
tight huddle, at just the right point near two red flags on the pad
outside the lodge to avoid the whirling blades of the helicopter as
it descends. We climb properly aboard, and the pilot manages
somehow to sweep through the storm, up along the high mountain
cirques and thread the eyes of the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   He drops slowly down on a snowy knoll, barely larger than his
craft. coldvery hard to see in the snowy, flat light. The descent
before us looks impossibly steep. I'm not sure we are having fun
yet.
</P>
<P>
   We buddy up, trying not, despite the blinding snow, to let our
buddies out of our sight. And all trying to heed the rule never to
get ahead of the guide. I get going too fast again, prompting a
warning: ``If you let yourself go below the guide one more time ...
you may be flying over a precipice, and it may be the last
precipice you fly over!''
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter, meanwhile, descends to pick up three more groups
of 10 dropping each group off a different mountain peak over a
1,000- square-mile area. They ski down to a designated spot, and
radio back to the helicopter to pick them up again and are able to
make eight or nine runs, with a total vertical descent of, say,
6,000 feet or more of skiing a day.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been much instruction so far on how deep-powder
skiing differs from groomed-trail, or hard-packed skiing _ apart
from learning about the skis themselves, the new ``fat boys,''
which are wider and shorter than downhill skis. The lack of
instruction is, particularly in my case, obvious: six falls,
exhausting to dig out of, on the first six turns.
</P>
<P>
   The differences in the two types of skiing are few, but they are
important. And they involve avoiding habits developed over a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   In deep powder do not keep your weight on the downhill ski when
turning. That is to say, do not shift all your weight to the left
ski when turning right, for example, as one must do in sharp fast
turns on most groomed or hard-packed snow.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, balance the weight evenly on both skis, keeping the
upper body turning with the skis, rather than away from them and
facing down the hill. (When I turn, with my old muscle memory
automatically shifting my weight to my downhill ski, the uphill ski
catches in the snow, spinning me out of control. I wonder if I will
ever get up.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, keep the ankles, knees and hips lightly bent but bouncy
and relaxed, with the body slightly _ but not too much _ forward
and in much more of a down and up motion, pressing down hard on the
snow and then rising up to take weight off the skis and ease the
turn in the powder. (The stuck brain keeps me bending the knees at
almost 90 degrees, which gives me stability at high speed on
groomed slopes but sets me too far back _ and this time backward in
another bad fall into the lovely, dark and deep.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Finally, avoid like another cold bath, sharp turns to check your
speed. Instead, start off straight down the mountain but then make
continuous shallow turns back and forth across the fall line, an
imaginary line straight down the slope.
</P>
<P>
   Turns in a kind of wavy, rhythmic way, singing a Viennese waltz,
or ``Love Me Tender,'' say, help establish the rhythm as you go. (I
have no trouble with the straight-down part. But the weight
distribution and the up-and-down motion continue to be problems.)
</P>
<P>
   By the second day, three feet of new powder has fallen
overnight, and it is still snowing. The mountains may be beautiful,
but who can see them. ``You are not doing well enough,'' Bryan, the
guide, informs me. ``You're out of control!'' (Me? What makes him
think that?) ``You're holding back the group.'' Bryan helps me
through the first successful series of shallow turns.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, the first rays of sun are poking through to
lower elevations and the first tunes of glory. But with still more
fresh powder and the warming weather, the avalanche threat rises.
Todd, another of the guides, inches his way across the top of the
first peak of the day. He signals the group to stop. He surveys the
area. He jumps hard on the snow. And a crack opens up a foot or so
above him. This touches off an avalanche that knocks him over and
sweeps him instantly and silently away.
</P>
<P>
   But he is high enough that, though on his side, he is able to
ride the crashing snow like the crest of a wave and push himself
behind a tree. A small mountain, a Class 2 avalanche (Class 5 is
the worst ) 150 feet wide, 90 feet deep and 300 feet long _ big
enough to bury the group _ passes by. Todd is not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The glory of the rest of the day comes in the body's finally
starting to do what it is told, in catching the rhythm of the
shallow turns. The back and forth, and back and forth, to the
strains, not to date this novice, of ``The Anniversary Waltz.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that I had been out of shape. I had trained for weeks
at a gym. But I was not prepared for the constant falling early in
the week, and many of the deep falls required just about all the
strength I had to extricate myself from the snow and get up again.
Yet, once the correct techniques were, well, not mastered, but at
least seemed to register with both the brain and body, the effort
involved was surprisingly small.
</P>
<P>
   On later days, it stops snowing and patches of blue appear. It
even becomes possible to make entire runs skimming along the tops
of delicious snow dunes and through groves of beautiful pines
without so much as a fall. Yes, now we are definitely having fun.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day, the highest peaks finally clear. Halfway
through the morning, a realization hits: skiing in any other
conditions may never be the same. How else is it possible to float
over the world as smoothly and peacefully and quietly? Where else
is white as white, or blue as blue? Where else is the stillness and
majesty and stirring within as true?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
