<SLUG> BC-COURT-STUDENT-FEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO RULE ON USE OF STUDENT ACTIVITY FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
state-run universities can use part of the activity fees they
collect from all students to subsidize groups that pursue political
and ideological goals that some students find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said it would review a ruling by the 7th Circuit
Court of Appeals that barred the University of Wisconsin at Madison
from using the fees when students objected.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in April 1996 when three law students at the
university sued the board of regents over the fees, arguing that
they did not want to subsidize groups that they disagreed with
politically or ideologically.
</P>
<P>
   The three students, who described themselves as conservative
Christians, identified at least 18 campus organizations _ including
the Women's Center, the Madison AIDS Support Network and the human
rights group Amnesty International _ that they did not want to
support.
</P>
<P>
   Student fees at the University of Wisconsin and other public
schools are distributed to applicants by the student government,
which decides how the money is allocated. At Madison, fees are $330
per year, with campus organizations receiving between 10 cents and
30 cents from each student.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the university defended the policy, saying the
student groups performed an important educational role.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, a federal trial judge ruled that the subsidies
unlawfully force some students to finance views they find
objectionable and thereby violate free-speech rights. The lower
court barred the university from using fees collected from
objecting students.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago agreed
with that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forced funding of such organizations significantly adds to
the burdening of the students' free-speech rights,'' the appeals
court said. The three-judge panel added that the university
``cannot use the allocable portion of objecting students' mandatory
activity fees to fund (those) organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling did not shield objecting students from
paying any activity fees. Rather, the ruling allowed them to
identify the political or ideological groups they do not want to
support and have their fees reduced on a prorated basis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Supreme Court ruled that public universities and
colleges cannot create a ``public forum'' for students and then
refuse to subsidize some student groups because of their viewpoint.
That decision said the University of Virginia wrongly refused to
subsidize a student-run Christian magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to that decision, the appeals court said in its 1997
ruling on student fees that if universities are not allowed to
discriminate in the disbursement of funds, ``it is imperative that
students not be compelled to fund organizations which engage in
political and ideological activities _ that is the only way to
protect the individual's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule on the case next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
