<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonable warmth will embrace parts of the central Plains
Tuesday afternoon as winds from the southwest warm by compression
on descent from the lofty Rockies. Readings will approach 80
degrees in a few spots in sunny western Kansas and western
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will stir winds in the lower atmosphere,
blending momentum from fast winds aloft with winds near the
surface. As a result, winds will average 20 to 40 miles an hour
across parts of western Kansas and western Nebraska. Blowing dust
may restrict visibility in some areas. Winds will gust over 50
miles an hour across the high plains of eastern Colorado and
southeast Wyoming, where gusts may exceed hurricane-force in a few
of the traditionally windy spots downwind of mountain canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Moderately heavy rains will douse parts of northern California
and southern Oregon as a potent jet stream disturbance pivots
inland from the Pacific. Thunder may accompany rain in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will flourish over the central Gulf
States Tuesday, with the heaviest rains likely occurring near the
central Gulf Coast, where the concentration of humid air will be
greatest. Extensive cloudiness and a few showers will extend
westward into Texas and southeast Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a gradual warming trend will continue in the sunny
Northeast, although winds from the west averaging 15 to 25 miles an
hour will detract from the mildness of the air along the New
England Seaboard. Gusts to 35 miles an hour are possible from Long
Island, N.Y., to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Still Formidable Arctic
</P>
<P>
   The high temperature at Prudhoe on Alaska's North Slope on
Sunday was minus 30 degrees, the latest date that such a frigid
maximum reading has been observed at the town. At night, the
temperature plummeted to a record minus 43 degrees. Despite
shortening nights and increasing hours of daylight, the Arctic is
still capable of producing frigid air. During the day, clouds or
snow-covered landscape reflect sunlight, limiting the rise in
daytime temperatures. At night, clear, calm conditions promote
rapid cooling, completing one cycle in the production of Arctic air
masses in spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
