<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOMAN-SUITCASES-ART-N     03-29 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOMAN-SUITCASES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINGERIE OR HARDWARE, IT'S A HEAVY BURDEN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Willy Loman is the world's most famous failed salesman, but what
did he sell? During the 50-year existence of ``Death of a
Salesman,'' Arthur Miller's words have entranced audiences with
Willy's inflated dreams for his sons, his muttering to himself, his
bad driving, his affair, his malfunctioning refrigerator, his
mortgage, his insurance payments and his suicide, all the while
refusing to disclose what Willy lugged in his valises.
</P>
<P>
   Willy's real wares may appear to be inconsequential because what
he sold was himself, and ultimately, there was no demand for his
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safer not to say what he sells,'' said Gerald
Weales, emeritus professor of English at the University of
Pennsylvania and the editor of a widely used study text about the
play. ``The assumption is that Miller was specifically unspecific.
But whatever he sold, it's heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time we see Willy (played by Brian Dennehy in the
current Broadway revival), he is carrying what seem to be the
world's heaviest valises. Shouldn't we care what's in them? Perhaps
knowing the products would help us understand his spiral into
emotional destruction. Let us hypothesize that they were jammed
with obsolete goods, suited to old tastes, making his failure more
understandable. You can be liked, you can be very well liked, but
how many orders can you write if you're selling goods nobody wants?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Wagner Co., Willy's employer for 34 years, was a
dinosaur, sending him on nearly useless jaunts to New England.
Maybe his company's incompetence turned Willy inept, and maybe he's
not the only one being downsized by Howard, old man Wagner's son.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps then, it would have been useful for Miller to tell us
what Willy was schlepping when he abruptly came back from Yonkers,
at the beginning of the play, cutting short his trip to New
England. O'Neill didn't hide the fact that Hickey in ``The Iceman
Cometh'' sold hardware. (Dennehy has played Loman and Hickey; how
much more motivation did he generate knowing that Hickey made his
living on monkey wrenches?) Yet Miller keeps us guessing.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how keenly disappointed Ben Loman, Willy's
adventuresome brother and a diamond mogul, must have felt when they
exchanged these words:
</P>
<P>
   BEN: And good luck with your _ what do you do?
</P>
<P>
   WILLY: Selling.
</P>
<P>
   BEN: Yes. Well ...
</P>
<P>
   Ben was unimpressed. A world traveler, Ben knew his little
brother had no idea how to get out of Brooklyn. But imagine if
Miller had extended their conversation, just a little bit, maybe
three lines that would have helped Ben understand Willy's vocation:
</P>
<P>
   BEN: Just what is it you sell, William?
</P>
<P>
   WILLY: Catnip mice, Ben.
</P>
<P>
   BEN: Fine. Very manly, William, great for building your boys'
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is inconsistent about his characters' professional lives.
Willy's son Biff is a farmhand with a penchant for thievery. Happy,
Biff's younger brother, is two assistants below the assistant buyer
of unknown merchandise. Willy's next-door neighbor, Charley, runs a
business and lends Willy $50 a week, but whatever he does is a
secret. Charley's son, Bernard, a rehabilitated nerd, is a lawyer
about to argue a case before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And Dave Singleman, the legendary salesman so admired by Willy
for being able to rack up prodigious orders from hotel rooms, sold
... who knows? But Miller does offer a few clues about what Willy's
wares were.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Willy's blind obsession about Biff's job interview with
Biff's old sporting goods boss, and his vivid memory of his older
son's triumphant high school football game at Ebbets Field, is a
vague hint that he was in that game. He loved sports, but Miller
provides no further evidence.
</P>
<P>
   What about the stockings Willy gives his Boston lover? Maybe he
sold a full line of lingerie. But hawking ladies' scanties hither
and yon for three decades is difficult to envision for Willy. He
seems more of a hardware guy. And if he sold women's undergarments,
it's nearly impossible to reconcile that with the sight of Willy's
wife, Linda, darning her old stockings.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller mentions three of Willy's accounts, two of them
prominent Boston stores. One is Filene's, which primarily sold
men's and women's apparel during the era of ``Death of a
Salesman.'' So was it men's socks or ladies' hosiery?
</P>
<P>
   The other Boston store, Slattery's, may provide the answer. No
longer in business (its inventory was liquidated in 1957 at
Filene's Basement), Slattery's was an apparel chain that catered to
women with high-class, midprice merchandise. Yet Slattery's may be
Miller's red herring, perhaps simply homage to his first wife, Mary
Slattery.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, wouldn't it be a kick for Dennehy to open his valises
to show off the neatly arranged espadrilles, velvet dresses and
brocade handbags, ready for sale? As Linda Loman says, ``Attention
must be paid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
