<SLUG> BC-LAMBS-BOOK-SEQUEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG AFTER `LAMBS,' DR. LECTER IS RETURNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hannibal the Cannibal is back. Dr. Hannibal Lecter, the
flesh-eating villain of Thomas Harris' 1988 novel, ``The Silence of
the Lambs,'' will continue his adventures in a sequel,
``Hannibal,'' delivered unexpectedly last Tuesday by Harris to his
publisher, Delacorte Press.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is being rushed into print with unusual speed, said
Harris' editor, Carole Baron, who is president and publisher of
Dell Publishing. (Delacorte Press is Dell's hardcover imprint.)
Mrs. Baron said that the book, which took Harris 10 years to write,
would go on sale on June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with Lecter know that he is a man of savage
appetites. Once he tore into the nurse who was taking his
electrocardiogram and ate her tongue, all the while keeping a
steady pulse rate of 85.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Baron was reluctant to reveal details of the new book's
plot, except to say that Lecter ``is pursuing his interests.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the manuscript was about 600 pages long and would be
about 480 pages in print. ``Although I had been discussing it with
Tom for the past few years,'' she said, ``I resisted asking when he
was going to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Baron said Harris had called her abruptly last week and
said, ``Are you busy?'' and then delivered the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learn more about Hannibal in this book,'' Mrs. Baron said,
opening the possibility that readers will learn some of the
motivation for his cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Baron did say that in the new novel Lecter, who escaped his
captors at the end of ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' would once
again face his old adversary, FBI Agent Clarice Starling. One of
Lecter's victims, who runs a family meat business and is now but
``a shadow of his former self,'' Mrs. Baron said, uses Starling as
bait to draw Lecter out into the open so he can wreak revenge.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third of Harris' books to feature the character of
Lecter, who also appeared in ``Red Dragon,'' published in 1981.
Harris, a former writer and editor for The Associated Press,
declined to be interviewed. ``He's very private and ultimately very
shy,'' Mrs. Baron said of him. His first novel, ``Black Sunday,''
was published in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The film version of ``The Silence of the Lambs'' won five
Academy Awards: best picture, and best director for Jonathan Demme,
best adaptation for Ted Talley, best actor for Anthony Hopkins as
Lecter and best actress for Jodie Foster as Starling. The film
rights to ``Hannibal'' are expected to attract intense interest as
well, Mrs. Baron said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
