<HEADLINE>
`FACING THE TRUTH': SOUTH AFRICANS WRESTLE WITH THEIR PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Bill Moyers had contented himself with reporting on the
hearings of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of South
Africa, that would have been a considerable contribution to
American viewers' comprehension of the horrors of apartheid. But
``Facing the Truth'' goes further. In interviews with the black
victims of white repression, Moyers inquires into the limits of
forgiveness and the lure of forgetfulness, while his encounters
with the former tormentors leave in their wake bitter questions of
individual responsibility and punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of women who lost their husbands and children to
murder squads is presented in near unbearable detail. Their
accounts bring home the meaning of being in the power of a regime
that treated black people as expendable; for some whites, the color
line was a license for barbarity.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers' interviews with the victims are deeply moving, but his
interviews with their torturers reveal what human beings are
capable of when restraints of common humanity are overridden by
orders from above or by ideology or simply by the privileges of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the old South Africa's state security apparatus who
were incriminated in atrocities have been granted amnesty on
condition that they tell the truth about the jailings, kidnappings,
beatings, tortures and murders. Just how complete or truthful they
are is in doubt, and the offer of amnesty _ an effort by the new
South Africa to clear the air _ seems to many of the victims an
easy way out for their persecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The defiant defenses of some whites can still chill. (``I was
doing my duty,'' says a hit-squad commander of his ``preventive
assassinations.'') One man tells of enjoying a barbecue while the
bodies of recently murdered captives were being burned. Former
Prime Minister F.W. de Klerk concedes that the police used some
``unconventional strategies'' and ``firm actions,'' but in the face
of much evidence he denies charges of state terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers also talks with blacks and whites who are joining in
trying to rebuild their country with some semblance of justice, but
their good will seems fragile given the existing inequities. A
black businessman provides the blunt statistics: Whites own 90
percent of the country's capital; 90 percent of blacks have
nothing. He calls the daily return trip from the luxurious white
enclaves where many blacks work to the shanty towns where they live
without running water or electricity a journey from ``splendor to
squalor.'' Reflecting on the contrast, a white college student says
the benefits of apartheid to people like himself have come with ``a
moral stain.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks Moyers returns to the subject in a conversation
with Archbishop Desmond Tutu. Tuesday night's two hours leave the
question of what sort of reconciliation is possible with so wide a
gulf between the races unbridged and so many cruel memories
unburied. ``May we have the bones back?'' survivors keep asking.
The hearings continue; the images mount; the past is unresolved and
perhaps unresolvable.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FACING THE TRUTH WITH BILL MOYERS'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Judith Davidson Moyers and Judy Doctoroff O'Neill, executive
producers; Gail Pellett, producer-director; Vanessa Procopio,
editor; Robert Shepard, director of photography; Mandy Jacobson,
associate producer; Deborah Rubenstein, director of special
projects. Produced by Public Affairs Television Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
