<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-29 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOUSE THAT'S FULL YET EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - There's a half-empty package of Klondike bars in the
freezer, the Neapolitan variety. Andy liked to have one at night,
before he went to bed. Photographs of grandchildren are stuck by
magnets to the walls and door of the refrigerator, along with a
drawing by a 6-year-old showing a ball coming off a bat and soaring
into space.
</P>
<P>
   Near the basement door on a shelf are a hat a gloves Dora used
to wear to shovel snow. On a hanger nearby is her favorite jacket.
Not too heavy. She never wore a heavy jacket, even in the coldest
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Coupons for coffee and laundry detergent and shampoo are stacked
in a small plywood shelf he built for her years ago and nailed near
the front door, next to the spare keys.
</P>
<P>
   In the cabinet above the stove are rows of spices in small jars.
Rosemary and nutmeg and cloves and garlic powder and basil.
</P>
<P>
   The things she touched last he tried to leave alone.
</P>
<P>
   The pad and pencil she kept near the telephone on the kitchen
table. The cough syrup above the sink. The earrings on the upstairs
dresser.
</P>
<P>
   For most of a year, after her death, he lived his life around
the objects she'd left behind, unwilling to move anything. &QL; 
ROSARIES, PICTURES, CARDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for a visit to Arizona he'd made the bed they'd
shared for over 50 years in the fashion she'd always had made it,
the top cover tucked under the pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Her rosaries are on the post where she left them.
</P>
<P>
   The picture of her in her wedding gown is on his nightstand,
where he left it.
</P>
<P>
   In a drawer on her side of the bed are the cards he'd given her
on Christmas and their anniversary and her birthday. In a drawer on
his side are the cards she'd given him.
</P>
<P>
   In a box on a shelf in their bedroom are baseball caps he'd
gotten over the years but no longer wore. On the hat rack at the
foot of the stairs are the ones he did.
</P>
<P>
   Home videos sent to them by their children are stacked next to
the VCR, on the television set, in the order he'd last watched
them.
</P>
<P>
   On top is the trip to Arizona in 1992, in which she was full of
laughter and he is strong enough to play with the kids, and nowhere
on the horizon are there hints of doctor visits or hospital beds or
coffins.
</P>
<P>
   The little stereo in the dining room has a Big Band tape in it,
stopped in the middle. His hearing was bad, but she played the
music as a kind of soundtrack to her chores, putting chairs in
order and straightening the tablecloth and organizing bills in a
basket on the china closet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOUSE IS FULL BUT EMPTY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the basement near his workbench are stacks of thin wood he
used to cut into shapes and paint and transform into Christmas
ornaments. Lions and tigers and Mickey Mouse and Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging from the ceiling by a string is one of his last
projects, a wooden helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   He'd planned to come back to their house and pick up where he'd
left off, but he never made it.
</P>
<P>
   It's something you don't expect, your parents' house, full but
empty. It's as if the whole thing should have been buried, and them
inside it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they're gone and what remains is the little desk in the
sun parlor where she kept a calendar with notations about who had
called and when. And the coffee table in the living room, which a
son pulled from the garbage at a local church. And the ``secret
compartment'' at the foot of the stairs where visiting children
would find toy soldiers and dolls. And the 1985 Pontiac in the
garage, its tank half full with gas.
</P>
<P>
   Something must be done about the house and the things they left
behind. But for now, everything was left in its place. The towels
in the hall cabinet. The shoes in rows in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   The phone in the downstairs hallway with the same old number,
which an out-of-town son dials up occasionally, just to hear it
ring and ring and ring. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
