<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST-UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Adds: STEALTH, NEWT, OLYMPICS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, March 30,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Another round of U.S.-led NATO air
strikes against Yugoslavia is under way Monday as a humanitarian
crisis continues to build in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
Yevgeny Primakov, Russia's prime minister, is expected to arrive in
Belgrade on Tuesday to talk with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ BRODEC, Macedonia _ The river of human misery
continues to spill across the border here, evidence that the
humanitarian crisis builds in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
Serbian telelvision was showing devastation from the NATO air
strikes on civilian sites in Kosovo. Also, reports that Dr. Ibrahim
Rugova, a key Kosovar Albanian negotiator, was killed over the
weekend while in hiding. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ WASHINGTON _ As NATO steps up its pounding of
Yugolsavia, the focus is turning more to the Serb troops and
paramilitary gangs terrorizing ethnic Albanians in the southern
province of Kosovo. More and more, it appears that this campaign
cannot be successful without sending in ground troops. An already
dicey question, fraught with political risk for the Clinton
administration, continues to rear its ugly head. Developing.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TROOPS-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ Where U.S./NATO troops are stationed
around the region. Developing. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STUDENT _ ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ A high school exchange
student from Kosovo currently living near Elizabeth City, N.C.,
said Friday he supports NATO's bombing of his homeland and other
military action despite the fact his parents are still living in
the war-torn Yugoslavian province. The student, a 17-year-old
ethnic Albanian, said he hopes the bombing will destroy Yugoslavian
President Slobodan Milosevic's ability to kill Albanians.
(Livingston, Elizabeth City Daily Advance).
</P>
<P>
   STEALTH _ DAYTON _ For decades, technology sleuths at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base have torn apart and studied
Russian-built warplanes to learn how they work -- and how to defeat
them. Now it may be Russia's turn. Russian counterparts to American
foreign technology analysts are undoubtedly eager for a chance to
examine pieces of the U.S. Air Force F-117 Stealth fighter that
crashed in Yugoslavia Saturday. It isn't clear what they can learn
from the flaming debris, but even badly damaged equipment can be a
prize to foreign technology analysts. During the Korean war,
American teams deliberately blew up wreckage of Russian-built
MiG-15 fighters just to get pieces small enough to throw into
helicopters and bring them back to Wright-Pat for study, according
to the National Air Intelligence Center at Wright-Pat. Right now,
the center has three Russian-built MiG-29 fighters in its
``exploitation center'' on the base. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News).
15.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-EDITOR _ ARLINGTON, Va. _ Seventeen years have passed
since Karen Jurgensen, the single mom of a 5-year-old daughter,
drove a thousand miles up I-95 to start a job on USA Today, a
newspaper that existed only in the minds of a few journalistic
visionaries. It was not a bad move.(Dart, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Monday. Usable until May 1, when Jurgensen takes over
at USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEWT _ Private citizen Newt Gingrich says he's heading back to
the grassroots, and will try to shape public policy by taking his
proposed platform to local GOP meetings beginning this fall. Social
Security private investment accounts, lower taxes and America's
leadership in the world will also be part of a book.
</P>
