<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Tuesday, March 30, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
day supervisor is Gary E. McCardell; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: Fresh NATO air attacks
shifted more toward Serbian positions in embattled Kosovo today as
the Clinton administration claimed the evidence of genocide by Serb
forces was growing to ``abhorrent and criminal action on a maxium
scale.'' By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO officials said Monday that
Slobodan Milosevic's military campaign against the ethnic Albanian
population of Kosovo was aimed at establishing a Serb-only enclave
inside the province to hold on to after the fighting ends. ``We
have the impression that there is a campaign under way to
ethnically re-engineer the inside of Kosovo, to achieve a solution
more acceptable to him,'' said Jamie P. Shea, Nato's chief
spokesman. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Undated) _ News analysis: As Yugoslav forces
kill and evict the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, a critical question
has emerged for the West: at what point does the brutality used by
Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, and the increasingly
personal attacks on him by the West, make it impossible to ever
negotiate with him again? By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Somewhere near the Kosovo border) _ Listening
to refugee voices: They tell of methodical, organized, systematic
expulsions by police and paramilitaries. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONITORS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The international monitors
who pulled out of Kosovo dejectedly reflect on what they might have
done differently, and desperately try to keep in touch with Kosovo.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOICES (White Plains, N.Y.) _ As the death toll mounts
along with the bombs, refugees and protests, so has public
uncertainty over the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. People
who accepted the Clinton administration's portrayal of the military
strikes as a clear-cut moral obligation _ the protection of a
vulnerable ethnic minority from the brutality of one stubborn man,
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic _ have now begun to
question just who is the enemy and what motivates him. In a series
of interviews over the past five days with ordinary people living
and working in White Plains, those doubts have grown more apparent
as they have absorbed more and more of the flood of information,
pictures and commentary about Yugoslavia from television, radio and
newspapers. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Along Belgrade's loveliest shopping
street, Knez Mihajlova, groups of young men filled with chauvinism,
anger and beer on Monday completed the trashing of the American
Center, the British Council, the Goethe Institute and the French
Cultural Center, as scattered policemen watched and chatted among
themselves. Belgrade is a city where people say ``ciao'' and drink
espresso, judge the latest Hollywood movies with asperity and surf
the net. But the war is dragging it farther from Europe, into
isolation, uniting the Serbs behind their soldiers, their Kosovo
and even President Slobodan Milosevic. American movies have been
withdrawn from the theaters, though the Original Levi's Store
across from the American Center was left untrashed by the mobs. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROTECT (Washington) _ One point of the NATO attack was
to protect ethnic Albanians in Kosovo; now they are worse off than
ever. Did the U.S. anticipate this? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DRONES (Washington) _ The drone, an unmanned aircraft, is
one of the best tools NATO has to learn what is going on in Kosovo.
But drones have not yet been used. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ Which allied units are where and
which would be needed if NATO changed its mind and decided on a
land attack. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Primakov, the Russian prime minister,
is going to Belgrade on Tuesday. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PILOTS (Aviano, Italy) _ What allied pilots are saying
about their missions over Yugoslavia. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these, we are considering stories on diplomatic
maneuvering among the allies and Russia and a story on the possible
relevance of the international convention on genocide.
</P>
