<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-420&AMP;ADD     03-29 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMAKOV HEADED FOR BELGRADE TO URGE NEW NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(kd) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Alarmed by the prospects of a widening war in the
Balkans, President Boris Yeltsin Monday dispatched Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov on a high-risk mission to Belgrade, Yugoslavia,
Tuesday to coax President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia back to
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Russia will insist first on a halt to the NATO bombing, which
top officials here again described as an barbaric act of
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the tough talk, Primakov's mission is seen as a sign
that after five days of bombing, Moscow is ready to commit its own
diplomatic muscle and test the influence it has on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, which will include Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and top intelligence
officials, may move on from Belgrade to the capital of a NATO
country _ perhaps Bonn, Germany _ if it sees any hope for a
negotiated settlement, news reports here said.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who abruptly called off a crucial visit to Washington
last week as the first wave of NATO missiles were being launched,
said Monday after meetings with Michel Camdessus, managing director
of the International Monetary Fund, that an agreement on relief for
Russia's crushing foreign debt was near.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kosovo crisis, which has given rise to new anti-Western
feelings across the Russian political spectrum, has put real
strains on relations with Western partners, raising fears that
Moscow is heading into a another period of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Ivanov showed little flexibility in
Russia's position as he lambasted NATO for hitting targets he
described as civilian and causing what he called a humanitarian
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO bears full responsibility for this and nobody will
succeed in covering this up,'' he said, accusing Washington in
particular of concocting ``threadbare schemes'' to blame the flight
of refugees on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov also accused NATO of covertly planning to send ground
forces into the region and of coordinating its aerial attacks with
the Kosovo Liberation Army. In particular, he said, representatives
of the United States and the West in the Organization of Security
and Cooperation in Europe mission, now based in Macedonia, had left
behind liaison officers within the Kosovo Liberation Army who have
been guiding NATO aircraft to Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At present, armed Albanian terrorists have launched a
large-scale offensive against the Serbs virtually throughout the
region,'' he said, repeatedly dismissing reports that Kosovo
Albanians were being pushed out of the province by Serbs as
propaganda spread by NATO.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Rumors are assiduously being spread that genocide has started
at this precise moment in time,'' Ivanov said. ``Genocide is being
perpetrated, but only as a result of NATO action.'' As for the
refugees now massing on Kosovo's borders, he said, their numbers
have increased ``because nobody wants bombs falling on his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov dismissed a previous peace mission by Russian liberal
democratic politicians, led by the former Prime Minister Yegor
Gaidar, with thinly veiled scorn. Although the Gaidar delegation
informed the government of its trip to Belgrade, he said ``they
represented only themselves,'' and he questioned the
``coincidence'' of their meeting with the special American envoy,
Richard Holbrooke, at an airport in Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev, the defense minister, said he had information that as
many as 1,000 civilians and 100 military personnel had been killed
so far by the NATO bombing. This was the latest in a series of
casualty figures issued by the Russians; they have yet to be
confirmed by Yugoslavs or others.
</P>
<P>
   Running through a list of NATO targets, Gen. Yuri Baluyevsky, of
the Russian General Staff, said more than 20 civilian sites had
been hit, including educational establishments, resorts, the
Gracanica monastery and historical monuments at Citinje, in
Montenegro, the other republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Russian reports last week of the downing of two NATO
planes, these reports could not be confirmed. The military attache
at the Yugoslav Embassy in Moscow refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's
international military cooperation department, said Russia had
taken further steps to cut its links with NATO by recalling
officers now in NATO countries on special training programs and
canceling all scheduled meetings with NATO colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the vehement language, Ivanov insisted Monday that
Russia rejected any return to a Cold-War stance. ``We do not want
to see our relations worsen,'' he said. ``We do not want to go back
to the relations that we had in the period of the Cold War, or to
be plunged into confrontation. This is not our choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
