<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8647 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT &LR;      03-29 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ALBANIAN BORDER, TALES OF VAST DESTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARINA, Albania _ Lindalita Kryeziv and her husband, Alban,
walked, tired, scared _ and suddenly homeless, broke and stateless
_ over this scraggly border crossing early Monday, a tiny part of
the ragged band of some 60,000 ethnic Albanians here hounded out of
Kosovo by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have nothing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something even worse: She had been separated from
her 18-month-old daughter and her sickly mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour earlier, her daughter, Elita, lying in the
arms of her mother-in-law, Hanife Kryeziv, had crossed the border
ahead of them in a cart dragged by a farm tractor. But now they
were nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   As she desperately searched from the backseat of a stranger's
car along the 15 miles of twisting road southwest of the town of
Kukes, where the refugees gathered, Mrs. Kryeziv recounted her
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kryezivs' apartment in the town of Suva Rekka early
Monday morning a half-dozen Serbian paramilitary agents pounded on
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were scared,'' Mrs. Kryeziv said. ``They said `You have
half an hour to get out of here and say hello to President Clinton.
You don't belong here. It's not your land, Kosovo.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had already written the name of a Serbian family on
their apartment door. All around her neighborhood, she said, other
ethnic Albanian families were being ousted and Albanian-owned
stores looted and smashed. The minaret of a local mosque was blown
up, recalling the destruction of Islamic buildings in Bosnia by
Serbs during their ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign there.
</P>
<P>
   ``All over the countryside you will only see cows and animals,''
she said. ``You won't see people.''
</P>
<P>
   Her story is almost identical to those told by virtually every
refugee interviewed in different parts of Kukes in the last three
days by journalists and Western aid workers: a tale of whole towns
ordered to flee by Serbian policemen in paramilitary units, the
people robbed along the way and stripped of identity documents down
to their cars' license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the striking similarities of the accounts appeared to
indicate that the Serbian campaign was methodic, well-organized and
systematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consistency of the reports is alarming,'' said Eugene
O'Sullivan, the head of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe's observer team here.
</P>
<P>
   And there were other, sinister reports, more difficult to
confirm, of killings by the Serbian forces and bodies left by the
side of the road, as well as whole villages set afire. A hundred
people were said to have been executed in the village of Celine,
among other such reports reaching Western aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth along the road the Kryezivs searched, following a
white scratch running along the battered pavement, perhaps the
trail of the steel rim of a broken rear wheel of the cart the
daughter and mother-in-law were in. But a youth by the side of the
road told them he had seen the cart pass by _ empty. ``This is like
a nightmare for me,'' Mrs. Kryeziv said softly as the couple got
out to search among the clumps of tired refugees.
</P>
<P>
   By their traditional garb _ bright, baggy pantaloons on the
women and girls, the white conical felt hats worn by Muslims among
the Albanians of the northern mountains on older men _ many of the
refugees appeared to be from the rural areas in the mountains and
valleys west of the Kosovo city of Prizrin.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden influx swamped Kukes, a town of about 20,000 people
about six hours north of Tirana, the capital, on dizzyingly steep
and crumbling roads across spectacular mountains. But desperate
efforts by the Albanian government and the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, the main agency running the relief
effort, in mobilizing hundreds of buses, army trucks and other
vehicles managed to move about 16,700 people southward toward
Tirana by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more made their way south crammed on carts pulled by
farm tractors and in cars distinguished by their lack of license
plates. ``It's almost orderly,'' O'Sullivan, said Monday as night
fell, ``as opposed to this morning, which was absolute chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials were distributing plastic sheeting for
protection in case of rain and had begun to organize food
distribution and medical care. In the main square, refugees
clutching whatever they escaped with, crowded around the buses as
they pulled up. But just before 8 p.m., a new wave of refugees _
about 20 cars and 1,000 people on foot _ began crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, the refugees clustered, looking stunned, along
the sidewalks in Kukes and at gathering places like the main square
or a truck park. And when asked, they told of burned villages,
looted homes, stolen jewelry and foreign currency _ German marks
preferred _ and reports of killings and other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs came and told us we have to leave for Albania,''
said Dervish Dervishaj, 66, from the village of Dillush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people leaving in tractors they didn't search so much,''
he said. ``The people with good cars they searched very well. They
took the foreign currency, and then they took the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They took all our identity documents and burned them, and they
took the plates off the cars,'' he said as dozens of people
clustered around a battered tractor and cart with half a dozen
women and belongings including a painted baby cradle piled on top.
``Without identity we won't have the right to be back in our own
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another refugee, Sejadin Krasniqi, said: ``They took the foreign
currency from the people. For the Serbian currency, they said
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Liman Fazliu, 58, from Dinaj, said: ``They were playing with us.
They said to make this sign or they would kill us.'' He made the
three-fingered sign of the cross of the Orthodox Church used by
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   As they talked, Alban Kryeziv moved silently through the crowd,
his young face grim, as he continued his search for his mother and
baby daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
