<HEADER>
A8651 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     03-29 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV31-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING TRAINING TAKES A HIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, March 31)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one thing I hate, it's when somebody from a Big Paper
Up North insults Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone's going to do a number on Sarasota, it should be me.
That is my job, I've been doing it for years and I haven't gotten
where I am today (a small desk downwind from the newsroom
refrigerator) by letting the Big Boys move in on my turf, or
stained beige carpet as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   I am referring, of course, to the article in the Feb. 26 issue
of The Wall Street Journal where writers Sam Walker and Jonathan B.
Weinbach (never trust a Big Paper writer who uses a middle initial)
``evaluate'' the spring training baseball parks in Florida and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Smith Stadium, the spring training home of the Cincinnati
Reds, is described as a ``nice but unremarkable distraction in an
otherwise shuffleboard-crazy resort town.'' The nicest thing the
writers could say about the team was that the Reds, this year,
finally lifted their long-standing ban on players' facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   Although the underachieving Reds may have looked like they were
playing shuffleboard the past few seasons, that is not something
you can blame on the citizens of Sarasota, most of whom spend their
free time coughing at Gordon Lightfoot concerts or honking at
tourists on U.S. 41. (Or perhaps it's the other way around.)
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, Sarasota might be a better place to live if it
were more crazy about shuffleboard and less crazy about a lot of
other things, like real estate development, new bridges and making
it illegal to be a teen-ager in downtown after 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffleboarders have tempers, just like everyone else I suppose,
but you seldom hear of gunfights erupting over a rules dispute or
an opponent running over someone simply because he did not play
quickly enough. This sort of thing happens on Sarasota's (and New
York's) highways far too often. (If cell phones were replaced by
cordless shuffleboard discs, I think America's highways would be a
lot safer.)
</P>
<P>
   Calling Ed Smith Stadium a ``nice but unremarkable distraction''
is so vague that I can't tell if it's a compliment or a complaint.
Some uncharitable sorts might say the same thing about The Wall
Street Journal or even New York itself, though the ``nice'' part
seems a bit of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into Marge Schott and her St. Bernard, Schottzie 2, the
other day at Ed Smith Stadium, which is something that's never
happened to me in the offices of The Wall Street Journal or on the
streets of New York. I'm not sure if that will make you feel better
or worse about Ed Smith Stadium, but I just thought you'd like to
know.
</P>
<P>
   The description of McKechnie Field, where the Pittsburgh Pirates
play in Bradenton, was more perplexing than unflattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKechnie Field has an urban flavor (foul balls pelt cars on
city streets) and an unadorned, slightly dilapidated feel that some
say make it the Wrigley Field of the Grapefruit League.'' The
writers went on to describe the parking around McKechnie as
``horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The writers were apparently unaware that the unadorned, slightly
dilapidated McKechnie Field underwent a major renovation six years
ago and is now, arguably, the most eye-catching public edifice in
all of Bradenton, which admittedly is not saying all that much.
Still, no less an authority than USA Today called McKechnie ``the
Fenway Park of spring parks. Green fence, green seats, the
definition of baseball intimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   True, this ``baseball intimacy'' may be hard to appreciate if
you are one of the unlucky drivers on Ninth Street West to have a
foul ball crash through your windshield, but that seems a small
price to pay for green fences and green seats. (Not to mention
green money, something you should bring plenty of if you go to any
spring training games, even those in shuffleboard-crazy Sarasota.)
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal writers were kindest, in their own way,
to Charlotte County Stadium, home of the Texas Rangers. (They
thought it was cool that the place is crawling with alligators,
which should tell you all you need to know about New York.)
</P>
<P>
   They also described Charlotte County Stadium as a great place to
snag batting-practice home runs, something that was apparently
written before the well-publicized fight between a fan and a
Rangers coach over a batting-practice home run ball.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say I disagree with everything the Big City Paper
wrote about our spring training parks.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, as written, that Charlotte County Stadium can get
cold at night, but if you get too chilly, you can go out in the
parking lot and wrestle an alligator or scuffle with someone over a
home run ball to help warm you up.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
