A8653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPING-LAWMAKER-NYTR     03-29 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPING-LAWMAKER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA LEGISLATOR IS A HAPPY CAMPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIRSTEN B. MITCHELL   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARNER, N.C. _ Buffaloe's Mobile Acres is 11 miles and a world
removed from the marble floors and brass chandeliers of the state
Legislative Building.
</P>
<P>
   The worlds collide at lot No. 92, where a sleek new 36-foot RV
gleams in the afternoon sun amid aging but tidy trailers. It's the
home away from home for state Sen. Dan Robinson and his wife of 37
years, Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Shunning the usual pick of Raleigh hotels and apartment
complexes where state lawmakers typically stay Mondays through
Thursdays, the Robinsons opted to bring their second home with them
to this capital city suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more or less decided even before the election that if I
was successful that we were going to use the mobile home,''
Robinson said as highway interchanges and suburban sprawl faded in
the rear-view mirror of his Mazda Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Robinson, who serves as her husband's legislative clerk,
first suggested the unusual living arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to talk her out of it during the winter months,'' said
Dan Robinson, a Democrat from Cullowhee in his first term. ``That
just didn't go over at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to give up on me,'' Jean Robinson
sighed as they sat in the RV's living area, outfitted with a couch
and three lounge chairs.
</P>
<P>
   With the election won, the Robinsons immediately began scouting
for campgrounds and eventually found Buffaloe's Mobile Acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a neater mobile home park,'' said Dan
Robinson, a retired football coach from Western Carolina University
in Cullowhee. His wife is also retired from the university, where
she spent a career as a secretary and where the couple met.
Cullowhee is in Jackson County, across the state line from South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed some extra secretarial work and they sent her over,''
Robinson said. Thirty-seven years, three children and three
grandchildren later, the couple still enjoy each other's company.
Wanderlust and their RV have taken them as far as Alaska and the
Canadian Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part,'' Jean Robinson said of living long-term in a
motor home, ``is we both have to share a bathroom.'' It's smaller
than some walk-in closets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a go-go dancer in the shower,'' she quipped.
``It's got a skylight and you're up on a ledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The RV is outfitted with two color televisions _ one in the
living area and a smaller one in the bedroom; a
convection-microwave oven; and a small washer-dryer combo that will
clean two or three shirts at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to water and propane, the park provides phone
hook-up. They pay $325 a month for the site, utilities included.
Legislators are paid $1,160 a month salary, plus $728 a week for
meals and lodging and $559 a month for expenses like postage and
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they most missed from home, they quickly agreed that
they often think about sitting on their glassed-in porch watching
birds.
</P>
<P>
   The Robinsons had visions of cooking dinner on a charcoal grill
and taking strolls in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the lifestyle,'' Jean Robinson said. ``It's what we
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, that life has eluded them with legislative work and
lobbyist receptions keeping them in Raleigh past sundown most
nights.
</P>
<P>
   (Kirsten B. Mitchell is chief of the Raleigh, N.C., bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
