<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IN BELGRADE MARKED BY PROTESTS, BOREDOM AND VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-MONITORS,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Along Belgrade's loveliest shopping
street, Knez Mihajlova, groups of young men filled with chauvinism,
anger and beer Monday completed the trashing of the American
Center, the British Council, the Goethe Institute and the French
Cultural Center, as scattered policemen watched and chatted among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the stones shattering the windows seemed in rhythm
with the sounds of another patriotic concert in the city center,
starring Ceca Raznjatovic, wife of the notorious Serbian
paramilitary leader Zeljko Raznjatovic, known as Arkan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ceca,'' a Serbian version of Cher, was famous before she
married Arkan, a proud pioneer of ethnic cleansing in Bosnia. But
she has taken to doing music videos with a live tiger cub, a
reference to the name of Arkan's brigades, the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   As ordinary Belgrade residents walked by, or stood to watch the
destruction, the young stone throwers also spray-painted obscene
graffiti on the walls, comparing NATO to the Nazis and making snide
references to President Clinton's sexual life.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the passers-by, they wore a ``target'' logo that
has swept Belgrade _ a gesture of contempt toward NATO's bombs that
is made more palatable by the fact that no NATO bombs have struck
the populated center of the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ashamed to see this,'' said a medical doctor dressed in a
fashionable pale-beige suit who identified herself only as Zaklina.
``But you know the bombs have made people crazy. They crack the
veneer of civilization, as if war excuses anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughed then, saying, ``Anyway, they are bored with being
down in the shelters, with the grannies.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade is a city where people say ``ciao'' and drink espresso,
judge the latest Hollywood movies with asperity and surf the Net.
But the war is dragging it farther from Europe, into isolation,
uniting the Serbs behind their soldiers, their Kosovo and even
President Slobodan Milosevic. American movies have been withdrawn
from the theaters, though the Original Levi's Store across from the
American Center was left untrashed by the mobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to say that only God could unify the Serbs,'' said
Aleksa Djilas, an historian and son of the late Milovan Djilas, the
most famous dissident of the Tito period. ``But now they've been
unified from heaven _ but by the bombs, not by God.''
</P>
<P>
   No one really feels they deserve to be bombed, Djilas said,
``even if they know that Milosevic's policies have played a big
role.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the government has urged citizens to run to
the air raid shelters for 12 or 15 hours a day, understanding that
collective panic provides a sense of solidarity with the nation and
its military.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you refuse to go down, or say that there is no point in
it, people get very angry,'' said Ilija, a former journalist in his
50s. ``People think you're belittling their plight or somehow
saying that it's all right that they're sitting in a shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much more suspicion around, with rumors of Western
spies and local dissidents planting radar guidance devices to
insure that NATO's bombs find their targets. Some Serbs insist,
conversely, that some devices have been planted in the hotels where
journalists are staying, intended not to guide the bombs, but to
deflect them.
</P>
<P>
   And the city authorities, while deciding that it is now safer to
keep Belgrade's street lights on, still insist that curtains be
drawn after 6 p.m., as if NATO's modern weapons still depended on
illuminated living rooms to find their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Yugoslavia faces its sixth day of bombing without
major civilian casualties, people are becoming inured to the sharp
wail of the sirens. Fewer spend all night in the shelters, but
there is little else to do, with nearly all the restaurants, clubs,
cafes and movie theaters shutting down at dusk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deepening sense of boredom _ the war is really very
boring, especially with this monotonous war propaganda on the
news,'' said a cosmopolitan Serb, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``My son is bored; he can't go out, except to visit
friends in their shelters, where it's boring. My little one is
bored, because all her favorite cartoons like Power Rangers have
been replaced by these interminable news programs.''
</P>
<P>
   So people are renting armfuls of videos, especially comedies,
like ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Serbs remain resourceful and ironic. A basement cafe
downtown has renamed itself ``The Shelter Cafe,'' offering
satellite television along with coffee and drinks. A placard put up
in a window along Knez Mihajlova read: ``F-117A. Crashed. Low
mileage. Foreign license plates. Cheap. Call after 4 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   And with cigarettes so scarce, people joke, the war is a superb
opportunity to quit smoking.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Milosevic government, through its censorship of the news
media, has isolated Belgrade and the rest of Serbia proper from the
real war going on to the south, in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While state television shows careful film of NATO damage, there
is little effort to discuss the activities of the military and
security forces in Kosovo. While Western politicians and
human-rights officials are making harsh accusations of atrocities,
killings and ``ethnic cleansing'' of the ethnic Albanian
population, Serbs are informed that their forces are simply
responding to the widespread terrorism of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army and its sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Djilas, the historian, said he considered that the coming visit
by Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to be a way for Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to deal with fierce domestic criticism of
NATO and doubted that it would produce anything substantive.
</P>
<P>
   But it would also add to what Zoran Djindjic, the leader of the
Democratic Party here _ and an organizer of pro-democracy
demonstrations against Milosevic two years ago _ called the
``mental filters of censorship and self-censorship'' that protect
ordinary people from the reality of atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of Milosevic's system is that no one knows
anything,'' Djindjic said. ``We don't know how the economy is doing
or what the Zastava factory is producing or how many are
unemployed, let alone what is happening in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the same process that allowed the Germans under Nazism to
discount evidence of the Holocaust, Djindjic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People first need to hear information,'' he said. ``Then, if
they hear it, will they believe it? And if they believe it, how can
they explain it?'' As they try to explain it to themselves, he
said, people will think ``Maybe they victims are guilty, somehow,
and deserve what they get.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, Belgrade's reform mayor for a few months in 1997, said
it was important to understand how much Milosevic depends on a
rural constituency that has always hated Belgrade, the
sophisticated metropolis. Yugoslavia's civil wars, over the last
decade, have brought more and more angry and impoverished Serbs
here from Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a rural fatalism now,'' he said. ``There is
more xenophobia, myth and superstition. All of this is only
accelerated by the war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
