MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) - It's something you don't expect, your
parents' house, full but empty. It's as if the whole thing should
have been buried, and them inside it. Instead, they're gone and
what remains is the little desk in the sun parlor where she kept a
calendar with notations about who had called and when. And the
coffee table in the living room, which a son pulled from the
garbage at a local church. And the `'secret compartment'' at the
foot of the stairs where visiting children would find toy soldiers
and dolls. And the 1985 Pontiac in the garage, it's tank half full
with gas. By E.J. MONTINI. Story moved in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
