<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0330-     03-29 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0330-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TINY, POOR ALABANIA BUCKLING UNDER FLOOD OF KOSOVO REFUGEES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0330.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Already Europe's poorest country, Albania was
being pushed to its limits Monday by a seemingly endless flood of
refugees from neighboring Kosovo in southernmost Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 75,000 of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians have crossed the
rugged mountains that rise between the countries since NATO air
strikes began last week aimed at forcing Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace agreement, aid agency and
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted and frightened, the refugees are being distributed by
the Albanian government to settlement centers throughout Albania, a
country where average residents have little more than the refugees
they now must host.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko on Monday said his
government expects nearly 100,000 more refugees -- reportedly
ordered out of their homes by Serb military forces -- to cross the
border Tuesday and pleaded for Western assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Albania (UNHCR)
confirmed Majko's forecast, and called on international relief
organizations to help assist 150,000 refugees in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems are being dealt with in absolute priority,'' the
agency said in a statement here in Albania's capital. ``The
sheltering of the refugees, the provision of food and non-food
items is being coordinated with all relevant bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR estimates that 7,000 refugees have entered Macedonia,
20,000 have entered Montenegro and 75,000-80,000 had entered
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates than as many as 550,000 people have been
displaced during the air campaign, which coincided with a major
Serb offensive against ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   For days, officials have reported that large groups of refugees
were making their way toward the border with Kosovo. Before the
NATO air strikes began, the border had been nearly closed by
Serbian officials eager to staunch the flow of guns from Albania to
separatist guerillas in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western aid workers said Monday they had lost count of the
number of refugees pouring in at a rate of maybe 4,000 an hour. The
isolated Albanian mountain village of Kukes was turning into a way
station where refugees were placed on buses destined for processing
centers elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the refugees are arriving in automobiles and in farm
wagons drawn by tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers said the refugees were being stripped of their
documents by the Serbs. Ethnic Albanians arriving by car said the
Serbs took their license plates and car documents.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Ilir Meta told the BBC most of the
refugees were women, children and the elderly, many of them
exhausted and in a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   Very few men of military age were seen among the refugees,
perhaps because the men have either gone into hiding or have joined
in the fight against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying incredible things,'' Meta said. ``They have
been forced from their homes and their homes have been burned. The
Serbian army and police told them the only hope of saving their
lives was to enter Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the refugees were crossing at Morina, on the Serbian
side, near Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo crossed the
border to Macedonia on Monday, aid officials said. A group of men
walking down the road near the town of Jegunovce near the
Kosovo-Macedonian border told of being forced from their homes by
masked Serb thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their houses were looted and burned, the men said.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women were separated and sent on foot toward the
Macedonian border. One man who only would give his first name,
Fatmir, said he and the other men had walked more than 20 miles
over rugged mountains to escape from Kosovo. ``They said get out or
we will shoot you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid for him,'' he said, pointing to his 16-year-old son
Zafer. He said another 200 men were still in the woods on the
Kosovo side of the border, afraid to cross.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not seen his wife, who was driving their tractor
out, since he took to the road. She is with his 13-year-old
daughter and 8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their personal catastrophes, none of the men said he
opposed the NATO campaign. Sulewmani, 53, expressed gratitude for
the attacks. ``NATO is good,'' he said. ``There was no other
method. They must keep going until all is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugee wave was so dense that it swamped the border
crossing at Morina because Yugoslav guards could not handle the
masses on their side of the border. Yugoslavia closed the border
crossing for nearly three hours Monday because the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian Parliament convened for a crisis session Monday,
and the government ordered all private companies to make minivans,
buses or other transport vehicles available immediately and send
them up to Kukes to help distribute refugees around the country.
The government already had sent 300 buses to pick up the refugees
but determined that this was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
