<HEADLINE>
AMAZING GRACE AMID URBAN MAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - At the base of the telephone pole where Officer Marc
Atkinson's patrol car banged to a stop, someone left a small Bible.
It is taped open to the Book of John, with the following passage
highlighted in yellow:
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest love a person can have for his friends is to give
his life for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The tiny book is attached to a piece of paper, on which is
printed in big green letters, ``Having not met most of us living
here, you have shown you are our friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Good Book must have been left here by one of the early
visitors to this maze-like industrial park west of the freeway and
north of Thomas Road. By Monday morning, the Bible had almost been
completely covered over with roses and carnations and daisies and
irises and lilies.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to one bouquet is a note reading, ``To the family and
friends of Officer Atkinson. So sorry to hear of your loss. My
thoughts and prayers will be with your always. Here is a small gift
from a Marine mom whose son came home from Desert Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson's reserve unit served in the war with Iraq, where
battle lines were more clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why the punks with the guns pulled into this
place when they noticed Atkinson tailing them Friday afternoon.
Narrow ribbons of asphalt criss-cross between low, stark buildings.
A car can disappear quickly around a corner, which is what
happened, police believe, to Officer Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   They say 17-year-old Felipe Petrona-Cabanas turned up 30th
Avenue off of Catalina, stopped, and waited for the 27-year-old
officer, a husband and father of a 6-month-old, to turn the corner.
</P>
<P>
   He was shot in the head and died, striking the power pole just
north of Barry Metals, next to a pair of feathery cassia bushes. On
Monday, men loading industrial-sized barrels onto trucks watched
their street fill with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   KTAR's mobile radio studio was parked across the street. The
voice of host Pat McMahon mixed with the noise of cars and trucks
and forklifts.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Kirkham drove down from Glendale with her two children,
2-year-old Deanna and 9-month-old Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna walked through the ring of orange traffic cones
surrounding the makeshift memorial. There were so many pretty
flowers for a girl to see, and she spotted a stuffed bunny, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to pay our respects,'' Holly said, looking down
at her daughter and saying, ``Put the bear down.''
</P>
<P>
   Deanna carried a small stuffed Panda that her mom wanted to
leave for Atkinson's infant son. It was hard for Deanna to let it
go, however. She cried. She couldn't understand what was going on
here. No one could explain it.
</P>
<P>
   Just as no one can explain those who (begin ital) haven't (end
ital ) staged high-profile visits to 30th Avenue and Catalina. That
group identified in the media as ``political, religious and civic
leaders,'' which includes the Rev. Oscar Tillman, Councilwoman Mary
Rose Wilcox, Rudy Buchanan Sr. They loudly seem to join every
protest against the police.
</P>
<P>
   Was Atkinson any less a victim?
</P>
<P>
   One card left among the flowers read, ``From an x-con many times
over who finally learned his lesson 15 years ago. May you be with
the Lord forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Another read, ``We'll miss you brother &AMP; friend _ 82B Squad.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a large homemade cross in the ground with Atkinson's
name on it. And several smaller crosses, one made of palm fronds
and pierced through with a Drug Enforcement Agency pin.
</P>
<P>
   And homemade condolence cards taped to the pole, with pens
attached by string so visitors can sign them.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be this way for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Then, slowly, everything will disappear again among the ribbon
of blacktop within the small maze north of Thomas Road, which is
inside the larger maze of metropolitan Phoenix, which already has
too many places where homemade crosses once marked the final
resting place of a cop. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
