<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO GROUND ATTACK WOULD REQUIRE THOUSANDS OF TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If NATO ground forces are ordered to fight Yugoslav
leader Slobodan Milosevic's drive to kill or expel ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo, experts said Monday that 100,000 to 200,000 troops, many
of them American, would be needed for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. Edward Atkeson said NATO military
planners likely would need a ground combat force with at least a
3-to-1 numerical advantage over the Yugolsavs, or about 120,000 to
150,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Such a force would require tanks and fast-moving light infantry,
said Atkeson, a senior fellow at the Institute of Land Warfare in
Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the soldiers likely would come from the United States,
Britain and France, because they have the best-trained ground
forces with the most advanced weaponry, Atkeson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a long time to build up a force like that, a
month at least,'' Atkeson said, adding that much of the force would
have to be shipped in.
</P>
<P>
   The force would require a nearby staging area, probably in
Macedonia, he added. But using Macedonia as a launch pad for a
ground attack could exacerbate simmering tensions between ethic
Serbs and Albanians in the southeast European nation, Atkeson said.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia was a former republic of Yugoslavia that gained
independence in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization would face
a formidable force in Kosovo _ about 40,000 Yugoslav troops, 16,500
police, 300 Soviet-built tanks, 700 artillery pieces and 700
armored vehicles. In addition, there are about 80,000 soldiers,
1,200 tanks and 1,400 artillery pieces scattered throughout
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. Kosovo is a
province of Serbia that is dominated by ethnic Albanians who are
under siege. Six days of punishing NATO air raids have failed to
bring Milosevic to the peace table to sign a treaty with the
Albanian population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pressure is building for mounting a NATO ground
attack.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, said over the weekend that while NATO currently has no
plans to fight a ground war in Kosovo, military officials last year
determined that up to ``hundreds of thousands'' of troops might be
required in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., urged the Clinton administration and
NATO not to rule out sending soldiers to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have intervened and we must now decide what actions are
necessary to succeed,'' McCain said. ``We are in it. Now we must
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Lt. Col. Ralph Peters, one of the Army's leading
strategic thinkers until his retirement last year, told CNN Monday
that a ground attack would require a minimum of 40,000 to 50,000
NATO troops plus another 50,000 reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Adm. Leighton Smith, the commander of a NATO air
attack against the Serbian nationalists in neighboring Bosnia in
1995, said the number of ground forces would depend on the breadth
of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are trying to establish a safe area for refugees,
that's one thing,'' Smith said. ``If you are trying to expel the
Serbs from Kosovo, you will need an enormously larger force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we better be prepared to take all of Kosovo if the
situation turns south on us. We can never lose sight of the worst
case,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haas, a senior member of the National Security Council
during the Bush administration, said Monday that 100,000 troops
would be required to occupy a portion of Kosovo to create a ``large
humanitarian zone'' for refugees free of the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said that any NATO force forcibly entering Kosovo would
need to be armed with some of the U.S. Army's most sophisticated
weapons, such as M1A1 tanks that saw service in the 1991 Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the troops could be pulled from a force of 30,000 NATO
soldiers currently enforcing a peace treaty in Bosnia. But
transferring the soldiers could have a downside effect by
destabilizing Bosnia, where a fragile peace is taking hold, Haas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO troops currently in the region include about 12,000
soldiers _ 400 Americans _ in Macedonia. They currently are
training for entry into Kosovo as part of a peace settlement, but
not as a battle force.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, about 2,200 U.S. Marines are afloat on ships in the
Adriatic Sea, off the coast of Montenegro, the other state in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
