<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8670 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSION-CREEP-HNS &LR;      03-29 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSION-CREEP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FACES PRESSURE TO EXPAND MISSION IN YUGOSLAVIA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 News Analysis  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, stung by combat losses when he
expanded the mission of U.S. troops in Somalia in 1993, appears to
be resisting mounting pressure to insert U.S.-led ground forces
into Kosovo to halt Yugoslav reprisals against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Aides insisted Monday that the president will not permit
so-called ``mission creep,'' that is, changes and additions to
military goals, to occur in the current allied effort in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes will not be needed, they contended, because
prolonged air attacks will destroy enough Serbian armed forces to
persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt the
murderous ``ethnic cleansing'' of Kosovo that has sent tens of
thousands of frightened refugees streaming into neighboring
nations.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart reiterated Monday that
the Clinton administration has ``no intention'' of dispatching
ground forces into Kosovo in a hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, the military leadership of this country, NATO,
the political leaders of NATO, believe we can accomplish our
military objectives through the air campaign that's ongoing,''
Lockhart explained, adding: ``We have no intention of deploying
ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   But Key Republican senators _ Armed Services Committee Chairman
John Warner of Virginia and John McCain of Arizona, a GOP
presidential candidate _ have urged Clinton to consider deploying
troops. McCain said Sunday that the threat of ground forces may
help persuade Milosevic to yield.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of defeating the marauding Yugoslav assassination
squads in Kosovo with air power alone has also prompted some
administration officials to tinker with their descriptions of U.S.
policies.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last Thursday National Security Adviser Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger said, ``We do not have, as the president
indicated, an intention to put ground forces in Kosovo in a combat
situation. If some have suggested that we go further than (bombing)
and put an American or NATO ground military force into the region
to invade the region, that is something we do not intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a Sunday TV interview Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, seemed to soften that formulation by saying,
``At this point in time, there are no plans per se to introduce
ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments suggested to some experts that the administration
is giving itself some room to shift gears.
</P>
<P>
   William J. Taylor Jr., director of political military studies at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies here, predicted
Monday that ``the mission is changing. We are going in with ground
troops. It's only a question of when.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Lt. Gen. George Harrison said the introduction
of ground troops is only a matter of time if the operation is to be
``satisfactorily completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivo Daalder, a former Clinton administration adviser in the
National Security Council, says he thinks the president will opt
for ground troops but added that their rescue operation may come
``too late'' to help the imperiled Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Contingency plans prepared last fall by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) estimated that the allies would need
150,000 to 200,000 ground troops to subdue defiant Serbian forces
if a peace settlement could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have long had a reputation as tough guerrilla
warriors. During World War II Adolf Hitler deployed 10 divisions
with 250,000 crack Nazi soldiers to Yugoslavia in a fruitless
effort to subdue the anti-German Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already agreed in principle to dispatch 4,000
American troops to Kosovo. But they would enter only as part of a
28,000-member allied force that would implement the first phase of
a negotiated peace agreement between the Yugoslav Serbs, who are
Eastern Orthodox Christians, and the rebellious ethnic Albanian
Kosovars, who are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's refusal to negotiate a peace agreement triggered the
allied bombing campaign that began last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials vowed then that the goal was to bomb
Milosevic to the bargaining table and to limit his ability to kill
or expel the Kosovars. They were vague about any subsequent phase
in the mission.
</P>
<P>
   But over the weekend they acknowledged that the allied bombing
campaign had expanded from hitting strategic air-defense targets to
a second phase of attacks on Yugoslav ground troops, 300 tanks in
or near Kosovo and 40,000 Yugoslav troops that had massed on
Kosovo's borders last week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the officials avoided offering any public rationale that
might justify ``mission creep''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, for example, refused Monday to publicly label the
Yugoslav reprisals against the ethnic Albanians as ``genocide.'' He
also rejected critics' claims that the allied bombing had provoked
the escalated Yugoslav attacks on Kosovo's Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   And he rejected suggestions by some senators that the United
States should change its objectives by arming the ethnic Albanian
guerrilla organization, the Kosovo Liberation Army, which seeks
independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the start of his presidency Clinton had a disastrous
experience in Somalia with ``mission creep'' when he redefined the
reason U.S. troops were there.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1992 outgoing President George Bush had launched a
U.S.-led United Nations humanitarian relief effort in war-torn
Somalia to stem starvation. Two months after gunmen for a defiant
Somali warlord, Mohammed Farah Aidid, ambushed some U.N. troops in
June, 1993, killing 24 Pakistani soldiers and wounding another 54
Pakistani troops, Clinton dispatched 400 elite Army Rangers to the
east African nation, saying their goal was to capture Aidid and
subdue his warriors.
</P>
<P>
   That October, in a raid gone wrong, 18 elite Army Rangers were
killed and more than 70 wounded following a 16-hour fire-fight with
the Somalis in the back alleys of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's mission failed to capture Aidid, the president
ordered 15,000 additional U.S. reinforcements to Somalia to aid in
the withdrawal of all U.S. forces there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0330-CO     03-29 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-0330-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS KOSOVO HUMANITARIAN CRISIS DEEPENS, PRESSURE FOR NATO GROUND
TROOPS GROWS
 &HT;    With TROOPS-BOX-0330; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0330.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the humanitarian crisis deepening in Kosovo
after nearly a week of NATO bombing, American and NATO officials
continued Monday to reject the option of sending ground troops to
fight in the Balkans, even as a growing number of military experts
questioned the effectiveness of an air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic military bullet here,'' Defense Department
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Monday when questions arose at the
Pentagon about whether ground forces were needed to stop allied
officials what say is ``genocide'' being waged by Serbian troops
against ethnic Albanians who are fleeing Kosovo by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Even if NATO countries decided immediately to send in ground
forces to prevent further atrocities in Kosovo, ``they would not be
there tomorrow,'' Bacon added. ``It would take a long while . . . a
matter of weeks or more than a month before these troops were on
the ground doing a job.''
</P>
<P>
   According to NATO estimates, Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic has more than 40,000 Serbian troops in Kosovo, along with
400 tanks, 300 armored personnel carriers and 400 artillery pieces.
In addition, there are only 14 roads into Kosovo, many of them
mined.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would mount a light attack against this,'' Bacon said.
``It would have to be an extremely heavy and determined attack. It
would take time to organize such an attack.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the Persian Gulf War, the attack by NATO ground
troops was preceded by a 40-day air campaign. But Iraqi troops
suffered only 25 percent autorotation during that 40-day bombing
mission, according to Air Force reports following the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planners have estimated that between 200,000 and 300,000
soldiers would be needed in a ground war against Serbian forces in
Kosovo, Yugoslavia's southernmost province.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress has endorsed the NATO air strikes that began
last Wednesday, there is little support for sending U.S. soldiers
into battle in Kosovo. Consequently, President Clinton has asserted
from the beginning of the air strikes on Yugoslavia that he has no
intentions of sending American soldiers to fight a ground war in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And as thousands of ethnic Albanians streamed out of Kosovo on
Monday with tales of horror, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
insisted that the new phase of low-altitude NATO bombing of Serbian
positions in Kosovo would succeed in forcing Milosevic back to
peace talks to end the strife between Serbs and ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, the military leadership of this country, NATO,
the political leaders of NATO believe we can accomplish our
military objectives through the air campaign that's ongoing,''
Lockhart said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Haas, a former national security adviser in the Bush
administration and now director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution, suggested NATO must now consider putting
ground troops in Kosovo. ``At this point, I think the costs of not
escalating are greater than the risks of escalating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Ivo Daalder (CQ both), a former Clinton administration
national security staff member, said that without the intervention
of NATO ground troops in Kosovo, ``there will be nothing left by
the time we have won the war'' with a long bombing campaign against
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a lecturer at Georgetown University and
Columbia University and an expert on the impact of technology on
warfare, noted that the kind of bombing NATO is currently
conducting is ineffective against mortars, rifles and anti-tank
guns -- ``the weapons that are extremely effective in ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon also questioned whether the NATO air strikes could
destroy enough Serbian armor to equalize the battlefield to allow
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) to resume their opposition to the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could take a month to do that,'' he said. ``In the
meantime, there may not be a Kosovo to save.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
