<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-RECORD-COX     03-29 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-RECORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reaching new heights: Dow Jones finally closes above 10,000
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finally closed above 10,000 on
Monday after trading above that historic benchmark three times
recently, only to fall back.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's 1.9 percent gain to a new high was part of a
broad-based increase in market prices that lifted all major stock
indexes at least 1.5 percent (the Russell 2000 small stock index)
to as much as 3 percent (the technology loaded NASDAQ composite).
</P>
<P>
   The 103-year-old index first topped the 10,000 mark on March 16
and again on the 18th and 19th before dropping back
</P>
<P>
   each time. Such buying resistance at psychologically important
levels is not unusual, and analysts never doubted that the Dow
would eventually close above 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the final push to ``window dressing,'' a
stock buying phenomenon that occurs at the end of each quarter.
Mutual fund and other money managers typically load up on
high-performance blue chip stocks so their portfolios will look
good to clients and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Big gainers included General Electric, whose shares rose $4.18
3/4 to $112; IBM, $5.18 3/4 to $177.56 1/4; Wal-Mart Stores, $3.43
3/4 to $95, and J.P. Morgan, $2.93 3/4 to $125.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday's move was worth about three trade days of normal
volatility, so it wouldn't be a surprise to see prices move much
less rapidly over the next few sessions,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's
market analyst Paul Cherney.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's 10,000 achievement didn't quell the concern of some
analysts that the market's strength is still limited to too few
stocks, leaving too many others behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``While euphoria over Dow 10,000 could send the market higher
short term, the performance disparity between the largest companies
and the rest of the market argues for limited upside potential,''
said Bruce Bittles, market strategist for J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the military action in Yugoslavia has added a new element
of uncertainty to the market. While the bombing has not restrained
buying so far, Robinson-Humphrey strategist Robert S. Robbins said
the bombing has its risks, including a possible broadening of the
conflict to other Balkan states.
</P>
<P>
   Bond selling pushed the 30-year Treasury yield to its fourth
straight gain ahead of today's meeting of the Federal Reserve
policy making committee. Analysts said bond traders are still
worried the Fed will raise interest rates because of the economy's
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
