<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-COX     03-29 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rambling virus spurs paranoia about Net
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Melissa continued her relatively harmless but
irritating ramble across the globe Monday, the forces of Internet
order mobilized against her.
</P>
<P>
   The computer virus dubbed Melissa hit hundreds of thousands of
computers that use Microsoft Word software, threatening to clog
e-mail servers as it cloned itself and sent copies to 50 names
pulled off the address books of unwitting recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa did not destroy computer hard drives or freeze PCs, so
damage seemed limited to a handful of places where the surge of
copied e-mail overwhelmed servers temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa did trigger paranoia about the vulnerabilities of
the world's increasingly networked economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melissa is written so that it's easy for people to create
derivatives that are malicious,'' said Chris Rouland, of
Atlanta-based Internet Security Systems. ``The bar has been
lowered.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what might have been a knock-off of Melissa appeared
Monday, aiming at users of Excel software.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa should not be dismissed as harmless, not in an age when
business depends on quick communication, said Rouland, who directs
an ISS team that hunts for security risks. ``In many companies,
e-mail is mission-critical.''
</P>
<P>
   ISS makes software to protect companies from hackers who want
access to confidential information or to tamper with company data.
ISS also has software that will help a company assess its
vulnerability to attack, including by virus.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other software companies used the opportunity offered
by Melissa to issue press releases Monday touting their products to
defend against viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sudden spotlight on Melissa, viruses and virus
scares have become routine on the Net. A new virus rises into the
news only when it is widely circulated or especially destructive.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Smets, president of BellSouth's Internet unit, said the
company sees troublesome viruses every couple of months. ``Some are
just pains in the neck. Others could be catastrophic. It's
certainly an issue to be contended with.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger in Melissa was its ability to clone itself 50 times
over each time a recipient clicked on the attachment that came with
it. With that kind of exponential growth, a few generations could
produce massive numbers of e-mails and overload a mail server.
</P>
<P>
   So when Melissa arrived Friday, BellSouth engineers started
tinkering with the company's software for stopping junk e-mail _
also known as ``spam'' _ and devised a screen that would catch
Melissa. The new software went onto BellSouth servers at 3 a.m.
Saturday, Smets said. ``If we had not introduced this plan of
attack, we'd be dealing with a much larger problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Viruses have been around for decades, although the proliferation
of the Net gives them ever-greater reach. Viruses with names like
Concept, Wazzu, Form and Jerusalem have raised concerns, spurred
anti-virus efforts and disappeared. But Melissa deserved special
attention, because it was the first to efficiently use e-mail in
spreading itself, said Steve White, senior manager of anti-virus
research at IBM.
</P>
<P>
   White said it is hard to say exactly what Melissa's creator had
in mind. Perhaps the goal was to annoy a particular target or
perhaps to gain the satisfaction of causing a worldwide nuisance.
It might even have been an accident caused by an overconfident
engineer playing with code.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, virus writers are not the same people as those trying
to tap into Pentagon computers or rewrite the messages on the
Coca-Cola Web site. And there are only a few hundred people in the
world writing virus code _ ``No more than are writing graffitti in
a major city,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many viruses, Melissa was named by the people who are
trying to smother it. But in conferring the moniker, anti-virus
forces took a cue from Melissa's creator, who wrote what seems to
be the name Melissa into the virus's code.
</P>
<P>
   White has been at the forefront of anti-virus efforts since a
1987 virus, coined Christma Exec, took control of his computer,
tapped out characters in the shape of a pine tree and then wrote
``Merry Christmas.'' That virus clogged IBM's e-mail system.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, computer infections have continued to waft through
cyberspace, and anti-virus software has ballooned into a $1
billion-a-year business. The Internet has also expanded into a
multibillion-dollar medium carrying business transactions, as well
as personal messages.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is now involved with Norton, which makes anti-virus
software, in an effort to write an ``immune system'' that can be
delivered to computers via the Internet at the moment that a virus
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   And while Melissa proved an annoyance, White said the infection
only proves that the system is basically healthy. Business went on,
even as Internet companies tried to stomp out the virus and
educated consumers deleted the message that carried the virus.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring Enterprises, the region's largest Internet service
provider, reported no significant change in the number of e-mails
it carried Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always an interesting balance, to balance the functions
that are terribly useful with the risks,'' White said. ``So far,
the world has found a pretty good balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
