u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAURUS-REDESIGN-COX     03-29 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAURUS-REDESIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taurus toned down for 2000
 &HT;    Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four years ago, Ford took its best-selling Taurus to
the cutting edge of design.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the sales crown and suffering criticism for the
Taurus' looks, size and price, Ford is stepping back from the edge.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Taurus, unveiled today at the New York auto show,
stresses safety and comfort in a more-conservative-looking package.
The Taurus and its Mercury Sable twin, which will be unveiled
Thursday in California, are built in Hapeville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said they were reacting to customers in the
latest redesign. What the customers said they wanted was more room,
a larger and more accessible trunk, new safety features _ and no
more ovals.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial oval shapes in the rear window and
audio/climate control pod are gone, replaced by rectilinear shapes.
And there are more cup holders, including ones that accept coffee
cups with handles or expand to hold large soft drinks. Also
available are power-adjustable pedals to enable short drivers to
sit father from the steering wheel and still reach the accelerator
and brake.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fixed the biggest problems,'' said Jim Hall, vice
president of industry analysis with AutoPacific in Detroit. The
1996-99 model, while actually bigger than the version it replaced,
looked smaller. ``In the upper-midsize car segment, people are
looking for size.''
</P>
<P>
   That model had less headroom; a smaller, hard-to-get-to trunk;
and a higher price than earlier models. The appearance also was
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 model, Hall said, Ford addressed those problems. The
new car has more rear-seat headroom despite being the same size.
The trunk is larger, easier to load and has hooks for grocery bags.
The price hasn't been set yet.
</P>
<P>
   And the looks, Hall said, are subjective. Some people liked the
distinctive ovals, while others did not.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has added a number of new safety features _ both standard
and optional _ to a vehicle that already has achieved top scores in
crash-test ratings, said David T. Marinaro, Ford's chief engineer
for Taurus and Sable.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are a restraint system that includes seat belt
sensors and pre-tensioners, two-stage air bags, a crash-severity
sensor and side air bags that protect both the head and chest.
</P>
<P>
   A child-friendly interior trunk release will be standard on all
new Ford vehicles, the company's engineers said, to decrease the
danger of a child getting trapped in a trunk. The T-shaped handle
glows in the dark so it can be seen in a closed trunk.
</P>
<P>
   The two 3.0-liter engines get horsepower boosts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury Sable will have ``brand differentiation, but it is
essentially the same car,'' said Ford spokesman John Jelinek.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of the new vehicles already are being inserted on
the assembly lines at the Hapeville and Chicago plants. The new
cars likely will arrive in showrooms in October, later than most
2000 models.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans to begin production in August with a gradual
switchover from the current models during the summer. No shutdowns,
other than the customary one in July, are planned. The two
Taurus/Sable plants had been closed for a week in February to help
trim inventory of the '99s.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials insist they are not going to rejoin the race to
make the best-selling car in America, a title the Taurus lost two
years ago to the Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Taurus is Ford's bread-and-butter car, analyst Hall
said, and ``the timing couldn't be better'' for a redesigned model.
</P>
<P>
   The only new competition in the segment is the Chevrolet Impala,
but Chevrolet doesn't have the plant capacity to build enough
vehicles to challenge the top sellers, Hall said. The Camry and
Honda Accord, which both had more sales than Taurus last year,
don't have any significant changes planned until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming No. 1 ``depends on how bad Ford wants it,'' Hall said.
``It's doable, but at a price.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the sales race usually involves increased sales to
rental fleets and profit-cutting price incentives, Hall said. Both
tend to cheapen the brand name.
</P>
<P>
   What Ford appears to be doing instead is making the brand
stronger and better aligned with its market segment than it did
with the last redesign.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
