<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-JOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta job machine to hum, report says
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The road to Atlanta's future is paved with jobs _ and
job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will lead the country in job creation over the next 25
years with an estimated 1.8 million new positions, according to a
report released Monday by Newsweek magazine and Kaplan, a New
York-based careers and education firm.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix and Houston tied for second with 1.5 million jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Careers 2000 guide identified health law, geriatric law,
physical therapy, venture capitalism, computer security, network
specialists and secondary schoolteachers as some of the hottest
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Being the No. 1 job center over the next quarter century carries
a price, and labor and economic experts wonder if Atlanta can
handle it.
</P>
<P>
   With transportation, water and school systems already stretched
to the breaking point, observers wonder how Atlanta will be able to
accommodate 2 million more workers, not to mention their families.
And with severe worker shortages expected to continue, where will
the workers come from?
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has had low unemployment most of this decade, and
increasing home sales and construction and a steady influx of
residents have helped put the city at the top of the Careers 2000
list.
</P>
<P>
   University of Georgia economist Jeff Humphreys isn't convinced
Atlanta will reach that distinction because of the severe limits on
its transportation, water delivery and sewer treatment systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge is transportation and infrastructure,''
Humphreys said. ``We can invest more in public infrastructure. If
we do that, then the estimates (of being No. 1) can be obtained.''
But being No. 1 might not be anything to brag about, Humphreys
said.
</P>
<P>
   Renters, retirees and people looking for a simpler, more rural
way of life see only higher taxes and more congestion ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this forecast is correct, Atlanta will stem from Bremen to
the west, Athens to the east, Macon to the south and approach
Chattanooga to the north,'' said Humphreys, who has been tracking
Atlanta's growth since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawl will force employers into the suburbs to be closer to
workers and ``there will be greater use of alternative
transportation,'' Humphreys said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, such bragging rights will be a boon for
homeowners, worker-hungry small businesses and ambitious
careerists.
</P>
<P>
   State Labor Commissioner Michael Thurmond was pleased with
Atlanta's ranking but warned job growth isn't likely unless the
state has enough skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers throughout Georgia, especially in the Atlanta area,
already face a shortage of skilled workers to fill their current
job openings,'' Thurmond said. ``And the situation will only worsen
unless we develop a long-range strategy to develop a skilled and
well-trained work force.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Labor Department projects the number of jobs in
Georgia will grow by 1 million by 2006. Roughly 700,000 of those
jobs will be in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the new jobs will be in service industries and
about one in four will be in wholesale and retail trade. The
fastest-growing jobs include computer engineers, systems analysts,
electronic pagination system workers, physical therapists and
medical assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
