<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ROBBERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE'S POET, DENYING CRIME, IS CONVICTED IN SOUTH AFRICA
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Mzwakhe Mbuli, a musician and writer known as the
People's Poet of South Africa, was convicted of bank robbery
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate and his two assessors, who help him evaluate the
evidence, unanimously rejected Mbuli's claim that he had been
framed and concluded that he and two other men had used pistols and
a Russian hand grenade to rob a bank of $2,600 in a Pretoria suburb
on Oct. 28, 1997. Mbuli's lawyer said he expected a long prison
term.
</P>
<P>
   Mbuli, 39, became famous in the 1980s by declaiming his protest
poetry at the funerals of anti-apartheid activists killed by the
police. With his deep voice booming his grim lyrics over cheerful
township-jive Zulu guitar plucking, he became one of South Africa's
top recording artists, a regular at televised ceremonies and the
chief praise-singer at Nelson Mandela's 1994 inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrest in October 1997, Mbuli has been held without
bail, mostly in Pretoria's maximum security prison. He sat
stone-faced Monday during the 4 1/2-hour reading of the
magistrate's decision. His wife broke down crying, as did many of
his supporters, but there were no outbursts of threats against the
magistrate, as there were in the trial's early days.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Mbuli said to a radio reporter: ``I am still very much
innocent. In the environment of lies, the truth becomes a
stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   He is to be sentenced April 22. Mbuli said he would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, Mbuli argued that he had been set up by
someone who called him offering information about a 1996 shooting
in which two men riddled his car with bullets as he cowered beneath
the dashboard. Told to go to a mall in the Johannesburg suburb of
Waverly, he took his licensed gun and two friends along. When he
arrived, he said, a man threw an envelope in the car and told him
to drive off. The police quickly stopped him, found that the
envelope was full of money and, he argued, planted other guns and a
hand grenade in the car.
</P>
<P>
   He said it might have been done because he had information about
drug smuggling and gunrunning by important figures in the African
National Congress and had tried to turn it over to civilian
officials who oversee the police. The magistrate issued no finding
on that.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have kept their distance from Mbuli since
his arrest, but Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, Helen Suzman and many
musicians went to the court to show support.
</P>
<P>
   Mbuli's lawyers did demonstrate that the police had ignored
correct procedures for lineups. In addition, Mbuli, who is 6 feet 4
inches tall and a well-known figure to black South Africans, said
again Monday that it was hard to believe that no one in the bank
recognized him if, as the police contended, he robbed it unmasked.
</P>
<P>
   At his trial, Mbuli vacillated between days of animated denials
and days of tired, vague answers to prosecutors' questions,
especially about his claim that he was set up by someone protecting
important political officials. After the 1996 shooting, Mbuli
publicly accused drug dealers, KwaZulu/Natal warlords and rival
musicians of trying to kill him. Some musicians publicly fought
back, saying his wife's family might have done it.
</P>
<P>
   The two other men in Mbuli's car, Ben Masiso and Happy
Shikwambane, were convicted on the same charges Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
