</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-BIGDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York Times, Amazon.com make key strategic moves
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a busy day for two of the Web's most popular sites, The
New York Times on America Online and Amazon.com. While the Times
was busy consolidating, Amazon was busy expanding its empire.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, soldiering on in its never-ending quest to become
the Wal-Mart of the Web, announced plans to open an auction area
that will compete with eBay, the Web's most popular auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon also announced plans to obtain a 50 percent stake in
Pets.com, the largest pet supply company on the Internet. ``This is
a marriage made in heaven and clearly positions us as the online
category leader,'' gushed Pets.com CEO Julie Wainwright in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pets.com sells everything from cat toys to ferret hammocks. For
the moment, Pets.com will remain a stand-alone site, although it
could very easily be incorporated into the main Amazon.com site,
which sells books, music, videos and gifts, along with toothpaste
and acne medicine from a previous acquisition, Drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to become to commerce what Yahoo! is to
content,'' said Jupiter Communications digital commerce analyst Ken
Cassar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon hasn't officially gone over to general merchant status
yet. They've got kind of a confusing business model. At the core
it's a retail business model _ they're still making most of their
money from selling products _ but they are looking for other
revenue streams as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Published reports say Amazon will aggressively market its
auction area within its retail space. For example, Beatles
memorabilia up for auction will be featured on Amazon's music
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Amazon has no plans to integrate Drugstore.com or
Pets.com into its ``one-click ordering'' system, which permits
repeat shoppers to order without having to fill out forms.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com is currently linked off the Amazon.com start page,
which certainly drives traffic, but Cassar says access to the
``one-click'' database is vital for long-term success and will
happen eventually. A recent Jupiter consumer survey revealed more
than one-quarter of potential online shoppers abandon the online
ordering process because they don't like repeatedly filling out
order forms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The New York Times, a strong daily news presence on
America Online since June 9, 1994, told AOL readers the site will
be ``moving mostly to a World Wide Web format,'' according to a
March 26 online letter to readers from Editor Rich Meislin.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in mid-April, the Times on AOL will mirror The New York
Times Web site (www.nytimes.com) rather than use AOL's proprietary
software to develop an entirely different product, according to
spokeswoman Lisa Carparelli.
</P>
<P>
   Carparelli says the Times' new format would allow advertisers to
use the same methods of targeting customers on AOL they currently
use on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also provide advertisers with graphic capabilities
that were previously unavailable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the industry has evolved, so has our relationship with
AOL,'' Carparelli said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to offer only the Web-based version to AOL users
was probably inevitable. Currently, the Times maintains two
separate online departments, one for the Web and one for AOL. It
appears to be simple good business sense to cease what appears to
be a duplication of efforts.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new Web-based format probably spells the end of
many of the Times' unique AOL features such as its message boards,
weekly news and arts chats, and the entertainment and news
archives.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's Sunday magazine, previously an AOL exclusive, will
eventually move to the Web site. An internal memo went out this
week to Times free-lancers who monitor the message boards and chat
rooms describing the dismantling of the AOL services. The memo said
the Times would try to find new assignments for some of the
free-lancers. There was no word if any full-time jobs will be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In his online message, Meislin told readers that AOL members
will still be able to access the Times for free after a one-time
registration. Web users have always been required to register,
while AOL members were not. One-year archives of news stories from
The Times with full articles and the paper's famous crossword
puzzle will be available to users for a nominal fee.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
