<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-LIGHTENBER     03-29 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-LIGHTENBERG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chen demoted as Perez becomes No. 5 starter
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Much to the chagrin of Kerry Ligtenberg
and Bruce Chen, the Braves' pitching situation became much clearer
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg will miss the entire season after deciding to undergo
``Tommy John'' surgery to repair ligament damage in his elbow. The
surgery will be peformed by Dr. James Andrews next Tuesday in
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, projected as the Braves' fifth starter, was optioned to
AAA Richmond because of a poor spring and is being replaced in the
rotation by friend and fellow rookie left-hander Odalis Perez. The
rotation is now set, with Tom Glavine facing the Phillies on
Opening Day, followed by Greg Maddux, John Smoltz, Kevin Millwood
and Perez.
</P>
<P>
   And Mark Wohlers apparently reclaimed the closer's role with
another strong outing Monday. He'll be joined in the bullpen by
John Rocker, Rudy Seanez, Mike Remlinger, Mike Cather and Kevin
McGlinchy.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg, examined Monday by Braves team orthopedic surgeon
Joe Chandler, was given the option of waiting a few more weeks to
test the arm again, but after almost three weeks of waiting, he was
ready to go ahead with surgery. He may be able to return as soon as
this time next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's better that I do it now than the middle of the
season,'' Ligtenberg said. ``That would be missing the rest of this
season and next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg will return to Atlanta for several weeks after the
surgery so the Braves can monitor his recovery, then he'll go home
to Minnesota to continue his rehabilitation. He could return to
Atlanta in early July to begin throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be the only saving thing about this; I'll get to
see my family and friends,'' Ligtenberg said. ``At the same time
I'd like to get back to playing as soon as I can. . . . .
(Chandler) wants me to take it slow. That'll be tough for me. I
have a tendency to go crazy and do too much. . . . . There are guys
who aren't able to come back from this. I look at it as a challenge
to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves reliever Pedro Borbon needed two full years to
recover from the same surgery in August 1996, and minor-leaguer
Damian Moss is still working his way back from surgery last June.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg expects to need only 12 months, maybe less. If the
ligament is only partially torn, the surgery will be less
complicated and the recovery time quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the best case,'' Ligtenberg said, ``to just go
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's main problem this spring was control, which is supposed
to be his strength. After five appearances this spring, Chen had a
6.00 ERA with 23 hits allowed and 12 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to put too much stock in spring training,'' Cox said.
``But in this case, he's not exactly where we want him to be. If he
goes with us he's only going to get a spot start here and there in
the first month and it makes sense to get him on a regular program
in AAA where he starts every fifth day guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Chen, the Braves can use Perez as a starter or out of the
bullpen, where he spent last postseason with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense to go this way,'' Cox said. ``This has
happened to Glavine, Smoltz, Maddux at his age. This is no
different than what they went through. . . . . Bruce is a great
kid. It's harder on me than him because I love the kid. I know he's
going to be an outstanding pitcher, he's going to be a big winner.
He's just not quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen was caught a little off guard by the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I didn't have a good spring,'' Chen said. ``I tried to
do my best. I can't be mad at myself because I really worked hard
in the offseason. I prepared myself real well for this opportunity.
The thing is, once you get a taste of this you don't want to go
back. . . . . I feel I can pitch here, but I didn't show that in
spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing might have been telling Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad because we got to be friends,'' Perez said. ``We've
been together for the last four years. He told me he's not going to
get mad with me because it's a baseball game and something can
happen. He told me, `You've got the opportunity now, go for the
opportunity.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was a starter in AA Greenville last year before the Braves
moved him to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy because I thought they were going to give me an
opportunity in relief and now I'm a fifth starter,'' Perez said.
``That's the opportunity I wanted. I just got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
