<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NY-PROTEST-NYT     03-29 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NY-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN-AMERICANS RALLY TO PRAISE NATO EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y. N.J., Ohio)   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(jw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wrapping themselves in the flags of their homeland
and of the country where they make their home, more than 3,000
Albanian-Americans marched from the United Nations to the Serbian
mission here Monday, praising NATO's bombing campaign over the
situation in the Serbian province of Kosovo and calling for ground
troops to support the air war.
</P>
<P>
   As they waved the Stars and Stripes and wore Albania's
doubled-headed black eagle on a red background on their backs,
several protesters burned or tore apart the blue, white and red
flag of Yugoslavia, of which Serbia is the major entity. When
police officers stopped them from setting another flag aflame on
Fifth Avenue, the protesters stomped and spat on it instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was ripping Serbs,'' said 12-year-old
Christopher Broui.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Lloyes DioGuardi of the Albanian-American Civic League
spoke to the demonstrators, who filled the sidewalk for more than
two city blocks on the edge of Central Park. ``It is a just war and
it is a war we hope all Americans will begin to understand has an
effect on them,'' Mrs. DioGuardi said.
</P>
<P>
   With their signs and slogans, the demonstrators compared
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, who sent in troops
against ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo, to Hitler. They chanted,
``Stop the Genocide,'' and ``Arm the Kosovo Liberation Army,'' the
separatist rebel group in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional crowd was dotted with small children wearing
camouflage outfits, and teen-agers carrying representations of
coffins, many of them infant-sized, as they marched up Third Avenue
from 42nd Street to 72nd Street, then back down Fifth Avenue to the
Serbian mission at 67th Street. Old men wore the off-white
skullcaps that symbolized Albanian pride, while younger men wore
berets with the insignia of the rebel group, or Yankee caps showing
their adopted culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only hope we have is from the American people,'' said
Xhedat Mekuli, 36, a maintenance worker who was born in Yugoslavia
but now lives in the Bronx. ``They have feelings for human rights.
I think they're the only people who can help our country, Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters expressed strong support for President Clinton
and NATO, but said that without ground troops, the air campaign
would simply hasten Milosevic's apparent efforts to cause ethnic
Albanians to flee Kosovo. Some said they want NATO to provide arms
to the ethnic Albanians; dozens of teen-agers even signed papers at
the rally volunteering themselves for service in the rebel group
</P>
<P>
   ``To have freedom, some people must die,'' said Rep. James
Traficant Jr., D-Ohio, who has introduced a resolution in Congress
calling for an independent Kosovo, at the U.N. portion of the
41/2-hour rally. ``But there is no going back. We must have a free
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd had personal connections to people in the zone
where fighting is taking place. The headquarters for a World Wide
Web site (www.kosova.com) that many Albanian expatriates relied
upon for news has been burned and now has only old information,
several protesters said.
</P>
<P>
   Milot Krashiqi, a construction worker living in Yonkers with his
wife and four children, said his father told him by telephone three
days ago that the streets of Klina, his village, were littered with
bodies. Monday morning, on CNN, Krashiqi said, he saw his father's
name on a list of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Selimaj, 47, who was born in Montenegro and came to the
United States 28 years ago, said he and his parents had not slept
well in days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no phone lines in and out, no power, no nothing, no
postal service _ it's a mess,'' said Hartim Kaba, 22, of Wayne,
N.J. He said he worried about his parents, who returned to Kosovo
for a visit a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we're doing something to stop the massacring going
on in Europe right now,'' Kaba said. ``If this stops the killing
even 1 percent, saves one or two lives, it's worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
