<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-RANKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval remains the players' choice
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe it's just coincidence. Maybe it's just that time
of year. A week away from the Masters and an occasion for game
faces to be put firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   Or, then again, it could be The Duval Effect.
</P>
<P>
   Now that David Duval has shot a 59, won more than $2 million
before April 1, won 10 events in 33 tries, won a Players
Championship, and officially taken over No. 1 in the world
rankings, what's left for the mere mortals of the PGA Tour to do?
</P>
<P>
   Practice, practice, practice.
</P>
<P>
   For a Monday at a PGA Tour practice range, this one at the TPC
at Sugarloaf in Duluth, Ga. for this week's BellSouth Classic had a
lot of talent on it. Players such as Billy Mayfair and Paul
Stankowski. Jose Maria Olazabal, the 1994 Masters champion. Heck,
even Japan's Jumbo Ozaki, who passed up the Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Duval won't be here until Wednesday for the Pro-Am, possibly
late today. Until then, all the rest of them can do is hit more
balls and marvel at what Duval has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to win Augusta next week,'' Stankowski decided,
firing a ball into the breeze. ``He's our only shot at winning the
Grand Slam. . . . It's hard to beat a guy who's got all the skills
and the mentality to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair, who won twice last year and is making his first
appearance at the BellSouth, could not agree more. Dethroning Tiger
Woods _ ironically, an absentee this week as defending champion _
in the rankings just made official what everyone already knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had this kind of stuff since the Nicklaus and
Palmer days,'' Mayfair said. ``It's amazing. And he's won from
Hawaii to Florida on all kinds of golf courses. Even if Tiger had
finished sixth Sunday, David still should have been No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing Augusta, Mayfair figured Woods had been dethroned from
his position there, too, the 1997 win withstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If David isn't favored,'' said Mayfair, ``who else could you
pick?''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Atlanta on a foreign exemption, Ozaki said of Duval
through his interpreter, ``Oh, yes, he is the strongest player. ...
How to beat him? I don't know. You should ask the younger U.S.
players.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you beat Duval?
</P>
<P>
   ``Take him out at the knees,'' Stankowski grinned.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
