u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-JAPAN-MARUYAMA-CO     03-29 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-JAPAN-MARUYAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maruyama's game has 'no weaknesses'
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shigeki Maruyama just might have been teasing an
American reporter who required a translator last week at The
Players Championship. The best player in Japan is perfectly capable
of such a put-on.
</P>
<P>
   Maruyama was asked: Why did you want to play in Atlanta? To face
some conditions that will better prepare you for Augusta National?
</P>
<P>
   Hal Tsunezumi, Maruyama's manager and translator, asked the
question in a lengthy manner. Maruyama, grinning some and frowning
some, gave a lengthy answer.
</P>
<P>
   Tsunezumi then turned and pronounced, ``He said, `I don't know.'
''
</P>
<P>
   There was chuckling, and Maruyama's 29-year-old face brightened.
It was the same look that has been painful to U.S. players on the
PGA Tour. One minute they are smiling and bowing with Maruyama at
the first tee. The next minute they are three down.
</P>
<P>
   The MVP of December's Presidents Cup, Maruyama tore through the
U.S. team, going 5-0. Even those who know Maruyama and his game
well were stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised he was 5-0, but the guy can really
play,'' said Brian Watts, who has played with Maruyama on the
Japanese Tour. ``In Japan we have a match play tournament, and he's
won it and finished second or third the other time, so the guy does
really well head-to-head. ... He's got a game with no weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also hard to miss on the golf course and easily discernible
from the other Japanese players. Puffing on a cigarette and often
walking too briskly for his caddie, Maruyama is more intense than
his perpetual off-course grin would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really good at the golf conversation,'' Maruyama said.
``Otherwise, I just smile a lot. ... I can't be a poker face all
the time. I make birdie, I'm happy. That's why I'm smiling all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Andersen Consulting Match Play, Maruyama defeated Steve
Stricker, Justin Leonard and Loren Roberts before losing to
eventual runner-up Andrew Magee.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody should be surprised at Maruyama's achievements outside of
Japan. He tied for 14th at the 1996 British Open, then 10th in
1997. Playing in his first PGA Championship at Winged Foot in 1997,
he was 23rd. Maruyama played six PGA Tour events in 1997, earning
$111,781 and finishing 161st on the money list. He won 37 college
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Bad outings like the 74-84 performance in The Players
Championship last week will not keep Maruyama from targeting his
fantasies. He still wants to finish in the top 10 in all the
majors. He wants to meet and play golf with his hero, Michael
Jordan. Maruyama has a ``23'' on his bag.
</P>
<P>
   Americans Jeff Sluman, Davis Love III and Fred Couples, who have
befriended Maruyama, are trying to set up a round with Jordan,
perhaps while near Chicago in August before the PGA Championship at
Medinah, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   How many shots to give Jordan? Maruyama holds up five fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking up golf at 10 years old, Maruyama found his spark by
watching American television. The freeze footage for the young
Maruyama became Tom Watson walking up the 18th fairway at Augusta
National, savoring an approaching victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment that Tom Watson was coming up the hill, he saw that
scene and said, `I want to be like him,''' Tsunezumi said. ``All
the patrons so happy and clapping. That's the reason he decided to
be a professional golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH CLASSIC
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Thursday-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: TPC at Sugarloaf, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV/Radio: 3-6 p.m. Thursday-Friday, USA; 2-4 p.m. Saturday,
NBC; noon-3:30 p.m. Sunday, NBC. WCNN (where available), 2-4 p.m.
Saturday, 1-3 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: Weekly badges, $50 sold through today (404-249-6400).
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
