<HEADER>
A8705 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-COLLEGE-COLUMN-LA     03-29 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLLEGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S ZITO DRAFTS NEW PLAN _ WITHOUT FAMILY TIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He entered last year's Major League Baseball draft
with a plan. It backfired.
</P>
<P>
   So Barry Zito has developed a new strategy. Zito, a junior
left-hander at USC who is college baseball's hottest pitcher, is
going it alone into this year's negotiations. He's told his father
Joe to sit this one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to chill out,'' Zito said. ``I'm 21. It's going to
be my name on the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   There probably will be a lot of figures on that piece of paper.
Zito has struck out 46 in his past three starts _ all wins _ and is
5-2 with a 3.29 ERA for the Trojans. He struck out 16 against
Oregon State on March 12, then repeated the feat on March 19
against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Zito, who is scheduled to start against Cal State Northridge on
Friday night at Dedeaux Field, struck out 14 in a complete-game win
over Washington State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is pitching well because he has put all the
distractions of 1998 out of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Zito, who is from El Cajon, pitched at Pierce College last year
after transferring from UC Santa Barbara following his freshman
season. He went 10-2 and then was drafted by the Texas Rangers in
the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Zito represented his son in negotiations and held firm on a
$350,000 request for a signing bonus. Barry Zito, a 6-foot-3,
195-pounder who throws in the mid-90s, said his father's
representation even before the draft may have made him slip to the
third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deterred a lot of teams (from drafting me),'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce home games were a sideshow when Zito pitched. Twenty to
30 scouts would show up on the Woodland Hills campus for his
starts; it was impossible for him not to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head is in the game now,'' he said, ``as opposed to all
that external stuff. Now I can just put (the scouts) out of my
head. I get fired up for every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Being at USC, the defending national champion, hasn't hurt
Zito's development, either. He credited his recent success with
long-tossing between starts. Long-tossing is when pitchers stand
about 330 feet apart and play catch. It's supposed to develop arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Pierce it was hard to find guys to throw 330 to
340 feet away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zito knows that when the season ends, so does his career as a
Trojan. He said he will definitely sign with whatever team drafts
him in June, and he hopes to go higher than the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly out of here after this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of nowhere: On the opposite end of the prospect spectrum
from Zito is CSUN left-hander Jim DeBiase, but his performance so
far this season has been just as pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   DeBiase, a Chatsworth High graduate who also pitched at Pierce,
beat Sacramento State on Sunday to stop the Matadors' six-game
losing streak. He improved to 7-2 after starting the season in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, DeBiase talked about his surprising success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mainly concentrating on hitting my spots,'' he said, ``and
basically trying to get a lot of ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBiase appeared in 20 games last year for CSUN, but only six
were starts. He struggled with his control, walking 42 in 541/3
innings. Before Sunday, DeBiase had only 27 walks in 602/3 innings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Win one for Gillespie: Head coach Mike Gillespie could win his
500th game at USC tonight if the Trojans can beat San Diego State
at Dedeaux Field. His record at USC is 499-283-2. Today also marks
the 25th anniversary of Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA head coach Gary Adams won his 1,000th game earlier this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
