<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8711 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND30-COX     03-29 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Down on the (hog) farm not such a pretty picture
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In North Carolina the hogs outnumber the people. Raised on
factory farms in sheds as long as football fields, the Tarheel
porkers live on slatted floors that allow their waste to drop into
huge cesspools. Hog sewage is then pumped into outdoor ``lagoons''
the size of Olympic swimming pools, producing clouds of stink that
rise up and cover whole counties. Health risks accompany this
assembly-line approach to swine farming, in particular when lagoons
collapse and pour tons of sewage into the state's waterways,
triggering massive fish kills. George ($2.95) investigates the
price we pay for the other white meat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More prim than glam: Now that the Academy Awards show has
devolved into a fashion event, we can dispense with movies and talk
about clothes. People ($2.99) does just that, calling the gowns of
the Oscars ``Sexy, Sexier, Sexiest'' and devoting 40 pages to an
unending parade of what appear to be prom dresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Life of the camera: No longer king of the dramatic image, Life
($4.99) nonetheless still recognizes wonderful photography. The
current issue announces the winners of a Life-sponsored photography
contest named for famed Life contributor Alfred Eisenstaedt, who
helped create the modern picture magazine. In Zed Nelson's
prize-winning essay on gun owners, printed in Time last July, we
see Mike, a shopper at a Dallas gun store, posed with his infant in
one hand and his pistol in the other. Max Aguilera-Hellweg is
another winner for his starkly lit tableaux depicting experimental
gallbladder surgery conducted by robotic devices. Also memorable is
Adam Brown's image of a massacre in a dappled forest in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Killer bugs: In Atlanta ($3.50) Vincent Coppola profiles C.J.
Peters, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's intrepid
hunter of killer viruses. Peters waded into Ebola-stricken villages
in Africa and watched a colleague die after nicking himself with a
scalpel during an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Any relation to Francis Ford? The peripatetic Coppola also
contributes to Men's Journal ($3.95) this month, with a report on
the rapidly crumbling nightmare called Hanoi. Here Coppola is
served snake and hard-luck tales by American expatriates, and the
bar of choice is the Apocalypse Now.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where's Kevin Bacon? An amusing foldout chart in Dossier
($3.95) demonstrates the web of associations between the members of
Atlanta's power elite and shows that no two movers and shakers down
here are separated by more than a few handshakes. Some of the lines
in this flow chart are a bit iffy, however. (Evander Holyfield and
Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs' connection is based on the fact that
they own property on the same street.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Atlanta-based Holiday Inn has its own
handsomely produced corporate magazine, available in every room,
called Navigator (free to guests) with the motto: ``Leave the
towel. Take this magazine.'' In the April-May issue is an account
of that pre-Columbian Irish explorer St. Brendan the Navigator and
a tribute to that perennial American icon, the cowgirl, and her
evolution from Dale Evans to the Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
