<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT     03-29 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARDS FROM A PATCHWORK SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
 (fb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite all the talk of joint ventures _ the revelation last
week that Helmut Lang and Patrizio Bertelli of Prada were quietly
putting their heads together, while everyone else in fashion was
swayed by the drama of who would control Gucci _ the fall
collections that recently ended in Europe and New York will go down
as the most individualistic in many years.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the intrepid fashion seeker _ and bad news
for anyone still asking, crankily, ``But what about hemlines next
season?''
</P>
<P>
   Very few women can be coerced into spending $4,000 for green
leather trousers embroidered with silver petals (which is what a
pair from Gucci will cost) simply because some fashion hierophant
declares it a trend. So designers must be practical idealists,
proposing sensational, one-of-a-kind styles. No woman in this era
of anonymous-looking clothes actually needs a pair of leather
trousers done up like a Mexican saddle. But she might be enticed to
 &UR; want &LR;  one.
</P>
<P>
   As Tom Ford said several nights before his Gucci show earlier
this month, over a dinner of pasta and fish in Milan: ``Two or
three years ago, `the look' is what you were going after. Now it's
about a piece, and each person can put that piece with a T-shirt
from the Gap or with her Prada pants.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the lady is no sucker.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, where fashion can magnetize vastly different groups of
people, whether Dutch, German or Japanese, and where arty boutiques
like Colette and L'Epicerie and Zampa sell everything from clothes
to ashtrays, there is, naturally, a tendency to push the frontiers
of style. ``In Paris, none of the collections looked alike,'' said
Jeffrey Kalinsky, an Atlanta-based retailer who plans to open a
store in Manhattan in August. ``Nothing is interesting if you can't
make it individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this does not mean you can't deduce from some 250
collections in New York, London, Milan and Paris at least five or
six themes that, come fall, won't look as if a bunch of hysterical
tailors got together under the bright lights of high fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K, OR WHY GO THERE?
</P>
<P>
   No matter what you think of the millennium buildup, it
represents a marvelously tempting opportunity _ Las Vegas rolled
into Hollywood with a dash of NASA thrown in. Well, it is
irresistible. But don't think that just because a few designers
toyed fantastically with lunar white and silver leather that anyone
really plans to go there. Nobody is going to the moon, as Karl
Lagerfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who interpreted the millennial fever best did so with
color and ingenious decoration. How else to explain the imperial
scarlet at Yohji Yamamoto and Gucci, the faded autumnal hues at
Cerruti and Prada, the deliciously arcane ruffles at Tuleh, and the
impression that even the most chronically sober designers, like Rei
Kawakubo of Comme des Garcons, had run their clothes through a car
wash of glitter? It's party time _ that's the millennial message.
Martine Sitbon adorned her minimalism with streamers of popperlike
ribbon. Christian Lacroix came up with terse skirts appliqued with
something resembling ecstatic bar graphs, though it was his
black-bonneted models who made one laugh. They were straight out of
Balzac.
</P>
<P>
   Very intriguing. But don't be surprised if a year from now, when
the fun is over, designers abandon all the decoration.
</P>
<P>
   THE JACKET REVISITED
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought the suit was passe _ upstaged by knits and
utility anoraks _ along come Calvin Klein, Josephus Thimister and
Lagerfeld to give the jacket a fresh verve. Both Klein and
Lagerfeld, in his collection at Chanel, cut them close to the body,
using felted wool or shearling to convey a sense of texture,
especially over glossy tops. Thimister revised the safari jacket,
using waxed cotton and tighter sleeves for an almost shrunken look.
The idea is to get beyond the basic jacket.
</P>
<P>
   EVENING BECOMES ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite electric. American designers like Oscar de la
Renta and Michael Kors gave evening clothes the most realistic spin
_ as cozily elegant sportswear. That means cashmere and cable knits
worn with ball skirts and, from de la Renta, who rarely gets his
social clientele wrong, slim silk trousers and good old American
parkas. European designers showed variations _ Ford with cobweb
knits over trousers, and Gilles Dufour at Balmain with full skirts
and sleeveless shearling tops. But the message was the same: don't
look too dressed up.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS AND CRAFTS A LA MODE
</P>
<P>
   Miuccia Prada started the trend for clothes with a handmade arty
look, and this season there was that lovey-dovey feeling all over
Milan, as designers fell for ruffles, peasant blouses, wallflower
prints and bed jackets _ admittedly a frumpy notion, but well done
by Lagerfeld at Fendi, where they were made out of sheared fur dyed
in sweet-pea tints. The trend has charm and, retailers say, staying
power.
</P>
<P>
   DENIM DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden jeans looked fine,'' said Linda Dresner, the
Park Avenue retailer, who also has a store in Birmingham, Mich.
``We saw them at Helmut Lang. We saw them at Chloe.'' Indeed, one
saw them everywhere _ from Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's two-tone versions with
tartan, to Jean Paul Gaultier's hilarious super-wide jeans with a
trompe l'oeil effect, to Stella McCartney's glossy silk jeans at
Chloe. Designers may be acknowledging the global trend toward
casual dressing, but there's a catch. This is denim with a couture
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   FUR AND LEATHER UNBOUND
</P>
<P>
   To say that fur and leather were themes of the fall collections
tells only part of the story. Not only were they everywhere; their
high-hatted appeal was constantly played down, the luxury skins
used like common cloth. No style offers more imaginative
possibilities for the independent fashion seeker, whether it's a
sleek cocoon of shearling by Veronique Branquinho for Ruffo, a
light-as-air sheared mink shift from Fendi, or Alexander McQueen's
sensational fur poncho, a look that more or less sums up the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Designers and fashion editors used to sound incredibly fatuous
when talking about the new woman _ who couldn't be dictated to, who
had her own style. But today the woman has actually caught up with
the cliche, to the amazement of fashion pros. ``She surprised us,''
said Nicole Fischelis, fashion director of Saks Fifth Avenue. ``She
gets it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
