<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT     03-29 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAHARISHI FIGHTS BACK AGAINST COPYCATS 
AFTER KENAR, A COMEBACK   
 PRADA AND LANG WILL COOPERATE
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardy Blechman, the owner of Maharishi in London, one of
fashion's newly hot labels, said he had hired lawyers to
investigate and possibly bring charges that designers are copying
his work. Blechman's designs, inspired by his interest in yoga and
named for the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi, a spiritual teacher, have
influenced men's wear for two years, said Vincent Ehly, the senior
buyer of designer men's wear for Barneys New York. ``More than any
other collection, it sets the tone for our sportswear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for men and women, Maharishi is sold by Barneys, Nylon
Squid and Saks Fifth Avenue, all in New York, and by Fred Segal in
Los Angeles and Collette in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to approach people in New York,'' Blechman said,
speaking of two companies that he refused to name that he said have
been particularly blatant copiers. While it is difficult for
designers to collect damages in lawsuits involving knockoffs,
courts have sometimes ruled in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   What has made Blechman's designs so appealing to customers _ and
copiers _ is that they tap into two of fashion's strongest trends:
meditation-inpired clothing, and sports and utility wear.
Flamboyant embroidery and beading add decoration and romance to the
clothes in a post-minimalist era.
</P>
<P>
   Companies as small as Nova and as large as Polo Ralph Lauren and
Donna Karan are now making clothes that come from sports, martial
arts and meditation, and many more are drawing upon military
uniforms. But when Blechman began four years ago, fashion was
sleeker and tidier. As the pendulum has swung in his direction,
business has taken off. ``Things are really mad here at the
moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AFTER KENAR, A COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   Is Kenneth Zimmerman by another name still the same? Zimmerman,
a Seventh Avenue habitue, hopes not. After placing Kenar in Chapter
11 bankruptcy last year, he has quietly resurfaced with the labels
Kenny Z and Emma Black. Last week, he was in his new one-room
office, where he had once leased the entire 25th floor. Like many
high fliers forced to touch down, he was philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks I'm nuts to be going back into business, but
if you love the business and know it, then what else can you do?''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman is now manufacturing in New York instead of Asia,
which allows him to fill orders in about two weeks rather than
several months, he said. The roughly 250 employees of Kenar have
been whittled down to 10 at his new company.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Black is the more expensive of the two lines, with dresses
at around $100. Kenny Z has inexpensive sportswear like black
stretch trousers or wool tank tops trimmed with velvet ribbon,
trendy additions to be cast off after a season. The collections
will be in stores for fall.
</P>
<P>
   The business is worlds removed from Zimmerman's defunct Kenar
label, which, though it sold midpriced clothing, was positioned as
a designer brand. There was a boutique on Madison Avenue, and
advertisements with supermodels like Linda Evangelista.
</P>
<P>
   PRADA-LANG JOINT VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Prada and Helmut Lang have entered into a joint-venture
agreement to promote the Helmut Lang label globally, it was
announced on Friday. Details of the arrangement were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Patrizio Bertelli, the chairman of Prada and the husband of
Miuccia Prada, was in Hong Kong on Monday and could not be reached
for comment. Lang, who is Austrian but is based in New York, said
through a spokeswoman that he was happy and called Bertelli ``a
brilliant businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   The venture puts two high-fashion, luxury competitors in the
same camp, a strategy Bertelli championed when he surprised the
fashion world last year by announcing he had purchased a 9.5
percent interest in Gucci. Gucci gave Bertelli a cool welcome, and
earlier this year he sold his stake to LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis
Vuitton, pocketing close to $140 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
