<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweating for success in Suwanee
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANEE, Ga. _ The Atlanta Falcons began rebuilding Monday, but
not via free agency or the draft. Instead, the offseason
conditioning program began at the team's training facility in
Suwanee as 47 of 59 players lifted weights and ran.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is strongly encouraged, as coach Dan Reeves believes
it fosters camaraderie, and helps reduce injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, 22 starters only missed a combined 20 of 352
possible starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly to build an endurance base you can maintain for 16
games,'' said recently-signed backup quarterback Danny Kanell.
``It's set up differently for different players so running backs
and quarterbacks aren't doing the same workout as linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable absences included running back Jamal Anderson, who lives
in Salt Lake City, free safety Eugene Robinson, who lives outside
Seattle, and cornerback Ray Buchanan, who works out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Judge Michael Moore Monday denied the request by former Falcons
wide receiver Tony Martin to delay until next year Martin's trial
on five counts of money laundering and one count of conspiracy. The
trial will begin May 3, in Miami. Moore did not rule on whether to
sever Martin's trial from the drug trafficking trial of Martin's
childhood friend, convicted drug dealer Ricky Brownlee. Reeves said
the Falcons might be interested in re-signing Martin depending on
the disposition of Martin's case. Dolphins' coach Jimmy Johnson has
met with Martin....Unrestricted free agent offensive lineman Greg
Bishop signed a two-year contract with the Falcons Monday. The deal
is believed to be worth about $4 million. Atlanta also re-signed
tackle Jose Portilla and tight end Ed Smith to two-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
