<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International Soccer: Italy braces for 'A' showdown
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Italian Serie A race is one of the hottest in years, and
Sunday's showdown in Rome between AC Milan and hosting Lazio could
go a long way toward sorting out what has been a very tight
five-team battle.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on top the standings and trying to win the Serie A for
the first time in 25 years, is finally realizing the fruits of a
$40 million offseason spending spree that yielded Italian striker
Christian Vieri and Marcelo Salas of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   And AC Milan, which dominated Italian soccer during most of the
1980s and early '90s, is clearly back in the picture after missing
out on European competition the last two years. AC Milan, in third
place with 48 points, seven behind Lazio, still has a number of
familiar faces on hand, such as defender Paolo Maldini. But German
striker Oliver Bierhoff has given the club a big scoring boost and
injected a badly-needed fresh approach to the country's most
glamorous club.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentina, which trails Lazio in second place with 50 points,
also has a key road game on Sunday, traveling to Inter Milan, which
has fallen on bad times. After the resignation of interim manager
Mircea Lucescu last week, the club announced that former Juventus
coach Marcelo Lippi would take over next season. That may not help
them now, as Inter is in ninth place and in danger of missing out
on Europe altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia: Players protest
</P>
<P>
   Around 40 Yugoslav soccer internationals have denounced last
week's NATO air strikes on their country, and some of those in
Spain are planning to boycott matches in protest. All Euro 2000
qualifiers in and around Yugoslavia Saturday and Wednesday have
been postponed, but several players returned home to look for their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Girondins Bordeaux defender Nisa Savaljic left the French club
to return to Montenegro, where his wife and two children fled after
the bombings began. And in London, Sasa Curcic of Crystal Palace
picketed 10 Downing Street, the home of British prime minister Tony
Blair.
</P>
<P>
   But new Atletico Madrid coach Radomir Antic called on his
countrymen based in Spain to call off the boycott and play, saying
their actions would not change matters.
</P>
<P>
   England: Scholes, Keegan heroes
</P>
<P>
   After just one game at the helm of England, new manager Kevin
Keegan may be interested in removing the term ``interim'' from his
description. England, which routed Poland 3-1 Saturday in a Euro
2000 qualifier at Wembley, got a hat trick from Paul Scholes, who
lately has had trouble cracking the Manchester United lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan had said that he would only coach for four games and
return to managing London club Fulham full-time. But Fulham
president Mohamed Al-Fayed said after the Poland win that a
full-time England job for Keegan would be ``my gift to the
nation.'' Keegan said: ``There might be a solution somewhere.'' . .
. Chelsea coach Graham Rix has been sentenced to a year in jail for
sex offenses against a 15-year-old girl. Ray Wilkins has replaced
him as manager Gianluca Vialli's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   France: Lizarazu injures knee
</P>
<P>
   French and Bayern Munich defender Bixente Lizarazu will be out
for at least six months after straining knee ligaments. Without
him, as well as the injured Zinedine Zidane, the French were held
to a 0-0 draw with Ukraine in Paris Saturday in Euro 2000 action.
France, which plays Armenia Wednesday, has called up Monaco striker
David Trezeguet to add some scoring punch. France is tied with
Iceland with eight points in Group 4, two points behind Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Fight, then win
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich teammates Carsten Jancker and Markus Babbel got
into a training match fight before Germany's Euro 2000 qualifier
against Northern Ireland, but it didn't have an adverse effect as
Germany won in a 3-0 rout in Belfast to tie Turkey for first place
in Group 3.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Gonzalez scores four
</P>
<P>
   After a humiliating World Cup and a poor start to Euro 2000
qualifying, Spain dumped on Austria 9-0 Saturday, as Real Madrid
striker Raul Gonzalez had four goals. The loss prompted Austrian
coach Herbert Prohaska to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Juventus duo strikes
</P>
<P>
   Juventus forwards Filippo Inzaghi and Antonio Conte scored for
Italy, which defeated Denmark 2-1 in Euro 2000 qualifying. Denmark,
the 1992 champions, is mired near the bottom of Group 1 and is all
but eliminated. . . . Lazio manager Sven Goran Eriksson has signed
a three-year contract extension keeping him on board through 2003
for an estimated $6.7 million, a figure that nearly doubles his
current salary.
</P>
<P>
   Around the globe
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday Times of London is reporting that officials from
Japan and South Korea lavished members of the FIFA board of
directors with such gifts as laptop computers and video games to
curry favor for their votes for hosting the 2002 World Cup. Both
countries will co-host, and FIFA member David Will of Scotland said
he was surprised by the nature of the gifts. ``It was small beer
compared to International Olympic Committee,'' he said. . . . Greek
manager Anghel Iordanescu resigned after Norway took a 2-0 win in
Euro 2000 qualifying, with both goals coming from Manchester
United's Ole Gunnar Solsjkaer. The new man in charge is Vassilis
Daniel. . . . Three Hong Kong men have been sentenced to 22 months
in jail each for their role in local match fixing scams. . . .
Former French World Cup organizing committee chairman Michel
Platini, recently named a special adviser to FIFA chairman Sepp
Blatter, not surprisingly backs his mentor's plans for a biennial
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Women: Mexico tough vs. U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women beat Mexico 3-0 at the Rose Bowl on Sunday
afternoon, but not as easily as in the past. After a scoreless
first half, Julie Foudy drew first blood for the Americans and
Kristine Lilly scored twice in the last six minutes to kick off a
domestic exhibition tour for the U.S. leading up to the Women's
World Cup this summer.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Meola tears knee ligament
</P>
<P>
   U.S. goalkeeper Tony Meola, traded to Kansas City in the
offseason, could miss half the season after tearing a knee ligament
earlier this month. Without him, the Wizards have given up seven
goals in two games, including a 3-0 loss to Chicago Saturday, and
have gone an MLS-record 460 minutes without scoring, dating back to
last season. . . . Cobi Jones, Clint Mathis and Greg Vanney scored
shootout goals for Los Angeles in a 1-0 win over Dallas. However,
Galaxy players were booed when they left the Rose Bowl field after
the game. The Galaxy, which led MLS with 85 goals last year, has
scored only one in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
