<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSION-CREEP (Washington) _ President Clinton, stung by combat
losses when he expanded the mission of U.S. troops in Somalia in
1993, appears to be resisting mounting pressure to insert U.S.-led
ground forces into Kosovo to halt Yugoslav reprisals against ethnic
Albanians. A News Analysis. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In less than a decade, the
internationalist majority in Congress has weakened, and Republicans
and Democrats have changed places as chief advocates and opponents
of using U.S. military might in regional conflicts such as the one
in Yugoslavia. We take a look at the shifting political sands. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ If NATO ground forces are ordered
to fight Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic's drive to kill or
expel ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, military experts say that as many
as 200,000 troops, many of them American, would be needed for the
mission. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Washington) _ Dealing a blow to
affirmative action supporters, the Supreme Court refuses to review
a program once used by the Dallas Fire Department to promote more
blacks, Hispanics and women. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STUDENT-FEES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to
decide whether state-run universities can dedicate a portion of the
activity fees they collect from all students to subsidize groups
that pursue political and ideological goals that some students
oppose. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-COMPUTING (Houston) _ The spread of the Melissa virus can
be traced to one very bad, very unsafe habit among Windows users:
sending Microsoft Word documents as e-mail attachments. A News
Analysis. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-PROSIGNIA (Houston) _ Compaq Computer announces a change
in its small and medium business program, expanding the way it
builds and distributes its new Prosignia line of computers. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY-PROTEST (Asuncion, Paraguay) _ A look at how the
opposition in Paraguay managed to compel President Raul Cubas to
resign and their newly discovered tactic: street protests. By JOHN
OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Republican congressional
majority left town for a two-week recess patting itself on the back
for reaching a budget agreement. But the thing is a fraud. It
doesn't address the tough question of which domestic programs to
cut and it provides a huge tax cut nobody knows how to pay for. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-FINAL (St. Petersburg, Fla.) _ Coverage of the NCAA
Championship game between top-ranked Duke and No. 3 Connecticut.
Tonight's contest will decide the national championship. By BILL
SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   NBA-ROCKETS (Los Angeles) _ Savoring an eight-game winning
streak and awaiting a matchup with the Los Angeles Clippers on
Tuesday night, the Houston Rockets are the hottest team in the NBA.
By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS-ROSTER (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ The Houston Astros pull a
couple of surprises as they release veteran pinch hitter Dave Clark
and reliever Xavier Hernandez in an effort to reach the 25-man
roster limit for next week's season opener. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
