<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside pro tennis: 'Williams show' a tearjerker for dad
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to blame Richard Williams for reveling in his family's
good fortune. The father of Venus and Serena Williams was flashing
large signs to the crowd and the TV cameras Sunday as his daughters
played it out in the final of the Lipton in Key Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   One message said, ``Welcome to the Williams show,'' and another,
``I told you so.'' The latter apparently referred to his prediction
of three years ago that Venus and Serena would be Nos. 1 and 2 in
the world some day.
</P>
<P>
   And in the middle of the match, won by Venus 6-1, 4-6, 6-4,
Williams once walked out of the stadium completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to cry,'' he said. ``I felt too ugly to
be out there crying. What was going through my mind was all the
problems we've had in tennis, bringing the girls up. . . . all the
gang members.. . . I was saying, 'Look where you are today.' It was
so difficult for me to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams reared his daughters in the ghettos of Compton, Calif.,
before moving them to Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., and he loves to
tell the story of the sisters hitting tennis balls with the volley
of gunfire sounding in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters didn't seem as emotional about their historic match,
the first final between sisters in WTA Tour history.
</P>
<P>
   Said Venus, ``In the end, we go home, we live life.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Serena, ``The family comes first, not a game that's going
to last 10 years at the most. Why would I want that to come between
someone who has always been a very special friend to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of their beliefs as Jehovah's Witnesses, the Williams
family doesn't display tennis trophies around their home. The
Waterford crystal trophy that Venus won Sunday at the Lipton will
be the first, however. It stands for something different.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The United States is seen as the Davis Cup underdog against
Great Britain this weekend, but the Americans have the better
head-to-head records. Todd Martin, up to a career-high No. 8 this
week, is 3-1 against No. 7 Tim Henman, 4-1 against No. 11 Greg
Rusedski. Jan-Michael Gambill is 2-0 versus Henman and has never
played Rusedski. Jim Courier is 1-0 vs. Henman, 3-0 vs. Rusedski.
The Brits, playing in Birmingham, England, have the homecourt edge.
. . . Pete Sampras, though uninvolved with the Davis Cup match, got
on the nerves of British captain John Lloyd last week when he
referred to Great Britain as a ``half-British, half-Canadian
team.'' Rusedski was born in Canada of British parents. ``He's
played for me for four years; he's never let his country down,''
Lloyd retaliated.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
