<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STUDENT-COX     03-29 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STUDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albanian student reflects on life in Kosovo
 &HT;    By Ginger Livingston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ A high school exchange student from
Kosovo living in the Albemarle region of North Carolina said he
supports NATO's bombing of his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The student, a 17-year-old ethnic Albanian, said he hopes the
bombing continues, even though his family has been unable to escape
the war-torn Yugoslavian province. Anything that will destroy
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic's ability to kill
Albanians can only be a good thing, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The young man, who spoke with The Daily Advance of Elizabeth
City, N.C., on the condition his real name, location and host
family not be disclosed, described the persecution and oppression
his family and other ethnic Albanians have endured during the past
decade from Milosevic's Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   It was that persecution that led the United States and other
NATO nations to begin bombing Kosovo, Serbia and other parts of
Yugoslavia last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to explain (why Serbs repress Albanians),''
said the student, who for purposes of this article, chose to be
called ``Valon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to explain the color blue to a blind man.
It's just a big hatred between people.''
</P>
<P>
   An uneasy alliance between Serbia and the Albanian majority in
Kosovo existedthrough World War II and the Cold War, until
Yugoslavia began unraveling in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions rose in Kosovo after its majority _ 90 percent Albanian
population _ began seeking what they had enjoyed to a limited
degree before World War I and during the reign of Yugoslavia's
Communist dictator, Josip Broz Tito: autonomy. Albanians and Serbs
living side by side had never much liked each other, yet they had
learned to be civil to one another. And in some instances, they had
even struck up friendships, Valon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then Slobodan Milosevic came into power,'' he said.
``(Albanians) were kicked out of school and most parents lost their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic accomplished this attack on Albanians by pandering to
Serbian nationalism, Valon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legend (created by Milosevic) that Kosovo is the heart
of Serbia and that without Kosovo, Serbs are nothing,'' Valon said.
</P>
<P>
   Valon was about 9 years old when Milosevic began persecuting
Albanians. Because he was a child, Valon didn't really mind being
prohibited from going to school. Hebecame aware his parents weren't
working and that his family was growing poor. Because his family
and others joined together to start home schools, Valon and other
Albanian children were able to receive an education.
</P>
<P>
   Valon's parents tried to make a living for the family by
starting their own businesses. According to Valon, The Serb
government in Kosovo forces Albanian businesspeople to pay three
times as much in taxes as Serbian businesspeople. Albanians also
have to pay twice as much for telephone and electrical services, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Milosevic came to power, Valon's city was a popular
tourist destination, attracting thousands of Germans and other
Europeans. After the Serbian dictator came to power, Albanians
became targets for extortion by Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to go out and hang out with friends, but you don't
have a chance because of the police,'' he said. ``If they see you
have a nice car or something, they pull you and say `give us
money.' If you don't give it, you get killed or beaten to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Valon says he experienced this treatment firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15 or 16, he said, he and his girlfriend were pulled
over by four Serb policemen. The policemen searched the teens and
their car looking for money. When they realized Valon and his
girlfriend had none, they began harassing Valon's girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Valon said he tried to stop them, but the four men beat him so
badly he was hospitalized for more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   That beating was not the first Valon endured at the hands of
police. When he was 13 or 14 years old, Valon participated in a
protest against Serbian oppression. When the police moved in to
break up the demonstration, Valon was among those severely beaten.
A news crew from CNN videotaped the injuries to his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just pain. If you want to fight for something with all of
your heart, you endure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence, Valon said he did not want to leave
Kosovo, even to participate in a foreign exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what could happen and it's better to share the pain,''
he said. ``But, (my father) said you have to go, you have to see
what is school, what America is like and what freedom is like,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Valon said he now realizes his father knew the violence was
escalating and was sending his son to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Valon managed a quick telephone call to his parents prior to the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear over the telephone the (warning) sirens. They
were scared and my mother was crying. Their one message (to me) was
'stay where you are,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the current dangerous situation in his homeland,
Valon said if he could, he would immediately return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful not knowing what happened with your parents, with
your friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his arrival in North Carolina, Valon's host mother
(who also asked not to be identified) discovered the young man kept
a lot of money with him. She said when she told Valon to leave his
money at home, he looked at her with apprehension, but complied.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, during a trip to Norfolk, Va., Valon
questioned her about how many police she saw in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said depending on where you lived you would see one, maybe
two or three, or none during a day,'' she said. ``He told me he
would see at least 300 to 400 police a day in Kosovo,'' she said.
Valon then explained to his host mother how crucial money is to
survival in Kosovo, and how the police extorted money from the
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Valon's host mother said despite the violence he has witnessed
and endured, Valon is a remarkably well-adjusted, bright, loving
young man with a good sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents have instilled all the good qualities a young man
should have,'' she said. ``He's a very outgoing person, but you
could tell from the beginning he was apprehensive. He has hard
feelings but his parents have instilled in him the value of the
preciousness of life. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   His host mother began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be able to meet his family and tell them how
much I appreciate (them) sending him. I know it took so much love
for them to send him here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Valon arrived in the Albemarle region, most people had
never heard of Kosovo. Since tensions in Kosovo continue to
escalate, he has had people ask him questions. He has also spoken
to several high school classes about the war.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes most people are sympathetic to his people's
plight and are more understanding of the need for the United States
and NATO to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Valon said he was extremely touched by President Clinton's
speech explaining his reasons for ordering the bombing. He said he
feels Clinton truly understands his people's suffering.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the United States and NATO continue the bombings long
enough to convince the Serbian people they have much to lose by
keeping Milosevic in power.
</P>
<P>
   And Valon hopes Albemarle area residents pray for his family and
the people of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston writes for The Daily Advance, Elizabeth City,
N.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
