<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich wants to move GOP with his priorities
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Out of office just a few months, former U.S. House
Speaker Newt Gingrich says he's planning a return to the grass
roots _ stumping to have his ideas become planks in the Republican
Party platform.
</P>
<P>
   In his first local appearance since leaving Congress, Gingrich
said this fall he will begin speaking at county, district and state
GOP meetings. Those talks, and a book due out early next year, will
lay out an agenda Gingrich concedes may take a decade to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich made his remarks Monday at a meeting of the Cobb
County, Ga. Chamber of Commerce Chairman's Club, whose members pay
a minimum of $5,000 to join.
</P>
<P>
   The top priority, Gingrich said, is reforming the Social
Security system. Gingrich again outlined a proposal he first
floated a year ago: Allow workers to put 2 percent of their pay
into a self-directed investment account. The so-called Social
Security Plus program would preserve Social Security without a tax
increase and without a cut in benefits, Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more importantly, it means that the poorest person in
Atlanta, when they go to work and pay a FICA tax, will end up as a
saver and investor,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he also will push for lowering the cost of
government so that a person's total tax bill, including local,
state and federal taxes, is no more than 25 percent of his income.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the most government should take in peace time,''
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the cost of government means privatization and
modernization, he said. ``You can't just take a meat ax to
things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirdly, he said, ``The U.S. has to learn to lead the world.''
The former speaker criticized President Clinton's handling of the
Kosovo crisis, saying Clinton hasn't yet told the American people
what U.S. goals are for involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're sitting in Bosnia and nobody is killing each other.
Does anybody really think that is healing? These are people who
have been killing each other for 600 years. What do you think is
going to happen three weeks after we leave?'' Clinton ``clearly''
intends to put troops in Kosovo, Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who recently became a senior fellow at the American
Enterprise Institute, resigned from Congress in January following
the Republican Party's poor showing in the November elections. He
was an Atlanta-area congressman for 20 years, including the last
four when he was speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also is forming a consulting firm and has created a
political action committee, Friends of Newt Gingrich, to supply
funding to fellow Republicans. He and his wife, Marianne, still
live in Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
