<SLUG> BC-PARAGUAY-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAGUAYANS USE PROTESTS TO EXERCISE POWER OVER POLITICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay _ Struggling to describe this historically
tranquil, landlocked South American nation, humorist P.J. O'Rourke
once wrote that ``Paraguay is nowhere and famous for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paraguay's reputation for passiveness may be coming to an
end. Last week, violent protests, which broke out after the
assassination of Paraguay's vice president, helped to topple the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked by the bloodshed, President Raul Cubas abruptly resigned
Sunday night, after just seven months in office. The angry
demonstrations turned into joyous celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got fed up and took to the streets,'' said Soledad
Villagra, a human-rights activist in Asuncion, the Paraguayan
capital. ``These were young people fighting for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez Macchi, the new president and former Senate leader
who took the oath of office Sunday night, began negotiations Monday
with legislators to form a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators already are at odds over how long the new
president should remain in power. Members of the ruling Colorado
Party said Gonzalez Macchi should finish Cubas' five-year term,
which expires in 2003, while the opposition leaders insisted on new
elections within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Cubas and the army general whose release from prison last year
sparked Paraguay's political crisis were granted political asylum.
Brazil allowed Cubas entry, and Argentina gave political asylum to
former Gen. Lino Oviedo, a close friend of Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo had received a 10-year jail sentence for leading an
aborted coup attempt in 1996. However, he was freed just days after
Cubas was elected last year. In response, legislators began
impeachment proceedings against Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was led by Vice President Luis Argana, leading many
observers to blame Cubas and Oviedo for his murder. But police have
turned up no evidence linking them to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a fifth person died of gunshot wounds received during
a melee that erupted Friday night when police and army troops tried
to disperse thousands of anti-government protesters. More than 100
people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that the violence was the key'' to Cubas'
resignation, said a western diplomat. ``When the blood started
flowing, he was getting blamed for all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Paraguayans consider the demonstrations a civic
triumph _ a shining moment of people power, following years of
defeat and dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1860s, for example, Paraguay went to war against
Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay and lost huge chunks of territory and
nearly half of its population. To protect itself, the nation turned
inward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has been isolated from the rest of the world for
140 years,'' said a European diplomat. ``The people who ruled were
not democratic. They were authoritarians.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest-lasting strongman was Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, whose
34-year regime earned him the nickname Tyrannosaurus. By the time
he was ousted in a military coup in 1989, most opposition leaders
were either in jail or exile.
</P>
<P>
   Even when democracy was established with free elections in 1993,
the Colorado Party, which has ruled for half a century, won the
presidency, and many Stroessner holdovers remained in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   There was an outbreak of protests in 1996 to Oviedo's coup
attempt. But the murder of Argana last week touched off clashes
that were far more intense and cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   Villagra, the human-rights activist, saw the clashes as proof of
a new society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paraguay is not a boring and timid country. It is a repressed
country _ which is different'' he said. ``But this was a wake-up
call that shows people can exercise much more power.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
