<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-OHIO-OLYMPICS-COX     03-29 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OHIO-OLYMPICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio group investigates possibility of making bid for 2012
Olympics
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Imagine the Greater Dayton area as part of a
regional Olympic village, with judo at the University of Dayton
Arena, wrestling at the Nutter Center and tennis at the ATP Tennis
Center in Mason, near Kings Island.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the vision of Cincinnati 2012, a group that wants
to bring the 2012 summer Olympic games to the Cincinnati region,
including Dayton and Columbus, Ohio, Indianapolis, Ind., Louisville
and Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by the group and released Friday concluded
that the idea is feasible, although some new sports facilities
would have to be built. The group plans to submit a detailed bid to
the U.S. Olympic Committee by March 31, 2000; the committee is to
choose a U.S. candidate city in fall 2002. International Olympic
officials will then select the site for the 2012 summer games
sometime in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a realistic chance of winning,'' said
Cincinnati 2012 President Nick Vehr, who resigned from Cincinnati
City Council to spearhead the effort. He called the region ``the
ideal location'' for the games.
</P>
<P>
   NBBJ Architects of Columbus and Anderson Consulting of Atlanta,
which worked on the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, came up with a
preliminary plan which would use the new Bengals stadium for
opening and closing ceremonies as well as soccer, the new Reds
stadium for baseball, Ohio Stadium in Columbus for athletics and
RCA Dome in Indianapolis for basketball. The plan also suggests
using the Nutter Center for wrestling and the UD Arena for judo.
</P>
<P>
   Vehr said he's had preliminary conversations with officials at
the proposed sites, but there have been no firm plans for using the
venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it would be very positive,'' said Maureen Pero,
director of the Downtown Dayton Partnership. ``I'm assuming they
would use our venues, and they'd be able to take advantage of our
hotel and hospitality industries.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they weren't mentioned in the study, Dayton's planned
minor league baseball stadium, riverfront area and bikeway system
could be used by Olympians, too, Pero said.
</P>
<P>
   The study said a new 32,000-seat arena, a new aquatics facility
and a 100,000-seat track and field stadium would be needed in the
region to accommodate the summer games.
</P>
<P>
   Vehr said the group has privately raised more than $2 million of
the estimated $7 million it would take to get the project to the
stage of being in the running as the U.S. candidate city.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati has stiff competition: Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles,
New York City, San Francisco, Tampa and Washington/Baltimore also
are vying to be the U.S. candidate site.
</P>
<P>
   Vehr said Cincinnati's cause is helped by the recent revelations
of lavish gifts being given to international Olympics authorities
by officials in Salt Lake City during the site-selection process.
``Cities are going to be selected on a level playing field'' and
the process will be more carefully scrutinized in the scandal's
wake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vehr said the area would benefit from an Olympics by getting
``the greatest influx of tourism and convention dollars that'll
ever occur in the history of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
