<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEALTH-COX     03-29 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Downing of plane might give Russian intelligence something to
study
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For decades, technology sleuths at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base have torn apart and studied
Russian-built warplanes to learn how they work _ and how to defeat
them.
</P>
<P>
   Now it might be Russia's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Russian counterparts to American foreign technology analysts are
undoubtedly eager to get their hands on pieces of the U.S. Air
Force F-117 Stealth fighter that crashed in Yugoslavia Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic turns over the wreckage
to Russian intelligence experts, they will comb it for clues to the
attack jet's vaunted radar-evading capability.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force spokesman Monday downplayed the service's concern
about Russia's access to the wreckage but admitted ``there's always
a concern'' when military technology falls into potentially hostile
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. no longer views Russia as an enemy, but Russia is
aligned with Serbia in opposing NATO's military actions. It also
exports many weapons, including anti-aircraft systems.
</P>
<P>
   The twisted, burned wreckage of the F-117 might yield little
useful information, or it might give up secrets that could make
Russian weapons more effective against Stealth _ an essential
feature in every new combat plane the U.S. has built or planned.
</P>
<P>
   For example, videos aired by Yugoslav television over the
weekend showed some large pieces of the aircraft exterior still
intact. The black jet's exterior skin and coatings are made of
special materials that absorb or scatter radar. Those pieces could
now be analyzed for their composition and tested against Russian
radars.
</P>
<P>
   The F-117 was the first aircraft lost by NATO forces since the
beginning of their air campaign against Yugoslav forces last week.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials still weren't saying Monday whether the
F-117 was downed by anti-aircraft fire. Citing unnamed U.S.
officials, some news reports said a surface to air missle made a
``really lucky'' hit, while others said a Yugoslav air defense
radar was able to track the jet.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it could mean Russia has already learned how to penetrate
the veil of stealth to at least some degree: Serbia's air defense
systems are Russian-made.
</P>
<P>
   The Aeronautical Systems Center at Wright-Patterson managed the
development and production of the F-117 in the 1970s and `80s, but
a spokeswoman referred questions about the downed jet to the Air
Combat Command.
</P>
<P>
   A command spokesman could not say Wednesday how concerned the
Air Force is about Russia's ability to learn much from the
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a concern about your highest technology falling
into enemy hands, but it's not our primary concern right now,''
said Air Force Lt. John Hutchinson, a spokesman for the Air Combat
Command at Langley Air Force Base in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said stopping Serbian aggression is the command's top
concern right now.
</P>
<P>
   He sought to downplay the likelihood that Russia will glean any
secrets from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the video footage we've seen, there really doesn't
seem to be much of the aircraft left,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the chance to study actual pieces of a Stealth aircraft can
only help Russian engineers improve whatever anti-Stealth
technology they may already have developed.
</P>
<P>
   At Wright-Patterson, the National Air Intelligence Center has
made a science of exploiting foreign aerospace technology since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the Korean war, our guys went in and grabbed pieces of
crashed MiG-15s,'' NAIC spokesman Rob Young said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, he said, a team from the then-named Air Technical
Intelligence Center used hand grenades to blast the wreckage of a
downed jet into pieces small enough to carry away in helicopters.
The pieces were spirited back to Wright-Patterson, where analysts
studied them and drew conclusions about the Russian-designed
fighter's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of work still goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Young said NAIC's ``exploitation center'' at Wright-Patt has
three Russian-built MiG-29 fighters, similar to the five Yugoslav
MiG-29s shot down by NATO warplanes over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   The NAIC planes were part of a fleet of 21 MiG-29s the U.S.
government bought in 1997 from the cash-poor former Soviet republic
of Muldova.
</P>
<P>
   Young said NAIC would not comment on what it might know about
Russia's foreign-technology efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are things that are universal,'' he said, but
he declined to speculate on how Russia might try to exploit the
wreck of the F-117.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
