<HEADLINE>
CHARMING YOUNG AUTHOR AT A LOSS FOR WORDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; 's London publicity tour coincided with last
week's London opening of ``Gods and Monsters,'' so  &UR; Ian McKellen &LR; ,
star of the movie, decided to bring the former White House intern _
they'd met at the Vanity Fair Oscars party a few days before _ to
the premiere as his date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at home and didn't have a date,'' he told the BBC. ``She
was coming to London and I thought, we want to give her a good
welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do seem to have a knack for picking unavailable men,''
Lewinsky told  &UR; Armistead Maupin &LR; , a close friend of McKellen's who
happened to be in London at the same time for the Festival of the
Word, an international literary event. Maupin, introduced to
Lewinsky at a reception after the movie's premiere, said she was
``very gracious and self-effacing'' and seemed to be ``a
tremendously good sport.''
</P>
<P>
   She told him that she finds herself speechless when people come
up during signings, as they often do, pour out their problems and
want her to save their lives. ``There's nothing I can do for
them,'' she said. If she could be honest, she told Maupin, she
would say, ``You're going to have to look somewhere else, honey.
I'm just as f_ up as you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said she was longing for the book tour to be over so
she could ``get back to Beverly Hills and have lots and lots of
therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, the Jewish Bulletin of Northern California
reports on ``Lewinsky's latest confession: Her  &LR; matz &LR; o balls are
`inedible.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO LEARN TO WAG YOUR TAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Matt Weinstein &LR;  and  &UR; Luke Barber &LR; 's new book, ``Work Like Your
Dog'' (Villard; $22.95) espouses consideration of dogs as role
models.
</P>
<P>
   A dog chasing a bone, for example, doesn't let a setback or
failure ruin its day. Dogs ``approach their work with not only
dedication, loyalty, discipline, sensitivity and love, but also
with joy, enthusiasm and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the dog's experiences on the down  &LR; side, rolling around
``in cow poop, dead fish or any other disgusting matter,'' the
authors say that ``many of us can relate to this kind of experience
in our own workday.''
</P>
<P>
   (Our caveat: Workers emulating dogs should keep in mind that
many of the standard canine greeting forms, as applied to
co-workers, may result in sexual harassment suits.)
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``Animal Attraction'' by  &UR; Roy Feinson &LR;  (St. Martin's;
$13.95) claims there's an animal archetype for every person, and
provides a series of tests to allow humans to identify their animal
counterparts. The author has determined that  &UR; Woody Allen &LR;  is a
snake,; &LR;  basketball coach  &UR; Pat Riley &LR;  is a sable; &LR;  and  &UR; Newt &LR; 
 &UR; Gingrich  &LR; is a warthog.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The Food and Drug Administration has approved the first
ulcer drug for horses. Gastric ulcers are common in horses in
``stressful environments,'' says the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOCAL LOOKERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In early celebration of the millennium, Architectural Digest is
out with its 100 Years of Design issue. To save Bay Areans from the
trouble of flicking their fingers through its 474 pages, Personals
has compiled a list of local lights (including places and former
local lights) mentioned as design icons or connoisseurs of style:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maya Angelou &LR; ;  &UR; M.F.K. Fisher &LR; ;  &UR; Czeslaw Milosz &LR; ;  &UR; Ansel
Adams &LR; ;
 &UR; David &LR;  and  &UR; Jackie Allswang &LR; ;  &UR; Bernard Maybeck &LR; ; the Ahwahnee;
 &UR; Julia Morgan &LR; ;  &UR; Michael Taylor &LR; ;  &UR; Nathaniel Owings &LR; ;  &UR; Natalia &LR; 
 &UR; Makarova &LR; ;  &UR; Paul Vincent Wiseman &LR; ; and  &UR; Clint Eastwood &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESTING IN PEACE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sylvester Stallone &LR;  has joined 50 members of Parliament and
celebrities campaigning for a permanent memorial to  &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Diana &LR; , reports the British magazine Sunday People. ``If she had
been American,'' said Stallone, ``a garden of remembrance with a
memorial plaque would have been erected within three months of her
death.''
</P>
<P>
   _ That New York tribute to  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR;  will be on April 23 at
St. Patrick's Cathedral, officiated by Cardinal  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; O'Connor &LR; . Organizers told the New York Daily News that
 &UR; President Clinton &LR; , who had ``expressed interest in attending
DiMaggio's funeral before learning that it would be a small, family
affair,'' will be invited. The newspaper said that &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Simon &LR;  may be there to sing ``Mrs. Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Balkans are people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michelle Phillips, entertainer and foreign affairs analyst, on
``Politically Incorrect.''
</P>
