<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-NYT     03-29 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER STUDENT ACTIVITY FEES REACHES SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Wis., Texas., Va.)  (fb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A nationwide dispute over student activity fees at
public universities reached the Supreme Court on Monday, as the
justices agreed to decide whether students have a constitutional
right to keep their money from going to groups whose political
messages they find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   This case, from the University of Wisconsin, represents one
skirmish in a war that is being fought on campuses and in
courtrooms around the country by politically conservative students
who object to a portion of their mandatory activity fees going to
environmental, feminist, social action or gay rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Five law students at Wisconsin, who described themselves as
conservatives and Christians, objected to 18 of more than 100
organizations that received cash grants from the student
government. The students won their suit both in the U.S. District
Court in Madison and in the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   These courts said the objecting students were in the same
position as union members who are entitled under Supreme Court
precedent to withhold the portion of their dues that goes to
support the union's political agenda. The First Amendment protects
the students against compelled speech, the lower courts said. Other
courts, including the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a 1992
case from the State University of New York, have ruled that
students could be required to support activities that contributed
to a ``marketplace of ideas,'' including ideas they did not like.
</P>
<P>
   In its Supreme Court appeal, the University of Wisconsin said
the 7th Circuit decision misconstrued the issue and ``undermines
the traditional role of universities as centers of free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Many universities share Wisconsin's system of imposing a
mandatory student fee and using a portion of it for various student
activities. The Supreme Court, in a 1995 case from the University
of Virginia, held that it was unconstitutional to exclude a
Christian student newspaper from eligibility for a share of the
activity fund there.
</P>
<P>
   That decision, Rosenberger vs. Rector and Visitors of the
University of Virginia, raised but did not resolve the question of
what rights individual students had to refuse to help subsidize an
undesired message.
</P>
<P>
   The issues have arisen at both private and public universities,
but since the Constitution applies only to government behavior, the
court cases have dealt only with public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In the Wisconsin case, Board of Regents vs. Southworth, No.
98-1189, the university is arguing that the lower courts failed to
apply the logic of the Supreme Court's decision in the University
of Virginia case. The court in that case said that by its
distribution of student activity fees, the university had created a
type of public forum, in which discrimination on the basis of
message was constitutionally forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for the new case, Wisconsin is arguing, is that
students whose fees go to support a panoply of viewpoints within a
public forum are not being compelled to support any one message.
Rather, their fees support the forum itself, in which they and
anyone else may speak. ``Learning to sort through, and at times
turn off, the multiplicity of ideas that find expression on a
university campus'' is a valuable part of the educational process,
the university's brief said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money at stake per student is small, under $10 a
semester, according to the university. Most of the fee of several
hundred dollars a semester goes for student health services, a
shuttle bus system, and other activities to which no one has raised
objections.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin law students, represented by a conservative legal
organization, the Northstar Legal Center in Fairfax, Va., say they
object to the ``blatant political and ideological activism'' of the
Campus Women's Center, which lobbied against an anti-abortion
measure in the Wisconsin Legislature; the UW Greens, which
distributed literature for Ralph Nader's presidential campaign in
1996; and several organizations supporting gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   There were also these developments at the Court on Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ AFFIRMATIVE ACTION: Over two dissenting votes, the court let
stand a ruling that invalidated an affirmative action plan to
increase the number of blacks and women in the higher ranks of the
Dallas Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, adopted in 1988 after an earlier consent decree
had failed to improve substantially the racial and gender balance
at the top levels, black and female firefighters who received
passing scores on promotional exams could be promoted to some
positions over white men with higher scores. In striking down the
plan, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in New Orleans, said
there was insufficient evidence of past discrimination to justify
it.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg objected that
there was ample evidence of past discrimination, including a
finding by the Justice Department in 1976 and failure to hire any
black firefighters until 1969.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was important for the court to provide guidance on
what kind of historical and statistical evidence could justify
affirmative action in a context such as this. The case was Dallas
vs. Dallas Fire Fighters Assoc., No. 98-966.
</P>
<P>
   _ SENTENCING RULES: Without comment, the court turned down an
appeal by a Florida inmate whose 11-year federal prison sentence
was based on a quantity of cocaine that police found in her home
after an illegal search. The evidence had been excluded from the
woman's trial, but was added for purposes of sentencing to the
smaller quantity that police found during a lawful search of her
car.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding the sentence, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in Atlanta, said that the exclusionary rule, which bars illegally
seized evidence at trial, does not apply to sentencing. The case
was Pryor vs. U.S., No. 98-7046.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
