<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-660&AMP;ADD-NY     03-29 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF AGREES ON FRAMEWORK TO RESUME AID TO RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund said on Monday that
it agreed on ``a broad framework'' to resume financial aid to
Russia, but American officials immediately warned that they would
permit only enough support to keep Moscow from defaulting on
international loans.
</P>
<P>
   The vague accord, the first since Russia's economic meltdown
last summer, followed a hastily arranged meeting in Moscow between
Michel Camdessus, the managing director of the fund, and Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov of Russia. But only hours after
Primakov's aides suggested that the IMF would lend Russia more than
$8 billion this year, the fund denied that Camdessus had discussed
specific amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials suggested that Russia would receive only a few
billion dollars this year. That would barely cover what Russia owes
the IMF this year, meaning that the aid may amount to a paper
transfer that allows Moscow a grace period on repaying its loans.
</P>
<P>
   American opposition to new loans to Russia is a reflection of
how deeply both diplomatic and economic relations between Moscow
and Washington have deteriorated in the past nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who helped engineer an IMF-led
$17-billion emergency bailout for Russia last year, is now
reluctant to provide more than token aid to the country. The July
bailout failed in August, when Russia devalued its currency and
then fired the team of economic reformers that the United States
was betting on to remake the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the IMF and Primakov have been involved in an
elaborate political and economic dance. Russia has refused many
politically painful economic reforms, but still insisted on a
resumption of aid. An accord was expected last week, when Primakov
was scheduled to arrive in Washington. But he turned his plane
around and returned home when he learned that NATO was planning to
begin its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Now Russia's opposition to the NATO bombing and suggestions that
Moscow might quietly resume military aid to President Slobodan
Milosevic have greatly complicated the IMF negotiations with
Russia. That became clearer than ever on Monday when, only hours
after Primakov declared an IMF deal was imminent, the Russian
defense minister claimed that a Russian-made air defense system
sold to the Yugoslav military was responsible for shooting down a
U.S. F-117A Stealth fighter on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said on Monday that they would open
themselves to congressional attack if they approved a resumption of
help to Moscow at a moment when Russia was resuming aid to
Milosevic. While the United States holds only an 18 percent vote on
the board of the fund, as a practical matter it could veto an aid
package. On Monday, officials went out of their way to make sure
that Primakov understood that the two issues were closely linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A U.S. judgment about an IMF program,'' a senior
administration official said, ``would depend on Russian economic
policy actions and could also be influenced by broader political
developments,'' a clear reference to tangible Russian support for
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kosovo was not straining relations with Moscow, the
United States was already trying to limit the IMF's re-engagement
with Moscow. American officials have already told the fund that
they would oppose offering what the Treasury refers to as ``new
resources'' to Russia, meaning that any loans could be used only
for repaying the fund or the World Bank. Under one possible scheme
under discussion, Russia would repay the fund, only to receive a
check for roughly the same amount the next day _ a move that, in
other contexts, is often referred to as check kiting.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have gone further, saying that by the end of
the year they want to make sure Russia pays more to the IMF in 1999
than the IMF pays Russia. But officials inside the World Bank and
the fund say they oppose that approach.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Camdessus was clearly seeking to mend fences in Moscow over the
weekend. He made a whirlwind tour of the Russian political elite,
meeting with parliamentary leaders, with directors of Gazprom, the
giant Russian natural gas company, and even dining with the
patriarch of Moscow and All Russia, Alexei II. He also talked on
the telephone with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia agreed to raise 60 billion rubles __ about $2.4 billion
at current exchange rates _ in new revenues, partly by postponing a
cut in Russia's value-added tax. The fund had protested the Russian
Duma's passage of the tax cut, noting that the VAT was one of the
few taxes that Russia successfully collects.
</P>
<P>
   The fund said it also reached an agreement with Russia that its
budget would run what is called a ``primary surplus'' of two
percent of the country's gross domestic product, or roughly $3
billion. The term refers to a surplus before payments for foreign
debts. But how the Russians would achieve that surplus, one senior
IMF official said, ``is still a considerable mystery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
