u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VET-BENEFIT-RESPONSE-     03-29 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VET-BENEFIT-RESPONSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Article brings big response to VA benefit
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ About 600 people _ just a fraction of those
eligible _ have applied for a newly restored federal benefit for
widows of military veterans who died in action or of a
service-related disability, Veterans Affairs officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That tepid response shows how ineffective the VA has been in
publicizing the availability of the benefit, veterans' and
survivors' advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   A story in the Dayton Daily News Sunday highlighting the VA's
Dependency and Indemnity Compensation benefit triggered more than
125 calls to the Montgomery County Veteran's Service Center alone
Monday, Director Denver Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 18 years I've been doing this, this is the greatest
response I've seen'' from a story on veterans benefits, Combs said.
The response overloaded the center's staff; most of the callers
were asked to leave their names and phone numbers and will be
contacted by staff members for further information, hopefully
sometime today, Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   The DIC benefit _ a tax-free, $861-a-month minimum payment to
those who qualify _ was reinstated in September 1998 for those
whose spouses died in World War II, the Korean War or the Vietnam
War, and who are currently unmarried. Spouses also may qualify if
the veteran's death was the result of a service-related disability,
or if the veteran was disabled for 10 years prior to death. For
more information, call the veteran's service office in your county.
</P>
<P>
   Combs said he has seen very little publicity from the VA about
the restored benefit, which he has discussed during televised
question-and-answer sessions on local cable-access channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (the VA) has done a very good job,'' Combs said.
``I've seen something on their web page, but how many widows surf
the 'net?''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Murphy Peterson, national legislative director of the
Gold Star Wives of America , said the number of applications the VA
has received since the benefit's reinstatement represents the tip
of the iceberg. Federal officials last year estimated 6,000 people
may qualify nationwide; Gold Star, which represents veterans'
survivors, projected that number to reach 10,000. The federal
agency has no way of tracking subsequent marriages and divorces of
veterans' spouses and cannot pinpoint a number of those who meet
the criteria, a VA spokesman said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the agency sent out a news release about the
reinstated benefits last fall and worked with veterans' groups and
other organizations to try to get the word out, but he acknowledged
it was difficult to reach widows of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Department spokeswoman Laurie Tranter said Monday the VA is
``working closely'' with the Gold Star Wives to spread the word of
the restored DIC benefits. The effort may receive a boost soon from
``syndicated columns'' on the subject, Tranter said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
