<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO DECIDE IF STUDENT-ACTIVITY FEES VIOLATE FREE
SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether a
state school violates the free-speech rights of its students by
requiring them to pay fees that are used to support groups which
they may oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The case pits the effort of public universities to ensure a
diversity of viewpoints on campus against students who do not want
to support groups with opinions and goals they find repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the University of Wisconsin is urging the justices
to overturn a federal appeals court decision that struck down the
school's use of mandatory student-activity fees to pay for a gamut
of campus organizations, even when individual students object to
certain groups.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christian law students at the university have
successfully challenged the school so far, arguing that the use of
their money to support abortion-rights and gay-rights groups
violates their First Amendment right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, upholding a lower court
decision, agreed with the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the university cannot discriminate in the disbursement of
funds, it is imperative that students not be compelled to fund
organizations that engage in political and ideological activities _
that is the only way to protect the individual's rights,'' the 7th
Circuit said.
</P>
<P>
   In its successful request that the court hear its appeal,
Wisconsin argued that a school's ability to be a forum for diverse
views would be undermined if it could not use student fees as a
general source of revenue to support various organizations with
different viewpoints. The state added that it distributes funds to
campus groups without any regard for the viewpoints they espouse.
</P>
<P>
   Countering the state, the law students argued that if the
justices eventually rule for the school, ``a state university could
force Jewish students to fund a Christian evangelical newspaper
(and) state universities could force African-American students to
fund neo-Nazi or Ku Klux Klan organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, a gay-rights group,
submitted a legal brief to the justices urging them to hear
Wisconsin's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few religious extremists who started this case should not
be allowed to dismantle an important avenue for fostering student
dialogue and debate because they don't like what some students
say,'' said Patricia Logue, a Lambda attorney who helped write the
group's brief. ``Campus groups have a long history of sparking
campus debate and engaging students in weighing new and contentious
ideas. We look to the Supreme Court to stop this narrow-minded
assault on a neutral system for supporting campus dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision in the case,
Board of Regents of the University of Wisconsin System vs.
Southworth, by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court also took the following actions Monday:
</P>
<P>
   Let the federal government continue giving extra help in winning
contracts on federal highway projects to companies owned by poorer
people. The court turned away arguments in a Utah case that said
the affirmative-action program adopted by Congress unlawfully
discriminates against companies owned by white men.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected the appeal of a Utah man whose request to give the
opening prayer at a city council meeting was turned down because of
its unusual content. The court, without comment, rebuffed arguments
that the city council in Murray City, Utah, unlawfully favored one
religion over another by rejecting the proposed prayer, called a
political harangue by a lower court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
