<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-ART-2TA     03-29 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 AS PEOPLE'S KNOWLEDGE OF KOSOVO GROWS, SO DO THEIR DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dilia Theodosakia can pinpoint the moment her apprehension about
the American-led bombing of Serbia, an operation she initially
considered the undertaking of a president she thoroughly distrusts,
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   It came last Wednesday, the first day of the attack, as she was
listening in her home near White Plains, N.Y., to her favorite
radio talk show, whose host, Bob Grant, she considers a
conservative soulmate. A guest on the show cast the conflict in
terms of the Holocaust, likening Serbian attacks on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo to Hitler's destruction of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said touched my heart,'' Mrs. Theodosakia said. ``He
mentioned that those people there are without protection and if we
don't help, who will help? It will be like the Jewish massacre in
World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few days, as she continued to hear and watch
the news in between her everyday activities of church choir
practice, family meals and shopping, doubts began to gather once
more.
</P>
<P>
   She saw anguished Serbian-Americans on television expressing
fear for their relatives in Yugoslavia. She saw interviews with
frightened Kosovo Albanian refugees fleeing their homes. And her
misgivings about President Clinton returned in the form of
questions about the effectiveness of bombs in forcing two peoples
to live in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning it seemed very simple,'' Mrs. Theodosakia,
57, a retired secretary, said Monday. ``Now, you don't know who's
right and who's wrong. Both sides are human beings and both are
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   As reports mount of casualties, bombs, refugees and protests, so
has public uncertainty over the NATO bombing campaign in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   People who accepted the Clinton administration's portrayal of
the military strikes as a clear-cut moral obligation _ the
protection of a vulnerable ethnic minority from the brutality of
one stubborn man, Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic _ have
begun to question just who this man is and what motivates him.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews over the past five days with ordinary
people living and working in White Plains, which is in Westchester
County just outside New York City, those doubts have grown more
apparent as these people have absorbed more and more information,
pictures and commentary about Yugoslavia from television, radio and
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   For most, the initial vision of the United States as a righteous
champion of good against evil remains instinctive and appealing. By
evoking World War II, and the image of a world that hesitated too
long in the face of Hitler's genocide, Clinton seemed to have
touched a chord in his address to the nation last week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite their lack of cynicism at the notion of the
United States as the international enforcer of justice, many people
tempered their idealism with skepticism about specific points _
about the president, the impartiality of the news media, the depth
of support from other NATO members, and official promises that
ground troops would not be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after the downing of an American warplane and the sight of
Serbs appearing to rally around their own president, the skepticism
is becoming more pronounced. Many of those interviewed _ retirees,
office workers, a shop owner, a maintenance man, a stockbroker _
said that the more they saw and heard over the past weekend, the
less they felt they understood the roots and possible outcomes of
this faraway conflict.
</P>
<P>
   And with that confusion has come the suspicion that the public
is not getting the full story of what has been and what will be in
Yugoslavia, either from journalists or from politicians.
</P>
<P>
   KURT OLSON
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning I really had very little information,'' said
Kurt Olson, the owner of Photo-Finish, a small film-processing
store in downtown White Plains. ``Now I understand, in a very
simple sense, that it's Serbians trying to cleanse ethnic
Albanians. But what I don't understand is: What is the conflict
between the Serbians and ethnic Albanians and why has it gone on so
long?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew that,'' he added, in an interview Monday, ``maybe I
could make a better judgment of how to put an end to this
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Olson said, he could support the military
assault on Yugoslavia as long as it was a NATO operation and not
just a unilateral crusade by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more apprehension when NATO is not behind the
operations,'' he explained last week, as he helped customers in his
small shop on Mamaroneck Avenue in the morning after the first
allied bombers attacked Yugoslav military targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it is,'' he added then, ``it reinforces that this part
of it is justified. It's not just Great Britain and the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a weekend's worth of watching television images of
attacks on U.S. embassies in Europe and Serbian demonstrations in
support of Milosevic, Olson has started to wonder if the seamless
alliance he counted on really exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just had some personal agenda for whatever reason, I
would assume NATO would not back us,'' he said Monday. ``But I'd
like to know if there's a third opinion out there, maybe from the
other members of NATO. What is their justification and their reason
for wanting to stop the Serbs?''
</P>
<P>
   He is growing increasingly wary of relying exclusively on
American sources of information, particularly the mainstream
television, radio and newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media reports we get in the United States say the Serbians
are trying to put an end to this whole race of people and that's
obviously wrong,'' Olson said. ``I would like to get some other
countries' points of view.''
</P>
<P>
   His plan, he added, is to conduct his own research on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll type in `Kosovo' and I'm sure there will be 100,000
sites. Then I'll just pick some from another country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clark, a Vietnam veteran who works at the Westchester
County Board of Elections, also has little faith in the accuracy of
mainstream news outlets. He said he came by his caution the hard
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Vietnam, they would say at night on the news that there
were 50 casualties that day, when I knew there were thousands,'' he
recalled last week, as he sat in the sun on a bus bench during his
lunch break. ``I listen to the talk shows on the radio. You get a
more honest view. I sit up at night and listen to the shows. You
listen to the topic. You get a lot of views.''
</P>
<P>
   On that Thursday, the second day in the bombing campaign, Clark,
a former marine who was born in Panama, was ambivalent about the
correctness of the NATO operation. He said he was firmly against
the use of ground troops ``unless it is necessary.'' It would only
be necessary, he added, if the United States itself were
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, the United States was justified in using force
during the 1991 Gulf war against Iraq and the Iraqi president,
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy Saddam was harassing some other country. Was it
Iran?'' Clark said as he tried to recall the historical
particulars. ``And action had to be taken. But we didn't accomplish
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to bomb, bomb where it hurts the right
target,'' he added. ``I spent two years in Vietnam and I saw kids
dying like flies out there. I was just 19 myself when I was out
there. They kept saying it was going to be over and it was going to
be over.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO campaign dragged on, Clark said he began to see more
parallels with the war he personally experienced and never fully
understood. And that makes him even more ambivalent about taking
sides and fully accepting the official view that military action is
justified to rein in the Serbs of Yugoslavia and Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like this,'' he said. ``Until I walk in another man's
shoes, I can't judge him. I'm not going to condemn the Serbs
because I don't know what their situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very, very strongly about that,'' added Clark Monday,
after a weekend spent with family, during which the war in
Yugoslavia took a distant second place to sports as a topic of
discussion. ``We are going to start getting casualties from this.
And I don't want another Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA MCCAULEY
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, Martha McCauley sifts the information she gets
about the conflict and killing in Yugoslavia through the filter of
her own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   A 69-year-old retired IBM worker who volunteers four days a week
as a teacher's aide at the same White Plains parochial school she
attended as a child, Mrs. McCauley has been paying close attention
to news about the bombing of Yugoslavia and reports of Serbian
atrocities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a reader, how can you miss it?'' she said last week,
standing watch over the playground of the St. John's the Evangelist
Church the day after the NATO airstrikes began.
</P>
<P>
   A faithful viewer of network television news and CNBC, and a
regular reader of the White Plains daily newspaper, the Journal
News, as well as Newsweek magazine and The Sunday New York Times,
Mrs. McCauley said she felt from the start that she understood the
stakes and the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to do this,'' she said. ``This Mihikovic, this
Mikilovic _ I can never remember his name _ doesn't seem to want
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing she saw on television or read over the next few days
shook her resolve that the United States is correct and even
obligated to protect Kosovo Albanians from Milosevic. Indeed, over
the weekend, seeing bedraggled Kosovo refugees being interviewed
after seeking safe haven in neighboring Macedonia and Albania, Mrs.
McCauley said she became even more determined in her condemnation
of the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard two people talking on CNBC and once said that this man
has always wanted to be in power and that's his main thing,'' she
recalled. ``And the other one, was this older Jewish fellow, and he
said there were reports way, way back of men being put on trains
and shot. He said it was like Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``And really, to me, I think this man has the mentality of
someone like Hitler,'' Mrs. McCauley added. ``I just don't think
he's going change and it is going to get worse and worse.''
</P>
<P>
   A note of buoyant pride slipped into her conversation the longer
the NATO campaign continued. She spoke, again and again, of her
father, who was drafted in World War II and left three children and
a wife to fight on the European front.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard for us all,'' she recalled. ``But, you know,
in later years I thought about father over there in Germany and
with the field artillery in France and I was kind of proud he was
one of those stopping those horrible things happening over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' Mrs. McCauley added, ``that our
country helps people.''
</P>
<P>
   DILIA THEODOSAKIA
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Theodosakia, the retired secretary, said she felt much the
sense of pride and satisfaction over the American role in what has
been explained as a mission to save ethnic Albanians from Serb
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   But with the relentless bombing over the past days, reports of
Serb civilian casualties and even the prospect that the celebration
of Easter could be marred by continued war, she has started to
waver in her convictions. She said she dreads the thought that
Clinton might send ground troops into battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does that, we'll have casualties,'' she said. ``I know
he promised he wouldn't, but the thing about the president is he
goes back and forth. One day it's yes. One day it's no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought that the bombs would last, maybe, a week, and
it would all be over,'' she added. ``But now people are starting to
attack our embassies. Did you hear? Even in Greece there were
people protesting against us.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest made a particular impression because Mrs.
Theodosakia's husband is of Greek origin. She herself was born in
Puerto Rico and, ever since the company where she worked closed
down two years ago, has been busy studying for her state exam to
become a registered nutritionist.
</P>
<P>
   But she makes time to stay informed about the world, and several
times a week she visits her local library to read The Washington
Post and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to things that concern the world, I'm
interested,'' said Mrs. Theodosakia. ``I'm interested because I
pray and I direct my prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that her certainty about the war in Yugoslavia is slipping
away, she is praying for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was listening to reports about the demonstrations in New
York City, by both Albanians and by Serbs,'' Mrs. Theodosakia said
Monday. ``I said to myself, what would I do if I wanted to join in
with one of those? And I realized that one day I would have to go
with the Albanians and one day, go with the Serbs. Because it's
very hard to take sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is,'' she added, ``it's something between them,
isn't it? They have to learn to live in peace with one another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
