<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AND IRISH PREMIERS URGE COMPROMISE IN BELFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ As an Easter deadline approached,
Prime Ministers Tony Blair of Britain and Bertie Ahern of Ireland
sought Monday night to persuade Northern Ireland's Protestant and
Roman Catholic leaders to compromise on the dispute that is
threatening to collapse the peace effort here.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is over the disarmament of the overwhelmingly
Catholic Irish Republican Army, which refuses to surrender a single
weapon, or an ounce of explosives. Protestant leaders say that if
the IRA does not disarm, its political wing, Sinn Fein, will be
excluded later this week from a cabinet of the new Northern Ireland
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is supposed to carry out the peace agreement
approved in Belfast last April 10, designed to end 30 years of
sectarian warfare in this British province.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, arriving here after spending the day in London dealing
with the situation in Kosovo, looked grim, saying before he met the
politicians that if they failed, this would be ``the greatest
betrayal of the people I can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern arrived from Dublin, where he had been under pressure to
state neutral Ireland's position on the NATO attacks in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is small buns compared to Kosovo,'' one British official
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to those involved in it,'' replied a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's talks came after a day of apparently fruitless
discussions between the two principal political adversaries, Gerry
Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, and David Trimble, leader of the
Protestant Ulster Unionist Party, who is also first minister of the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has the power to deprive Sinn Fein of ministerial posts
in the new cabinet and said he would do so unless he was convinced
that the IRA had made a ``credible beginning'' to disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   If Sinn Fein were excluded, officials and experts say, the peace
effort would be crippled, if not destroyed, possibly leading to a
new round of sectarian violence between paramilitaries of the
Protestant majority and the Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement approved a year ago would give more
political power to this province's Catholic minority, and give more
influence in northern affairs to the overwhelmingly Catholic
Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Adams points out that the peace agreement does not require
disarmament before May, 2000, and that the IRA's 21-month
cease-fire is evidence of its support for peace.
</P>
<P>
   An Easter deadline for agreement had been set after Mo Mowlam,
Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, said she would start the
process of naming a cabinet this Wednesday or Thursday. The new
cabinet must be formed in order to pave the way for the transfer of
home rule powers to the Assembly. The province has been governed
directly by Britain since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   While she could extend the deadline, as she has in the past, Ms.
Mowlam invited the two prime ministers to her official residence
outside Belfast Monday night to meet Northern Ireland political
leaders with a view to achieving a compromise in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRA has repeatedly said unequivocally that it will not
disarm, politicians were looking anxiously to the guerrilla
organization's annual Easter proclamation, expected this week, for
a change of tone, possibly softening its stand on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and experts note that any compromise would have to be
one that both Adams and Trimble could defend as honorable to their
hard-line supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
