<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bypassing Louvre Lines With On-Line Tickets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Paris can now avoid long lines for entrance to the
Louvre. Advance tickets are available on the Internet through
Ticket Web, an Oakland-based online ticketing company. The tickets,
good for admission any time until Jan. 31, 2000, to the Louvre's
permanent collection, can be purchased at www.ticketweb.com or
through the Louvre's Web site, www.louvre.fr. Tickets are also
available at (510) 594-1400; fax (510) 594-1401. Ticket Web accepts
Mastercard and Visa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ticket holders enter through the Richelieu Passage, a separate
entrance between the Place du Palais Royal and the Cour Napoleon.
Prices for March _ the price is updated the 1st of each month,
based on the exchange rate _ were $7.50 for entrance before 3 p.m.
and $4.50 after 3 p.m. and on Sunday (the first Sunday of each
month is free). There is a service fee of $1 an order and $1.60 a
ticket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Louvre is open daily except Tuesday from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.,
and until 9:45 p.m. on Monday and Wednesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where the Big Ones Are Always Reeled In &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fishing enthusiasts visiting Fort Lauderdale, Fla., don't have
to be on a boat to enjoy their sport. This winter the World Fishing
Center, a museum and recreational complex, opened with exhibits and
hands-on displays about freshwater and saltwater fishing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center has 10 themed areas, including a World Fishing Hall
of Fame with records and documents recounting great fishing feats,
and a Catch Gallery with video simulation where visitors can engage
in virtual fishing with the help of experts.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Fish Gallery, with a display of aquatic life; a
Tackle Gallery that features antique and contemporary rods, reels
and lures, and a Places Gallery, where visitors can use electronic
maps and touch-screen technology to research the best places to
fish the world over.
</P>
<P>
   For children under 8, there is a Discovery Room, where they can
assemble imaginary fish, or dress in full fishing gear, ride in a
boat and negotiate imaginary waters in search of magnetic fish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a boardwalk surrounded by three and a half acres of
swamp, marshland and mangroves leads through some of Florida's
natural habitats. A marina display includes six fishing boats,
among them the Wheeler, sister ship of Ernest Hemingway's Pilar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center is on a 51-acre tract near Fort Lauderdale's airport.
The circular entrance road surrounds a 5,000-pound stainless-steel
sculpture by Kent Ullberg depicting a swordfish. In the main lobby,
the floor resembles the bottom of the sea, while wooden boats and
aluminum fish hover overhead.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $9, $7 for 65 and older, $5 for ages 3 to 12 and
free for children under 3. The center is open every day except
Christmas. Information: (954) 922-4212. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Mercer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several Red Sea Reefs Open Again to Divers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   n response to requests from tour operators and scuba divers, the
Egyptian government has decided to allow diving once again off
about 15 islands in the Red Sea where it had been prohibited
because of ecological concerns. It is now permitted at Zabargad,
Rocky, Brothers and Abul Kizan islands, with limits on the number
of divers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two trips are allowed each week: a one-week excursion to the
Brothers islands and a 12-day tour of the other islands. Each tour
group may have no more than six boats, with a maximum of 15 divers
a boat. The diving fee is $5 a person. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These islands are well known for their coral reefs and diverse
fish populations. More than 10 islands in the Red Sea are still off
limits to divers for conservation reasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More information about scuba diving in Egypt is available from
the Egyptian Tourist Authority, 630 Fifth Avenue, Suite 1706, New
York, N.Y. 10111, (212) 332-2570, or www.touregypt.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meiji Treasures Displayed in Delaware &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after Commodore Matthew Perry led an American
fleet into Tokyo Bay in 1853 and began to open Japan to the West,
the Shogun warlords there put down their swords and the emperor was
restored to power. The years that followed, until 1912, are known
as the Meiji era. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Splendors of Meiji: Treasures of Imperial Japan,'' which opens
at the First USA Riverfront Arts Center in Wilmington, Del., on
Saturday, will showcase the art of that period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 450 works of art in metal, lacquer, bronze, ceramic,
enamel and porcelain, made as Japan was emerging from centuries of
isolation, will be on view. Among the highlights are a bejeweled
silver koro, or incense burner, shaped like an elephant; a gold
lacquer cabinet; a lacquered elephant-tusk vase, and a highly
enameled and gilded ceramic bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these objects were made by the ``artists to the Imperial
household,'' about a dozen men singled out by the emperor for their
craftsmanship. Before entering the seven Japanese-style display
galleries, visitors may stop for an eight-minute film that presents
a historical overview of Japan at the time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The works are now part of the Khalili Collection, assembled by
Nasser D. Khalili, an Iranian-born collector who lives in London
and also owns troves of Islamic art, Middle Eastern antiquities,
and Indian and Swedish textiles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which closes on Sept. 6, will be open daily
(last entry is 6 p.m.). Admission is $13, with discounts for
seniors, students and children. Dated and timed tickets are
available at (302) 777-1600 or (888) 395-0005 or at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 hotels in the Wilmington area are offering
overnight packages, including tickets. Prices for double-occupancy
rooms start at $118 and go up to $325 or higher. Information: (302)
652 4088. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The First USA Riverfront Center is at 800 South Madison Street
in Wilmington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Las Vegas Gamblers, Now It's Debt in Venice &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Las Vegas milestone will be reached on April 22 when
gondolas appear in the desert, courtesy of the Venetian Resort
Hotel Casino, across the Strip from the Mirage. Besides the Grand
Canal, other Venetian landmarks reproduced at the hotel are the
Campanile, St. Mark's Square, the Ca' d'Oro and (for unlucky
bettors) the Bridge of Sighs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standard rooms (there are 2,718, plus 318 suites) measure about
700 square feet, with two beds equipped with draped canopies, a
sunken living-room area and two 27-inch TV sets. Baths, 130 square
feet, will be well paved with Italian marble. Each room will be
equipped with a fax-copier-printer with separate telephone line and
three dual-line phones.
</P>
<P>
   If all that sounds businesslike, it's no accident: the hotel is
connected to the Sands Expo and Convention Center, one of the
largest in the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The culinary doges overseeing restaurants at the Venetian will
include Joachim Splichal, Emeril Lagasse and Wolfgang Puck.
Gondoliers get a break at the Venetian: they work indoors, out of
the heat, on a waterway through the Grand Canal Shoppes, an
air-conditioned mall that will be fully operational by May 14, with
traditional glassblowers and mask makers in addition to upscale
merchants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During daylight hours, when the clock in the Campanile chimes
the hour, 400 to 500 white homing pigeons will be released outside
and circle the landmarks in the square before returning to their
roost in the hotel's parking garage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Rome wasn't built in a day, and ditto for Venice: the hotel
spa, a branch of the Canyon Ranch, and the pool area won't be ready
until June. Room rates will range from $119 to $399, with an
average of $167; to reserve, it's (888) 283-6423 or on the Web at
www.venetian.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Siano &QL;
</P>
