<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS SWAP POSITIONS ON MILITARY INTERVENTION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Ronald Reagan dispatched U.S. troops to the
tiny Caribbean Island of Grenada in 1983, Republicans in Congress
cheered his courage for confronting the Marxist regime. Many
Democrats questioned his use of military firepower to stamp out
world conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   And when George Bush sought congressional approval to move
against Iraq in 1991, Republicans backed him, arguing that the
region was of strategic importance to the U.S. Many Democrats,
meanwhile, fretted that the president would be plunging the nation
into another Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   However, when Democrat Bill Clinton won the White House, the
positions on Capitol Hill were reversed. Congressional Democrats
who once questioned bombing campaigns abroad have largely stood
behind the president as he sent troops to Haiti and launched
airstrikes in Bosnia and now Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who just a decade ago argued for a strong U.S.
military presence around the world, have been critical of Clinton's
military forays, arguing that he is meddling in too many foreign
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate vote endorsing the Kosovo strikes, only 16
Republicans joined all but three Democrats in approving the
administration's action. By contrast, on the resolution endorsing
the Persian Gulf War, only 10 Democrats joined Republicans in
approving that action.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cite a range of reasons for the flip in party stands,
from increasing isolationism in the Republican Party to a confusion
of what U.S. foreign policy should be in the aftermath of the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime political observers say the switch is hardly
surprising, given the pressure on members of Congress to back a
president of the same party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George W. Bush were president, I suspect that some of the
Republicans would become interventionists and Democrats would be
less interventionist,'' said former Texas House Democrat Charles
Wilson, who often backed his party and the GOP in supporting
military action.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Republicans appear to harbor a great degree of
antipathy toward Clinton. ``They just don't believe him,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision to commence airstrikes against
Yugoslavia occurred soon after Clinton's impeachment trial, which
strained party relations on Capitol Hill and may have caused an
irreparable rift between Congressional Republicans and the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the byproducts of the kind of partisanship we have seen
on Capitol Hill is the knee-jerk reactions on both sides. You have
Republicans who oppose the president simply on the basis of
partisanship, and Democrats who are backing him, who in other
circumstances would be savaging him,'' said Charles Cook, a
political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Others said that many of the lawmakers tend to take their cue
from party leaders on international matters, particularly with the
demise of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cold War mentality was so much easier to deal with. There
were clear enemies. We knew the good guys and the bad guys. There
was a consensus on many of the fundamentals. The consensus today is
gone, and like so much else in Washington, it is all about politics
and who wins and who loses,'' said Mark Rozell, professor of
political science at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, neither party has developed a coherent policy to
deal with international relations. Some experts believe Clinton has
been operating on an ad hoc basis in deciding where to intervene,
while Republicans have not been able to coalesce behind a single
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party has a coherent vision of foreign policy. No one
has figured out the post-Cold War matrix,'' said Marshall Wittman,
an analyst at the conservative Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts have noted the increasing isolationism within
the Republican Party, articulated by such leading figures as
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians also cannot rely on the public for direction,
since polls show that many voters are confused and ambivalent about
military actions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
