<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: )  
 SPORTS COLUMN: FINAL FOUR _ THE SURVIVAL OF THE FITTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Just by being here, they were superior
beings, the Dukies and the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   They had outlived the other 308 Division I teams in the land,
had lived through conference tournaments, subregionals, regionals
and the Saturday semifinals, just to entertain the nation Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the national college basketball final, Duke was taking on
Connecticut in just about the ugliest domed stadium ever slapped
down on the face of this earth.
</P>
<P>
   The two schools had trekked through the killer month of March,
through changes of weather, changes of climate and jet lag in the
case of Connecticut. (Duke has so much prestige that it was never
even forced to reset its clocks, both internal and external.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the two schools had endured every vicious germ the
airlines so generously recycle in their air systems: every flu,
every bug, every virus, every microbe, every streptococcus, every
ache, every pain, every vague malaise that air travelers pass back
and forth to each other through the alleged ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Flying around the continent for the last four months, being
sneezed upon by thousands of strangers, these two teams had
probably been within a degree or two of separation from every
illness known to humankind. While most frequent travelers come down
with a new sore throat, a new headache, for every frequent-flier
segment, these kids were still running up and down the court.
Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's only loss may indeed have been traced to the flu, during
its longest trek of the season, out to Alaska at the end of
November. With Shane Battier just staggering back from the flu,
Duke lost, 77-75, to Cincinnati, which Coach Mike Krzyzewski
mentioned the other day _ not that Coach K was making excuses, mind
you.
</P>
<P>
   After two trips to wintry Chicago and one to New York in
January, Duke then romped over three rivals in the Atlantic Coast
Conference tournament in Charlotte, N.C. Gone are the bizarre old
days when the second-best team in the country could be left out of
the national tournament for the sin of losing the ACC final, but
Duke took no chances.
</P>
<P>
   Things worked out so well for Duke in Charlotte that the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament committee let
the Blue Devils stay right there for the East subregional, and they
then romped up the interstate to their home away from home in the
Meadowlands for the regional.
</P>
<P>
   Then down here in Florida, they beat Michigan State in the
semifinal in the most lopsided 68-62 game anybody will ever see,
after which Coach K lectured us that these were two great teams
that had just played a great basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's 37-1 record going into Monday night indicates character,
talent and strength _ and good immunity, too.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, with its 32-2 record, had actually overcome greater
demons, both bacteriological and psychological. The Huskies romped
through the season with the gloomy history of never having
qualified for the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Their longest trip was in August, for a series of exhibitions,
where they visited the Changing of the Guard in London and rode
camels in Israel, after which they came home and trudged through
the sinus-challenging schedule of the Big East _ one game in Miami,
and a lot of places in the land of the wind chill factor.
</P>
<P>
   March was the real test. The Huskies came down to the big city
and were nearly beaten by Seton Hall before winning, 57-56, in
their first game of the Big East tournament, after which they won
two by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the sojourn. There was a nasty snow squall in Denver,
and when the snow stopped, Denver was dun brown in early March, its
mile-high oxygen supply challenging their lungs and their muscles.
Coach Jim Calhoun kept running in fresh bodies, and the Huskies won
two easily.
</P>
<P>
   Having adjusted to Mountain time, the Huskies stayed out West.
There was an inexplicable rainstorm in Phoenix on the day before
the regional, but then the sun came out in the arid landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was battered around by an intense band of Iowa
players, and then was tested by a wild-eyed bunch from Gonzaga. Now
Connecticut was in its fourth distinctively different climate in
four weeks _ sparkling bays and graceful bridges, palm trees and
herons, quite enough incentive to avoid thawing-out Connecticut for
a few more hours.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game would be played with 40,000 people in
attendance. The fans were situated so far away that they couldn't
see the players, much less sneeze on them.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had the credentials of a national champion. Both
teams had a chance to get home without an epidemic of sore throats
and runny noses, truly the sign of champions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
