<HEADLINE>
MEET YOUR CLUBS ON THE LINKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skiing and golf are two of the most popular sports for
vacationers. And they share another trait: the equipment essential
to each is bulky and inconvenient to take on a trip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lugging skis or golf clubs through airports and
entrusting the equipment to airline baggage handlers, you can rent
them at the vacation destination. But that can add up (club rentals
are about $35 a round at Hilton Head Island, S.C.), and a course
like Pebble Beach requires all the help you can get _ including
familiar clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Rental skis vary widely in quality, and skiers may feel more
comfortable with their own skis and bindings, which can translate
to safer skiing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is another solution: package-shipping companies like
Federal Express and United Parcel Service can carry your skis and
clubs for you. Even for travel within the United States, however,
this falls into the Aspen class of vacation amenities.
</P>
<P>
   A round-trip ticket for your golf clubs on UPS, with second-day
delivery, will be about $120, and $90 for your skis and poles. But
if you'll be on the links or the slopes for a week or so, it's
competitive with daily rentals.
</P>
<P>
   It also relieves the strain on baggage limits. Passengers on
domestic flights get two free checked-in bags, for which the
airlines assume $1,250 in liability (the price of a good set of
golf clubs). And there is less concern about loss or theft: with
the serial number on a shipping receipt, you can trace a parcel on
the Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Fedex do not keep statistics on how many golf
bags and skis they ship, but unscientific observations indicate
that the package-service strategy is slowly catching on among
American sports enthusiasts. Paul Witt, a spokesman for the Vail
family of ski resorts, said that about 20 percent of guests at
Pines Lodge in Beaver Creek shipped their skis in via air freight.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley, a pricey resort in Utah, has expanded a program
with Fedex this season after a successful trial last winter. And
Golf Bag Express, which started offering golfers door-to-resort UPS
delivery of their clubs a year ago, is now up to 100 bags a day.
</P>
<P>
   Krista Thompson, a spokeswoman for Deer Valley, (800) 558-3337,
said that its program began in the 1997-98 season, when it was
available only to guests staying in a Deer Valley hotel. The skis
go directly to a free ski-storage area next to the lift-ticket
office.
</P>
<P>
   It proved so popular, she said, that now anyone _ including
skiers at nearby Park City _ can have skis shipped to the resort.
Guests call the resort, which notifies Fedex to charge a special
flat rate. Second-day air shipment of a set of poles and skis
(boots are extra) is $45 one way from Fedex offices in the United
States. Each shipment is insured for up to $500, Ms. Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to try ski-shipping in these waning days of the
season, don't expect to find a Deer Valley-type program at most ski
resorts. Aspen abandoned a similar program after a trial period.
You'll have to take your skis to a local parcel-service office and
determine the rate based on distance, weight and speed of delivery.
A recent sampling of rates in Norwalk, Conn., showed that a pair of
skis and poles could be sent second-day air to Vail for $34.75 on
UPS, (800) 742-5877; $29 on Fedex, (800) 463-3339, and $21 on
Airborne Express, (800) 247-2676. When shipping skis and poles,
taping them together prevents damage from jostling within the
shipping container.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Felton, a spokesman for the Breckenridge resort, said that
shipping skis ahead hadn't caught on there. One reason is its
proximity to Denver's airport. ``It was designed with skiers in
mind, so it's easier to bring your own skis,'' he said. ``And we
see a lot of people who feel very comfortable using rented skis.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers, on the other hand, are more attuned to the feel of
their own clubs. But a loaded golf bag (14 clubs plus balls, tees,
umbrella, ball retriever and a sweater) is much harder to caddy
through airports.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rick Binger, director of operations for Golf Bag Express, (800)
237-6200, says that it took two years of work with UPS to develop a
compact shipping container tough enough for a golf bag. ``Folded
up, it's about the size of a dozen golf balls,'' Binger said. This
bag, made of thick plastic, is sent to the customer from the
company's El Segundo, Calif., office with a shipping label that
alerts the resort or pro shop to expect the golfer soon after it
arrives. A second bag is required for the return trip.
</P>
<P>
   Before loading the golf bag into the shipping container, Binger
recommends placing the golf bag in a soft travel bag. If the
second-day air service is chosen ($59 one way within the United
States, including home pickup), the bag should reach the resort in
two days. For golfers who can stand to be separated from their
clubs for longer periods, there's a less costly ground service,
which should take five business days and costs $59 round trip or
$32 one way.
</P>
<P>
   For most trips there appears to be no saving in shipping clubs
yourself. A recent stop at the Fedex office in Norwalk, Conn.,
yielded the following one-way rates to ship my bag, which was in a
hard shipping case and had a few dozen balls along with the clubs:
$74.75 for second-day air and $44.25 for ground-only to Hilton
Head; $79.50 second-day air and $63.50 ground-only to Pebble Beach,
Calif. Luckily, I drive to Hilton Head and Pebble Beach greens fees
are out of my price range. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golf Bag Express does not yet ship overseas, Binger said, so
you'll have to trust your clubs to the airlines or rent a set if
you go to Scotland, for example. For what it would cost to ship
them to St. Andrews _ about $500 round trip, according to the
Norwalk Fedex office _ you could buy a top-of-the-line driver.
</P>
<P>
   Golf Bag Express insures a shipment for up to $1,000. If that is
not enough to re-equip your bag, extra coverage is sold at $5 for
each $1,000. Binger offered another tip: ``Cut a broom handle about
an inch or so longer than your driver, then put it in your bag,''
he said. If your bag slams head-first into an airplane bulkhead,
you're a lot less likely to have a broken or bent club. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Binger and Ms. Thompson of Deer Valley said that guests
should call 14 days ahead to allow time for packing materials to
arrive, pickup by the shipper and delivery _ longer for
ground-only. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now, most big ski and golf resorts are accustomed to having
sports equipment show up before its owners. Nonetheless, it helps
to call ahead to advise that you'll be shipping your equipment
separately and to ask the resort for the proper address and
delivery instructions so you'll get it as quickly as possible once
you arrive. My experience has been that most ``shipping delays''
are due to mishandling after a package arrives.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like such a great idea that you are also
considering shipping all your luggage _ clothes, shoes, etc. _ you
aren't the first to think so. Witt, the Vail spokesman, said that a
growing number of guests were doing just that, paying the extra
cost to avoid the annoyance of trying to sneak an oversize bag into
the passenger cabin or waiting at a baggage carousel _ or worse
yet, filling out a lost-bag claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
