<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-MARKETPLACE-775(2     03-29 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MARKETPLACE-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES THE DOW MEASURE UP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(fb) 
 By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a staple of the nightly news, of daily
conversations at dry cleaners and doughnut shops, overheard in
cell-phone conversations and in cocktail party chatter.
</P>
<P>
   When Americans talk about the stock market, they talk about the
Dow Jones industrial average. For roughly a century, ``How'd the
market do today?'' has inevitably been answered with a reference to
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its longevity and accuracy as a barometer of the
progress of the stock market, the 30 stocks of the Dow industrial
average have, in recent years, failed to keep up with the gains of
smaller, more sought after companies that are part of other indexes
that track the overall market. Since the beginning of 1995, the Dow
has lagged behind by a few percentage points each year the returns
of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, the broader index that
most professional investors on Wall Street use as a benchmark for
their own portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has fallen even further behind the Nasdaq composite
index, rich with the technology stocks that lately have been the
market's biggest gainers. Even the unwieldy Wilshire 5000, the
universe of stocks which, despite its name, encompasses more than
7,000 companies based in the United States, has climbed at a rate
more than 1 percent a year faster than the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises the question: Does the Dow matter anymore?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is still yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dow has come in for a lot of criticism for a long time,''
said Steven Leuthold, a market analyst whose research firm, the
Leuthold Group, is based in Minneapolis. ``People complain that it
has a limited number of stocks, they complain about the way the
index is calculated,'' based on the numerical price of stocks
rather than the total market value of the companies it tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the rather amazing thing is how accurately, over
time, it has tracked a broader index like the S&AMP;P 500,'' Leuthold
added. ``There are times when the two get out of sync. But we use
it because it is still the first thing people refer to when they
talk about how the market did today.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the Dow, with a gain of nearly 9 percent, is
more than 1 percentage point ahead of the S&AMP;P 500. But those gains
mask a growing disparity in the overall market. While the major
stock indexes are trading at or near record highs, three-quarters
of the stocks in the S&AMP;P index, and 88 percent of the stocks traded
on the New York Stock Exchange, are more than 10 percent below
their all-time highs.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the gauges can be traced to how they are
calculated. The Dow industrial average is price-weighted, meaning
that high priced-stocks, like IBM at over $177 a share, have more
of an effect on the Dow than do low-priced stocks like Disney, at
about $33. That is true even though a company with a low share
price but substantially more shares in circulation could be worth
more.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the S&AMP;P indexes are weighted by market
capitalization, meaning that the indexes are most influenced by
companies whose total stock market value _ derived by multiplying
their share price by the number of shares in circulation _ is
greatest.
</P>
<P>
   A system such as the Dow's price-based system was necessary in
the late 19th century, when the Dow was first compiled and the
calculations had to be done with pencil and paper. The first
calculations, in 1896 with a group of 12 stocks, were very simple:
add the stocks' prices and divide by 12.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the average is calculated by dividing the sum of the
prices by a fractional divisor, currently about 0.225. That means
that each $1 change in the price of a Dow stock moves the average
by about 4.44 points.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of superfast computers and instant reporting of
changes in stock prices, any index can be calculated in a
microsecond, adjusted for stock splits and dividends. More
importantly for the companies that devise and market indexes for
use with options, futures and other derivatives contracts, an index
can be frequently tinkered with through the removal and replacement
of companies without difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   That has caused new indexes to sprout like mushrooms, with each
seeming to slice the stock market into ever-smaller pieces.
Bloomberg lists 417 indexes tracking U.S. equity markets alone.
</P>
<P>
   From a statistical perspective, however, the Dow is among the
most efficient gauges around. It uses only 30 stocks, which
together account for close to a quarter of the stock market's total
value. The S&AMP;P 500's components, which together account for about
four-fifths of the market's total value, are, by comparison, much
closer to a full census than a sampling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Recently, critics of the Dow have argued that the older gauge,
having missed the upswing caused by the Internet investment mania,
lags behind too far. From the beginning of 1995, when the latest
leg of the stock market's upward march began, through the end of
1998, the Dow climbed 24.3 percent annually, compared with 27.8
percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   The difference stems primarily from the absence of the
technology giants Intel and Microsoft from the Dow industrials.
While the Dow has contained IBM since 1981 and Hewlett-Packard
since 1997, those stocks have not performed as well as Intel and
Microsoft, the stars of the new economy built around personal
computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Over longer periods, however, the gauges track quite closely.
Since the beginning of 1980 through the end of last year, the Dow
gained 13.4 percent a year, compared with 13.6 percent for the S&AMP;P
500. Including reinvested dividends, a measure known as total
return, an investment in the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 would have come
even closer _ an average annual gain of 17.72 percent for the Dow
industrials versus 17.65 percent for the S&AMP;P
</P>
<P>
   Even when measured since the beginning of 1990, the two
benchmarks differ by an average of less than a half of 1 percent a
year: 17.8 percent for the S&AMP;P 500 versus 17.4 percent for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of indexes in part comes from the desire to
more closely track certain sectors of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what you want a benchmark to be,'' said Leah
Modigliani, an equity strategist at Morgan Stanley. ``It serves to
represent a universe of investments, to act as a benchmark'' for
investment managers to measure their own performance.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, stock market gauges have also provided an
alternative investment, one that frequently can be had at a lower
cost than charged by traditional portfolio managers. Today, index
mutual funds and unit investment trusts track virtually every stock
market gauge imaginable, from subsets of Internet stocks to the
entire universe of publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, the Dow has a lot of problems that are well
known,'' said Theodore R. Aronson, a money manager and market
analyst at Aronson + Partners in Philadelphia. ``I nonetheless
marvel at how experts in the field allude to it. And it's still
hands-down the most popular shorthand for how the market's done. I
wake up each morning as National Public Radio is reporting the Dow,
which they still do to two decimal places. Think about how
meaningless that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Leuthold, people seem to be increasingly frightened
by the Dow's amplitude. Hundred-point swings in the Dow often
result in bigger headlines in the next day's paper, even though 100
points recently represented little more than a move of 1 percent in
the average.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow crossing 10,000, perhaps the excitement that has
come with each 1,000-point mark will die down. But the 10,000 level
might also represent a level that has greater historic resonance to
investors. For once it reaches the Promised Land, will the Dow be
able to move on?
</P>
<P>
   Consider that for six periods from 1963 to 1982, the Dow Jones
industrial average approached or crossed the 1,000 level, only to
retreat back into triple digits. The first of those concluded a
fantastic run of three and a half years, during which the Dow
gained more than 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow first finished a full day of trading above 1,000 in
November 1972. But it was not until a full decade later, at the
beginning of the bull market in late 1982, that the Dow average
firmly climbed above the 1,000 mountain. Today, of course, it looks
more like a molehill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
