<HEADLINE>
UNMANNED AIRCRAFT READIED FOR BALKANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Nev.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(jw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States has sent at least three unmanned
drone airplanes, known as Predators, to the Balkans to detect and
photograph Serbian troops and air defense systems and to document
Serbian attacks against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Pentagon
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo planes carrying the Predators and the equipment needed
to operate them began arriving in Bosnia on Wednesday, said Mike
Estrada, spokesman for Nellis Air Force base, which is the
Predators' home base in Las Vegas. It will take at least two more
days to finish setting up the necessary equipment to navigate the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   These remotely piloted reconnaissance airplanes can be sent over
the most heavily defended targets. Moreover, they can take video
film and relay images of events on the ground as they are
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials refused to say why these aircraft had not
been sent earlier so that they would have been ready when the air
war began.
</P>
<P>
   While they are not stealth airplanes and can be picked up on
radar, they are so small they are difficult to see and hard to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large van acts as its control stations with lots of
antennas,'' Estrada said. ``The airplanes themselves were broken
down and put into large boxes we call coffins and now have to be
reassembled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Predator's equipment includes a daylight camera, an infrared
system for use at night and radar that can see through clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Predator can stay up in the air for more than 24 hours and
photograph whatever you want,'' Estrada said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8768 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1     03-29 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1,250(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REFOCUSES TARGETS TO HALT SERBIAN ATTACKS ON ALBANIANS IN
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map showing
targets of attack is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO air attacks shifted toward Serbian troop
staging areas in embattled Kosovo on Monday as the Clinton
administration claimed that evidence of ``genocide'' by Serb forces
was growing to include ``abhorrent and criminal action'' on a
massive scale.
</P>
<P>
   The language was the State Department's strongest yet in
denouncing Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic as reports
increased of Serb assassinations of ethnic Albanian leaders and of
the scorched-earth torching of Kosovar villages.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of refugees continued to flee in terror from
Serb forces, pouring into neighboring Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro and compounding the Balkan region's massive refugee
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic has adopted what can only be described as
a siege mentality,'' said British Air Commodore David Wilby at NATO
headquarters in Brussels. ``He believes he can realign his ethnic
problems in one week and that NATO unity will crack in that same
period,'' he said of the nonstop refugee flow that officials fear
could further destabilize the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said their air assault was directed increasingly
at Milosevic's field forces in Kosovo as the suffering there
worsened among ethnic Albanians. ``Major attacks'' were delivered
Sunday night on the 243rd Serb combat group at Donja Somanja in
Kosovo, according to NATO military officials who said the Serb unit
has been directing attacks on Kosovar Albanian villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade claimed its forces had shot down a second NATO plane,
but this was not immediately confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are indicators that genocide is unfolding in Kosovo,''
said State Department spokesman James Rubin, invoking a word heady
with implications of proof and punishment in international law.
There is no reason to await confirmation before using the word, he
argued, ``because we can clearly say crimes against humanity are
being committed'' that carry penalties of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Let me say that the abhorrent and criminal actions,
I mean on a massive scale, are occurring in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the new air assaults in Kosovo were thus
far directed at troop staging areas, rather than at tanks,
artillery pieces, and the small mobile military units that the
Serbs have been using in their attacks on Kosovo villages. The A-10
``Warthog'' plane designed to make low-run, low-speed attacks on
tanks and field artillery was reported taking to the air for the
first time in the six-day-old NATO assault, but there were no
immediate reports of any dramatic success in stopping Serb attacks
on Kosovar civilians.
</P>
<P>
   More U.S. warplanes were committed to the NATO operation Monday,
including B-1B bombers equipped with a variety of bombs, such as
cluster ``bomblets.'' More EA-6B Prowler aircraft designed to
confuse enemy radar systems were also dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic military bullet here,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Ken Bacon, facing increasingly sharp questions about the
efficacy of the air attacks in the face of the heightened Serbian
onslaught against ethnic Albanians. ``There is not a quick
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said he was
alarmed by reports of ``some of these refugees being herded into
concentration areas'' by Serb forces. He cited one report,
unconfirmed as yet by eyewitnesses, of 20,000 refugees concentrated
around Srbica. ``We remember the way in which many refugees were
herded together and executed by the Serb forces during the civil
war in Bosnia,'' he added ominously.
</P>
<P>
   As doubts and criticism of the NATO assault increased, one
immediate question was whether the political leaders of NATO might
ease restrictions on the missile and bombing attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a question that I would like to address
today,'' Wilby responded when asked at a briefing whether the NATO
command had prevented the allied bombers from attacking Serbia's
Interior Ministry in Belgrade, where the operations in Kosovo are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was denounced by NATO officials for waging a
``scorched earth'' siege in routing the ethnic Albanians, whose
autonomy within Serbia was stripped away by the Serbian dictator 10
years ago. Kosovo, the southern province of the Serbian republic in
which ethnic Albanians account for nine-tenths of the population,
is hallowed ground to the Serbs, and a touchstone in Milosevic's
ultranationalist campaign to maintain power.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Kosovo villages were reported under assault and burning
between Pec and Klina on Monday, with Albanian residents fleeing
the Serbs, NATO said. Three villages west of Pristina, the Kosovo
capital, were also reported aflame by NATO officials, who have
tended to offer the public more specific details on the Kosovo
scene than their American counterparts here.
</P>
<P>
   As calls mounted for more immediate results by NATO, President
Clinton interrupted a Virginia golf outing to telephone British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder.
At the Pentagon, the Joint Chiefs of Staff met in private, with
Kosovo heading their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front, administration officials expressed
little optimism that Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's trip
to Belgrade Tuesday would bear much fruit in the way of ending the
NATO assault unless he somehow reverses Milosevic's adamancy in
refusing to retreat from his year-long Kosovo campaign. Some
officials voiced concerns that Primakov might push the Serbs into a
deal short of what NATO is demanding _ autonomy for Kosovo under
the protection of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   It was still not clear Monday what brought down an F-117 stealth
fighter over Yugoslavia on Saturday. Bacon said American military
officials still do not know the cause of the crash, in which the
pilot survived and was rescued. Bacon declined to comment on
reports that some Pentagon officials were convinced the aircraft
was hit by a surface-to-air missile, or that there appeared to be
bullet holes in one wing.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million ethnic Albanians _ a fifth of the province
_ were already reported to have fled their homes over the past
year. Tens of thousands more have taken to the roads since the NATO
bombings began, with some even being stripped of their
identification papers and being forced to pay bribes at the Serb
borders, according to NATO complaints. The refugees are being
prodded by Milosevic's troops and paramilitary police as well as by
what NATO officials described as murderous gangs in mufti bearing
such names as the Vucak Wolves, already infamous from earlier
ethnic wars.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty thousand Kosovo refugees have descended upon hard-pressed
neighboring Albania since last weekend, according to State
Department officials who estimated the flow was continuing at 2,000
per hour. In Macedonia, there were an estimated 22,000 refugees as
U.N. relief officials held emergency meetings to deal with the
crisis. In Montenegro, at least 28,000 refugees have flowed in from
Pec, the Kosovo border city that remained under siege and burning,
according to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday night Serbian forces rounded up Albanian men
throughout Pec and marched them off in an unknown direction,''
Wilby reported as NATO and Clinton administration officials
heightened warnings that war-crime investigations will be pressed
all the way down the Serb military command to line officers in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your responsibility,'' declared Cook, angrily
addressing the Serbian officers corps. ``We know the chain of
command back to the political leadership in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said the Kosovar villages were despairing. ``Helicopters
are being used against the civil population,'' he said.
``Paramilitaries enter towns and villages and terrify the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the war misery of the Kosovars deepened, the White House
denied the NATO raids had only encouraged Milosevic to hasten the
routing of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were faced with a choice here, which was do we act or do we
not act?'' said Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman. ``And we
think by acting we will make him pay a price,'' he said. ``The
reason they, as a group, are better off is that this was done in
the past with impunity,'' he said of the Serb assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Cook, facing similar questioning, declared, ``If we
had not acted, all of you would now be asking why we stood by while
this ethnic cleansing took place.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House declared once more that there was ``absolutely
no change'' in the president's insistence that American ground
troops would not be used against the Serbs. Pentagon officials
emphasized that an adequate troop operation could take weeks to
mount, if it ever were decided upon, because the Serbs already have
40,000 troops in Kosovo backed by hundreds of tanks and artillery
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The reported atrocities cited by the State Department and NATO
officials, who stressed on-site confirmation was not yet possible,
included 20 village school teachers who were said to have been
gunned down by Serbs in front of their students in the village of
Goden, according to Cook. NATO reported Serb gunmen had tracked
down and executed at least five prominent ethnic Albanians,
including Batan Haxhiu, editor of the main ethnic Albanian
newspaper, and Fehmi Agani, a member of the Kosovar Albanian peace
negotiating team that met in February at Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials strenuously denied that the air assaults had
prompted the heightened Milosevic onslaught against the Kosovars,
noting that Serb forces have been massing in Kosovo for months and
were aggressively on the move when NATO felt obliged to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a campaign under way to ethnically re-engineer the
makeup of Kosovo,'' said Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman in
Brussels. ``To reshape the political map of Kosovo so that
Milosevic later on would hope to achieve a negotiated solution more
favorable to Belgrade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
