<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVORKIAN-725(2TAKES)     03-29 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVORKIAN TRIAL SENDS A MESSAGE, BUT WHICH ONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian may be the nation's most visible
and vocal advocate of assisted suicide. But many proponents of
assisted suicide believe his second-degree murder conviction last
week, in the death of a seriously ill man, could help them.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the debate over assisted suicide is reaching into
state legislatures and ballot initiatives, many experts and
advocates say Kevorkian, who claims to have helped more than 130
people die, has made things harder for the assisted-suicide cause.
They say his provocative style may have attracted supporters and
raised awareness of the issue, but it has also alienated some
people who might have been sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   And advocates say that by videotaping himself giving a man a
lethal injection, bringing the tape to the CBS News program ``60
Minutes,'' and daring prosecutors to charge him with murder, he was
trying to move the legal system farther and faster than most
Americans were ready to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a sideshow or a distraction,'' said Dr. Timothy
E. Quill, a Rochester, N.Y., doctor who became one of the
standard-bearers for the assisted-suicide movement after he wrote
an article in 1991 describing how he had helped a patient kill
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Quill added, ``I think there was a growing desire on everybody's
part to sort of slow him down or stop him, because he was pushing
it farther and farther.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a desire that these advocates found difficult to express
publicly until now, for fear of losing Kevorkian's loyal followers,
who consider him courageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a fear that if they publicly indicated
Kevorkian was a loser and they wished he would go away, it would
create too much Sturm und Drang in the movement,'' said David J.
Garrow, a historian at Emory University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of assisted suicide say the advocates of it are
merely engaging in spin control, and the verdict will actually have
the effect of making assisted suicide less acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no win for them,'' said Dr. Gregory Hamilton, the
president of an Oregon-based group called Physicians for
Compassionate Care. ``This gives a message to people in America
that killing sick people is not the answer to life's problems, that
it is appropriate to have laws against it and to punish the
perpetrators of these crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But George Eighmey, the executive director of a group in Oregon
called Compassion in Dying, which fought successfully for the
nation's only law permitting assisted suicide, said the conviction
helps the mainstream wing of the movement because it came in a case
of euthanasia, in which a third party administered the patient's
fatal dose of chemicals, instead of the patient taking them on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Though many Americans do not generally make the distinction
between euthanasia and assisted suicide, Eighmey and other
assisted-suicide advocates say they do not support euthanasia
because it takes the final control of the decision to die out of
the patient's hands. They also say polls show that people are more
comfortable supporting laws like Oregon's, which took effect in
1997. That law not only requires the patient to take the lethal
drugs without help, but stipulates that a patient committing
assisted suicide must be terminally ill and that two doctors must
determine the patient has less than six months to live.
</P>
<P>
   The people Kevorkian assisted were not always terminally ill,
and he supports either method of helping someone die. His
conviction came in a case in which he injected Thomas Youk with
lethal chemicals. Youk, 52, had amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or
Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prosecutors tried and failed four times to convict
Kevorkian in non-euthanasia cases in which the patient administered
the drugs or carbon monoxide by pulling a string or using a switch.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, advocates like Eighmey say the verdict will
convince more people that laws are necessary to make some types of
assisted suicide legal, while outlawing more extreme measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know the unacceptable limits and we now, as a society,
can move in the direction of those acceptable limits,'' Eighmey
said. ``I think Dr. Kevorkian's trial messages, let's move in the
direction of the more moderate Oregon model, instead of the
Kevorkian model.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of assisted suicide say that it is disingenuous to
attempt to make a distinction between euthanasia and assisted
suicide because once it is legal for doctors to give lethal doses
of drugs to terminally ill people, they will find reasons to argue
that people who are too disabled to take the drugs themselves
should be allowed to ask someone to help them die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed a slippery slope,'' said Dr. Rex Greene, the
president of the Los Angeles County Medical Association.
``Sanctioning this will eventually lead to the kind of activities
that Kevorkian has typified.'' Not every assisted-suicide advocate
believes the verdict will advance their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could force more doctors to go underground, and patients to
figure out ways to do this without the help of doctors,'' said Dr.
Faye Girsh, the executive director of the Hemlock Society, which
supports assisted suicide and euthanasia and sees little
distinction between the two. ``This will certainly not embolden
other doctors to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian's lawyer, David Gorosh, who plans to appeal the
conviction, said his client will ultimately be ``lauded as a hero
in history.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if Kevorkian, who has said he will starve
himself in prison, will be nudged completely out of the limelight
of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid we haven't heard the last of him,'' Quill said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, some 20 state legislatures have either rejected or
blocked laws legalizing assisted suicide and voters have rejected
ballot initiatives in California, Washington and Michigan. A
handful of states have explicitly outlawed it. But the issue
remains a contentious one and proposals to legalize assisted
suicide are pending in Maine and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are watching the effects of the Oregon law. In its
first year, 15 people took their lives under the law, a result that
advocates say proves that assisted suicide can be legalized
responsibly. But critics say those results prove little. They say
that a recent case of a man whose brother-in-law said he helped him
commit assisted suicide shows that the line between assisted
suicide and euthanasia is easily blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who oppose assisted suicide say they expect more
public support for assisted suicide laws, since many people say
they want the right to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more pressure on legislatures to legalize,''
said Dr. Steven Miles, a geriatrician at the University of
Minnesota, although he said that because of the verdict, fewer
doctors will risk performing assisted suicides while the practice
remains illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Quill thinks the movement is more likely to have success
persuading the public to accept more moderate steps, such as
counseling patients about stopping eating and drinking to hasten
their death, which is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, many involved in caring for the terminally ill,
including some who support assisted suicide, hope for another
result too, one that could affect many more people. They hope there
will be increased momentum in the growing movement to improve the
care of chronically ill and dying patients so that fewer people
will believe that assisted suicide is their best option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go before we can be optimistic about
end of life care _ pain control, Medicare entitlement, hospice
care, home care,'' Miles said. ``Now, the argument for palliative
care gets much stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
