<HEADER>
A8772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV04-NYT     03-29 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY SHALL RETURN  
 GIVERNY IN BLOOM  
 HAWAII LAYOVER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Do you know of any agencies that organize trips to
World War II sites in the Pacific (Guadalcanal, Iwo Jima, etc.)? _
Joseph M. Hassett, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Among the possibilities you may want to pursue are these,
which turned up on the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Valor Tours, 10 Liberty Ship Way, Sausalito, Calif. 94965, (800)
842-4504, www.valortours.com, was founded by Bob Reynolds, a World
War II pilot. Its General Wainwright tour to Corregidor is May 2 to
11. You will tour the island fortress, visit Bataan and participate
in a memorial ceremony. Price: $2,200 a person, double occupancy,
with air fare from San Francisco, rooms and many meals.
</P>
<P>
   Midway is the destination of a trip from June 18 to 23. The
island's varied wildlife is one of the main attractions, along with
visits to pillboxes, guns, airstrips and other relics of battle.
Price: $1,595 a person, double occupancy, with air fare from
Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   The company's annual cruise through the Solomon Islands wartime
sites, including Guadalcanal, is July 29 to Aug. 10. Among the
stops is the island of Lumbaria, where President Kennedy's PT boat
was based. The cruise is on the 21-passenger, 125-foot Spirit of
Solomons. The price is $3,900 to $5,000 a person, double occupancy,
with air fare from Los Angeles, depending on cabin choice.
</P>
<P>
   Pactours, (800) 245-4129 or www.pactours(AT)ite.net, will offer
a Return to Guam tour July 18 to 23, to mark the 55th anniversary
of the island's liberation. Besides visiting battle sites, veterans
will have breakfast with the governor of Guam and march in the
Liberation Day Parade, where the island's residents will have a
chance to express their gratitude. The price of $1,895 a person,
double occupancy, includes air fare from most major United States
cities, four nights in the Guam Hilton, bus transportation, tour
guides and some meals.
</P>
<P>
   Military Historical Tours, 4600 Duke Street, Suite 420,
Alexandria, Va. 22304, (800) 722-9501, will conduct its own Guam
liberation tour, the Last Hurrah, July 19 to 25. Gen. Louis H.
Wilson, who won the Medal of Honor on Guam and has retired from the
Marine Corps, will be the tour host. The price of $2,295 a person,
double occupancy, includes round-trip air fare from Los Angeles,
accommodations at the Guam Hilton, daily breakfasts and some other
meals, battlefield tours and reserved seats at the Liberation Day
parade.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also mark the 55th anniversary of the
liberation of Peleliu with a tour Sept. 11 to 16. The hosts will be
two retired marine officers, Gen. Ray Davis, who won the Navy Cross
on the island, and Col. Joe Alexander, a corps historian.
</P>
<P>
   Peleliu, a five-square-mile atoll in the Palau chain, was the
site of a fierce two-month battle starting in Sept. 15, 1944, that
resulted in heavy casualties. The tour is based on Koror, where
boats leave to visit the battlefields on Peleliu and Anguar. The
price, $2,595 a person double occupancy, includes air fare from the
West Coast, a one-night stop in Guam, tours, all breakfasts and
some other meals and accommodations at the Palau Pacific Resort.
Optional extensions to Manila, Honolulu and Corregidor are
available. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Could you please tell me when is the best time to
visit Monet's house in Giverny to see the gardens in full bloom? _
Leah R. Herzfeld, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Claude Monet, a founder of Impressionism, moved to Giverny in
1883 and lived there until his death in 1926. In the last decade of
his life, with his eyesight failing, he painted his series of
water-lily murals. And tourists now flock there to see the gardens
that inspired the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The house, called the Fondation Claude Monet, and its vast
gardens opened for the season on Thursday, and will remain open
until Oct. 31. You may visit daily except Monday, from 10 a.m. to 6
p.m. Call (33-2) 32.51.28.21; $5.80 for the house and garden, $4
for the garden only.
</P>
<P>
   Some fruit trees are already in bloom, but the period when the
most color can be seen is from mid-May until the end of June. This,
of course, is also the most crowded period. If you avoid weekends,
when crowds are nearly unbearable, you will have some elbow room.
Weekdays can be busy, too, with schoolchildren arriving by the
busload on field trips. Wednesday is the day with the lightest
school traffic, the staff says.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what month you visit, there should be some plants in
bloom, according to the staff. If you go by train, you will leave
from Gare St.-Lazare. Take the train toward Rouen, and get off at
the Vernon station. There, you should find tour buses or cabs for
the 10-minute trip to Giverny. The round-trip train fare should be
about $30 second class, $45 first class.
</P>
<P>
   By car, Giverny is about an hour to 90 minutes from Paris, along
the Paris-Rouen A13. Exit after the first toll from Paris and
follow the signs to Vernon, then signs to Giverny, across the
bridge over the Seine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)A friend and I will be going to Hawaii for a few
days after a two-week trip to China. Can you recommend any
bed-and-breakfasts in or near Honolulu that are quiet, near the
water and accessible by public transportation? We would like to
spend about $100 a night. _ Salvina L. Scerri, New York, N.Y.(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Your choices will be much greater if you consider the entire
island of Oahu. There are not many B&AMP;Bs near Waikiki, but Joanne
Trotter operates an inn at a beautiful old traditional-style home
in a residential area about a 20-minute walk from the beach. It is
surrounded by large old trees, and if you are bird watchers, you'll
enjoy the fairy terns. Call (808) 923-3905.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to shop for your breakfast, consider these:
</P>
<P>
   Ke Iki Hale in Haleiwa, on the North Shore, is a long ride by
bus, but it is accessible by public transit and sits on a
spectacular beach. It is not fancy, and there's no breakfast. But
there is a market nearby. Ask for one of the oceanside units, which
start at $138. Call or fax (808) 638-8229.
</P>
<P>
   On windward Oahu, Pat O'Malley operates Pat's Kailua Beach
Properties, (808) 261-1653, with a wide range of rentals, most on
or near beautiful Kailua Beach, starting at $65 a night, with a
three-night minimum. It's on the bus line. No meals, but food and
restaurants are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Also on windward Oahu, Lanikai Bed &AMP; Breakfast is across the
street from Lanikai Beach, right on the bus line. From $65 a night,
without breakfast (although it still calls itself a bed and
breakfast); there's usually a three-night minimum. Call (800)
258-7895 or (808) 261-1059.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
