<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0330-C     03-29 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0330-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUNISHING NATO AIR CAMPAIGN NOT STOPPING 'SCORCHED EARTH'
CAMPAIGN IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TROOPS-0330; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0330.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attacking civilians with helicopters, leveling
villages with heavy artillery and executing victims at will, Serb
troops stepped up what NATO called a ''scorched earth'' campaign
across Kosovo on Monday, putting to flight an estimated 300,000
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO reported that Serb paramilitary thugs executed a prominent
Kosovo diplomat, a newspaper editor and two other people in the
Kosovo capital of Pristina, in what human rights officials said
confirmed their worst fears about the terror unleashed inside the
tiny province.
</P>
<P>
   In a chilling echo of Serb tactics in Bosnia earlier this
decade, an estimated 20,000 ethnic Albanians have been herded
together by Serb forces near the town of Srbica, west of Pristina,
NATO officials said, with others rounded up near Prizren further
south, where a half dozen neighboring villages were ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Further west, the city of Pec, important commercially and
culturally, was ``substantially destroyed,'' after men were
ominously rounded up and women and children ordered to flee or face
slaughter, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters at alliance
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a desperate race against the savage ground tactics,
U.S. and allied forces turned a punishing air campaign directly
onto Serb military positions throughout Kosovo. American pilots
flew battlefield-grazing A-10 tank killers for the first time and
struck with other warplanes from higher altitudes at troops,
barracks and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The White House continued to rule out the use of ground troops,
insisting that air power alone could exact a painful toll on Serb
forces and, eventually, strip them of their ability to wage terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, the military leadership of this country, NATO,
the political leaders of NATO, believe we can accomplish our
military objectives through the air campaign that is ongoing,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. ``We are in what
could be the early part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth day of air strikes, American pilots flew A-10
Thunderbolt warplanes, built during the Cold War as a defense
against a Soviet tank invasion in Europe. The planes fly low and
slow over combat zones with the aim of destroying tanks, armored
personnel carriers and heavy artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces now have roughly 400 tanks, 300 armored personnel
carriers and 400 heavy artillery pieces in and around Kosovo,
supporting some 40,000 troops and hundreds of paramilitary thugs
rampaging across the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also ordered five heavy B-1 bombers -- which can
carry up to 84 500-pound bombs, or 30 cluster bombs, each of which
unleashes 200 armor-piercing bomblets -- to the region, in a sign
that the United States plans to pound Serb troop positions and
vehicle columns with massive firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the B-1 bombers would
arrive in the area before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also dispatched five additional EA-6Bs, jets used
to jam radar and other electronic systems critical to air defense
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom also beefed up its air arsenal, ordering four
additional Harrier jets -- also capable of attacking ground combat
forces at relatively close range -- and eight additional Tornado
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the NATO attacks are being repackaged daily to bring
to bear the most potent and swiftest possible firepower directly
onto the forces carrying out the terror in Kosovo on the orders of
of Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether I'd call it a race against time,'' said
Bacon. ``From the beginning it's been a race against Milosevic . .
. It is a race against Milosevic's murderous ways.''
</P>
<P>
   As refugees staggered across Kosovo's border into Albania at the
rate of 4,000 per hour, the State Department, for the first time,
suggested that Serb forces might be carrying out genocide, a legal
term with specific ramifications for the prosecution of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abhorrent and criminal actions, I mean on a massive scale, are
occurring in Kosovo,'' State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These include ethnic cleansing, war crimes and crimes against
humanity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday in Pristina, Serbs executed Fehmi Agani, who was a
member of the Kosovar Albanian delegation to the recent peace
negotiations in France, NATO reported. He was killed shortly after
attending the funeral of a prominent human rights lawyer, who was
executed, along with his two sons, in Pristina on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, Serbs executed Baton Haxhui, the editor in chief
of a popular Albanian newspaper in Kosovo, NATO reported.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of additional atrocities poured out of Kosovo. While
impossible to verify each report, Lockhart said the overall picture
was as credible as it was shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have increasing reports, as people come across the border,
of atrocities, of men being separated from their families, of
executions, of towns being burned down, people being told to leave
within hours of face execution,'' Lockhart told reporters at the
White House. ``There are clearly an increasing number of these
reports, and we find them credible.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials described in grim vignettes the brutality of the
ongoing repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helicopters are being used against the civil population.
Paramilitaries enter towns and villages and terrify the people,''
British Air Force Air Commodore David Wilby said at NATO
headquarters. ``Seven villages were set on fire between Pec and
Klina. Three villages west of Pristina were also burning, more
examples of the scorched-earth policy to discourage refugee
returns.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials insisted, however, that the Serb actions had been
planned for weeks by Milosevic and would have taken place with or
without NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current campaign is not a spontaneous outburst following
NATO's operations,'' Shea said. ``It looks much more like a
planned, conceived and executed . . . campaign against the civil
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Shea, ``We clearly see who is the victim and who is the
victimizer in this very, very difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence of Serb designs to permanently rid Kosovo of
as many Albanians as possible, Shea said, troops were demanding
that Kosovars relinquish their passports even as they were being
forced at gunpoint to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Refugees entering Albania are being stripped by the Serb
border forces of their passports, their ID cards, their papers,''
Shea said. ``It's almost as if their identities are being cancelled
out, as if they're being declared nonpersons, and, of course, that
makes any subsequent effort to return them to Yugoslavia much more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook told reporters in London
that Milosevic is trying to impose ``a new apartheid in Europe,
based on the cleansing, the forcible removal and execution of
people of the wrong ethnic identity in his region.
</P>
<P>
   ``That practice belonged to the Middle Ages. It does not belong
to the modern Europe,'' Cook said. ``We are right to fight it, and
that is why we cannot sop military action until we have stopped
that repression on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials estimate that more than 3,000 people
have been killed in a year-long crackdown on ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, a province in the republic of Serbia, one of two states,
along with neighboring Montenegro, making up the rump Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the State Department estimated that more than a
half million people have been forced from their homes in the
province -- nearly one fourth of the population of 2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, that number could be low. The Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, which has been closely
monitoring the Kosovo situation for months, estimated that there
were more than 280,000 displaced people inside the province as of
Monday, a number likely rising by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday, there were an estimated 65,000 Kosovar Albanians
that had crossed into Albania; perhaps 30,000 in neighboring
Montenegro; and another 20,000 in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-nation NATO alliance launched air strikes against
Yugoslavia last week, after the collapse of intensive international
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel Albanians -- who seek independence for the province --
agreed earlier this month to end their attacks on Serb security
forces if Serbs would accept a U.S.-backed peace plan calling for a
NATO peacekeeping force of 28,000 troops -- 4,000 of them American
-- in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insisted Monday that the diplomatic door remains
open, and that air strikes can end anytime if Milosevic agrees to
the peace framework.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov was scheduled to meet
with Milosevic in Belgrade on Tuesday, pressing a diplomatic end to
the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were not optimistic about Primakov's meeting, but
stressed that the White House supports any effort to persuade
Milosevic to accept the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome those who have influence on Belgrade who will take
a message about what it is they need to do in order to end this
allied air campaign,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been a partner in the international efforts to broker
peace in Kosovo. Moscow has been an avid critic of NATO airstrikes,
though, against its Slavic brethren, the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
