<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN LEADER VOWS TO END DECADES OF CORRUPTION AND RIGHTS ABUSE

</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The president-elect of Nigeria came to New York on
Monday to say that his country, an international pariah for 16
years, is now headed firmly toward democratic rule, privatization
of its huge oil industry and an end to decades of official
corruption and severe human rights abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Olusegun Obasanjo, 61, whose election on Feb. 27 was welcomed by
the West, appeared frank and direct as he spoke about Nigeria's
unsavory reputation. But he declined to offer specifics on what he
vowed would be sweeping reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you are used to bad news from Nigeria,'' he said,
adding that his country had been ``among the leading corrupt
nations of the world.'' He added: ``There is virtually no sector of
our society that has not been wounded. We have to bind the wounds
and bring conciliation and unity, give people hope and a sense of
belonging and participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is Africa's most populous nation, with 108 million
inhabitants. It suffered a ruthless dictatorship under Gen. Sani
Abacha, which ended last June after five years when Abacha died
unexpectedly. His successor, Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, began a
series of reforms, including elections, which ended in victory for
Obasanjo, a retired general and former president. He is to be
inaugurated on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo exuded charisma and self-confidence at the news
conference on Monday, with his powerful frame cloaked in a majestic
blue robe. He said his trip here, part of a world tour, was aimed
at reassuring political and business leaders of his sincerity,
skill and determination.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected in Washington on Tuesday to meet with top
American officials, including Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and, tentatively, President Clinton, as well as leaders of the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund. He arrived here from
Europe, where he had offered his message of hope to the leaders and
investors of France, Germany and Britain, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Large advertising spreads in international newsmagazines and on
CNN in recent weeks have also sought to drive home the point that
Nigeria, one of the world's largest exporters of oil, has embarked
on a new course.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo was asked Monday if he would follow the South African
model of healing society's wounds with the equivalent of a Truth
and Reconciliation Commission to investigate the misdeeds of his
predecessors and their aides. He declined to commit himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am on the saddle, then I'll make definitive
pronouncements,'' he said. He added that he did not now have the
information he needed. For example, speaking of his own
imprisonment for three years in 1995, he said he did not know the
story behind it.
</P>
<P>
   He was slightly more forthcoming in an interview with a
syndicated columnist, Jonathan Power, that appeared in The Los
Angeles Times on Sunday. On corruption, he said, ``You must show
that the practices you want to get rid of are punished,'' and
added: ``I will more than crack the whip. I will use the whip.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, a Yoruba from southern Nigeria, is said to have close
links to northern military leaders and was viewed during the
election campaign as a bridge between the two regions. He is the
only Nigerian ruler ever to have stepped down voluntarily, which he
did in 1979. At the time, he set the stage for a democratic system,
which was overthrown a few years later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
