<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-AFFIRMATIVE-HN     03-29 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-AFFIRMATIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REFUSES TO HEAR APPEAL TO REINSTATE
AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court refused Monday to hear Dallas'
appeal to reinstate the Fire Department's affirmative-action
program, which a federal court had struck down as discriminatory
against white men.
</P>
<P>
   While setting no national precedent, the justices' action left
intact the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' decision that the
city had failed to justify its preference for promoting women and
minorities as essential to remedy past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that affirmative-action programs are
constitutional only if they are ``narrowly tailored'' to remedy the
lingering effects of past discrimination. But the justices have yet
to define clearly how serious the effects must be to warrant
favoring women and minorities in employment and contracting
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, citing the
court's failure to define when affirmative-action plans are valid,
objected to their colleagues' refusal to hear Dallas's appeal. The
two justices _ who are President Clinton's only appointees to the
high court _ argued that the constitutionality of
affirmative-action programs nationwide will remain in question
until the high court gives definition.
</P>
<P>
   Under Supreme Court rules, at least four of the nine justices
must vote to hear an appeal before the high court will consider the
case. The court did not disclose whether any of the other seven
justices joined Breyer and Ginsburg in voting to hear Dallas's
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had argued that the 5th Circuit failed to give sufficient
weight to the low numbers of women and minorities in senior
positions at the city's fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas also argued that the appeals court did not adequately
consider the history of discrimination in the fire house. The U.S.
Justice Department filed a civil-rights lawsuit against the city in
the 1970s, which Dallas settled in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas adopted its affirmative-action plan in 1988, when three
of the department's 103 lieutenants were black, three were Hispanic
and all were men.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Department began promoting black, Hispanic and female
firefighters ahead of their white male colleagues who had scored
several points higher on the promotion examination.
</P>
<P>
   As of March 31, 1993, 17 of the department's 158 lieutenants
were black, seven Hispanic and four female, the city said.
</P>
<P>
   White firefighters who were denied promotion _ and successfully
challenged the affirmative-action plan _ countered that, while
discrimination might be a serious problem in the city's fire
department, artificially boosting the test scores of women and
minorities was not a constitutional solution. They argued that the
city should have beefed up its efforts to increase the number of
minorities and women through other methods, such as better
recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that minorities and/or females continue to be
underrepresented in certain jobs does not mean that alternative
remedies have not been effective, but only that they do not operate
as quickly as out-of-rank promotions, based upon race and/or
gender,'' the white male firefighters argued in urging the justices
to reject Dallas's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
