</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NEWSPAGE-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW RISES 184.54 TO FINISH THE DAY OVER 10,000 FOR THE FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
 (fb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow achieved a perfect 10 on Monday. Thousand,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two weeks of thrust and parry, U.S. stock traders
pushed the Dow Jones industrial average above 10,000 on Monday and
kept it there until the end of the day's trading. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed at 10,006.78, up 184.54 points, or 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although 10,000 on the Dow was little more than a psychological
hurdle for investors, the market's move is significant in what it
reflects: unparalleled strength of the U.S. economy and American
corporations' dominance of the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   American companies are taking for themselves more and more of
the world's profits. ``Back in 1990 the U.S.'s share was 36
percent; last year it was 44 percent,'' said Jeffrey M. Applegate,
chief investment strategist at Lehman Brothers in New York. ``That
goes a long way toward explaining why U.S. equities have had such
exemplary performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Dow has doubled in less than four years; it reached
5,000 in November 1995. It is up nearly ten-fold since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market's ability to sustain itself through all sorts of
climates and economic conditions _ inflation/deflation, growth/lack
of growth _ has been impressive,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, president
of Birinyi &AMP; Associates in Greenwich, Conn., and global trading
consultant for Deutsche Bank. ``The ease and the consistency:
that's what's so surprising about the market.''
</P>
<P>
   A lurking concern, however, is just how narrow the market's
advance has been. A growing portion of Americans' money is devoted
to the 30 well-known companies in the Dow and the stocks in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which is near its peak. But many
portfolios have not matched the performance of the Dow and the S&AMP;P.
That's because a relatively small number of stocks have pulled the
indexes higher. The winners have been the best-known stocks with
household names, stocks like General Electric, American Express and
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The number of stocks that are down significantly in the broad
market far outpaces the number that are at their peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 76.4 percent of all stocks traded in the United States are
trailing the S&AMP;P's return by 15 percent or more. On the Nasdaq, 93
percent of stocks now fetch prices 10 percent or more below their
peaks, while 88 percent of the stocks on the New York Stock
Exchange fall into this category. Among the S&AMP;P stocks, three out
of four are at least 10 percent off their highs.
</P>
<P>
   According to statisticians at Salomon Smith Barney, the stocks
in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index were on average 22.6 percent off
their highs as of Friday, while the New York Stock Exchange issues
were on average 33.4 percent below their peaks. Revealing how
concentrated this rally has been among big stocks with household
names, the Nasdaq stocks are on average 41.8 percent lower than
their peaks. These include many of the hot technology and Internet
stocks so popular among investors.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has the road to Dow 10,000 been pothole free. The
financial crisis that began in Asia with the devaluation of the
Thai baht in July 1997 and migrated to Russia last summer and then
to Brazil late in the year gave stock market investors their first
taste of significant losses in eight years. But three cuts in
interest rates by the Federal Reserve Board turned stocks around
last fall, and they have not looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Economic problems still simmer overseas: fourth-quarter data
from Japan, Germany and much of Latin America show gross domestic
product falling there. Indeed, despite the strength of the U.S.
economy, the group of seven industrialized nations is expected to
show economic growth slowing to a 2.6 percent annualized rate in
the fourth quarter of 1998, well below the 4.3 percent generated by
these nations in the comparable period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But difficulties abroad have only served to make the U.S. stock
market more of a haven to investors worldwide. Because the U.S.
economy is almost alone in experiencing a boom right now, stocks of
big American companies are viewed as the best way for investors to
take advantage of the good times. Even escalating hostilities in
Kosovo did not dampen investor enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph J. Acampora, director of technical research at Prudential
Securities was an early Wall Street believer in Dow 10,000. On
March 16, when the average first topped 10,000 and then retreated,
Acampora exulted: ``It's exciting. It's America. We all should get
up and sing God Bless America. These are our big stocks that are
leading. It's anything but irrational.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The stock market surely is America today. An estimated 45
percent of U.S. households own equities, up from about 14 percent
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   And Americans who have been in the market during the 1990s have
been riding a superpowered engine of wealth creation. Over the past
decade, according to the Federal Reserve System, the value of
stocks held by U.S. households has risen 381 percent, before
inflation, handily beating real estate assets, which were up 55
percent for the period. The value of stocks held by American
households rose to $10.77 trillion last year and represented 25
percent of total household assets, up from 8 percent 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's increasing enthusiasm for stocks has been well
founded. For the last five years, the compounded annual return on
the S&AMP;P 500, including dividends, has averaged 24 percent, more
than double the 10.9 percent median annual increase in the index
since 1926.
</P>
<P>
   Declining interest rates, low inflation, increasing productivity
as a result of advancements in technology _ all have helped propel
American corporations to new levels of efficiency and the major
market averages to levels that are lofty by most measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lower rate structure has clearly been the majority of
strength in the market,'' said Ned Riley Jr., chief investment
officer at BankBoston. He argues that lower rates account for 80
percent of the return in the stock market this decade. ``Only 20
percent was the result of expanding earnings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But interest rates would never have fallen had inflation not
dwindled. On an annualized basis, consumer prices are rising 1.6
percent, well below the average annual rate of 3.2 percent since
1926.
</P>
<P>
   One reason inflation is virtually nonexistent even after years
of economic strength is that labor costs remain in the cellar. So
even as the economy expands, traditionally a precursor to increased
inflation, there is little threat of overall price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors behind the push to Dow 10,000 include an increase
in the nation's money supply, falling commodity prices and a very
recent and large decline in total shares outstanding in the market.
In the fourth quarter of last year, for example, the total shares
outstanding shrank by $178 billion, meaning investors had fewer
stocks from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rising tides of both the Dow and the S&AMP;P indexes have
not been enough to lift all investors' fortunes. With so many
stocks underwater, the market's rally sits on thinner and thinner
pilings.
</P>
<P>
   It is in fact a worry to many strategists that the market has
become even more bifurcated _ a few haves and many have-nots _ than
it was last year. While investors rhapsodize over big, famous-name
stocks like Microsoft and McDonald's, smaller issues are scorned.
The Russell 2000 index of small-capitalization stocks is down 7.7
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Timothy J. Morris, chief investment officer of Bessemer
Trust in New York, argues that this market split makes sense. ``You
could make a very strong argument that investors have acted
rationally, rewarding companies that have very strong earnings
gains and penalizing ones that haven't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, until the market's rise broadens to include more
than the top household-name companies, fears remain that the rally
will fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Acampora of Prudential Securities predicts that the Dow will hit
11,500 this year, a 15 percent gain from Monday's close. And it may
not be a coincidence that the average pressed through 10,000 just
two trading days after Abby Joseph Cohen, the Goldman Sachs
strategist who is also Wall Street's favorite bull, raised her
estimate slightly for stocks this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the forces that have helped push the market higher have
been losing steam in recent weeks. That leads some market analysts
to wonder how much more investors can expect from stocks this year.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in the nation's money supply has slowed substantially
this year. That growth in money, as measured in the broadest sense
to include money market funds, currency in circulation, checking
and savings accounts, helped stabilize the stock market during the
financial crises last fall. Much of the additional money found its
way into equities. A decline in that growth could put a lid on
stocks. Early this year, according to Christine Callies, equity
strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston, annualized growth in
money supply fell to 8.4 percent from 16.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates have also been nudged higher by bond traders,
nervous that strong economic growth in the United States could
ignite inflation. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond stands at
5.64 percent, well above the 5.1 percent level at year end. The
jump could be temporary, of course, but every increase in rates
makes bonds slightly more attractive when compared with stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry is that violent price swings in stocks are
increasing. According to the Leuthold Group, in the first two
months of the year, the S&AMP;P closed each day with an up or down move
of 1 percent or more 45 percent of the time. Between 1992 and 1998,
such moves took place only 8 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Dow reached the milestone on Monday, Tom Telegades,
who said he works for an Internet company, shrugged off its
importance on his way through Grand Central Terminal. ``I'm in the
market, but it has no impact on me whatsoever,'' he said. ``It
doesn't make any difference in my investment strategy. I'm not
doing anything extra because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' overall enthusiasm is not surprising, given stocks'
recent bravura performance. According to James Paulsen, chief
investment officer at Wells Capital Management in Minneapolis,
during the past five years, the stock market has declined about one
out of four days. Only during the bull stampede beginning in 1926
and extending to 1929 was there less downward movement in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This outsized performance has also brought stocks to valuations
never seen before. The stocks in the S.&AMP;P. 500 are trading at 34
times their earnings, more than double the median valuation of
around 15 for the index historically. And the value of the U.S.
stock market now exceeds the nation's gross domestic product by a
sizable amount.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, U.S. stocks are still very much the place to be.
Eight years of rising share prices are a powerful draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
