<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA GRANTS ASYLUM TO ACCUSED PARAGUAYAN GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The Argentine government Monday denied
a request by the newly installed Paraguayan government to extradite
its former military chief, who is accused of having ordered the
assassination of the Paraguayan vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine Interior Ministry announced that the former
commander, Gen. Lino Oviedo, would be granted political asylum, an
act that will surely create tensions between two partners in the
Mercosur trade union.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the new Paraguayan interior minister, Walter
Bower, said it would respect Argentina's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo's flight here on Sunday night to seek asylum and the
request for his extradition put Argentina in the middle of a
political crisis in Paraguay. The situation boiled over on Tuesday
with the assassination of Vice President Luis Maria Argana and
intensified on Sunday with the forced resignation of President Raul
Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   A Paraguayan judge Monday ordered Cubas to be placed under house
arrest on charges of negligent homicide stemming from the deaths of
several protesters last week. Bower later said Cubas had
parliamentary immunity and could not be detained. As a former
president, he is a senator for life.
</P>
<P>
   The protracted crisis dates from what was interpreted as a
failed coup attempt by Oviedo, a populist, in 1996 to oust
President Juan Carlos Wasmosy. Oviedo ran for president last year.
But during the campaign he was imprisoned on charges related to
that episode. That led to Cubas' election.
</P>
<P>
   When Cubas defied the Supreme Court in August and freed Oviedo
as one of his first acts in office, that set off a move to impeach
him by congressional opponents and by Argana. His assassination by
men in military fatigues set off street demonstrations and violence
that finally forced Cubas to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayan prosecutors have accused Oviedo of having
masterminded Argana's assassination. A Paraguayan judge has also
accused him of involvement in the slayings of six young
demonstrators who marched against Cubas' government last week.
</P>
<P>
   As 60,000 people gathered on the streets of Asuncion on Sunday
night to celebrate the emergence of Sen. Luis Gonzalez Macchi as
Paraguay's new president, Oviedo spirited himself out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested at a military airport outside Buenos Aires on
Sunday after he and his family had arrived in a small plane without
a flight plan, immigration papers or permission to land.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Argentine President Carlos Saul Menem, who was on a
trade mission in Italy, told reporters that ``we are going to take
our time'' before deciding whether to extradite or grant asylum.
Four hours later, the Interior Ministry announced that asylum would
be granted, for reasons that were unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's decision may ultimately help tip the scales of the
struggle between the forces that back Oviedo and those who support
Gonzalez Macchi. There is a long tradition of Latin American
politicians' playing significant roles when under asylum in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   The two competing forces represent opposing factions of the
Colorado Party, which has ruled the landlocked country of 5.7
million people for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina and Brazil, the two most important countries in
Mercosur, which includes Paraguay and Uruguay, intervened jointly
to help defend civilian rule in 1996. But Menem has long had good
relations with Oviedo, who has styled himself as a populist in the
tradition of Gen. Juan D. Peron of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition request was personally made by Paraguay's top
prosecutor, Jorge Vasconcellos, Monday morning in Buenos Aires.
Congressman Angel Ramon Barchini, who accompanied Vasconcellos from
Asuncion, said Oviedo was ``the man who thought up and is morally
responsible for the assassination of the vice president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
