<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-PROSIGNIA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
COMPAQ EXPANDS BUILD-TO-ORDER LINE OF PCs 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Compaq Computer Corp. announced a plan Monday to
expand sales of its new build-to-order Prosignia line of PCs,
including selling the machines for the first time in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The PC maker also said some of its largest resellers would take
up space on its Houston factory floor, building Prosignia systems
for small and medium businesses as orders come in.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also introduced a new server for small businesses that
should make it easier to set up and operate a network. The
Prosignia NeoServer will sell for as little as $1,399.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement built on an initiative that Compaq
launched in November to staunch the growth of arch-rival Dell
Computer Corp. and others who sell PCs directly to customers.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with reporters and analysts Monday,
Compaq executives said the company's push to reach small and medium
businesses was working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of our (Prosignia) sales are incremental to
Compaq _ they are new business,'' said Chief Executive Eckhard
Pfeiffer. ``Almost half of the new business has been a switch from
purchasing from Dell or Gateway.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq stock closed at 31-1/2 Monday, up 5/16 in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Prosignia line of desktops, servers and portable
computers is sold either via phone, on Compaq's Web site or through
the company's network of resellers.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said the Prosignia line will be sold through
office-supply stores Office Max, Office Depot and Staples, as well
as through CompUSA, a computer superstore. In all, 600 stores
nationally will carry the line.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will be able to see display models in the stores, then
order them via kiosks that currently are used to sell some Presario
consumer machines.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's Web site will be redesigned to make it easier to get to
the areas where customers can buy machines direct. The new look
will be unveiled today.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also will launch a new program called PartnerDirect,
which will make it easier for resellers to order and deliver the
Prosignia line.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, Ingram Micro and TechData _ two giant
resellers _ will set up shop on Compaq's factory floor, taking and
fulfilling orders from customers and smaller resellers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq calls the overall program Customer Choice, and Pfeiffer
said it gives its small and medium business customers a variety of
ways to buy the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Brock, an analyst with Access Media International, a New
York City-based market research firm, said Compaq has developed ``a
pretty impressive model.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough balance to strike between direct, retail and the
resellers,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also announced a new Prosignia notebook computer that
uses Advanced Micro Devices' K6-2 chip. The Prosignia 150, which
starts at $1,799, marks the first time Compaq has used the K6-2 in
a business product. The last Compaq business computer that had an
AMD chip used a clone of the 80486 processor in the now-defunct
Prolinea line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
