<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW CLOSES ABOVE 10,000, REFLECTING STRONG ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two weeks of thrust and parry, stock traders pushed
the Dow Jones industrial average above 10,000 and kept it there
until the end of the day's trading. The Dow closed at 10,006.78, up
184.54 points, or 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although 10,000 on the Dow was little more than a psychological
hurdle for investors, the market's move is significant in what it
reflects: unparalleled strength of the economy and American
corporations' dominance of the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the shuffle of the Dow's record-setting day was a
solid performance by broader gauges. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 27.37 points, or 2.1 percent, to 1,310.17,
while the Nasdaq composite index jumped 73.67 points, or 3 percent,
to 2,492.84.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT REORGANIZES INTO 5 UNITS
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's president, Steven Ballmer, announced the
reorganization of the company into five divisions that he suggested
would act with some independence. Brad Chase and Jon DeVaan will
run a newly created consumer and commerce group that includes the
Microsoft Network. The other new units are the Business and
Enterprise division, the Consumer Windows division, the Business
Productivity group for ``knowledge workers'' like telecommuters,
and the Developer group.
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS WRITER STRIKES AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   A software detective who has assembled a dossier of the author
of a rapidly spreading computer virus, called Melissa, thinks the
virus writer has struck previously and that his activities are
already well known to computer security experts.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK ISSUES A PROFIT WARNING
</P>
<P>
   In a radical departure for the traditionally secretive company,
Eastman Kodak warned that its first-quarter earnings would come in
below expectations but gave detailed, and much rosier, forecasts
for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER ASSOCIATES TO BUY RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   Computer Associates International, the fourth-largest maker of
software in the United States, agreed to buy a rival, Platinum
Technology International, for about $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WORLDCOM SEEKS INTERNET LINKS
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom, seeking advanced wireless Internet links, is said
to be investing about $200 million in what is known as the wireless
cable business. It is buying bonds of three small wireless cable
operators, CS Wireless, People's Choice and Wireless One, and
shares of another, CAI Wireless Systems.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM TO OFFER AUCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Furthering its ambition to be involved virtually any time anyone
sells anything on the Internet, Amazon.com plans to let individuals
and small businesses conduct auctions on its popular Web site,
beginning Tuesday. Shares of Amazon.com rose nearly 8 percent,
closing at $149.625, up $10.5625.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG TO CONSOLIDATE OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   KPMG, the fifth-largest accounting firm, said it would
consolidate most of its operations into two regional groupings as
it seeks to transform a loose association of firms into a unified
global business.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC CUTS HINDER ACCESS
</P>
<P>
   Greater American access to Saudi Arabian petroleum has been put
on indefinite hold, senior Saudi officials said after a new OPEC
agreement was reached. That agreement, aimed at raising prices by
reducing production, was essentially negotiated by Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI RAISES TELECOM ITALIA BID
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti raised its hostile bid for a bigger rival, Telecom
Italia, by 15 percent, to 60.4 billion euros, or about $64.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   VIAG AND ALGROUP ABANDON MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Viag, Germany's third-largest utility, and Algroup, the world's
biggest maker of packaging for the pharmaceutical industry,
abandoned their $8.7 billion merger plan because they could not
agree on terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
