<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-RADAR-NYT </SLUG>
 
CONTROL EQUIPMENT FAILURES DELAY FLIGHTS AT DULLES  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First a radar dish at the edge of a runway quit.
Then on the radar screens where the airplanes should have been a
strange line appeared that ``looked like an EKG,'' according to one
controller. Finally the smell of smoke filled the control room. In
all, four separate failures at Dulles Airport led to the delay of
more than 100 planes on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was errors made repairing the first failure,
but part was just bad luck, said Stanley Rivers, the top Federal
Aviation Administration official in charge of air traffic control
equipment, performing a Monday mrning post-mortem.
</P>
<P>
   Paul M. Rinaldi, president of the Dulles local of the National
Air Traffic Controllers Association, said part of the problem is
``how aging this equipment is, and how badly we need to replace
this equipment.'' Rinaldi said that much of the equipment that
failed is scheduled to be replaced in May 2002, if the FAA can hold
to its current schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The control room at Dulles is a Terminal Radar Approach Control,
or TRACON, which handles traffic en route to airports in the
Washington area, and is one of the 25 busiest such centers in the
country. Dulles itself is a major airport for international and
long-haul domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered failures are common, but the events at Dulles included
a very unusual problem, an electrical component that smoked as it
failed. About 18 controllers were ordered out of their control room
on Sunday morning, and when they returned, they did so two at a
time, in 15-minute shifts to avoid overexposure to fumes.
</P>
<P>
   About 114 airliners were delayed in leaving on Saturday and
Sunday, the FAA said; an undetermined number of inbound aircraft
were put in holding patterns or told not to take off.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began before 7 a.m. on Saturday, when the
controllers in the TRACON lost contact with a radar at the edge of
the airfield. A technician concluded that there was a problem with
the power supply for the link between the radar and the
controllers' screens, and replaced some components. The radar went
back into service at 10:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But at 1:45 p.m. it failed again. Technicians decided that a
sensor that decides when to start a cooling fan had failed, and
triggered a power interruption. The system was running again at
8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   During the failure, controllers were patched through to another
radar, which has a blind spot several miles wide where planes
approach Dulles from the west. And the back-up radar provides less
frequent updates, so controllers spaced out planes, five miles from
each other instead of three, creating delays.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:40 a.m. on Sunday, controllers started seeing something on
their screens ``like you would see in Star Wars when they go into
hyper-drive,'' said Rinaldi. While that was being fixed,
controllers were sent to one screen in the tower at Dulles that was
still working. But then one of the screens in the main control
room, one floor under the fishbowl tower, began to smoke, delaying
a return to normal operations until 11:15 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
