<HEADLINE>
CREDIT RATING AGENCY WARNS N.H. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Moody's Investors Services fired a shot across
the financial bow of the State of New Hampshire Monday by placing
$1.73 billion in debt owed by the state, its muncipalities, and
school districts on its Watchlist.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a warning that credit ratings are in danger of being
lowered. A lower credit rating means higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has the financial wherewithal to pay the estimated
$1.5 billion cost of public education but still can't figure out
how to divvy up the bill, the rating service said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state Legislature has considered many proposals for new
revenue sources, including taxes on income, property, capital
gains, businesses, and cigarettes,'' said Moody's vice president
Michael Bartsch in a statement Monday. ``No single source or
combination of sources has achieved political consensus or emerged
as the leading candidate at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action came on the eve of a planned vote by the
400-member House on a school financing proposal passed by the
Senate last week. Because that plan relies in part on an income
tax, however, Governor Jeanne Shaheen has pledged to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen's own plan, which relies largely on increased business
taxes and revenue from gambling, has yet to pass in either body.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is under orders by the state Supreme Court to find
a replacement for its unconstitutional system of funding schools by
April 1.
</P>
<P>
   There is still time left on the clock but perhaps not much,
Moody's warned. ``If future events warrant, however, Moody's may
downgrade the ratings of affected bonds issued by cities, towns,
school districts, and the New Hampshire Municipal Bond Bank, and
possibly the general-obligation bonds of the state, as well,''
Bartsch said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for another New York bond-rating agency, Standard
and Poor's, said New Hampshire has not been placed on its watch
list nor are there plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated $3 million per day in local school property
taxes slated to become illegal Thursday, Shaheen was quick to
assure lenders that the state will find a way out of its impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that we will arrive at a solution before the
timely payment of any debt service is jeopardized,'' the governor
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
