<SLUG> BC-OAKLAND-BROWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BULLISH JERRY BROWN BARGES ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.) (jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ After three decades in politics, Jerry Brown
knows how to relish the bombshell moments.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, after he announced the ``resignations'' of
the popular police chief and two other city department heads _ his
biggest bombshell as mayor _ reporters and television news people
were calling nonstop, outraged critics were dishing out sound
bites, and Brown, peaceful as a monk, was wowing a small gathering
of citizens celebrating Greek-American Independence Day at City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put our city on the map,'' said Steven Angelopoulous,
sounding like actor Roberto Benigni after he won his Oscars.
``Every one in the nation is watching us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun,'' Brown said. And clearly, at that instant, he
was. The famously dour Jerry Brown actually sort of smiled.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not all been fun. In the past several weeks, the
ex-two-term governor and ex-three-time presidential candidate has
begun trying to make good on the promises he made at his
inauguration in January and reawaken this city ``of unfulfilled
potential'' (not to mention his own political career). Brown has
been scrutinizing city departments, lining up his own management
team, doing, as he said in an interview, ``what any new mayor would
do.'' But with almost every move, there have been increasing
rumblings that the 61-year-old novice mayor is charging too hard,
too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters _ and there are more and more of those weighing in on
the letters pages of the local papers _ say they are thrilled by
the pace Brown is setting. But critics accuse him of issuing orders
and declaring what is good and bad for this long-maligned, racially
diverse city of 400,000 without the input of the people who
supported his landslide victory. They say he is acting like the old
Jerry Brown, which is to say, the young Jerry Brown, a Know-it-All.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies and protests _ both at City Hall and in front of the
downtown loft Brown calls home _ greeted his public pronouncements
against Chief Joseph Samuels Jr., who happens to be a deacon in one
of the most politically active churches in the city. Brown has also
faced protests for inviting the Marines to hold urban war games in
Oakland, for endorsing a state senator's proposal to replace the
management of the city's schools with a trustee the mayor would
appoint, even for the manner in which the city manager (who is, in
effect, his deputy) told all city department leaders that their
jobs were in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry is acting like the governor of Oakland,'' complained
Shannon Reeves, the 30-year-old president of the local chapter of
the NAACP, who came in third in the list of 10 political contenders
Brown defeated to become mayor. ``Jerry Brown's whole objective is
to get back on the national scene, so he's moving as fast as he can
so he can show the national politicians he's a player. He's not
consulting the people of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a coalition consisting of leaders of the clergy has
circulated two petitions in recent weeks _ one urging respect for
the police chief, the other in support of a local solution to
school changes _ another coalition of religious leaders has been
standing by the mayor at each potentially explosive public
engagement. The parallel reactions to his style are the kind that
have followed Brown throughout his political life. He infuriates
some, exhilarates others.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brown knows there are worse things for a
politician to be called than hard-charging and brash. In a way, he
seems to be replaying the adrenaline-charged first months of his
last political comeback 10 years ago, when he became state chairman
of the Democratic Party after a six-year hiatus from politics that
followed his losing Senate bid against the then-obscure Pete
Wilson. Greeted as a celebrity, if not a savior, almost everywhere
he goes, Brown can still afford to pooh-pooh his crop of critics as
a small, noisy group of naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone, he said, acknowledges that crime is a problem,
that the school system, which became a national laughingstock for
briefly embracing ebonics a few years ago, needs drastic help and
that downtown, where the Starbucks shutters up at night and on
weekends, needs an infusion of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Oakland has great potential and I'm tired of
waiting for it,'' Brown said, sitting preternaturally straight in a
hard-backed chair in his office after his remarks to the
Greek-American Independence Day celebration. ``Oakland is poised
for change. I want to reduce the crime, I want people to return to
the city. I want vertical density back in Oakland. That's what
we're trying to accomplish here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Samuels' six-year tenure as police chief, crime in
Oakland, with a largely poor, minority population, has decreased,
but not as drastically as it could have, given the national trend,
Brown said. He compared Oakland's 81 murders last year with the 63
in San Francisco, a city twice its size, and shook his head. But
when asked if it would be fair to compare Oakland to a city with
more similar demographics, such as Detroit or Washington, he waved
his hand dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a lot better,'' Brown said impatiently. ``We're
bringing in people, we're bringing in artists and business people.
But in order to accomplish our goal, attract people and make this a
better city for the people who've suffered the bad times, we've got
to bring crime way down. That's the priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Alfred Smith, senior pastor of Allen Temple Baptist
Church, where the outgoing police chief is a member, said he
worried that Brown was going to bring in a chief who would focus on
statistics rather than community relations.
</P>
<P>
   Under Samuels' six-year tenure, Smith said, crime has gone down
more than at any other time in the city, while relations between
the police and the community have improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know what Jerry Brown is going to do,'' Smith
said, ``because he hasn't told us. Is the city of Oakland going to
go the way of New York under Giuliani? And does that mean we're
going to face what's going on in New York City right now?''
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors that Brown plans to bring in a former New York
police chief to run the Oakland department _ rumors that he refused
to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every mayor has the right to bring in the people he or she
thinks will do the best job,'' Brown said. ``That's what I intend
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Reeves of the NAACP said there was a rumor spreading
around the city that Brown was hoping to use Oakland as a
springboard to the U.S. Senate. The scenario, he said, is that Al
Gore will pick Senator Dianne Feinstein as his vice presidential
running mate, and Brown will run for her Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking that far ahead,'' Brown said, his brow
furrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that that election was just a year away, he shook his
head. ``I'm focusing on Oakland,'' he said. ``Shaking things up.
Turning things around.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, caught his political cliches and smiled, for the
second time in less an hour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
