<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY LEADERS DO LITTLE ON BUDGET BUT TRY TO FIX BLAME
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With the start of the new fiscal year just three
days away, Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders did nothing
to resolve their budget differences Monday and instead bickered
over who was to blame for the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   The day began on an unusually contentious note when Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, called Joseph Bruno, the
Republican majority leader of the state Senate, ``a wimp'' and all
but dared him to defy the Republican governor's recent threat to
veto any legislative budget that did not restrain spending next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on WROW-AM Monday morning, Silver strongly
suggested that Pataki would back away from his threat if Bruno and
his Senate colleagues ``would show they exist in Albany, that they
are not tools of the governor, which is all they are showing
themselves to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If they showed they could override, then the
governor would think twice about talking in such heroic terms.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki and his Republican colleague, Bruno, immediately
fired back, dismissing Silver's attacks as unnecessary and accusing
him of causing the impasse by seeking to spend imprudently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is the Assembly is completely
unrealistic and totally off the charts in what they are proposing
to spend,'' Pataki said at a news conference Monday morning. ``It
would leave the state with huge, multibillion-dollar deficits and
beyond. We're not going to let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, for his part, laughed off the suggestion that he lacked
the fortitude to exercise independence from the governor. ``I don't
think anyone who knows me considers me a wimp, including the
speaker,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Silver of seeking to increase spending in
``irresponsible ways.'' Bruno said he believed that the speaker was
``intent on diverting attention'' and blamed him for having
``slowed the process down'' and having ``really brought it to a
standstill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally feel that we cannot overspend this year,'' Bruno
said. ``So I am more in tune with the governor in terms of spending
this year than I am with the Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange underscored just how deeply divided state leaders
remained over the budget for the coming fiscal year, which begins
Thursday. After two years of steep spending increases, Pataki has
vowed to keep a lid on spending in the next fiscal year. He has
proposed increasing state spending by 1.8 percent, to $72.66
billion, despite the state's $2 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans want to raise spending by at least 2.7
percent. The Assembly's Democratic majority has proposed an
increase that it puts at 4.6 percent but that Senate Republicans
put at 5.4 percent and the governor's office says is closer to 8
percent. Pataki has criticized the Senate and Assembly plans,
threatening to veto them if they are not scaled back.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The negotiations over the budget are so deadlocked that the
Senate and the Assembly once again failed to meet in conference
committees Monday to try to work out their differences. Bruno and
Silver blamed each other for the failure to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The conference committee process between the Senate and the
Assembly began last year and represented a major break from the way
budgets have historically been adopted in Albany. Until 1997, the
governor and legislative leaders negotiated the budget in secret
meetings. Last year, the Senate and the Assembly, in a bid to make
the process more public and involve more legislators, met in
conference committees to negotiate a budget publicly with little
direct input from the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki applauded the process but then vetoed more than 1,000
line items worth more than $1 billion in spending, most of it in
Democrats' pet projects. Though the vetoes surprised lawmakers from
both parties, Democrats who control the Assembly are the most wary,
fearing a repeat of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
