<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN BORDER   FILLS WITH REFUGEES, FRANTIC TALES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ For the villagers of Celin, the shelling,
executions, and forced march out of Kosovo started only hours after
NATO dropped bombs on Yugoslavia, an attack meant to drive away the
Serbs and stop their assaults on ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early hours Thursday, 43-year-old Masar Rexhepi
recalled, 12 Serbian tanks surrounded the village, sending Rexhepi
and others fleeing into the mountains. One family, told by the
Serbs that they would be safe as long as they stayed indoors,
huddled in their home.
</P>
<P>
   Rexhepi found their bodies that night in the family's courtyard,
13 people dead from bullet wounds and burned so badly that Rexhepi
could only identify five of the corpses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were crying and screaming,'' said a shaken Rexhepi, one
of the town's survivors and now among the estimated 60,000-plus
terrified refugees who have streamed over the border from Kosovo to
Albania in the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   The small northern town of Kukes looks like a massive refugee
camp, as ethnic Albanians _ reportedly forced at gunpoint or by
intimidation to leave _ flood Albania. Extended families of crying
infants and shivering adults, with only a few bags of belongings
among them, sit helplessly along the grimy streets, waiting to get
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   A noisy line of cars, tractors, and weary, tearful pedestrians
has been weaving its way across the Morino crossing, near Kukes.
Officials for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees estimate that
more than 60,000 have crossed there, and another 1,500 have come
over a neighboring border checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-strapped government of Albania sent hordes of buses to
bring Kosovars to the capital Tirana and other towns, but officials
say there is not nearly enough room in refugee camps to accommodate
them.
</P>
<P>
   Cars and buses clogged the narrow, badly paved road that winds
up and down the mountains between Tirana and Kukes _ a road where
vehicles are usually few. Open-topped trucks were packed with
refugees wrapped in blankets against the cold mountain winds.
</P>
<P>
   The massive, apparently enforced departure could be the biggest
episode of ethnic cleansing in this decade's series of Yugoslav
wars. For these Kosovar refugees, the journey has been a
terrifying, grueling trip from perhaps Europe's most dangerous
country to its poorest one.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to confirm the refugees' reports of what Serb
forces did. But many refugees told credible-sounding stories, and
there is a strong consistency to the pattern of brutality they
ascribe to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' tales begin with shelling and shooting _ including
executions _ by Serbs in camouflage army uniforms. The military
men, refugees said, then rounded up villagers, brought them to a
central point, such as a school, and separated the men from the
women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Passports, identification cards, driver's licenses, money, and
license plates were confiscated, the refugees reported.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers then were ushered to the border by a combination
of Serb trucks and forced marching. Many said the Serbs, often
pointing the butt of a Kalashnikov at villagers' heads, required
them to yell ``Long Live Serbia!'' while holding up their thumb and
first two fingers of their right hands in a Serb nationalist
salute.
</P>
<P>
   Vefai Rexheni, a deaf man who could not understand the Serb
order, was dragged off and hit with a rifle when he did not perform
the Serb salute, said a math teacher. The Serbs shot him dead, said
his wife, who witnessed his slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The group of about 5,000 rounded up in Celin were loaded onto
trucks and driven to Zhura, about three miles from the border,
Rexhepi said. Then, ordered to keep their hands clasped behind
their heads, they were marched to the border in rows of three.
</P>
<P>
   Those who made it into Albania include a substantial number of
fighting-age men, an indication that the Serbs are not conducting
wholesale killing of men, or even of men they might suspect of
being members of the Kosovo Liberation Army. The KLA has been
fighting for independence from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees told of alleged atrocities. Ramodan Shaqiri, 37,
said he and his wife, seeking basement shelter from the Serb
shelling, had viewed the bodies of 37 neighbors who had been shot
and whose faces had been mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming theme of the refugees' stories, however, is
less one of mass murder and more one of a calculated plan to drive
Albanians from Kosovo permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole of Kosovo has moved,'' said Nazishi Bytyci, 23, as
she sat on a lawn in Kukes strewn with garbage, gravel, and the
whitened bones of farm animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
