<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; INVESTORS _ &LR;  The big landmark in Michael Medwid's investing life
wasn't when the Dow Jones industrial average hit 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1992, when the biotech firm he worked for gave him 900
stock options that &UR;  &LR; he cashed in for $50,000. That hefty sum
transformed Medwid into an avid market watcher, helped him buy a
home, and served as seed money for an investment portfolio that has
grown to about $180,000 _ about 90 percent of which is in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Medwid is among millions of Americans who dipped their toes into
the stock market for the first time this decade _ and then plunged
up to their knees, waists or chins. By Ilana DeBare
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEN&AMP;NOW _  &LR; When the Dow Jones industrial average first closed
above 1,000, President Richard Nixon had just been re-elected by a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and North Vietnamese negotiators had agreed to a new round
of peace talks to end the Vietnam War. U.S. astronauts were getting
ready to walk on the moon for the last time. Bill Gates was a nerdy
high school senior in Seattle. A three-bedroom house in San
Francisco cost $35,000. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECON _  &LR; With Asian economies swooning and technology exports
dropping, it is easy to conclude that the local economy must be on
the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, according to a new study by the UCLA Anderson Forecast.
By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMAZON.COM  &LR; _ Amazon.com, already the Internet's largest
retailer, is expanding into another booming Web business _ online
auctions. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET _  &LR; (column) Wake me up when its over. All of this Dow
10,000 rot is about as stimulating as washing down two tabs of
Excedrin PM with an herbal tea chaser. In case you haven't heard
(and didn't read the rest of the paper), the Dow Jones industrials
closed at 10,007 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG &LR;  _ (column) Question: When will Scholarshare, that new
state-sponsored college savings plan, begin accepting applications?
A Chronicle article last year said it would be up and running by
February, but I haven't heard anything about it since then. Arthur
M. Louis has the answer
</P>
