<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-BUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER VIRUS LEAVES MANY USERS REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nasty computer virus with an innocuous name has swept across
the Internet, leaving hundreds of thousands of infected computers
in its wake Monday and flooding electronic mailboxes with millions
of unwanted messages.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus was first detected on Friday and has rapidly
spread. Although the virus apparently causes no permanent damage to
a computer, it is considered dangerous because it spreads by
stealing electronic mail addresses from a user's e-mail address
book. As a result, Melissa is transmitted among users who know each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses are computer programs that act like infections, secretly
spreading themselves from one computer to another.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Melissa's capacity to overwhelm e-mail systems and
because it has spread with such shocking speed, managers of
corporate computer networks toiled all weekend in an effort to
stave off disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Emergency Response Team, or CERT, a
federally-funded watchdog agency at Carnegie Mellon University,
received reports of major problems caused by Melissa at 250
companies, with a total of 100,000 individual computers. Microsoft
Corp., Intel Corp., Lockheed Martin Corp., and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
either restricted or shut down their e-mail systems to avoid
infection. The FBI said military and government computers were
sabotaged, along with thousands of other institutions' systems.
</P>
<P>
   The virus also had the technical services departments at
Boston-area firms scrambling. Cahners Business Information, a
magazine publisher in Newton, shut down Internet access during the
weekend to avoid spreading the virus. ``We got hit with it along
with the rest of the world, on Friday afternoon,'' said spokesman
Evan Albright. ``Thank heaven we had the weekend to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cognos Inc. in Burlington, Internet service wasn't restored
until 4 p.m. Monday, as administrators flushed the virus from
e-mail servers at 30 locations around the world. ``It was back to
the fax, back to the phone for a lot of things,'' said spokeswoman
Roberta Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the world's leading makers of anti-virus software
quickly created upgrades that would block the Melissa virus and
posted them on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus is based on a powerful and controversial
feature of the word processing program Microsoft Word _ the ability
to embed little programs called ``macros'' inside Word documents.
The virulent macro was spread among people who received e-mail and
opened up an attached Word document. The macro inside Melissa
automatically e-mails up to 50 copies of itself to other people,
who in turn can spread the virus even further.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, president of Phar Lap Software in Cambridge and a
frequent critic of Microsoft's software design policies, said that
with a few modifications, the virus could easily have ordered each
infected computer to delete all the files on its hard drive. Were
such a virus to get loose inside a corporation or government
agency, the damages could run to millions of dollars. ``Why should
a word processing document have that kind of power?'' Smith
wondered.
</P>
<P>
   To Microsoft group product manager Andrew Dixon, the answer is
simple: Customers like macros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a capability our customers have asked for,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith believes Melissa was originally posted on an Internet
message board devoted to pornography. Either accidentally or on
purpose, someone attached the Melissa document to a piece of e-mail
and sent it to somebody else. And that's when the trouble began.
</P>
<P>
   There's no danger in reading the e-mail containing Melissa. But
if the recipient uses Microsoft Word and opens the attached
document, it may infect his computer. If the computer also contains
Microsoft's popular e-mail program Outlook, Melissa will send
copies of itself to the first 50 names in the Outlook address book.
If any of these 50 people activate Melissa, and also have Word and
Outlook on their computers, the cycle begins again.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Melissa messages were streaming across the Web.
Shocked virus-watchers at CERT took the unusual step of issuing a
press release to quickly warn the public of the danger. ``This was
widely covered in the media on Sunday,'' said Jeff Carpenter,
CERT's incident response team leader, ``and we think that has
helped mitigate the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter says that Melissa illustrates the power of the
Microsoft Word macro system. ``You can do some pretty neat things
with it, but you can also do some things that are malicious as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   CERT recommends that users of Microsoft's Office software switch
off its capacity to run macros embedded in documents. ``The
potential for malicious action is greater than the benefit that
they provide,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, a similar virus, called Papa, was
discovered Monday. Papa is programmed to send out even more
infected e-mails than Melissa, although it has a bug that sometimes
prevents it from working, said Srivats Sampath, general manager of
McAfee software, an antivirus company. E-mails from the Papa virus
include an attached spreadsheet file. When the user opens that
file, the virus sends 60 infected e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phar Lap Software's Smith hopes to use another
controversial Microsoft feature to track down the creator of the
Melissa virus. Earlier this month, Smith made headlines with his
discovery that Microsoft Word documents contain embedded serial
numbers that can be used to identify the computer that generated
them. Smith said he has analyzed an original copy of the Melissa
document and found such a serial number. He now plans to scour the
Internet for other documents with the same serial number, which
might reveal the identity of Melissa's creator.
</P>
<P>
   If identified, this person or persons can expect a visit from
the FBI, which has assigned its computer crime unit to investigate
the Melissa affair.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Melissa's creator could be fined up to $350,000
and be sentenced to up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
