 Column: Scholarshare To Begin Soon
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  When will Scholarshare, that new state-sponsored college
savings plan, begin accepting applications? A Chronicle article
last year said it would be up and running by February, but I
haven't heard anything about it since then.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You are correct in assuming that Scholarshare
enrollment has been postponed. The latest estimate from the
California Student Aid Commission, which will administer the
program, is that Scholarshare will accept applications starting
around the middle of this year. The program has been delayed by a
prolonged search for an investment adviser and by an unexpectedly
complicated effort to draft all the necessary rules and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   This generous program _ made possible by the federal Taxpayer
Relief Act of 1997 _ will be worth the wait. Although the rules are
still being developed, word has it that you may be allowed to
contribute as much as $100,000 per child to an investment pool,
with the earnings on your money compounding free of federal or
state taxes until you make withdrawals to pay for your child's
education. Once the money is withdrawn, it will be taxed at the
child's tax rate, which presumably will be lower than your own.
</P>
<P>
   More details about Scholarshare can be found on the Student Aid
Commission's Internet Web site at  &LR; www.csac.ca.gov &LR; , or by calling
(916) 526-7590, Ext. 6.
</P>
<P>
   IPO Information
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I learn which initial public offerings of stock are
coming to the market and when?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: The most comprehensive source of IPO information appears
to be IPO Monitor, an online service whose Web site is at
 &LR; www.ipomonitor.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The subscription price is $29 per month, or $290 for a full
year, which works out to a $24.17 monthly rate. The fee is payable
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   A subscription entitles you to e-mail alerts listing all new IPO
filings as they become known and tracking the performance of IPOs
after they go to market. By exploring the Web site, you can get
updates on pending filings when the stock price or other terms of
the offering are changed.
</P>
<P>
   IPO Monitor sets aside a separate Web page for each company
making an IPO, complete with the company's income statements,
balance sheets and other crucial information. There also is
commentary on IPOs in general, and some in particular, from IPO
Monitor's in-house analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you can profit from all that information is another
question. It is hard for an individual investor to get a piece of
an IPO unless you happen to be well-connected _ for example, a
favored customer of one of the underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Some brokers, such as Charles Schwab, Fidelity Investments and
E-Trade, don't play favorites. They make a limited number of shares
in a limited selection of IPOs available to their customers on a
first-come, first-served basis.
</P>
<P>
   Disability Retirement
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am 54 years old, and have been paying into a tax-sheltered
annuity for many years through my employer, the state government. I
was recently diagnosed with Lou Gehrig's disease, with a prognosis
of perhaps five years of life remaining, and am preparing to take
disability retirement. I may not live to age 591/2, when I would be
allowed to withdraw money from the annuity without paying the 10
percent penalty tax. Is there an exception to the penalty-tax rule
in my case? I'm probably going to need that money as my medical
expenses shoot up.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Appearances to the contrary, the government really does
have a heart. You won't have to worry about the penalty tax,
because you will qualify for an exemption two different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Once a physician officially certifies that you are totally and
permanently disabled, you can withdraw as much money as you wish
from your annuity without penalty. You will, however, be required
to pay taxes on your annuity income at your ordinary rate.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption applies not only to annuities, but also to 401(k)
plans and Individual Retirement Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you remain employed for a while, you will be permitted
to make penalty-free withdrawals while still on the payroll if you
use the money specifically for medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   That rule applies to anyone with large medical bills, whether
they are retiring or not. It would apply, for example, to people on
medical leave who intend to come back to work.
</P>
<P>
   If your medical expenses in a given year exceed 71/2 percent of
your adjusted gross income, the amount of the excess can be
withdrawn without penalty from your retirement account. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Again, while there is no 10 percent penalty under this scenario,
you would have to pay ordinary taxes on your withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
