<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Mega-Merger Talk in Oil Industry Helps Push Dow Over
the  Top 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Wake me up when its over. All of this Dow 10,000 rot is about as
stimulating as washing down two tabs of Excedrin PM with an herbal
tea chaser. In case you haven't heard (and didn't read the rest of
the paper), the Dow Jones industrials closed at 10,007 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopee. That, and two bucks, will get you an overpriced cup of
charred Italian roast. The Dow rose 1.9 percent yesterday to
finally closed above the dreadfully insignificant 10,000 barrier on
its fourth try.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index kicked some
serious tail yesterday, rising 3.1 percent to close at 2,492.84.
Forget the Dow, it was the high-octane Nasdaq, with its more than
4,000 stocks, that had the banner day. Primed by huge run-ups in
technology stocks, such as a $25.75, or 23 percent, surge in
Internet darling iVillage, the Nasdaq outpaced the Dow on the
Industrials' big day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEAL TIME? &LR; : Yet when it comes to what finally put the dowdy
Dow over the hump, it was big oil _ including San Francisco's
Chevron _ that helped fuel the final push beyond 10K.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron _ one of the 30 big-caps that comprise the Dow _ rose
nearly $3 to $89.63 yesterday. In fact, the entire oil patch caught
fire (with all due respect to those endangered by Chevron's
refinery explosion in Richmond last week) after word spread that
another major merger was in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, which itself is the byproduct of British Petroleum's
recent buyout of Amoco, confirmed reports that it is negotiating to
buy Atlantic Richfield of Los Angeles. Arco jumped $9 to close
yesterday at $74.63 on the news. The high tide lifted all boats:
The American Stock Exchange oil index soared 4 percent to close
yesterday at 461.2.
</P>
<P>
   If BP Amoco is successful in its bid for Arco, the combined
company would produce more oil and gas than any other oil company
save for the proposed Exxon-Mobil merger, which has yet to close.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all of these international oil titans meeting at the
alter, where does that leave independent-minded Chevron?
</P>
<P>
   Chevron chief executive Ken Derr, who is expected to step down
in the next two to three years, has articulated on numerous
occasions that Chevron isn't for sale. Nor is he interested in
bulking up through the acquisition of smaller oil companies, such
as Conoco, Phillips or Texaco, just for the sake of getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at (merger) opportunities if it makes sense for
Chevron and our shareholders,'' Derr reiterated at a San Francisco
news conference yesterday about gasoline additives.
</P>
<P>
   Derr is leaving the door cracked open for a possible marriage
but doesn't appear too eager to merge at a time when most other oil
companies are running into each other's embraces.
</P>
<P>
   So how much longer can Chevron afford to remain solo?
</P>
<P>
   Not very long, says Fadel Gheit, a senior financial analyst with
Fahnestock in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal readers of Street Smarts may recall that Gheit predicted
in a December column that either Texaco or Arco would be the next
second-tier oil company to get bought (it looks like Arco is a
goner). He also said Chevron would need to partner up in order to
remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Gheit hasn't changed his tune.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the analyst now predicts that ``by the year 2000, you
will no longer see an independent Chevron or Texaco.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron chief Derr ``has done a marvelous job. Unfortunately, it
is not enough to compete in the current environment,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has ``been building muscle, but its competitors are
taking steroids,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   Low crude prices are driving major oil companies together in
attempt to reduce exploration and marketing costs. And while major
oil-producing countries in the Middle East agreed to try to reduce
production and increase prices, Gheit says it would be a mistake
for Chevron to think that the pact will make it easier for it to
compete with what he calls the new `'super-majors,'' such as
Exxon-Mobil and BP Amoco (and Arco?).
</P>
<P>
   So what's next for Chevron?
</P>
<P>
   The analyst paints two scenarios. One is that Derr reconsiders
his opposition to merging and agrees to a deal with Exxon-Mobil
after their pending mega-deal is approved by regulators _ which
could occur as early as August, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The other is that Chevron would merge with Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron needs to get significantly bigger, and the only
logical way for it to grow is through (buying) Texaco,'' Gheit
says. ``It's a layup.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron and Texaco, which is based in suburban New York, have
the oldest and most successful international refining and marketing
alliance in the oil industry, and their companies have ``tremendous
synergy,'' Gheit says. Chevron would not comment on whether it
would consider a deal with Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with a Chevron-Texaco deal is that the combination
would still be far smaller than the other super-majors, Gheit says.
But still, it would give them a fighting chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these two companies don't start to move. They will be left
behind,'' Gheit says.
</P>
<P>
   That said, without even considering its potential as a merger
candidate, another financial analyst thinks that Chevron's stock is
a good value.
</P>
<P>
   John Hervey of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette told his firm's
clients yesterday at San Francisco's Mandarin Hotel that Chevron is
underpriced compared with its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Hervey predicted that Chevron's stock price will be trading at
19.6 times the company's projected earnings in 2000. That compares
to a price/earnings ratio of 20.4 for the entire industry in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chevron is ``one of very few majors to deliver
rising production over the next two to three years'' while still
reducing its costs, said Hervey, who has a price target for Chevron
of $95 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shucks. If Chevron is a bargain now, what kind of upside would
there be if Derr surprisingly agreed to merge with, say,
Mobil-Exxon?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, we could be talking about Dow 11,000 before any of
that dreamy speculation comes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Or worse yet, we could be looking at 9,000. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
