<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Street's Siren Song Lures Millions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The big landmark in Michael Medwid's investing life wasn't when the
Dow Jones industrial average hit 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1992, when the biotech firm he worked for gave him 900
stock options that &UR;  &LR; he cashed in for $50,000. That hefty sum
transformed Medwid into an avid market watcher, helped him buy a
home, and served as seed money for an investment portfolio that has
grown to about $180,000 _ about 90 percent of which is in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the market with a bang,'' acknowledged Medwid, 37,
a San Mateo resident who now works for Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   Medwid is among millions of Americans who dipped their toes into
the stock market for the first time this decade _ and then plunged
up to their knees, waists or chins.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 percent of American households now own stock, up
from 32 percent in 1989, according to the Economic Policy
Institute, a Washington D.C., think tank.
</P>
<P>
   And one of every four dollars in assets held by American
households is now invested in stocks _ up from one in 10 dollars in
1989 and more than at any time since World War II, according to the
Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  This unprecedented rush into stocks by average Americans has
helped the market crash through one milestone after another, as it
did yesterday when the Dow Jones industrial average closed 6.78
points above 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of the market has been particularly strong in Silicon
Valley, where stock options are a common benefit and everyone seems
to knows someone at an Internet startup that's about to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Bohn, 29, works at ComputerLiteracy.com, an online
retailer of technical books for computer professionals. She had
never invested in individual stocks until she moved to the Valley
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I were consulting for technology companies, and
we saw the (investment) potential there and wanted to get
involved,'' Bohn said. ``In the valley, all your neighbors work at
technology companies. Everyone job hops. You can get information on
a lot of companies to help you make investment decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The market's siren song has brought new rituals to daily life.
Many white-collar workers now check their stock holdings online
each morning as casually as they fill up their coffee mugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Ho, 25, started investing four years ago, when he was still
in college and the market was starting on its steepest four-year
climb in history. Since then, he has nursed $50,000 in family money
into a $175,000 portfolio _ primarily by investing in technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What older investors might see as an unprecedented bubble,
younger investors like Ho see as normal market growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pretty much double your portfolio in three years,''
said Ho, a University of California at Berkeley engineering
graduate who works at a Palo Alto venture capital firm called
Charter Growth Capital. ``If you focus on Internet stocks, you can
do it in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without investing in the Internet, older and more
conservative investors have also increased their stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Greenan, 52, is a Walnut Creek attorney who as a young man
put all his investments into real estate. But during the past five
years, he shifted nearly all of his assets into stocks _ either
individual equities or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fastened my seat belt and ended up with a return of 35
percent last year,'' Greenan said.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Confetti, 61, is a former steel company employee whose
family owned stock in only one company when she was growing up _ a
gas well that never paid off.
</P>
<P>
   She had counted on receiving a traditional pension from her
employer when she retired. But in 1994, she was laid off and given
a lump-sum payment instead of a guaranteed pension for life. About
a third of that is now invested in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never really played the market, but my financial adviser
said it was a good place to put my money to fight inflation,'' said
Confetti, of Pittsburg. ``Last year, I made about 19 percent
overall. Now I tell my children to put money in their 401(k)
(stock) accounts. Especially with Social Security being so
uncertain, it's the best thing they could ever do.''
</P>
<P>
   How will the novice investors who've jumped into the bull market
in the past few years respond if there's a serious crash? No one
really knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough for a lot of newcomers like myself if
the bull market ends,'' acknowledged Ho. ``People will have to look
for value rather than momentum. That will take a lot more work. A
lot of people won't be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with today's bull market, not everyone is sharing in the
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The richest 10 percent of American households own 88.4 percent
of all stock, while the remaining 90 percent own just 11.6 percent,
according to the EPI.
</P>
<P>
   And while the richest 1 percent of households have stock
portfolios averaging $2.5 million, the poorest 40 percent have
portfolios averaging just $1,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock ownership is broader than it used to be, but it's far
from thoroughly democratized,'' Mishel said. ``The notion that
everyone holds stock and benefits from the market is quite an
exaggeration.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, sometimes even successful stock investors question
how much they're really benefiting.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the cost of living in the Bay Area, especially
housing, is so high that even a large portfolio can seem
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   With a wife and young son, Medwid is hoping to move into a
larger home. But he's somewhat daunted by Silicon Valley prices:
The median cost of homes sold in Santa Clara County in February was
$388,000, and the average cost was $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to get to the level of a $500,000 or $600,000 house
in an area with good schools, the housing market would just eat up
all of my investments,'' Medwid said. ``I'd be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at these investments by themselves, they've done
spectacularly,'' Medwid said. ``But when you look at the cost of
things around you, it's not so great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
