u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-NYT     03-29 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEXICAN BANKS WILL ENTER GUILTY PLEAS IN MONEY-LAUNDERING CASE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (fb) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two of Mexico's biggest banks have agreed to plead
guilty to criminal charges of money laundering, officials said on
Monday, bringing a swift end to the most important legal cases
stemming from a major investigation into the movement of illegal
drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the banks, Grupo Financiero Bancomer SA and Grupo
Financiero Serfin SA, will forfeit millions of dollars already
seized by the government and pay fines of $500,000 each. In return
for their pleas, which are to be entered in U.S. District Court
here on Tuesday, the banks will probably be allowed to continue
doing business in the United States, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is a triumph for a group of federal prosecutors,
Justice Department officials and U.S. Customs Service officials who
resisted strong pressure from both the Mexican government and the
banks to have the criminal charges dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Mexican campaign included appeals to Attorney
General Janet Reno and other Justice Department officials by senior
Mexican officials and by James R. Jones, a Washington lawyer for
one of the banks who served as the U.S. ambassador to Mexico during
the undercover customs investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous victory, particularly for those people
who felt the banks should be held criminally liable,'' said one
official of the U.S. attorney's office here. ``And there was a
great deal of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   But the guilty pleas also raise questions about what many
officials described as the reluctant handling of the case by some
of the federal prosecutors in Los Angeles, and about the
consideration that was given by some in the Clinton administration
to scaling back charges against the banks to avoid further strain
on relations with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors did retreat on one of the three indictments they
brought last year against Mexican banks, agreeing not to pursue
criminal charges against Banca Confia, a smaller Mexican bank that
was subsequently bought by Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Confia would acknowledge its liability for
violations of less serious money laundering statutes in the civil
code and forfeit about $12.2 million that has been seized from its
accounts. Citigroup, which bought the bank after it had been taken
over by the Mexican government and after the alleged money
laundering by its employees occurred, does not face any liability
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although criminal money laundering convictions against Bancomer
and Serfin will prompt hearings by the Federal Reserve Board,
officials said, the U.S. attorney's office has agreed to testify
that the banks cooperated in the case with the expectation that
they will avoid being barred from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ambitious, three-year undercover investigation that
preceded it, the government's legal struggle against the banks was
plagued from the start by internal divisions, officials familiar
with the case said.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials said federal prosecutors who included the
principal assistant U.S. attorney on the case, Duane R. Lyons,
argued that the banks should not be indicted on criminal charges
because it was not clear they had benefited from the actions of the
bankers who were ultimately charged with helping drug traffickers
to launder millions of dollars in illicit earnings.
</P>
<P>
   A first group from among the several dozen bankers, businessmen
and suspected traffickers indicted in the case last May will also
go on trial this week.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the officials added, Lyons was persuaded to seek
criminal indictments by officials from the Justice Department, the
Federal Reserve Board and other prosecutors. Lyons did not return a
telephone call asking for his comment.
</P>
<P>
   But many law-enforcement officials involved in the case said the
prosecutors had initially planned to file criminal money laundering
charges against at least four more banks whose employees were
implicated in the case. Only because the prosecutors were so behind
in preparing their indictments were those banks not charged, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One such bank, Banco Industrial de Venezuela, went so far in its
counterattack as to file suit against the U.S. Customs Service for
$4 million it said it lost during the undercover operation. The
bank was not indicted, but the head of its Miami branch, Esperanza
de Saad, the sister of a former Venezuelan cabinet minister, is
being prosecuted for money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   And though the suit was later dropped, officials said, the
drumbeat of Venezuelan complaints continued. Last Nov. 4, officials
said, the assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs,
Peter Romero, called in the Venezuelan ambassador to the United
States then, Pedro Luis Echeverria, and delivered a formal protest
in response to the ambassador's sharp public criticism.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, Venezuelan officials finally received a letter from
the U.S. attorney's office in Los Angeles saying that Banco
Industrial was not the target of any criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   After first praising the customs operation, Mexican officials
also shifted to bitter criticism, threatening publicly to prosecute
undercover agents who conducted meetings in Mexico with bankers and
drug traffickers, and warning of the impact the prosecutions could
have on the Mexican economy.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Clinton visited Mexico last month, those
complaints moved a senior aide on the National Security Council,
James Dobyns, to ask officials at the Justice Department how he
might speak with prosecutors on the case to discuss the
foreign-policy concerns it raised.
</P>
<P>
   Although two officials said a telephone conference call was
tentatively scheduled for Feb. 8, it did not take place. One senior
official who spoke on the condition of anonymity insisted that the
White House dropped the idea of its own accord. Dobyns declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
