<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE WITH IT: FREE AGENCY IS A GAMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Los Angeles Kings forked over a
$4.25-million divorce settlement to defenseman Steve Duchesne last
week, bringing his 1998-99 take to around $8 million, general
manager Dave Taylor made it clear the team would be very careful
before dipping into the free-agent market again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me,'' Taylor said, ``is if a player has
a great year, he's looking for top dollar, and when he doesn't have
a great year the risk is still with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, that indeed is the way it is, and if a team doesn't
like it, one of its options is to opt out of the free-agent market
and try to build a winner through the draft or by making savvy
trades.
</P>
<P>
   Any method of building a team, however, includes no warranty. A
trade that looks brilliant when consummated can look foolish soon
thereafter. A top draft choice can flop. Attempts to sign
restricted free agents usually fail, because the player's original
team invariably matches the offer. And the most expensive players,
unrestricted free agents, can be busts.
</P>
<P>
   When a prime unrestricted free agent (a player who will command
a multiyear deal worth more than $10 million) doesn't pan out, the
financial burden on the team that signed him is enormous. Thus,
before signing such players, teams ought to decide not only whether
the player will help the team win, but whether the player will
attract fans.
</P>
<P>
   If the player cannot do both, the team probably is better served
shopping the bargain rack.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks did that late last summer and landed Fredrik
Olausson, who will wind up making eight times less than Duchesne
this year but has had a season roughly eight times better.
</P>
<P>
   Given its local flavor, the Duchesne-Olausson comparison is
especially vivid. It is not unique, however.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Uwe Krupp signed with Colorado last summer and will
be paid $4.1 million this season but has been plagued by back
trouble and has appeared in just 22 games. Defenseman Gary Suter
signed with San Jose for $2.8 million this season and played in one
game before an elbow injury ended his year.
</P>
<P>
   In goal, no team made a smarter move last summer than Carolina,
which signed Arturs Irbe (25-18-11, 2.30 goals-against average) for
$550,000, roughly one-tenth what the New York Rangers are paying
Mike Richter (24-27-8) and the Toronto Maple Leafs are paying
Curtis Joseph (31-22-6).
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars may be pleased with right wing Brett Hull (28
goals, 51 points), who is earning $4.5 million. But the Rangers
signed right wing John MacLean for $2.3 million, and he had 50
points entering Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Is Chicago's William Wirtz, whose team is among the NHL's worst,
happy to have paid center Doug Gilmour $6 million this season?
Gilmour had 56 points and a minus-16 defensive rating, and is out
for the year with a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis paid Geoff Courtnall $3.5 million this year, and he
had 10 points in 21 games before going on the injured list with
post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes are in first place, so they haven't groused much
but has Ron Francis (44 points) been worth $5 million?
</P>
<P>
   It is pointless for teams to complain after the fact about their
misspent dollars. The time to make a wise decision is before
offering a huge contract.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe it, consider that at season's end, Wayne
Gretzky _ the best player and box-office attraction ever _ will
miss the playoffs for the fourth time in the past six years. &QL; 
STANDING PAT
</P>
<P>
   Did Detroit buy a third straight Stanley Cup by acquiring
defensemen Chris Chelios and Ulf Samuelsson and forward Wendel
Clark at last week's trading deadline?
</P>
<P>
   The league-leading Dallas Stars, who were comparatively quiet at
the deadline, are hoping they already had enough on their roster to
win their first Cup. Ultimately, though, they may wish general
manager Bob Gainey had added some depth on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys have worked all year on the details they've been
asked to work on to be a good team, with their eyes on playing in
the playoffs against the top competitors,'' Gainey said. ``And
they've proven they were willing and they should be given a chance
to do it. So they will.'' &QL; 
BULKING UP
</P>
<P>
   Kudos to the Red Wings for doing whatever it takes for a chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it and I've been in this
business 30 years,'' Wings coach Scotty Bowman said after his
team's wild day of trading. ``I think it gives us a better feel in
the room that this team means business. There's only certain
opportunities that teams have, and there's a lot of good teams out
there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings, however, may be the best of the bunch _ again. &QL; 
MUMBO JUMBO
</P>
<P>
   With a break in the schedule last week, the Philadelphia Flyers
disappeared into the woods for six hours of ``team building,'' a
program run by a Canadian motivational group that usually works
with large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really fun,'' right wing Mikael Renberg said. ``They
set up ropes on the trees that looked like a spider net, and we had
to find a way through these big holes in it without touching the
ropes. You had to pretend the ropes were electrified, and if you
touched it you had to wear a blindfold and the other guys on your
team had to get you through.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Barry Melrose days, when the Kings were in a state
of collapse, motivational guru Tony Robbins was brought in, with
little lasting effect. The Flyers should prepare for similar
long-term results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
