<SLUG> BC-SONY-MGM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY PICTURES, IN ACCORD WITH MGM, DROPS PLAN TO PRODUCE JAMES BOND
MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it was a movie, it might have been called ``The
Spy Who Got Knocked Cold.'' But it is reality, and Sony Pictures
Entertainment on Monday suffered a defeat in a longstanding legal
dispute with Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   MGM, a unit of the P&AMP;F Acquisition Corp., announced a settlement
under which Sony Pictures dropped its plan to produce new James
Bond movies.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat, which seemed all but certain after MGM obtained a
temporary restraining order several months ago, is particularly
difficult for Sony Pictures, and not just in financial terms. It
strikes at the heart of the movie studio's stated strategy of
focusing its efforts on movie franchises that spin off numerous
sequels.
</P>
<P>
   The studio has thus far failed to begin any such profitable
franchises and its president, John Calley, had said earlier that he
was pursuing the James Bond movies as a way of tapping into this
lucrative business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Sony Pictures will pay MGM $5
million to settle the lawsuit, MGM said. In return, MGM said, it
will pay Sony Pictures $10 million for the rights to an early James
Bond spoof, ``Casino Royale,'' which was produced at Columbia
Pictures, a Sony unit, and for all international rights to the
James Bond films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of this case reaffirms that James Bond resides at one
address _ that of MGM and Danjaq, his constant home for the last 37
years,'' Frank G. Mancuso, MGM's chairman, said in a statement.
Danjaq LLC. is the company controlled by the family of the late
Albert (Cubby) Broccoli, who had produced the early Bond films and
was part-owner of the rights to make the movies, along with United
Artists, an MGM unit.
</P>
<P>
   The James Bond movies have been box office hits for nearly four
decades _ the first installment was ``Dr. No,'' in 1962 _ making
them one of the most durable and profitable franchises in history,
along with the Star Wars and Star Trek franchises. The last Bond
film, ``Tomorrow Never Dies,'' was released in December 1997, and
had revenue of about $350 million. The next movie, ``The World is
Not Enough,'' starring Pierce Brosnan as 007, is scheduled for
release in November.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the films, about the dashing, martini-sipping
British secret agent, have been produced at MGM and they continue
to be among the most profitable films produced at that studio.
</P>
<P>
   The current dispute began 18 months ago when Sony Pictures, a
unit of the Sony Corp. of Japan, announced that it had signed a
deal to produce additional Bond movies with Kevin McClory. McClory
had been a producer of ``Thunderball,'' and the virtual remake of
that film, ``Never Say Never Again.''
</P>
<P>
   He has asserted that he helped develop the James Bond concept
with Ian Fleming, the author of the original books about the sexy,
unstoppable agent, and had the rights to produce additional films.
MGM has said he had the rights to produce only ``Thunderball''
remakes.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute became personal when MGM filed a suit not just
against Sony Pictures but also named Calley. Calley had been the
head of MGM's United Artists studio before moving to Sony Pictures
and there have long been reports of friction between him and
Mancuso. But that portion of the suit was also dropped with the
settlement announced on Monday. A parallel suit against McClory is
scheduled to go to court on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Pictures issued a statement acknowledging a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
