<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Local Economy Doing Well Despite Asia
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
With Asian economies swooning and technology exports dropping, it
is easy to conclude that the local economy must be on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, according to a new study by the UCLA Anderson Forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The study, scheduled for release Tuesday, said job growth in
Northern California was 3.2 percent last year compared to 2.6
percent for the United States as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Even techie Santa Clara County, which is highly vulnerable to
the Asian flu, posted an employment increase of 3.3 percent in
1998, although job growth there slowed significantly in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Incomes grew even faster than jobs in California last year.
Driven largely by high-paying, white-collar positions, personal
incomes grew 6.6 percent in California last year over 1997, the
largest increase since 1990 and significantly higher than the U.S.
rate of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The personal income category includes wages, salaries and
unearned income such as stock dividends. Plumper wallets bode well
for sales of everything from cars to homes to jewelry to towels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth last year was very, very good and generally speaking,
we are at least continuing in the first quarter the very rapid pace
we saw in 1998,'' said Ted Gibson, chief economist for the
California Department of Finance. ``Despite Asia, everything seems
to be going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the strength in California and the Bay Area, in
particular, is attributable to business services, a diverse sector
that includes management consulting, computer maintenance,
photocopying, advertising and software development.
</P>
<P>
   The number of business service jobs in the state jumped 10.3
percent last year, with technology-related positions increasing at
about double the overall rate. The sector has added some 400,000
jobs in the past five years, according to Tom Lieser, executive
director of the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half of 1998 was much stronger than we had
projected as recently as last December,'' said Lieser. ``The Asian
situation is (a factor), but it's not large enough to offset the
domestic strength we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, trade is a concern. Exports, which account for about
one-fifth of the California economy, dropped 4.2 percent last year,
with the fall-off accelerating as the year progressed, according to
the study.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not confined to Asia, which accounts for as much
as half of California's export market. Shipments to Western Europe,
Mexico and Canada moderated dramatically, and in some cases fell
into negative territory in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and other electronic equipment, which declined by 8.1
percent, were not the only exports to suffer. Agricultural products
such as processed foods fell 4 percent and chemical exports dropped
3.1 percent as the global economy remained listless.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Jose area, job growth remained positive but slowed
sharply to 1 percent in December 1998 compared to December 1997,
and from 3.3 percent in 1998 as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   That compares to December job growth of 2.4 percent in San
Francisco, Marin and San Mateo counties, 2.4 percent in Alameda and
Contra Costa counties and 3.4 percent for the state, which got its
biggest economic boost from the central part of California.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its problems, Santa Clara's 3.5 percent unemployment
rate in February was still well below the national average of 4.3
percent. San Francisco's unemployment rate stood at a minuscule 2.6
percent while Oakland's tallied 3.6 percent, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what's going on in Asia, Santa Clara County's doing
pretty well,'' said Gibson. ``Who would have thought they could
lose that big of a chunk of their market and still have growth of
even 1 percent?''
</P>
<P>
   California economists are optimistic that the Asian economies
will turn a corner in the next year or so. Gibson believes Santa
Clara will continue to plod along at a modest pace until Asia picks
up steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take is that things won't change much over 1999, but we may
see the beginnings of a recovery late this year or in early 2000,''
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieser forecasts job growth in California at 3.4 percent this
year and 2.3 percent in 2000 and 2001, compared to smaller U.S.
increases of 1.8 percent in 1999, 1.1 percent in 2000 and 1.5
percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   After many years of weakness, construction last year turned
dramatically upward, hitting its highest level since 1990. Another
strong year is expected in 1999, although construction still lags
its peak in the mid-1980s, according to the Anderson study.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence for the Pacific region is near the all-time
high hit in 1989, said Lieser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
