<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON.COM-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON.COM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Amazon.com's Next Page _ Online Auctions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Amazon.com, already the Internet's largest retailer, is expanding
into another booming Web business _ online auctions.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion, planned in the next few weeks, pits Amazon
against auction giant eBay and moves the book, music and video
seller into one of the Web's more profitable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon plans to host person-to-person auctions for more than 800
types of merchandise, including antique scientific instruments,
movie memorabilia, jewelry and, of course, Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   The move into auctions is part of the booksellers's strategy of
turning itself into a giant Internet shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced yesterday an agreement to purchase a
50 percent stake in Pets.com, a San Francisco online pet-products
retailer. Last month, Amazon acquired 46 percent of Seattle startup
Drugstore.com, a seller of pharmaceuticals, over-the-counter
medicines and beauty aids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the place where people can buy anything they
want to buy,'' said Bill Curry, an Amazon spokesman. Anything, that
is, except firearms, live animals and pornography. Like eBay,
Amazon will ban those items from its auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts called the initiative a smart way to squeeze more
revenue out of Amazon's 8 million customers and to find new ones.
The company plans to charge fees for listing products and for
completed sales based on a percentage of the price of the item. A
button on its home page will link users to auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has a great opportunity to convert (customers)
from one-click buyers to one-click bidders,'' said Kate Delhagen,
director of online retail research at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But Delhagen and other analysts said the online auction business
poses risks, even for an experienced Web player like Amazon. Unlike
the sale of books or videos, Amazon will not have control of its
auctions because buyers and sellers deal directly with each other.
That's caused problems for eBay, because some sellers have used the
site to auction off illegal items or to defraud buyers. The San
Jose company recently instituted policies to combat fraud, and it
banned firearms and weapons from the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon has built a phenomenal brand name, partly by being
almost religious about customer satisfaction,'' said Ken Cassar, an
analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York. There's a risk
that auction bidders and sellers won't be as scrupulous, Cassar
said.
</P>
<P>
   To help address that problem, Amazon is offering what it
describes as a ``guarantee'' against fraud. When customers feel
they've been cheated, the company will reimburse them for costs on
purchases up to $250. There is no fee for this guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Amazon's move into auctions poses a significant
challenge for eBay. Amazon has 8 million customers, nearly four
times the 2.1 million registered users on eBay. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``EBay should be worried,'' Cassar said. ``I wouldn't expect
that existing eBay customers are going to free &LR; flee, but I do think
this could put a dent in the company's future customer acquisition
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, officials at eBay didn't appear to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon.com is a savvy Internet competitor, and has done a very
good job in the area of business-to-consumer Internet commerce,''
the company said in a statement. ``However, this is a very
different business than the person-to-person space in which eBay is
the leader and ... (has a) significant competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's shares jumped $10.56 to $149.63 yesterday, while shares
in eBay fell $6.72 to $147.78.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2155EST &QL; 
