<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATTACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRSTRIKES SHIFT TO FOCUS ON MOBILE SERB UNITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO on Monday promised ``around the clock'' air
attacks in Yugoslavia, as Russian leaders prepared to meet with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for consultations the United
States and allies awaited warily.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth day of allied bombardment against Milosevic's military
included U.S. A-10 ``Warthog'' ground-attack planes to target
tanks, indicating a new focus on mobile Serb units in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo. The Pentagon announced a further buildup of
U.S. planes in Europe for the NATO campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian situation in the region appeared to
deteriorate. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said 4,000 refugees an hour
poured over the Kosovo border into Albania. Five prominent ethnic
Albanians _ including Fehmi Agani, a participant at the recent
cease-fire talks in France _ were reportedly executed in Kosovo as
part of what NATO called a ``scorched-earth policy'' by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and NATO insisted that the allied
airstrikes had not led to the increase in ethnic violence, and
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called testily for pundits and
politicians to stop second-guessing the military mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage everyone to stop trying to write the
conclusion of this story at the end of each day,'' Lockhart said.
``This is a phased military campaign, a systematic assault on
President Milosevic and the Serbian military. This will take time,
and we will continue doing it until our military objectives are
met.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby of
Britain's Royal Air Force, said the airstrikes ``will continue to
go around the clock _ around the full clock _ to make sure that we
get our pressure on'' Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin spokesman Dmitri Yakushkin said Russian President Boris
Yeltsin ordered Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev to travel to
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim of the trip is to coordinate steps (with Milosevic),
which could help find a political solution to the conflict which
has emerged because of NATO's military action,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has strenuously criticized the NATO attacks on a fellow
Slavic nation, but has limited its objections to largely symbolic
steps.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said the United States
welcomes ``any diplomatic efforts'' but a U.S. official said
expectations for the mission ranged from ``modest to nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' Rubin said, ``NATO will continue air
operations until such time as President Milosevic halts his
offensive and commits to a settlement based on the Rambouillet
accords.''
</P>
<P>
   The accords, written by NATO allies, call for a cease-fire in
Kosovo that would be policed by allied troops. Fighting began when
the largely ethnic Albanian province sought independence from
Serbia, one of two republics that make up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanian delegation signed the document, but
representatives of Milosevic refused, calling the plan an
unwarranted attack on Yugoslavia's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was part of the so-called Contact Group that sponsored
the sessions in Paris and Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, alliance spokesmen
indicated that the Yugoslav air-defense system had been damaged
enough to allow a shift to specific operational targets in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major weight of our efforts focused on operations and
installations supplying the paramilitary, military and (special
police) forces in Kosovo,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   As Lockhart did at the White House, Shea expressed disdain for
short-term assessments faulting the military effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that President Milosevic is very tenacious, but so
are we,'' Shea said. ``Is the mission working? Yes, we are being
effective. Yes, the mission is working. This is a methodical,
systematic and progressive air campaign to strip the Serb
leadership bare of their military capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   To help, the United States is sending additional B1B bombers to
the area, along with five EA-6B Prowler anti-radar aircraft and
more tanker planes, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   Air Commodore Wilby, on NBC's Today, said the new phase of the
air campaign is showing signs of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``From yesterday, we were getting extremely heartening news from
sources which said that there was evidence that our campaign was
beginning to work,'' Wilby said. ``It was beginning to disrupt
them. It was beginning to worry them. And we will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   At a subsequent NATO briefing, Wilby said the Yugoslav
air-defense system showed ``less response'' overnight Sunday than
previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in our minds that it is shaky,'' Wilby said.
``I'm not saying it's down, I'm not saying it's a totally
neutralized threat. There will always be a threat from that air
defense. But we have got very capable aircraft, and we will
prosecute the job that we need to do to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea joined Lockhart in disputing the idea that the NATO
airstrikes had led to more violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd stress that the current campaign is not a spontaneous
outburst following NATO's operations,'' Shea said. ``It looks much
more like a planned, conceived _ and executed, now _ campaign
against the civil population'' prepared as the Yugoslav delegation
was rejecting the Rambouillet cease-fire proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to stop this catastrophe and stop this
killing,'' NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that the number of refugees from Kosovo who have
streamed into already struggling Albania has doubled to 60,000 in a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see an effort to destabilize neighboring countries by
flooding them with refugees,'' that tax the economic and social
structures, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO believes about 280,000 displaced people remain in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was ``particularly disturbing'' that Yugoslav police
officials are charging at least 1,000 deutsche marks (about $550)
to cross into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko said Serb authorities were
demanding refugees hand over official identity papers before
crossing into his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if their identities are being canceled out,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
