<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-PROBE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO CLUB CLOSES PROBE INTO IRWINDALE SPEEDWAY DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GARARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ The United States Auto Club on Monday closed
its investigation into the death of a 23-year-old sprint car driver
who died from injuries suffered in an accident during practice at
Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Diemert of Roseburg, Ore., died Saturday afternoon when
his car struck the wall between turns 3 and 4. At the time, he was
traveling about 100 mph. Witnesses said the accident occurred when
Diemert attempted to avoid a car that was stalled on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Maddox, the USAC chief steward charged with investigating
the accident, said the fatal accident occurred when Diemert failed
to see a yellow caution light warning of the stalled car.
</P>
<P>
   ``A car had spun on the track; the caution light had come out,''
said Maddox, who witnessed the accident. ``It was apparent to me
that Casey did not see the caution light. He got over the wheel of
another car and went into the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 15 cars on the track at the time of the accident,
Maddox said. Diemert's death occurred during the first practice
session on opening day at the $10 million Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In his investigation, Maddox concluded that everything was done
properly. All the cars were mechanically inspected before the
practice session, as was all the safety equipment on cars and
drivers, Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything checked out,'' Maddox said. ``It was an impact that
was unsurvivable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Irwindale Police were called to the scene, they did
no formal investigation of the accident, Irwindale Police Lt. Rick
Woodmansee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, we get names of people involved,''
Woodmansee said. ``It would be kind of tough for us to do a fatal
accident investigation. They take four or five hours to do and you
can't hold up the races.''
</P>
<P>
   As for auto racing: ``(Death) is just one of the things that
comes with the territory,'' Woodmansee said.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting an autopsy, a medical examiner for the Los
Angeles County Department of Coroner ruled Diemert's death an
accident. A routine toxicology report will be performed to
determine if Diemert had any drugs or alcohol in his system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that in all auto accidents,'' said coroner's spokesman
Scott Carrier. ``It's a very normal procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Diemert's father and the owner of the car, James Diemert, was
reached Monday at the family home in Roseburg. He recalled his
son's brief racing career and the events leading up to Casey's
death Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   James Diemert remembered his son as an ``exceptional driver, who
raced every minute he was on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Diemert began racing at age 16. He raced street stocks,
trucks and sprints, James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was another car on the track, he'd try to catch it or
pass it. He had to have somebody out there to compete with,'' the
father said. ``He was a racer. He had his foot down and his elbows
out all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was at the track, James Diemert said he didn't see
the accident that resulted in his son's death. And because he had
turned his back to the track, he never saw the caution light.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happened, (the yellow light) had just come out. It
couldn't have been out for very long because I had turned away to
go meet him (in the pits),'' Diemert said. ``I had to go around the
back of the track to do that, and when I got there, it had already
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements are pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
