<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BP-ARCO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AND ARCO SAID TO EDGE TOWARD DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic showing two companies at a glance is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BP Amoco is close to an agreement to acquire the Atlantic
Richfield Co. in a stock swap worth about $28 billion, executives
close to the talks said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The executives also said that some of the top executive officers
at ARCO including its chief executive, Michael R. Bowlin, were not
likely to remain in their jobs if an agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies are expected to meet on Wednesday
to consider the deal.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, which was formed last December in a merger of British
Petroleum and the Amoco Corp., forming the word's third-largest oil
company, and ARCO confirmed the negotiations in a joint statement
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They cautioned, however, that an agreement had not been reached
and that the discussions could still be called off.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, shares of ARCO surged Monday, rising $8.6875, or
13.3 percent, to $74.0625, in heavy trading on the New York Stock
Exchange. The American depository shares of BP Amoco, each of which
represents six ordinary shares, were also up sharply, climbing
$4.5625, or 4.5 percent, to $105. In London, BP Amoco shares rose
40 pence, or 3.9 percent, to 1,077.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO, based in Los Angeles, has most of its operations on the
West Coast, where it is a large refiner and seller of gasoline. It
has about 26 percent of the gasoline retail market in California.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that ARCO would flesh out BP Amoco's national
refining and marketing business, which is strong in the East and
Midwest but not on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It also has major oil and natural gas fields and production in
Alaska, gas fields in Indonesia and is making an effort to get a
foothold in the Caspian Sea region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying ARCO would transform BP Amoco from a very powerful
regional company to a truly global oil company,'' said J. Robinson
West, the chairman of Petroleum Finance, an industry consulting
group based in Washington. ``In the past, they have cut costs very
well, but this gives them growth as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The main force in building up BP Amoco has been Sir John Browne,
its chief executive, who took over a slow-moving and troubled
company in 1991 and helped to transform it into an industry
pacesetter by sharply cutting costs and forming alliances with
other oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   His takeover of Amoco last August helped lead to the purchase of
the Mobil Corp. by the Exxon Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the current talks, ARCO is being advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. and Salomon Smith Barney, a unit of Citigroup. BP Amoco is
being advised by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   If Browne were successful in buying ARCO, analysts said it would
put great pressure on other large oil companies such as Texaco Inc.
and the Chevron Corp. to also find merger partners. The stocks of
most major oil companies rose Monday, with shares of Texaco up
$2.1875, to $57.75, and Chevron up $2.8125, to $89.625.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said Monday that BP Amoco would
offer about $28 billion in stock for ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good deal for ARCO shareholders,'' said Adam
Sieminski, an analyst with BT Alex. Brown, because they would gain
shares in a growing company.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO has been severely hurt by the big fall in crude oil prices
last year, which sharply lowered its earnings and led to loss in
the fourth quarter. Analysts began to wonder whether it could keep
paying its substantial yearly dividend of $2.85 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that one of the main reasons BP Amoco was
interested in ARCO was that both companies have big holdings and
production in Prudhoe Bay, Alaska, where they made major finds in
the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO has largely lived off its production there, generating
money to build its refining and chemical business.
</P>
<P>
   For a time the company was an industry leader, being one of the
first oil companies to add convenience stores to its gas stations.
It has 1,700 in seven Western states, with 900 in California. It
also built two large refineries, one in Cherry Point, Wash., and
the other in Carson, Calif. Both can process more than 200,000
barrels of crude oil a day.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than concentrating on exploration to find another Prudhoe
Bay, however, the company went into the petrochemical business and
bought tankers to transport crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   As the production began to run down in Alaska, the company began
an aggressive program to find more oil but had disappointing
results. In the 1990s, it sold its chemical business to finance
more exploration and bought an independent oil company, Union Texas
Holdings Inc. of Houston, last year to strengthen its overseas
exploration operations.
</P>
<P>
   Its refining and gas station business has also been under
pressure as new low-cost independent refiners have entered its
markets, and other refiners have merged their operations and cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO has not joined the industry in building stations where
customers can use a wide variety of credit cards to fill up at the
pumps. It still relies on cash and debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think that employees of the former Amoco, who were
considered savvy marketers of gasoline, will be of great help in
revamping ARCO's gasoline business.
</P>
<P>
   While ARCO has been more of a no-frills seller of gasoline, it
nevertheless has been making good money at it, with profits from
its stations surpassing many of its larger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking Bloomingdale's, we're talking Sam's,'' said
Sieminski, referring to the discount retail chain. ``They're price
conscious and they're doing very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBRYO-MIXUP-NYT &LR;      03-29 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-MIXUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
COUPLE IN EMBRYO MIX-UP TENTATIVELY AGREE TO GIVE UP ONE BABY
</HEADLINE>
   (fb) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last April, Donna Fasano and Deborah Perry-Rogers
arrived separately at a fertility clinic in Manhattan filled with
hope and apprehension. Both women had tried without success for
years to conceive a child. Both had the same doctor, and they had
appointments on the same spring day to be implanted with fertilized
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Fasano, of New York City, was pregnant with
twins, but Rogers, of Teaneck, N.J., was not pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, the lives of two women who had never met
became unexpectedly entangled: they were told, according to lawyers
for both women, that a mistake had occurred. The lawyers said that
Dr. Lillian Nash had implanted Fasano not only with four of her
eggs fertilized by her husband, but also with several other
fertilized eggs, apparently from Rogers and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   DNA tests showed that Fasano was the biological mother of one
baby, but not the other.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, the mix-up was confirmed when Fasano gave
birth to two healthy boys. One baby, like the Fasanos, is white.
The other, like the Rogerses, is black.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, lawyers representing the Fasanos announced a stunning
solution to the mix-up: the Fasanos will raise one boy, but they
will allow the Rogerses to raise the other, if DNA tests confirm
that the Rogerses are the biological parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fasanos have reared, loved and cared for both children as
their own,'' said Ivan L. Tantleff, one of three lawyers
representing the New York couple. ``She is doing this because she
loves her boys, and she is a victim here, not the culprit. She
doesn't look at them as white and black. She looks at them as her
sons. She is torn apart by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement came two weeks after the Rogerses filed a
lawsuit that seeks custody of one boy and claims negligence,
malpractice and breach of contract on the part of Nash and two
other physicians. Tantleff informed the lawyer for the Rogerses,
Rudolph Silas, on Monday that the Fasanos had decided to allow the
other couple to raise one of the boys, pending the results of the
DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Silas said he reached an astonished Mrs. Rogers late Monday
afternoon with the news. ``She was very excited to hear the good
news and overwhelmed after so many failed efforts to conceive,'' he
said. ``Delighted, overwhelmed and mostly tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said neither couple would speak with reporters, and
Tantleff said the Fasanos refused to release photographs of the
babies or their names. The Rogerses and the Fasanos are expected to
meet for the first time within a week, with the two brothers.
Tantleff did release a handwritten statement by Mrs. Fasano.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't my doing,'' Mrs. Fasano said. ``People with
infertility problems should be able to go to their doctors and
trust them to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fasano then seemed to address Nash and the other two
doctors. ``To them, it may be a job,'' she said. ``To me, it's my
life. She may have given me two beautiful babies, but she destroyed
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``We both want what's in the best interest of the
child. We're giving him up because we love him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nash could not be reached for comment; her answering service
said Monday afternoon that her office had closed for the day.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, the Rogerses have accused Nash, Dr. Dov B.
Goldstein and an embryologist named only as Dr. Obasaju with
negligently mishandling their embryos. Tantleff said the Fasanos
were planning to file a separate lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Silas said the Fasanos will probably be dropped as defendants in
the Rogerses' suit since the custody issue appears to have been
resolved. Before Monday's announcement, Silas said the Rogerses had
been undergoing counseling and had been emotionally distraught.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had approached this at the end of many years trying to
conceive,'' Silas said, referring to Mrs. Rogers. Now, he said,
there was reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly raises the possibility of a happy ending for all
parties,'' he said, ``at least happier than it would have been if
there had not been two children.''
</P>
<P>
   Tantleff said the Fasanos will insist upon a visitation
agreement so that the boys will know each other as brothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
