<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROOPS-BOX-0330-COX     03-29 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROOPS-BOX-0330-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO TROOPS STRENGTH IN THE BALKANS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TROOPS-O330.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The following are some current numbers on NATO
troops in the Balkans:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A 28,000-member peacekeeping force is proposed to go into the
Kosovo province under the peace agreement signed by ethnic
Albanians; 4,000 of those would be American.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Already a force of about 12,000 British, French, German,
Italian and Dutch peacekeepers have been moved down into Macedonia
as the first wave of those peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NATO maintains a 32,000-member multi-national force of
peacekeepers in Bosnia-Herzegovina as part of the Dayton Accords;
about 7,000 of those are from the U.S. 1st Cavalry Div. based at
Fort Hood, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There is an expeditionary unit of 2,200 U.S. Marines aboard
ship in the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The United States has a 1,200-member reinforced infantry unit
at Aviano Air Base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And if NATO ground troops were to become necessary:
</P>
<P>
   --There are an estimated 75,000-100,000 in the Serb military;
40,000 Yugoslav troops are stationed in and around Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   --Experts estimate 200,000-300,000 NATO troops would be needed
in a ground war in Kosovo against those Serb forces to quell the
fighting there.
</P>
<P>
   Source: North Atlantic Treat Organization; Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
