<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MARCH 30
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CISCO-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Mar. 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Mar. 23,
about the transmission of voice calls using Internet technology
misstated the location of the headquarters of Vocall
Communications. It is in Mountainside, N.J., not Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-NOISE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Mar. 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Mar.
17, about noise cancellation technology misstated the reduction in
the magnitude of sound that would be achieved by going from 100
decibels to 85 decibels. Because decibels are measured on a
logarithmic scale, the reduction would be 82 percent, not 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Mar. 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Mar.
17, misstated the cost of a new ICQ instant message service called
Signaler, which notifies users of messages even if they are not on
line. The service, from NECS, a subsidiary of the Bell South
International Group, costs $9.95 per year, not per month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
