<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS &LR;      03-29 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS INCREASE; US LOOKS TO RUSSIAN VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO trained its bombs on Yugoslav ground troops
and as refugees streamed Monday from Kosovo with fresh horror
stories of genocide, US officials turned warily to Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov's planned visit to Belgrade Tuesday as a
possible first step toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who scrapped a US visit after the NATO airstrikes
began last week, made for an unlikely beacon of hope. Russia, a
longtime Serbian ally, protested the bombings from the outset, and
even Monday, several Russian officials blamed ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo for the mass destruction sweeping the southern province.
</P>
<P>
   But on the sixth day of NATO airstrikes, amid growing anxiety
that the reported atrocities by Serbian forces might not be stopped
without ground troops, Western officials spoke of Primakov's
pending visit with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in
increasingly optimistic terms. NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
paid Primakov a personal compliment, saying: ``I know his
diplomatic skills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he will be able to convince Milosevic to stop and
return to the path of negotiations worked out at Rambouillet,''
Solana said, referring to the recent failed peace talks in France.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said: ``We welcome those who
have influence on Belgrade, who will take a message about what it
is they need to do in order to end this allied air campaign. It
could be constructive.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's impromptu trip follows the urging of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, who also sent several other top Russian
officials. It also followed a deal Monday with the International
Monetary Fund, which will loan more money to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Defense Ministar Igor Ivanov confirmed that the purpose
of Primakov's trip was to ``coordinate steps which could help find
a political solution to the conflict,'' though he blamed the crisis
on the West, saying it ``emerged because of NATO's military
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite continued international criticism, US and NATO
warplanes stepped up their attacks on Yugoslav forces, zeroing in
on ground troops widely reported to be committing atrocities
against Albanians. In addition to reportedly sending in the A-10
ground-attack planes, a large low-flying aircraft known as the
``Warthog,'' the United States made plans to increase its airpower
with additional B-1B bombers and EA-6B aircraft, said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reducing the Yugoslav ability to sustain operations,''
Bacon said. ``But the impact of choking off supply lines and
eliminating ammo facilities and fuel supplies, of course, is a
delayed impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ethnic Albanians, exhausted, petrified and traveling
by foot, continued to flood into neighboring Albania and Macedonia
by the thousands. They told horrible stories of mass lootings and
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, fearing the flood of refugees, appealed urgently to
neighboring countries to open their borders to accept refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached our limit of 20,000 refugees,'' Deputy Premier
Radmila Kiprijanova said at a news conference. ``A larger number
will result in the destabilization of the country and the region,''
Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   Among those murdered execution-style were five ethnic Albanian
leaders, including Fehmi Agani, a delegate to the recent peace
talks in Rambouillet, France, NATO officials said. Baton Haxhiu,
the editor-in-chief of the main Kosovar Albanian newspaper, Koha
Ditore, was also among the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what's going on at the borders, you have what
appears to be a textbook definition of ethnic cleansing,'' Lockhart
said at the White House. State Department spokesman James Rubin
said there were ``indications genocide is unfolding in Kosovo,''
calling the massacres and the resulting crisis ``abhorrent and
criminal action on a maximum scale.''
</P>
<P>
   To help combat the growing potential for disaster, particularly
in Albania, one of the poorest nations in Europe, where some 60,000
refugees have fled in the past week, the United States gave $8.5
million to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to
help pay for relief items such as blankets and medicine, according
to Assistant Secretary of State Julia Taft. Food supplies were also
being sent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remained about what further steps the United States
should take within the borders of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   After six days of bombing, and with no signs Milosevic would
relent anytime soon, some military analysts increased their call
for officials to consider the possibility of using ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have a better option for ending this war, I
don't know how they can rule ground troops out,'' said Michael
O'Hanlon, a senior analyst at the Brookings Institution. Senator
John McCain, Republican of Arizona, made similar remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But others continued to express serious reservations about such
plans. Representative Sam Gejdenson, Democrat of Connecticut, said,
``With the exception of Senator McCain, there's almost a universal
aversion to ground troops.'' Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, also a
Connecticut Democrat, agreed, saying he was ``surprised at those
calls,'' and that the risk of sending in troops are ``higher than
the stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real potential for a quagmire _ a situation where
we find it hard to get out, a situation of combat, not peacekeeping
troops,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said NATO had ``no intention'' of
sending ground troops into Kosovo, which analysts have said would
require some 200,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic military bullet here,'' Bacon said. ``Even
if a decision by some NATO countries was made to deploy ground
troops from parts of Europe into Kosovo, it would take a long
while.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center released a national poll Monday showing
Americans favor NATO strikes only for a limited time, and only as
long as ground troops were not involved. Only a minority said they
thought the Kosovo situation is a serious problem for the United
States, while more than half were ``very worried'' about troop
casualties. Sixty percent said NATO has a responsibility to act.
But only 47 percent said that responsibility fell to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   All of which helped explain US officials' increasing eagerness
for the visit by Primakov to succeed. Vice President Al Gore, who
has close contact with Primakov and who last week told Primakov
about the airstrikes, prompting the Russian to cancel his US trip
in mid-flight, canceled his own six-day vacation this week.
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright has also had conversations
with the Russian foreign minister, Ivanov, both Sunday and Monday,
spokesman Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have not backed away from their assertion that
Serbs are not to blame for the conflict. Indeed, Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev blamed NATO Monday for killing some 1,000
civilians in the airstrikes. And Ivanov blamed NATO for protecting
the Kosovo Liberation Army, casting it as the terrorist instigators
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But as Primakov's visit neared, US officials tried to brush
those differences aside. The ultimate aim is for the strikes to
end, Lieberman said. ``I hope we'll get to a point _ and maybe
Primakov's visit will open the door _ where Milosevic is ready to
talk peace again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
