<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE IN DOW IS MATCHED BY OTHER SHARE MEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average's surge above 10,000
highlighted a session that saw broader market gauges move sharply
higher, pushed by merger talk in the oil patch and continued strong
demand for a relatively small group of big technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally did it,'' said Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment
strategist at Lehman Brothers. ``To some extent, Dow 10,000 is just
a number. But it is psychologically important.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the fourth day this month that the Dow has broken
through 10,000, the previous being on March 19. But enough sellers
emerged in those earlier sessions to push the index below that
level by the close of trading.
</P>
<P>
   By the closing bell on Monday, though, the Dow had risen 184.54
points, or 1.88 percent, to 10,006.78. Earlier in the day, the Dow
rose as high as 10,089.48.
</P>
<P>
   The close above 10,000 came nearly a year after April 6, 1998,
when the Dow first closed above 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the shuffle was a powerful performance by broader
market gauges.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 27.37, or 2.1
percent, to 1,310.17. The gain put the index close to its record of
1,316.55, set on March 18. The Nasdaq composite index, up nearly 14
percent this year, jumped 73.67, or 3 percent, on Monday, to
2,492.84, just under the peak of 2,510.09 it hit on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   To some analysts, the session's most encouraging development was
a good gain in the shares of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index, which tracks smaller-company stocks,
gained 5.84, or 1.5 percent, Monday, to 399.76. Still, the Russell
2000 is down by more than 5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, the bulk of the market's gains have been
concentrated in a small number of big, well-known companies. Many
analysts have questioned whether the market can continue to advance
if the leadership does not widen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious we are operating in a very narrow window of
strength,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at
Credit Suisse First Boston. ``In this kind of marketplace, prices
can go a lot higher, but you have to look very clearly at the kind
of risks you are talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Market averages, including the Russell 2000, were helped by news
that BP Amoco &UR;  &LR; is in talks to acquire ARCO &UR;  &LR; for about $28 billion
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO jumped 8 11/16, to 74 1/16, on the news, and the American
depository receipts of BP Amoco gained 4 9/16, to 105. Chevron, a
Dow component, gained 2 13/16, to 89|. Exxon, which is also part of
the Dow, gained 1 7/16, to 73. And Phillips Petroleum gained 2
7/16, to 48 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues were also big winners.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was the Dow's best performer, rising 5{, to 177~. Microsoft,
which split its shares 2 for 1 last Friday, gained 3\ on Monday, to
93]. Intel jumped 4}, to 121 7/16. And Cisco Systems rose 4 13/16,
to 110.
</P>
<P>
   Word that Computer Associates had agreed to buy Platinum
Technology International for $3.5 billion in cash also helped to
lift prices in the technology sector. Platinum Technology soared 14
3/16, to 24 1/16; Computer Associates gained 3 1/16, to 37.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service stocks, which have been cited by some analysts
as undervalued, also improved.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch gained 1 15/16, to 90 11/16. Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter rose 2}, to 105]. And Chase Manhattan rose 1}, to 82\.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
