<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSI     03-29 1908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE-TO-HOUSE ATTACKS BY SERB PARAMILITARY FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROGZIYA, Yugoslavia _ Systematic, methodical, and deadly, they
came house to house, dressed in their Australian bush hats and
bright green camouflage uniforms, brandishing side-holster bayonets
and AK-47 automatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   They are known as ``the Frenkis,'' the Serbian paramilitary
forces carrying out what they call ethnic cleansing in a brutal
expulsion of ethnic Albanians from the Kosovo town of Pec
(pronounced Pesh).
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not leave even one Albanian alive in Pec,''Arsim
Kelmendi, 34, said Monday just hours after fleeing for his life in
the predawn darkness from the smoldering remains of the town
roughly 10 miles from the Montenegro border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are horrifying. They are evil,'' Kelmendi said, shivering
in an icy rain at the border crossing where tens of thousands of
refugees from Pec formed a human tide of misery and fear pouring
into this relatively safe part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The second-largest city in Kosovo, Pec has become the grim
setting for among the worst atrocities committed by paramilitary
forces loyal to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. Behind much
of the ethnic cleansing in Pec is an obscure and shadowy covert
military unit loyal to one of Milosevic's secret police commanders,
Franko ``Frenki'' Simatovic, from whom the Frenkis take their name.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, eyewitnesses said the units have worked in
coordination with Milosevic's Yugoslav army and Serbian police in
an effort to force out almost all of the ethnic Albanians who made
up nearly 90 percent of the population of roughly 100,000 in Pec
and neighboring villages.
</P>
<P>
   The area of Pec is the ancient seat of the Serbian Orthodox
Church and a holy land to the ultranationalist forces who want to
rid it of the overwhelmingly Muslim Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Simatovic, who some believe is alive and others say was recently
killed by Albanian guerrillas, emerged from the state security
department of the Serbian Interior Ministry, according to a former
interior minister who is now a member of the anti-Milosevic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   They are referred to within the ministry as jojna linija, or
``the military line,'' said the former minister and witnesses
trying to build a case against Milosevic in the war crimes tribunal
in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Frenkis'' and other paramilitary units, such as Arkan's
Tigers, carried out a murderous campaign from 1991 to 1995 during
the war in Bosnia and Croatia in the former Yugoslavia. They are
believed to recruit convicts, then train and arm them, and set them
loose on ethnic communities. In Bosnia and Croatia in the early
1990s, they participated in some of the worst massacres of the war
and committed vast looting of homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are criminals and killers,'' said the former interior
minister, a respected government official who has spent a lifetime
as a military leader and in high-level political posts. Saying he
feared for the safety of his family in Belgrade, he spoke on
condition he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenkis descended on Pec in January, just weeks before the
world focused on futile peace talks in France. As many as 1,000
members of the force, working in units of up to 10, methodically
established a base for their campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with dozens of witnesses, including two ethnic
Albanian members of the international monitoring committees who
remained in Pec until Monday, reveal a horrifying picture of the
suffering and fear and killing of ethnic Albanians that enveloped
Pec, not only in the six days since the NATO bombing began, but
months before.
</P>
<P>
   After stealing cars and trucks for transportation, the units
carried out several sporadic attacks, beginning with a fire-bombing
in the village of Ljodja, outside Pec. One woman described seeing a
load of dead bodies in the back of a military truck from the
balcony of her home days after the firebombing. One of the members
of the international monitoring team who visited the site on Feb.
21 said, ``The village does not exist amymore. They burned it to
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   This was only an introduction to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When the first air raid siren sounded Wednesday afternoon,
signaling that the NATO attacks were underway, the Frenkis wasted
no time exacting swift and sustained revenge on the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the siren was going, they came and they smashed the
windows on my house. They broke into my cafe and they destroyed
everything,'' said Kelmendi.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, witnesses say, they had begun the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Halil Dylenikum, 30, was found, his throat slit, lying in a
small stream that trickled through the neighborhood of Ilirjana. He
was still wearing the jogging suit and running shoes neighbors say
they had seen him wearing earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him lying face up,'' said one neighbor, who asked not to
be identified because he still has family in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although a precise death toll is impossible to determine, two
members of the monitoring team, who also spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said they believed, based on the first-person accounts
they had heard in recent days, that at least 30 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Others have disappeared. Mentor Chavoli, 20, called from Kosovo
Monday to a friend, who told him that his uncle, Hacim Kocan, 45,
had been kidnapped and was feared dead. He had gone out to buy
food. All that was found was his bicycle and a quart of milk by the
side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are sure he is dead,'' said a friend of the family who
spoke with Chavoli from the other side of the border. ``So now they
have left to get out to save their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Frenkis were active in Karagagac, a
neighborhood near the center of Pec.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of a unit descended on the home of Valir Basha.
They broke through his front door, ordered him and his family out
of the house, and took to the roof. They doused it with gasoline
and ignited it. As the paramilitary forces fled, the house exploded
in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Kelmendi, who lives next door, tried to help his neighbor put
out the fire. But the Frenkis tossed a grenade, he said, and the
fragments from the blast knocked Basha off his feet, the shrapnel
tearing through his skin. Somehow, he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of witnesses described a pattern of cooperation among the
Frenkis, the Serbian Police, and the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenkis served as shock troops, witnesses said, coming to
the homes of ethnic Albanians and firing bursts of machine gun fire
at the windows and ordering them out. Then the Frenkis would
proceed to loot most of the homes of anything valuable, often
stripping women of jewelry. Men who tried to resist were beaten.
Some were taken to unknown locations.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the initial assault came the sound of Yugoslav Army
tanks. They fired incendiary shells into the homes, engulfing them
in flames. Many witnesses described seeing their homes and all
their belongings go up in a bright-orange blaze that gave Pec an
eerie glow in the darkness as the city burned, block by block. From
a hillside on the outskirts, an army artillery position shelled
ethnic Albanian neighborhoods nightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw houses burning, cannons firing shells every day. It is
all day and all night,'' said 18-year-old Edita, who nursed a
newborn in a ramshackle house of a relative where she had sought
refuge across the border in the republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   She was surrounded by 25 family members who recounted their own
tales of what they had seen in Pec in recent days. One, Ayna Gogad,
37, stared out a window at the snow-covered mountains outside. Her
eyes were fixed on a pass where she hopes her husband, her two
teenage sons, and a daughter will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my husband, `Please, let's not separate. I can't live
if something happens to you,' '' she said, before she packed into a
car with 12 relatives and raced to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone on the street risked arrest, beatings, and death. Scores
of young men between 18 and 35 have been rounded up and taken to
the Karajac Sports Center next to an army barracks, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the days of the NATO bombing, the violence has been
relentless.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Saniya Studenica, 80, said she saw her neighbor
shot. The Serbian police rang the doorbell of Abdel Rahman Salimi,
40, and when he came to the door, there was a burst of five shots.
Salimi collapsed in the doorway, bleeding but alive.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, unable to find care for him in Pec, rushed him,
bleeding, across the border. He is now in a hospital, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Halid Bachiri, 65, was gunned down in front of his two children,
said several relatives and neighbors. Men in fatigues came to his
house and asked him and his family to step outside. When he did
not, they shot him in his doorway. Bachiri, called a ``good man, a
good father,'' was highly respected in the ethnic Albanian
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he spoke, the room would be quiet,'' said a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this misery, virtually every refugee said they
supported the NATO airstrikes as the only way to destroy
Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO ground forces don't come, there will be no Albanians
left alive in Kosovo,'' said Margarita Gjikoli as she rushed to
catch a bus to a refugee camp and waved goodbye to neighbors and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Gjikoli had escaped with Bachiri's brother and comforted him as
the van they were packed into plodded along in a column of hundreds
of cars, tractors, and horse-drawn carriages that lined the roads
to the border Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in this border town of Rogziya was one of confusion,
sorrow, and apprehension. The refugees had made it to Montenegro,
the smallest of the two republics that make up what is left of
Yugoslavia. Here, a Western-leaning government has opposed
Milosevic and said it would accept refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But Montenegro is deeply divided. About half support Milosevic,
and the arrival of tens of thousands of refugees has already begun
to stir resentments among nationalist Serbs. Some lined the roads,
taunting and waving Yugoslav flags at the miles-long column of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos and cold rain at the bus station just on the
Montenegrin side of the border, Father Thomas Pietri, his white
clerical collar ringed with dirt and his black suit soaking wet
after hours walking across the border, said he was a refugee like
everyone else. Although the pro-Milosevic Serbs often fuse their
Orthodox Christian faith with their nationalism, they treated
Albanian Catholics no different than Albanian Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Pietri said a group of six men dressed in camouflage uniforms,
who he believed were Serbian police, came to his church in Pec
Sunday at 5 p.m., after Palm Sunday services. About 100
parishioners had gathered for sanctuary and to attend the services
marking the beginning of Holy Week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the soldiers told the priest that all of them would have
to leave by 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a deadline. Go, or you will be killed,'' the soldier
told the priest and his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' the priest asked defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a military order,'' Pietri was told.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about the use of Christian symbols and traditions in
the campaign of terror by Milosevic's forces, Pietri said, ``Let
God be their judge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
