<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NUHN-LANGDON-COX     03-29 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-LANGDON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ When Trajan Langdon was 14 years old and
had played exactly three games in high school, the Anchorage Daily
News proclaimed he would become the best basketball player in the
history of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, media gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was any pressure or anything. After all, Langdon
only had to top the fabulous Muff Butler to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 14?
</P>
<P>
   I wonder why the paper waited so long.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon has fulfilled the gypsies' prediction. He is a
three-time first-team All-Atlantic Coast Conference player and
acknowledged emotional leader on the nation's No. 1 college team,
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils spent Monday night trying to bedevil Connecticut
and establish themselves as the undisputed Team of the Decade with
three national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Trajan Shaka Langdon was named after Trajan, the Roman emperor
who ended the persecution of Christians, and Shaka, a leader who
organized the Zulu tribe of Africa into a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes being named after your uncle seem a little trite,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Langdon was a natural athlete, but one who always wanted more.
In grade school, when most of his classmates were frolicking in the
snow at recess, Langdon would shoot a basketball alone at an
outdoor rim.
</P>
<P>
   Zero degrees? Twenty below?
</P>
<P>
   Big deal. Gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even feel the ball with the gloves on,'' he said.
``But it was a challenge. It was good practice to dribble the ball
in the snow. You never knew what way it would bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   The glass is half full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coached for 34 years and have never had a player work as
hard as he did,'' said his high school coach, Chuck White.
``Whatever he's gotten, he's earned it 10 times over by working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   What he got was three state high school championships and three
State Player of the Year awards.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, coach Mike Krzyzewski sold him on Duke. Even though
over the previous four years the Blue Devils had won two national
titles and finished runner-up for another, the program was headed
into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Coach K had back surgery and missed most of 1994-95, Langdon's
freshman season, which ended 13-18. Recruiting suffered. Then
Langdon missed his sophomore season with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (freshman) season was very humbling,'' the 6-foot-3 guard
said. ``It was as if Duke ceased being Duke overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon came back in 1996-97 and in the next two seasons, Duke
was 56-13, but the Devils lost to Providence in the second round of
the tournament in '97 and lost to Kentucky in a regional final last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon's mission was to see that doesn't happen again. When
Temple jumped to an 10-5 lead in the East Regional final last week,
Langdon was ready with his reply. He hit a runner in transition;
stopped on the right key and nailed a trey; hit another trey; then
another.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven points in four possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As pure a shooter as I've seen in the game of basketball,''
said Temple coach John Chaney. ``He only needs to look through a
hole in the needle to see the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the rock,'' said teammate Shane Battier. ``Anytime we
get a little frazzled, all we have to do is look at him and see his
calm demeanor and realize that everything is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came here with snowshoes on,'' Krzyzewski joked Sunday.
``We had to get him regulation basketball equipment before he could
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now all he wants is a regulation ring.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
