<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for its special Telecommunications Section
for Tuesday, March 30, on the New York Times wire. For questions,
please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or the business desk at
415-536-5172.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BUNDLING  &LR; _ Americans love to buy things in bulk _ think Costco,
Sam's Club, Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Now phone companies are seizing on this affection for
``one-stop-shopping,'' offering customers a potpourri of products _
local, long-distance and wireless phone service, and sometimes
Internet access and cable TV service _ from a single provider and
itemized on a single bill. By Deborah Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE &LR;  _ Antonio Randolph is kneeling outside a home in Orange
County's Aliso Viejo, splicing a long, thick piece of cable.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, a cable technician for Cox Communications, connects
the end of the spliced wire to a cream-colored plastic box that
he's attached to the side of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a red light on the box begins flashing and
Randolph smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dial tone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a few splices, tugs and screws, Randolph has done something
monumental: He has brought competition to the local phone market by
getting a cable TV line to do double duty as a phone line. By
Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WIRELESS  &LR; _ The explosion of wireless phone companies may be
great for consumers, but it can also be awfully confusing. By
Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEGOTIATE  &LR; _ Robert Marshall used to pay a whopping $800 a
month for long-distance calls. Now, the Walnut Creek businessman
spends just $200 even though he hasn't cut down on his calling. His
secret? Negotiation. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; WEBINFO _ &LR;  With the rapid pace of area code changes across
the country, keeping track of friends and relatives is harder than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some phone companies, realizing that they can capitalize on
people's desire to stay in touch, have started offering national
directory assistance for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of about 95 cents per call, consumers can get one or
two phone listings for any city in the country, without having to
know the area code.
</P>
<P>
   But if paying a buck to find your Uncle Phil seems too steep,
there is a cheaper way _ the Internet. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOLLFREE  &LR; _ Everyone know that making a phone call to an 800
number is free. But not everyone knows that it's easy to get your
own 800 number _ also for free. By Carolyn Said
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAGERS  &LR; _ For everyone who's been buzzed, beeped or paged,
here's a thought _ what if that gadget on your hip or in your purse
could buzz, beep and page right back?
</P>
<P>
   That's only the beginning of what you can do with the new,
two-way pagers just beaming onto the market. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NETPHONES  &LR; _ Want to save money on international telephone
calls? Forget the big carriers, whose rate structures would make a
cryptographer dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   The hippest way to talk to someone overseas is to place a
telephone call using your PC. You can reach phones almost anywhere
in the world by using PC-to-phone technology, and the person at the
receiving end probably won't know the call is coming from a
computer. By David Einstein
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
