<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAGERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Shades of Dick Tracy _ 2-Way Pagers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
For everyone who's been buzzed, beeped or paged, here's a thought _
what if that gadget on your hip or in your purse could buzz, beep
and page right back?
</P>
<P>
   That's only the beginning of what you can do with the new,
two-way pagers just beaming onto the market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sending and receiving pages, these tiny gizmos
can handle e-mail and brief voice messages in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, by loading optional software onto a corporate network,
a company can allow two-way pagers to tap into Windows e-mail,
databases and organizers _ tasks that used to require laptop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   All this from a gizmo small enough to clip onto a belt and that
can run for a week or more on AA batteries.
</P>
<P>
   But before you scrap your venerable one-way pager, consider the
cost of this two-way novelty.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way pagers made by companies like Motorola, Glenayre and
Research in Motion range from $200 to $400, though most vendors now
offer rent-to-own programs that can eliminate this up-front
expense.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way service provided by carriers like SkyTel, PageMart,
PageNet and Bell South Wireless Data can cost from $25 to $100 per
month, depending on the volume of characters you send and receive.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way pagers also can be a challenge to use, given that you
reply by tapping away at a keyboard with buttons the size of those
on a pocket calculator.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, market analysts see two-way technology growing from an
insignificant part of the pager universe _ they represented just a
few hundred thousand units of the 50 million pagers in service last
year _ to 13 percent of the market in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-way paging is reaching a saturation point,'' said Cynthia
Hswe cq  &LR; with Strategis Group of Washington, D.C. ``Two-way is the
only way for the market to grow. But first, the industry has to
change people's perception about what paging is about.''
</P>
<P>
   The exact service varies depending on the pager manufacturer and
the service provider. But in general, all the systems offer the
following incoming services:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Ordinary alphanumeric pages up to 500 characters. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Voice-mail messaging. &LR;  People trying to reach you can phone a
toll-free number and dictate a message to an operator, who types it
in and sends it to the pager as a text message.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Incoming e-mail messages &LR; . These work provided they are sent
to your pager number, for example, 555-5555 &LR; skytel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Guaranteed delivery &LR; . If you are paged on a one-way unit and
your pager is off when the message comes, you miss it. Two-way
pager networks keep sending out the message until your device
acknowledges receipt.
</P>
<P>
   In the outbound mode, two-way pager users can:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Send a return page,  &LR; using the keyboard, to any other
alphanumeric pager.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Send a voice message to any phone.  &LR; In this case, the pager
owner taps out a message and inputs the phone number to be dialed.
The information travels over airwaves to the pager service, which
dials the number. Someone must be there to answer. (Sorry, you
can't leave it on voice mail _ yet.) If your party does answer, the
pager service renders your text message into digitized sound.
So-the-voice-does-sound-robotic, but what can you expect from a new
technology?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Send an e-mail to anyone on the Internet. &LR;  ``I can do this
while sitting in my car,'' said Toni Cupal, marketing manager for
the wireless division of Glenayre in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   John Stupka, chief executive of Mississippi's SkyTel, said a key
feature of two-way paging is that it makes people reachable _ while
giving them control of when and how they respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love e-mail because they can send and respond to
messages when they want,'' Stupka said. ``Two-way paging offers the
same convenience. You can receive a message in the middle of a
meeting and send back a quick, short response without the
distraction of using a cell phone.''
</P>
<P>
   SkyTel began deploying the first two-way paging network in 1995.
But the service really wasn't practical to use until Motorola
started selling its PageWriter 2000 two-way pager in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And it is only this year, with the appearance of several
competing two-way carriers and pager manufacturers, that the
service is starting to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year we've truly had competing services with
nationwide coverage,'' said Gerry Purdy, editor of the Mobile
Letter, which follows the handheld market. ``We'll have to see
whether corporate professionals view two-way pagers as an
alternative to one-way pagers used in conjunction with a cell
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers of two-way pagers hope to distinguish their
products by encouraging third-party software developers to create
add-on services that turn two-way pagers into something like a
cross between a laptop and a personal organizer.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo's Corsoft Corp. is an example. Chief executive Chirag
Patel sells a program that allows a server computer running
Microsoft Exchange to send and receive data to and from two-way
pagers. Corsoft charges $300 to $500 per pager-user. The client
version of the software is downloaded to the pager via the user's
PC _ all the two-way pagers come with recharging cradles that plug
into a PC, so they double as a link that allows the pager to
communicate with the desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   With Corsoft's software running on server and pager, the person
using the two-way pager can access various Microsoft Exchange
functions, including e-mail, the calendar and the contact database.
``The pager becomes a wireless, remote access device to get at
information stored on your networked PC,'' Patel said.
</P>
<P>
   Because two-way pagers _ not to mention such ancillary services
_ are new, there isn't much experience with them yet.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Seybold, who follows the wireless industry from his
office in Boulder Creek (Santa Cruz County), said two-way pagers
have the makings of a killer device _ they're small enough to carry
everywhere yet powerful enough to connect to contacts, calendars
and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Seybold is particularly fond of the BlackBerry two-way pager
from Research in Motion, a company in Ontario, Canada. The
BlackBerry costs $400 to own or $20 a month to rent. Two-way
service, delivered over the BellSouth Wireless Data network, costs
a flat fee of $40 a month _ an advantage over other services that
meter usage and can charge up to $100 per month for unlimited
sending and receiving .
</P>
<P>
   Seybold said using BlackBerry has cut down on his monthly cell
phone bill because he now uses the two-way pager to e-mail quick
replies to colleagues whom he used to call.
</P>
<P>
   Industry pioneer SkyTel has taken note of flat-rate pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry is used to charging by the character,'' Stupka
said. ``Our challenge is reducing our complicated rates to
something friendlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stupka is keeping his sights set on the ideal user:
``It's anyone who spends more than 50 percent of their time away
from their building, desk or cubby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
