<SLUG> BC-KODAK-OUTLOOK-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KODAK ISSUES RARE WARNING ON EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., worried that analysts were ignoring the
informal cautions it had been sounding about its first quarter,
turned up the decibel level Monday. In a radical departure for the
traditionally secretive company, Kodak warned that its
first-quarter earnings would come in below many analysts'
expectations but gave detailed, and much rosier, forecasts for the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who have time and again dumped Kodak's stock on the
slightest whisper of negative news, broke with tradition, too.
Although several analysts lowered their first-quarter estimates
after the announcement, Kodak's shares held firm, rising 37.5
cents, to $65.625.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think the lower first quarter will have any bad
implications for the year,'' said Jack L. Kelly, an analyst with
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., whose view was widely echoed by other
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's announcement, Kodak reaffirmed its prediction that
its 1999 earnings would come in at $4.81 to $5.24 a share, or 10
percent to 20 percent more than last year's $4.37 a share. But it
warned that the improvements would not show up immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Kodak predicted earnings of 73 to 80 cents a share
for the first quarter, below the Wall Street consensus of 82 cents.
However, it said its second-quarter earnings would bounce back to
$1.50 to $1.59 a share. And it predicted earnings of $2.58 to $2.85
a share for the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Although the news sent analysts scrambling to adjust their own
quarterly forecasts, most accepted Kodak's statement that the year
remained promising and retained ``buy'' recommendations on the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their estimates are right, then at 13 times earnings, this
is still a cheap stock,'' said B. Alexander Henderson, an analyst
with Prudential Securities Research.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak does face problems in the first quarter. The strong dollar
and shaky overseas economies continue to take their toll on Kodak's
overseas sales. Kodak remains under intense competitive pressures
in its film business, and it is running into extra costs associated
with its acquisition of Imation's medical business in August.
</P>
<P>
   But Kodak just sold its cash-draining copier business to
Heidelberger Druckmaschinen A.G., shedding a unit that lost $15
million last quarter and will probably lose $10 million in this
one. Kodak's cost-cutting programs are ahead of schedule, and it
has moved some manufacturing operations to low-cost areas like
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely good reason to believe that the second half
will be better than the first,'' Robert Stern, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more heartening to analysts is that Kodak's film sales,
while not soaring, have remained strong, while sales of the
company's digital products are picking up. ``The top line just
doesn't look so daunting anymore,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig, an
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's new openness with its numbers seems to prove yet again
that there is no zealot quite like a recent convert. Until
recently, Kodak's management steadfastly refused to forecast
anything, maintaining variously that it feared lawsuits if they
were wrong and that forecasting was the analysts' job, not theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the answer wasn't a matter of public record, they simply
did not answer the question,'' Ulysses Yannas, an analyst with
Mercer, Bokert, Buckman &AMP; Reid, said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts welcome the changed attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kodak is finally realizing that its stock has been penalized
for the uncertainty that has historically surrounded its
earnings,'' said Michael Ellmann, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first crack in Kodak's secretive armor came on Jan. 14, when
George M.C. Fisher, Kodak's chief executive, forecast earnings and
cost cuts for the full year. Then, on March 3, Kodak's chief
financial officer, Harry L. Kavetas, appeared at an office
equipment industry conference sponsored by Salomon Smith Barney and
told analysts they could expect Kodak to ``strengthen and broaden''
its communications with investors.
</P>
<P>
   Kavetas also said that Kodak's earnings would not improve until
the second half of this year. Several analysts lowered their
earnings estimates then. Indeed, the consensus of the First Call
Corp., which tracks company earnings, had already dropped to 82
cents from 89 cents a month earlier when Kodak issued its earnings
alert Monday. Even though some analysts cut their estimates by more
than a dime, the consensus was down just 4 cents, to 78 cents, on
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the analysts were already within that range,'' said
Thomas O'Keefe, a research associate at First Call.
</P>
<P>
   But many were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was still this misalignment between the internal and
external views of what would happen,'' said Charles S. Smith, a
Kodak spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
