<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEGOTIATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Haggle for Low Phone Rates, Bonuses
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Robert Marshall used to pay a whopping $800 a month for
long-distance calls. Now, the Walnut Creek businessman spends just
$200 even though he hasn't cut down on his calling. His secret?
Negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers don't think about bargaining with their
long-distance company. But for those willing to haggle, the rewards
can be significant: better rates, more frequent-flier miles, free
minutes or cash bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I negotiate everything,'' said Marshall, an international
trade and finance consultant who does a lot of business in
Australia and in his native New Zealand. He used to pay $1.42 a
minute for these calls until he bargained AT&AMP;T down to 75 cents a
minute. To whittle his rate further, he switched carriers twice,
eventually lowering his rate to less than 29 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   He was happy until he heard that his carrier, a dial-around
service called Worldxchange, had an even better deal _ an
introductory rate of just a nickel a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I couldn't get that because I wasn't a new
customer,'' Marshall recalled. But he insisted, so the company
agreed to the nickel rate for 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   No deal, said Marshall. He wanted 90 days _ and he got it.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers find it easier to switch than fight. But often,
you can get the best deal by negotiating with your current carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how much you're worth to them and how much it will
cost to get you back, so they'll probably be the most responsive,''
said Sam Simon, chairman of the Telecommunications Research and
Action Center, a Washington consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said phone companies' rate plans rarely are negotiable.
Where you'll have the most wiggle room are promotions and benefits
such as frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies aren't likely to charge you 8 cents a minute
when they're charging everyone else 9 cents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What they may do is allow you to participate in a special
promotion, but it's up to you to do the research.
</P>
<P>
   Find out what promotions are available and ask for them, Simon
advised. Ask the company to extend a promotional rate for an extra
six months or to bump up the number of frequent-flier miles you're
getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they give rewards, you can ask for extras. You can ask that
fees be waived for a couple months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The TRAC founder recently took his own advice. When he switched
long-distance companies, he asked his new carrier to pay the $5
switch fee. The company offered something better: 250 free minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to ask, `What other promotions do you have that I'd
qualify for? What else do you have?''' Simon suggested.
</P>
<P>
   But he also cautions that companies won't negotiate with
everyone. Don't expect much if you don't spend a lot on
long-distance calls. The more you spend, the more likely carriers
are to go out of their way to get or keep you as a customer.
</P>
<P>
   Suzan and Stewart Cochrane, a San Mateo couple spending $60 to
$80 a month on long-distance, were able to bargain for a better
deal after AT&AMP;T raised rates for calls to England. The Cochranes
call relatives there two or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   The couple say they found out about the rate increase, from 12
cents to 15 cents a minute, when they received an unusually large
bill. Surprised, they called AT&AMP;T, which told them the rate change
had been published in the newspapers and that there wasn't anything
the company could do about it. The Cochranes switched to MCI, which
had offered them a 12-cent rate.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, AT&AMP;T called and asked why they'd switched.
They explained _ and suddenly AT&AMP;T was able to restore their
12-cent rate. To sweeten the deal, the company tossed in a $100
check. AT&AMP;T has since lowered rates again, to 10 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't normally volunteer anything,'' said Suzan Cochrane.
``You just have to be bold enough to ask.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
To help evaluate phone services, TRAC publishes comparison reports
of top carriers. To get a residential-service report, send $5 and
an envelope with 55 cents in postage to TRAC, P.O. Box 27279,
Washington, D.C. 20005. Small-business reports are $7. For more
information on TRAC, see  &LR; www.trac.org &LR; . &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
