<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIRELESS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A Flat-Out Simpler Approach to Wireless Phone Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The explosion of wireless phone companies may be great for
consumers, but it can also be awfully confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the more than 59 wireless phone plans now available in
the Bay Area. There are plans for digital service and analog
service, with contracts and without contracts, with peak talk times
and off-peak talk times, with roaming fees or activation fees and a
sliding scale of per-minute rates. And that doesn't even take into
account choosing a phone.
</P>
<P>
   If it makes you dizzy, take heart: There may be a simpler way.
</P>
<P>
   Many cellular phone companies, such as AT&AMP;T Wireless, Sprint PCS
and GTE Wireless, now offer customers one rate for all calls,
regardless of where they're calling to and from. There are no
long-distance charges, and talking on your phone while traveling in
another city doesn't cost any extra.
</P>
<P>
   The trend, known as flat-rate pricing, is giving consumers a
cheaper way to make wireless phone calls and is helping carriers
attract more customers.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say flat-rate pricing has evolved because
wireless companies finally are responding to consumers, who have
long complained about confusing plans, high per-minute rates and
exorbitant roaming fees for calls made while on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of those costly fees has become the battle cry of
wireless carriers, who are struggling to convince customers that
cell phones are an affordable alternative to traditional
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a carrier has a nationwide network, it must pay other
wireless carriers hefty fees to handle calls outside its geographic
area so that customers can use their phones across the country. The
fees, known as roaming charges, are then passed on to wireless
customers at rates that can reach 60 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Those fees have stopped many customers from using their phones
for more than local or emergency calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers hate roaming charges,'' said Jeff Goldberg, editor
of WirelessDimension.com, a Web site that tracks cell phone plans
and helps consumers choose the best one. ``They don't understand
them, and the rates are fairly high.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry analysts expect roaming fees to soon go the way of
the rotary-dial phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a year or two, you won't be able to find roaming anymore,
and good riddance to it,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The death of roaming fees has come about largely because of
AT&AMP;T, which was the first company to announce a single rate for its
wireless service. The Digital One Rate plan, which is not available
in the Bay Area, has been siphoning off customers from Bell
Atlantic and other regional wireless carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although other companies made no roaming an option, last May
was the first time a carrier made this a standard feature,''
Goldberg said. ``It's been an astounding success for AT&AMP;T, and
other carriers almost had no choice but to follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is flat-rate pricing, which is available in the Bay
Area from GTE Wireless, Nextel, Sprint PCS and, on a limited basis,
through Cellular One, a joint partnership between AT&AMP;T and
AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   For $30 to $160 a month, customers get a bucket of minutes they
can use anytime and anywhere. There is no distinction between local
and long-distance calls, with customers paying the same amount to
make a call at home in San Francisco and while on vacation in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Although customers are paying a flat rate, the cost of the calls
usually boils down to between 10 cents per minute and 25 cents per
minute, depending on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   GTE Wireless, for example, offers nationwide rates ranging from
10 cents to 15 cents per minute. The plans cost between $95 per
month for 650 minutes of air-time to $155 per month for 1,500
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has a flat-rate plan that applies only to
states west of the Mississippi. Rates range from $40 for 100
minutes to $140 for 1,550 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One offers flat-rate plans ranging from $50 for 300
minutes to $110 for 1,000 minutes, for calls made within
California. Depending on the plan, the cost per minute ranges from
11 cents to 17 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a look at our customers and found that the majority of
people who roam, roam within California,'' said Erin Eggleton, a
spokeswoman for Cellular One. ``We wanted to take this step first
and provide customers with a flat rate in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Cellular One does not have a nationwide network, it has
no immediate plans to do away with roaming fees outside California,
Eggleton said, but is continuing to look at partnerships with other
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   With Sprint PCS' Free and Clear Plan, customers pay about 10
cents per minute for calls nationwide. The plans cost between $70
and $150 for 600 to 1,500 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With flat-rate pricing, you get better value and a plan that's
simple to understand,'' said Chip Graves, area vice president for
Sprint PCS. ``You know what your phone bill is going to be in
advance, and you never get charged for long-distance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what attracted customers like Courtney Chan, who said he
wanted to know in advance what his monthly cell phone bill would
be. He also wanted to make long-distance calls without being
charged exorbitant per-minute rates.
</P>
<P>
   He signed up with Sprint PCS, and for $30 a month, Chan can make
120 minutes of calls, anytime and anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free long-distance is great; it's cheaper than my house
phone, so it's a great option,'' said Chan of San Francisco. ``I
use the phone a lot more than I did before. Calls that I wouldn't
have made before I make now.''
</P>
<P>
   But flat-rate pricing is not for everybody. While heavy users
and frequent travelers will benefit from these plans, those who use
their cell phones minimally and only at home actually could wind up
paying more for a flat-rate plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't roam, these national plans don't make a lot of
sense,'' Goldberg said. ``If you use the phone a lot during the
evening and on weekends, these plans are something you'd want to
look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the per-minute rates might seem cheap, consumer experts
warn that unless people use all the included minutes, they can wind
up paying a lot more than they would with a traditional plan.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if a customer pays $95 for 650 minutes but uses
only 450 minutes per month, that person actually winds up paying 21
cents per minute, instead of 15 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Because the average wireless consumer uses about 200 minutes per
month, the plans might not be best for the majority of people.
</P>
<P>
   To find out which plan may suit them, consumers can check out
 &LR; www.wirelessdimension.com.  &LR; The Web site, which is free, asks a
series of questions about customer preference and then recommends a
list of plans available in that customer's hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
