<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUNDLING-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUNDLING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Phone Firms _ One-Stop Shops
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Americans love to buy things in bulk _ think Costco, Sam's Club,
Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Now phone companies are seizing on this affection for
``one-stop-shopping,'' offering customers a potpourri of products _
local, long-distance and wireless phone service, and sometimes
Internet access and cable TV service _ from a single provider and
itemized on a single bill.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies say they can offer customers substantial
discounts on packages of telecom services, which offer come with a
single per-minute rate for all calls.
</P>
<P>
   The trend, known as ``bundling,'' is in its early stages, but
industry watchers expect it to explode.
</P>
<P>
   But while telecom companies say bundling will help simplify our
lives, there are potential drawbacks. Customers may have a harder
time comparing prices _ for example, someone who makes a lot of
calls to Canada but doesn't use a wireless phone might have a hard
time figuring out which package offers the best long-distance
price. And bundling actually could raise costs for customers who
don't embrace it, as companies increase charges for things such as
calling-card calls, long-distance and other services in an attempt
to push people toward bundles.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, phone companies are plugging along with the idea
that the more services they offer, the better, and industry
watchers say we better get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the new playing field,'' says Jeffrey Kagan, a
telecommunications analyst in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AT&AMP;T Corp. became one of the first nationwide
carriers to offer a bundled package of communications products for
a flat rate. With the Personal Network plan, customers pay $29.99
per month, plus 10 cents per minute, for all local, long-distance,
wireless and calling card calls, including those to Canada, the
United Kingdom and parts of Mexico. The plan also includes a
personal 800 number that rings at a customer's home phone. For
another $15 per month, customers can get their Internet service
through AT&AMP;T's WorldNet as well. Down the road, cable TV also will
be a part of the package for an additional fee.
</P>
<P>
   The plan offers a savings off what customers would pay if they
purchased all those services separately from AT&AMP;T. For instance,
customers who buy services a la carte pay a $4.95 flat fee in order
to get that 10-cents-per-minute rate, but that doesn't include
calls to Canada, the United Kingdom or Mexico, which cost more. And
without the Personal Network plan, calling-card calls are 25 cents
per minute and Internet service is an additional $19.90.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The full plan is not available in the Bay Area because AT&AMP;T
does not have its own branded wireless product here. But customers
here can pay $10 a month and get 10 cents a minute on all local and
long-distance calls from their home phone, including those to
Canada, Mexico and the United Kingdom. For an additional $15, Bay
Area customers can add online service.
</P>
<P>
   And AT&AMP;T's announcement is just a foreshadowing of what's to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom are developing
their own bundled packages that soon will allow local consumers to
get almost every telecom product conceivable from a single
provider.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A New Jersey company called RCN Corp. is now laying fiber
optic cable around the Bay Area so that it can deliver a bundle of
local phone, long-distance, cable and Internet services to San
Francisco residents by the end of the year. And regional phone
companies, such as Pacific Bell, also plan to offer a package of
services including local, Internet, wireless and, eventually,
long-distance to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of one-stop telecom shopping isn't new _ MCI tried it
several years ago with its MCI One plan, which combined
long-distance and other services on a single bill. But MCI was a
little ahead of the curve, reselling services to a public that
wasn't ready to embrace bundles, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with so many providers vying for attention and with such
complicated pricing schemes, customers are looking for a simpler
and cheaper way to get their phone, cable and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere between 20 percent and 30 percent of customers want
the convenience of a single bill and a single point of contact,''
says Vince Tobkin, director of technology and telecommunications at
Bain &AMP; Co., a research firm in San Francisco. &UR;  &LR; ``Customers will buy
a bundle of services for that convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have caught on and realized that customers who buy
a multitude of services from a single company are less likely to
leave that provider on a whim because they have a financial
incentive to stay.
</P>
<P>
   With plans like AT&AMP;T's Personal Network, customers are forced to
stick with the carrier for a multitude of services to get the best
rates. For example, the 10-cent rate only applies to customers who
get both their long-distance and wireless service from AT&AMP;T. That
makes it harder to leave when MCI comes dangling a carrot.
</P>
<P>
   And RCN, which already operates in Boston, New York and
Washington, D.C., offers customers discounts when they use more
than one RCN service. Customers who get $30-per-month cable service
from RCN get $3 off their bill if they add phone service and even
more of a discount with Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get a customer using more than one of your
services, the chances of them leaving your company drops
dramatically,'' Kagan said. ``Companies make more money and get
`sticky' customer loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   And the competition is getting fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 Telecommunications Act, which allowed cable,
local and long-distance companies to get into one another's
business, nearly a dozen mega-mergers have occurred in the
industry, spawning giant corporations capable of offering a wider
variety of services than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is that during the next 10 years, a handful
of giant, global telecom providers will emerge, leaving the smaller
companies in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of all of these mergers is to enable companies to
provide the broadest array of telecom services through any
medium,'' said industry consultant Herschel Shosteck. ``The winners
are going to be the companies that provide a full array of bundled
services, and in order to do that, they are going to have to be in
every dimension of telecom.''
</P>
<P>
   By joining forces, telecom companies are able to trim fat from
their combined operations and save money by itemizing every service
on a single bill. Companies are expected to pass those savings
along to consumers, giving customers a cheaper, easier way to get
telecom services.
</P>
<P>
   While prices probably will go down, bundling will make it harder
for customers to do comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The migration to bundled services will happen largely because
companies will raise prices on a la carte services. Just this
month, AT&AMP;T announced a series of price increases on individual
services, such as calling-card calls. Although the company denies
that the increases have anything to do with the Personal Network
plan, analysts disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``What AT&AMP;T is basically saying, and absolutely others will
follow, is `We are going to pass on economies of scale to
customers, but we are going to rationalize our pricing by
convincing customers to get services from us and only us,'''
Shosteck said. ``There are going to be increases in the prices for
separate services to encourage consumers to move to bundled
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer groups have expressed fears that this is unfair
and will force customers to buy services they don't want. The
Consumers Union in Washington, D.C., recently voiced concern that
bundling would recreate giant monopolies. But the companies say
customers will benefit from bundling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers like packaging or bundling for three reasons: They
like to buy stuff that works together ... they like it if it
enables them to get discounts, and they like it if the company is
easy to do business with,'' said Steve Dimmitt, Pacific Bell vice
president of consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Dimmitt said Pac Bell already is experimenting with bundling,
offering customers discounts when they sign up for additional local
phone features, such as voice mail, Caller ID and call waiting. And
the company currently puts local phone and Internet service on the
same bill.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of this year _ assuming Pac Bell gets into
long-distance _ Dimmitt said the company plans to offer a bundled
package of local, long-distance, wireless and Internet service at a
discounted price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick here is to be flexible enough to give consumers
everything they want,'' Dimmitt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
