<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Phone calls over cable TV lines are a cheaper alternative
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Antonio Randolph is kneeling outside a home in Orange County's
Aliso Viejo, splicing a long, thick piece of cable.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, a cable technician for Cox Communications, connects
the end of the spliced wire to a cream-colored plastic box that
he's attached to the side of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a red light on the box begins flashing and
Randolph smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dial tone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a few splices, tugs and screws, Randolph has done something
monumental: He has brought competition to the local phone market by
getting a cable TV line to do double duty as a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in Aliso Viejo and neighboring parts of Orange County,
Randolph and his fellow Cox Communications technicians are blurring
the line between cable TV and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Customers in these Southern California communities are among the
first in the nation to get their dial tone over cable TV
lines. &UR;  &LR; The same wires that bring them HBO and CNN now allow them
to call relatives and friends across the world.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is known as cable telephony, and it soon will be
coming to a channel near you.
</P>
<P>
   A True Alternative
</P>
<P>
   During the next year, AT&AMP;T Corp. will work with
Tele-Communications Inc. to test and deliver cable telephony in the
Bay Area. When it's up and running, it will be one of the first
true alternatives to Pacific Bell for local phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the idea of competition is attracting customers in Cox
territory. With lower monthly prices for phone lines &UR;  &LR; and with
cheap local and long-distance rates, Cox already has attracted
33,000 cable telephony customers _ about 15 percent of the
customers in the 17 Orange County communities where it offers cable
service.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the product is evident to anyone who walks
into the Cox office in Aliso Viejo. Technicians are scrambling
around, picking up equipment and checking in with supervisors
before heading out to install telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really popular,'' said Randolph, who does between
four and five installations a day. ``Most people say they're happy
to have a choice. And they know Cox is a good company with good
customer service, so they're eager to get service from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, TCI and other cable TV firms can offer cable telephony as a
result of the 1996 Telecommunications Act, which lifted
restrictions and allowed cable and telephone companies to dip into
each others' business. Since the law was passed, the companies have
spent billions of dollars to upgrade their cable lines and develop
technology to deliver local and long-distance phone service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which recently merged with TCI, doesn't have a firm start
date for its cable telephone service, but officials say they'll
spend 1999 upgrading and testing the system in 10 cities across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   One of those trials is going on in Fremont, where a handful of
TCI employees quietly are testing the phone service over the
company's cable TV lines.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry DiFrancisco, AT&AMP;T's executive vice president of wireline
telephony, said the company is hesitant to name a start date
because AT&AMP;T wants to make sure the product is flawless before
offering it to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge is how do we build the infrastructure and
bring tens of millions of customers onto the network,'' he said.
``We don't want to introduce it and say we can only accommodate
several hundred customers.''
</P>
<P>
   And it takes time before the system is ready to go. Cox, which
began offering phone service about a year and a half ago, still is
not able to offer it to all customers. Officials say they are
rolling it out slowly as they upgrade the system, construct the
proper infrastructure and hire technicians to install the service.
</P>
<P>
   Each installation can take anywhere from 45 minutes to two
hours, meaning technicians can do only a few per day.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; How It Works
</P>
<P>
   To make cable telephony work, cable companies must install new
equipment at their main offices and at the customer's house.
</P>
<P>
   With Cox's product, the company has installed voice processors
in its head-end facility _ the building where all the signals are
processed. Those processors convert the telephone and voice signal
sent over the cable lines to a radio frequency that can be
transmitted over a voice network.
</P>
<P>
   At the customer's house, technicians such as Randolph must
install new coaxial cable, which is capable of sending and
receiving data, along with a voice port, which powers the telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   The cream-colored box, which is known as a network interface
unit, is what enables customers to talk over their cable lines. It
converts the phone call from a radio frequency, which is what cable
TV uses, to a telephone signal.
</P>
<P>
   The NIU is then attached to the home's inside wiring, allowing
customers to use their existing telephones and wall jacks for cable
telephone service. Cable telephony works just like regular phone
service; the only difference is that instead of telephone wires
carrying the call, underground cables are routing it through.
</P>
<P>
   So far, customers seem to like the service, especially the
price. AT&AMP;T hasn't disclosed its pricing for TCI's service, but
Cox's rates are significantly less than Pac Bell's.
</P>
<P>
   A single phone line costs $10 a month, and additional lines are
$5 per month. Pac Bell charges $11.25 per month for every phone
line.
</P>
<P>
   Cox also offers cheap rates for local toll and long-distance
calls. Within California, toll calls are 5 cents per minute and
long-distance calls are 10 cents per minute. Customers are not
required to use Cox as their long-distance provider and can choose
other carriers like AT&AMP;T or MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaper Service Deal
</P>
<P>
   Like TCI, Cox also offers the AtHome cable-modem service, which
allows people to access the Internet over their cable lines at fast
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to provide all these products means customers can get
their local, long-distance, cable TV and Internet service from a
single company and for a cheaper price.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to provide local phone service and give consumers
``one-stop shopping'' is what's driving AT&AMP;T to offer telephony via
TCI's lines. Companies want to be able to capture and keep as many
customers as they can, something that's made easier when consumers
are getting all their services from one provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical part of AT&AMP;T's strategy for the future,''
DiFrancisco said. ``It's clear that the world is changing ... and
this is AT&AMP;T's way of blending together any service _ local,
long-distance, video, entertainment and Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancisco said the company hopes to attract 20 to 30 percent
of local phone customers in the Bay Area to its cable telephony
product. In addition to TCI, AT&AMP;T also has signed a deal with Time
Warner cable, which offers service in parts of Southern California
and on the East Coast, and is working on other agreements,
DiFrancisco said.
</P>
<P>
   Courting Customers
</P>
<P>
   But whether customers will bite remains to be seen. Although the
Cox rollout is viewed by many as a success, there still are a lot
of customers who have not and will not make the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge power of incumbency, and consumer inertia is a
very powerful tool,'' said Bruce Leichtman, director of media and
entertainment strategies for the Yankee Group, a Boston research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   While some people already have made the switch, they are the
``low-hanging fruit,'' Leichtman said _ the customers who were
ready to jump to almost any competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the market might not be as easily swayed, Leichtman
said, particularly because it will take a long time before cable
telephony is widely available.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you have to build it and make it available. The next
part of it is, once it is built, will customers (adopt) it? That
remains to be seen,'' he said. ``To the consumer, it's not about
what the provider can provide, it's about what the customer wants.
It's going to be a challenge, but the AT&AMP;T name on the phone will
help a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some customers, like Remus Rafols of Aliso Viejo, already are
convinced of cable telephony's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   As Randolph installed a phone line in Rafols' bedroom, Rafols
smiled as he recounted what the incumbent provider told him about
getting a phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pac Bell told me I couldn't get a third line in the house
without permission from the residential association,'' said Rafols,
who shares the house with seven other people. ``So the owner told
me to go to Cox. They said it was no problem and it's even cheaper.
I like the idea of getting my phone from Cox because they are a
good cable company.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials say they hope to seize on some of that same
frustration in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``With AT&AMP;T's brand image, we feel we'll have an attractive
product to offer,'' DiFrancisco said. ``Everybody wants a choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
