<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOLLFREE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOLLFREE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Toll-Free Numbers Make It Easy to Stay in Touch
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carolyn Said &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everyone know that making a phone call to an 800 number is free.
But not everyone knows that it's easy to get your own 800 number _
also for free.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance companies now routinely offer personal 800 numbers
_ toll-free numbers that ring at a regular home phone _ to their
residential customers with no extra monthly fees. In fact, one
long-distance firm, MCI WorldCom, hands out toll-free numbers to
each and every one of its residential customers _ about 20 percent
of the 100 million U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   For people who want family and friends to be able to reach them
easily, or who are on the road a lot, a personal 800 number is
cheap and convenient. The toll-free numbers can be called from
anywhere in the United States. The customer's only cost is the
per-minute rate for incoming calls _ at most about 15 cents to 35
cents a minute. Often, customers pay just their regular
long-distance rate, which can be as low as 10 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   For parents of college kids, a personal 800 number provides a
direct link with the dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds an extra element of control,'' said Charlie Sutlive, a
spokesman for MCI WorldCom. ``If a child goes off to college with a
calling card, they can use it to call anyone. If you give them your
personal 800 number, you know they can only use it to call you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefani Rose, a political science major at St. Mary's College in
Moraga, said her parents' toll-free number means she can call home
frequently, even if she just has a quick question to ask.
</P>
<P>
   The toll-free number proved invaluable a couple of weeks ago,
when Stefani and some friends went skiing at Sugar Bowl and one of
them hit a tree. During the lengthy wait in the Truckee emergency
room, none of the students had any change or a phone card to make
calls. Rather than hassling with calling collect (which is possible
only when someone is home on the other end), Rose called her family
in Oregon on their 800 number.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the numbers help elderly relatives stay in touch.
``You can give the number to your grandparents or parents who may
be on a fixed income so they don't have to worry about spending
their money to call you,'' said telecom analyst Jeffrey Kagan.
``It's cheaper than calling collect.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefani's father, Robert Rose, an appraiser in Medford, Ore.,
said: ``Having an 800 number is like a little gift for my mother
and daughter to help them keep in touch without having to pay for
the call.''
</P>
<P>
   People who travel a lot find that having a personal 800 number
can cut down on exorbitant hotel phone bills. ``You can't beat it
for calling home from the road,'' said Kagan. ``Calling
long-distance from your hotel room is the biggest rip-off there
is.'' Most hotels charge a flat $1 rate for calls to toll-free
numbers but tack on 30 percent or higher surcharges for
long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   A personal toll-free number can be more secure than a calling
card number that you have to punch in at a public location. ``If
someone is shoulder-surfing you at an airport phone booth, they
won't be able to steal the number and make long-distance calls with
it _ the worst they can do is use it to call your house,'' said
Fred Voit, senior analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Personal 800 numbers aren't suitable for businesses: Usually,
you don't get to pick your number, so there's no clever mnemonic
like CALLMOI to help customers remember it. Because the pool of 800
numbers is drying up fast, companies like AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom
actually assign you an 800 (or 888, 877 or other toll-free prefix)
number along with a unique four-digit PIN that identifies you. That
way, they can put 9,999 customers on a single 800 number. (Sprint,
however, gives its residential customers a toll-free number that
works without a PIN.)
</P>
<P>
   A business is better off paying a little extra for a ``regular''
toll-free number that doesn't require punching in an extra four
digits.
</P>
<P>
   Toll-free numbers have come a long way since their introduction
in 1967. They started as special, dedicated lines that corporations
paid big bucks to install and use. In the late '80s, toll-free
numbers became available through regular phone lines, leading to an
explosion in use by small and medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies started offering personal 800 numbers to
residential customers several years ago but usually charged an
installation fee, a monthly fee and slightly higher per-minute
rates.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, phone companies dropped the set-up and monthly
fees, aligned the per-minute rates with their regular rates and
made personal 800 numbers an integral part of their service
packages.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which has 60 percent of the market, offers personal 800
numbers through several plans, including its new Personal Network
plan, a bundle of local, long-distance, wireless and toll-free
service, all for 10 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, many customers don't realize that they can easily
get their own toll-free number through their long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   A survey in October by the Yankee Group found that 13.5 percent
of MCI customers knew they had an 800 number _ even though the
figure should have been 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say awareness and use should soar as cost-savvy
customers are learning to shop around and analyze phone service
features.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is more ready for it today than ever,'' Kagan said.
`Customers are used to 10-10-321 and other (dial-around services).
Marketing of telephone services has become hot. All of a sudden,
toll-free service is positioned to take its place among marketing
successes like dial-around.''
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Rose put it: ``When you leave a message for someone to
call you back, if it's your dime, they'll call you back a lot
quicker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
