<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8874 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETPHONE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-29 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETPHONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Using Your Computer to Make Phone Calls
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Want to save money on international telephone calls? Forget the big
carriers, whose rate structures would make a cryptographer dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   The hippest way to talk to someone overseas is to place a
telephone call using your PC. You can reach phones almost anywhere
in the world by using PC-to-phone technology, and the person at the
receiving end probably won't know the call is coming from a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, PC-generated calls to far-off places are less
expensive than regular phone calls. For 10 cents a minute, you can
talk to someone in Western Europe. Japan can be called for less
than 20 cents a minute. And you can make that hotel reservation in
Fiji for under $1 a minute.
</P>
<P>
   You also can place calls to phones within the United States
using your computer, but that's not a money-saving proposition.
Daytime PC-to-phone calls cost about 15 cents a minute whether the
call is local or long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   About the only reason to place a domestic call from your PC is
if you want to talk to a customer representative at an Internet
shopping site. Increasingly, online retailers are providing links
that let you have a conversation with a live person.
</P>
<P>
   To place a PC-to-phone call, you need a software program known
as a dialer, a microphone to talk into and a PC speaker for hearing
the person on the other end of the line. (The most convenient
solution is a headset with a built-in microphone.)
</P>
<P>
   You also need an account with a company that can take calls from
your PC and connect them to a phone. Several companies both provide
the necessary software (for free) and handle your calls for you.
Two of the most popular are Net2Phone  &LR; (www.net2phone.com)  &LR; and
Delta Three &LR;  (www.deltathree.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Here's how a PC-to-phone call works:
</P>
<P>
   _When you place a call, your speech is digitized and compressed,
then transported over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _When the digitized signal nears its destination, a special
``gateway'' operated by the company handling the call changes it so
that it can be recognized by an ordinary phone. The call is then
completed through local phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   _When the person on the phone talks, the process of converting
the signal is reversed, sending it back to your PC.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having to go through all that, voices come through loud
and clear. With most PC-to-phone systems, the sound quality is just
as good as a regular phone call.
</P>
<P>
   There is one catch, however. If your Internet connection isn't
fast enough, there can be delays in the signal that will make you
think you're talking to somebody on the moon. A 56K modem is barely
adequate for PC-to-voice, and to make it really shine, you need a
high-speed connection using a cable modem, DSL or a T1 line.
</P>
<P>
   PC-to-phone technology isn't the first stab at using the
Internet as a telephone system. For several years, it's been
possible to conduct voice conversations between two PCs. That
hasn't really caught fire, however, despite the fact that you can
talk to anyone in the world in this way with no long-distance
charges whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   PC-to-PC phoning, it turns out, has some pretty significant
drawbacks. It's terribly inconvenient because both the caller and
the person receiving the call must have the same telephony software
installed on their computers. What's more, the person getting the
call must be online and ready to accept it when it comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that there is no way for anyone to make money
on PC-to-PC calls, which transmit your voice over the Internet just
as if it were e-mail. Without a profit motive, there has been no
rush to standardize PC-to-PC software and make it really universal.
</P>
<P>
   PC-to-phone calls, by comparison, represent a promising source
of revenue for companies that route the calls between the Internet
and the telephone system.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, during the next few years, all the major long-distance
carriers are expected to shift large segments of their business
from standard telephone lines to the main pipelines that run the
Internet. When that happens, international phone calls may become
so cheap that the PC-to-phone system will offer no cost advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
