<SLUG> BC-MARKET-RECORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW TOPS 10,000 MARK   AND STAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market rose above the 10,000-point
milestone Monday and stayed there, finally breaking a barrier that
has come to symbolize a remarkable period of prosperity for the
country.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its history, the Dow Jones industrial
average finished the day above 10,000, closing at 10,006.78, up
184.54 points, after weeks of flirting with the mark. Even as NATO
bombs fell on Yugoslavia, investors _ energized by merger talks
between BP Amoco PLC and Atlantic Richfield Co., which drove up oil
company shares, and by huge gains in blue-chip technology stocks _
drove the market upward.
</P>
<P>
   While the day's event represented only a 1.9 percent increase in
the Dow, the index has risen more than 7,000 points this decade. On
April 17, 1991, when the Dow broke 3000 for the first time, the
economy began what would become the longest-running peacetime
expansion in US history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fantasy land for investors,'' said Ned Riley, chief
investment officer for BankBoston Corp. The average yearly return
in the 1990s, about 20 percent, is double the yearly average return
over the past 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cautioned the Dow could fall back below 10,000 Tuesday.
But Monday's trading was big news on Wall Street, which lately has
marked time _ and profits _ in increments of 1,000 points.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the greater significance of the market's new high,
however, may be what it portends for the future, investment experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10,000 level ``is a deceptive number,'' said Thomas O'Neill,
chief investment officer of Fleet Financial Group. Though the index
overall is at a new high, the majority of stocks have sunk in
recent months. Many money managers are concerned that the market
may not continue at its present rate of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Laubscher, a veteran market analyst who works at Tucker
Anthony Inc. in New York, said the soaring Dow masks weakness in
most stocks. That's because money managers, when in doubt, invest
in the large and profitable firms that make up the index like
pharmaceutical giant Merck &AMP; Co., General Electric Co. and Walt
Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   If the market rally doesn't broaden to include other stocks,
Fleet's O'Neill said, ``it won't be a healthy long-term condition''
that would suggest strong future growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's rally went well beyond the Dow. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index, a broader market indicator, had a stronger day,
gaining 2.13 percent, compared with the Dow's 1.88 percent rise.
The S&AMP;P 500 added 27.37 points, closing at 1310.17.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq rose even more, gaining 3.05
percent, or 73.67 points, to 2492.84.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned Dow, which has few technology stocks, is no
longer a reliable gauge of the market, analysts said. For example,
Microsoft Corp., which trades on the Nasdaq but is the nation's
most successful computer company, is not among the 30 stocks that
make up the index.
</P>
<P>
   The true start of the current bull market can be traced back to
1982 when a market rally was sparked by falling interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   After a bear market for much of the 1970s, the Dow climbed past
1000 for the first time on Nov. 14, 1972, and crashed in October
1987. But, the Dow recovered and soared, breaking through 3000 in
1991; 4000 and 5000 in 1995; 6000 in 1996; 7000 and 8000 in 1997,
breaking through 9000 on April 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered as the Dow reached its milestone, after two
weeks of watching it rise above 10,000 briefly, only to dip below
it. Monday's rally came on the heels of a 169.5-point rise Thursday
and a small decline Friday. The day's activity brought more ups and
downs: The market rose above 10,000 around 2:30 p.m., fell below it
for a time and broke through to trade above it during the final
hour before trading halted at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing stocks on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners by
1,829 to 1,127.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last, we made it _ a new record,'' said Marshall Acuff,
stock strategist for Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``We
certainly have been working on it. It took a while in coming, but
we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The gains were the result of a confluence of positive factors.
News that BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield were in merger talks
signaled that other deals could follow in the struggling oil
industry, driving up the market.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Richfield stock rose 8 11/16, closing at 74 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also had a good day, continuing recent strong
performance. IBM gained 5 3/16, closing at 177 9/16, and Sun
Microsystems rose 8, to 124 1/2. Intel rose 4 3/4, closing at 121
7/16.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the psychological factor of a 10,000 target.
``Ten thousand has acted as kind of a magnet, bringing stocks up to
that level,'' said Bill Morton, chief executive of the Boston Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, the Dow's high closing price had little significance.
The higher the market gets, the less numeric import can be
attributed to each increase of 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal because people think it's a big deal,'' said
Samuel Hayes, a finance professor at Harvard Business School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
