<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS &LR;      03-29 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ROLE GROWS   WITH PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just a week ago, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov ordered his Washington-bound plane turned around after he
learned that NATO intended to bomb Yugoslavia despite Moscow's
objections.
</P>
<P>
   The midflight U-turn seemed to sum up how little Russia's
opinion meant when NATO had serious business to do. But after a
week of massive NATO bombardments, Serb defiance, and harsh
criticism from Moscow, Russia is suddenly relevant again.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the US-led alliance will be ignoring Primakov when the
Russian premier, bolstered by the promise of a new loan from the
International Monetary Fund and the backing of NATO members France
and Italy, leaves Tuesday for urgent peace talks in Belgrade with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's mission could produce a breakthrough in the Kosovo
crisis _ or deal the Clinton administration a devastating blow by
exploiting cracks that have appeared in the alliance. That depends
on whether Primakov can get Milosevic to sign a peace agreement
ending the Serb offensive and reported atrocities against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, and under what conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his mission is . . . very welcome by Clinton
officials, but they are also very nervous,'' said Michael McFaul,
of the Washington-based Carnegie Endowment for Peace. ``A real
concern for the Clinton administration is that Primakov is in the
driver's seat, and that allows him to draft his own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia was part of the six-nation Contact Group that mediated
between the Serbs and Kosovo's ethnic Albanians before the the
bombings began, and Russia encouraged Yugoslavia to sign an
agreement that would give Kosovo autonomy. But both Russia and
Yugoslavia, traditional allies who share Orthodox Christian
religion and a Slavic ethnic identity, oppose stationing NATO
troops in Kosovo to implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One concern for US officials is that Primakov might make a deal
with Milosevic that substitutes European monitors for NATO troops,
something France and Italy, under domestic pressure to end the
airstrikes, might be willing to approve.
</P>
<P>
   That would put the Clinton administration ``in an awkward
position,'' McFaul said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russia has issued harsh daily criticism of NATO's
airstrikes, it has made mostly symbolic moves, such as suspending
contact with NATO, while avoiding any action that could
significantly affect relations with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Russian analysts credit this tactic to Primakov, the wily former
intelligence chief, who has slowly consolidated power since his
surprise appointment to prime minister in September. Primakov's
Cold War rhetoric, accompanied by protests across the political
spectrum, in the media, and in the street, has raised the question
of whether the West underestimated Russia's reaction to the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Primakov's anti-Western posture has left the
Russians in a position to travel to Belgrade as a friend while
leaving Moscow the option of trying to pressure Milosevic to
approve a political solution NATO would find acceptable. Such a
solution would be a major diplomatic coup for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has intervened this way in the past, most successfuly
early last year when, as Russia's foreign minister, he extracted
last-minute concessions on arms inspection from Saddam Hussein to
halt planned US airstrikes against Iraq. Both Primakov and US
leaders took credit for the last-minute breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, who will accompany
Primakov along with Russia's defense, intelligence, and foreign
policy chiefs, sought to show that Tuesday's trip to Belgrade was a
purely Russian initiative. He said Moscow had not asked NATO to
halt its daily airstrikes on the Serb capital during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going there not to save face for anyone, but to stop
aggression,'' Ivanov said in a news conference. Privately, Russian
officials say they are confident that a positive outcome could
indeed save face for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's trip appeared likely to further upstage President
Boris N. Yeltsin, who was planning to use his annual address to
parliament as a forum to denounce NATO's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin had sent a delegation of three leading liberal
politicians to Belgrade on Sunday. Primakov announced his trip
after Milosevic declined to meet with the trio.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov got another boost Monday when the IMF agreed in
principle to extend a loan to help Russia pay off billions of
dollars in foreign debt. The new loan, reportedly worth $4.8
billion, is a victory for Primakov, as the IMF had suspended a $22
billion aid package to Russia after the country's financial crash
in August.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the IMF and the Clinton administration had demanded
proof that Primakov had a plan to reform Russia's huge state-owned
natural resource monopolies, improve revenue collection, and crack
down on waste and corruption. But the new credit comes without
signs of significant improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money was clearly given for political reasons,'' said
Sergei Markov of the Moscow-based Institute for Political Studies.
``Western countries have decided to underscore that the
disagreements with Russia are local, not global.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
