<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL DIALLO PROTEST AT POLICE HEADQUARTERS IS HELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two weeks and more than 1,200 arrests, the last
of the daily protests outside Police Headquarters that have placed
the death of Amadou Diallo at the center of the city's political
consciousness was held Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The final protest took place as the Bronx district attorney
announced that the four police officers who shot Diallo will be
arraigned Wednesday on criminal charges. Three Democratic members
of Congress _ Eliot Engel of the Bronx and Major Owens and Nydia
Velazquez, both of Brooklyn _ were among the 166 people arrested
for civil disobedience. But one protester in particular attracted
the attention of veteran police officers at the scene: William
Bracey, a compact man in a tan three-piece suit and a brown fedora.
</P>
<P>
   Bracey, 79, was the department's chief of patrol from 1979 until
1982. On Monday, he returned to the building where he once held
command to be placed under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel I'm obligated to be here,'' said Bracey, a
member of the National Organization of Black Law Enforcement
Executives. ``This is not just a black problem. This is not just a
community problem. This is a people problem, and police officers,
chiefs and whatnot, are people, and we have families, children,
people that will be affected if we don't do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking on from the crowd was Carleton Irish, 71, a former
police sergeant who was teamed up with Bracey in 1954 as a rookie
patrolman in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart to see a man like Bill Bracey taken away in
handcuffs,'' said Irish. ``I think he wanted to make a point, that
these are not crazies who hate the police. These are people who
hate what has happened to the Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests began 15 days ago with a few dozen people chanting,
``No justice, no peace!'' outside 1 Police Plaza, and grew by the
hundreds after Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., and former Mayor David
Dinkins were arrested. It ended on a buoyant note in the sunshine
Monday, as the Rev. Al Sharpton told the protesters they could take
credit for helping force changes in the Police Department and the
city's political discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started they said it was silly, they said it was a
publicity stunt,'' Sharpton said, echoing the phrases that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani had used to dismiss the protests. ``The mayor, 15
days ago, said to meet with black officials would be pandering. Now
he's meeting with everybody he can.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, for his part, sought to balance his remarks on the
protests by expressing his sympathy for the Diallo family, his
support for the Police Department and his anger at the personal
attacks against him. He complained that several protesters held
aloft signs that compared him to Adolf Hitler and the Police
Department to the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   The police union, the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, spent
more than $150,000 on advertisements published in newspapers Monday
denouncing what it called a rush to judgment of the four police
officers involved in the Diallo case and of the department as a
whole. The union has planned a large demonstration of off-duty
police officers for Tuesday outside the Bronx County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the four officers who shot and killed Diallo _
Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy _
said they were telephoned by Bronx prosecutors Monday and told to
be prepared to surrender their clients for arrest Wednesday morning
at an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx district attorney, Robert Johnson, said in a statement
that an indictment would be unsealed Wednesday. The statement did
not say what the charges would be, but a law enforcement official
and a lawyer connected to the case who spoke on the condition of
anonymity have said the four officers would be indicted on charges
of second-degree murder in the Feb. 4 shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
