<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEC-PRIVATIZATION-2TA     03-29 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEC-PRIVATIZATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY'S PLAN TO PRIVATIZE ANGERS SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in a raging bull market, some New York Stock Exchange
companies wallow in neglect. A few, like dusty antiques in the
attic, turn out to be gems.
</P>
<P>
   PEC Israel Economic Corp., a holding company that has stakes in
Israeli ventures, is one such company. Management takes a low
profile. Analysts ignore the company. The stock price has gone
mostly downhill since the early 1990s. So forgotten is PEC that it
is slated for extinction, with its largest shareholder preparing to
buy up the remaining shares and delist it as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The delisting, however, comes as several PEC investments,
including a stake in Cellcom, Israel's largest mobile telephone
operator, are scheduled to go public and capture a market value
that analysts believe will greatly exceed the amount that PEC says
they are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Discount Investments Corp., a company controlled by the Recanati
family of Israel, is the majority PEC shareholder that wants to
privatize PEC. By doing so, it would not have to share any future
gains in the market value of PEC assets with other stockholders,
disgruntled shareholders contend.
</P>
<P>
   The offer to privatize PEC was made several months after
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the investment bank, paid $78 million for a
9.5 percent stake in the Israeli holding company that controls
Discount Investments. Goldman, jointly with Lehman Brothers, also
happens to be a lead underwriter of Cellcom, which plans to list
shares in the United States shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Minority PEC shareholders have filed lawsuits to block the deal,
contending that the offer substantially underestimates the value of
the investments PEC has made over the years. Unless the suits
prevail, the delisting is a done deal because Discount Investments
already holds an 80 percent stake in PEC. Shareholders will
formally vote on the proposal at a shareholder meeting Tuesday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict involves a tangled story of American-Israeli
economic connections that turned sour. Some shareholders see the
demise of PEC as an ignominious end to a company founded in 1926 by
Justice Louis Brandeis of the Supreme Court. He and other Zionists
established the company to support Palestine at a time when Jews
there had difficulty raising money for even the most basic
necessities, like housing and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, until the Israeli stock market boom of the 1990s made
it easier for Israeli companies to raise capital, PEC was run as
much as a charity as a corporation. Its stock is still widely held
by Jews around the world who once regarded it as much as a donation
as an investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company was never supposed to be about squeezing every
last dime out of shareholders,'' said Murray Greenfield, a retired
72-year-old Israeli broker who sold PEC stock to Jewish visitors to
Israel in the 1960s. ``It was about building Israel. If Brandeis
woke up today he would not be the happiest man in the world, I can
tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   For more recent shareholders, PEC's privatization is a fresh
lesson about the risks of investing in undervalued companies. Some
investors said they snapped up PEC stock in recent years because
the price fell far below the level at which analysts estimated the
value of its underlying investments. These investors were hoping
PEC would eventually enjoy a run-up in the value of Israeli
companies that went public after the 1993 peace accord with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Like PEC, some investment holding companies trade at a discount
to the book value of their underlying assets, especially when
management is indifferent. But PEC's discount _ more than 46
percent, according to an estimate made by an analyst at Lehman
Brothers late last year _ was large enough to make PEC a prime
target for investors seeking the most undervalued companies on the
U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pity is that this is happening just as some of PEC's
investments are just about to take off,'' said one large
shareholder who declined to be identified because his company has
legal action pending. Among the largest minority shareholders are
mutual funds run by Credit Suisse Asset Management and Vanguard
Group.
</P>
<P>
   PEC's management team, which includes two members of the
Recanati family, declined to comment through a spokesman on the
lawsuits or the buyout offer, citing Securities and Exchange
Commission regulations that they say prohibit them from speaking
publicly while the offer is pending. Goldman, which stands to
benefit if the Recanatis have their way at PEC, also declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But in documents, the company says that the $30-a-share purchase
price for the shares of PEC that Discount Investments does not
already own is fair, pointing out that the price is 32 percent
higher than what the shares were fetching before Discount
Investments made a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, PEC management hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to
appraise its value. After Merrill's review, Discount Investment
raised its bid to $30 a share from $25.50. Merrill called the $30
price fair, a fact that PEC officials said validates the latest
offer.
</P>
<P>
   But some shareholders fault Merrill for collecting as much as
$625,000 from PEC in fees if the deal flies, but failing to extract
from PEC management the sort of information Merrill normally seeks
to judge the fairness of a deal. Merrill acknowledged in its
fairness opinion, for example, that it did not have access to the
management of Cellcom, the mobile phone operator and what many
consider to be the portfolio's hidden jewel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been afforded the opportunity to meet with the
management of Cellcom Israel, the company's largest single holding,
and thus have not been able to discuss with such management the
business prospects of Cellcom,'' the Merrill review states.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Israeli newspapers have reported that Cellcom plans to go public
in the United States this year. Both Merrill and Goldman competed
for the right to underwrite that company's shares, which are
expected to generate considerable investor interest because of
Cellcom's rapid growth and its status as the No. 1 provider of
mobile phone services in Israel, itself a leader in per-capita use
of cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   In its fairness opinion, dated Dec. 11, Merrill explored various
ways to value Cellcom and settled on a range of $2 billion to $2.5
billion. More recently, Israeli news reports and Wall Street
analysts close to the company have placed a value on Cellcom closer
to $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill officials declined to comment in detail on the fairness
opinion. But a spokesman said the opinion explored the reasons that
PEC shares traded at such a heavy discount to the value of its
individual investments. It also weighs the possibility that
Cellcom's plan to go public could be delayed by a downdraft in the
American stock market, as it was late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders opposed to Discount Investments' offer contend that
the discrepancy between Merrill's valuation of Cellcom and the
price underwriters now hope to achieve in the initial public
offering amounts to $11 a share for PEC's current holders. Discount
Investments, they say, should pay at least $41 a share instead of
the $30 being proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting shareholders also say that the understatement of
PEC holdings goes beyond Cellcom and extends to PEC's stakes in
several private companies and real estate holdings in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The offer to take PEC public, these shareholders say, does not
account for a recent spike in the value of its stake in Gilat
Satellite Networks, which just went public on the Nasdaq market
last month. Another example: PEC has the right to convert a loan it
made to United Pan-Europe Communications, a European cable
television company, into shares in that prosperous concern.
Shareholders say they consider that conversion right a lucrative
opportunity that they will miss if PEC is privatized anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that some long-dormant PEC investments are starting to
ascend can be seen in the value of Discount Investment stock listed
on the Tel Aviv stock exchange, the shareholders said. Discount
Investments' assets mirror many of those held by PEC, as the two
invest side by side in many ventures. The two, for example, each
hold a 12.5 percent stake in Cellcom, and have identical positions
in many other Israeli technology and industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Discount Investment stock has been on a tear, with shares rising
from less than 80 shekels, or about $19, at the time it offered to
buy the shares of PEC it did not already control last fall, to more
than 140, or about $34.68, in recent days, an all-time high. PEC
shares on the New York Stock Exchange, which closed Monday at
$29.6875, rose in December when Discount Investment made its
$30-a-share offer, but are still well below 1993 highs.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the issue seems destined to end up in court. But for
some shareholders, it's an unfortunate paradox that American Jews
who once bought PEC shares to support cash-short Jews in Palestine
would wind up in court contending that Israeli financiers are
profiting at their expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' said Greenfield, the former broker and PEC
shareholder. ``But if they are hellbent on profits, then at least
we should have our share.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
