<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WARRIORS-STARKS-8     03-29 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WARRIORS-STARKS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARKS HAVING A BLAST WITH THE WARRIORS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The volcano finally blew 10 days ago, erupting at 9:37 p.m. in
the fourth quarter of a game against Seattle. It promptly shook the
timeout huddle of the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just went off,'' veteran Warrior guard Bimbo Coles said of
his new teammate, John Starks. ``He started screaming and pounding
his chest, `You gotta get hyped! You gotta have heart!' It was
wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all like, `Oh. This must be the other personality.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Johnny, still living and dying by the bomb and
emotionally carrying a team. The Warriors did not let Seattle back
in the game. Starks hit the game-clinching 3-pointer with about two
minutes left, and he is still ribbed about the outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because as a teammate, I love him,'' Coles said.
``When I was in Miami and we were going at it with the Knicks, I
hated him. He has that effect on people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at New York now. You can see they definitely lack an
emotional leader. They don't have anyone to get them up.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 10 years, the Knicks came West last week
without Starks. Traded for Latrell Sprewell in a deal that also
brought Terry Cummings and Chris Mills to the Warriors in January,
the shooting guard who once seemed tethered to Madison Square
Garden now kick-starts another franchise.
</P>
<P>
   This one does not have aspirations for a championship anytime
soon, but Starks has helped the Warriors remove the stain of a
19-63 season, one forever remembered for the star player choking
the coach after 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   At 12-16. the Warriors are only one game out of the Western
Conference's eighth and final playoff spot and their frenetic style
of play has again enraptured Bay Area basketball fans.
</P>
<P>
   Starks is averaging 14.1 points, 5 assists and 3.5 rebounds _
his best numbers since the 1994-95 season. But he is also playing
more and shooting a career-low percentage of .368 through 28 games.
After the victory over Seattle, he missed 15 shots in a loss at
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is Starks going to stop shooting?'' inquired a caller
named Eduardo from San Francisco, venting on KNBR radio last week.
``He killed us last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the program host defends Starks, saying his
attributes balance out the occasional 23-footer with 23 seconds
left on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing changes, except the call letters.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking his usual intensity for a stretch, Starks warned Bay
Area reporters earlier this month that he was returning to his old
self _ the hyperkinetic, emotional guy from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably feel the same way New York fans did about him,''
said Tim Roye, the Warriors' play-by-play announcer. ``They love
him for his energy and his histrionics. But the night he goes 5 for
20, they wish he would take a few less shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, though, he's been perfect for this team. The Sprewell
teams, there just wasn't any leadership or work ethic. John has
helped change the attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates embrace him. His coach, P.J. Carlesimo, lives with
the bad because he knows the good is around the corner. And Starks
has helped vindicate Warriors general manager Garry St. Jean, who
two months ago was pilloried for giving up Sprewell for three aging
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game kind of suits the West Coast,'' Starks said through
his cackling giggle, the one that sounds like an idling lawn mower.
``I've adjusted pretty well to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks spoke as he sat in front of his cubicle one night
recently, the lone Warrior left in the locker room. Compact disks
competed for time and space with his high-tops and his fan mail.
Pondering how he picked up his life in New York and moved it into a
downtown Oakland hotel in a span of two months, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while to sink in, but this is a business,'' he said.
``We all know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors and Knicks do not play this regular season, most
likely canceling Starks' return to the Garden until next season.
When the Knicks face the Indiana Pacers at the Garden Tuesday
night, they presumably will be reminded of his absence in view of
his memorable duels with Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Starks has acted the part of a mature veteran since the trade,
saying all the right things about fitting in and contributing.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Jackie, and his children, John Jr., 10, and Chelsea,
7, came to visit over spring break. He said he plans to keep his
home in Stamford, Conn., and maintain a residence in New York. He
talks to his former teammates frequently, sometimes telephoning
Patrick Ewing a few times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk trash,'' Ewing said. ``Then he tells me to keep it
going, keep playing hard and don't worry about all the
distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he ever imagined the mercurial Starks as counseling
another player, Ewing just smiled and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wish he was still here,'' he said. ``He's a
friend. We hung out on the road and we hung out here. He's
definitely missed. He's a good friend. You only play this game for
so long, and then it's over. But the relationships you develop,
that's what going to last.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With 48 hours of rumors to warn him, a numb Starks was
officially traded on Jan. 21. Unlike Charles Oakley, he does not
hold a personal grudge against Ernie Grunfeld, the team president
and general manager. But he believes it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had another run left in us,'' Starks said. ``When
you trade away two of your core guys _ guys that go on out there
who are committed to winning and being vocal when things are going
bad so that they push each other _ then you lose something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just regret that I'm not able to finish my career there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month against Dallas, Starks hit an arching, teardrop jump
shot to seal a victory with 10.8 seconds left. After the shot, he
began pointing to his chest and yelling at Coles: ``We're Warriors,
baby! Warriors hang in there!''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those awkward, almost comical, scenes in which
Coles was at first not sure how to respond. This wild man, his face
contorted, slapping him on the back, pointing to the team logo with
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Starks used to do the same thing in New York, Coles
finally warmed to the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to the craziness now,'' he said. ``In a lot of ways,
John Starks just grows on you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
