<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,250(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REFOCUSES TARGETS TO HALT SERBIAN ATTACKS ON ALBANIANS IN
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to recast lede, raise quotes on `genocide'
higher, condense graf on downed F117; Pickup 9th graf pvs, Pentagon
officials ...; INSERTS new 12-14 grafs bgng, Bacon said ..., to add
more quotes from Pentagon spokesman; Pickup 12th graf pvs, In
London ...) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map showing
targets of attack is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO bombers hunted for Serbian troops in embattled
Kosovo on Monday and the administration said evidence of
``genocide'' by Serbian forces was growing to include ``abhorrent
and criminal action'' on a vast scale. The language was the State
Department's strongest yet in denouncing Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   There were also more reports of assassinations of ethnic
Albanian leaders and of the scorched-earth torching of Kosovar
villages by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of refugees continued to flee in terror from
Serb forces, pouring into neighboring Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro and compounding the Balkan region's massive refugee
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic has adopted what can only be described as
a siege mentality,'' said British Air Commodore David Wilby at NATO
headquarters in Brussels. ``He believes he can realign his ethnic
problems in one week and that NATO unity will crack in that same
period,'' he said of the nonstop refugee flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are indicators that genocide is unfolding in Kosovo,''
said State Department spokesman James Rubin, invoking a word heady
with implications of proof and punishment in international law.
There is no reason to await confirmation before using the word, he
argued, ``because we can clearly say crimes against humanity are
being committed'' that carry penalties of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Let me say that the abhorrent and criminal actions,
I mean on a massive scale, are occurring in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said their assault was directed increasingly at
Milosevic's forces in Kosovo. ``Major attacks'' were delivered
Sunday night on the 243rd Serb Combat Group at Donja Somanja,
Kosovo, according to NATO military officials who said the unit had
directed attacks on Albanian villagers.
</P>
<P>
   But military officials acknowledged that the hunt for Serbian
forces was complicated by the fact that they were operating in
small and dispersed groups.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade claimed its forces had shot down a second NATO
warplane, but this was denied by the Pentagon. Officials continued
to withhold information on what had brought down an American F-117
stealth fighter over Yugoslavia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the new air assaults in Kosovo were thus
far directed at barracks, headquarters and other bases, rather than
at the tanks, artillery pieces and small mobile military units
deployed in the fiel against Kosovo villages. A-10 ``Warthog''
planes, designed to make low-run, low-speed attacks on tanks and
field artillery, were reported taking to the air for the first time
in the six-day-old NATO assault, but there were no immediate
reports of any dramatic success in stopping Serbian attacks on
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   More American warplanes were committed to the NATO operation
Monday, including B-1B bombers equipped with a variety of bombs,
such as cluster ``bomblets.'' More EA-6B Prowler aircraft designed
to confuse enemy radar systems were also dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic military bullet here,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Ken Bacon, facing increasingly sharp questions about the
efficacy of the air attacks in the face of the heightened Serbian
onslaught. ``There is not a quick solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said one problem was that Serbian troops and special
police are widely dispersed through the area and operating in small
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started first with the infrastructures and the supply
lines, and we will move as quickly as we can to actual forces,''
Bacon said. ``The problem is that although we are going to hit
increasingly staging areas where we find them, as I tried to
indicate, there aren't large concentrations of troops at this
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're attacking villages from different directions in small
groups,'' Bacon continued. ``So that is a complicating factor.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said he was
alarmed by reports of ``some of these refugees being herded into
concentration areas'' by Serb forces. He cited one report,
unconfirmed as yet, of 20,000 refugees concentrated around Srbica.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remember the way in which many refugees were herded
together and executed by the Serb forces during the civil war in
Bosnia,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   One immediate question was whether the political leaders of NATO
might ease restrictions on on targets like the Ministry of the
Interior in Belgrade, where much of the Kosovo onslaught has
reportedly been mapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a question that I would like to address
today,'' Wilby responded when asked whether the NATO command had
prevented the allied bombers from attacking the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was denounced by NATO officials for waging a
``scorched earth'' siege in routing the ethnic Albanians, whose
autonomy within Serbia was stripped away by the Serbian dictator 10
years ago. Kosovo, the southern province of the Serbian republic in
which ethnic Albanians account for nine-tenths of the population,
is hallowed ground to the Serbs, and a touchstone in Milosevic's
ultranationalist campaign to maintain power.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Kosovo villages were reported under assault and burning
between Pec and Klina on Monday, with Albanian residents fleeing
the Serbs, NATO said. Three villages west of Pristina, the Kosovo
capital, were also reported aflame by NATO officials, who have
tended to offer the public more specific details on the Kosovo
scene than their American counterparts here.
</P>
<P>
   As calls mounted for more immediate results by NATO, President
Clinton interrupted a Virginia golf outing to telephone British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder.
At the Pentagon, the Joint Chiefs of Staff met in private, with
Kosovo heading their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front, administration officials expressed
little optimism that Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's trip
to Belgrade Tuesday would bear much fruit in the way of ending the
NATO assault unless he somehow reverses Milosevic's adamancy in
refusing to retreat from his year-long Kosovo campaign. Some
officials voiced concerns that Primakov might push the Serbs into a
deal short of what NATO is demanding: autonomy for Kosovo under the
protection of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million ethnic Albanians _ a fifth of the province
_ were already reported to have fled their homes over the past
year. Tens of thousands more have taken to the roads since the NATO
bombings began, with some even being stripped of their
identification papers and being forced to pay bribes at the Serb
borders, NATO said.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees are being prodded by Milosevic's troops and
paramilitary police as well as by what NATO officials described as
murderous gangs in civilian clothes bearing names like the Vucak
Wolves, names already infamous from earlier ethnic wars.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty thousand Kosovo refugees descended upon hard-pressed
neighboring Albania today, according to the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees. State Department officials estimated the flow was
continuing at 2,000 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, there were an estimated 22,000 refugees as U.N.
relief officials held emergency meetings to deal with the crisis.
In Montenegro, at least 28,000 refugees have flowed in from Pec,
the Kosovo border city that remained under siege and burning,
according to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Clinton administration officials heightened warnings
Monday that war-crime investigations will be pressed all the way
down the Serb military command to line officers in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your responsibility,'' declared Cook, angrily
addressing the Serbian officers corps. ``We know the chain of
command back to the political leadership in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said the Albanians remaining in Kosovo were despairing.
``Helicopters are being used against the civil population,'' he
said. ``Paramilitaries enter towns and villages and terrify the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the war misery of the Kosovars deepened, the White House
denied the NATO raids had only encouraged Milosevic to hasten the
routing of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were faced with a choice here, which was do we act or do we
not act?'' said Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman. ``And we
think by acting we will make him pay a price,'' he said. ``The
reason they, as a group, are better off is that this was done in
the past with impunity,'' he said of the Serb assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Cook, facing similar questioning, declared, ``If we
had not acted, all of you would now be asking why we stood by while
this ethnic cleansing took place.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House declared once more that there was ``absolutely
no change'' in the president's insistence that American ground
troops would not be used against the Serbs. Pentagon officials
emphasized that an adequate troop operation could take weeks to
mount, if it ever were decided upon, because the Serbs already have
40,000 troops in Kosovo backed by hundreds of tanks and artillery
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The reported atrocities cited by the State Department and NATO
officials, who stressed on-site confirmation was not yet possible,
included 20 village school teachers who were said to have been
gunned down by Serbs in front of their students in Goden.
</P>
<P>
   NATO reported Serbian gunmen had tracked down and executed at
least five prominent ethnic Albanians, including Batan Haxhiu,
editor of the main ethnic Albanian newspaper, and Fehmi Agani, a
member of the Kosovar Albanian peace negotiating team that met in
February at Rambouillet, outside Paris. The NATO attacks began when
those talks stalled two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials strenuously denied that the air assaults had
prompted the heightened Milosevic onslaught against the Kosovars,
noting that Serb forces have been massing in Kosovo for months and
were aggressively on the move when NATO felt obliged to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a campaign under way to ethnically re-engineer the
makeup of Kosovo, to reshape the political map of Kosovo so that
Milosevic later on would hope to achieve a negotiated solution more
favorable to Belgrade,'' said Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman in
Brussels, indicating Milosevic may be seeking to carve a Serb-only
region in Kosovo..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
