<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ANOTHER ALBANY BUDGET IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the start of a new fiscal year, Gov. George
Pataki and the New York State Legislature are not even close to
agreement on a new budget. Even worse, the progress made last year
in opening up the budget process has been cast aside because of the
inability of all parties to agree on basic revenue and cost
estimates. As usual, few outsiders are paying attention, so the
governor and the lawmakers feel little pressure to compromise. In a
switch from years past, the current impasse results from surplus,
not scarcity, and squabbling over how best to spend money in a time
of plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Budget breakdowns and delays are routine in Albany. But the
major new factor this year is the surprisingly enhanced power of
Pataki. Not only does he remain popular, and confident enough to
exhibit national political ambitions, the governor also is enjoying
an unanticipated advantage from reforms that were designed to give
new clout to the legislature. The most important reform,
inaugurated last year, had the Senate and Assembly deliberate
openly, resolve their differences in budget conference committees
and send Pataki a budget that was nearly on time. The idea was to
avoid the old habit of deciding the budget among ``three men in a
room,'' namely the governor and the leaders of the Senate and
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The reform backfired, however, at least in the view of the
legislature. The governor, feeling miffed at being shut out of the
budget as it sailed through the legislature last year, simply
vetoed large portions of it. The legislature lacked the votes to
override, as it does this year. Sheldon Silver, speaker of the
Democratic-controlled Assembly, has fallen back on the old practice
of passing a Democratic budget, with more spending than the
governor wants for education and health, and hoping for public
pressure to bend Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pataki ran for re-election with a lavish budget that
increased spending by 8 percent from the year before. Now he wants
to increase it by less than 2 percent. The Assembly wants to
increase it by 4.6 percent, and the Republican-controlled Senate is
in between. There are ingredients in here for agreement. The first
should be to reject Pataki's steep cuts in education and payments
to hospitals, nursing homes and health clinics. The second should
be to use as much of the surplus this year as possible for
budgetary reserves or debt retirement _ not new spending or new tax
cuts. As a step to hasten the process, the Assembly and Senate can
try to agree quickly on cost and revenue estimates for the options
they face. They may discover that other accords can follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
