<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LIONCOUNTRY-SLIDE     03-29 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LIONCOUNTRY-SLIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No water slides for Lion Country
 &HT;    By Marc Freeman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Finally siding with furious residents, Palm
Beach County commissioners on Monday denied Lion Country Safari's
proposal to build a water park but allowed a hotel and a Ferris
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 homeowners from the Deer Run and Fox Trail communities
cheered the commission's 5-1 vote, which ended more than six months
of bitter debate about adding water slides to the 660-acre
drive-through animal preserve in the rural western part of the
county.
</P>
<P>
   Lion Country, which insists it needs a popular summertime draw
to compete against Disney's Animal Kingdom and other Florida
tourist attractions, is free to try again when it gets an access
road separate from the one the residents now share with the park.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal favored by three commissioners would allow the
22.6-acre water park if the county extends Okeechobee Boulevard a
half-mile to a new Lion Country entrance. The only entry now is off
Southern Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The road extension is not now in the county's plans or budget.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Trail President Michael Sinclair said his neighbors hope the
park plan doesn't return for fear it would ``ruin their way of
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Mary McCarty, who cast the lone vote supporting the
water park, said the county should ask tourism officials to allow
hotel bed-tax dollars to cover road costs, which were not known
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the defeat, Lion Country President Leon Unterhalter
said he may not build the approved 147-room bungalow-style hotel
because its summer customers were to be mostly guests of the water
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' he said after Monday's five-hour zoning
hearing. ``The water park is good for the county and good for the
western area.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote, with Commissioner Burt Aaronson out recovering from
heart surgery, wasn't as lopsided as it appears. A succession of
ties had stymied commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   In those split votes, Chairwoman Maude Ford Lee and
Commissioners McCarty and Carol Roberts supported the water park as
long as Unterhalter would be required to meet 60 conditions dealing
with everything from traffic to noise. Commissioners Tony
Masilotti, Warren Newell and Karen Marcus voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Roberts suggested the board postpone action until
Aaronson returns in two months. As residents screamed, ``No!''
Masilotti and Marcus blasted the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Commissioner Aaronson's heart has had enough,'' Marcus
said. ``We shouldn't put pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   To help reach closure, McCarty announced she would become the
fourth and deciding vote to kill the water park.
</P>
<P>
   That initiated a reshuffling and the final 5-1 vote, during
which McCarty reversed herself again and voted for the water park.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the board allowed Lion Country to build a
70-foot-tall Ferris wheel as part of an expansion of its
walk-through Safari Village. The board didn't have much choice
because Lion Country won approval to add amusement rides in 1976,
though it never built them.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents yelled from their seats Monday that the Ferris
wheel doesn't belong either. But Masilotti, who represents western
Palm Beach County, said homeowners had nothing to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well folks, you can't see it and you can't hear it,'' he said.
``I don't see why it's harmful to anyone in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   But with its hopes for a water park at least temporarily dashed,
Lion Country may decide not to build the Ferris wheel either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to step back and think about what we're going to bring
back'' to commissioners, said park representative Ellen Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Freeman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
