<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      03-29 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE TO SEEK OUSTER OF LOUIMA JURY PANEL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After more than 600 prospective jurors filled out
questionnaires Monday to begin the jury selection process in the
case of police officers charged with brutalizing Abner Louima,
lawyers for the officers said they would ask the judge to dismiss
the entire panel because some of its members gave interviews to
reporters as they left the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers contended that the entire panel had been tainted and
a new one should be summoned, even though it appeared that only a
small number of the prospective jurors paused to answer a few
reporters' questions on the sidewalk outside federal District Court
in Brooklyn. Others were seen waving off reporters and television
crews who approached them as they left the building.
</P>
<P>
   The potential jurors who gave the interviews, some of which were
broadcast on television later Monday, violated the instructions
they had been given not to discuss the case with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective jurors had also been instructed that the jury
would be anonymous, and that their identities would not be made
known to the public or to the lawyers and other parties in the
case, either as members of the jury pool now or if they were chosen
to be jurors, in line with a decision by the judge in the case,
Eugene H. Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had requested an anonymous jury, not uncommon in
highly controversial cases, to keep the jurors' judgments from
being tainted by outside pressures, which the prosecutors had
argued could well occur in the racially and politically charged
case.
</P>
<P>
   Four white officers are on trial on charges of violating the
civil rights of Louima, a Haitian immigrant, after he was arrested
in a street brawl in Brooklyn in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say all four beat him in a police car and that two
of them later tortured him at the 70th Precinct station house, one
by shoving a stick into his rectum, causing severe internal
injuries, and the other by holding him down. A sergeant, the fifth
defendant, is charged with trying to cover up the reported beating
in the police car. All the defendants say the charges are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for at least three of the officers said Monday that at a
hearing scheduled for Friday, they would ask Nickerson to dismiss
the entire panel of prospective jurors and start anew. One of the
lawyers, Marvyn M. Kornberg, said, ``The purpose for which
anonymity was created in the first instance is violated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, who represents Officer Justin A. Volpe, held that even
if only a small minority of the panel gave interviews, and even if
an interview was not broadcast or published, ``if it happens that
that person is selected for the jury, some reporter may know who he
or she is but the lawyers won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a law professor at New York University, said he
did not think that Nickerson would disqualify the entire panel, but
that when he questioned prospective jurors individually _ a process
scheduled to begin in about two weeks _ he would ask if they spoke
to the press and dismiss those who said they had.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective jurors whose interviews were broadcast on television
described the queries on the questionnaire, which is intended to
determine such things as their specific knowledge and opinions of
the Louima case and their general views about police treatment of
minority members.
</P>
<P>
   They also spoke of matters like whether they wanted to serve in
the trial. One man said on television that his employer ``told me
to get out of it as soon as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
