<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-PURDUE-ART-NYT     03-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WHO TRANSFERRED FROM PURDUE GIVE DUKE EXTRA INCENTIVE IN
FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
(fb) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final score was low, the fewest points in the history of the
women's tournament final, but perhaps that was because the stakes
have grown so high.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue scored only 17 points in the first half Sunday night,
another tournament final record for futility in a half. But in the
end, Purdue soared to win the school's first women's college
basketball championship with a 62-45 victory against Duke that was
gratifying, if inelegant.
</P>
<P>
   The 107 points scored were a low for a final since the National
Collegiate Athletic Association began overseeing the tournament in
1982, but the weekend of Final Four games broke ground in other
significant and esthetic ways.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when there are rumblings that the women's championship
round of the NCAA might be moved in the calendar to avoid clashing
with the men's Final Four, Duke, an intrepid team with a appealing,
pass-happy playing style, and Purdue, a close-knit, persevering
group with a charismatic coach, brought new faces and story lines
to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the two teams proved that one can have a
compelling women's Final Four without Tennessee or Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   If the final had its rough edges, it was also a breakthrough for
Purdue and the Big Ten Conference; neither had won a women's
national title before Sunday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   The victory should help establish Purdue as a national
collegiate power in the burgeoning women's game, something Duke's
team felt it too accomplished in some measure with its ascent
through the tournament as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we've done is huge,'' Duke's Georgia Schweitzer
said. ``When people hear about Duke now, they're not just going to
think about the men.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke Coach Gail Goestenkors said, ``We made a big step forward,
although the end goal was to win the last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasing the end goal seemed to be the very problem for both
teams in the early going Sunday night when turnovers and missed
shots had each team scrambling to find any offensive rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue and Duke had played fluid, orderly games in their
semifinal victories Friday night, but midway through the first half
Sunday, the score was an unsightly 9-to-8.
</P>
<P>
   Players from both teams later acknowledged that their focus on
the prize disturbed their focus on the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty ugly first half,'' the Duke point guard Hilary
Howard said. ``You could attribute it to nerves maybe, or being too
anxious to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Or too anxious to win, especially against former teammates.
Duke's Nicole Erickson and Michele VanGorp had played for Purdue
before transferring to Duke two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season and when you get to the championship final
it's easy to try so hard you kind of overwhelm yourself,'' Purdue
Coach Carolyn Peck said. ``That's OK''
</P>
<P>
   It was OK for Peck because her players, who were a little more
seasoned to big-game pressure, found their way out of their
first-half funk. Duke just played worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us ever got into a flow,'' Erickson said. ``It was an
ugly game. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it appeared that top-ranked Purdue, which had
defeated Tennessee and the semifinalist Louisiana Tech in the
regular season on its way to 32 consecutive victories, had more
veteran leadership and more balance.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue also had secret weapons. Katie Douglas, a 6-foot-1-inch
forward, had the foot speed and size to harass Duke's smaller
guards whenever they tried to set up Duke's halfcourt offense.
Douglas made it very difficult for Duke to get the ball inside to
the 6-6 VanGorp, who took only 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   And Purdue handled the adversity of a sloppy first half with
more grit. Purdue's senior leaders, Ukari Figgs and Stephanie
White-McCarty, had played for three coaches in their four years.
They had watched as Erickson, VanGorp and two other teammates fled
the program when Lin Dunn was unceremoniously fired as the coach in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The other Purdue players stuck around and they grew closer,
relying on each other because they had no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   And when White-McCarty was helped from the court, dragging a
sprained ankle with four minutes to play Sunday, they rallied
again.
</P>
<P>
   White-McCarty's injury stunned and rattled the boisterous Purdue
cheering section that was seated just behind the Purdue bench.
Their upset and concern seemed to filter down to the bench area,
where there was a bit of chaos briefly as players tried to console
White-McCarty, who was also trying to get herself back into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs calmed her teammates and told White-McCarty to take a seat
for the evening. Led by Figgs, Purdue then went out and played its
most poised basketball of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had got through a lot of hard times a long time ago,''
Figgs said. ``We knew we could get through one more.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue scored the next 13 points, making 12 consecutive free
throws at one point. Duke's hopes faded with more turnovers and
even fewer good shots. ``I'm not one for making bold statements,''
Peck said when it was over. ``But I think the games and quality of
play here this weekend was very good for the game. There was a lot
of teamwork, some competitive pride. We saw some new faces, a new
champion and some excellent basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what the championship and the Final Four is all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACALL-COX     03-29 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bacall works the crowd in Atlanta appearance
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She still has that Cheshire cat smile, half-ironic,
half flirtatious. The voice remains husky, low and tobacco-cured.
And although she is now 74, actress Lauren Bacall was instantly
recognizable to the 2,000 fans gathered to see her Monday at the
Fox Theatre, where she shared stories of her famous life and
answered questions for nearly two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance, part of the Unique Lives &AMP; Experiences lecture
series, began a bit stiffly as Bacall read from a prepared text.
But when she left the podium and took a hand-held mike, the evening
turned into a warm and intimate conversation as she answered
questions about Bogie (famous husband Humphrey Bogart), Hollywood,
happiness, politics and aging.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Award-winning actress often used her flair for the
dramatic, opening with a passage from Tennessee Williams' ``Sweet
Bird of Youth'': ``Time is the enemy of us all.'' But unlike other
female film legends of Hollywood's golden era _ Bette Davis or
Ginger Rogers, for example _ Bacall seems to have seasoned with
age, the passing of time making her more attractive, self-effacing,
confident and accessible. The only time she displayed any signs of
being a septuagenarian was in her slow movements across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Although her show opened with film clips that have become movie
history (such as the famous ``You know how to whistle don't you?
Just put your lips together and blow'' from ``To Have and Have
Not''), Bacall managed to come down off the silver screen. Dressed
in a black pantsuit with knee-length jacket, she entertained the
mostly female audience by interspersing tidbits from her years in
Hollywood (such as the first time Bogart kissed her) with wisdom
from her years as careerist, single mother, widow, divorcee and
Hollywood survivor.
</P>
<P>
   With four standup microphones placed in each aisle of the Fox,
Atlanta fans waited patiently to hear Bacall answer their
questions:
</P>
<P>
   On Bogart: ``I wanted to marry him as much as I wanted to
breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   On being a working mother: ``It never occurred to me I was
making some kind of statement.''
</P>
<P>
   On the lecture series: ``Anytime I have to appear as myself, I'm
totally nervous.'' On today's Broadway: ``I'm sick of revivals. I
want to be in something original.''
</P>
<P>
   On today's Hollywood: ``Look at films like `Central Station' and
`Life Is Beautiful.' When foreign films make that much of an
impression, it shows you how little Hollywood is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, in her suite at the Four Seasons Hotel,
Bacall seemed as flattered as a schoolgirl when asked if she put a
lot of effort into looking much younger than her 74 years. ``God
no,'' she said, laughing. ``I've never been one to look in the
mirror much. It may be because I've kept working. I haven't sat
around and waited. That's one reason why I love doing these
conversations (such as the show at the Fox). I still have something
to contribute. You've got to have a goal and a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   And hers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Staying alive is my main one,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
