<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WILL REORGANIZE INTO 5 UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heralding an era he referred to as the ``vision version 2.0,''
the Microsoft Corp.'s president, Steven Ballmer, announced the
reorganization of the company Monday into five divisions that he
suggested would act with some independence.
</P>
<P>
   In a morning teleconference held with his friend, William H.
Gates, who co-founded the company, Ballmer, who became president of
Microsoft eight months ago, said that he was beginning to reinvent
the company, the world's largest independent software maker,
focusing it on initiatives that he said were largely ``customer
driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, who has a reputation as a hands-on manager who likes to
burrow deeply into the company's different businesses, said that
the reorganization had nothing to do with the bitter antitrust
lawsuit Microsoft is now fighting with the federal government and
19 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Ballmer said in response to a question about
whether the software publisher was simply looking for a new
divisional structure that might facilitate a future breakup
instituted by the Justice Department. He added, ``There's certainly
no breakup of this company into smaller companies that I would find
acceptable, and we're certainly not in any way thinking of that as
a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates said that it was ``inappropriate'' to comment on
settlement talks with the Justice Department and state attorneys
general that were scheduled to begin Tuesday in Washington. He said
his two objectives going into the discussion were that the
company's Windows operating system retain its integrity and that
the company maintain its ability to add innovations to its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Under the reorganization announced Monday, Microsoft has been
divided into five separate divisions, and two veteran executives
have been named to head its troubled online operations.
</P>
<P>
   These are the five new groups within Microsoft under the
reorganization:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Business and Enterprise Division, which will focus on
software for information technology customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Consumer Windows Division, which will focus on developing
Windows for the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Business Productivity Group, which will focus on products
for so-called knowledge workers, which includes telecommuters and
home-office workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Developer Group, which will focus on software developers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Consumer and Commerce Group, which includes the Microsoft
Network, will focus on bringing consumers and businesses together
on line.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced an expanded 14-member executive
committee, which analysts said was intended to help decentralize
the management of the giant software company, based in Redmond,
Wash. The group, which will be headed by Gates, will meet monthly
to discuss the company's broad goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hidden between the lines is the reality that this can no
longer continue to be the Bill and Steve show,'' said an executive
who is close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally favored the reorganization, and the stock
market was positive as well, sending the shares up $3.25, to
$92.375, on the first day of trading after a 2-for-1 split.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense,'' said Arthur V. Russell, an analyst
with the brokerage firm of Edward Jones, adding that it would
``allow Microsoft to get closer to its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said neither investors nor consumers were likely to see
any immediate change from the reorganization. However, he said, if
the reorganization is successful, eventually customers will see
more reliable products and intensified marketing efforts, while
investors could see increased sales and higher returns.
</P>
<P>
   Under the reorganization James Allchin, a technologist, will run
two groups: the Business and Enterprise Division and the Windows
division, aimed at developing the Windows operating system for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Microsoft veterans, Brad Chase and Jon DeVaan, will
run the Consumer and Commerce Group, and Paul Maritz will supervise
the software-developers group. Robert Muglia will oversee the
division aimed at knowledge workers.
</P>
<P>
   All of the executives named except DeVaan have testified at the
antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was not mentioned Monday, the company's Windows CE
consumer operating system for hand-held computers and set-top boxes
has been split between the Business Productivity Group and the
Consumer and Commerce Group.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from Monday's announcement were two Microsoft veterans
who have played significant roles in the past. Ballmer said that
Brad Silverberg, who had been a key executive both in the company's
Windows desktop business and its Internet effort, had recently
returned to work half-time after a leave of absence and had an
office several doors down from his own.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Silverberg would serve as an adviser to him and
that he was already being peppered with e-mail from him.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when he was asked why Nathan Myhrvold, who heads the
software publisher's basic research efforts, had not been named to
the company's expanded executive committee, Gates said that
Myhrvold's work had a research and not a business focus.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has until now been organized into three
technology-oriented groups: computer operating systems,
applications, and other activities similar to its online business.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews Monday and during the teleconference,
Ballmer stressed that he was attempting to streamline the company
to make it more responsive to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to talk about is the reinvention of Microsoft,''
he said, adding that the company would now shift its focus to a
changing model of computer technology, one not so radically focused
on the desktop personal computer as Microsoft has been.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has increasingly found itself under attack from
competitors that argue that the computer industry is entering a
post-PC phase and that new growth will largely come in areas in
which Microsoft is not dominant, such as hand-held devices and
wireless appliances. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
