<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIKELEE-ACTIVISM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lee to students: Do your own thing
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Spike Lee charmed an audience of mostly University
of Georgia students Monday night even after he had warned them that
he didn't plan to ``be here very long.'' He was well aware that
``CBS Got Game'' and he wanted to see it.
</P>
<P>
   But as Duke and Connecticut neared tip-off time for the NCAA
Championship, Lee still was leaning on the podium and patiently,
and often humorously, answering questions, although by then he had
mentioned the game a few times.
</P>
<P>
   But this standing-room-only crowd of over 1,200 came to hear
America's foremost black director and they didn't seem inclined to
let go.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, raised in Brooklyn and educated at Atlanta's Morehouse
College, didn't bring the controversial baggage that seems to have
followed him since he broke on the scene in 1986 with ``She's Gotta
Have It.'' He didn't shy away when asked sensitive questions, but
he wasn't the attack dog as he is usually portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here today because of my parents. When (after four years
of school) I told my parents that I wanted to make films, they
encouraged me. You know, most of us are not from well-off families
and parents have to work two shifts and go into hock just to get
you through those four years. And you don't want to come home and
say, `I want to be a poet,''' Lee said as the crowd laughed.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee urged the students to follow through with whatever they
wanted to do, even if it meant ``fighting through whatever guilt''
their families may lay on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get to that point in life where you end up
saying `I coulda', shoulda' woulda'.' Even if you have to wash
dishes for 10 years, you ought to pursue your goal.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he got the film bug after he had just about completed
his four years at Morehouse, where he majored in mass
communications. He said he considered West Coast graduate schools
like USC and UCLA but they wanted ``astronomical GREs'' that he
didn't have. NYU, a noted film school, didn't require GREs. In
telling that story, his first aside came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never believed that standardized test scores should be the
only criteria for getting into school. I am not saying you should
do away with them, but that you should consider other things,'' he
said and the crowd seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   He took a swipe at the recent Academy Awards, which he called a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone was set when Whoopi (Goldberg) came out in white
face. The Academy Awards was a joke. We keep reading about all the
advances African Americans have made in the (industry) and then you
watch the Academy Awards . . .you see it as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the question and answer session with the students, Lee
addressed ``He Got Game,'' his story of a relationship between a
father (Denzel Washington) and his basketball-star son (Ray Allen)
that seemed to be a favorite among the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it because I like sports. I love basketball. I am sure
blacks said `Spike's selling out' because it was so different from
my other movies.''
</P>
<P>
   And he brought the crowd to hysterics. A black student asked him
if he planned to make a true Egyptian movie that showed Egyptians
as people of color. He interrupted the student asking:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter? You don't like Elizabeth Taylor? You don't
think she looks like Cleopatra?''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's new movie, slated for release in July, is ``Summer of
Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   Plott Brice writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
