<HEADER>
A9033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-BASS-NYT &LR;      03-29 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-BASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OUR FORGOTTEN NATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAY OTTULICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the fish, stupid!
</P>
<P>
   Last year's New York state Department of Environmental
Conservation survey indicates that the number of anglers is
declining. The demographic reality of our future flyfishers
indicates that they are not particularly geared to sitting about in
sedentary discussion of the relative worth of dubious fly patterns,
cane-rod workmanship or the minutiae of method. Lamentably, they
have been reared, even more than my generation, on rock-and-roll
music, audio-visual stimulation, extreme sports, and instant
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Take children flyfishing for stocked trout on public water in
the East and watch as their attention span shrinks with every
passing minute. Take the same children to a warm-water fishery with
aggressive wild smallmouth along with the other ``fish in the
'hood'' _ rock bass, fall fish, sunfish _ and they will have a
blast. More important, they will be hooked on flyfishing for life.
</P>
<P>
   The ethereal jump to a dedicated concern for the environment and
a quest for understanding the wonders and relationships of the
natural world will inevitably follow, but first you have to get
their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Living and guiding in the northwest corner of Montana for almost
a quarter century, I became well acquainted with the activity of
wild fish in their native habitats. West Slope cutthroats and
Columbia red band rainbows would regularly be slandered as dumb
because of their bold propensity to hit any fly offered, while
``experts'' from points east would proclaim their stocked fish more
intelligent because of their selectivity and wary demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the reality is that wild trout are by natural
selection genetically engineered to make the most of the short
growing season of their high-altitude, natural environments, while
hatchery stockies have become behaviorally altered and genetically
retarded by the manipulations of man. To the unenlightened, the
poorer the fishery, the smarter its fish become.
</P>
<P>
   Forget stocked trout. River smallmouth or black bass in the
eastern United States are the wild freshwater fish of the
flyfishing future, the new wave, Generation X, millennium fish, the
fin de siecle uebertrout. They represent a direct, yet long ago
broken, hyperlink to the past in our North American flyfishing
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Most modern-day flyfishers have encountered smallmouth bass as
merely an incidental side catch in the pursuit of trout on the
cusp, or transition, sections between cold- and warm-water
fisheries. Catching unimpressive, diminutive (9-ounce) specimens on
6 weight, or heavier, trout rods would be the equivalent to
flyfishing for trout with a stiff saltwater rod. What gratification
is there fishing with a telephone pole?
</P>
<P>
   But when you make river smallmouth your quest, gear up with
light 3 or 4 weight rods and angle in their prime habitat _ steep
gradient, warm water rivers and kills with rocky pocket water and
cascading ledge pools _ then and only then will you experience
their true potential.
</P>
<P>
   Smallmouth are smashmouth-aggressive attack dogs. Throw a
streamer fly or leech pattern in pocket water and two or three will
bolt out to ambush it. Twitch an attracter pattern in feigned
helplessness as it drifts over a deep pool and await an explosive
take. Smallmouth inhabit the same lies and holding areas that
customarily hold trout; look for them on the slow-water side of
current seams, beneath foam lines, the undercut banks, behind the
rock, lurking below the underwater ledge, hiding beneath the debris
in an eddy, the downstream side of a gravel bar.
</P>
<P>
   Smallmouth's original range stretched from Minnesota and the
Dakotas, included the Mississippi drainage south to the Ozarks, the
Tennessee River, the Ohio River and all of the Great Lakes and
their tributaries, all the way east to the grand cataracts of the
St. Lawrence. They readily invaded the Mohawk and Hudson watersheds
with the opening of the Erie Canal, and further railroad stockings
continued to spread them to their present distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Flyfishing for river smallmouth provides the closest freshwater
equivalent in the East to what I would term Montana Action: The
reaches where they are most abundant are practically deserted, and
you will have them to yourself. River smallmouth for the majority
of fly-fishermen have truly been our forgotten other native.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-29-99 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990329.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-29 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-SECRETS-     03-29 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-SECRETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SAFEGUARDING NUCLEAR SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, March 30:
</P>
<P>
   Top officials of the Energy and Justice Departments and the Los
Alamos National Laboratory were amazingly careless in their
handling of a scientist suspected of stealing nuclear secrets for
China, judging from two reports last week by The Times' James
Risen.
</P>
<P>
   It was in June 1996 that the Federal Bureau of Investigation
began investigating Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwanese-born American citizen,
for possibly leaking nuclear weapons designs to China. Yet for more
than two years, Lee maintained his top level security clearance,
was assigned to highly sensitive weapons work and was even briefly
allowed to employ a Chinese citizen as a research assistant.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials initially seemed more concerned with not tipping
off their suspect to the investigation than they were with keeping
him away from additional weapons secrets. Even after the FBI told
the Energy Department that Lee could be removed from weapons work,
he kept his job and his security clearances for more than another
year. He was finally dismissed this month.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has promised strict new
security procedures for the weapons labs. Congress will rightly
hold him to that promise. But the changes must be carefully
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional proposals to discourage exchange programs with
foreign labs, for example, could actually weaken America's nuclear
security. Visits to U.S. labs help Russian scientists learn new
technologies for dismantling Moscow's nuclear arsenal. These same
programs also allow American scientists into Russia's and China's
hitherto secret weapons facilities. Care must be taken to keep
foreign visitors from unauthorized snooping. But the exchange
programs themselves should be extended, not curbed.
</P>
<P>
   The most important change needed is much more careful selection,
training and supervision of employees in weapons design and
simulation. More thorough background checks should be carried out
and clearances promptly lifted when there is serious suspicion of
misconduct. The Clinton administration must move wisely to protect
vital secrets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
