<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: HAUNTING WHAT-IF LEFT FOR TALENTED CUBANS
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-TV-SPORTS) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ The baseball commissioner and the owner of the
Baltimore Orioles sit on either side of Fidel Castro for 11
innings, talking baseball like good buddies, and eat his food and
drink his wine as he spends hours showing off his knowledge of the
game. Other major league officials and team owners show off color
pictures taken of them with the world's longest-running despot and
can't wait to get home to display them for their friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Omar Linares has not had, nor will he ever have, the chance
to show that his five Cuban League batting championships, each with
an average over .400, were worthy of a job as a third baseman with
a major league team. Jose Contreras struck out 10 Baltimore batters
and shut them out on two hits for eight innings on Sunday, but he
will never get to test his wily pitching and sharp scouting eye in
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Linares, Contreras and their friends are condemned to a what-if
future: what if Castro had allowed them the opportunity to play
with Mark McGwire and Roger Clemens and not just against
overmatched amateurs in tournaments around the world? They will
never know what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Their situation, however, does not stop Major League Baseball
from going to Cuba in an effort to open a window, to improve
relations between the countries. But what good is improving
relations if the plight of the Cuban players is not improved?
</P>
<P>
   And while officials and owners ate Castro's pork and lobster at
the National Palace last Saturday night, children asked for bubble
gum on the crumbling streets of Old Havana. They were not the
children of the players _ the stars, after all, do receive elite
treatment, using the term relatively _ but they were the children
of the players' fans and future fans themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball people were impressed with the Cuban team that nearly
sent the Orioles home in shame. Not all of the players on the team
could play in the majors, but some of them could, just as the
Hernandez half brothers do and just as Tony Oliva and Perez did.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to see the Cuban team, Chuck LaMar of Tampa Bay
said Monday while waiting for the flight off the island, was not
just special but ``extremely special.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost players over the past few years because of the
defections they've had,'' LaMar, the Devil Rays' general manager,
said, ``but it's obvious that the flow of talent continues. For a
baseball man, it was an honor to be able to see them play on their
home turf, to see that they still have the abilities that we all
thought they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beattie, the Montreal Expos' general manager, was impressed
that the Cubans were not awed by the professional major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fouling off pitches, good major league pitches,''
Beattie, a former pitcher, said. ``They were able to battle and put
the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitchers, he added, didn't give in to the hitters, at least
not after Charles Johnson hit a 3-0 fastball for a second-inning
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said no more of that,'' Beattie said. ``They were
throwing 3-0 breaking balls. They had a strikeout- throw-out double
play on a breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Contreras walked Will Clark intentionally to pitch to Albert
Belle, a move unheard of in the States. But Belle promptly grounded
to third base for the start of an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't only that he hit into a double play,'' Beattie
noted, ``but they had him played the way they were going to pitch
him. The guy was right down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Angelos, the Orioles' owner, said other teams would go to
Cuba in the future. The Yankees could be next because Cuban fans
want to see the Yankees. And the Cuban team will play in Baltimore
on May 3, then perhaps in New York and other cities as relations
continue to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Cuban system, it will remain the same as long as
Castro lives. Based on his performance last weekend, that might be
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie told of Castro's triple-header Sunday: the 11-inning
game, an evening reception for baseball people and a post-midnight
reception, lasting until 3 or 4 in the morning, for musicians who
were here for a festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were probably 300 or 400 people there,'' Beattie said.
``You all stood in line and met him. It wasn't just that you
introduced yourself and walked on. He had something to say to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   An impressive man, at 72, no doubt. But his 40-year-old system
is less impressive and he has failed his favorite people, his
baseball players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
