<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-CABLE-NYT </SLUG>
 
MCI WORLDCOM SAID TO BE INVESTING $200 MILLION in WIRELESS DEAL 
 (fb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom Inc., seeking advanced wireless Internet links, is
investing about $200 million in what is incongruously known as the
wireless cable business, executives close to the plans said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom is the No. 2 long-distance phone company, after
AT&AMP;T, and the No. 1 Internet carrier. Even so, it has become
frustrated in trying to use lines owned by the Bell local phone
companies to connect to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells must lease their lines to other companies that want to
use them, and the Bells say that process is easy. The Bells'
competitors, including MCI Worldcom, almost invariably contend that
the process is arduous and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   So, the executives close to the transactions say, MCI Worldcom
is buying the shares and bonds of four so-called wireless cable
operators: CAI Wireless Systems Inc., CS Wireless Systems Inc., the
People's Choice TV Corp. and Wireless One Inc. Control of those
companies could allow MCI Worldcom to avoid using the Bells in some
places.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, the cable television channel, first reported the plans
Monday. It said the company might have already spent as much as
$300 million to $400 million, but executives close to the deals
said MCI Worldcom had committed only about $200 million to the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The companies in which MCI Worldcom is investing have tried to
use wireless technology to transmit signals from the television
stations that most consumers view using cable. Though
direct-broadcast satellite systems have proven effective, the
land-based wireless technology embraced by the wireless cable
operators never proved broadly cost-effective for transmitting
television signals. Nevertheless, MCI Worldcom apparently believes
that the spectrum owned by the wireless cable operators could be
used efficiently to transmit Internet data.
</P>
<P>
   CS Wireless, People's Choice and Wireless One are all in
financial trouble, and control of those companies may lie in their
bonds, rather than in their shares, allowing MCI Worldcom to
accumulate control through the traditionally secretive corporate
debt market. As for CAI, executives close to the deals said
securities regulations would soon force MCI Worldcom to disclose a
large investment in that company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to gain control of the wireless cable carriers cheaply
and quietly would be a move typical of Scott D. Sullivan, MCI
Worldcom's chief financial officer, who has developed a strong
financial reputation in the telecommunications industry for his
swift seizing of opportunities and his delivery of consistent
earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
