<HEADLINE>
A MANIC DAY FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ The Los Angeles Dodgers' muddy roster situation
became clearer Monday, one week before the team's opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The club placed pitcher Antonio Osuna and infielder Alex Cora on
the disabled list, retroactive to March 25. Left-handed pitcher
Chris Haney and infielder Scott Livingstone were reassigned to the
minor-league camp and infielder Juan Castro and catcher Angel Pena
were sent to Triple-A Albuquerque. Also, right-handed reliever Doug
Bochtler elected to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest roster decision is whether the team carries two or
three catchers. General manager Kevin Malone said that won't be
decided until Saturday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Dodgers elect to go with three catchers, they would
be leaning toward using four outfielders until they can get their
catching corps down to two, which most likely would be Todd Hundley
and Rick Wilkins. Paul LoDuca remains in the mix although Pena
impressed manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Angel I like him, but if I wasn't able to catch him
half the time, I didn't want him sitting,'' Johnson said. ``I like
everything he does. Calls a good game, a good catcher, a good
thrower. I'm not going to bring him up so he can catch three days a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said the Dodgers would likely go with seven infielders.
That group is all but set. The starters are third baseman Adrian
Beltre, shortstop Mark Grudzielanek, second baseman Eric Young and
first baseman Eric Karros, and there are only three other healthy
infielders in camp _ Jose Vizcaino, Dave Hansen and Tripp Cromer.
</P>
<P>
   Cora is also still considered in camp, but he broke his right
hand two weeks ago and won't be ready for another two to four
weeks. Hansen apparently survived despite hitting .205 while his
main competitor, Livingstone, hit .364.
</P>
<P>
   In the outfield, the quartet is obviously Gary Sheffield, Devon
White, Raul Mondesi and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who is yet to pitch this spring because of since-subsided
soreness in his pitching elbow, is eligible to come off the
disabled list April 9. The Dodgers want him to pitch in five or six
games before they activate him.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said the Dodgers would try to head west Wednesday with 31
players, needing to cut down to 25 after Sunday's exhibition with
the Yankees. He said he would try to find major-league jobs for
Haney and Livingstone via a minor-league trade.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard to Blue Jays?: If the Dodgers elect to start the season
with two catchers, which would mean five outfielders, it could be
Jacob Brumfield beating out incumbent Trenidad Hubbard. If that
happens, Hubbard could wind up with the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the Blue Jays have kept an eye on Hubbard. Toronto
is in the market for a fourth outfielder and Hubbard could fit that
role.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers and Blue Jays would have to work out a deal
for the trade to happen since the Dodgers won't release Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, who missed more than two weeks with thumb and shoulder
injuries, is hitting .100 this spring. The speedy Brumfield, who
played for Johnson in Cincinnati, is hitting .293.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Pitching coach Charlie Hough said
pitcher Ismael Valdes would start for the Dodgers against the
Angels on Friday at Edison Field. Carlos Perez and Darren Dreifort
are also slated to pitch against the Angels.... Reliever Jeff
Williams is scheduled to pitch for the Dodgers today as they
continue to search for a left-hander in the bullpen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
