<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-TYPEWRITER-ERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITERS' DEN PUTS SQUEEZE ON TYPISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't need a military historian to tell you who
is winning the typographical wars. You know the answer. Bit by bit
_ byte by byte? _ computers have pushed typewriters to the same
musty shelf where you'll find buggy whips, bottles of cod-liver oil
and, any day now, New York City subway tokens.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you look carefully, you can spot bands of typewriter
holdouts here and there, dedicated souls who refuse to give up the
fight. It's hard not to think of those grizzled Japanese soldiers
who burrowed deep in the jungles of the Philippines and stayed
there for decades after World War II was over.
</P>
<P>
   One redoubt is finding itself under fire, a small group of
typewriter users who fear they are about to be declared personae
non gratae at, of all places, the Writers Room in Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible in this hypersensitive age to be technologically
incorrect? These typists believe that is what they have become, and
even though others say their concern is overblown, they feel about
as welcome as FBI agents at a Gotti family picnic.
</P>
<P>
   In case you do not know the Writers Room, it is a quiet haven
for novelists, playwrights, historians, cookbook writers, you name
it. It came into being in 1978 when refugees from the Frederick
Lewis Allen Memorial Room, an exclusive writers' retreat in the New
York Public Library, decided that the city needed a more democratic
sanctuary for scribblers to do whatever it is scribblers do,
including taking a nap while waiting for the Muse to alight on
their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the Room was to deny no writer the opportunity
to write,'' said Roberta Brandes Gratz, an urban historian who was
an original Roomster, along with well-known authors like Nancy
Milford and Lois Gould. The Writers Room now occupies a loft at 10
Astor Place above a Barnes &AMP; Noble store and Astor Wines and
Spirits, an admirable combination for a writers' hangout, you might
say: books and booze.
</P>
<P>
   The first members were mostly typewriters users. But now the
computer is king, and many laptoppers cannot endure the steady
clackety-clack from the half-dozen or so surviving typists (which
is kind of funny, given how insufferable Roomsters initially found
the R2D2 blips and squawks of the computers).
</P>
<P>
   So the typists were banished to a room of their own, where they
still bang away in splendid isolation on their Royals and
Smith-Coronas. On the main floor, only the faint clicking of
laptops pokes through the hush. Any new typist wishing to become a
member _ and none is now on the waiting list _ has to agree to use
a silent machine.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like peace in our time.
</P>
<P>
   But the technological entente is crumbling because of a problem
familiar to any New Yorker: lack of space.
</P>
<P>
   The Writers Room has some 300 members, with 100 more people,
computer types, clamoring to get in. Where to put them? Looking
around, the administrators laid eyes on the special room for the
typists, who do not always show up. There it was, the computer's
new frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some sort of prejudice against typewriters,'' said
Donna Brodie, the Room's executive director. ``There is simply an
imbalance in the service that's provided. There's a real-estate
crisis in New York, and young writers have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some laptoppers complain that if anything, it is the typists who
consider themselves a privileged caste. Not so, the typists reply.
They feel the atmosphere has turned hostile, and are convinced the
goal is to squeeze them out even if the Room's president, Tom
Shachtman, says nothing has been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Why cling so hard to an obviously outdated technology?
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfection I see on the computer screen I find
dangerous,'' Lois Gould said. ``It looks good, therefore you think
it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Another writer, Frances Whyatt, said the typewriter ``slows you
down enough to make you better,'' a point echoed by a younger
typist, Corey Sabourin, at work on his first novel. ``When I revise
a chapter,'' he said, ``I'm basically retelling the story to myself
instead of cutting and pasting the way you do with a computer. It
brings me deeper into the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Shachtman insists no one is looking ``to do any behavior
modification whatsoever,'' the typewriter users are not so sure.
``There's this irrational exuberance for technology,'' Sabourin
said. But, he cautioned, ``one size does not fit all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
