<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUPERMARKET-FIGHT-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF SUPERMARKET HAS VILLAGE IN AN UPROAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARWICK, N.Y. _ Those who insist that big business always wins,
who believe that concrete and asphalt are destined to inherit the
earth, have never witnessed the power of well-placed raffia ribbons
and certainly have never lived in a place like this.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, people in Warwick have been debating the
future of their Grand Union supermarket with a level of passion
more often reserved for presidential elections. The fight became so
intense recently that the mayor lost his job over it.
</P>
<P>
   To hundreds of residents of this idyllic Orange County village
of 6,000, the fate of their only downtown supermarket _ whether it
should modernize and move into a strip mall proposed for a plot of
farmland, or remain an old-fashioned Main Street grocery _ had come
to symbolize the fate of small-town America. And perhaps because so
many of those residents had just fled nearby Rockland County and
northern New Jersey for tiny, rural Warwick, they were prepared to
fight the specter of suburbanization to the end.
</P>
<P>
   So scores of these newer, commuter residents _ advertisers,
lawyers, public relations specialists and artists _ made phone
calls, printed fliers on home computers and fastened green ribbons
of protest to their neighbors' trees and mailboxes. On March 16,
calling themselves the Green Ribbon Group, they helped spur the
largest voter turnout in Warwick's history, defeating Mayor Frank
Lacalamita, a 24-year veteran of town and village offices, and
winning a majority on the village board. They have effectively
stopped Grand Union from building on the farmland, and are working
on plans to control Warwick's future growth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, they have antagonized many lifelong village
residents, who say they have been waiting for years to get more
jobs and businesses to add to the tax base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Warwick's a hick town and it's got to grow,''
said Leo McGovern, a retired postal worker who was born and raised
in the village and considers its quaint roadside farms nothing but
``dilapidated old buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Warwick's Main Street would fit better on Cape Cod, he said: ``A
man can't buy a pair of pants or a pair of shoes here. All we have
is craft stores, women's dress stores and that's it. But these
newcomers, with their ribbons and their groups and their
organizations, they don't want nothing to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar debates are simmering in many communities across the
nation, and they promise to heat up with the approach of the 2000
elections, in which Vice President Al Gore has signaled that he
will make curbing suburban sprawl a major part of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Warwick, sandwiched between the department-store meccas of
northern New Jersey and the shopping centers of Orange County,
seems an unlikely place to take such a stand. Many of its newer
residents, people who commute to jobs in New York City and
Westchester, hardly have time to keep up with their children, let
alone join in village politics.
</P>
<P>
   John Stage, a Warwick native who traveled the world as a
magazine photographer before retiring here, believes it is
precisely their status as outsiders that helps the newcomers
recognize the rarity of a place where merchants know their
customers by name and the hardware store has been selling nails for
100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Steyer, owner of Warwick's only liquor store, on Main
Street, said: ``Nobody's really against growth. It's just that
somehow, some way, it's got to be controlled, unlike what's
happening all over the rest of America. We want to avoid becoming a
Bergen County or a Long Island, because, frankly, all those towns
end up becoming outhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket battle began in the early 1990s, when Grand
Union Co. decided that it needed to expand its store to compete
with a newer Shop-Rite store about a mile away. Contending that
there was not sufficient space on Main Street, Grand Union asked
the village to rezone a 10-acre plot of farmland owned by Orange
County Trust, a Middletown bank, for a strip mall. The supermarket
chain and the bank joined with Pyramid Construction Co., a mall
developer in Ramsey, N.J., for a public relations and advertising
campaign to sell the mall to residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the attitude here was like, it's inevitable,'' said
Jane Newman, who lives next door to the proposed building site.
``It's developers, and you're a pathetic, lonely voice in the
crowd, so don't even bother. We were fighting the idea that
progress looks like malls. It doesn't have to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The parcel that looked so attractive to Grand Union was adjacent
to the 160 acres of rolling fields, winding paths and scenic duck
ponds settled in the 18th century by Warwick's founding family, the
Wellings, and bought in 1982 by Ms. Newman, an advertising
executive from New York City, Helen Jones, a food stylist, and
their husbands. For 17 years they had stubbornly guarded their
preserve from builders.
</P>
<P>
   Using Ms. Newman's living room as a command center, hundreds of
residents deluged the mayor with phone calls and letters begging
that the rezoning be denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was moving out of Manhattan to retire in Warwick
and do nothing,'' said Ms. Newman, rewrapping rolls of green ribbon
strewn across her dining room table. ``Certainly not to run a
political campaign. But what blew my mind is the board got nearly
1,000 phone calls and letters on this and they didn't budge. It was
just a complete travesty of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   So in August, they turned to grass-roots politics, forming the
Green Ribbon Group and supporting Anthony Portelli, who had been
trying to unseat Lacalamita for years.
</P>
<P>
   On Election Day, they mounted a huge get-out-the-vote effort
with volunteers like Stage, 72, who marched up and down a road at 5
a.m. wearing a sandwich board. All three Green Ribbon candidates
were elected to the five-member, nonpartisan village board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sweep was so unexpected, everybody just went crazy,''
said Stage, who used his home, a former tannery built in 1830, as
election night headquarters for the anti-mall forces. ``There are
all these hardened advertising people coming in from jobs in New
York City just going bonkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Grand Union's corporate vice president for public
affairs, Don Vaillencourt, says the chain still plans to move its
supermarket elsewhere in Warwick, even Lacalamita said that ``it
would be an embarrassment'' for the company to continue pushing for
the farm site.
</P>
<P>
   But the former mayor believes that development is inevitable in
Warwick, whose population has increased 30 percent in the last 30
years. ``The village is bursting at the seams right now,'' he said.
``We need a new supermarket that can handle all these people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping the lands open and the farms intact, I have no
question that that's a good idea, but there comes a time when
somebody says: `I don't want to farm anymore. I want to sell my
land and make a profit and go on a vacation.' And why shouldn't
they be able to sell it to a business developer? It's still a free
country.''
</P>
<P>
   And Warwick will no doubt continue to struggle with growing
pains. On Main Street, the post office and library need more space,
and two car dealerships want to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason so many of our Main Streets disappear is that they
lose that essential mix of businesses,'' said Carol Bartanowski,
who heads the village's merchant group. ``You can't have a
gift-shop Main Street. You've got to have services people need and
use every day. Once that heart is gone, you can't ever go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
