<HEADLINE>
ESPN, SI! DAY FOR BASEBALL AND CIGAR AFICIONADOS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN could not have improved much on its telecast of Sunday's
game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban all-stars short of
hiring Ted Koppel to be host of a town meeting about the production
of deadened baseballs in Fidel Castro's Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Miller and Joe Morgan were in loose, midseason form, showing
their evident immersion in the game, which Baltimore won, 3-2, in
11 innings. It felt like a typical ESPN Sunday night telecast,
largely because the Cuban team was more than competitive, which
freed Miller and Morgan from spending downtime spinning tales of
the great smuggled Cuban cigars they have smoked.
</P>
<P>
   But the game's unusual subtext _ Castro _ was always present
because of the frequent reaction shots of the Cuban president, who
was flanked by Bud Selig, the baseball commissioner, and Peter
Angelos, the Orioles' owner. They reportedly argued about the
revenue chasm between large and small markets. From reading
Castro's lips, I believe he cautioned his guests that they must
share all local television revenues or face economic catastrophe in
Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   When the Orioles scored their third run, Miller said, ``Angelos
is enjoying that more than the local jefe.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, Castro threw up his arms in frustration,
and Miller said, ``I hope he didn't take it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Jed Drake, ESPN's vice president for remote production, said the
exhibition was a ``unique and magical'' event, from taking Morgan
to a downtown park where the denizens ceaselessly debate baseball
to showing Cuban viewers their players in super slow motion for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The day's scene stealer was Conrado Marrero, an aged Cuban who
pitched for the Washington Senators from 1950 to 1954 (he recorded
a 39-40 record) and taught at Cuba's Sports Institute. Called on to
throw out the first pitch, Marrero tossed out seven _ and dared
Brady Anderson to step up to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe you, Brady,'' Morgan said. ``You tried to bunt
on an 84-year-old pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller: ``He was nervous. If he swung and hit it back to
the mound, there'd be an international incident.''
</P>
<P>
   The extended first-pitch act was vintage Marrero to Bob Wolff,
the senators' announcer from 1947 to 1961. ``Connie was one of the
Senators' all-time popular players,'' he said. ``He was a wily,
chunky guy, always with a cigar, even on the bench. He could really
make the ball do tricks. He was one of many Cuban players the
senators had. He was an excellent pitcher on a lousy team, a great
character who kept everybody laughing with his jokes and antics.''
</P>
<P>
   A Milestone for Emrick
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Devils-Penguins game on MSG Network will be Mike
Emrick's 2,000th professional hockey game, dating to his radio days
with the minor league Port Huron (Mich.) Flags on WHLS-AM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The station gave me a red suitcase, which had a two-channel
mixer and a little antenna. And the engineer made a headset for me
out of a coat hanger, with the microphone slipped into an end of
the hanger, which was bent into an eye-screw,'' Emrick said. He
donned that primitive headset for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Emrick's path led to the Maine Mariners of the American Hockey
League, the Philadelphia Flyers, his first stint with the Devils,
fill-in radio work for Rangers games, ESPN, SportsChannel America,
a second tour with the Flyers, a second hitch with the Devils (now
in its sixth season), CBS and now, Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very lucky to get to 2,000 because there was a cancer
scare in 1991,'' he said from his home near Port Huron. ``Ernie
Harwell, whom I love listening to up here, said you have to lucky
to do what you love.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoops Before War
</P>
<P>
   At 6:58 p.m. Saturday during the Connecticut-Ohio State
semifinal of the National Collegiate Athletic Association men's
basketball tournament, CBS showed good sense in offering a crawl
informing viewers that an American stealth fighter had gone down
over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS displayed bad news judgment by not returning to the
breaking story with more complete studio reports. Instead, CBS used
its breaks for commercials, program promos, an interview with Craig
Kilborn, the new host of CBS' ``Late Late Show,'' and a 3-point
shot contest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MSNBC, CNN and Fox News Channel showed Serbian video
of the fiery, downed fighter. CBS opted not to let a war interfere
much with March Madness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
