<SLUG> BC-GAY-WOMEN-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREND IS SEEN OF CLINICS CATERING TO LESBIANS, WHO OFTEN SHUN
HEALTH CARE
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's always an uneasiness when the doctor wants to
talk about sex, a young woman said at a recent meeting of her
lesbian support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when they ask, `Are you having intercourse?' And you
say, `No,' '' said the woman, with amber skin and a short Afro.
``Then they ask, `So you are not sexually active?' And you say, `I
didn't say that.' Then they ask, `Well what do you do?' And you
have to decide whether to lie or whether to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming out was once the predominant topic for groups like this
one, All the Queens Women, which gathers each month at the borough
hall in Queens. But the issues for these women have evolved. No
longer battling for a voice in the feminist movement, no longer
consumed only with their gay brothers dying of AIDS, lesbians have
turned their attention to their own health.
</P>
<P>
   As the young woman spoke the other night, the discussion leader,
Katherine Strieder, nodded. ``It's a scary choice,'' she said. ``If
you lie, then you may not get the information you need to take care
of yourself. And if you come out, your doctor may become really
uncomfortable with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Experiences like that have forced many lesbians to drop out of
the health care system, experts said, putting them at greater risk
for preventable illnesses and making them more likely to die from
diseases that are treatable if detected early. Many surveys have
found that most lesbians avoid going to the doctor for routine
checkups _ especially gynecological exams _ because of hostility
from doctors, or because they are uncomfortable talking about
issues that may reveal their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risks, lesbian health has been virtually ignored by
the medical establishment. But a growing movement, led primarily by
lesbian health care providers and political advocates, has pushed
the issue forward.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are a growing number of health care centers that
cater to lesbians, including two that opened recently in Manhattan:
the Beth Israel Medical Center established the Gay Women's Focus in
Union Square 18 months ago, and the Michael Callen-Audre Lorde
Community Health Center opened in Chelsea a year ago. Callen-Lorde
is the largest primary health care center in the nation devoted to
lesbians, bisexuals, gay men and ``transgenders'' _ an umbrella
term for transsexuals, cross-dressers, hermaphrodites and others
with unconventional sexual identities. Similar centers have opened
in Boston, San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Institute of Medicine, a division of the
National Academy of Science, issued a report on lesbian health that
urged the federal government to support studies that would identify
conditions for which lesbians are at risk and that would test
long-held myths, including that lesbians are less susceptible to
sexually transmitted diseases and that they are more susceptible to
breast cancer, alcoholism and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesbians have gone from an invisible population to a visible
and desirable population,'' said Dr. Jane Petro, a surgeon in
Westchester County. ``Hospitals all over the place are looking into
the idea of opening clinics for lesbians because they are starting
to realize that lesbians have special issues and concerns, and that
it's good business.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lesbian advocates worry that clinics like Callen-Lorde and
the Gay Women's Focus keep lesbian health care at the margins of
the medical community. They say they would rather see more efforts,
like one by Planned Parenthood, to make all health care providers
aware of the concerns of lesbian patients. Planned Parenthood
officials said their program teaches counselors not to assume
patients are heterosexual and uses interviewing techniques that
make it easy for all women to discuss their sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree, however, that until such training spreads, there is
still a need for lesbian health care havens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we should not be discriminated against,'' said
Lillian, a 61-year-old patient at the Gay Women's Focus. Like other
lesbian patients, she agreed to be interviewed on the condition
that her last name not be used. ``We should be able to talk openly
about ourselves and our partners with doctors. That would be great.
But that is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, after Lillian contracted Hepatitis C, she
appreciated being able to talk openly with her doctor about her
lesbian partner. ``I wanted to know whether we could kiss or drink
out of the same glass, not to mention sex,'' Lillian said.
``There's no way I would have asked a straight doctor those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with chronic high blood pressure and asthma, Sandy, a
61-year-old resident of Staten Island, avoided going to the doctor
for years until she found Callen-Lorde. Instead, she said, she used
energy healers and chiropractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you tell a doctor, `I am a 61-year-old celibate
lesbian?' '' Sandy said. ``What doctor could handle that?''
</P>
<P>
   Money has also been a barrier. While studies have shown that
women, in general, are less likely than men to have health
insurance, the problem is greater for lesbians because they cannot
depend on husbands with family insurance policies, and lesbians
with health insurance at work are usually unable to add their
partners to their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, experts said, even many lesbians with insurance
avoided doctors. If they got sick, they often relied on the
grapevine to find sympathetic doctors. Many of those doctors were
themselves lesbians, and their patients' experiences pushed them to
advocate national studies of lesbian health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joan Waitkovitz, director of the Gay Women's Focus at Beth
Israel, remembers what it was like in the early 1980s when her name
was part of that grapevine. ``There was an unpublished list of
numbers that circulated,'' she recalled. ``Everyone knew the tailor
on Sixth Avenue who would alter a man's suit to fit a woman. And
everyone knew the friendly doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, almost all studies on lesbian health were small and
financed with grants from the Lesbian Health Fund, established in
1992 by an association of lesbian doctors. Last year, it gave out
30 grants, totaling $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   But now mainstream scientific organizations are underwriting
such research. A Chicago scientist, Tonda Hughes of the University
of Illinois, for example, has started the first federally financed
study of lesbians and alcohol abuse with a $400,000 grant from the
National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Some large women's health studies _ the Women's Health
Initiative, a study of more than 100,000 women by the National
Institutes of Health, for example, and a different study by Harvard
University of more than 100,000 nurses _ have also added questions
about sexual orientation to their surveys.
</P>
<P>
   In its January report, the Institute of Medicine identified
cancer and mental health among lesbians as two areas in critical
need of research. Many doctors feel that lesbians may face greater
risks for breast and cervical cancers because they are less likely
than heterosexual women to go through the hormonal changes that
come with having children. And the stresses of living in a world
with widespread homophobia has made mental health a serious
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Callen-Lorde, funded by a $7.6 million dollar state government
bond and $3.5 million in donations, was named after Michael Callen,
the advocate for AIDS causes, and Audre Lorde, the poet who died of
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The center receives more than 1,000 patient visits a month. At
least half the patients are women, because of an energetic outreach
campaign that includes advertisements in gay newspapers and staff
visits to lesbian community meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Patients at the center pay on a sliding scale according to their
income. Soon, administrators said, the clinic will accept health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to use us as their family doctor, for regular
preventive care,'' said Dean LaBate, executive director of the
center. ``We want to be the health provider of choice, not just the
provider of last resort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
