<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 ASSIST TO BRADLEY FOR WIFE'S BOOK  
 AN AIDE'S QUIET EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JAMES BARRON with DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At every book party there is an Academy Awards-like
moment when the author tries to thank everyone who had anything to
do with the just-published work. And so Ernestine Schlant looked
over at the tall man near the door and said, ``Thanks to my
husband, Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley _ former basketball star, former U.S. senator,
potential presidential candidate _ smiled. After all, he did have
something to do with the book, besides whatever manuscript-reading
chores he may have undertaken: He is credited with taking the
postage-stamp-size picture of Ms. Schlant on the back of ``The
Language of Silence: West German Literature and the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schlant, a professor of German and comparative literature at
Montclair State University, said ``The Language of Silence'' had
been a 10-year project. She said she set out to look at how German
writers had looked at the Holocaust, starting with the Cold War and
ending with unification.
</P>
<P>
   Why writers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought literature was a more reliable indicator, and Bill
agrees with me so I can say it, than our politics or politicians,''
she said during the party, at Leo Baeck Institute, on 73rd Street
near Lexington Avenue, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Schlant's high school classmates was on hand, but the
crowd had a decidedly Princeton flavor, the place where Bradley
first came to basketball prominence. Among those with ties to
Bradley's alma mater were Dr. Ruth Westheimer (whose son went to
Princeton); Steven Cohen (who taught at Princeton before he became
a professor of Russian studies at New York University); Cohen's
wife, Katrina Vanden Heuvel (who graduated from Princeton in 1981
and is the editor of The Nation); John McPhee (who wrote a
biography of Bradley in the 1960s and has taught a course at
Princeton for more than 20 years) and Cornel West (who graduated
from Princeton in 1970 and now teaches at Harvard).
</P>
<P>
   ``She's like a dear sister,'' West said. ``They're very much
like family. We're all pushing for the campaign, but this is nice
because it's a wonderful text on the whole problem of evil in
modernity.'' That led to a discussion of the Amadou Diallo shooting
and what he hoped Bradley would say about it in a forthcoming
speech.
</P>
<P>
   An Aide's Quiet Exit  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the last four years, Colleen Roche has had one of the
toughest jobs in public relations: press secretary to the always
interesting, sometimes confounding and occasionally volatile Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. One day she was trumpeting the administration's
crackdown on crime, the next trying to put a positive spin on the
mayor's rocky relations with black and Hispanic officials.
Virtually everything she said was news.
</P>
<P>
   But the days of being on call 24 hours a day are over. Ms.
Roche, 41, is leaving this week to join the public relations firm
of Linden Alschuler &AMP; Kaplan. The move means that she will be able
to spend more time with her husband, Peter Casolaro, a prosecutor
in the office of Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to City Hall, Ms. Roche was communications director
for the State Division of Criminal Justice Services and deputy
press secretary for Morgenthau. Neither job brought her anywhere
near the scrutiny she has received as Giuliani's conduit to _ or
buffer against _ the city's press corps.
</P>
<P>
   The job ``is probably one of the most complex jobs in the United
States,'' Giuliani said during a public farewell Monday. ``Colleen
has handled it with exceptional professionalism, has handled it
with great honesty and integrity. She's done an absolutely superb
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roche complimented her co-workers, then answered a question
not asked but still burning. ``The one thing I will not be doing,''
she said, ``is writing a book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
