<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-FINALS-COX     03-29 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-FINALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONNECTICUT 77, DUKE 74: UConn believe it, Huskies
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ In 1990, Duke gave the University of
Connecticut the greatest basketball heartache in its history when
it beat the Huskies at the buzzer for a spot in the Final Four.
Monday night in a game that will go down as one of the NCAA
Tournament's greatest upsets, UConn returned the favor in stunning
fashion, beating the seemingly-unbeatable Blue Devils 77-74 to win
the 1999 NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   UConn (34-3) snapped Duke's 32-game winning streak with a
determined performance for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, which was going for its third national title of this
decade, had its chances in the closing seconds. Down 75-74, the
Blue Devils got the ball back after a miss by Khalid El-Amin with
20 seconds left. That's when Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski picked
senior Trajan Langdon to go one-on-one with Augusta's Ricky Moore.
Langdon forced a shot and was called for traveling with 5.4 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin then made two three throws with 5.2 seconds remaining.
Langdon tried to get off a final three-point shot but end the game
on the floor as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by as many as six, 63-57, with 9:34 to go, Duke finally
clawed its way back and tied the game at 66-66, on Chris
Carrawell's driving shot in the lane with 4:53 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton put UConn back up two, 70-68, with a pair of
free throws with 3:50 remaining and then stretched the lead to five
with a three-pointer after a turnover by Duke's Will Avery. UConn
still led by four, 73-69, at the two-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   But Duke climbed back to within one after Carrawell's missed
shot was grabbed by Shane Battier and kicked back out to Trajan
Langdon, who canned a three-pointer with 1:44 left to make it
73-72.
</P>
<P>
   With the shot clocking winding down, Khalid El-Amin scored from
the baseline with 1:05 left to put UConn up by three, 75-72.
</P>
<P>
   Then Avery hit a pair of free throws with 54.1 seconds left to
bring Duke to within one 75-74.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton led all scorers with 27 points while Langdon had 25.
</P>
<P>
   Up 39-37 at halftime, Duke expanded its lead to five, 46-41, on
Brand's layup with 17:58 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn simply would not go away, rallying to tie the game
49-49 on a pair of free throws by Hamilton with 14:47 remaining.
The score tied two more times before UConn took a four-point lead,
57-53, on a basket by Albert Mouring with 12:35 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still up by two, 59-57, Hamilton knocked down a 3-point shot off
a fast break and Duke failed to score on two straight possessions.
After a free throw by Edmund Saunders, UConn had its largest lead
of the game, 63-57, with 9:34 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Duke, the ACC champions, kept fighting back and climbed
within two, 65-63, on Chris Carrawell's 15-footer with 7:28
remaining, and the stage was set for the final dramatic minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Duke jumped out to a 9-2 lead in the first 3:17 of the game, and
then Augusta's Ricky Moore got hot, scoring nine of UConn's next 13
points. The Huskies put together a 15-4 run in just over four
minutes to take a 17-13 lead with 12:29 remaining in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Duke came back with a 10-1 run of its own, fueled by another
Augusta native, Will Avery, who scored five straight points. The
Blue Devils led 23-18 with 11:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn would not wilt under the Duke pressure as the Huskies
came right back to tie the score at 24-24 on Richard Hamilton's
bucket at the 8:25 mark.
</P>
<P>
   UConn took another four-point lead, 36-32, on Hamilton's basket
with 1:29 left, but it would not last.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Langdon hit a long 3-pointer at the top of the key and on
the Blue Devils' next possession, made another 3-point shot with
Moore literally hanging on to him. Langdon was awarded a free
throw, which he made to covert the four-point play and put Duke up
39-36 with 24.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton added a free throw with 1.7 seconds left and Duke held
held a 39-37 lead at the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Moore ended the half with 13 points after hitting 6 of 8 shots
from the floor. UConn handled the Duke defense well enough to shoot
53.1 percent from the floor (17 of 32).
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
