</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY AUTHORITIES CITE MERITS OF GROUND ACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
(Eds: SUBS 5-8 bgng `Some 2,000 ...,' to UPDATE numbers, add
anonymous Pentagon official commenting on Joint Chiefs meeting;
Pickup 8th graf pvs, While confronting ...) 
 (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-PROTECT, KOSOVO-DRONES,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-MONITORS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-PILOTS.) 
(jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If NATO nations ordered ground troops to Kosovo, a
force of 30,000 to 40,000 troops could be assembled in days and
would be sufficient to protect many refugees from further attack,
according to several current and former American commanders.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have emphasized they are not planning to send
ground troops into Kosovo, but American generals had estimated that
any ground action would require as many as 200,000 soldiers to
quell the fighting, a force that would not be ready for months.
Thus far, allied political leaders have balked at committing even a
single soldier to combat in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The commanders said the smaller number of troops, backed by air
power, could sweep into the besieged province and create safe
havens for the tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees who
are fleeing Serbian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. George Joulwan, who retired in 1997 as NATO's military
commander, said that a 12,000-member European force in Macedonia
poised to enter force any Kosovo if a peace agreement, could take
on a new mission within seven to 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,200 Marines aboard ships in the Adriatic could respond
even quicker. Additional NATO forces could flow in from bases in
Europe and the United States over the next few weeks, depending on
road and port conditions. A 1,200-member American reinforced
infantry battalion is based in Italy. In Bosnia, 8,200 troops from
the elite 1st Cavalry Division in the international peacekeeping
force could be tapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go all the way to Belgrade,'' Joulwan said
in a telephone interview from Madrid. ``You'd give that force
limited objectives, create a corridor, focus on the refugees and
save some lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a scaled-back NATO operation would have to overcome the
deep reluctance of the Clinton administration and NATO to push for
a mission that greatly increases the likelihood of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the situation's military urgency, the Joint Chiefs
of Staff met Monday on short notice for about an hour to weigh
developments in Kosovo. A Pentagon official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said if ground forces were discussed, it
was only in passing.
</P>
<P>
   While confronting the approximately 40,000 Yugoslav troops in
and around Kosovo would pose enormous risks, a NATO force of equal
size would have several advantages, the commanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's infantry and armored forces are untested against
well-trained NATO troops, and would be the targets of a withering
air attack. Its heavy weapons would come under fierce attack from
allied artillery and tanks, which are trained to engage the enemy
from miles away.
</P>
<P>
   And with NATO warplanes controlling Serbian skies and bombing
supply, fuel and communication lines, Yugoslav forces would be cut
off and isolated from reinforcements, military experts say. NATO's
edge in intelligence and reconnaissance would also give the allied
forces important advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're credible, but we shouldn't be overawed by their
army,'' said Lt. Gen. William Carter III, a retired chief of staff
of Southern NATO forces who helped direct the allied operation in
Bosnia. ``In many cases, our respect has been translated into
making them taller than they are. I'm not convinced we need the
size forces that people are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Leighton Smith, a former commander of southern NATO forces,
agreed: ``It's entirely possible you might be willing to take a
geographic area and make it a demilitarized zone. That might
require a much smaller force than one to eject the Serb army from
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of these former commanders, as well as several
current ranking officers, said at the very least, NATO and
administration officials should not be so adamant about ruling out
a ground campaign, if nothing else than to give President Slobodan
Milosevic pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've telegraphed that we're not prepared to come in on the
ground, and that's coloring his reaction to the air campaign,''
said one senior Army general. ``Milosevic figures he can string
this out, and see if the NATO alliance cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   While political leaders continue to rule out ground forces
publicly, there are signs that allied officials are leaving the
door ever so slightly ajar for a ground option. Asked Monday if any
contingency planning was under way for land forces, NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea said, ``Not for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Army logisticians on their own conducted a detailed
assessment of what American forces in a Kosovo operation might
need, patterning such a contingency on the four-year-old
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at how you link things in Bosnia like supply
lines and electronic lines, into the theater in Kosovo,'' said one
senior officer. ``We haven't received any official directive to do
this. It's just prudent planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a peace agreement, NATO ground forces would face a
daunting set of perils. Between 17,000 and 20,000 Yugoslav troops
now occupy Kosovo, an area the size of Connecticut, with another
20,000 soldiers outside the region.
</P>
<P>
   These forces are equipped with more than 400 tanks, 300 armored
personnel carriers and more than 400 artillery pieces in the field,
or in garrison, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Only 14 roads lead into Kosovo, Bacon said, two from Macedonia,
and these roadways and bridges are pocked with land mines.
Surface-to-air missiles still threaten NATO aircraft. In addition
to regular army forces, there are roving paramilitary groups that
could threaten NATO forces with guerrilla or terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO operation forcibly entering Kosovo would have to
anticipate all these threats. Last fall, NATO determined in a
confidential assessment it would take 200,000 troops to invade and
occupy Kosovo, and several weeks to muster those troops.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, President Clinton remains opposed to using
ground troops to supplement the air strikes, despite growing calls
for him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But some administration officials say the real hurdle to sending
ground forces is political, not military. The administration has
not prepared the American public, Congress or its NATO allies for a
protracted, even if limited, ground operation.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, American officials predicted Milosevic's defiantly
brutal response. As a result, administration officials acknowledge
there has been little formal planning for a ground option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miscalculated,'' conceded one administration official who
is deeply involved in the crisis. ``We thought when the bombing
started Milosevic would play the victim, not turn into Adolph
Hitler Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   With reports of atrocities mounting and hundreds of thousands of
refugees on the move, pressure to launch a ground operation may be
inexorable if the air campaign fails to stop the Yugoslav
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the killings continue, how can you have 12,000 NATO troops
5 to 10 miles from where the atrocities are being committed, and do
nothing?'' Joulwan asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
